<SLUG> BC-NY-PRISON-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDDHIST MONK LEADS WALK TO PROMOTE PRISON REFORM
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By HUBERT B. HERRING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOBBS FERRY, N.Y. _ The streets of this Westchester County town,
where shiny sport utility vehicles grudgingly share space with
joggers, featured an unusual sight on Sunday: eight people walking
single file, one holding aloft a long purple ``prayer banner,''
another holding a banner heralding a ``Prison Reform Walk.''
</P>
<P>
   As they walked they drummed and chanted, creating a hypnotic
rhythm that echoed blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   The group had walked for nearly a month, 15 to 18 miles a day,
starting northeast of Albany and zigzagging down the state. Along
the way they visited a number of prisons, trying to spread
awareness of what they see as the injustices of the prison system,
including overlong sentences, insufficient educational
opportunities, and use of the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Some walk for only a few days, some have come the whole way. The
driving force is a Buddhist monk named Jun Yasuda. Sister Jun came
to this country from her native Tokyo 20 years ago and has been
taking part in walks ever since, for causes from peace to Native
American rights.
</P>
<P>
   Why walk? ``It's simple,'' Sister Jun said. ``Humans for many
thousands of years were just walking.'' She walks nearly half of
each year, she said, and has numerous contacts to tap when shelter
or a meal is needed.
</P>
<P>
   These walkers spent the night before sleeping on the floor of
South Presbyterian Church here _ as self-proclaimed ``beggars,''
they take food and shelter where it is offered _ and attended the
church service at 10 a.m. But before that Sister Jun had the group
up and walking, banners aloft, in full chant.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we're packed, Jun-san starts walking,'' said Denise
Laffan of Atlanta, the group's other monk, employing the Japanese
honorific all the walkers use for the leader. ``She's not one to
sit around.'' After the service, they hit the road again quickly.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday, after stops including Rikers Island, they plan to
end the walk with a daylong fast at the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Jun, 50, lives at the Grafton Peace Pagoda, northeast of
Albany _ a volunteer-built temple on 10 donated acres where the
walk began. She lives there ``free of the material world,'' she
says, unconcerned with mundane matters such as health insurance.
And if she should get sick? She shrugs off the possibility. ``If
you worry about yourself, you cannot do anything,'' she said.
``It's the world that is really sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Her order, Nipponzan Myohoji, has one prime focus: to walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very small order with a very big vision,'' Sister
Denise said. ``Whoever's working for peace and justice, we're
walking, supporting, praying with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Amy Hutto said she met Sister Jun on another walk and traveled
here from Berkeley, Calif. ``She's so solid,'' Ms. Hutto said. On
the previous walk, ``I gravitated toward the calmest thing, and
that was Jun-san.''
</P>
<P>
   Heads turned and cars slowed as the group processed along
Broadway. One walker, Greg Brown, said there had been taunts in the
past. But on Sunday, there were approving honks, and thumbs-up
signals.
</P>
<P>
   The walkers are a diverse group. ``I'm a former newspaper
reporter,'' said Sister Denise, 38. ``But then it came to me: you
should live as if your faith is a matter of life and death.'' So
she ``started a journey'' that led to her becoming a monk eight
years ago..
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see this as a protest,'' she said. ``It's about
connecting, changing our hearts _ that will bring down the prison
walls.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, a 20-year-old from upstate New York who works at a record
store, told of vigils outside various prisons. ``We'd bow to the
guards, and a few bowed back, which was cool,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Audrey Stewart, 20, lives in Ithaca and paints houses to support
her peace work. ``Prisons are the next version of slavery,'' she
said, voicing special contempt for private prisons. ``Once you
reduce people to moneymaking objects, all concern for their rights
goes out the window.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ms. Hutto, 35, is a recovering drug user. ``To walk and
pray,'' she said, ``is very healing and grounding.''
</P>
<P>
   Some are Buddhists, but not all. But the chants Sister Jun
leads, the spirit she brings, are Buddhist in nature. ``The
Buddhist way,'' Sister Jun said, ``is we have no fences. To put
people in cages is not a solution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
