<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GISELLE-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GISELLE` ACCENTS ROMANTICISM'S PLAY ON REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.) (sw) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The San Francisco Ballet has never included
``Giselle'' in its permanent repertory. As if to compensate for
this not-so-dreadful omission, Helgi Tomasson's new staging for the
company has an opera house grandeur that ``Giselle'' deserves but
rarely receives.
</P>
<P>
   The production's spectacular scale, with its large corps,
unusual play with space in the decor, stage machinery (with sylphs
whizzing in the air) and brilliantly presented dramatic detail,
brings out the essence of ``Giselle'': the difference between the
real and the supernatural.
</P>
<P>
   ``Giselle'' in these two aspects is the epitome of 19th-century
Romantic ballet. Created in 1841 at the Paris Opera as the
brainchild of the poet Theophile Gautier, the ballet was not the
first to use this two-part Romantic formula. If the work has
survived (although modified by choreographers over 158 years), it
is thanks not only to Adolphe Adam's landmark score but to its
perfect summary of Romanticism's real-supernatural dichotomy.
</P>
<P>
   This is a delineation that Tomasson's staging, presented through
this weekend with the premiere on Thursday night, emphasized so
clearly at the War Memorial Opera House here.
</P>
<P>
   The village of Act I when Giselle, the peasant girl, is seduced
by Albrecht, a count in disguise, is not the usual intimate scene.
Its local color extends to the vistas of the fields beyond the
village where the folk harvest their grapes.
</P>
<P>
   Open space thus greets the viewer in Act I and a mysteriously
closed forest begins Act II, when Giselle joins the spirits, or
wilis, ghosts of jilted maidens who died before their wedding day.
</P>
<P>
   In this open-closed contrast the Danish designer Mikael Melbye
has offered a startling and persuasive twist on viewer
expectations. His German village looks so realistic that it is not
surprising to learn that Melbye has based his scenery on the real
town of Thuringen in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Like the 1841 decor, his includes a castle in the background. It
is modeled on Schloss Burgk, which still exists in the town.
Moreover the realism is enhanced by the three-dimensional effect of
a set with built houses and a fence, not painted decor.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast there is none of the usual clearing in the woods at
the beginning of Act II. A row of gnarled trees separates only
after Myrtha, queen of the wilis, enters.
</P>
<P>
   The gala opening on Thursday was a tribute to the company's
outgoing chairwoman, Patricia Hellman, whose family made a major
contribution to the $750,000 production. The performance was led by
Lucia Lacarra and Yuri Possokhov while the Friday cast was led by
Tina LeBlanc and Roman Rykine.
</P>
<P>
   If some principals need to reach for more depth, Tomasson has
done wonders with the corps, moved the action quickly along and
infused it with dramatic detail.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Ballet apparently staged a single performance
of the work in 1947 under Anton Dolin's direction. The Tomasson
contribution is evident first in the dramatic logic. The wilis bend
and rise as they enter, as if coming out of the earth. Giselle
retreats into her grave at the end by sinking in the deep curtsy
performed by the corps. Suddenly she is sucked into the wings and
Albrecht, rising, returns to lie by her grave in tender melancholy.
</P>
<P>
   Tomasson has rechoreographed some of the ensembles in Act I
distinctively and the peasant pas de deux has been replaced by two
men and three women. The music by Friedrich Borgmuller,
interpolated in 1841 for this passage, has been augmented now by a
Borgmuller piano piece (``Shepherd's Return''), orchestrated by the
company's conductor, Emil de Cou.
</P>
<P>
   This extra music goes to the impressive Kristin Long for a solo,
while the traditional music is used for virtuoso display from the
men, Guennadi Nedviguine and Gonzalo Garcia. The latter pulled off
a new bravura step, a composite of a barrel turn and revoltade turn
in the air, while Nedviguine was splendid in his classical style.
The women, who included Claudia Alfieri and Vanessa Zahorian,
dazzled as well.
</P>
<P>
   It is a bit of a jolt to see stylistic references to
Bournonville in this pas de cinque. Nothing however prepares one
for the completely new interpolated brief pas de deux that Tomasson
has created in Act I before Hilarion, Albrecht's rival, reveals the
count's identity.
</P>
<P>
   Tomasson's choreography is neo-classical, with a modern attack,
and Giselle, leaning on Albrecht's arm, has a high arabesque that
looks Balanchinian. The music comes from an 1854 edition of the
score used by de Cou. Whether this musical passage was ever staged
is doubtful but it exists in that copy of the score.
</P>
<P>
   The Romantic expressiveness in this production comes from the
exquisitely coached mime. Ms. Lacarra portrayed a beautiful wisp of
a village girl in Act I, with a harrowingly effective mad scene.
But her technique faltered unacceptably. In Act I, she could not
hop on toe and her footwork was too blurred in the diagonals of
turns. In Act II she missed the deep arabesques and steady balances
that are Giselle's signature.
</P>
<P>
   Her Albrecht, Possokhov, seemed deliberately reined in until a
sudden passionate burst of yearning colored his performance from
the end of Act I to the end. Rykine was obviously directed in the
same way and while dancing more elegantly on Friday, did not have
believable rapport with Ms. LeBlanc, whose beautifully danced
Giselle needs only more depth.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Damian Smith was a handsome, mean Hilarion, with
Muriel Maffre as a splendid, icy Myrtha. On Friday, Peter
Brandenhoff was handsome and meaner and Sabina Allemann's vigorous
Myrtha had its own splendor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
