<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLAZABAL SHOWS HIS CLASS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ The Masters and the moment belonged to Jose Maria
Olazabal. The man so hobbled he couldn't walk in 1996 was striding
_ no, gliding _ up the 18th fairway on Sunday, a two-shot lead in
his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   This was the crown jewel in Olazabal's comeback from a
career-threatening foot injury and, accordingly, a majestic crowd
stood ready to receive him up at the green.
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal made them wait, though out of concern not conceit.
</P>
<P>
   The Spaniard didn't want the courage of his playing partner,
Greg Norman, to get lost in his own coronation. And so, incredibly,
indelibly, Olazabal stopped until Norman, lagging behind so as not
to rattle his friend's stage, caught up.
</P>
<P>
   Together they walked up to receive their due, the disappointment
of yet another near miss here by Norman displaced by the most
eloquent show of sportsmanship since Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa
exchanged hugs and handshakes and air kisses during their home run
derby last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can I say? I was in a situation (Sunday), you know, that
I wanted to win the green jacket,'' said Olazabal, who closed with
a 1-under-par 71 to win his second Masters title. ``But at the same
time, I was playing with Greg and from my point of view, he
deserves the jacket as much as anybody else. I knew (at 18) he was
facing a tough moment again, and I think it was nice for me to wait
for him and walk the last few yards together.''
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal's nickname, Chemma, must be Spanish for classy.
</P>
<P>
   The sweeping crowds that fanned out over Augusta National Sunday
were firmly behind Norman from the start. He was the people's
choice, his every birdie _ and his one eagle, on the par-5 13th _
eliciting roars that jumped like flames as his scores were posted
on the giant leaderboards all over the course.
</P>
<P>
   Norman, 44, is three years removed from his career nadir _ a
six-stroke, final-round collapse that handed Nick Faldo his third
Masters title. To hear him talk, a lot of wonderful things have
happened since then.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, from the second Norman walked purposefully into view
here Sunday, it was obvious he'd have an easier time shaking his
shadow than the memory of that long afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear from the silence that hung in the air, heavy as
humidity, whenever a drive of his didn't split the fairway or an
approach shot of his didn't dissect the glass-hard greens. Make no
mistake: The gargantuan gallery following Norman was red-faced not
as a result of the sun's rays but from holding its collective
breath.
</P>
<P>
   When Norman bogeyed the par-3 12th and three-putted from the
fringe for a bogey on No.14 after carding his eagle on 13, the
sense of foreboding was palpable.
</P>
<P>
   The 13th green was also the scene of a Hallmark moment. Norman
made his best iron shot of the week count by draining a 25-foot
putt for a 3 to take the lead outright at 7 under.
</P>
<P>
   Norman's nirvana lasted all of 60 seconds, or however long it
took Olazabal to step up and sink a 21-foot birdie putt to match
Norman at 7 under. Norman, recognizing in Olazabal's stroke a
challenge received and put away, pointed at Olazabal like a
basketball player acknowledging the teammate who had fed him the
ball for the easy basket.
</P>
<P>
   In a matter of speaking, the two competitors were on the same
team, united behind a Red Cross flag.
</P>
<P>
   If Norman couldn't win _ the three-time Masters bridesmaid faded
to third this time, three shots behind Olazabal _ it was only
fitting that 1998 champion Mark O'Meara slipped the green jacket
around Olazabal's shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   When Norman underwent right-shoulder surgery shortly after the
Masters last year, Olazabal was one of a paltry few among his peers
who sent Norman a note wishing him well in his recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Most professional athletes aren't spiteful, just self-absorbed.
So when Mark McGwire seeks out the family of Roger Maris after
hitting his 63rd home run and Olazabal seeks out Norman before
clinching his second major, you applaud the man more than the
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ollie has a good heart,'' Norman said. ``He takes time to make
sure you're OK. He takes time to walk across the putting green, the
locker room, to say hello. He cares about the things that go on
around him.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind every act of kindness, there is another. When Olazabal
was recovering from a pinched nerve in his back that delivered
intense pain to his right foot, Norman checked in on him regularly.
This softer, compassionate side Norman kept largely under wraps for
the longest time. To his peers and the public he was a
swashbuckling hustler, the Rupert Murdoch of the links.
</P>
<P>
   Then a 46-year-old icon took one Masters title from Norman, an
Augusta native chipped in from 140 feet to snatch another right out
from under his nose and he just plain dropped a third.
</P>
<P>
   The grace with which Norman handled his 1996 collapse opened
people's eyes and then their hearts. All of the sudden he was seen
as not just a great golfer but a pretty decent man.
</P>
<P>
   Just like Olazabal, as it turns out. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
