<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLAZABAL CAPTURES SECOND MASTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Just three years ago Jose Maria Olazabal was
virtually confined to his home in Fuenterrabia in northern Spain,
his future in golf uncertain because of debilitating problems with
his feet. He watched the Masters on television, saw his friend Greg
Norman fall apart in the pressures of the final round, and made a
silent promise that someday he'd return.
</P>
<P>
   Paired with Norman in Sunday's final round of the 63d Masters at
the Augusta National GC, Olazabal made the monumental trek up
golf's most celebrated hill to the 18th green secure in the
knowledge that he would be helped into a green jacket by defender
Mark O'Meara. There were times when Olazabal couldn't walk, let
alone play the game he loved. Now he had gone full circle.
</P>
<P>
   When Olazabal sank his final putt to complete a magnificent tour
of these hallowed grounds in 8-under par numbers of
70-66-73-71_280, he had won the Masters for the second time with a
gritty performance in fiercely unkind winds that tested the
players' character as the leaderboard became a listing of many of
the game's top stars. Olazabal's effort represented a triumph of
the human spirit.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of Norman was a constant, and he was returning from
inactivity following shoulder surgery shortly after the Masters a
year ago. If he had seen his six-shot lead over Nick Faldo three
years ago go by the boards on a disheartening afternoon, he
returned to the cheers of the crowds and threatened to pull it off
until he couldn't rise to the occasion one more time in the final
round of a major.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it all came down to the par-5 13th, where Davis Love
pulled his tee shot into Rae's Creek, and even though he salvaged
par, he saw time was running out.
</P>
<P>
   Just moments later, Norman found the putting surface in two, and
hit a curling 25-foot right-to-left putt for an eagle. Olazabal,
who was on the green in three and could have dropped two shots in
what had become match play, rolled in his 21-foot putt for birdie.
</P>
<P>
   This set the table for a final run, and when it ended Olazabal
had another Masters win, to go with his first five years ago,
before what originally was diagnosed as a foot injury was
discovered to be a lower back ailment and threatened his career.
There was a time he couldn't get out of bed, and he was inactive
for 18 months. But, ``I try not to think about what happened in the
past,'' Olazabal said.
</P>
<P>
   The final tally showed Olazabal winning by two shots over Love
(71), three over Norman (73), and four over Bob Estes (72) and
Steve Pate (73). Five players were tied for the lead on the front
nine, including the game's hottest player, David Duval (70_285),
who faded with a double bogey on the 11th, Lee Westwood (71_285),
Lee Janzen (76_288), Love, and Norman.
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal, who led after Rounds 2 and 3, saw the lead slip away
with bogeys on the third, fourth, and fifth holes before he
regrouped with a birdie 2 on the sixth. From there until he rolled
in a 3-foot putt on the 18th, he played in 4 under, with birdies on
the 10th, 13th, and 16th. When Olazabal holed out on the 18th,
Norman warmly embraced him. They'd remained tight friends through
their surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   Love, who made a significant breakthrough when he won the 1997
PGA Championship at Winged Foot as a rainbow appeared, had hoped
for better. After making the turn in level par 36, he made a
remarkable par on the par-5 13th after he pulled his tee shot into
the water, rolling in a 25-foot putt to save par.
</P>
<P>
   On the par-3 16th, Love hit his tee shot into the rough left of
the green. His chip shot hit the green, took a definite turn to the
right and slowly rolled some 20 feet back to the cup for a birdie.
Love was alive and breathing. He would par the 17th and 18th, but
Olazabal would birdie the 16th when he hit a 6-iron to 3 feet.
</P>
<P>
   That birdie put him in control, and after his tee shot on the
par-4 17th caught a bit of the Eisenhower tree, he was able to hit
a 5-iron second shot on and get down in two to take a two-shot lead
to the 18th and take the victory stroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great day for me,'' said Olazabal. ``I'm very proud of
myself. When I was at my lowest I never thought I was going to play
golf again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
