<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX FINALLY TASTE DEFEAT 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-DEVIL RAYS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ He was the last option, but not the
solution.
</P>
<P>
   Down to his final out Sunday afternoon, Red Sox manager Jimy
Williams asked a lame man not to walk, but to pinch hit.
</P>
<P>
   But there would be no miracle finish, the kind that has made
Kirk Gibson a highlight reel immortal. Nomar Garciaparra, who at
the time was still a candidate to go on the disabled list with a
strained left hamstring, struck out, dropping the curtain on a 5-4
loss to the Tampa Bay Devil Rays that ended a five-game winning
streak and the distinction of being the last undefeated team in the
big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in a tough situation,'' said Jeff Frye, whose
seventh-inning single after Damon Buford's double had brought the
Sox all the way back from a 4-0 deficit created by two-run home
runs by Fred McGriff and Mike DiFelice in the first two innings off
wild Sox starter Pat Rapp.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hadn't hit for a while,'' Frye said. ``To expect him to do
that would have been tough. I mean, we all know he's superhuman,
but I'm just being realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, sent to the plate with pinch hitter Scott Hatteberg
aboard after a two-out walk, went down swinging against closer
Roberto Hernandez, who got away with a hanging slider after
Garciaparra had run the count to 2 and 2, fouling off three
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a hitter who swings at everything in the strike zone,''
Hernandez said after saving Tampa Bay's first home win. ``Luckily,
this one was out of the zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatteberg was the last of 14 runners stranded Sunday by the Sox,
who left the bases loaded once and two men on in five other
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, the last of three pinch hitters used by Williams in
the inning, said the manager told him during the eighth inning he
might be asked to hit.
</P>
<P>
   Did Garciaparra feel the sore hammy during the at-bat?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said. ``I felt a strikeout.''
</P>
<P>
   Having come back once to tie, the Sox were trying to answer the
eighth-inning home run surrendered by reliever Derek Lowe to Danny
Clyburn, who in five previous at-bats had struck out three times
and grounded into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Clyburn, formerly an outfielder in the Orioles' system who hit
his only previous major league home run off Tim Wakefield last
September in Fenway Park, drove a 1-and-1 pitch over the
center-field fence with two out.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe, who didn't give up a home run in 53 relief appearances
last season, now has been taken deep twice in his last two
appearances. The first one was a no-harm, no-foul number by McGriff
with two outs in the ninth inning of a 4-1 Sox win Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   This one caused collateral damage. ``He got beat with his best
pitch,'' pitching coach Joe Kerrigan said. ``He got beat with his
sinker. He went down like a man. He's going to be pitching a lot
more in situations like that, so he'd better get used to having a
short memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's too good a pitcher to let this one linger.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe said the sinker he threw started outside but, instead of
diving, came back over the plate like a cut fastball. ``Horrible,''
Lowe said. ``There are a lot of pluses to pitching in the eighth or
ninth inning, but if you give up a home run, you can be the goat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to getting back out there. But you know,
I've given up seven home runs with the Red Sox, and four of them
have come here _ two last year (as a starter), two this year. I
can't wait to get out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Clyburn's home run, the Sox bullpen had been as coldly
efficient as it had been in the previous five games. The only
difference Sunday was that there were two new contributors. Lefty
Rheal Cormier struck out the side (including Jose Canseco and
McGriff on six pitches in the fifth) and had four Ks in all in his
two innings, while Kip Gross retired all three batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   Cormier, coming back from elbow surgery, hadn't pitched in a
major league game in two years. Gross, coming back from Japan,
hadn't pitched in a big-league game since 1992. And neither had
taken the mound for the Sox since the last week of spring training
in Florida, nearly two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both those kids pitched great,'' Williams said, ``considering
they hadn't pitched in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Jose Offerman, who has been an automatic two hits a game for the
Sox, singled and scored on Mike Stanley's base hit for the Sox'
first run in the third, then hit a bases-loaded single in the sixth
to make it 4-3. When Frye tied it in the seventh, Williams already
was thinking ahead to the ninth, and Nomar.
</P>
<P>
   Williams first used Brian Daubach, who opened the ninth by
striking out. Frye tapped to the mound for the second out before
Hatteberg, batting for Jason Varitek, walked on a full count. By
then, Garciaparra already was on deck, in place of Donnie Sadler,
who had a single in his last 11 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to hit a gapper, send up a good hitter and give
it a shot with one out to go,'' Williams said. ``He's been taking
batting practice.''
</P>
<P>
   By using Garciaparra, Williams was essentially eliminating the
chance that the shortstop would be going on the DL. The Sox could
have backdated Garciaparra on the DL to last Wednesday, the day he
sustained the injury running the bases in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put that Ouija board out there, it's in your hands,
All-State,'' Williams said of playing Garciaparra. ``For me, it was
the right thing to do in today's game. It just didn't work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
