<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QBS COULD BE THROWBACK TO CLASS OF '83 
</HEADLINE>
 DRAFT-QUARTERBACKS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's all guesswork, of course. Oh, the guys with the
stopwatches have judged the quarterbacks' arm strength, their speed
in the 40, and how quickly they release the ball. But even they
don't know for sure what they have.
</P>
<P>
   What they do know _ or at least think they know _ is that when
the first two rounds of Saturday's National Football League draft
are over, at least five and possibly as many as eight QBs will have
been selected.
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, could make it the largest QB class since 1983,
when six signal-callers were selected in the first round. Those
Super Six QBs thus far have made 11 Super Bowl appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a whole, this class is excellent,'' said Philadelphia
Eagles director of football operations Tom Modrak, whose team might
select a QB with its first-round pick (second overall). ``There's
quality and there's depth, which is unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Those quarterbacks considered in the elite group are, in
alphabetical order, Kentucky's Tim Couch, Central Florida's Daunte
Culpepper, Syracuse's Donovan McNabb, UCLA's Cade McNown, and
Oregon's Akili Smith.
</P>
<P>
   After that, there are Ohio State's Joe Germaine, Washington's
Brock Huard, Kansas State's Michael Bishop, Tulane's Shaun King,
and Miami's Scott Covington. So one can see why this is being
referred to as a deep position.
</P>
<P>
   Depth is part of the reason comparisons are being made to the
Class of 1983. But it will take some extraordinary performances to
match that group, which included John Elway, Dan Marino, Jim Kelly,
Todd Blackledge, Ken O'Brien, and Tony Eason.
</P>
<P>
   But mistakes were made in 1983, just as they will be Saturday.
While Elway was the clear-cut choice as the No. 1 quarterback in
'83, there is no such player this season. Couch, who left Kentucky
a year early, is regarded as the slight front-runner and the
most-likely No. 1 pick by the Cleveland Browns. But Smith, a
6-foot-2 1/2-inch, 223-pounder who has what many scouts believe is
the best arm, has been climbing in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday Couch worked out for the Browns for the second time, and
afterward coach Chris Palmer said he was impressed _ but had not
decided between Couch and Smith. ``I would say they're neck and
neck coming down the stretch,'' he told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Even Elway, one of the best quarterbacks of all time, did not
have a smooth journey at the start. The Baltimore Colts picked him
first, but they were so bad that Elway threatened to make baseball
his full-time career unless the Colts traded him, which they did _
to Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The second QB selected in '83 was not Marino, another Hall of
Famer in waiting, but Blackledge, a then highly regarded player
from Penn State whom Kansas City took with the seventh pick.
Blackledge lasted six seasons with the Chiefs and never was a
full-time starter.
</P>
<P>
   Marino was the next-to-last pick of the first round, chosen 27th
by the Dolphins. One of the teams passing up Marino was the
Patriots, who chose Eason out of Illinois with the 15th pick,
rather than the University of Pittsburgh's Marino. (Eason was a big
reason the Patriots made it to the Super Bowl in 1986.)
</P>
<P>
   This year's selections will be just as difficult. Couch?
Culpepper? McNown? McNabb? Smith? Who really knows?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost as if you could take a magician's hat and put the
names in there on slips of paper and pull one out,'' said
first-year Eagles coach Andy Reid. ``They're that close.''
</P>
<P>
   But they do have some different styles. Couch, Culpepper, and to
some extent Smith have more of the classic drop-back style that the
traditionalists revere.
</P>
<P>
   McNabb, coming out of Syracuse's multi-function offense, is more
like former Colorado star Kordell Stewart of the Steelers, a player
some believe is the prototype for the next generation of QBs, more
of an athlete than a pure thrower.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is McNown, who has the quality all coaches like,
which is that he finds ways to win games despite measurements by
the scouts that don't stand out.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone doubts the worth of that, remember a guy named Flutie
out of Boston College? Or the 1990s version of Flutie, Jake
Plummer, who came out of Arizona State and got the Cardinals into
the playoffs last season?
</P>
<P>
   Other factors also must be considered. Take Smith. Despite only
one full year's experience as a starter at Oregon, he is hardly a
kid. He'll be 24 in August and spent three years playing minor
league baseball in the Pirates organization.
</P>
<P>
   Or Culpepper, a ``genetic freak,'' as his Central Florida coach,
Mike Kruczek, calls him. ``At 6-5, 250 pounds, the guy can do a 4.5
40,'' he said. ``You don't see quarterbacks like that.''
</P>
<P>
   As the NFL prepares for a new century, the quarterbacks who will
succeed, say the experts, must be of a different breed than those
of a generation ago. They must have strong arms, quick feet, and
move with the speed and grace of a running back.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, those types of quarterbacks would have been welcomed
in 1983, but with bigger, quicker linebackers and linemen these
days, quarterbacks must be quicker, not bigger, to avoid them.
</P>
<P>
   Culpepper would seem to fit a lot of molds, but he seems to have
been downgraded because of the lack of quality opposition that he
faced the last two years. Either that, or because scouts don't know
how to classify a QB that big and fast.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps those people need to use the ``eye test,'' the way Hall
of Fame Jets QB Joe Namath did one afternoon last fall. ``I just
saw this kid on TV named Daunte Culpepper,'' Namath said on Pete
Rose's nationally syndicated radio talk show. ``He's from the
University of Central Florida and he's the best passer I've seen in
I can't remember how long, expect for maybe Dan Marino.''
</P>
<P>
   Culpepper makes it even simpler. ``I've told all the pro people
I've talked to that if they want someone who is going to help them
win games, they should pick me,'' he said. ``And that's what it's
all about, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately it is about whether the QBs can win, which won't be
known for another four or five years, if not longer.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the evaluation process is more subjective, more open
to debate. When the Class of 1999 holds a five- or 10-year reunion,
chances are only a few of the first tier of QBs will have made a
significant impact, and that someone picked in the third, fourth,
or fifth round will be the reigning star.
</P>
<P>
   What no one seems to be debating is that one way or another the
QB Class of '99 has no shortage of candidates for such roles of
stardom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
