<HEADER>
A4201 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-ANALYSIS-     04-12 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO. 13 NOT LUCKY ENOUGH FOR NORMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Greg Norman was on the 13th hole, a mere stroke
from the lead, some 198 yards from the pin of the par-5 hole.
Norman then took a 4-iron, made his second swing on the hole, and
what ensued ``was one the best shots I've hit in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   This was better than Norman could have scripted. Or worse. The
ball flew directly at the stick, rolling some 20 feet beyond, a
straight downhill putt. Norman struck the ball with his putter. It
was sent perfectly into the center of the cup. The eagle had
landed. Perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   Norman now was in the lead, a stroke to the good of the other
player on the 13th green, Spain's Jose Maria Olazabal. An eagle on
the 13th on Sunday afternoon more often than not is the lethal blow
of the Masters, particularly when it is struck by one of the
players in the last twosome.
</P>
<P>
   Strange.
</P>
<P>
   Norman never smiled when his eagle landed. Not even a hint of a
smile. He tipped his cap to the mad roar, that surge of electricity
that sizzled down in that far corner of Augusta National, but that
was all. Unknown to him, pal Nick Price was on the 18th green when
the red 7 was posted by Norman's name on the scoreboard here, and
Price stopped his task on the green and stood and clapped for
approximately 10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   But the look on Norman's face was almost grim.
</P>
<P>
   More work to do, that look said. Or maybe the look said, ``Oh
no, I'm back here again, with a chance to win the Masters.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman's caddy had walked over to him and said, ``You knew you
were going to make that, didn't you?'' And Norman had agreed. So
confident, so sure, so certain. Followed by that look that said
none of the above.
</P>
<P>
   Norman's moment of glory was precisely that, a moment. He led
the Masters by a stroke, but that lead could be measured in seconds
because that is how long it lasted. Perhaps 60 seconds, or maybe
70, after Norman's eagle, Olazabal stepped up to his ball and made
his birdie putt. Norman and the Spaniard were tied; it was almost
as if the look on Norman's face said it would be too good to last.
</P>
<P>
   When Olazabal made his putt on 13, Norman recalled thinking, ``I
knew the game was on. I never doubted that he would make his. It
was just the way the thing was building up; it was quite
extraordinary.'' Now, a reason for the look. Norman knew.
</P>
<P>
   Norman would have to know, of course. There can be few who read
golf stories who don't know that Norman has been close to winning
the Masters three, four, five, six times and never has. Sometimes
because of the gods. Sometimes because of other golfers. Sometimes
because of himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that I've climbed a pretty good mountain (Sunday),''
Norman would say, after it ended as it always has ended here,
unhappily on the scoreboard. ``Not a molehill, but a mountain. I
feel good about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Masters flew away from Norman almost as quickly as his eagle
flew in. On the 14th, his 7-iron from 153 yards ``landed 8 yards
further than I wanted'' and skidded over the green. Norman chose to
putt from about 15 feet off the green, but there was a rise between
his ball and the hole, and Norman was fearful of going over it too
fast ``and the ball'd be off the green.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little apprehensive there, gunning it down there,''
said Norman. His hesitancy was obvious, his putt was well short,
and he missed the par putt. One stroke was quickly gone, and his
tie for the lead, too. ``But that's probably my first
not-going-through-the-ball stroke that I've made all week, and
that's why I three-putted from the fringe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 15th was not good. Some might choose to place Norman's play
on the 14th and his play on the par-5 15th in the pantheon of his
other Sunday horrors here and they might be right. On his drive,
``I tried to hit a hard smoker, turn it off the (newly planted)
trees (on the right), but I caught it a little bit high on the
driver face, and that's why it didn't turn over.''
</P>
<P>
   When he reached his ball, ``there was some mud on it,'' and he
chose to lay up and not go for the green in 2. But his cautious
approach betrayed him because when he hit his approach from 94
yards out with a sand wedge ``the ball just carried a little bit
right and went into the bunker. I just wasn't meant to make 5
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly when he couldn't hit the green from 94 yards with a
sand wedge. As it was, Olazabal promptly ended matters by parring
the 15th to Norman's bogey, and then making a birdie on the par-3
16th.
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal, a friend of Norman's (each had to overcome physical
woes in the last several years), said Norman ``deserves a green
jacket as much as any other golfer.'' For certain, Norman deserves
plaudits for his sheer courage in getting back to the top of the
leaderboard when that particular leaderboard has toppled over onto
his psyche so many times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel pretty good,'' said the Australian. ``I feel pretty
good within myself to do what I did. Don't take that the wrong way.
I'm still disappointed I didn't win and sad I didn't win.''
</P>
<P>
   He is a newer man since his total collapse to Nick Faldo on
Sunday three years ago, a man who has found balance in his life,
his family, too, and it is not a life strictly of golf and money.
``I'll be honest,'' he said, ``I was more disappointed in '96 than
I am right now. No question about that. Ninety-six was a totally
different animal tournament-wise, person-wise, and result-wise than
this was.''
</P>
<P>
   If he had to put a percentage on his feelings, he said, ``I feel
80 percent success, 20 percent failure. That's the way I feel right
now, whereas back in '96, there was probably 90 percent
disappointment, 99 percent, maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   For sure, he concluded, no matter how his feelings of success
and disappoinment in 1999 compared to 1996, ``There was a heck of a
lot more difference leading up to it (this year).'' This time,
Norman seemed to enjoy his Masters experience, instead of being
tormented by it.
</P>
<P>
   Except, perhaps, for that moment when his eagle putt dropped
into the cup on 13.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
