<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-LAKERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUZZLING SONICS CARVE UP LAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Those still trying to get a solid read on
the Sonics might have better luck solving a Rubik's Cube.
</P>
<P>
   A 5,000-piece puzzle might even be less perplexing than this
team has been this season.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the riddle continued Sunday as the Sonics rolled
over the Los Angeles Lakers 113-109 at the Great Western Forum. How
does a team beat Western Conference powers Houston, Portland and
the Lakers, yet lose to sub-.500 teams such as Denver, Sacramento
and Vancouver in a 10-day span?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can figure out this team let me know,'' Sonics coach
Paul Westphal said. `` ... The good news is if we make the playoffs
we don't have to play Vancouver or Denver. It's just crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Sonics should play all their remaining 14
regular-season games against playoff-caliber teams and on national
television.
</P>
<P>
   As much as this season has been one big accident for the Sonics,
they came up with their strongest showing of the year in front of
the NBC cameras. The Sonics discarded the Lakers with balanced
scoring and energy that lately seems to be reserved for the better
teams.
</P>
<P>
   That at least bodes well for the postseason, with all the
injuries and poor performances the Sonics have endured.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like we can put together a string of victories and get
rolling,'' forward Vin Baker said. `` ... We're going to be very
dangerous (in the postseason). Even with our record, I don't think
teams want to see us in the first round.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics figured to gain steam after beating the NBA-leading
Portland Trail Blazers last Thursday. The victory, though, was
negated the next night when the Sonics suffered an embarrassing
road loss to the lowly Vancouver Grizzlies.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Sonics responded with a season-high point total
while climbing back to the .500 mark. They are 18-18 and moved a
half game in front of Phoenix for the seventh seed in the
conference playoff race _ with the Suns visiting KeyArena
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our record doesn't indicate what type of team we are,''
swingman Dale Ellis said. ``We're getting better and better even
though our loss total is fairly high.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' record hasn't been this bad since the 1991-92
season. However, Ellis could not have been more right Sunday.
Unlike most .500 clubs, the Sonics played the Lakers tough in every
facet of the game.
</P>
<P>
   They were most impressive during crunch time in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   With the game tied 88-88 and 3:41 remaining, the Sonics reeled
off a 10-2 run that Gary Payton finished with a fastbreak dunk. The
team's offense was in high gear, executing and hitting shots to
keep the Lakers at arm's length.
</P>
<P>
   The play that iced the game came with 59.6 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics collected a rebound off a missed free throw. Moments
later, Payton threw a lob pass to Baker for an emphatic dunk that
put the Sonics ahead 102-95.
</P>
<P>
   They made 11 of 14 free throws in the final minute to put away
the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' defense was just as fierce, holding the Lakers to
one field goal for more than five minutes down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like a Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde team. Sometimes we come
to play. Sometimes we don't,'' Payton said. ``I don't know who we
are so we have to keep this consistent. Hopefully guys can keep
playing the way they've been playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal used an eight-man rotation, challenging his top guns to
carry the team. And they did.
</P>
<P>
   Payton finished with 33 points and nine assists, Baker had 27
points and eight rebounds, Hersey Hawkins aggressively pursued a
season-high 20 points and Detlef Schrempf added 14.
</P>
<P>
   Baker the most forceful in his third game back since returning
from injury. He attacked the basket and went right at and around
Lakers center Shaquille O'Neal, who quietly compiled a game-high 38
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the quickest he's been all year,'' Westphal said of
Baker. ``Earlier in the year he wasn't able to make those quick
moves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics were the aggressors most of the game. They led by as
many as 11 points in the second half. They trailed for only 30
seconds in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``On certain possessions and key points of the game, when we
felt we should have gotten to the ball, they beat us to it,'' Laker
guard Kobe Bryant said. ``They were a step quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   A testament to the Sonics' fervor was their work on the glass.
They beat the Lakers, 41-37, on the boards. The Lakers also were
hard-pressed to score easy baskets in transition against the
Sonics' defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realistically, you get a lot more motivated against the
Houstons, Portlands and the Lakers,'' Hawkins said. ``Somehow we've
got to find a way to get up against the Vancouvers.''
</P>
<P>
   The only hairy situation happened before the game, when center
Olden Polynice complained of back spasms on the bus ride to the
arena. But trainer Frank Furtado treated him, and Polynice finished
with eight rebounds while helping to hold O'Neal to 18-for-30
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how tough it gets we have 14 games left and we have
a chance,'' Westphal said. ``Our destiny is in our own hands. I
know they're giving it all they have, and if they keep doing that
good things will happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
