<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4206 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLDRAFT-CULPEPPE     04-12 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAUNTE'S INFERNO: HIS BURNING DESIRE 
</HEADLINE>
 DRAFT-CULPEPPER-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ The wait shouldn't be too long. Maybe an hour on
Saturday afternoon. And then Daunte Culpepper will know.
</P>
<P>
   That's the tough part, the not knowing. Oh, he's gotten some
idea. Maybe he'll go to Philadelphia, maybe Cincinnati, or
Baltimore. Not Cleveland. He's pretty certain of that. Maybe even
New Orleans, or some place he hadn't figured on, because someone in
some ``war room'' got antsy and had to have him on his team.
</P>
<P>
   Culpepper has been wondering for months now as he's flown to
different parts of the country, answering questions, getting
weighed and measured like a piece of prime beef. But he's no
different from Cade McNown, Tim Couch, Akili Smith, Donovan McNabb,
and the rest of the quarterback class of 1999, which is being
called the best in a generation by the draftniks.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it has required nothing more than getting out of bed
in the new house in south Orange County he has rented since January
and meeting some coach for a chalk session of Xs and Os.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Cincinnati Bengals coach Bruce Coslet did a couple
of weeks ago. He flew down to Orlando, sat down with Culpepper and
former Bengals quarterback Ken Anderson, and threw all sorts of
questions at him. What would he do on third and 22 from his 5 with
his protection breaking down? What would he do if he saw a
defensive back slip and fall out of the corner of his eye? Stay
with the play or wing it?
</P>
<P>
   So many questions. So much uncertainty. So many changes, such as
announcing his engagement to longtime girlfriend Kim Rhem in
January, and moving into the new house. Proving himself all over
again, as if he were some untested freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he has wanted to shout, Can't you see what I've done
the past two years? All those touchdowns, and all that yardage?
Can't you see that I was the Most Valuable Player in a postseason
all-star game?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Central Florida wasn't Florida State, and, yes, he screwed
up a few plays in a game against Auburn. He doesn't try to fool
anyone into thinking he is Superman, although at 6 feet 4 inches,
255 pounds, with 4.52 speed in the 40, sometimes people forget
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Genetically, God gave him everything,'' says Central Florida
coach Mike Kruczek, who played at Boston College and for the past
two years has watched Culpepper run his pro-style offense with the
skill and precision of a surgeon. ``He's got size, speed, and
brains. He's got the smarts. He's the prototype of the quarterback
of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Kruczek is obviously biased, but he believes that of the Class
of '99, Culpepper will be the biggest star. ``I don't see anyone
coming out that is better than Daunte,'' Kruczek said. ``McNown,
Couch, McNabb _ I think the upside to Daunte is greater than all of
them. I haven't followed the NFL closely, but I will from now on.''
</P>
<P>
   Culpepper says he has enjoyed the past four months. ``It's a
process I have to go through,'' he said. ``I'm very excited. It's
been a lot of fun, going to different places. It's been a great
ride for me.''
</P>
<P>
   New Philadelphia Eagles coach Andy Reid says he is interested in
Culpepper because of his physical makeup. ``He weighs 250, runs a
4.5 40, and thinks he can beat Michael Jordan in basketball,'' said
Reid with a laugh. ``He's intriguing.''
</P>
<P>
   Culpepper has not made the mistake of publicly expressing where
he wants to go. ``Besides,'' he says, ``I have no idea who really
is interested. Teams are not going to tell you their true
feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that he isn't interested. ``Sure, I want to know,'' he said.
``I'm anxious to start playing football again. That's what I love
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Culpepper's career at Central Florida ended on a bittersweet
note. Despite his marquee value and the Golden Knights' 9-2 record,
they didn't receive a bowl bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very big letdown for myself and the team,'' he said.
``We wanted to go to a bowl. You win nine games and don't go to a
bowl. It was a huge letdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Culpepper says he makes the step to the next level with an air
of confidence. ``I felt I was born to play football at the
professional level,'' he said. ``That's what I'm going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Eagles, Bengals, and Ravens have expressed the most
interest, Culpepper says he has not closed his mind to any
possibility. ``It will be a new system; I have to learn the game
over and prove myself over again,'' he said. ``But that's a
challenge I like. And one that I feel I'm ready to handle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
