<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BOX-OFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE MATRIX' KEEPS GRIP ON TOP SPOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``The Matrix'' continued to dazzle moviegoers as
the science-fiction thriller took in an estimated $22.2 million at
2,903 theaters during Friday-Sunday to dominate the nation's
weekend box office, studio sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Warner Bros.' release, highlighted by eye-popping special
effects amid Keanu Reeves leading a rebellion against computers,
showed solid staying power as it lost only 20 percent of its
audience from its opening weekend to push its 12-day total to $72.9
million. ``The Matrix'' is already the third-highest grosser this
year after ``Analyze This'' with $85.9 million and ``Payback'' with
$79.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``These results are the best we could have hoped for,'' said
studio distribution chief Dan Fellman. `` `The Matrix' has become
America's must-see film. We're attracting all ages and a lot of
repeat business.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said ``The Matrix'' has connected well with its core
audience of male teen-agers and young adults. ``It really hit well
with its target customers,'' said movie analyst Arthur Rockwell.
``That's why it has great legs.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source tracking service,
predicted ``The Matrix'' will draw $140 million by the end of its
run and credited the studio with smart scheduling. ``It turned out
better not being released in the summer, when there's so much
competition,'' he noted. ``Young moviegoers will go to a film any
time of the year if it's what they want to see.''
</P>
<P>
   20th Century Fox's romantic comedy ``Never Been Kissed'' opened
respectably in second with $11.7 million at 2,455 theaters.
``Kissed,'' which stars Drew Barrymore as a reporter infiltrating a
high school, performed in line with expectations and could top $50
million by the end of its run, according the Bucksbaum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it will cross over to the date crowd because it's not
just a kids' movie,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Three holdover comedies bunched together for third, fourth and
fifth place, led by Paramount's second weekend of ``The
Out-of-Towners'' with $5.3 million at 2,105 theaters, followed by
Disney's second weekend of ``10 Things I Hate About You'' with $5.2
million at 2,276 sites and Warner's sixth weekend of ``Analyze
This'' with $5.1 million at 2,351 locations. Disney distribution
executive Chuck Viane, noting ``10 Things' '' overall take of $20.5
million places it close to turning a profit, said, ``We're very
happy with it because it was done for the right price.''
</P>
<P>
   Sony's low-cost ensemble comedy ``Go'' generated a moderate
opening in sixth with $4.7 million at 1,563 theaters. Director Doug
Liman's previous effort, 1996's highly praised ``Swingers,'' posted
total grosses of $4.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks' fourth weekend of Sandra Bullock's ``Forces of
Nature'' finished seventh with $3.7 million at 2,335 theaters to go
past $42 million overall. Miramax's opening of ``Twin Dragons,''
the U.S. debut of one of Jackie Chan's Hong Kong action-adventures,
showed little punch in eighth with $2.7 million at 1,129 sites.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the top 10 were Disney's third weekend of ``Doug's
1st Movie'' with $2.3 million at 2,152 locations and Miramax's 18th
weekend of ``Shakespeare in Love'' with $2.2 million at 1,614
theaters. ``Shakespeare,'' with seven Academy Awards, has totaled
$87.5 million since its December release.
</P>
<P>
   Universal's third weekend of ``EDtv,'' starring Matthew
McConaughey, faded to 11th with $2.1 million at 2,494 theaters, a
steep 52 percent decline from the previous weekend as audiences
continued to ignore strong critical support for the comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows star power is so important at the box office to
distinguish a movie from all the competition,'' Bucksbaum noted.
</P>
<P>
   Artisan's limited opening of ensemble comedy ``Foolish,'' with
Master P and Eddie Griffin cast as brothers, posted impressive
results with $2.2 million at 305 sites.
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks' ``Prince of Egypt'' hit the $100 million milestone
over the weekend with $362,000 at 644 theaters, becoming the 182nd
movie to top that mark. A record-setting total of 16 films released
in 1998 grossed more than $100 million, led by DreamWorks' ``Saving
Private Ryan'' with $214 million.
</P>
<P>
   Overall grosses hit about $81 million, down about 6 percent from
the same weekend a year ago. Year-to-date grosses have hit $1.5
billion and trail 1998's by about 8 percent due mostly to the
blockbuster numbers generated last year by ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   The weekend started with the AMC chain raising top prices at
several top-grossing megaplexes to $8.50.
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell said the move may backfire despite the expected surge
in business next month for ``Star Wars Episode 1: The Phantom
Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They may have hit a point where demand could start to fall
off,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Matrix'' will receive a challenge next weekend from
Universal's opening of Eddie Murphy's prison comedy ``Life.'' Also
opening will be Warner's thriller ``Goodbye Lover'' with Patrica
Arquette.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
