<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIVER-LISTING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNAKE, CEDAR RIVERS INCLUDED ON GROUP'S ENDANGERED LISTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HEATH FOSTER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Two majestic _ and politically embroiled _ Washington
rivers are among the 10 most-endangered in the nation, a national
environmental group says.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to force the removal of four dams on the lower
Snake River that have decimated salmon and steelhead runs, American
Rivers on Monday will name the Eastern Washington tributary as the
No. 1 river facing ``severe environmental degradation.''
</P>
<P>
   And in an unexpected attempt to influence the city of Seattle's
final deliberations over how much of the Cedar River's water should
be set aside for struggling fish, the group added that King County
river to its high-profile endangered list for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   American Rivers' annual list is a reflection of the strategic
priorities of the environmental group rather than a true measure of
pollution in the nation's rivers.
</P>
<P>
   The Cedar River supports the largest sockeye run in the
continental United States and is one of the six municipal water
supplies in the nation so clean it requires no filtering, said
George Schneider, the water resource manager for the Seattle Public
Utilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not rivers that are cesspools,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the list puts public pressure on government
agencies that must weigh the needs of the environment against those
of people.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Snake River, federal agencies will decide
soon whether to side with an emerging scientific consensus that
breaching the Snake dams offers the best chance of bringing back
endangered fish runs. Their views have caused panic among
dam-dependent Eastern Washington farmers, and U.S. Sen. Slade
Gorton, R-Wash., has made opposition to breaching a central issue
in his re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to list the Cedar is a surprise attack on Seattle
Mayor Paul Schell's proposed management and habitat conservation
plan for the river's pristine, 90,546-acre watershed.
</P>
<P>
   The forested valley reaching high in the Cascade Range is all
city-owned, and the city provides water to 1.3 million people in
Seattle and 28 suburbs _ nearly one in four Washington residents.
About two-thirds of that water comes from the Cedar.
</P>
<P>
   The habitat conservation plan the city hopes to sign with the
federal government will allow the city to continue to take water at
its 99-year- old dam while protecting endangered species such as
Puget Sound chinook salmon. If approved, it would shield the
watershed's operation from regulations stemming from the Endangered
Species Act. The city's final proposal is due in May.
</P>
<P>
   Some environmental elements of the plan have been widely
applauded. They include a proposal to end logging in the watershed,
to restore habitat and to create a fish ladder allowing salmon to
spawn above Landsburg Dam for the first time since 1909.
</P>
<P>
   But because the agreement will last 50 years, environmentalists,
King County, the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers and the Muckelshoot
Tribe are fighting to ensure it also offers fish the water they'll
need to rebound.
</P>
<P>
   They are calling for a moratorium on further withdrawals from
the Cedar pending studies on how much water chinook salmon need.
</P>
<P>
   Katherine Ransel, of American Rivers' Northwest office, said the
current plan allows the city to more than double water withdrawals
for the expanding suburbs without providing for fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``This plan allows for unbridled growth,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Holly Coccoli, a fish biologist for the Muckleshoot Indian tribe
who has studied the Cedar for nearly a decade, said the river can't
serve many more people and stay healthy for fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city of Seattle is already serving about a million people
from the Cedar River, and that is a lot of people for such a small,
short river,'' she said. ``Maybe it's time for us to say we have
altered this river enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Fueling the controversy is the fact that it's hard to pin city
officials down on exactly what their intentions are for the river's
excess water.
</P>
<P>
   The Cedar produces about 550 million gallons of water a day.
Seattle Public Utilities says that an 1888 claim allows the city to
use 300 million gallons, but in the past 40 years it has taken only
about a third as much as it could. Because of conservation
measures, withdrawals from the Cedar have not increased over the
past decade.
</P>
<P>
   In its draft plan, the city proposes leaving a minimum of 45
percent of the river's natural flow, or 250 million gallons per
day, in the river for fish. City biologists say that is ample for
fish recovery, and is well above the guaranteed flow the state
Department of Ecology set in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves about 183 million unallocated gallons per day for
city use.
</P>
<P>
   Schell aide Lisa Fitzhugh said it would be foolish for the city
to agree now to never use any of that water. Until the region
develops alternate water supplies, the city has a responsibility to
help growing communities that face water shortages, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feds agree this (habitat conservation plan) is a great,
scientifically-based, supportable plan for fish,'' she said. ``And
Seattle wants to keep its flexibility to supply water for people
because future supplies haven't come on line yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle is expected to grow by about 114,000 people to a
population of 650,000 in 2020, and King County will grow by 26
percent, from 1.65 million residents in 1997 to 2.1 million in
2020.
</P>
<P>
   Schneider, the city water resource manager, said if Seattle
agrees to a water cap, it would close off such options.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't intend to support the future growth of the region on
the back of Cedar River, but we want to have the advantage of using
unallocated water where it makes sense for people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups say that before the city embarks on such a
plan, it should require suburbs to conserve more.
</P>
<P>
   But Fitzhugh said the city can't refuse water to the suburbs if
they don't conserve. Such preaching could cause the suburban cities
to refuse to partner with the city on other problems, such as
housing the homeless, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups insist the city should study what the
chinook salmon need before they agree to shifting Cedar River water
to other rivers, or sign the conservation plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 0057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
