</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BULLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS HOLD ON FOR VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Five days ago they had a meeting. They were not there
to talk about a crisis. It was a meeting to talk about winning.
Antoine Walker remembers the key moment in that Celtics session.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, we had 17 games remaining in the season,'' Walker
said Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, ``and I think it was (associate head coach) Jim
O'Brien who said, `Let's go 12-5.' Since that time, we're 3-1.''
</P>
<P>
   Win No. 3 since The Meeting came Sunday &UR;  &LR; night at the
FleetCenter, 87-81, against the Bulls. O'Brien didn't mention
anything about artistry when he made his 12-5 statement. He just
wanted the players to ease up a little on the Lottery accelerator,
because they seemed to be flooring it toward the inevitable May
trip to Secaucus, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The 17,169 people in the arena can tell you that Sunday &UR;  &LR; night's
win wasn't memorable, but it was obviously better than the
alternative. In their shortened season, the 13-23 Celtics haven't
had many good things happen to them, so it was appropriate that the
shot that secured the game for them was, well, a little awkward.
</P>
<P>
   Vitaly Potapenko, a 285-pound center not known for his
long-range jump shot, was standing 21 feet from the basket with the
shot clock heading toward zero. The Celtics held an 83-80 lead, and
the game clock was moving toward 14 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard the guys yelling, `Shoot it,' '' Potapenko said. So
the center, who finished with 8 points, fired a desperation fling
at the hoop. It went in. It was 85-80 and, unofficially, the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about that?'' said Walker, who had 23 points and 11
rebounds. ``We need to have some luck around here. It's about time
we got some luck, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Potapenko joked that the play was designed for him because ``the
coaches know I'm such a good jump-shooter.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Celtics were able to laugh about the game when it was
over, they didn't have much room for fun when it was unfolding (and
unfolding very slowly). The biggest contradiction came in the first
half. The Celtics made 52 percent of their shots, the Bulls made
only 34, so the score was . . . tied at 37?
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason for that is that we turned the ball over so much
early,'' said Walter McCarty, referring to Chicago's 13-3 turnover
advantage in the first 24 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting 52 percent and not having a lead to show for it is
uncommon in the NBA. That statistical quirk, as well as the score,
made Bulls coach Tim Floyd happy. After the game, the first-year
coach said something that should make score-happy fans cringe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like it was going to have to be a game in the low 70s
or high 60s for us to have a shot,'' he said. ``We don't have a lot
of weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   The two weapons they had were Toni Kukoc (23 points) and Ron
Harper (19). Take away their contributions and you have 7-of-30
shooting from Chicago starters. Still, that was enough to keep the
Bulls within 7 points the entire night. They trailed, 66-61,
entering the fourth quarter. They were able to close the deficit to
76-75 on a Harper 3-pointer with 6:43 left. But two minutes later,
Walker answered with a 3-pointer of his own.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the Celtics couldn't increase their lead to more
than 4 until Potapenko's shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good win for us,'' Celtics coach Rick Pitino said.
Before saying that, Pitino surprised many people when he began his
postgame press conference with a barrage of coachspeak. He was not
happy with his team's post defense or containment. ``We shot well,
ran the offense well, and played good defense _ with the exception
of ball containment.''
</P>
<P>
   The team got plenty of work from its backcourt. Ron Mercer and
Dana Barros played 45 and 44 minutes. Mercer added 18 points and 6
rebounds; Barros had 10 points, 12 assists, and 2 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Although Walker would say later that a win over the 10-27 Bulls
didn't ``tickle my fancy,'' it still allowed him to have a better
performance against the team from his hometown. The last time he
saw them, Harper was giving him the choke sign and fans were booing
his 2-of-15 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Neither happened Sunday &UR;  &LR; night. Harper was blowing verbal kisses
afterward and most fans left happy. And O'Brien left the building
knowing that the team is a win closer to reaching the number he
challenged it to get five days ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
