<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOX SCORE CONSTRUCTED BRICK BY BRICK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Ron Harper was sure of one thing Sunday &UR;  &LR; night. He's
going to be hearing from his buddy, Michael Jordan, sometime real
soon. He's also sure that he's going to be getting the call, not
making it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't calling him,'' Harper said. ``You know, one of his
famous quotes was that he could probably do it all himself. Well I
can hear him say that: `Forty-nine points? I could get that
myself.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan did get 49 points all by himself quite a bit. He scored
49 or more points 50 times in his career. There were many nights
when his supporting cast would score 49 points and no one noticed.
This time, the world dropped its collective jaw because the
supporting cast is now the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls played the Celtics Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, a mere 24 hours
removed from one of the most mortifying performances in NBA
history. They lost, at home, to Miami by the still unthinkable
score of 82-49. It was the fewest points scored since the
introduction of the shot clock 44 years ago. Upon seeing the
result, Princeton called to see if the Bulls wanted its game tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's output increased dramatically against the Celtics _
how could it not? _ but the Bulls still lost, 87-81, their 27th
loss in 37 games. They're on a pace to lose more games in this
shortened season than the previous two Chicago teams lost in full
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   In an almost diabolical twist, the Bulls' next game is Tuesday
night in Miami. In this year of Chicago payback, no one in the East
will enjoy exacting revenge more than Pat Riley. His Heat twice got
the playoff boot from Michael &AMP; Co. and he can pass Red Auerbach
and move into third place for all-time coaching wins with 939.
(Lenny Wilkens and Bill Fitch are 1-2.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to show them we're not the same team we were
(Saturday),'' said the Bulls' Randy Brown. That shouldn't be too
hard.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting has been the Bulls' undoing all year. They are one of
two teams _ the Nets are the other _ shooting less than 40 percent
(39 percent). Against Miami on Saturday night, in fashioning
quarters of 8, 15, 10, and 16 points, the Bulls shot a spiffy 23
percent. Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, they shot 39 percent, which, in their
world, is the norm.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (Miami) game was definitely in the back of our minds,''
said Brown, who was 2 for 12 from the field. ``We didn't want to
fall behind in a hurry and then have everyone thinking, `Here we go
again.' ''
</P>
<P>
   They actually led after one, were tied at the half, and were
within 3 in the 48th minute. We could suggest that having played
the night before might have taken its toll, but how could that be
an excuse when you score 49 points?
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty-nine points,'' Celtics coach Rick Pitino said in
disbelief. ``We had 67 (on Friday) and I couldn't fathom that. . .
. That's unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls passed 49 on a Cory Carr jumper with 6:36 left in the
third quarter. Chicago felt the game had to be in the ``low 70s or
high 60s'' for it to have a chance. Honest. That's what Tim Floyd,
the Bulls' coach, said afterwards. He was serious. He was talking
about his offense, not what Greg Norman needed Sunday to win.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bulls were concerned about going into the NBA Record Book
in such a wretched manner, they didn't show it before or after.
Toni Kukoc was watching the Masters with rapt attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stuff happens,'' Bill Wennington said, although he didn't say
the word ``stuff.'' ``Sometimes you step over it. Sometimes you
step in it.'' He said he hadn't bothered to read any stories of the
game. ``I did a lot better at not reading the papers than I did in
shooting the basketball,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harper addressed how horrible the play has been this season. The
reasons are many: overzealous coaches, poor shooters, clueless
players, diluted talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ugly basketball being played out there,'' he said. ``Some
days, you turn on the TV and you see some ugly games. But I'm not
embarrassed. We played hard. We just didn't make any shots.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Floyd's take as well. He liked the effort. He just
didn't like the shot selection. And typical of the coaching mindset
these days, he said the 49-point game was not nearly as
disconcerting as the game 10 days earlier against Orlando when the
Bulls _ are you sitting down? _ allowed 115 points.
</P>
<P>
   The coach liked what he saw Sunday &UR;  &LR; night a lot more than the
night before. But it was another loss. Harper's still going to have
some explaining to do when M.J. rings him up. No one has to remind
Harper of what he doesn't have anymore, least of all the one who
made it thus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
