<HEADLINE>
BURNS WON'T LET BRUINS REST ON LAURELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Bruins were breathing a collective sigh of relief
Sunday while enjoying a much needed day of rest. The club just
finished playing six games in 10 days to start the month and earned
10 of a possible 12 points, securing a playoff spot in the midst of
that run.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it will have a few days to nurse a variety of injuries
before ending the season with three games in four days against
contending clubs _ Pittsburgh, Buffalo, and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL standings continue to run through the Mixmaster on a
daily basis, and Boston could finish anywhere from fifth place in
the Eastern Conference to eighth. Coach Pat Burns continues to
stress that he doesn't care who the team's first-round opponent is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care where we finish, it doesn't bother me,'' Burns
said. ``What bothers me is how we're going to play going into the
playoffs. I don't care where we finish, I just want to make sure
we're on our game when we go in. If you start picking your spots
and who you want to play, you're in deep trouble. Let's just go in
there and be playing well, because you're going to have to play the
good teams anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said he doesn't want his players to gain any false sense
of security. If the teams sit out stars in an effort to give them
some rest before the postseason, which Burns has talked about
doing, he doesn't want his players to get the wrong idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played a lot of games in a lot of nights in the last run
and now we have three days to prepare for those games that are
coming up,'' he said. ``These are teams that are probably a little
bit better. I just hope they don't decide to rest players, too, and
the games become something of a psychological thing where if we do
beat a team easily, we think that's how it's going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Not much has been easy for the Bruins this year. They started
out by missing players because of holdouts and then had to scramble
the lineup because of injuries to key personnel that kept players
out for long periods. Back in late January and into early February,
the Bruins had the potential to sink like a stone. The bottoming
out came in a 5-4 loss to the Islanders at home Feb. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the team has racked up a 17-8-5 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made up some big ground,'' said center Tim Taylor, who was
outspoken about his club's woes during that rough stretch when the
Rangers and Florida had the Bruins' postseason hopes in peril.
``Obviously, we're very positive with the way things are going now.
We're ready. We're keen to play, we're excited to play. At that
time, I just think collectively we weren't playing well together
and not as a team. Some individuals were playing well, some
weren't. On any given night, some guys were going well and some
guys weren't. We'd make one or two mistakes and the puck would be
in our net.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns has his players back to executing the system that was
largely responsible for the remarkable improvement of last year,
which was 30 points better than the season before. Taylor said the
fact they now are embracing that again has accounted for how
they're playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've turned that around and gotten back to our system of last
year,'' he said. ``Everyone plays the same and performs the same
function out there and we know what's going on and we're playing as
a team. We all know the better the team does, the better everyone
else is going to do and not just for this year, for years to
come.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were grateful to get rid of Tampa Bay, which they
played twice in a three-day span. Both contests were stinkers,
although Boston won one. But everyone agreed this mini-break could
not have come at a more perfect time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel it's good for us; we've gone through a big stretch,''
said Taylor. ``It's always nice to have a break when you win a game
and (we've) only lost two in our last 13. We'd be kind of tired and
disgusted with ourselves if it had gone the other way and we had
two wins in our last 13 games. It is a good time for us. A lot of
guys have bumps and bruises. Through this dogfight of eight months,
it's really catching up to us. Now, we'll get this little break to
refresh ourselves for this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Tallas played in goal the last two games, giving Byron Dafoe
a break. It's likely Dafoe will play all three of the remaining
contests to tune up for the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said the Bruins all will benefit from the extra few days
before they finish up the stretch that begins Thursday night at
home against the Penguins. An afternoon game against the Sabres
follows on Saturday, and they close the regular season with the
Flyers in Philadelphia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
