<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELCHER HIT HARD AGAIN IN LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Angels pitcher Tim Belcher took one look at
teammate Omar Olivares and proclaimed: ``It's your fault!'' for the
beating the Texas Rangers laid on Belcher and the Angels on Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher, who was only half-kidding, got hammered for five runs
and 11 hits in three-plus innings in the Rangers' 6-3 victory
before 23,175 at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   It came only one night after Olivares threw 71/3 scoreless
innings against the same big-hitting Rangers lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Omar had them so frustrated so much last night,'' Belcher
(0-1) said. ``Then they get somebody with not quite the same
movement on the ball, they're going to come out hacking, and that's
what they did.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers certainly came out swinging in the first inning,
when Tom Goodwin and Mark McLemore opened with back-to-back
triples. By the time the inning was finished, the Rangers had five
hits and a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   With the way Rangers starter Aaron Sele is throwing, the Angels
were in for a long night. Sele gave up three runs in 52/3 innings,
but only one run was earned, coming on Troy Glaus' second homer of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Sele (2-0), who threw seven scoreless innings against the Tigers
in his first start, struck out 10 and lowered his ERA to 0.71. But
it should not come as a surprise. In seven career April starts as a
Ranger, Sele is 7-0. Overall in his career, Sele is 15-3 in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the best I've seen him throw,'' said Angels right
fielder Tim Salmon, who went 0 for 4. ``When he's got a curveball
like that and he's throwing it for strikes, he's tough. It's got
such a big break it goes out of your normal line of sight. And he
throws it enough, you've got to respect it, making his fastball
that much better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if you can throw the curveball any better than he
did tonight,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said. ``He threw it in
the strike zone, out of the strike zone and had a quality fastball
and slider.''
</P>
<P>
   As good as Sele has been in his first two starts, Belcher has
been bad. Belcher gave up five runs in 41/3 innings against the
Indians on opening night. And with his performance Sunday, his ERA
actually went up from 10.38 to 12.27. Belcher, though, shrugged it
off. He said control has been his biggest problem, but it's not
something he can't work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I got my (rear) kicked,'' he said. ``It's happened
before and I'm sure it'll happen again. They were far better
hitters than I was a pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason to be concerned other than having a bruised
ego. It's not fun. The middle of the diamond is a lonely place when
hits are flying all over the place. But if I've learned one thing
in my career, sometimes you push the panic button too quickly and
start changing things. If I've learned one thing, it is not to do
that. Two bad outings is not going to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't exactly the type of performance the Angels wanted to
have, especially considering it was a nationally televised game and
against the defending AL West champions. Angels left fielder
Orlando Palmeiro had an embarrassing moment, dropping a routine pop
fly to shallow left hit by Ivan Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those nights,'' Angels manager Terry Collins
said. ``It wasn't a very pretty game.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with Glaus (2 for 4) the only other bright spot for the
Angels was the performance of reliever Al Levine. Levine, released
by the Rangers at the end of spring training, gave up only one
unearned run in four innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas bullpen, though, was just as good. Tim Crabtree threw
21/3 scoreless innings and John Wetteland threw a scoreless ninth
for his second save.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
