<HEADLINE>
MARINER ROMP HELPS NEW SHORTSTOP FIND COMFORT ZONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ For Giomar Guevara, redemption came quickly Sunday and
in the typical Mariner fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Guevara is the fifth Mariner to spin through the shortstop
turnstile in the season's first six games. He was promoted from
Class AAA Tacoma Sunday to replace Carlos Guillen, who will miss
the rest of the season after tearing the anterior cruciate ligament
in his right knee Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the second play of the first inning, Guevara charged a ground
ball and threw wildly for an error. On the second play of the
second inning, he did the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the third inning, he forgot about his defensive
troubles the way the Mariners usually do _ by helping out the
high-powered offense. Guevara hit a run-scoring double, part of an
eight-run third that sent Seattle to an 11-8 win over the Oakland
Athletics at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Guevara's hit was the sixth of seven in a row for the Mariners,
tying a 17-year-old club record. But any joy a victory brought was
tempered by the sting of losing Guillen, who went down just days
after shortstop Alex Rodriguez's knee injury, which will keep him
from the lineup 4-6 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard people say things happen in threes,'' said Mariners
starter Jamie Moyer, who allowed five runs in 62/3 innings but
earned his first win of the year. ``Geez, not to be the bearer of
bad news, but I seriously hope that third thing doesn't happen to
anybody on this ballclub. It's very unfortunate, but you deal with
it and move forward with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners will move forward with Guevara and newly signed
veteran Domingo Cedeno at shortstop, and David Bell remaining at
second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure everybody in this clubhouse feels bad for Alex and
especially for Carlos, but when the game starts you've got to go
out and try to win,'' Bell said. ``And you've got to feel like
we're good enough to win. If you don't, you're going to be in
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Home runs from Edgar Martinez, Russ Davis and John Mabry, and
hits from everybody in the lineup by the third inning, showed the
Mariners offense should survive. Pitching and defense? Going off
Sunday, there is work to be done.
</P>
<P>
   Guevara said he dropped his elbow on the wild throws, and while
the 26-year-old is considered a strong defensive player with a good
arm, the angles of his throws could give him problems.
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen should get a boost in about a week, when veteran
Mark Leiter is expected to be ready to come off the disabled list.
Leiter played catch Sunday and felt no pain, and manager Lou
Piniella is looking forward to having him back to share set-up
duties with Jose Paniagua.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the Mariner bullpen has allowed 14 earned runs in
182/3 innings for a 6.75 earned run average.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer left Sunday's outing with a runner on second, two outs and
a 10-4 lead. Brett Hinchliffe walked John Jaha and allowed a
run-scoring single to Eric Chavez before getting out of the inning
on a slick play by first baseman David Segui.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, Hinchliffe left with a run in and a man on
second, and Paniagua allowed a run-scoring single and ground out
before escaping. Consecutive doubles greeted John Halama in the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella's other ninth-inning option, Jose Mesa, surrendered
four runs in one inning on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't walk people in late-inning situations, and you can't
fall behind hitters consistently,'' Piniella said. ``You've got the
lead, make the other team beat you with the bat. You start walking
people and the ump starts squeezing you, you're pitching behind in
the count and you've got to lay the ball in there.''
</P>
<P>
   SUZUKI MEETING: Piniella met with reliever Mac Suzuki, who was
cited for drunk driving after a hit-and-run accident early Friday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something he should learn from,'' Piniella said. ``It's
part of the maturing process of a young man. ... It's something
that shouldn't happen, but it can happen to anybody. Nobody got
hurt. It's an experience that shouldn't repeat itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki, who was visited in the clubhouse Sunday morning by an
official from major league baseball, would not discuss the
incident. He pleaded not guilty in King County District Court
Saturday and was released on $1,500 bail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 0110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
