<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLAZABAL SAVORS UPHILL WALK TO SECOND MASTERS TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ It might not have been a compelling conclusion to
a golf tournament that is supposed to yield dramatic shots in
majestic surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   For Jose Maria Olazabal, the Masters was special nonetheless.
The 33-year-old Spaniard won his second green jacket, fending off
the charges of Davis Love III and Greg Norman Sunday at Augusta
National.
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal shot a 1-under-par 71 to finish at 8-under. Love also
had a 71 and was two strokes behind. Norman, the sentimental
favorite, led briefly after an eagle at the 13th hole but finished
third at 5-under.
</P>
<P>
   Between September 1995 and February '96, Olazabal did not play
golf. He could barely walk, suffering from a lower back hernia.
</P>
<P>
   For the longest time, he just wanted to walk again. Golf was not
a priority then. So this leap from his couch in Spain to victory
stand at Augusta was a moving development that caught up to
Olazabal afterward.
</P>
<P>
   He could barely keep from crying as he walked up the 18th
fairway, acknowledging the applause with Norman. Then the tears
came in the media room when someone asked him what he will do as
soon as he gets home.
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal paused, held his head in his hands before finally
replying: ``I will embrace my family, for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Patience and perseverance paid off for Olazabal when he couldn't
walk, and they served him during Sunday's round as well.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived at the course, Olazabal was nervous. He couldn't
eat or drink.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't swallow, not even water,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As he waited for his 3 p.m. tee time, Olazabal realized that if
he was going to win, it would be in a breeze _ many of them,
gusting every which way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult on this golf course to judge the intensity
of the wind, the direction of the wind, what the ball's going to do
when it gets up in the air,'' he said. ``I knew the scoring was not
going to be low. If anybody was scoring really low, he must play,
you know, like angels.''
</P>
<P>
   Heaven-sent, Olazabal was not. He appeared down and out on the
front side, bogeying Nos. 3-5.
</P>
<P>
   At the par-3 4th, he was fortunate to escape with a four, taking
two blasts to emerge from a trap. After his bogey at 5, Olazabal
had slipped to 4-under, bringing a crowd back into the hunt. He
righted himself at the par-3 6th, hitting a 6-iron within nine feet
and sinking the birdie putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``That got me going again,'' Olazabal said.
</P>
<P>
   On the back side, the gallery was goading Norman but courteously
supporting Olazabal. At 13, Olazabal doused a seemingly pivotal
hole for Norman, retaining the momentum as well as a share of the
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Norman hit a 200-yard 4-iron approach, leaving himself a
25-footer for eagle. Olazabal laid up and faced a 25-foot birdie
butt. Norman got his eagle, but Olazabal followed it in, and the
two leaders headed to the 14th tee at 7-under-par.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as he hit it, it looked to me like it was going in all
the way,'' Olazabal said. ``And while that ball was rolling, I was
saying to myself, just try to make yours because I didn't want to
go one stroke behind. Making that putt was an important boost.'
</P>
<P>
   Norman relinquished his share of the lead with bogeys at 14 and
15. The bogey at 15 was particularly curious given the
circumstances. Norman faced a 94-yard shot to the hole with plenty
of green to work with and slapped it into a bunker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some mud on my ball,'' Norman said. ``I just tried to
squeeze the sand wedge out. And when I squeezed it out there, the
ball just carried a little right.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman blasted out but missed his par putt, the ball lipping the
cup and making a right turn. The green was completely in the
shadows, and Olazabal was about to leave Norman in the dark and in
the dust.
</P>
<P>
   That left Olazabal with a two-shot lead over Norman and one-shot
lead over Love, who had just chipped in for birdie at the 16th to
move to 6-under.
</P>
<P>
   As he stood on the 16th tee, Olazabal took an excessive amount
of time sizing up the situation, studying the wind, wondering what
to hit. He finally chose a 6-iron to execute a 170-yard shot. It
landed 3 feet from the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a wonderful shot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So was the next stroke, a delicate one that amazed Olazabal as
he performed in a crowded theater so quiet you could hear a putt
drop.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't imagine what a 3-footer that was,'' he said. ``Down
the hill, lightning quick, left to right. I don't know how the hell
I made that putt.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman tried to respond, hitting his approach within five feet,
but he missed his birdie putt, blood seeping from the Shark at
Augusta again.
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal wrapped it up with a par-saving 7-foot putt on the
hardpan 17th green, keeping his two-stroke lead over Love with one
hole to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I die for a 4 on that hole,'' said Olazabal, who did not have
a three-putt during the entire tournament. ``And when I got that 4,
I knew the jacket should be mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Routinely, Olazabal got his par on the 18th, appropriately
ending the tournament with an uphill battle on a hole that rises
toward the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult for me to express how I feel at this
particular moment, especially after what I went through,'' Olazabal
said. ``I'm very proud of myself. I'm a really happy man. It's an
achievement that I didn't even dream about when I was low.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
