</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RANCH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOYS RANCH TRIAL DECISION AT HAND: 5 EX-WORKERS FIGHT MURDER
COUNT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DENNIS WAGNER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Five former employees of Arizona Boys Ranch face a
crucial hurdle this week in their battle against charges that they
killed a 16-year-old client at the home for delinquents in March
1998.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants will appear Tuesday in Pinal County Superior
Court for a preliminary hearing, where Judge Richard Fields is
expected to decide whether there is probable cause for a trial.
</P>
<P>
   Although most preliminary hearings are perfunctory events,
defense lawyers said they intend to use the forum as a three-day
minitrial in this case. And it will be preceded with a hot dispute
over motions seeking to dismiss the charges entirely.
</P>
<P>
   The five defendants _ Linda Babb, Geoffrey S. Lewis, Montgomery
Hoover, Michael M. Moreno and Troy M. Jones _ face counts of
first-degree murder and child abuse in the case of Nicholas
Contreraz, a Sacramento youth who died of lung infections after
days of punishment and taunting at a boot camp in Oracle.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys reacted angrily last month when the Pinal
County Attorney's Office replaced a manslaughter indictment with
the first-degree murder counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened to Mr. Contreraz is a tragedy,'' said Ed Novak,
co-counsel for Hoover. ``Everyone regrets his death. But no one is
at fault with respect to his death.''
</P>
<P>
   After an initial indictment was withdrawn, Pinal County
prosecutor Janna Vanderpool filed new charges last month. Defense
lawyers were stunned when she elevated the case to first-degree
murder and added a provision for ``dangerous crimes against
children'' _ an aggravating circumstance that would drastically
magnify penalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just off the wall,'' said Stephen M. Weiss, counsel to
Babb, a Boys Ranch nurse who reportedly labeled Contreraz a
malingerer and failed to detect his illness after a bout of
vomiting and diarrhea. ``They (prosecutors) are just trying to
squeeze us.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanderpool declined interview requests. Charles Ratliff, a
spokesman at her office, said: ``We're going to let the preliminary
hearing speak for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, defense lawyers have filed a rash of motions seeking
dismissal of the charges. Among their claims:
</P>
<P>
   _The case should be thrown out because prosecutors have not
identified specific acts as a basis for the criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   _The first-degree murder complaint was motivated by
prosecutorial vindictiveness. Defense attorneys claim that
Vanderpool ``upped the ante'' in retaliation for their successful
move to squelch the manslaughter indictment because of grand jury
bias.
</P>
<P>
   _The ``dangerous crimes against children'' allegations should be
dropped because Arizona statutes say that is valid only when the
victim is younger than 15; Contreraz was 16.
</P>
<P>
   _The whole case should be dismissed because Vanderpool filed the
criminal complaint with Pinal County Superior Court Judge Gilbert
Figueroa, who had been recused. Defense lawyers used legal
``strikes'' to recuse four Pinal County judges available for the
case. As a result, it was transferred to Fields, a Pima County
Superior Court judge.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary hearings, which allow hearsay evidence, are held to
determine whether there is probable cause to bind defendants over
for trial. Most such proceedings are perfunctory _ uncontested by
defense attorneys who save their arguments and strategy for trial.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Vanderpool is expected to use testimony from a
criminal investigator, a coroner and a medical expert to establish
probable cause. Defense attorneys, in turn, plan to grill those
witnesses in an effort to show that their clients were not
responsible for Contreraz's death, and did not abuse the boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one is far from perfunctory,'' said Mike Piccarreta, an
attorney for Jones. ``I'm sure we're prepared to do anything to
pull the plug on the prosecution.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers condemned the prosecution for filing
first-degree murder counts. They also blasted Vanderpool for
listing the child abuse allegations as dangerous crimes against
children _ an aggravating factor that, if upheld, would result in
mandatory prison sentences of 17 years or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theoretically, the death penalty is available,'' Piccarreta
said. ``This is hardball.''
</P>
<P>
   The death of Contreraz set off a chain reaction of woes not only
for the youth's family, but for Boys Ranch and its employees.
</P>
<P>
   California, which supplied most of the youth placements,
withdrew all of its boys and issued a scathing report on
mistreatment of juveniles. The Arizona Department of Economic
Security conducted an exhaustive investigation documenting abuse or
neglect on the part of 17 ranch employees.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a DES threat to withhold an operating permit, Boys Ranch
agreed to a settlement with the state that calls for a major
overhaul of programs, policies and operations.
</P>
<P>
   The ranch, known for its tough, hands-on rehabilitation methods,
closed all but one of six campuses. Most employees were laid off.
Bob Thomas, longtime president, was replaced.
</P>
<P>
   The client population has dropped to 40 from 600, leaving Boys
Ranch with virtually no revenue. The non-profit organization,
nearly a half-century old, is struggling to survive and rebuild. &QL; 
Dennis Wagner can be reached at (602) 444-8874 or at
dennis.wagner(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
