<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS SHUT OUT COYOTES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- If Sunday evening's game was any indication, the
Phoenix Coyotes and Mighty Ducks are fully prepared to rumble if
the two teams meet in the first round of the Stanley Cup playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks took a big step towards making that a reality with a
3-0 before 17,174 at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   It was game filled with playoff-type intensity, one that ended
on a wild note thanks to Phoenix's volatile captain Keith Tkachuk.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk threw his stick at Teemu Selanne, who was about to score
his league-leading 46th goal into an empty net in the final minute
of play, bowled the winger over after he had released the shot and
then leveled Kevin Haller. That led to a full-fledged brawl,
highlighted by a fight between Jaime Pushor and Rick Tocchet.
</P>
<P>
   For his efforts, Tkachuk picked 22 minutes in penalties.
</P>
<P>
   But the Ducks, who desperately needed to get back on track after
going 0-3-1 in their previous four games, weren't about to make a
big deal of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just part of the game,'' said Haller. ``Guys get
frustrated when they lose a close game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we win, it doesn't matter what they do to us,''
said Ruslan Salei, who had been a target of the Coyotes all season.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks (35-32-12) improved to 3-1-2 versus Phoenix and moved
back into fifth place, one point ahead of St. Louis. They also
prevented the Coyotes from clinching fourth place in the Western
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   It was all thanks to an emotional, hard-working effort, the type
that has been missing in action since the team clinched a playoff
spot.
</P>
<P>
   The added effort paid big dividends in the Phoenix end of the
ice. In the first period Paul Kariya forced a turnover along the
right wing boards, cut to the right circle and beat Nikolai
Khabibulin with a brilliant wrist shot high over the Phoenix
goalie's glove at 3:21. It was Kariya's 37th goal of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a great play by Paul,'' said Anaheim coach Craig
Hartsburg. ``There aren't many guys who can make that shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams squandered power play chance after power play chance.
Phoenix's 26th ranked power play unit was unsurprising 0-for-6. But
Anaheim's top-ranked unit was 0-for-7 and didn't manage a shot on
goal until its fifth opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   But the Ducks forechecked their way to a two-goal advantage
midway through the third period. Anaheim's unsung duo of Jim
McKenzie and Jeff Nielsen kept the puck alive behind the Phoenix
net and converted that pressure into a 2-0 lead at 11:52.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mac makes a Wayne Gretzky-like pass,'' said Nielsen, who cut
across the slot and beat Khabibulin high on the glove side for his
fifth goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was great team goal,'' said Hartsburg. ``That line (which
also includes Ted Drury) was good all night and it's good to see
them get rewarded.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix outshot Aanheim 40-31, but Guy Hebert managed to record
his club-record sixth shutout of the season. Tkachuk did deflect a
shot by him five minutes into the second period, but both of his
skates were in the crease and the goal was waved off.
</P>
<P>
   Hebert, who along with the rest of the team has numerous shakey
moments recently, said there was no reason not to be ready for a
game with Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have Tocchet laughing at you and (Dallas) Drake
running everybody ... if that doesn't bring out the best in you
it's going to be a long night,'' said Hebert. ``It's a fun game to
play in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
