<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS CHOOSE WORDS CAREFULLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Although it's been documented that the Ducks would
prefer to play Phoenix in the first round rather than Detroit or
Colorado, they were very careful not to give the Coyotes any
bulletin board material after Sunday's victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are all really tough teams,'' said Teemu Selanne,
refering to Phoenix, Detroit and Colorado. ``It doesn't matter who
we play against, we are just worried about playing at our own
level. We want to build confidence in the last three games. It's
tough to turn things around if you don't have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Guy Hebert admitted he'd like to play Phoenix, but went out of
his way to explain it has more to do with the rivalry, then
thinking Phoenix is an easy mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our past history would just make it exciting, said the Anaheim
goalie.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Ducks center Steve Rucchin did not play for the ninth time in
the last 10 games due to a groin injury he suffered in practice on
March 20.
</P>
<P>
   Rucchin was having the best season of his career before getting
hurt -- 23 goals and 61 points in 66 games -- and he's clearly
frustrated by the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I lay in bed and want to scream,'' said Rucchin, who
suffered a setback when he attempted to play against New Jersey on
March 31. ``This is an especially fun time for this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Teemu Selanne, who tried to rush back from a thigh injury
earlier this season, cautions that Rucchin must take his time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's such important player, he can't rush, he's got to be 100
percent for the playoffs,'' said Selanne.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks have especially missed Rucchin's defensive skills and
his prowess in the face-off circle.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim was also without defenseman Pascal Trepanier who is out
for the season after suffering a torn ACL while playing basketball
on an off day last week.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Winger Tomas Sandstrom left the game due to dizziness in the
first period and did not return. Sandstrom was knocked head-first
into the Phoenix bench by Bob Corkum. Antti Aalto moved up from the
checking line to replace Sandstrom.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kariya had three shots in the game to increase his season
total to 414, tying him with Bobby Hull for the third most in NHL
single-season history. After Kariya passes Hull, he will take aim
at the 426 shots Phil Esposito recorded in 1971-72.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya has no chance of beating Esposito's all-time record of
550 set in '70-71.
</P>
<P>
   Coming into Sunday's game Jaromir Jagr was second to Kariya with
327.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
