<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION SHOW SIGNS OF SELF-CONFIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ A few months ago, the Revolution were on the
verge of becoming a collective basket case. The team lacked
confidence, and there was an overall depressed feeling, often
masked by unrealistic optimism, which was manifested in
record-setting defeats.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Revolution appear to have regained some self-belief.
They have avoided the collapses that plagued them last year, in
defeats of 5-1 to Los Angeles (twice) and 6-1 to Columbus. And,
after surrendering last-minute goals, they have regained their
composure.
</P>
<P>
   When the Revolution fell behind to D.C. United in the final
seconds of the first half of their home opener Saturday night, they
recovered quickly before 18,373 at Foxboro Stadium. After appearing
vulnerable, saved only by the extraordinary goalkeeping of
player-coach Walter Zenga, they rallied in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a 2-2 tie after regulation time. And though the
Revolution lost in the shootout to remain with 3 points in three
matches, this is the first time in four seasons they have outscored
the opposition at this point in the season. This is also the first
time they have avoided defeat in regulation time in the first three
matches.
</P>
<P>
   Although Major League Soccer fails to reward tie games, even a
shootout failure cannot overcome the soccer axiom that the weaker
team feels a sense of accomplishment by preventing the opposition
from winning. And, the Revolution's 4-3 goal differential is
encouraging, since only four MLS teams outscored the opposition
last season.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses remain, but the Revolution are receiving optimal
contributions from Ivan McKinley and Johnny Torres, who were
ineffective last season. Dan Calichman and Richard Goulooze have
been effective in central defense. Zenga's goalkeeping has been
spectacular. And Giuseppe ``Beppe'' Galderisi added inspiration in
his debut as assistant coach, though his hiring has not been
confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows their role on the team, and that is something
we lacked in recent years,'' said defender Ted Chronopoulos, who
made his team-leading 87th appearance Saturday. ``We have more
leadership in the locker room from Dan, plus Walter and Beppe. The
young guys might have been thinking, here we go again, after we
fell behind. But those guys were saying, `We can do this.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We might have put our heads down last year. But we showed a
lot of composure. We showed we are not quitters.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution are hardly a complete team, with key players
recovering from injuries. And their lack of midfield play has
placed even more pressure on the defense. But Edwin Gorter and Jair
provided creativity against United, and Joe-Max Moore converted an
exceptional free kick to compensate for an otherwise ineffective
performance.
</P>
<P>
   This is a crucial stretch for the Revolution. They meet Columbus
Saturday and visit D.C. United April 24. By then, the team's
identity could be established and the tone for the season
confirmed. This is still a fragile situation, and the Revolution
are not yet playing from a position of strength. They consider it
an accomplishment to draw at home against D.C. United, which tells
much about the relative strengths of the teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution were outplayed for much of the contest, but
trailed for a total of only 16 minutes, the first time they have
fallen behind this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we were behind a lot, and that puts pressure on
you,'' Chronopoulos said. ``We were erratic in the first half
(against United), giving up a lot of simple passes. We were leaving
too many gaps in the second half. But, we are playing with a lot
more confidence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
