<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPECIALS-BUDGET-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No. 2533 - April 12, 1999  
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. NATO'S BOMBS AND MOVIE BLOCKBUSTERS Even in its first days,
the crisis in Kosovo presented itself as a miniaturized, modernized
version of the vivid battle epics of the past season, ``Saving
Private Ryan'' and ``The Thin Red Line.'' In the analogy, Milosevic
is a low-rent Hitler; his ethnic cleansing, a B-movie Holocaust.
Early reports were peppered with Spielberg-like plot lines : the
rescue mission behind enemy lines that endangers many to save one,
the lumbering B-52 bombers still in service after all these years.
Once again we're fighting alongside our allies to stop the mass
murder of a helpless ethnic minority. By Jacob Weisberg. From The
New York Times Magazine. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 2.
INSIDE THE KOSOVO LIBERATION ARMY After NATO's air strikes against
Yugoslavia, the Kosovo Liberation Army is set for a long guerilla
war to win an independent Kosovo now and a Greater Albania later.
To Washington's chagrin, the KLA rebels have supplanted Kosovo's
moderate leaders and won the support of most of its ethnic
Albanians. Chris Hedges, who writes from inside the rebel group,
says that Serbian brutality has left the KLA bent on secession.
From Foreign Affairs Magazine. (Hedges is currently a Neiman Fellow
at Harvard University; he was The New York Times' Balkan Bureau
chief from 1995 to 1998.) A. THE REBEL VOICE IN KOSOVO B. INSIDE
THE KOSOVO LIBERATION ARMY C. KOSOVO BECOMES A POLITICAL TIME BOMB
D. THE K.L.A. IS WILDLY UNLIKELY TO HAND OVER ITS GUNS
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
THE SPERMINATOR Reproduction is a individual, personal matter. We
cannot assume that a man pursuing parenthood while alive would have
wanted to father children from the grave. Yet, in fact, retrieving
sperm from the dead is now so common that the American Society of
Reproductive Medicine has developed a protocol, ``Posthumous
Reproduction,'' for dealing with it. And one bioethicist coined a
term for this new kind of father : the sperminator. By Lori B.
Andrews. From The New York Times Magazine. Full-length (3,300
words) + edited article available. 4. THE PHYSICS OF TRAFFIC Two
theoretical physicists ponder the snarly equation of highway
traffic and come up with possible cures for congestion. Using
computer models that treat cars on highways like molecules in a
gas, an American and German physicist team offer more than a road
paved with good intentions. By Robert Sapolsky. From Discover
Magazine. 1,000 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
TAKING THE THIRD The first person pronoun has been displaced in
America : I am no longer me, I am he. Is it a way to avoid
responsibility, to be less egocentric ... or what? By John Powers.
From The Boston Globe Magazine. 1,500 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
TWENTY BOOKS TO PUT AN END TO CREEPY SEX Misbehaviour in high
places has given sex a bad name. Here is a selection of 20 books
that eliminate tawdry from torrid. In most cases, the 20
recommended books were written at a time when the boundaries of
censorship were still being defined and literary stakes were high.
By Richard Victory. From Washingtonian Magazine. 1,000 words. 7.
HAVE SKIS, HELICOPTER, AWE AND TERROR In what is commonly called
'helicopter skiiing,' participants fly by helicopter to the
mountain peaks and ski in deep power snow. The skis are wider and
shorter. Important differences also involve turning method and
basic body stance. By Holcomb B. Noble. From The New York Times
Science Times. 900 words + graphic. 8. WHEN NO-ONE READ, WHO
STARTED TO WRITE? When it comes to explaining the origins of
writing, scientists are largely at a loss. But many at a recent
symposium favoured a broad explanation of writing's origins in the
visual arts. Their views clashed with a widely-held theory that
writing grew out of the pieces of clay that Sumerian accountants
had used to keep track of livestock and stores of grain. By John
Noble Wilford. From The New York Times Science Times. 2,200 words +
photo + graphic.
_______________________________________________________________ 9.
THE INNER BEZOS Amazon.com's founder Jeff Bezos figured out how to
sell books on the web and now he wants to sell you everything else.
Simple, right? So why is he the only one pulling it off? By Chip
Bayers. From Wired Magazine. 5,000 words. (N/A Japan.)
_______________________________________________________________
