<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
  (For release on Sunday, April 18.) 
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for paperback
books. See BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending April 3, at
almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000 other
retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all such
outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of nonfiction can change from week to week, reflecting
changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE PILOT'S WIFE, by Anita Shreve. (Back Bay/Little, Brown,
</P>
<P>
   $13.95.) After learning that a plane flown by her husband
</P>
<P>
   has exploded, a woman tries to unravel the secret life
</P>
<P>
   he led.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE READER, by Bernhard Schlink. (Vintage, $11.)
</P>
<P>
   A German high school student falls in love with a
</P>
<P>
   former Auschwitz employee.
</P>
<P>
   3. MEMOIRS OF A GEISHA, by Arthur Golden. (Vintage, $14.)
</P>
<P>
   The life of a young woman growing up in Kyoto who has
</P>
<P>
   to reinvent herself after World War II begins.
</P>
<P>
   4. THE LONG ROAD HOME, by Danielle Steel. (Dell, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A woman who grew up in a fractured family finds the
</P>
<P>
   courage to confront the past.
</P>
<P>
   5. THE STREET LAWYER, by John Grisham. (Island/Dell,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) A young lawyer discovers his
</P>
<P>
   prestigious firm's dirty secret.
</P>
<P>
   6. THEN CAME HEAVEN, by LaVyrle Spencer. (Jove, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   After the death of a close friend, a nun's relationship
</P>
<P>
   with the widower and his family takes a new turn.
</P>
<P>
   7. DIVINE SECRETS OF THE YA-YA SISTERHOOD,
</P>
<P>
   by Rebecca Wells. (Harper Perennial, $13.50.) Three
</P>
<P>
   generations of Southern women.
</P>
<P>
   8. YOU BELONG TO ME, by Mary Higgins Clark. (Pocket,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) A radio talk-show host attempts to expose a
</P>
<P>
   killer who targets lonely women.
</P>
<P>
   9. THE MACGREGORS: Daniel _ Ian, by Nora Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   (Silhouette, $6.99.) Two romantic stories about the
</P>
<P>
   members of a clan.
</P>
<P>
   10. MESSAGE IN A BOTTLE, by Nicholas Sparks. (Warner
</P>
<P>
   Vision, $6.99.) After finding an enigmatic
</P>
<P>
   letter, a divorced woman encounters love.
</P>
<P>
   11. CHARMING BILLY, by Alice McDermott. (Delta,
</P>
<P>
   $12.95.) At a party to celebrate a man's
</P>
<P>
   memory, many secrets of the past come to life.
</P>
<P>
   12. THE MARK OF THE ASSASSIN, by Daniel Silva. (Fawcett,
</P>
<P>
   $6.99.) A CIA officer must confront a notorious assassin.
</P>
<P>
   13. FORTUNES OF WAR, by Stephen Coonts. (St. Martin's, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Japan, Russia and America engage in conflict that could
</P>
<P>
   wipe out civilization.
</P>
<P>
   14. WHERE THE HEART IS, by Billie Letts. (Warner, $12.)
</P>
<P>
   A pregnant teen-ager finds help and
</P>
<P>
   caring in a small Oklahoma town.
</P>
<P>
   15. ANNIE'S RAINBOW, by Fern Michaels. (Zebra, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A crime committed 10 years earlier imperils
</P>
<P>
   a woman's romance and thriving business.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. OCTOBER SKY, by Homer H. Hickam Jr. (Island/Dell,
</P>
<P>
   $6.99.) A memoir of Coalwood, W.Va., where the author
</P>
<P>
   learned to build rockets.
</P>
<P>
   2. TALKING TO HEAVEN, by James Van Praagh.
</P>
<P>
   (Signet, $6.99.) A ``world-famous medium'' discusses
</P>
<P>
   communication with the other side. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3.(x) ARE YOU SOMEBODY? by Nuala O'Faolain.
</P>
<P>
   (Owl/Holt, $11.95.) The memoir of a Dublin journalist.
</P>
<P>
   4. THE PERFECT STORM, by Sebastian Junger.
</P>
<P>
   (Harper Paperbacks, $6.99.) The story of the
</P>
<P>
   nor'easter of 1991, focusing on a single crew.
</P>
<P>
   5. BITTER HARVEST, by Ann Rule. (Pocket, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   The marriage of a professional couple in Kansas
</P>
<P>
   ends under mysterious, violent circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   6. THE MILLIONAIRE NEXT DOOR, by Thomas J. Stanley
</P>
<P>
   and William D. Danko. (Pocket, $14.) An analysis
</P>
<P>
   of the lives of wealthy Americans. (b)
</P>
<P>
   7.(x) INTO THIN AIR, by Jon Krakauer. (Anchor/Doubleday, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Ascending Mount Everest in 1996, the deadliest season in
</P>
<P>
   history.
</P>
<P>
   8. UNDER THE TUSCAN SUN, by Frances Mayes.
</P>
<P>
   (Broadway, $13.) Life in the Italian countryside.
</P>
<P>
   9.(x) OUR DUMB CENTURY, edited by Scott Dikkers. (Three
</P>
<P>
   Rivers, $15.) Newspaper headlines making fun of great
</P>
<P>
   events of the past century.
</P>
<P>
   10.(x) A CHILD CALLED ``IT,'' by Dave Pelzer.
</P>
<P>
   (Health Communications, $9.95.) The autobiography
</P>
<P>
   of a man who survived his mother's abuse. (b)
</P>
<P>
   11.(x) TENDER AT THE BONE, by Ruth Reichl. (Broadway,
</P>
<P>
   $13.) A memoir by the restaurant critic for The
</P>
<P>
   New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   12.(x) GUNS, GERMS, AND STEEL, by Jared Diamond. (Norton,
</P>
<P>
   $14.95.) A physiologist attributes Western dominance to
</P>
<P>
   geographical advantages.
</P>
<P>
   13. THE COLOR OF WATER, by James McBride.
</P>
<P>
   (Riverhead, $12.) A black writer remembers growing
</P>
<P>
   up with his white mother in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   14.(x) EMOTIONAL INTELLIGENCE, by Daniel Goleman.
</P>
<P>
   (Bantam, $13.95.) Factors other than IQ that contribute
</P>
<P>
   to a successful and happy life. (b)
</P>
<P>
   15.(x) ADVENTURES OF A PSYCHIC, by Sylvia Browne and
</P>
<P>
   Antoinette May. (Hay House, $12.95.) A psychic
</P>
<P>
   tells her life story.
</P>
<P>
   16.(x) SLAVES IN THE FAMILY, by Edward Ball. (Ballantine,
</P>
<P>
   $15.95.) A family chronicle by a journalist whose forebears
</P>
<P>
   owned thousands of slaves. (b)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. DR. ATKINS' NEW DIET REVOLUTION, by
</P>
<P>
   Robert C. Atkins. (Avon, $14 and $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Ways to lose weight and achieve a healthy body. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. PROTEIN POWER, by Michael R. Eades and Mary
</P>
<P>
   Dan Eades. (Bantam, $6.50.) Two physicians offer a
</P>
<P>
   protein-rich, low-carbohydrate plan for losing weight.
</P>
<P>
   3. CHICKEN SOUP FOR THE COUPLE'S SOUL, compiled by Jack
</P>
<P>
   Canfield, Mark Victor Hansen et al. (Health Communications,
</P>
<P>
   $12.95.) Inspirational stories about love and relationships. (b)
