<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) 
 The Week in Review  
 (bl)  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hoping for an Instant Replay &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On opening day of the baseball season in St. Louis, the luster,
the drama and anticipation _ the pure pleasure _ of much of last
season appeared to have hardly skipped a beat. As soon as Mark
McGwire came up to bat in the Cardinals' half of the first inning,
the sellout crowd of nearly 50,000 stood and cheered. And they kept
standing in prolonged homage as the millennium's Sultan of Swat _
the huge, rippling-muscled man who last season hit 70 homers,
breaking Roger Maris' hallowed, single-season home-run record by an
amazing nine _ walked. He struck out in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   But in the fifth McGwire, naturally, homered.
</P>
<P>
   Could this have been a harbinger of another resounding baseball
season, a season like the one that clearly marked a return for many
to the so-called national pastime, something that had been in
rather bad odor since the strike of 1994?
</P>
<P>
   Would McGwire and his virtual doppelganger, Sammy Sosa, make
another run at the record? Would the sullen Albert Belle, who also
homered in his first game for the Orioles? Could the Yankees
possibly repeat their magnificent performance? Might a Tony Gwynn
streak to a batting average of .400 for the year? Might there be
exciting division races, something lacking last season?
</P>
<P>
   However it turns out, it seemed that on opening day a nation was
returning with gusto to the days when it wanted to be taken out to
the ball game, to have some peanuts and Cracker Jack, and not to
care if it ever got back.
</P>
<P>
   _ By IRA BERKOW
</P>
<P>
   Breaking a Family Tradition &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For a time, it looked as if the son would go the way of the
father, toughing it out in great style. But John A. Gotti had
learned another lesson from watching his father: If the government
wants to put away a mobster, it can be pit-bull relentless. It
tried John J. Gotti four times before convicting him of murder in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   So on the eve of his trial, the younger Gotti cut a deal that
would give him what his lawyers, using parlance not customarily
heard in the underworld, described as ``closure.'' With striking
humility, Gotti pleaded guilty in White Plains, N.Y., to running a
criminal racket. The charges could send him to prison for seven
years, but Gotti received assurances that the plea would end all
other investigations.
</P>
<P>
   What prompted Gotti to fold his cards was learning that the
names of his jurors would be kept secret _ heightening the jurors'
sense that they had something to fear from Gotti _ and that even if
he won in White Plains he would soon be indicted in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOSEPH BERGER
</P>
<P>
   An Inauspicious Start for a Chinese Premier's Visit  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Curse the stars, or whatever one blames for bad timing, but
Prime Minister Zhu Rongji of China walked into a minefield when he
visited Washington on the second stop on his nine-day, six-city
tour of America. The 70-year-old Chinese leader, known for his
hands-on management of his nation's economy and for his blunt
speaking style, impressed people in the capital with his candor.
But he blamed U.S. politics for the failure to close a deal for
China to enter the World Trade Organization, an agreement both
Chinese and U.S. negotiators said was agonizingly close.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said China was ``not quite there yet'' on its
long-standing application to join the world regulatory body on
trade. But the real issue was the sour political environment,
including fresh concerns about human rights and Chinese pilferage
of U.S. military secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Two months earlier or later, the two sides might have been able
to close the deal and send Zhu home with a prize, one Chinese
official ruminated. As it is, they will now go back to the
negotiating table and try to sign an agreement by the end of the
year. And Zhu, demonstrating a Chinese version of a stiff upper
lip, continued his tour of the United States with a stop in Denver,
to be followed by Chicago, New York and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOSEPH KAHN
</P>
<P>
   Check Out Your Driver
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court handed a warning to automobile passengers: You
give up your privacy rights when you get into the car, and if the
driver gets into trouble with the law, so may you.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled that as long as police have probable cause to
search a car for illegal drugs or other contraband, they can search
all closed containers in the car, including, in this case, a
passenger's pocketbook.
</P>
<P>
   Police need not suspect the passenger of a crime, Justice
Antonin Scalia said for the 6-3 majority, explaining that
``passengers, no less than drivers, possess a reduced expectation
of privacy'' when they get into a car.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LINDA GREENHOUSE
</P>
<P>
   Too Much Cash? Just Give It Away.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Flush with cash from the soaring stock market, the nation's
foundations gave away a record amount of money last year, according
to a recent study. Foundations made an estimated $19.5 billion in
grants in 1998 to not-for-profit organizations, according to the
Foundation Center, a New York group that tracks foundation giving.
The amount represents an increase of about 41 percent since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The bull market has made donors more generous and fattened
endowments, according to the Foundation Center, which based its
1998 estimates on survey responses from more than 1,000
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   _ By REED ABELSON
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Accusations of Overcharging at Nuclear Cleanup Sites
</P>
<P>
   Cleaning up radioactive pollution at former nuclear weapons
plants has been tedious for workers and expensive for taxpayers,
although generally profitable for the contractors. Now an
accountant for two contractors at the Hanford nuclear reservation
in Washington state has filed a suit that says the contractors have
been illegally marking up their bills, adding overhead charges to
expenses that do not qualify.
</P>
<P>
   The contractors acted like a restaurant that pockets the
waitress' tips, according to the accountant, David Carbaugh, who
also claims he was fired for trying to alert the Energy Department.
The contractors, Fluor Daniel Hanford and Westinghouse Hanford Co.,
deny the charges, which were filed in U.S. District Court in
Spokane.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MATTHEW L. WALD
</P>
<P>
   A Guilty Plea in the Kidnapping and Murder of a Gay Man
</P>
<P>
   In Laramie, Wyo., where the murder of Matthew Shepard six months
ago provoked national soul-searching over violence against gay
people, Russell Henderson pleaded guilty to kidnapping and
murdering Shepard, a college student. He was sentenced to serve two
consecutive life terms in prison.
</P>
<P>
   To escape the death penalty, Henderson may have bargained with
prosecutors to testify in August in the capital murder trial of his
former friend, Aaron McKinney. In court, Henderson said McKinney
was the mastermind of the crime, choosing the student as a victim,
and then beating him savagely.
</P>
<P>
   Wyoming authorities have declined to classify the murder as a
hate crime or a murder motivated by hatred of gays.
</P>
<P>
   McKinney is expected to try to use the ``gay panic'' defense,
arguing that his uncontrollable anger was ignited by a sexual
advance by Shepard.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a Denver television reporter, obtained letters
written from jail by McKinney. In one letter peppered with
misspellings, McKinney, a high-school dropout, wrote to a female
friend that Shepard ``said he was gay and wanted a piece of me.''
In response, he wrote, ``Being verry drunk and homofobick I flipped
out and began to pistol whip'' the student.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES BROOKE
</P>
<P>
   Drastic Action to Seal Leaks of Nuclear Secrets
</P>
<P>
   The current furor over the Clinton administration's handling of
evidence of Chinese atomic espionage is now forcing the
administration to scramble to plug leaks at America's three major
nuclear weapons laboratories, where it has been accused of
responding sluggishly to security problems.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most dramatic actions taken since the spy scandal
erupted last month, Energy Secretary Bill Richardson ordered a
suspension of all scientific work on the computer networks
containing America's most sensitive nuclear weapons secrets at the
Los Alamos, Sandia and Lawrence-Livermore laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   He took the action because he was convinced that security
problems had left the computer networks vulnerable to espionage.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Richardson decided to close down the networks for an
indefinite period after receiving an internal review that found
that security measures at Los Alamos and Lawrence-Livermore were
still below standard.
</P>
<P>
   Closing down the classified computer networks affects thousands
of workers at the weapons labs, and effectively halts most
classified work related to the maintenance of the U.S. nuclear
weapons inventory.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES RISEN
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
