<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 09:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4474 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN-COX     04-12 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Missouri outguns the NRA
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the poobahs of the National Rifle Association are wondering
what that odd thing in their laps is, it is their head. Missouri
voters handed it to them last week, in a referendum that quashed
the NRA's attempt to bring them the joys of concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri outlawed concealed weapons in 1875 when Jesse James and
his lads were marauding the state, which was less charmed up close
by their predations than the myth-makers of outlaw chic were back
East.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA has ramrodded repeals through the Missouri legislature
but has been frustrated by a governor who was having none of it.
Hence the referendum, in which the guns-for-all campaign outspent
opponents 4-to-1 but at the end of which Missourians outvoted the
gunners 52 percent to 48 in a large turnout.
</P>
<P>
   Missourians Against Crime, so-called, is crying foul in a
twisted whine that, boiled down, claims the election was unfair
because nobody important _ guv, newspapers, major pols, law
enforcement officials _ was on its side.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA dropped close to $4 million on this little venture _
dues payers might wish to think about that _ and in truth was not
pitching anything all that extraordinary, at least by current
standards. Not long ago most states forbade concealed weapons, but
the gun lobby has been picking off legislatures one by one.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-one states now permit concealment, and Missourians were
only being asked to join the party. Most, however, failed to see
the appeal in the NRA's proposition that the more guns, the safer;
that the good life lies in turning our public space _ streets,
parks, malls, freeways, ballfields _ into zones of wary mutual
firepower.
</P>
<P>
   The vote reflected poll numbers that go back decades, both in
its overall outcome and its breakdown. City and suburban aginners
outvoted rustics. Perhaps NRA's greatest on-going success is in
convincing the rural and small-town hunting culture that any limits
on any firearms _ indeed, as in this case, any failure to
proliferate firearms _ means the next thing you know, you won't be
allowed to shoot moose, or whatever.
</P>
<P>
   For all its braggadocio and bullying, the NRA has always
chickened out on two crucial points. It has refused to press its
absolutist Second Amendment claims to a definitive Supreme Court
ruling, knowing perfectly well the right to bear arms is
conditional.
</P>
<P>
   And it has dodged plebiscites, a skittishness fully vindicated
by its flop in Missouri. The gun lobby took the risk because it is
stalled in Congress for a change, has suffered some setbacks in
cities and gun sales are stagnant.
</P>
<P>
   But undeterred, the NRA now moves its tent to Denver, for its
annual convention. The city's mayor credits his council's 1993 gun
and crime controls for halving the homicide rate, but an
NRA-sympathetic Republican legislature and governor are moving to
make it easier to carry concealed weapons and to bar local
governments from regulating firearms.
</P>
<P>
   When kids play, it's bang-bang, you're dead. When the NRA plays,
it's somehow bang-bang, you're alive. It's a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
