<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 09:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4476 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-MEXICO-FUGITIVES-RE     04-12 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-MEXICO-FUGITIVES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICIAN TURNS FUGITIVE: NOT UNUSUAL IN MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A Mexican governor suddenly runs afoul of the top
authorities. Instead of appearing in court to defend himself, he
goes on the lam. Later, he sends a message from a clandestine
location saying he is being persecuted by aides to the Mexican
president and fears for his life.
</P>
<P>
   Last week that was the news from Mexico _ the story of Mario
Villanueva Madrid, the governor who became a fugitive from drug and
racketeering charges.
</P>
<P>
   But broadly speaking, it's also an old story. It was the story
of Pablo Chapa Bezanilla, the deputy attorney general who went
underground in 1997; and of Gerardo de Prevoisin, the president of
Mexico's largest airline, who fled into hiding three years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The general outlines also fit the story of Mario Ruiz Massieu, a
former drug czar who fled Mexico in 1995, and of Carlos Cabal
Peniche, a bank president who lived clandestinely for four years
before his arrest in Australia in November.
</P>
<P>
   There are so many other such cases that to Mexicans, the public
figure turned fugitive has become something of cliche.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our system, there's a thin line separating public officials
from outlaws, and legality from illegality,'' said Homero Aridjis,
a Mexican poet and head of International PEN, the writers' group.
``Overnight, they can leave behind their prerogatives of power and
turn into fugitives.''
</P>
<P>
   To Americans, the idea of running from justice seems like a bad
one even for common criminals, much less for state governors,
federal prosecutors or top corporate executives. But in Mexico,
most recent cases demonstrate the opposite: Fleeing justice usually
pays off.
</P>
<P>
   With the justice system awash in graft and vulnerable to
political pressure, those who clash with the president and his men
but have enough money to flee usually defend themselves more
effectively from exile or even from underground than from a Mexican
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like Mario Villanueva who become fugitives are experts
in our authoritarian system,'' said Lorenzo Meyer Cosio, a
historian at Mexico City's Colegio de Mexico. ``They know that if
you confront the president, there is no court or judge or defense
team that can protect you.''
</P>
<P>
   Villanueva, the governor of the Caribbean state of Quintana Roo
who clashed with President Ernesto Zedillo and his associates, fled
into hiding last month. Tuesday, the day after his six-year tenure
ended, an arrest warrant was issued for him. Villanueva faxed
newspapers to decry the ``lynch mob'' atmosphere in which
prosecutors were manufacturing evidence to ``destroy me physically,
psychologically and morally.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Mexicans view former President Carlos Salinas de Gortari,
who left Mexico during a 1995 dispute with Zedillo, as a kind of
fugitive. In exile in Ireland, he has not been charged with any
crime. His brother Raul, however, was convicted in January for the
murder of a rival politician, illustrating how badly trials can go
here for defendants who do not flee; Raul's conviction came despite
multiple contradictions in the government's case and proof of
evidence rigging.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Chapa, the deputy attorney general who in 1997 was
indicted for planting a skeleton to incriminate Raul Salinas in the
murder case, demonstrated the wisdom of going underground.
</P>
<P>
   With police closing in, Chapa fled his home in the trunk of his
car, and later sent a letter to newspapers calling himself a
``refugee in self-defense.'' Chapa was later arrested and jailed in
Spain and extradited. But by then he was well-prepared for legal
skirmishes, and once in Mexico was quickly freed.
</P>
<P>
   Another fugitive who beat the system is Angel Isidoro Rodriguez,
a banker who fled to Spain in 1994 after he was accused of fraud.
The Spanish authorities arrested and jailed him last year, but
after his extradition to Mexico, lawyers quickly obtained his
release, too.
</P>
<P>
   Several fugitives have floated the threat that they could reveal
details of high-level corruption or criminality, and many Mexicans
believe that has helped them in their battles with the authorities.
</P>
<P>
   De Prevoisin, the airline chief who fled into exile when he was
charged with embezzling $72 million in 1994, later accused
Zedillo's party of extorting $8 million from the airline during his
election campaign. De Prevoisin eluded arrest until last year and
is currently fighting extradition from Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Cabal Peniche, a banker and friend of former President
Salinas, fled Mexico in 1994 amid charges that he participated in a
$700 million fraud. Authorities traced him to Australia, where he,
too, is battling extradition. Cabal has also threatened to reveal
details of his donations to Zedillo's campaign, estimated at $4
million. ``I am being persecuted because of the threat that it is
believed I represent to the system,'' he said recently.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 0922EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
