<DOCNO> NYT19990412.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 09:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5932 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-TAX-CUT-REVIEW-ART-     04-12 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-TAX-CUT-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMETIMES A TAX CUT CAN BE A HARD SELL 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This is the time of year _ just as Americans are
grousing over their tax returns _ when Republicans and their allies
try to stoke the flames of tax rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   Come mid-April, they like to re-enact the Boston Tea Party,
America's original tax revolt, or stage mock funerals for the tax
code or toss the thick tomes that contain the nation's tax laws
into trash cans. This year, the National Federation of Independent
Business, a lobbying group for small business, is planning to hand
out aspirin at post offices to last-minute tax filers.
</P>
<P>
   But these stunts seem only to highlight what's missing: the kind
of grass-roots uprising that inspired California's Proposition 13
restrictions on property taxes and swept Ronald Reagan into office
nearly two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   This public quiescence is puzzling to the proponents of tax
relief who think that now more than ever it is the time for
significant tax cutting or an overhaul of the tax code. They point
to the fact that federal tax receipts, which are estimated to reach
$1.8 trillion by the end of the federal fiscal year this October,
will amount to 20.6 percent of the gross domestic product. That is
a level unmatched since World War II. They also argue that the
federal surpluses that began appearing last year after a decade of
deficits make the idea of sweeping tax cuts feasible again.
</P>
<P>
   Americans, however, appear to have turned their political
energies and interests elsewhere. It is not that they would reject
a tax cut. A private poll that the National Republican
Congressional Committee distributed to House Republicans at a
retreat in February found that 67 percent of Americans favored a
tax reduction of 10 percent across the board.
</P>
<P>
   But voters seemed more ambivalent about tax cuts when they were
asked how they wanted the government to use the federal surplus.
Given a list of options, 31 percent of those polled said they
wanted the money devoted to Social Security, 26 percent to reducing
the national debt and only 18 percent to tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans are now telling Americans they don't
have to choose. They argue that the Republican budget plan for the
new fiscal year will protect Social Security funds and still have
money left over for tax cuts that grow to $800 billion over a
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts say it is economic expansion that has
decreased the public interest in tax cutting. The unemployment rate
is nearing a 29-year low, and the flush times have left most
Americans with money in their pockets and blunted the
anti-government animus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you have good times it makes it harder for tax cutters
like myself and Republicans to make the case you're being bit in
the wallet,'' said Stephen Moore, an economist with the Cato
Institute, a conservative research center. ``Ronald Reagan wouldn't
have been elected in 1980 with the tax cut proposal if we weren't
in a time of economic crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   But in charting the change in attitudes, it is also instructive
to remember the nature of the 1970s economic crisis. That was when
President Gerald Ford made ``Whip Inflation Now'' his motto. When
Howard Jarvis caught the imaginations of Californians and propelled
Proposition 13 to victory in 1978, double-digit inflation was
pushing taxpayers into higher brackets unaccompanied by any real
increase in income. It was also increasing the assessed values of
their homes _ prompting higher property taxes. The biggest victims
were lower- and middle-income Americans, who could be easily moved
into higher tax brackets.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Reagan's 1981 tax act not only cut taxes, it
indexed tax brackets, adjusting them so that inflation alone would
not push people into higher brackets even if they had seen no real
increase in their income.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the irritants in the tax system, like inflation
pushing people up through brackets, have been taken care of now,''
said Iris Lav, the deputy director of the Center on Budget and
Policy Priorities, a liberal non-profit research group.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, inflation nearly disappeared. And instead of
viewing their home as their most important nest egg, many
middle-class Americans are now relying on investments and 401k
plans _ wealth that is not taxed until the stocks are sold.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for the lack of rebellion is that the tax burden
is not shared equally. Because of the deficit reduction plans of
1990 and 1993, the rich are paying a larger share of federal taxes
than before. But the tax burden on the middle class and working
class has decreased. Examining an array of taxes, the Congressional
Budget Office found that the 20 percent of families at the middle
of the nation's income scale earned an average income of $38,400 in
1995 and paid 20.2 percent of that in federal taxes. This year,
this group is projected to earn $45,100 on average and pay 18.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Such tax trends have led Americans to look beyond the present.
``We're in a period now where in a variety of fronts, particularly
education, Social Security and Medicare, Americans actually want
government to do something,'' said Geoffrey Garin, a Democratic
pollster. ``They are not willing to sacrifice government's ability
to deal with those problems for the sake of a tax cut.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosperity has even caused some Republicans to question the
supply-siders, who still hold enormous intellectual sway in their
party. ``Republicans have always been dominated by supply-siders
who said, `cut taxes' at every possible moment,'' said Rep. Joe
Scarborough, R-Fla. ``The lesson of '95 and '96 has been if you cut
federal spending, the markets respond, interest rates drop and the
economy explodes that way, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what you call that,'' Scarborough said. ``It's
not Keynesian. It's not supply side. Maybe its Greenspan
economics.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, even without a tax rebellion, it is likely that
Congress will enact some kind of tax relief this year. President
Clinton now uses the tax code as his chosen instrument of social
policy instead of direct-spending programs. His budget proposed tax
credits for child and health care amounting to $4.1 billion in tax
reductions in fiscal 2000 and $32.6 billion over five years.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, who are determined to put new muscle in what has
long been their signature issue, have proposed a modest $15 billion
in tax cuts for 2000 growing to $800 billion over a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``My rule of politics is nobody ever lost an election by cutting
taxes,'' said Moore. ``It's always a good bread-and-butter issue
for the Republican Party.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 0925EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
