<HEADER>
A4511 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MERCENARIES-BO     04-12 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MERCENARIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOULD-BE SOLDIERS HEAD TO JOIN KLA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ Almost four dozen men, some dressed in
camouflage fatigues, arrived in darkness, saying they had traveled
from Germany to join the Kosovo Liberation Army's fight against
Serbian troops.
</P>
<P>
   The men appeared to be unarmed and exhausted. One said they had
been on the road since Thursday, when they left Nuremburg in a
caravan of buses.
</P>
<P>
   All were ethnic Albanians who had fled to Germany from Kosovo in
the past two years, but who had decided it was their duty to
bolster the besieged rebel troops, according to one member of the
group. He would not identify himself except to say that he is 38
years old and that his first name is Hisen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are tired,'' he said shortly before 3 a.m. in the apartment
of a resident of Kukes, about 30 minutes from the border. ``But we
are ready to fight right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither the backgrounds of the 47 men nor their mission in the
mountains of northern Albania could be independently verified, and
nearly all of them declined to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   But their arrival bolstered reports that Kosovars living in
Western Europe _ and even some foreigners _ have been coming into
the region over the past week, as accounts of atrocities committed
by Yugoslav forces have increased and as Kosovo Liberation Army
officials have acknowledged that they are in dire need of help.
</P>
<P>
   Hisen said a group of 90 ethnic Albanians living in Switzerland
is on its way to help, too, along with dozens of Kosovars who had
fled to Slovenia and Austria.
</P>
<P>
   In another indication that would-be reinforcements are arriving,
a Kosovo Liberation Army guard in uniform was seen at a checkpoint
near the border Sunday, greeting a family from Macedonia reportedly
coming to visit relatives who had recently joined the rebels. The
guard, Refki Cenaj, 27, said 1,200 soldiers from abroad are
expected to arrive in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here from Kosovo,'' Cenaj said. ``I picked up a group
to train. We'll go back in groups of 30 or 40.''
</P>
<P>
   Ilaz Ramajli, a spokesman for Kosovars in the capital city of
Tirana, said he had been told of men arriving from ``around the
world'' to join the Kosovo Liberation Army. But he added that their
efforts would be meaningless without the help of NATO ground
troops, an assessment Kosovar leaders made a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the addition of untrained ground forces otherwise could
affect the fight against the Serbs remains in great doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are signs that NATO's bombing is taking its toll
on the Serb troops _ who reportedly are starting a campaign inside
Kosovo to recruit ethnic Albanian men _ the Kosovo Liberation Army
has always been badly outmuscled in weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has consistently declined to give direct support to the
rebels, whose tactics frequently include terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The US policy has basically been to let the rebels wage an
independent campaign, though a bill is pending in Congress to
supply the Kosovo Liberation Army with arms and President Clinton
has hinted that Washington might eventually support an independent
Kosovo if Yugoslav president Slobodan Milosevic does not
capitulate.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the United States were to assist the Kosovar force, its
structure is so disorganized that it is often hard to know who is
in charge. Ibrahim Rugova, the elected leader of Kosovo for nearly
a decade, is apparently under house arrest in Belgrade but has long
been considered ineffective anyway. His de facto successor is
Hashim Thaci, a KLA official who has reportedly been in hiding
outside the province for months.
</P>
<P>
   The network of KLA soldiers also appears to be haphazard.
Truckloads of them tear up and down the disintegrating roads in the
region, with Kalishnikov rifles slung across their backs, and their
destination and purpose unclear.
</P>
<P>
   The new arrivals were unsure of how they would operate. After
arranging their itinerary in Nuremburg, Hasen said, the group
departed April 8 without making any contact with Kosovo Liberation
Army leaders.
</P>
<P>
   He said they drove through Austria to Italy, where they caught
the ferry to the western coast of Albania.
</P>
<P>
   They then drove eight hours and arrived at 2 a.m. Sunday in
Kukes, where Hassen said they contacted a Kosovar commander to
discuss arrangements for going to a training camp.
</P>
<P>
   They expected 10 to 15 days of training before being sent over
the border into Kosovo. ``We hope in terms of winning the war that
the US and NATO will supply us weapons,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is needed, '' added Hisen, who said he is
originally from Mitrovica, where he worked in a bus agency until
fleeing to Germany two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Serb troops inside Kosovo are apparently trying to
lure young ethnic Albanian men away from the Kosovo Liberation
Army, according to refugees who arrived from the province Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Sabit Bullatovci, 48, an engineer from a nearby town, said three
Serb military officers came to his house at 8:30 p.m. last Friday
and asked him to find 500 volunteers. The Serbs said they would
``give us weapons and armaments to fight NATO and then we would be
safe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said if we didn't join, we had to leave the house the
next day at 8 a.m. If not, they would kill everybody,'' Bullatovci
said. He said he immediately rejected their request, and the men
pushed him no further.
</P>
<P>
   Bullatovci said he believed the request was a ploy by Milosevic
to pit ethnic Albanians against ethnic Albanians, and to deliver
young Kosovars to their deaths more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we provided the men, they would be killed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 young men crossing the border the previous night
said they had also been approached by Serbs looking for ethnic
Albanian recruits. All said they had quickly refused, and said they
also assumed the question was a trick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
