<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-PRINT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READING THE TINY PRINT CAN BE HAZARDOUS TO YOUR HEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1999 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As I was working on my taxes the other day _ mumbling things
like ``Deduct THIS, Uncle Sam'' _ I took a break, picked up a
magazine and began flipping pages. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because I already was into a fine-print mode, when I hit one of
those astonishingly weird ads for some kind of prescription drug I
stopped. In this case, the tablets being pushed were to help lower
cholesterol levels. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (I've been working on keeping my cholesterol down without drugs
ever since I discovered a few years ago that my count was exactly
equal to Dan Quayle's, and I wished to share nothing in common with
him if I could help it.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ad I was reading took up four pages. The first two were your
standard glitzy come-on, featuring graphs and testimonials from
people taking the stuff. But the next two were in teeny-weeny print
that most of us couldn't read without a digitally enhanced
electronic microscope. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the newspaper business we call tiny type ``agate,'' but real
agate looks like a 72-point headline next to the print in this
magazine ad. (By the way, a Food and Drug Administration
spokesperson tell me the FDA requires pharmaceutical companies to
print all this stuff in ads for prescription drugs. The firms don't
do it just to use up their ad budget or to weaken your eyes so
you'll buy their vision-enhancing drugs, if any.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Who reads this stuff?'' I asked myself. And, being a pretty
fair conversationalist, I answered, ``Why are you asking me? I have
no idea.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I try not to ignore me when I talk to myself. My parents taught
me good manners and, though they're gone now, they would be proud
to know I continue to answer myself when I hear me address myself. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, I thought, I'll see if I can make out any of the words
here. So I rented a digitally enhanced electronic microscope and
began staring at the itsy-bitsy words. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, push me in a puddle and call me a swimmer. Friends, you
really don't want to get into this stuff. It's enough to make your
knees hollow. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first three words I made out were ``nursing rat pups.'' I
didn't even know that's what you call baby rats. Never needed to
know. Never wanted to know. Am sorry I know now. Will try to
forget. Several more hours of squinting finally made clear that
this sentence had to do with a recommendation to mothers who
breast-feed not to take this stuff. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It got worse. The next words to achieve clarity were: ``Brain
hemorrhage and optic nerve vacuolation were seen in another female
dog that was sacrificed in moribund condition after 11 weeks of
escalating doses. . .'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Which reminds me of something I forgot to tell you at the start
_ up there where I was snarling at Uncle Sam: No animals died in
the production of this column. Which, apparently, is more than I
can say for the production of the drug I was reading about. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rats and dogs, however, weren't the only animals in the small
print. There were also ``Chinese hamster lung cells.'' Look. I'm
not against using animals in test labs when necessary to save human
life. I know which is more important. But that doesn't mean I want
to have the animals or their parts named and described for me. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Next I hit discussion of ``severe congenital bony deformity,
tracheo-esophageal fistula and anal atresia,'' and I quit. I felt
weak. I sensed my cholesterol had slipped dangerously low. I
grabbed some fried chicken and cheesecake and went back to my
taxes. Maybe Uncle Sam really needs my money, I thought. Maybe the
poor devil is on this cholesterol-lowering drug. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
