<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    While some cities balk, Atlanta plans to party
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After many months of trying to drum up interest in a
huge downtown New Year's Eve bash in Atlanta, planners now say the
merrymaking is coming together. A tighter-than-hoped-for budget,
though, will reduce the street party from its original schedule of
Thanksgiving through Jan. 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've shrunk the promotional time but saved the main events,''
said John Bevilaqua, president of Creative Marketing Strategies
Inc., the event-planning company spearheading the effort. The plans
are shaping up this month because ``the clock is ticking. ...
There's a sense of urgency now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But ironically, just as Atlanta's party plans are jelling, some
communities are starting to downscale or even cancel celebrations
due to lack of interest, funding difficulties or concerns about
computer bugs biting at midnight. For example, Party 2000, a
five-day concert and party that organizers had planned to hold on
5,000 acres in Southern California, appears headed toward a
figurative Death Valley. The organizers' Internet site recently
announced that ``owners of Party 2000 have decided to literally
give the production away to any person or company (with) the
financial resources'' to pull it off. So far, no takers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, The Associated Press is reporting that island nations
near the international dateline, such as Fiji and Tonga, are
scaling back expectations for revelry. Though hotels will be booked
as they always are during the week between Christmas and New
Year's, plans for using big tents to accommodate millions of
visitors have evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   In St. Paul, Minn., the organizers of that city's big party are
changing the celebration date to Dec. 30. Obviously, that will make
the midnight countdown a tad less exciting, but at least the crowds
won't have to worry about Y2K, the computer bug that threatens to
disrupt some equipment when the date changes. St. Paul officials
say they don't expect any serious Y2K problems but moved up the
celebration date in part because they fear potential partiers may
stay home Dec. 31 just in case of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But Bevilaqua says he has no Y2K concerns. ``We talked to
Georgia Power, and they aren't worried'' because fixes have been
made, he said. Besides, the event will take place outside where no
one will have to ride an elevator or fly in an airplane, so not
many things can go wrong, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bevilaqua says he has raised more than $3 million in pledges
from corporate sponsors for the event, to be called the ``Carnivale
of Lights.'' With the encouragement of the Atlanta Convention and
Visitors Bureau and the city, Bevilaqua has developed an outline
for a party involving fireworks, illuminated parade floats, lasers
and other lights.
</P>
<P>
   The plan now calls for a Dec. 18th kickoff. At that time,
downtown and Midtown will be lighted by ``lasers, high-tech image
and film-projection systems, building wash lighting, automated
xenon search lighting and many additional, high-impact lighting
systems,'' according to the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   On New Year's Eve, an illuminated parade of colorful floats will
wind down Peachtree Street from Midtown to downtown and then over
to Freedom Park, not far from the Civic Center MARTA station.
Belivaqua says he expects 500,000 to 700,000 people to gather there
for music and other entertainment. At midnight, a laser and
fireworks show will light up buildings and the sky over downtown
and Midtown.
</P>
<P>
   Bevilaqua said that when he started trying to pull together this
event, there was ``a lot of confusion'' over what would be
sanctioned by the city and supported by corporate sponsors. But at
this point, ``we're all joining hands and going forward,'' he said.
The final plans and list of sponsors will be announced about May 1,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   So let others scale back or fret about computer bugs. In
Atlanta, the party is just getting started.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on Y2K, visit these sites:
</P>
<P>
   _www.bytewise.com/1atlyear2000/
</P>
<P>
   _www.igc.org/millennium/
</P>
<P>
   _www.everything2000.com
</P>
<P>
   _www.countdown2000.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
