<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Our heartbeats interwoven in life, death
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Spring always makes me acutely aware of life's
rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   All around us, nature is vigorously awaking. Trees are leafing,
tulips and jonquils are blooming, calves are frolicking and nests
are filling with the constant peeping of new life.
</P>
<P>
   But the rhythms of life also include death. Three of my friends
recently lost a parent. It wasn't unexpected, given their advanced
ages and medical conditions; and yet, in our society it seems death
is always unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   For these friends, all close to my own age, it was the first
parent they'd lost. It's an emotional blow that signals a new life
stage for which we're rarely prepared. How do we grasp that those
who gave us life now are dead?
</P>
<P>
   On a recent weekend, we went to visit the newest member of our
extended family, a month-old great-nephew. As his parents sat
beaming on the couch, we held this new life and marveled at his
beauty and perfection.
</P>
<P>
   Tiny fingers and toes, a mouth no bigger than a button, dark
blue eyes gazing everywhere and seeing nothing clearly _ he
embodied the miraculous in every molecule of his being.
</P>
<P>
   His 2-year-old sister bent to kiss his downy head, as instructed
by parents, and then scampered off to play peek-a-boo under the
coffee table.
</P>
<P>
   New beginnings were popping up in that house like mushrooms
after a spring rain.
</P>
<P>
   As I held this promise of new life, however, my mind was
somewhere else _ on my brother in California, who at that very
moment was undergoing triple bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   In my arms, this newborn's tiny heart beat strongly and quickly,
ready to take him miles into the future. Far away, another heart
was beating only through the miracle of modern medicine, with no
guarantees on how many more miles it would take its owner. In yet
another part of the country, another heart _ our mother's _ beat
much more slowly in a steady, vigilant prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Heartbeats and rhythms of life, all interwoven.
</P>
<P>
   On the drive back home, we were awed by the beauty of the spring
wildflowers along the highway. Bluebonnets, Indian paintbrushes and
primrose formed a vivid palette against the greening roadsides. In
the car, our three boys rumbled and grumbled with the fullness of
their own lives. It was a poignant drive, as I waited for the cell
phone to ring and bring us news about my brother.
</P>
<P>
   For Christians, spring also is the season of resurrection. No
surer sign exists that death is part of life and life is part of
death. What was dead comes to life; what was lost is found; despair
turns to inexpressible joy; a barricaded tomb opens and is empty.
What we expect to find, we often don't.
</P>
<P>
   Do we spend our lives denying death? Unrealistic as it is, do we
expect that it will not touch us? Or do we spend our lives
expecting death? Awaiting impending disaster in every illness,
every surgery, every unexpected turn in the road of our lives?
Either way, what we expect to find, we don't.
</P>
<P>
   The call about my brother finally came that day. He made it
through his surgery with three newly formed arteries. The heart of
this man was back in its rightful place. The road before him would
be long and hard, but at least it was still before him.
</P>
<P>
   We came home with a picture of our new grand-nephew, which now
beams out at us beside the other family pictures on our piano _ the
one of his sister in her Christmas dress, his cousin in a pumpkin
Halloween costume, my parents at their 50th wedding anniversary, my
sister and her family, our three boys in last year's school
pictures, my parents-in-law, now both gone . . . and my brother.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald. She can be
reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
