<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Lament for the last shag
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The carpet was brought to rest at the end
of the driveway in a big brown roll. It looked like a cheap stogy
tossed away as unsmokable by a discerning giant.
</P>
<P>
   But this was not just any old, smelly carpet. This was The Last
Shag Carpet in America. Its removal after a quarter-century of wear
marks an end of an era. To dispose it, I didn't know whether to
alert the Smithsonian or the EPA.
</P>
<P>
   The '70s are symbolized by a number of cultural artifacts _
leisure suits, platform shoes, Donna Summer albums ... but these
all are things you could toss as cultural indicators changed. You
may have given that leisure suit to the Goodwill to celebrate the
fall of the Berlin Wall. Maybe you traded the double-knit jacket
for a power suit after you placed your first junk-bond order. With
good conscience you dumped the Donna Summer, Bee Gee and Fleetwood
Mac albums when you bought your first CD player. You might have
caused the Cabbage Patch dolls to disappear two closet cleanings
into middle school.
</P>
<P>
   But a shag carpet is different. Flooring is a choice you must
live with, and live with for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Like other bad decisions, I shirk all responsibility for this. I
was in high school when this carpet was brought to the showroom.
</P>
<P>
   I was not the person who said, ``Oh, brown and tan shag
carpeting! Just the thing for a house with animals! The stains will
look like they were meant to be there!''
</P>
<P>
   I was not the person who said, ``shag carpeting, like disco and
American Motors, is here to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Not me. I'm just the guy who bought the house assuring everyone
I'd get around to doing something about the flooring. It took me
only seven years.
</P>
<P>
   When the time rolled around for the carpet's final roll-up, it
was rotting and tearing in places. It had spots that smelled like a
warm day at the zoo. The pad beneath it was decaying into little
piles of noxious powder. I expected the carpet workman to handle it
wearing hazardous-material jumpsuits and respirators. After they
finished setting up roadblocks.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the carpet filtered the sand of a quarter-century of
summer beach trips and the dirt of 1,000 stabs at gardening. Woven
into its pile were stains from five documented dogs and cats, past
and present. Nicotine and 250 other toxic trace compounds were
added by a former owner who chain-smoked. Spills from a dozen
parties and two very active children blended into its mottled color
pattern. Hidden inside its fibers were enough Legos to build a
small-but-intricate deep-space probe and enough pennies to buy
three white vinyl belts at the thrift store.
</P>
<P>
   That much life and living can overwhelm anything made of cloth.
Maybe not right away, but eventually and certainly within a quarter
century.
</P>
<P>
   After we rolled up the carpet, the kids felt faint, the cat ran
away and the dog growled at it ominously. He seemed concerned this
might be a living thing. He was not so far off.
</P>
<P>
   The old shag looked particularly evil in the bright light of the
outdoors. Something it hadn't seen since the Ford administration.
</P>
<P>
   We tend to think of houses as dead, static things. They aren't.
They rot. They change personality. A string of them will relate
differently to each other over time. They will start off identical
but have nothing to do with each other by the time they are
teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   For good or ill, houses change with us, just slower and more
painfully than the other things we live with.
</P>
<P>
   This house was a perfect '70s house at one time. Although it's
still a creature that time forgot, it is evolving.
</P>
<P>
   On bad days I felt like I was living in the ruins of the ``Brady
Bunch'' set. Doing my '90s business amid shag carpet,
pumpkin-colored tile and busy kitchen wallpaper with little flowers
and repeated pictures of old-fashioned coffee pots, pans, forks and
wooden spoons.
</P>
<P>
   The wallpaper was a pleasure to remove, although I was talked
out of using a flame thrower or explosives to do it. Collateral
damage. And now the house has shed its shag like a snake crawling
out of old skin, leaving this brown tube on the lawn.
</P>
<P>
   This creature may have stronger powers of adaptation than I used
to think. Maybe all it needs is just one more trip to the hardware
store.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
