<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teachers, like moms, know when to keep quiet
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Benji and I are in the throes of an academic
disagreement when his little sister Sally comes in to claim her
lunch money. She stands hesitantly to one side of my desk, watching
and listening as Benji
</P>
<P>
   emphatically denies there are any misspelled words in his essay.
``I used the spellcheck,'' he tells me, expecting that to be the
end of the discussion. I shake my head and remind him that even the
smartest computers (which our hand-me-down dinosaurs aren't by a
long shot) are incapable of figuring out what's on his mind. ``You
at least have to come close.''
</P>
<P>
   He points to a couple of red circles in the second paragraph and
demands to know what's wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a thing,'' I assure him, ``if what you meant was:
`Marvin's mother set the table with some rye beard(sic) for toast
and a bowel(sic) full of strawberry jam because it was his
favorite.' Is that what you wanted to say?'' Benji's mouth drops
open and he starts eyeballing me like I'm kidding. I assure him I
wouldn't joke about a thing like this.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly, his attitude shifts to one of irritation. ``So tell me,
Ms. Schuett, if I can't be sure the spellcheck is going to get it
right, what do I do? I can't possibly memorize every single word in
the whole dictionary.'' I remind him that folks have been spelling
for a long time _ ever since Wilma Flintstone scratched the first
grocery list on her cave wall: basket of berries, shank of beast,
and a six-pack of Mountain Dew. Long before Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   Benji's not laughing. In fact, he's scrunching up his nose which
probably means he's stifling a sneeze or repositioning his
wire-frame glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Then Sally pipes up. ``Stop doing that to your nose, dummy. Mom
warned you what would happen if you keep doing that. Right Ms.
Schuett?'' I blindly agree and assure Benji that his mother knows
best.
</P>
<P>
   Benji's not in the mood for nitpicking. He tells his sister to
shut up and sets out to call my bluff: ``OK, Ms. Schuett,'' he
grins, ``what (SET ITAL)does(END ITAL) my mom say about my nose?''
</P>
<P>
   I place my hand over my eyes in a crummy imitation of Johnny
Carson doing Karnak the Omnipotent, and tell Benji that his mother
told him that if he didn't stop wrinkling up his nose like that,
he'd wake up one morning and discover it was stuck that way.
</P>
<P>
   Benji's amazed. ``How'd you know that?'' he asks doubtfully.
``Did you talk to my mom?'' I told him I didn't need to because the
consequences of juvenile nose wrinkling were universal knowledge
among mothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you think my nose got turned up on the end?'' I ask
innocently. Benji's not having any so he swings the subject back to
spelling. Sally's seen enough and is ready to go to lunch. She
demands her lunch money but Benji refuses to fork it over.
</P>
<P>
   Sally stomps her foot in an adept imitation of righteous
indignation, but when she realizes Benji is unmoved, she tries a
different tack. Blackmail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ms. Schuett,'' she asks slyly, ``have you smelled anything
funny around Benji lately?'' Her brother glares at her, reinforcing
the old ``if looks could kill'' cliche, and warns her to shut up.
She sticks out her hand, palm up, waiting for her money. Benji
pretends to spit in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's it, bird breath!'' Sally warns her brother as she turns
to me and dissolves into a giggle-fit. ``Guess what, Ms. Schuett.
The cat peed in Benji's sneaker. Pass it on.''
</P>
<P>
   Exasperated, Benji and his stinky sneaker stomp out of the room.
I loan Sally lunch money, and silently promise myself never to
admit to either one of them that I had already known about Benji's
misfortune. He'd been smelling like a sandbox all week.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, teachers, like mothers, don't tell everything they
know.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
