A4620 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALKER-COLUMN13-COX     04-12 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Equal pay eludes America's women
 &HT;    By Ana Pecina Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ In America, money talks.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, money puts its foot smack dab in its mouth.
</P>
<P>
   A very interesting item arrived by fax on Equal Pay Day. That
was Thursday, in case you missed the story.
</P>
<P>
   One of the things that happened Wednesday was a roundtable
discussion of the still existing pay gap between men and women in
the labor force. The president's Council of Economic Advisers
reported last year that women earn about 75 cents for every dollar
a man earns.
</P>
<P>
   The president is pushing the Paycheck Fairness Act in Congress.
In 1963, President Kennedy signed the Equal Pay Act. That was when
women still earned 58 cents for every dollar paid to male workers.
I guess it didn't take.
</P>
<P>
   During last week's discussion, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton
remarked that many still claim inequitable pay is a ``made-up
problem'' but that such discrimination is very real though very
subtle.
</P>
<P>
   The fax statement I received, in response to Equal Pay Day
efforts, was from the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, an essay under the
name of Thomas J. Donohue, president and CEO. He acknowledges ``a
few bad actors'' but agrees it is reasonable that women and men
with the same experience doing the same job should be paid the
same. However, he fears more government intervention, more lawsuits
and a stagnant economy if the act passes.
</P>
<P>
   You know, the same hysterical stuff we hear whenever the minimum
wage goes up, except that the predicted end to small business in
America has yet to happen. The other thing that's failed to happen
is equal pay.
</P>
<P>
   The ``subtle'' discrimination is not too subtle if you take a
look around. Donohue states that if women workers really came that
cheap, then everybody would have an all-female work force.
</P>
<P>
   Look in the classroom, sir.
</P>
<P>
   See the women teachers.
</P>
<P>
   See the rotten pay.
</P>
<P>
   See the men? No. They have gone to higher paying jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the many other low paying jobs and job categories and
see them populated by women. Watch salaries drop as women enter
once male dominated fields, even medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the lowest paying job, producing and rearing children.
We dollar-loving Americans talk a great line. We go on about how
important it is that children have a good beginning and how they
need someone to care for them and how, well, we just wouldn't be
here without our mamas.
</P>
<P>
   So what do we pay them?
</P>
<P>
   Not a dime.
</P>
<P>
   Because you see, it's their choice. Mr. Donohue says so. He
quotes a study, by two women no less, that ``women in their 20s and
30s who have never had children make virtually the same amount as
their male counterparts.''
</P>
<P>
   What is the message there? Have kids and pay the price? Don't
have kids and you'll earn equitable pay? If that message is heard
by many more, Mr. Donohue won't have anyone to fill those
low-paying jobs because if we have fewer babies, it means fewer
workers. And as happens with a shrinking labor force, salaries will
go up.
</P>
<P>
   Wait. Maybe I misjudged him. Maybe he does really want pay to go
up _ for everyone!
</P>
<P>
   Talk about a master of subtlety.
</P>
<P>
   Ana Pecina Walker is managing editor of the Longview
News-Journal, P.O. Box 1792, Longview TX 75606. E-mail:
awalker(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
