<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Casting Net can turn up a sea of fishing info
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Think of it as a fish Net.
</P>
<P>
   For a fisherman, the Internet is almost as handy as a good
source of red wiggler worms or a lifetime supply of Red Coachman
flies. And now that it's spring, many of us will leave the ghostly
light of the computer monitor for some time spent in the sunshine
on a river or lake.
</P>
<P>
   Let's take a look at some of the fishing information you can
find on the Web. Since this column is produced in Georgia, we'll
also look at some sites that offer specific help for here. Don't be
discouraged if you live in another state. A few minutes with a
search engine such as AltaVista or Yahoo! will produce plenty of
localized fishing sites.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to fishing, all of us are beginners. Even if you
know a lot about trout fishing, you may not know beans about
catching bluegill bream. A bass expert may be able to cite chapter
and verse on the various plastic worms available but be mystified
when it comes time to head north for a vacation fishing trip for
walleyes.
</P>
<P>
   So we'll start with a page called the Fishing Network at
www.the-fishing-network
</P>
<P>
   .com/. This is a terrific site because _ like a good tackle box
_ it contains almost everything you'll need. There are sections
that offer specific fishing advice for the various species of
freshwater fish; weather forecasts; chat areas where you can tell
your fishing story to someone who actually would like to hear it;
information on records (that way you'll know if that big bream is a
world-record-sized catch); calendars of outdoor and fishing
expositions and shows; and even a nice selection of fishing clip
art if you'd like to decorate a Web page or just add a picture of a
fish to an e-mail or newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Now that you have gathered some information, you'll want to get
a fishing license. After all, the money you spend for the license
will be used to stock the rivers and lakes, so it's money well
spent. Besides, those who don't have a license can find that the
fines make for a very expensive trip.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, you can get all the information you need about
licenses and fishing regulations at a Web site run by the state at
www.dnr.state.ga.us/dnr/wild
</P>
<P>
   /fishingreg/. You'll find out, for example, when the season
starts for various types of fish and how many you're allowed to
catch. And, for those who want to try fishing but are reluctant to
buy a license, go to www.dnr.state.ga
</P>
<P>
   .us/dnr/wild/fishingreg/freefish
</P>
<P>
   .html and find out about ``free fishing days'' in Georgia when
no license or trout stamp is required.
</P>
<P>
   Next you'll want to find out where the fish are biting. A good
source for Georgia information is located at www.wmi.org
</P>
<P>
   /bassfish/reports/GEORGIA/. You'll find a complete list of
lakes. Click on the place that interests you, and you'll get a good
report. Each report is dated, so you'll know how recent the
information is. (If you live in another state, try www.wmi.org
</P>
<P>
   /bassfish/reports/ and check to see if your state is listed so
that you can get the same type of information.)
</P>
<P>
   Finally, if you really want to put your computer to work as a
fishing buddy, you can download a program that offers you advice.
You'll enter information about the weather, time of year, species
of fish and then get help from the program. You can download a free
demonstration version of the program at ourworld
</P>
<P>
   .compuserve.com/homepages
</P>
<P>
   /strattech/fishexpe.htm (look for the link at the very bottom of
the page). Or you can order the commercial version of the program
for $26.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
