<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE-HEART13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    10-year-old bounces back after heart transplant
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ten-year-old Nick May rides his bike, goes swimming
and plays basketball just like his friends.
</P>
<P>
   But when May takes off his shirt in the summer, he looks a
little bit different. His tanned chest has a long scar _ a reminder
of the heart transplant he had when he was a baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the bump is kind of cool,'' said May, who has green
eyes and brown hair. ``It makes me a little special.''
</P>
<P>
   Like thousands of other children's hearts, May's heart didn't
work right when he was born. Instead of having four chambers in his
heart, May only had three _ a condition considered life
threatening.
</P>
<P>
   The heart needs to work correctly because it has to pump all the
blood and oxygen through the body. If it isn't able to do that _
either because of a defect or disease _ the body gets tired and
doesn't work right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the heart just wears out like a car engine,'' said
Dr. Robert Vincent, the medical director of pediatric heart
transplants at Egleston-Scottish Rite Medical Center in Atlanta.
``Sometimes, we can do surgery to fix it. But sometimes, we just
need to replace it.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the case with May, who had a heart transplant when he
was almost 2 years old.
</P>
<P>
   But most kids don't have such serious problems. For example,
more than half of all children are born with heart murmurs. Murmurs
are unusual sounds that doctors hear as they listen to blood
flowing through the heart _ similar to listening to water flowing
through the pipes of a house, Vincent said.
</P>
<P>
   But of those, only 5 in 1,000 actually have a problem that needs
to be fixed, he said. ``Heart murmurs are very common, but heart
defects are very rare,'' Vincent said.
</P>
<P>
   The most common defect is called ``ventricular septal defect,''
Vincent said. Usually, it is found and corrected in babies by the
time they are only 4 months old. This defect is basically a hole in
the wall between the heart's two pumping chambers, keeping the
organ from working correctly. Surgery can fix the problem.
</P>
<P>
   And because medicine has gotten better, most children with heart
problems can live like anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   May's days are like other kids' _ he throws on his clothes, eats
breakfast, and takes out the garbage (one of his many chores)
before going to school. At school, he participates in gym and
recess. He loves spelling. And at the end of the day, he does his
homework, helps with dinner and plays with his best friend, Clay.
</P>
<P>
   There are some differences, his mom, Susan May, says.
</P>
<P>
   May cannot play football, and he can't wrestle. That's because
doctors don't want to take a chance of someone hurting his heart.
And he must rest periodically while playing games. Unlike others,
he has no nerves to his heart because they had to be cut during his
transplant operation. That means his brain can't receive any
messages from his heart about how hard it's working. He has to plan
rest times to let his heart relax a little.
</P>
<P>
   And he has to take lots of pills so that his body doesn't reject
his new heart. In the morning, he has to take seven pills that are
pink, white and yellow. And in the evening, he has to take four
more pills.
</P>
<P>
   He also has to deal with two common questions: Where did his new
heart come from, and how much does it cost?
</P>
<P>
   Susan May said the surgery cost more than $100,000 and Nick
May's monthly medicine bill is $500. May's heart came from a little
boy who was accidently run over by a truck in his driveway.
</P>
<P>
   It is very sad for Nick and his family to think about this
child. But they are also very grateful that the child's parents
were kind enough to donate the heart even though their child died.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the greatest joy for me,'' Susan May said, ``is I've
got my child here with me because someone gave an incredible
gift.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
