<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Allies continue bombings in Yugoslavia
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Air strikes continued last week against the Serbs in
Yugoslavia, even though the Serb government said its attacks on the
Albanians living in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo were over.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and its North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) allies started attacking the Serbs three weeks ago. The
allies say the Serbs were trying to kill or displace the Kosovar
Albanians. The Kosovar Albanians want their province to be free of
Serb control.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin of Russia, a country that is friendly to
the Serbs, is threatening to aim Russian missiles at NATO countries
if bombings of Yugoslavia continue. LOST WORLD
</P>
<P>
   Scientists hit fossil jackpot
</P>
<P>
   Paleontologists (scientists who study dinosaurs and other
ancient forms of life) have found their own ``Jurassic Park'' off
the coast of England _ except all the dinosaurs are dead. The
scientists don't mind, though, because they can still learn a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Usually fossils are buried deep and are spread out. However, the
Isle of Wight fossils are concentrated in two tiny strips of land
very close to the surface. The tides and strong winds remove layers
of rock from the cliffs, unearthing the fossils.
</P>
<P>
   A PINE MESS
</P>
<P>
   Don't climb the tress
</P>
<P>
   We've all heard rules like ``No jumping on the bed'' and ``No
ball-playing in the house.'' But what about ``No climbing on the
trees''?
</P>
<P>
   That's what a park ranger told a man and his two daughters in
New York City's Central Park. The dad was fined $1,000 because his
daughters sat in a Japanese white pine tree.
</P>
<P>
   The dad says, ``Please give me a warning. I will make sure that
it will not happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   But park officials say it was too late _ the tree was damaged.
They said the trees are not native to New York and cost several
thousand dollars each.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   Gymnast's family makes up
</P>
<P>
   Olympic gymnast Dominique Moceanu may have found peace with her
parents.
</P>
<P>
   The 17-year-old gold medalist sued for her independence in the
fall, saying her father wasted the money she earned as a
professional gymnast. Her parents placed her money in a trust fund,
which they controlled. Moceanu would gain access to the money at
age 35.
</P>
<P>
   A judge declared her an adult in October. But it wasn't until
last week that she signed a financial settlement with her parents.
The details of the agreement were kept secret.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
