A4633 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-REPORT13-COX     04-12 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-REPORT13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Public Agenda well-informed
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Its tag line, the ``Journalist's Inside Source for
Public Opinion and Policy Analysis,'' might turn off any nonworking
journalist. But don't let it. The public opinion Web site is
worthwhile for anyone who enjoys informed debate.
</P>
<P>
   The contentious issues of our time are listed along the left
side of the opening page of the Web site, www.publicagenda.org. A
click on one, abortion, brings a list of options organized under
two sections: ``Understanding the Issue'' and ``Public Opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Understanding the Issue'' includes an overview of the topic,
including statistics and a history of the debate.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Notable &AMP; Newsworthy'' subsection offers links to recent
stories relevant to abortion, including stories about the hunt for
Eric Robert Rudolph in the Blue Ridge Mountains of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Fact File'' subsection offers a litany of statistics. For
abortion, the stats include age groups, the number of weeks into
the pregnancy that the abortion takes place and the reasons women
give for having them.
</P>
<P>
   The subsection called ``Framing the Debate'' lays out the major
perspectives. In this case, it's ``respecting life,'' ``respecting
the right to choose'' and ``respecting differences.'' Another link,
``Sources and Resources,'' offers hyperlinks to other Web sites,
contacts, phone numbers and addresses for some of the organizations
that follow the issue, such as the American Civil Liberties Union
and the Alan Guttmacher Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The second section, ``Public Opinion,'' has links to stories on
major points of view on the topic. Also included is a discussion
about how to avoid misrepresenting some of the statistics.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site is run by Public Agenda, a nonpartisan, nonprofit
public opinion research and education group based in New York City.
The organization was founded in 1975 by social scientist and author
Daniel Yankelovich and former Secretary of State Cyrus Vance.
</P>
<P>
   Public Agenda considers its mission to help leaders understand
the public's point of view on major policy issues and to help
citizens understand critical policy issues so they can make better
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   New color copiers
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard recently released a new round of digital color
copiers starting at $499.
</P>
<P>
   The HP Color Copier 160/170 is expected to sell for around $499.
The HP Color Copier 260/270 has a suggested retail price of $599.
The new copiers are sold at HP retailers.
</P>
<P>
   HP is gearing the copiers for the small-business market. The
copiers can copy color brochures, business presentations and
promotional materials. Small runs of color marketing materials or
presentations can be copied for 10 cents per copy, according to
Hewlett-Packard. The copiers handle up to 10 copies per minute.
</P>
<P>
   More information about the copiers is available at
www.hp.com/go/copiers.
</P>
<P>
   Check this calendar
</P>
<P>
   If your company or you are too financially conservative to
upgrade to the new line of full-service calendar software products,
there is a free version online.
</P>
<P>
   Jintek's ScheduleOnline is geared for the small to midsize
businesses. The calendar is available at www.scheduleonline.com.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego-based company is billing itself as the intranet
solution for organizations without the resources to get or run
full-service software applications. Intranets are private
Internets.
</P>
<P>
   The calendar functions let users maintain personal calendars,
set up meetings within their organizations and check for schedule
conflicts. If a user picks a specific date for an appointment, the
calendar function offers the choice of automatically sending an
invitation e-mail to attendees.
</P>
<P>
   PC Magazine said of ScheduleOnline: ``Ideal for organizations
needing to manage their people, places and things, ScheduleOnline
is fast and highly functional. ... Groups seeking online management
assistance should start by looking at this elegant and useful
site.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
