<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    First-aid kit can help you survive computer crash
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Back when I owned a 1968 MG-B _ when gasoline was 29
cents a gallon and nerds owned slide rules instead of computers _ I
could keep my car running myself.
</P>
<P>
   All that was required was a moderate amount of bravery, socket
wrenches and a bank account that was deposited in a half-gallon
wine jar. But as time passed, cars got more sophisticated with
computers that monitor and control the engine, fuel injection
systems and electronic modules that are meant to be replaced, not
fixed.
</P>
<P>
   It is the same with computers. When I started out, we not only
fixed our own computers, we built them. The computer programs, in
those earliest days, were written in a language called BASIC, and
software stores didn't exist. Instead, we created our own programs
by typing in computer code (often copied directly from one of the
early computer magazines).
</P>
<P>
   Even with all that, computers were fairly easy to understand and
fix. There were two big factors going for us. For one, we knew
something about the computer since we built it with chips,
resistors and late-night curses. For another, it was a relatively
simple beast, like that old MG-B of mine.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, computers are so complex that most of us are way over
our heads when it comes to working on them. Besides, today's users
are very different from the earliest computer enthusiasts. The
computer is now an appliance, and just as most of us don't expect
to be able to work on a refrigerator, few users have much interest
in learning how the thing works.
</P>
<P>
   All that said, there are a few things you can do yourself to
protect your computer against future troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with a crash recovery disk. You'll need it if your
computer takes a page from the behavior of that old MG-B and
refuses to start one day. There are a lot of possible reasons for
that calamity, ranging from a hard disk with mechanical problems to
conflicts caused by installing a new device or software. You'll
eventually care about the cause, but _ before you can reach that
state _ you'll need to get the computer going. The crash recovery
disk bypasses the hard disk and any problems there and gets the
computer going.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, this is one case where that complex computer of yours
will make things easy. Just double click to open the Control Panel,
open up the Add/Remove Program icon and select the tab labeled
Startup Disk. Just follow the instructions you'll find there to
create the disk. Since space is limited and you'll find the process
fairly painless, we'll move on to the next item.
</P>
<P>
   Think of this step as creating a first-aid kit for your
computer. If you've ever had a computer disaster, you already know
how that can freeze your brain. The disk with the drivers for your
video card becomes impossible to find, the manual that you got with
your computer _ the very thing you need to work on the problem _
has disappeared. And you can't even find the right-size screwdriver
to open up the computer case.
</P>
<P>
   You can already see where I'm going. Find a small plastic box
and fill it with everything you'd need if your computer crashed.
Add the crash recovery disk you just made, all the manuals for your
computer and accessories, the Windows installation disk, and
screwdrivers to open up the machine as well as the disks you'd need
to reinstall your regular programs. Make sure you include
passwords, network settings and user names for your Internet
account.
</P>
<P>
   A prudent person would add a bottle of aspirin to that first-aid
kit. The aspirin won't help the computer, but you'll probably need
it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
