</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHTOOLS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    USB camera ran afoul of immature technology
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Those of you who waded through the past couple of
episodes may have been left with the idea that the Philips USB PC
Camera, which provided me so many hours of gleeful entertainment,
is a total waste of time. That is not the case.
</P>
<P>
   I ran afoul of what we cognoscenti call ``immature technology.''
I had no sooner reached this conclusion than what should arrive but
an electronic message from a computer columnist at another large
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   He said he got a few chuckles at all the problems I had with
this little gadget, especially in light of the fact that he found
the Philips USB Camera to be very easy to install.
</P>
<P>
   I figured the curse of the Bus of Doom was already working on me
when he gallantly went on to say that he thought both views were
valid, and the culprit was the Universal Serial Bus its own self.
Its technology, in his opinion, was not yet mature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes to show that people should read more than one
review,'' he remarked. Amen.
</P>
<P>
   So the camera is one of those things that might work for you,
and then it might not. I imagine that the older your computer is,
the less likely it will be to work.
</P>
<P>
   Immature technology is something that was invented about the
same time as computers. It used to be, in the good old days, that
technology was allowed to mature in the laboratory before it was
inflicted upon the public. No longer. In the computer business, we
hop from one grand invention to another like a frog between lily
pads.
</P>
<P>
   Today's greatest thing since sliced bread will, in a year or so,
be replaced entirely by the greatest thing since the greatest thing
since sliced bread. What's more, we know it. Every year, Intel
produces a microprocessor many times faster than last year's. They
know they're going to do it. We know they're going to do it. The
question is, why can't they skip a few iterations, and then let us
slide happily along for a few years without having our computers
become obsolete before they get dusty?
</P>
<P>
   I don't really know. Trying to find out seems somehow like
asking Wotan why he decided to come down to Earth and start messing
with mortal women. But I suspect the applause of delighted
stockholders has something to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   Something like the Universal Serial Bus comes along, and
everyone has to figure out how to make something to plug into it.
But it takes some time, apparently, for everybody's USB to be the
same. When they are all the same, the technology is mature, and
will be ready to be rendered obsolete by something immature.
</P>
<P>
   It has always been thus.
</P>
<P>
   I can recall spending almost an entire day in the back room of a
computer store watching a very knowledgable salesman-technician
trying to make a 300-baud, state-of-the-art Hayes modem and
software work with my CP/M computer.
</P>
<P>
   The miserable thing wouldn't even take over the line and dial
for the first couple of hours. Somehow he got past the point of
dialing, but it wouldn't sustain a connection. It never would work.
</P>
<P>
   The store is gone now. So is Hayes. I know people who can talk
faster than a 300-baud modem could transmit data. But
communications technology is basically mature _ you plug your modem
into the receptacle with a little telephone icon beside it, plug
the phone line into the modem, turn on the computer, and the
chances are the computer will find the modem and set it up
automatically. Then the software will search for the modem, find
it, and set itself up. Not every time, but usually.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
