<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane S. Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Q: Please tell me how round toothpicks are made. I can imagine
little men standing before little lathes, yet I can't quite accept
that vision. _Jim Reece
</P>
<P>
   A: Here is the lowdown from Diamond Brands _ parent company of
toothpick giant Forster. Forster makes 7.2 billion toothpicks per
year. One-hundred-inch birch logs are cut into blocks which are
cooked with raw steam and veneered with a lathe. Veneered wood
sheets are processed in a dryer to remove moisture, cut into card
sizes and fed into a molding machine, which makes 12,000 round
dowels per minute! The dowels are then polished and pointed. The
final step is a shaker machine that packs 250 round toothpicks in a
box _ one box per second. Tomorrow, class _ how they make flat
toothpicks, which outsell round ones. Who brought America this oral
gratification device for adult men in pickups? Charles Forster in
1869, after noticing Brazilians whittling toothpicks from orange
trees. Until that time toothpicks were nondisposable items. To get
the idea across, Forster hired young men to demand disposable
toothpicks in restaurants all over Boston. Q: I have a request from
a German exchange student. Can you locate a Duke University
basketball jersey for him? _Eric Anderson
</P>
<P>
   A: Sure he doesn't want a UConn one instead? Order Duke Blue
Devil team wear _ golf shirts to shorts to volleyball T-shirts _ by
calling (800) VIA-DUKE. Basketball jerseys (royal/white,
reversible) are $25.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Last summer I had twins and my first cousin had quads. We
were talking about how we are all related. I think that I am her
children's second cousin and that our children are third cousins.
She thinks that she is my children's second cousin and that our
children are first cousins once removed. What is it? Would you
explain how someone is related once or twice removed? _Monica
Carlson
</P>
<P>
   A: Your children and her children are second cousins, says
genealogy whiz Erna Martin at the Texas State Library and Archives.
And your relationship to the quads? First cousin, once removed.
Here is the system for relationships in a nutshell: Find the
ancestor common to two people. The common ancestor is ``zero.''
Count down the generations to the subjects you are defining (in
this case, you're No. 2 from the common ancestor and your cousin's
quads are No. 3). Subtract one from the smaller number of
generations (No. 2 minus 1) to establish the cousin relationship.
Voila! First cousins. Next, subtract the smaller number of
generations from the larger number (No. 3 minus No. 2) to yield
``times removed.'' Thus, you're first cousins once removed. Too
much to remember? Send me a stamped, self-addressed envelope for a
copy of the ``Relationship Chart,'' which does the work for you _ a
fill-in-the-blank for first through seventh cousins and even those
pesky fourth cousins, three times removed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the best way to get my credit report? _Carol Jennings
</P>
<P>
   A: Credit reports are available from three bureaus, and all
charge for the reports. Fees are waved for residents of some states
(not Texas) and for those who have been denied credit, insurance,
employment or rental housing based on an incorrect report; the
unemployed seeking employment; or victims of fraud. The three
companies are: Experian (TRW), P.O. Box 2104, Allen, Texas
75013-2104, at (800) 682-7654; Equifax, P.O. Box 105873, Atlanta,
Ga. 30348, at (800) 685-1111; and Trans Union, P.O. Box 390,
Springfield, Pa. 19064, at (800) 916-8800.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I need your readers' help! I substitute in area elementaries
and teachers are glad for me to help students learn to collect
stamps. I did this for years when I had my own classroom. Would
readers be willing to tear the canceled stamped corners of their
mail and put them in an envelope to me? _Pam Binder
</P>
<P>
   A: Easy way to encourage young philatelists, readers. Send
canceled stamps to Binder's Stampfinders, 9605 Gambels Quail Drive,
Austin 78758-6224.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I know you can take metal mini-blinds outside and wash them
down with a hose but I have two-inch, white, wooden blinds in my
home. How do I clean these? They are really dusty. If I water-hosed
them down on a sunny day when they would dry quickly, would I be
doing them any harm? Also what can I use to clean the white plastic
patio furniture? It got really dirty over the winter and nothing
seems to get it white again. _Linda Rives
</P>
<P>
   A: Do not use water on wood. Drapery and blind expert Candy
McWilliams at ABC Blind and Drapery says the only way to get them
clean is to vacuum the blinds and then wipe each slat individually.
That is what they do for the wood blinds on display. The patio
furniture should respond to either a power sprayer or hand washing
with bleach and water (about one cup bleach to six cups water). A
good scrub brush and patience usually works. Q: Suddenly, all my
wife's gold rings _ college ring, wedding band, special rings, all
14K gold _ have started to stain her fingers as if the darn things
were made of brass. This problem shows up intermittently and is
somewhat embarrassing to her. Is she secreting (if that's the
proper word) some chemical causing this problem?
</P>
<P>
   _J. Johnson
</P>
<P>
   A: Your wife's body chemistry may have changed, says Austin
jeweler Benard Laves. She may be reacting to a metal used in 14K
gold _ nickel, copper or zinc. Dr. Eugene Schoch Jr. advises your
wife to get a general physical checkup to see how/if her body
chemistry has changed and to look at the medications she is taking.
As long as her general health is good there is no reason to believe
this is a sign of anything serious _ just an inconvenience.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where did Camp Lejeune gets its name? I think I may be
related to whomever it is named for.
</P>
<P>
   _Lucille LeJeune
</P>
<P>
   A: You may be related to Maj. Gen. John A. Lejeune, leader of
the Second Division (Army) in World War I and major general
commandant of the Marine Corps from 1920 through 1929. Marine
Barracks New River in North Carolina was renamed Camp Lejeune at
the end of 1942. Born in Pointe Coupee, La., Lejeune graduated from
the U.S. Naval Academy in 1888. Lejeune's Marine career began in
1890.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What ever happened to that wonderful actor Gardner McKay, who
was on ``Adventures in Paradise?''
</P>
<P>
   _Polly N.
</P>
<P>
   A: Captain Adam Troy, Korean War vet and trouble-shooter, sailed
the ocean blue in the Tiki III from 1959-62. If the Pacific had a
Route 66, Troy would have been on it _ sailing from adventure to
adventure. McKay, ne George Cadogan Gardiner McKay, is a
playwright, winner of several National Endowment for the Arts
grants and a Drama Critics Circle Award. His novel, ``Toyer,'' is
available in area bookstores such as Barnes and Noble.
</P>
<P>
   Write to the skipper/teacher/sculptor and raiser of African
lions in care of his publisher, Little, Brown and Co., 1271 Avenue
of the Americas, New York, N.Y. 10020.
</P>
<P>
   Q: This summer I am traveling through Canada with my best friend
and her parents' carnival. I am interested in buying a pet hedgehog
to take with me. I know that hedgehogs are legal in Canada (except
Quebec _ where I am not going). Will I be allowed to cross the
border with my pet? I will be in Canada about a month and plan to
keep the hedgehog in my house trailer. I need to know whether to
buy my hedgehog now or after the summer is over! _E.M.
</P>
<P>
   A: Dr. Rod Livingstone of the Canadian Food Inspection Agency
(it regulates animals in and out of the land of the maple leaf)
says the hedgehog may enter the country as a pet without any
problems _ no proof of vaccinations, etc. Hedgehog travel from some
countries into Canada is restricted when there is reason to believe
disease may be carried by the animal. However, you do need an
import permit to bring your pet back into the United States. Call
the U.S. Department of Agriculture at (301) 734-8364 to arrange for
a permit.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Basically the only thing needed to perpetrate I.D. fraud is
your name, Social Security number and a valid mailing address. I
have to give my Social Security number to my employer. Who else
must I give it to? What basis do I have for turning down a request?
_D.K.W.
</P>
<P>
   A: According to Social Security spokeswoman Sandra Talbot,
``Giving your Social Security number is voluntary, even when you
are asked for the number directly. You can refuse.'' Some
businesses see it as an easy, unique number to use for record
keeping without realizing the danger of identity theft. If your
number is requested, Talbot advises you ask why it is needed; how
it is going to be used; what law requires you to give the number;
and what the consequences are if you refuse. Sometimes there is a
way around using the number; sometimes not, as in the issuance of a
Texas driver's license.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The Wilkinson Sword Company of England made the first and, in
my opinion, the best stainless steel razor blades. I have been
unable to locate them lately. Could you find a local source? _Jack
Jennings
</P>
<P>
   A: Nope. Wilkinson _ at least in the United States and Canada _
is now Schick. Call (800) SHAVERS to describe the razor you have
and find out which Schick product will work with it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can a 26-year-old like me get a chance to play pro
football _ like the NFL or something? Who would I contact? I have
been out of high school nine years and don't plan on going to any
major colleges. Would that count against me? _David V.
</P>
<P>
   A: Have any game tapes? If so, you might be asked to try out for
Austin's first indoor football team, the Texas Terminators, says
president Jeff Parnell. Send the tape to 609 W. Sixth St., Suite B,
78701. Best-case scenario, you could be on the field in a matter of
days. This is a great place for the NFL scouts to ``discover'' you.
Parnell warns would-be football players, ``Lots of guys look good
in a T-shirt and shorts, but we want to see what you can do in
pads.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Could you help me find a copy of Johnny Carson's last show?
We have three tapes of early years but not the last show. We miss
Johnny. _Tommie P.
</P>
<P>
   A: The final show, ``America Says Farewell,'' is no longer
available by itself. It is part of a set of retrospective shows. To
order ($44.99), call Movies Unlimited at (800) 523-0823. Carson was
not always the king of late night. His other television shows
included Sunday afternoon's ``Carson's Cellar,'' a short-lived CBS
show called ``The Johnny Carson Show,'' the forgettable ``Earn Your
Vacation,'' a stint as a substitute host for Jack Paar and a host
for the game show ``Who Do You Trust?'' Contact Jane Greig, author
of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX, 78767; (512)
445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
