<SLUG> BC-NETWATCHER13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Salon brings depth to Kosovo coverage
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``The cruelty is unimaginable,'' writes Laura Rozen,
who is covering the war in Yugoslavia from nearby Macedonia for
online Webzine Salon.com. Rozen is an excellent storyteller, and
her reports of the tragedy of the Kosovars _ businessmen,
secretaries, housewives, blue-collar workers and schoolchildren
suddenly stripped of everything but the clothes on their backs _
are riveting.
</P>
<P>
   It's a must-read for those who want to go beyond political
posturing and understand what really is happening to the displaced
people of Kosovo and the bomb-weary residents of Belgrade
(www.salon.com/news
</P>
<P>
   /feature/1999/04/05/kosovo/).
</P>
<P>
   Salon's coverage of the war in Yugoslavia has a breadth and
depth unexpected of a nontraditional, Web-only publication. While
Rozen reports from the scene, Joe Conason stays home, but wonders
why potential presidential candidate George W. Bush hasn't taken a
stand on the NATO bombings in an article called ``The Wobblers''
(www.salonmagazine.com/news/col/cona/1999/04/06/conason/).
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush's nervous failure to take a stand on the most pressing
question of the moment recalls Margaret Thatcher's admonition to
his dad, George Sr., when hostilities started in the Persian Gulf:
`Don't go wobbly on me now,''' Conason writes. ``Bush's wobbling on
Kosovo is the inevitable product of his urge to please all factions
in his divided party.''
</P>
<P>
   This news coverage is a strong showing from Salon, which stormed
its way into the Web news business last year with sensational and,
some say, biased coverage of the Clinton sex scandal and its
30-year-old revelations of an affair by Rep. Henry Hyde, chairman
of the committee conducting the presidential inquiry. Now the site
ranks in the top 500 most popular sites on the Web and seems to
have reporters doing real reporting from every corner and every
angle of the Kosovo story.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo coverage is just another high point in what's been a
pretty big week for Salon. First, founder and CEO David Talbot
finally wrestled away the Salon.com Web address with a promise of
stock and an undisclosed payment to Roy Frederickson, owner of two
beauty salons in Austin, Texas, who had hoped to develop a portal
for the hairdressing industry. Previously, the 1.2 million monthly
Salon junkies have been getting to the site by bookmarking
Salonmagazine.com or salon.net or salon1999.com, the address the
site launched with in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Salon took over the Salon.com address Monday (4/5) and launched
a redesigned site that separated content into areas including news,
arts, technology, health, books and the popular ``Mothers Who
Think.''
</P>
<P>
   This one small shift makes stories easy to find. And the stories
are worth finding whether it's breaking news about Yugoslavia, or
David Ratoff, or Michelle Goldman deconstructing Gwyneth Paltrow.
Salon seems have its pulse on what people are talking about,
thinking about, wondering about or might actually be doing, as is
the case of Thomas Scolville's workplace serial ``Silicon Follies''
(www.salon.com/21st/follies/about/about.html).
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a medium for New Yorker-type content. It's a
medium for newspaper-type content,'' Talbot has said. ``What the
Web is mostly known for at this point is cud-chewing punditry.
That's fine. It's a good medium for that. We decided we want to go
beyond that and start breaking stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Talbot says he knows his boutique publication can't compete with
massive newsgathering organizations such as CNN or MSNBC, but as
Talbot's staff continues to go where the news and pop culture are
heading, he may have also unwittingly found the secret to making
content profitable.
</P>
<P>
   To paraphrase James Carville: It's the interactivity, stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Salon's stable of ``cud-chewing pundits,'' who write for the
magazine, combined with the ``cud-chewing pundits'' who post
messages to Salon's Table Talk and who log onto one or more of the
200 discussion groups on the Well, the celebrated online community
Salon acquired Wednesday, could really make Salon a salon. The
artists, writers, technology geeks, academic types and other deep
thinkers who populate the Well will now be able to ``chew their
cud,'' about the news and trends of the day _ the same topics so
comprehensively covered in Salon.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Salon nor the Well will say just how Salon will
integrate it on the Web _ if it plans to integrate it at all. But a
few carefully placed links on the Well site could attract just the
sort of sophisticated, Web-savvy readers Salon covets. They're
exactly the type who might pony up $25 to become Salon members,
too.
</P>
<P>
   With the acquisition of the Well, Salon may be on its way to
having it all _ content, community and commerce. It's a combination
readers on Main Street and investors on Wall Street may find
irresistible. So, keep an eye out for those war dispatches _ and an
initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
