<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Windows looks at 15 common PC problems
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Computers and operating systems break down all too
often. Now you can find solutions to some problems in the April
issue of Windows magazine. Its cover story is devoted to fixing 15
common PC problems. You'll find suggestions on how to fix scanners
that don't scan, sleeping computers that don't wake up and random
system hang-ups.
</P>
<P>
   The April issue of Windows also includes a preview of the coming
upgrade of WordPerfect Office Suite, the biggest competitor to
Microsoft Office. Windows gives WordPerfect Office a generally
thumbs up review. It says maker Corel has focused on making the
program easier to use. There are a couple of new features, such as
one that lets you preview a change in style before making it
permanent in a document.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   Springtime is academic test time, and there's some new software
out to help kids prepare. Emergency Prep is a computer CD that
offers a crash course in preparing for college admission tests.
It's a one-week course that claims to offer techniques for educated
guessing as well as time-saving strategies. Emergency Prep is
published by Kaplan, the leader in test preparation courses, and
Knowledge Adventure. It's available for both Macs and PCs.
</P>
<P>
   You can command a futurist tank battleship in ``Thunder
Brigade,'' a new arcade-type game from Interactive Magic. In
``Thunder Brigade,'' you command a flying tank. It's well-armed and
highly mobile. You move across a dozen different planets, fighting
as a member of a freedom brigade. The bad guys are members of the
Halon Empire, described in the game as ``cruel warmongers.'' You
play as a member of the Earth Alliance, ``a highly disciplined and
well-equipped'' group of fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   Here's a Web site that's different. NY-Taxi.com offers a tour of
the Big Apple _ from a cab driver's perspective. The site is based
on a popular new book, ``New York City From a Cab Driver's View.''
It's written by a real cab driver named Clever Da Silva. I kid you
not. You'll find this site at www.ny-taxi.com/.
</P>
<P>
   Check out the bookstore of the future at NetLibrary. This is a
site that offers totally electronic books for sale. That is, you
download these books onto your computer for reading. NetLibrary
also offers some free books, which are in the public domain. You'll
find NetLibrary at www.netlibrary.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
