<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4656 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     04-12 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, April 12, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Tuesday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-MASS (Oakland, Calif.) _ Women gather at a park for a
joyful religious ceremony. They call it a Roman Catholic Mass.
Others call it heretical. For the first time in the country, on a
regular, public basis, women are holding prayer services that until
now have been conducted in secret, within hundreds of homes but by
invitation only, a sort of liturgical underground. By ELIZABETH
FERNANDEZ.
</P>
<P>
   DAM-CONTROVERSY (Spencerville, Calif.) _ Spencerville died a
century ago when its copper mine played out, but its namesake
wildlife refuge lives on. Now, while Interior Secretary Bruce
Babbitt and other environmentally attuned officials are closing
obsolete dams to free rivers, the Yuba County Water Agency wants to
build a dam that would flood much of a rich wildlife habitat in the
Sierra Nevada foothills. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   MISSING-TOURISTS (Eureka, Calif.) _ Inside their modest,
pale-green California bungalow, the routines of family life for
Jens Sund and his three children go on much as they always have as
part of Jens Sund's effort to preserve some sense of normalcy for
his family, despite the mid- February slayings of his wife, Carole,
15-year-old daughter Juli, and family friend Silvina Pelosso, 16,
after their visit to Yosemite. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTA-McAULIFFE (Troy, N.Y.) _ Despite the death of her
daughter Christa McAuliffe in the 1986 Challenger explosion, Grace
Corrigan remains a supporter of space exploration. ``I think it is
necessary to do all the exploring they can do,'' she said. By TIM
O'BRIEN.
</P>
<P>
   SF-SCHOOLS (San Francisco) _ San Francisco public schools have
astounded educators nationwide by posting six years of consecutive
test score gains. But an Examiner analysis raises questions about
whether the gains are real or manipulated. By JULIAN GUTHRIE.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PEACE-STUDIES (Colonie, N.Y.) _ It's not necessary to get
arrested while studying peace. But it helps. Peace studies programs
flourish on 250 campuses nationwide, including Notre Dame, Syracuse
and Colgate. By ALAN WECHSLER
</P>
<P>
   PICTURE-SHOW (Canadian, Texas) _ The end was near for Main
Street's Palace Theatre, even with the nearest multiplex 100 miles
away. Then last year a businessman pumped nearly $1 million into
the decaying Palace, restoring it to its mid-century prime. But the
Palace is not an anomaly _ Texans have restored nearly 100
small-town theaters in the past two decades. By THADDEUS HERRICK.
</P>
<P>
   FOUR-POSTER-BEDS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Four-poster beds add an
elegant, eye-catching touch to any bedroom, whether the posts are
ornamented with a fabric tester and fabric curtains or not. The
popularity of this style of bed spans three centuries and
continues. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) Column on sweet potatoes. By KATHY
HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-COMMUNITY (Glenmont, N.Y.) _ Some people are preparing for
Y2K _ the threat of computer problems when the calendar turns to
2000 _ by moving to the country and buying generators and guns. But
others are doing the opposite. In churches, in schools on campus or
in private homes, rather than causing panic, the threat of trouble
on New Year's, 2000, is bringing people together. By ALAN WECHSLER.
</P>
<P>
   AGING-BOOMERS (San Francisco) _ I just received another offer
for a newsletter on aging. It promises that if (and only if) I
subscribe, I will look better, feel better, enjoy life more and
generally be the terrific person they think I should be. What's
wrong with who I am now? Apparently, everything. By RUTH SHERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-MIDWAY (Undated) _ The Battle for Midway in 1942 pitted
American against Japanese naval forces that clashed in the sea and
air over a spit of coral and sand 1,000 miles from nowhere. ``The
Battle for Midway,'' a National Geographic special airing Wednesday
on TBS, offers a compelling look at this great naval encounter. By
MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Undated) Column on troubled women finding job
skills. By L.M. SIXEL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Just a few years ago, I was a
champion at the San Francisco national sport of dining out. The
goal is to find a great restaurant before it's reviewed and the
food ghouls arrive, all ordering exactly the same things mentioned
in the review. Now I've moved on to a higher level of foodiedom. By
ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The following quotations are
from news stories that have appeared since January. The italicized
paragraphs are from ``Shifting Fortunes: The Perils of the Growing
American Wealth Gap,'' published by the Boston-based organization,
United for a Fair Economy. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ The fragility of the NATO
coalition grows, it seems, almost by the day as airplanes from the
alliance bomb ever more targets in Yugoslavia with perhaps marginal
effect to bring Slobodan Milosevic to heel. Second-guessing is
rampant. By HARRY ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) Column on Texas politics. By CLAY
ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   FLORES-COLUMN (San Antonio) _ Estelle Lawton, a public health
nurse supervisor, is no longer surprised to hear 50-year-old women
tell her they've never done a breast self-examination. The stresses
and cultural taboos faces by poor, minority women make them
particularly vulnerable to breast cancer. By VERONICA FLORES.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
