<P>
   In New Guinea's rain forest, environmentalists and business
executives are learning that what's good for this pristine world is
also good for the bottom line. The author, a professor of
physiology and an avid bird-watcher, makes his 17th visit to New
Guinea and discovers an elusive bird _ a cassowary _ living near
the oil fields. What makes it possible for this big, shy,
ostrichlike bird _ rarely found anywhere near the disturbances
people create _ to survive alongside the country's largest
operating oil and natural gas field?
