<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: Caveat emptor: just stop looking
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I get all creepy-crawly even writing this. We are indebted to
New York Times arts reporter Carol Vogel for informing us of a
British exhibit headed our way in the fall. The show is called
``Sensation,'' and that is fair warning. Art is meant, sometimes,
to inflame and outrage. This exhibit bears a particularly onerous
load.
</P>
<P>
   Vogel says the show will include a dead shark afloat in
formaldehyde, a man's head cast in frozen blood and a depiction of
an artist's dead, naked father. The Times article itself is
accompanied by a photo of a pig, split longitudinally, titled
``This Little Piggy Went to Market.'' The show, expected to attract
the young and the senseless, should get all the censorious
attention it screams for. We're suckers for provocation.
</P>
<P>
   What to do? Easy. Don't censor. Don't go. Don't look. Let the
marketplace speak, not the censors.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, the American Nazi leader George Lincoln Rockwell made
a speaking appearance at Antioch College in Yellow Springs, Ohio.
As soon as Rockwell began his customary rant, the audience silently
walked out. Rockwell was left sputtering angrily at the mike. He
had not been censored. Worse, he had been ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
