<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4808 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ATROCITIES-BOS     04-12 1805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ATROCITIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS ATROCITY REPORTS RISE, SO DOES THE FRUSTRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ The pattern of atrocities against ethnic
Albanians is emerging like a photograph slowly developing, one
horrifying image after another.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence mounts, but the question remains: Will those
responsible ever be held accountable? Will Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic be prosecuted by the international war crimes
tribunal?
</P>
<P>
   Desperately trying to document a case for the prosecution amid
the chaos of a refugee crisis, Sheri Fink of the Boston-based
Physicians for Human Rights scribbled notes Saturday of the
testimony of refugees who had just arrived across the border.
</P>
<P>
   A 70-year-old woman from Pristina told of Serb paramilitaries in
black ski masks ordering her from her home at gunpoint, while a
next-door neighbor who resisted was stabbed to death on her front
step.
</P>
<P>
   Shaken and distraught members of a village near the border had
come to her with rumors _ not independently verified _ that Serb
troops had lined up 20 young men and forced them into a ditch, then
tossed in a grenade to kill them all.
</P>
<P>
   Fink's group is part of a network of international human rights
organizations and investigators from the United Nations and the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, all intent on
putting together the documentation they will need to bring those
responsible to justice.
</P>
<P>
   The work is painstaking and time-consuming. The stories must be
corroborated, and must be thoroughly spelled out in long
interrogations of witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   But human rights workers here say they have been too busy
pitching in to meet the emergency needs of more than 600,000
refugees who have fled Kosovo into bordering Macedonia, Albania,
and Montenegro, in the worst humanitarian crisis in Europe since
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to roll up our sleeves and work on the urgent
needs of these people,'' Fink, 30, a physician, said as she tried
to find a few hours to continue questioning of victims before she
returned to a medical tent at the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all want to see these atrocities exposed and the people who
committed them brought to justice,'' she said. ``Of course it is
frustrating that we can't focus on that right now. It is worrisome
because at some point, if you wait too long, you can lose the
truth. Memory is a strange thing. Stories can slip away. Important
details vanish.''
</P>
<P>
   Truth is becoming a perishable commodity as the days of this
crisis turn into weeks. As the victims are bused here and there,
and as rumors whip through the camps, the true history of this
horror may be vanishing, and with it the chance at ensuring that
perpetrators are prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   The findings of preliminary field reports, just compiled by the
OSCE, were made available to The Boston Globe. They are not
extensive, but they do form an image of a campaign of terror.
</P>
<P>
   There are scores of accounts of people ordered from their homes
at gunpoint, of looting, of sporadic summary executions for those
who refused to leave. There are allegations of systematic rape and
pillage, which have been reported by the Pentagon. But all of these
accounts must be verified.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, the world's rights detectives are struggling to
piece together a case involving a crime scene that stretches across
the rocky terrain of Kosovo, where they are not allowed access, and
a list of hundreds of thousands of potential witnesses who are too
busy fleeing for their lives to stop and fill out questionnaires on
what happened to them.
</P>
<P>
   The international community is in many ways far more prepared
for this crisis in the Balkans than for the Bosnia conflict that
began in 1991. It wasn't until two years later that a war crimes
court, the International Criminal Tribunal for the Former
Yugoslavia, was formed, based in the Dutch capital, The Hague.
</P>
<P>
   The tribunal has indicted more than 80 people so far _ six of
whom have been convicted, one acquitted. Charges were dropped
against 18 others.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most notorious Yugoslav war criminals remain
fugitives, and critics say the international peacekeepers have not
done enough to capture them.
</P>
<P>
   The budget of the tribunal has grown to $94 million and its
staff to 625. The tribunal also may benefit from extensive NATO
satellite imagery to help document the case.
</P>
<P>
   But amid the overwhelming refugee crisis, some rights workers
say they fear that as horrible as Milosevic and his forces' acts of
``ethnic cleansing'' are, the opportunity to prosecute those
responsible will slip away if they don't turn their attention to
the task immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Some tribunal critics point out that The Hague has no
investigators yet in Macedonia and only a handful in Albania, where
the bulk of the Kosovar refugees fled.
</P>
<P>
   Early Saturday, in a hotel in Skopje, 12 members of human rights
monitoring groups met to try to coordinate a strategy. Agencies
divided up responsibilities to document the human rights
violations.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Human Rights Watch, Amnesty International,
Doctors without Borders, the OSCE, Physicians for Human Rights, and
other groups met with the United Nations High Commission for Human
Rights, which is taking the lead role in coordinating their
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Bernd Borschardt, deputy head of mission for the OSCE, said:
``We are right in the middle of a humanitarian crisis. So for the
people going through that, they have not been ready to talk to us
yet. They are too focused on their own very desperate situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Borschardt was the coordinator for the OSCE inside Kosovo, where
a staff was monitoring human rights violations until the
organization ordered its staff workers out three weeks ago as the
negotiations between Milosevic and NATO collapsed and conflict
seemed inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   He described the frustration of not being in Kosovo to document
and expose the atrocities being reported. There was a sense of fury
among rights workers that Milosevic should have escaped outside
scrutiny while carrying out a campaign of terror. But, he said, the
monitors, as much as they wanted to stay, had to leave or face
almost certain death.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I looked out my office window and saw tanks rolling by
piled up with looted goods from homes next door, I knew it was time
to go. That was about saving lives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, he was working frantically, answering one phone call
after another, and trying to organize his staff. He showed
frustration with the difficulties of coordinating with
investigators in Albania, where, he said, ``reliable but
unconfirmed'' reports of widespread rape and atrocities were
surfacing.
</P>
<P>
   The organization does not have investigators in Montenegro
because of the dangers present for them in the smaller of the two
republics of Yugoslavia. He said the organization was bringing in
92 more people to assist in the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Jiri Dienstbier, the former Czech foreign minister and special
UN envoy for human rights, had just arrived and was rushing from
the hotel to the field to assess the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to collect as much information as possible to
determine Milosevic's strategy, to determine exactly how and why he
systematically cleared the areas he did. But these investigations
will be long and deep. It will have to take time,'' Dienstbier
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to move fast to document these cases,'' he added. ``It
is true that time is very important. But we also have to move in a
way that is thorough and methodical and detailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   The rights workers also have been slowed because the victims are
simply in too much distress. They are waiting in six-hour lines for
daily food packets, and many were desperately trying to reunite
families splintered by the chaos of the border crossings and the
camps they have been forced into in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   At a wall plastered with hand-written notes of family members
trying to connect with separated loved ones, Faik Dragusha, 60,
peered through bifocals with one cracked lens, searching for any
news of his son.
</P>
<P>
   Dragusha, an oil truck driver, said that he and his family had
been waiting in a line of refugees several miles long at the border
three days ago when Serb paramilitary troops approached their car.
One of the soldiers smashed the car window with the butt of his
rifle and ordered Dragusha's 24-year-old son out of the vehicle and
took him away.
</P>
<P>
   Dragusha fears he may never see his son again. But consumed with
trying to get news of his son, he has not taken the time to
communicate the incident to human rights workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to find him. That is the only thing I can do right
now,'' he said as he wandered back into the rows of tents.
</P>
<P>
   As a cold drizzle began to fall at dusk Saturday, notes on a
wall, written in felt tip markers began to run.
</P>
<P>
   In a far corner of the sprawling Brazde refugee camp, a member
of the OSCE human rights monitoring team, Ed Knowles of California,
was sitting behind a folding table under a tent. One woman,
Lulieta, 23, approached the tent hesitantly with a story of how her
family had been ordered out of their home at gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   She wanted to be sure that Knowles documented it. But over two
hours, she was the only one who came, and eventually Knowles was
called on to go and help out with the OSCE's processing of
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Knowles had been inside Kosovo until three weeks ago. He said
that he had been documenting atrocities and seeing a pattern
forming in the weeks leading up to the NATO strikes. But after they
began, the atrocities took on a ferocious intensity, Knowles said.
</P>
<P>
   The paramilitary forces, a dozen different bands with names like
Arkan's Tigers, White Eagles, and the Frenkis, attach themselves to
what is known as ``the MUPs,'' a Serb nickname for the special
police under the Serbian Ministry of the Interior.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a witchhunt,'' Knowles said, explaining that civilians in
the towns and villages lead the paramilitaries to homes of ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going on right now inside there,'' Knowles, said,
gesturing to the rocky hillsides in the distance where the border
lies, 5 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday afternoon, Fink drove out to the border to see if
any refugees were getting through. She was stopped by Macedonian
police, who refused to let her pass into the no man's land where
there were unconfirmed reports that refugees were not being
permitted through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is important and very much of the essence, but these
atrocities will not go away,'' Fink said. ``We just have to work
much harder to make them come to light. I have to believe that. I
have to believe that Milosevic and those repsonsible won't get away
with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
