<DOCNO> NYT19990412.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4810 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALKANS-VOICES-BOS &LR;      04-12 1552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALKANS-VOICES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINDOWS ON A WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 
(Editor's note: As NATO's assault on Yugoslavia began last month,
Globe reporter Patti Hartigan e-mailed a contact in Belgrade to ask
for an on-line account of what was happening. She has received
scores of responses.)
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the face of the crackdown on independent media in Yugoslavia,
the Internet has become a prime source of information in Belgrade
and beyond. It is functioning as a virtual town square in the
war-torn Balkans; residents surf the Web for credible information,
post messages on bulletin boards, and send e-mail all over the
world. Complete strangers _ from Kansas to Kosovo _ are discussing
the conflict on line. The global village has never been more vital.
</P>
<P>
   A single query produces a deluge of responses, from private
diaries of Belgrade mothers worried about their children, to
missives from activists agonizing over the fate of the ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo, to Americans searching for ways to help the
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   This communication is both immediate and intimate, yet detached
and distanced. There is always a surreal quality, an eerie feeling,
that comes with virtual communication, but it is vastly more
pronounced during a time of military conflict. There is a curious
mix of empowerment and impotence: to be so close, yet so very far
away.
</P>
<P>
   What follows are various voices from the war zone. Some were
relayed to the Globe via the Internet and others were obtained from
various Web sites monitoring the situation. Each has been verified.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Every evening, at dusk, my hands start to tremble without
control. It goes on for a few hours. I heard that some other women
have the same symptoms of fear of air raids after dusk. Men behave
differently; they raise their voices and have more opinions than
usual on matters of life and death. We are afraid of their death
more than of our death. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``My father dreamed all last night that he was saving me from
the bombs. He was sleepwalking as he used to do when he was young,
taking me as a baby in his arms and rushing to the door. It went on
for years, his war trauma, until it stopped with this new war. He
passed it on to me. I started dreaming his dream. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends and enemies from all over the world ask me, `Do you
realize how terrible it is in Kosovo?' I do, I really do, and I
feel guilty that we feel bad here without having the horror they
do. But our war, for the past 10-50 years, has always been this
kind of invisible horror. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel we are being cut away from the rest of the world, more
bridges down, more friends and enemies pointing out to us here how
bad we are, more crazy people here making careers on screaming how
we are heavenly people. And the people? In cellars or just in beds
waiting for nothing. I dreamed last night of bombs falling in my
cellar, in my bed, and afterwards feeling relieved and free. I
should stop writing. I hate my dreams, thoughts, and words.''
</P>
<P>
   Jasmina Tesanovic, feminist author and educator in Belgrade, via
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The streets are different. We used to have heavy firing at
night but not so much during the day. Now there is shooting all of
the time, day and night. It's not fighting, just shooting in all
directions. Everyone is shooting outside. It is going on now. . . .
Only women dare go out. The men are too vulnerable. But there were
no shops open and nothing to buy. Already we started using the food
that we had set aside as reserves. . . . We have four families
living in a three-bedroom flat, fifteen people. So we have more
mouths to feed. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not afraid that someone will come and kill me if it will
be a quick death. Nowadays, only living started scaring me to
death. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Another e-mail, a few hours later:
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been ordered to leave the apartment. We're going NOW,
I don't know where. Pray for me.''
</P>
<P>
   A correspondent, who asked not to be identified, for the
Institute on War and Peace, sending e-mail from Pristina. As
reported on the institute's Web site, http://www.iwpr.net.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this ends quick, and at the end, after one century
under Serbia, the people of Kosova get to see some freedom. After
all, I'd rather die from NATO bombs than from Serbian tortures,
rapes, massacres.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we talk soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ciao, V.
</P>
<P>
   ``P.S. Oh yeah, I forgot, kiss Bill Clinton for me once. I will
name my son after him.''
</P>
<P>
   An e-mail from Kosovo posted on www.alb.net; names were altered
for protection.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like you to know that we haven't been ignorant, nor
indifferent about what has been going on in (Kosovo). Most of us
have relatives and friends living there, and the news always found
a way to leak through. . . . Why didn't we do anything about it?
That is a question which mystifies me, too. Maybe that's the sin we
are paying the price for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I would like to make another point here, too. When we did
eventually take to the streets in the massive student demonstration
here in Belgrade during the winter of '96-'97, the world gave us no
support at all. I kept freezing my butt off (excuse the language)
for three months to no avail. . . .The teachers' protest, when I
nearly got beaten up by a policeman, got no support. So one thing
led to another, and here we have this mess today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am . . . angry with the political leaders of my country. . .
. Personally, I am more afraid of them than NATO, because NATO will
leave and those freak-heads are staying. May God help us with
them!''
</P>
<P>
   Vesna Novakovic, 44, a teacher and translator in Belgrade, via
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Political differences have now vanished. This is caused by
general condemnation of NATO air strikes. It seems that national
homogenization has never been stronger than it is now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I think that both the international community and
the Yugoslavian government are to be blamed for neglecting the
serious problem of ethnic minorities in Kosovo in the past decade.
Public opinion is now unified; everyone is talking about the
difficulties of the dominant people/nation in Serbia. There is a
general neglect of the burning question of the Albanian population
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   By this act of violence all the layers of liberal and democratic
resources which we planted and raised throughout these ten years
are now destroyed. I am feeling as if all perspective of my future
is vanishing. These days I cannot do my regular job in the Belgrade
Circle office, and even less can I read, write or translate
texts.''
</P>
<P>
   Obrad Savic, editor in chief of the Belgrade Circle Journal, via
e-mail from Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What they call shelters are actually dark, smelly and damp
cellars, because most buildings are like buildings in every city
center _ old. My mom's building dates from 1934, and as socialism
in Yugoslavia was not prone to maintenance, compared to Prague, for
example, a collateral damage can easily come just from the blast
ripple. And she doesn't even want to go to the shelter, says it's
boring just to sit there.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanja Oduber, a Belgrade native and freelance journalist living
in Aruba, via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A systematic terror is very foreseeable, not only against
anti-nationalist or anti-fascist (activists) but anyone who is not
ready to strangle the other ethnic individual on the spot. Did
others tell you that men over 16 can't go out? The most active
general said yesterday . . . (that) all suspicious characters will
be disciplined duly and neatly. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``This message is becoming my diary, I would rather give a
lecture on the subject one day when/if it becomes possible to speak
out of the present codes.''
</P>
<P>
   Zarana Papic, social anthropologist and assistant professor at
the University of Belgrade, via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Operating in war conditions involves enormous risks and we are
prepared to run those risks until we are physically prevented from
doing this job. Visits from the police almost daily, and hours of
questioning, indicate that increased repression is possible in the
future. The introduction of courtmartials and threats to bring back
the death penalty not only aggravate the psychosis but present a
clear and immediate danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are leaving the country in droves, but we believe that
someone must remain to pick up the pieces of the democratic
processes when the war is over. Many achievements on the democratic
front have now been destroyed. Somebody with the will and the
ability to build democratic institutions must remain. Foremost
among those institutions are the independent media which are the
basis for any democratic change and reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Statement of the independent Belgrade radio station, Radio B92,
posted on their Web site on April 1, the day before the station was
shut down by Serb police.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Our slogan used to be: `Don't trust anyone, not even us.' To
this we have now added, `But keep the faith.'
</P>
<P>
   ``(The) struggle continues. We shall never surrender.''
</P>
<P>
   Posted on Radio B92's web site on April 2. The station has not
reported any new stories since.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
