<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !!! Cookie's Fortune Robert Altman, in a light, warm,
audience-pleasing mood, fills the screen with Southern eccentrics
in an archetypal Mississippi Delta town. The film is anchored by
the low-key decency of Charles S. Dutton as a man wrongfully
accused of murder, and by Glenn Close's wicked witch of the South,
busily staging a production of ``Salome'' and behaving as if she
wants everyone's head on a platter, not just John the Baptist's.
(PG13) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   !!! Dream Life of Angels French filmmaker Erick Zonka makes an
assured and increasingly moving debut in this naturalistic and
always spontaneous tale of two young women in the city of Lille,
drifting between nowhere jobs and nowhere boyfriends. If Hollywood
had made this film, it would have seemed cute or rigged; Zonka
fills it with existential tang. (R) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   !!! Go Doug Limon's follow-up to ``Swingers'' is slick and edgy
and barely conceals the obviousness of its manipulations, but it
lives up to its title, as it propels a screenful of Angelenos
through a wild couple of nights. Sarah Polley is the standout here,
as a woman fleeing the consequences of an amateur drug deal gone
nighmarishly wrong. (R) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   !!! Never Been Kissed Drew Barrymore's winning streak continues
in the romantic comedy that casts her as an undercover reporter who
goes back to high school and gets the chance to relive her painful
adolescence, this time without the humiliations and the zits. The
sweetness of her smile tilts the film toward the romance in this
romantic comedy, never a liability in a date movie. (PG13)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 1336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990412.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4815 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-PEACE-BOS &LR;      04-12 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PEACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE QUIET MAN WHO BROKERED NORTHERN IRELAND'S PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
MAKING PEACE 
By George J. Mitchell. Knopf. 
192 pp. $24. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's very little that Protestant unionists and Catholic
nationalists in Northern Ireland agree on. But one of those things
is that had it not been for George Mitchell the Good Friday
Agreement that crafted a political settlement in Northern Ireland
last year would not have been reached. The recent breakdown in
talks between the parties, over the decommissioning of IRA arms,
has thrown the process into crisis, but that detracts nothing from
Mitchell's contribution.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, the former US Senate majority leader from Maine,
brought to the task of chairing the negotiations in Belfast the
honest, straightforward approach that made him a popular figure on
Capitol Hill for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   In this account of his four years shuttling to and from Northern
Ireland, first as President Clinton's envoy, then as the mediator
who knocked heads together and got a deal done, Mitchell tells a
story that is very much a reflection of the author: understated,
sometimes even dull, but always honest and eminently fair. At its
best, the book conveys the tension, drama, and high-wire diplomacy
that almost doomed the peace process but ultimately was its
salvation.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell is a diehard Red Sox fan, and his love of such a
star-crossed team no doubt prepared him well for Irish tragedy.
Sometimes this book descends into the kind of inside baseball that
will make tough reading for those who do not follow Anglo-Irish
relations closely. Yet Mitchell's account of the negotiating
process, especially the last few fraught days at the dark and dingy
Government Buildings complex at Stormont in East Belfast, is
compelling stuff and sets the benchmark against which any
subsequent books on that part of the peace process will be judged.
</P>
<P>
   One of the strengths of the book is that while Mitchell is
refreshingly honest in his descriptions of the various political
leaders in Northern Ireland, he is remarkably restrained and
nonjudgmental. He resists the temptation to call the Rev. Ian
Paisley, the fundamentalist preacher whose hard-line unionist party
tried to wreck the talks at every turn, a blustering bigot. But
Mitchell's impassive description of Paisley's hateful carping, and
especially the role Paisley and his party played in smearing Martha
Pope, Mitchell's longtime aide, allows readers to draw their own
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Globe played a small role in exposing that scandal.
The British and Irish tabloids that carried the smear that Pope was
having an affair with a convicted IRA bomber were forced to print
retractions and pay her six figures in monetary damages after a
British official gave an interview to the Globe denying the
existence of the intelligence reports that the newspapers cited as
the basis for their claims. Mitchell held his tongue during the
scandal, but he makes it clear that he resents both Paisley and
British intelligence agents who smeared Pope.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell's humanity shines through. When the IRA stormed the
children's ward at a Belfast hospital, shooting and wounding police
officers who were guarding one of Paisley's deputies, Nigel Dodds,
Mitchell was appalled. At the time of the attack, Dodds was
visiting his 7-year-old son, who suffers from spina bifida.
Mitchell called Dodds to comfort him, observing, ``He belongs to a
party that strongly opposed me, but this was beyond politics,
beyond reason, beyond humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell is an intensely private man. But the glimpses he
provides into the strain the peace process placed on his personal
life are revealing and humanize what could have been a dry account
of diplomatic derring-do. He writes poignantly of being torn
between his duty to his family and his duty in Belfast. He was
initially told by the White House that his commitment would be a
few months. It turned out to be four years, and Mitchell constantly
wrestled with being away from his wife and, later, their son.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Heather, miscarried their first child while he was
stuck in Belfast, listening to politicians drone on about
grievances real and imagined. His beloved older brother, Robbie,
died while the politicians dickered about on simple procedural
matters. He recounts movingly the final conversation he had with
his brother, and how he lay down in his hotel room and cried when
he hung up the phone.
</P>
<P>
   The last few days of the talks, when he literally sequestered
the negotiators and ordered them to reach an agreement or tell the
world why they failed, demonstrated how crucial Mitchell's past
experience as a judge and a consensus builder in Congress was to
clinching the deal.
</P>
<P>
   He says the deal would have collapsed if the Irish government
had not agreed over the last few days to water down language in the
agreement that Protestant unionists found objectionable. The Irish
premier, Bertie Ahern, and his British counterpart, Tony Blair,
emerge as determined, pragmatic leaders who locked themselves away
to get the deal done.
</P>
<P>
   For all his bipartisan success in the Senate, Mitchell says his
accomplishments in Northern Ireland gave him the most satisfaction
of anything he's done in public life. Despite ongoing difficulties
that were much in evidence in the last week, he predicts the
agreement will survive and that democracy will evolve in Northern
Ireland. He bases that belief on his interaction not with
politicians, but with ordinary people, who have willed that the
peace hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Good Friday Agreement will endure because it is fair and
balanced,'' Mitchell says, using words that could very well
describe this book.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell could have written a more sensational book, making all
sorts of inflammatory remarks about the colorful, sometimes
maddening people he had to put up with while he earned no salary
and suffered from perpetual jet lag. But that is not his style, and
that is very much why, after 30 years of killing each other, people
in Northern Ireland now have a chance to live more normal lives.
</P>
<P>
   As they say in Belfast, good on ye, George.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kevin Cullen is the Globe's bureau chief in London.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
