<HEADER>
A4818 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASS-FOREST-BOS &LR;      04-12 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASS-FOREST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE CUTS ARE URGED IN MASSACHUSETTS FORESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Massachusetts has lost 85,000 acres of forest since 1985, most
apparently to new subdivisions, malls, and businesses, while trees
have continued to reclaim abandoned farms and pasture in Western
Massachusetts, according to a new federal survey.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, existing forests are growing older and
thicker, perhaps a little too much so, according to some forestry
specialists who contend that some judicious clear-cutting would
improve forest health and aid birds and wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   The new inventory by the US Forest Service found that forests
covered 62.5 percent of Massachusetts last year. That was down from
64.2 percent when the last report was done in 1985, but up from an
apparent century low of 59 percent in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little surprised by the numbers, because I actually
thought the losses could have been worse,'' said Matthew J. Kelty,
a silviculture professor at the University of Massachusetts at
Amherst.
</P>
<P>
   ``The forest as a whole is aging and getting fuller with, for
the most part, larger, taller, denser trees,'' Kelty said.
</P>
<P>
   While aesthetically pleasing for homeowners and hikers, the
thicker and higher forest canopy may be less than ideal
ecologically, Kelty and others said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rivers, a senior Department of Environmental Management
official who participated in the study, said the study suggests
that Massachusetts could be especially vulnerable if a hurricane
like the 1938 storm hit inland areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid if we were to have a hurricane like that now, the
damage would be a lot greater'' than it would be if the forest had
more saplings and medium tree, Rivers said.
</P>
<P>
   Measured by relative density, two-thirds of Massachusetts forest
tree volume is ``sawtimber'' trees, those big enough to yield 12-
and 8-foot-long pieces that can be milled into lumber.
</P>
<P>
   Another 28 percent is made up of poletimber, intermediate-sized
trees at least five inches in diameter. Only 6 percent is seedlings
and saplings.
</P>
<P>
   A healthier mix, some specialists said, would be closer to 20 to
30 percent small growing trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need more seedlings and saplings in there,'' said Carol
Alerich, the Forest Service official who compiled the report.
Stands of small, growing trees invite songbirds, moose, and deer,
while a better distribution of young trees can even out losses of
older trees to storms and rot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wildlife biologists are always telling the foresters to do
more clear-cutting, rather than less, because we're not doing any
now,'' said Kelty. Selective clearing of 3- to 10-acre parcels
might be a good policy in state and private forests and wildlife
preserves.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials conducted the survey by scrutinizing 18,000
aerial photographs of the state to measure forest cover, then
having 28 trained foresters observe tree composition in 798 6-acre
plots to estimate trends in 3.1 million acres of forest, Alerich
said.
</P>
<P>
   Across Massachusetts, Alerich said, five out of six trees being
removed are being lost to land clearing, rather than lumbering.
</P>
<P>
   The only species found to be under pressure for lumber use is
the red oak, which since 1985 has been selectively removed 10 to 20
percent faster than stocks have grown.
</P>
<P>
   While the state's environment could benefit from having more
oaks in early growing stages, removal rates are far from allowing
oaks to be crowded out by other species, Alerich said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, species such as hemlock and red maple are
growing several times faster than they are being removed. In the
case of hemlocks, this trend could provide a needed cushion if the
wooly adelgid, a lethal parasite that has begun invading the Bay
State, becomes a widespread threat.
</P>
<P>
   In Worcester County, forest cover has fallen by 9.4 percent
since 1985, or 66,000 acres, apparently because of exurban growth
and homebuilding. Every city and town in Worcester County gained
population during the 1980s, census figures show, a trend that
demographers estimate has continued since then.
</P>
<P>
   After recovering 200,000 acres from 1972 to 1985, Eastern
Massachusetts has since lost 4.5 percent of its forest, or 54,000
acres. Meanwhile, the western four counties' forest land grew by
2.7 percent, or 35,000 acres, continuing a decades-old trend of
forests there reclaiming former agricultural land.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys made in 1915, 1928, and 1953 indicated that
Massachusetts forests totalled about 3.27 million acres. That
figure dipped to 2.95 million in 1972 amid the post-World War II
boom of suburban development and highway construction, but 250,000
acres came back by 1985.
</P>
</TEXT>
