A4822 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-HEALING-BOS &LR;      04-12 1527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-HEALING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIES IN CRISIS LEARN TO COPE, STAY TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROUND ROCK, Texas _ The date is etched like a jagged scar on
Janelle's psyche: Jan. 10, 1998, the day she first hit her
5-week-old son. Not once, but twice. Hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Logan was an easy target, I took a lot of my aggressions
out on him. When I slapped him, I wanted to do it again. And I
did,'' she said. Her hard eyes softened, then dripped tears down
her cheeks and onto her Mickey Mouse T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   A 32-year-old single mother who works at a 7-Eleven store,
Janelle seemed destined to be separated forever from Logan _ by law
or by death. ``The way things were going, either way he wouldn't be
here,'' she said. ``He would have been taken away permanently or I
would have killed him. It sounds so awful, but it's true.''
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, in most places, those are pretty much the only
options, and some child advocates maintain that permanent removal
doesn't happen often or fast enough to protect at-risk children.
</P>
<P>
   But here, in a bucolic setting flanked by strip malls, there is
another way.
</P>
<P>
   After Janelle's son was temporarily placed with her sister, a
therapist referred Janelle (who asked that her last name be
withheld) to the Texas Baptist Children's Home, a nonprofit
organization with a unique program founded on a deceptively simple
notion.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is that sometimes it is best to keep families in crisis
together, not in their own homes but in structured settings, to
work through their problems with heavy doses of supervision,
financial assistance, faith, and compassion.
</P>
<P>
   Called the Single-Parent Family Care Program, the effort has
attracted widespread interest _ though few imitators _ as notorious
cases of child abuse and neglect, followed by calls for systemic
reform, seem to occur as regularly as the seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent example in Massachusetts occurred in January,
when five children, ages 22 months to 13 years, were found dirty
and shivering in the unheated basement of their Everett home.
Police said the house was strewn with trash, animal feces, and
soiled clothes. Neighbors and school officials had filed 13 neglect
complaints in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   There is no telling whether that mother and her children would
have fit in at the Texas Baptist Children's Home, but officials say
they have done wonders in cases that seem far worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can intervene quickly, with the mother and children
together, you can prevent a lot of the agony, a lot of the future
problems, a lot of the future needs,'' said Debbie Nagle, the
program's administrator. ``The key is to see the family as a
system, not as a group of individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1950, the Children's Home is on a 112-acre campus 20
miles north of Austin. The grounds resemble graduate student
housing, with a picturesque chapel and other buildings made of
yellow limestone separated by playgrounds, a tennis court, and wide
stretches of grassy space. The home's primary function is to
provide residential care and follow-up help for abused and
neglected children, hundreds of whom are served every year.
</P>
<P>
   The Single-Parent Family Care Program, celebrating its 20th
anniversary, is centered in three large homes, called cottages.
Each can house up to five families and a staff couple who supervise
day-to-day life, provide on-site counseling, and serve as a model
for parenting and life skills. On a recent visit, there were 12
mothers, ages 22 to 49, with 17 children ranging in age from 6
months to 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   Families remain an average of about four months _ some stay just
a few weeks to weather a financial crisis _ but Janelle has been
here for just over a year. Sitting in the living room of a cottage
called Family House, surrounded by homey touches like flowered
quilts and framed copies of the Lord's Prayer, Janelle seemed as
comfortable as the overstuffed furniture.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment she moved in, on March 11, 1998, Janelle and the
Children's Home staff worked on reuniting her with Logan, an
energetic boy with a genetic disorder that has misshapen his face
and skull.
</P>
<P>
   A Wisconsin native who said she survived a childhood of incest,
Janelle described an arduous process of daily counseling to deal
with her anger, followed by supervised visits with Logan, to
overnight stays with a baby monitor in her room, which allowed
cottage staff members to listen as she cared for her son. By last
August, they were together full time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to get well,'' she said. ``A year out of my life for
the life of my son was nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Now living in an efficiency apartment adjacent to one of the
other cottages, Janelle and Logan plan to move from the Children's
Home as soon as she finds an affordable apartment. Like all the
mothers here, she has developed money management skills, with the
staff's help, to stretch her limited income.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to move, to get out on my own and prove to myself
that I can do it,'' she said. ``But here I still have the safety
net. When I'm out for a month or three months, or however long, I
can always come back here for help.''
</P>
<P>
   As she tells her story, other women wander through, on their way
to work or school _ idleness is not an option _ or to pick up their
children from day care.
</P>
<P>
   One of the women is Adel Sawey, a 49-year-old single mother
whose 11-year-old son, Christopher, had been living in a
residential care cottage at the Children's Home. She moved into a
family cottage so they could be together under the watchful eye of
Dena Ransom, the ``house mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a few days, Christopher will be moving into Sawey's
small, spotless room with mauve carpet, decorated with photos and
colorfully painted wood works of art she creates. Sawey sought help
for Christopher, who suffers from attention deficit disorder and
depression, when she began losing control, taking out her
frustrations on him with her belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I would hurt him. I knew I needed help. . . . I didn't
have the tools to take care of him,'' she said through tears. ``One
day I will take my son from here with a happy heart. This place
represents hope to me.''
</P>
<P>
   There is good reason for Sawey's optimism: The Single-Parent
Family Care Program claims a remarkable success rate. One survey
conducted in 1995 showed that 92 percent of residents from 1991-95
were still living in their own homes or subsidized housing, 60
percent were employed, and 28 percent were attending school full
time. Upon admission, 70 percent had been unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the program served 24 families, and only one was
deemed a failure. That case involved a mother who repeatedly used
drugs while in the cottage. ``There is a point where we can only go
so far,'' Nagle said.
</P>
<P>
   Up until that point, the program does a remarkable amount for
its residents, providing them with not just shelter but food,
clothing when needed, and all other household necessities. In
exchange, the women do chores in the cottages and are asked to pay
a $50 monthly program fee, more to give them a sense of
``ownership'' than to raise money, Nagle said.
</P>
<P>
   The program costs $215,000 a year _ or about $58 per family per
day _ a fraction of the $3.9 million Children's Home budget. The
home gets about a quarter of its money from the Texas Baptist
Cooperative Program, a church charity; a quarter from its
endowment; and the rest from gifts and other sources. It takes no
state or federal aid. ``That way we don't have to deal with a lot
of government restrictions,'' Nagle said.
</P>
<P>
   But with a capacity of just 15 families, the Children's Home
gets 30 referrals for every family it can accept, Nagle said. The
agency plans to double the capacity _ perhaps making room for
single-father families _ and to open a similar program in another
Texas city.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the expansion plans, no one here claims the program is a
cure-all. It works mainly for motivated parents who are willing to
do whatever it takes to keep their families intact. ``If a woman is
a chronic welfare mother, she doesn't fit,'' said Jerry Bradley,
the home's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   An important undercurrent of all activities at the Children's
Home is Christian faith, as ubiquitous as children on bicycles.
``We're unashamedly Christian, but we're in no way going to force
our thinking on any of these women,'' Nagle said.
</P>
<P>
   Former residents, many of whom stay in touch with cottage staff
members, are eager to attest to the program's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even now, if we need anything, the Children's Home will help
us,'' said Leslie Searle, who in the early 1990s spent more than a
year here with her two children, now 13 and 10. She will soon begin
law school at Texas Tech University.
</P>
<P>
   To hear Nagle tell it, all it takes is a little money, a lot of
patience, and a plan to teach women to help themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone feels like they're backed into a corner, everything
feels so bleak, give them hope, and it does so much,'' she said.
``We want them to be safe and comfortable, but not so comfortable
they don't want to leave.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
