<SLUG> BC-DAM-CONTROVERSY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WALDO RESERVOIR' THREATENS WILDLIFE REFUGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPENCEVILLE, Calif. _ Spenceville, Calif., died a century ago
when its copper mine played out, but its namesake wildlife refuge
lives on. Now, environmentalists fear the very heart of the refuge
may be cut out by their worst nightmare: a dam.
</P>
<P>
   While Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt and other
environmentally-attuned officials continues to push dams to free
rivers, the Yuba County Water Agency wants to build a dam that
would flood much of the richest wildlife habitat in the Sierra
Nevada foothills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Waldo Reservoir'' is only a name on the map of the Spenceville
Wildlife Preserve today. But the water agency sees it as a future
reservoir covering 3,500 acres, providing flood protection for Yuba
County, which has a history of catastrophic flooding.
</P>
<P>
   The agency insists that the Waldo dam is just one of many
possible features in a comprehensive flood control plan for the
Yuba River watershed, and that environmentalists are overreacting.
Nevertheless, Mother Lode grass-roots organizations have taken up
battle stations to squelch it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't mitigate for the damage it would cause,'' said Julie
Carville, a Nevada City biologist, author, wildflower expert and a
leader of Friends of Spenceville.
</P>
<P>
   The reservoir formed by a Waldo dam would fragment one of the
finest pieces of publicly held oak woodland in California, drowning
the area's rich flora and disrupting feeding, nesting, spawning and
migration patterns of wildlife, environmentalists say. Further,
they contend, the reservoir would cover the old copper mine,
allowing acid residue to seep into the water. When water levels
drop, they fear the residue would ring the reservoir, creating both
an eyesore and a health hazard.
</P>
<P>
   Managed by the state Department of Fish and Game, Spenceville
encompasses 11,213 acres of woodland and rolling hills of easy
hiking trails and splendid scenery.
</P>
<P>
   The preserve is also home to 175 species of birds, including
wild turkeys and several rare species, such as the reclusive black
rail.
</P>
<P>
   No one argues the need for better flood protection in Yuba
County, where the Yuba, Feather and Bear rivers converge. The
county has been ravaged by 10 major floods this century, most
recently in 1997 when 100,000 people were evacuated, 850 homes were
damaged or destroyed, and 16,000 acres flooded by a break in the
Feather River levee at Arboga, south of Marysville.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is whether it takes a dam to provide that protection.
In the first phase of its flood control study, the water agency's
board rejected alternatives, such as levee setbacks, enlarging
river channels or creating a bypass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We calculated that we couldn't pass on the flood risk
downstream,'' said Curt Aikens, the water agency's point man for
the flood control project.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed Waldo dam _ 220 feet tall and 4,000 feet wide _
would create an ``off-stream'' reservoir 6 miles from the Yuba
River, capable of holding 300,000 acre-feet of water.
</P>
<P>
   Because normal flow from Dry Creek, which runs through the
preserver, is insufficient to fill such a large reservoir, most of
the water stored by the dam would be transported in huge pipes from
Englebright Reservoir, upstream on the Yuba River.
</P>
<P>
   County officials say the new reservoir would allow them to keep
lower water levels in the main reservoirs on the Yuba and Feather
rivers, ensuring extra capacity when the rivers are at flood stage.
</P>
<P>
   But the South Yuba Citizens League, Friends of Spenceville and
two dozen other local organizations contend that the planned
reservoir is unnecessarily costly, as well as a blight on one of
the Sierra foothills' great beauty spots.
</P>
<P>
   The Waldo Reservoir would flood the abandoned Spenceville copper
mine, which contains more than 100,000 cubic yards of toxic
tailings. ``They'd have to truck all that soil away,'' biologist
Carville said.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Fish also has expressed concerns about the
dam. In its first look at the plan, the department responded with a
list of more than a dozen objections focusing on the damage to an
area of ``exceptional species richness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
