<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4827 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUDORA-BIRTHDAY-BOS &LR;      04-12 1331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUDORA-BIRTHDAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAULKNER'S TOWN HONORS A TOWERING EUDORA WELTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSON, Miss. _ Eudora Welty once said that sharing a literary
landscape with William Faulkner was like living near a mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Welty weaved a gentle tapestry of words in contrast to
Faulkner's sound and fury, yet in the four decades she has survived
him, she, too, has gained international recognition while winning
their home state's deep affection, which was denied to Faulkner in
his lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   When Welty reaches her 90th birthday Tuesday, the celebration in
Mississippi will be as quiet and mannered as one of her novels.
Frail with age, she will more than likely spend the day in her
home, friends say, enjoying the visits of a few companions who drop
by to see her regularly, swapping yarns and laughter.
</P>
<P>
   In Faulkner's hometown, Welty is being honored, in absentia, at
the annual Oxford Conference for the Book this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Though she won the Pulitzer Prize for fiction in 1972, and was
awarded the Medal of Freedom by President Jimmy Carter in 1980
before being inducted into France's Legion d'Honneur in 1996, ``she
is really just now being discovered,'' said Noel Polk, a Welty
scholar and English professor at the University of Southern
Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was thought of as female, and somehow inferior to
Faulkner,'' Polk said in a telephone interview. ``But what goes
unsaid is that what lies near a mountain is usually another
mountain. Miss Welty has established herself as a new mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   Welty reigns as the belle of letters in a state that has
produced extraordinary talent. Today, Mississippi writers not only
mention Welty in the same breath with Faulkner, they talk of her
courage during the troubled 1960s, when segregation fell in
sunbursts of freedom marches, bombings, and murders.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's an absolutely wonderful writer,'' said Josephine Haxton,
a novelist who uses the pen name Ellen Douglas. ``But she's also a
steady political person who stood for decency and for the rights of
people in Mississippi and never sought the limelight for herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Haxton, who lives in Welty's neighborhood in Jackson, recalls
that Welty was once asked if she feared the Ku Klux Klan might
attack her home. ``You know,'' Welty replied, ``people who burn
crosses don't usually read The New Yorker.''
</P>
<P>
   It was in The New Yorker that one of Welty's strongest short
stories appeared in 1963, shortly after NAACP leader Medgar Evers
was killed by a sniper a few miles across town in Jackson. Entitled
``Where Is the Voice Coming From?'' it is a narrative told by a man
consumed by racial hatred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I says to my wife,'' the story begins. `` `You can reach and
turn it off. You don't have to set and look at a black nigger face
no longer than you want to, or listen to what you don't want to
hear. It's still a free country.' I reckon that's how I give myself
the idea.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``idea'' was to stalk an NAACP official and shoot him down
in the driveway of his home.
</P>
<P>
   The story was written before the murder was linked to Byron De
La Beckwith, a white supremacist from the Delta, yet the narrator
bears an uncanny resemblance to him.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, shortly after a Mississippi jury convicted Beckwith of
the murder more than 30 years after the killing, Welty was asked
how she had been able to capture Beckwith's personality. She
dismissed her prescience.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment she heard the news of Evers's death, she said,
``We all knew who did it. Because we all knew Beckwiths. It wasn't
necessary to know that man, Beckwith.''
</P>
<P>
   Welty never married. She has lived for nearly 75 years in the
comfortable house her parents built across a tree-lined street from
Belhaven College, a Presbyterian school a few blocks from the state
capitol.
</P>
<P>
   As a young woman, Welty worked for the Works Progress
Administration, one of President Franklin D. Roosevelt's New Deal
programs that brought relief to Mississippi. She traveled the
state, taking photographs as evocative of that desperate period as
Walker Evans's images in ``Let Us Now Praise Famous Men.''
</P>
<P>
   Welty's shadow haunts the foreground of one of her most
remarkable pictures, a lonely setting of columns at the ``Ruins of
Windsor,'' all that remained of a plantation mansion destroyed by
fire.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago she was asked if she had planned to use her
shadow to add mood to the photograph. ``Of course not,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her modesty is a characteristic that carries over into her work.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is much less an elitist than Faulkner,'' said Richard
Ford, a prize-winning novelist who grew up in Jackson. ``She's much
better educated than Faulkner. She benefited from coming along
after Faulkner. He established a camp farthest out, and it had a
good effect on her because her work was encouraged to be more
accessible.''
</P>
<P>
   Reading Faulkner is a deep and mysterious exercise, the
equivalent of a Catholic Mass said in Latin. Welty's books are
similarly enriching, but are written with the simple eloquence of a
Methodist service in the church she attended as a child.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his power as a writer, Faulkner was scorned as a
pretentious figure in Oxford. Townspeople never forgave him for
returning from World War I with British airs, false claims of
heroism, and an ensemble of tweedy clothes. They called him ``Count
No Count.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Faulkner was a resident alien,'' said Barry Hannah, a
masterful short story writer who lives in Oxford and teaches at the
University of Mississippi. ``The difference is that Miss Eudora was
a permanent fixture through thick and thin. During the civil rights
horrors, she gave us hope that a decent white artist could survive
in a state that reflected South Africa's values. It took a lot of
guts.''
</P>
<P>
   In an essay published in The Atlantic Monthly in 1965, three
years after Faulkner's death, Welty defended her colleague after a
literary critic declared that Faulkner should be reassessed because
he was, ``after all, only a white Mississippian.''
</P>
<P>
   The books Faulkner left behind could speak volumes in answer,
she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The color of his skin would modify it just about as much as
would the binding of his book. Integrity can be neither lost nor
concealed nor faked nor quenched nor artificially come by nor
outlived, nor, I believe, in the long run denied. Integrity is no
greater and no less today than it was Saturday and will be
tomorrow. It stands outside time.''
</P>
<P>
   Employing her own style, Welty is as lyrical as any of the great
American writers of the 20th century. Elegant passages run through
Welty's prose like golden threads.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Optimist's Daughter,'' her novel that won the Pulitzer
Prize, she portrayed a selfish, small-minded widow:
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps she was forty. There was little even of forty in her
looks except the line of her neck and the backs of her little
square, idle hands. She was boney and blue-veined, as a child she
had very possibly gone undernourished. Her hair was still a
childish tow. It had the tow texture, as if, well rubbed between
the fingers, those curls might have gone to powder. She had round,
country-blue eyes and a little feist jaw.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is better at taking the density of lived experience
that seems imperceptible and making it thrilling,'' Ford said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 40 years younger than Welty, Ford has a boyhood memory of
his mother pointing out the famous lady while shopping at a Jitney
Jungle Supermarket in Jackson. He did not meet Welty until years
later, but became a steadfast friend.
</P>
<P>
   At a literary gathering shortly after he won the 1995 Pulitzer
Prize for his own novel, ``Independence Day,'' Ford paid homage to
Welty by choosing to read from her work rather than his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admire her terrifically,'' he said the other day. ``And she
is a hero for a lot of women writers who were faced with a decision
to go at it alone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
