<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DEBATE ABOUT `SPRAWL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO &UR;  &LR;  -- Vice President Al Gore has defined a major
domestic issue for 2000 and some Republicans have responded
eagerly: ``Sprawl? We're for it.''
</P>
<P>
   In think tanks and partisan periodicals, an ideological war is
underway for the hearts, minds, and car keys of a huge and no
longer silent majority of Americans, suburbanites.
</P>
<P>
   The war is worth fighting if only for the intellectual effects
on both parties. Democrats have historically been unable to stand
prosperity. Issues of growth, planning, and traffic do not stiffen
the sinews or summon up Democratic blood the way work and wages
once did.
</P>
<P>
   For Republicans, champions of the American home and hearth,
focusing on some area other than the bedroom would be healthy. The
garage will do.
</P>
<P>
   Indulging a vice presidential habit, Gore overstates the case
against sprawl. ``A gallon of gas can be used up just driving to
get a gallon of milk,'' he has said, implying that Americans are
not as wise and prudent as, say, Al Gore. (The biggest roadblock
facing Democrats in presidential elections has been the slogan,
``We're from the government and we're here to help you.'')
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan favors ``smart growth,'' which the Heritage
Foundation calls ``a program in search of a problem,'' arguing that
`` `Smart growth' could be no growth.'' The March 22 cover of
National Review features characters from the TV cartoon ``King of
the Hill'' lined up behind a backyard barbecue with the combative
headline, ``They're OK!''
</P>
<P>
   For decades, suburbia has quietly accumulated political power.
In 1952, Chicago cast 41 percent of the vote in Illinois. In 1996,
its share was 20 percent. The same decline eroded other Democratic
strongholds. New York went from 48 to 31, Detroit from 29 to 8,
Baltimore from 39 to 10, and Boston from 15 to 7 percent of the
state's vote.
</P>
<P>
   As both parties adjust to demographic reality, Steven Hayward of
the Pacific Research Institute of San Francisco, sees an elitist
plot by Democrats. ``The answer is readily apparent: to get us out
of our cars,'' he writes in National Review.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no exaggeration to say that for most smart-growth
advocates, the car is a rolling cigarette, and General Motors is
the moral equivalent of Philip Morris. In `Earth in the Balance,'
of course, Gore wrote that the internal combusion engine `is posing
a mortal threat to the security of every nation that is more deadly
than that of any military enemy we are ever likely to confont
again.' It is this animus against the car that explains why the
smart-growth crowd is fixated on high-density development.''
</P>
<P>
   So Democrats must now pry the cold, dead fingers off the
steering wheel of a typical suburbanite's beloved sports utility
vehicle? The symbolism is not that neat.
</P>
<P>
   Suburbia, one of the great unintended consequences of American
life, is a Republican invention. When President Dwight D.
Eisenhower signed the Defense Interstate Highway Act of 1956, he
launched a massive, if unRepublican, government subsidy that would
help empty cities, destabilize the industrial economy, and create
sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   Today, as suburbia has matured, The New Democrat, published by
the Democratic Leadership Council, devotes an issue to ``The Revolt
in America's Suburbs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From coast to coast, sprawl is being undermined by its own
constituency,'' writes Richard Moe and Carter Wilkie, coauthors of
``Changing Places: Rebuilding Community in the Age of Sprawl.'' Moe
and Wilkie point out that ``Sprawl became the sleeper political
issue of 1998, when voters from California to Cape Cod approved
some ballot initiatives related to growth management.''
</P>
<P>
   Politicians follow election returns. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania
and Christine Whitman of New Jersey are antisprawl Republican
governors. But governors do not inhabit a think-tank world. In the
platforms of 2000, the debate about sprawl will enliven, inform,
and motivate both parties.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
