</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY LUCK, OR GENIUS, CLINTON, NATO GAINING GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If President Clinton had announced before launching air strikes
against Yugoslavia that he would not rule out sending ground
troops, Republicans might have had on their side what they did not
during the impeachment process _ public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   But the tide is turning, and what the public would have rejected
just three weeks ago is looking far more tolerable today.
</P>
<P>
   As if by a stroke of luck, a stroke of political genius, or a
bit of both, there has been in recent days a groundswell of support
by both political parties, as well as by the American people, for
sending ground troops to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Given Clinton's skill at getting out of difficult situations,
the public approval he is now receiving for his handling of NATO's
war against Slobodan Milosevic has to be at least partly attributed
to his own political and diplomatic acumen.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, his ability to turn public opinion to his favor is
sometimes helped by his adversaries sharp tongues and
mean-spiritedness, which is more distasteful to the electorate than
the president's own actions.
</P>
<P>
   This is what apparently has happened during NATO's air
offensive. As NATO stepped up the bombing, Milosevic stepped up his
``ethnic cleansing'' offensive, turning his forced evacuation of
ethnic Albanians from Kosovo into a humanitarian disaster of epic
proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Even Clinton's supporters were initially critical of his policy
and war strategy against Milosevic. Although the heads of the other
NATO countries were deeply involved in planning the offensive, it
was Clinton who was targeted for the most criticism from those
within and outside the United States. When a jet fighter was shot
down on day five of the bombing, support for the strikes eroded
even further.
</P>
<P>
   And when, on day eight, three American soldiers were captured by
Serbian troops, it was viewed by both Clinton supporters and
detractors as a coup for Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   However, Milosevic made the same mistake Clinton's Republican
enemies did with impeachment: He overplayed his hand, threatening
to put the soldiers on trial as war criminals. Clinton regained the
backing of the populace when he demanded the soldiers' release and
emphatically stressed that Milosevic would be held responsible if
anything happened to them.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Milosevic got the message. The media reported a
trial was no longer imminent. Later, as the bombing increased and
spread to Belgrade, Milosevic began calling for a cease-fire and a
limited pullback of his troops.
</P>
<P>
   When the NATO alliance, familiar with Milosevic's self-serving
tactics, rejected the offer, he hinted that the soldiers would be
released. Milosevic began to backtrack on the release when NATO
responded that the soldiers had to be released unconditionally.
Nonetheless, when it appeared Milosevic was seeking some relief
from the constant bombing, Clinton's and NATO's strategy began to
look as if it was making an impact.
</P>
<P>
   One theme throughout this war is that the countries that make up
NATO are united as never before. And much of the credit for this
unity goes to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Television and newspaper images of the hundreds of thousands of
ethnic Albanian refugees gathered in large fields have stunned and
angered the world. At first, the anger was directed at Clinton and
his NATO allies, suggesting that this catastrophe was their fault,
and the air campaign was an utter failure. However, most Americans
began to realize that these events were not the result of NATO's
strategy, but another example of the vicious policies of Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   As images of Kosovo refugees _ especially women and children
with little food or shelter _ continue to mark the daily news, the
call for ground troops has become louder and louder, from the halls
of Congress to homes and workplaces across the country.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt there are legitimate questions as to whether the war
plans against Milosevic were thoroughly reviewed, or whether
Milosevic's accelerated ``ethnic cleansing'' was actually
anticipated. But these issues are secondary. What happens now is
what's important.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the offensive against Milosevic appears to be working
well enough for Clinton to continue the current course, even though
he now has support to commit US troops. Not a critical murmur was
uttered when it was announced that 2,000 support troops would
accompany the Apache helicopters being sent to Albania. No matter
how they describe them, these soldiers are the closest thing to, if
not being, ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   If in the coming days Clinton decides that a commitment of
ground troops is, finally, necessary to stop Milosevic, his onetime
critics will probably say that he had no other choice if NATO is to
prevail. And that is, basically, what this has come down to.
America, as part of NATO, cannot afford to lose this war and face
worldwide embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   The goal now is to bring this conflict to a successful end. As
long as Clinton is involved, the odds are that he, along with the
NATO alliance, will prevail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
