<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4839 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEN-BOOM-BOS &LR;      04-12 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-BOOM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN LIKES, DISLIKES SET THE AGENDA FOR THE REST OF US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are more teenagers now than at any time in our history:
30.9 million Americans between the ages of 12 and 19. Their rank is
expected to swell to 33.6 million in 2005 as the children of the
baby boomers come of age, the so-called ``echo generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Teenagers' ability to shape the culture, or to determine what
sells, is nothing new. But the degree of their influence is, as
today's teens set a wider agenda than any generation before them.
</P>
<P>
   It's not only in Hollywood, where stars selected by teenagers _
Adam Sandler and Leonardo DiCaprio _ have created box office
benchmarks in movies like ``The Waterboy'' and ``Titanic.'' ``We
picked our stars and these kids are picking their own,'' said Casey
Silver, former chairman of Universal Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not only in the media, where Teen People magazine, just
a year old, has a circulation of more than 1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the consumer culture, teenagers are making their
likes and dislikes known by what they will spend their money on _
and they have plenty to spend. They contributed some $141 billion
to the US economy last year, according to Teenage Research
Unlimited, a consulting firm known as TRU that tracks spending
patterns. Without mortgages or college loans to pay off, teens are
free to spend what they have. On average, a teenager spends $99 a
week, $28 from their parents, $71 from their own money. On average,
teenagers receive $77 a week from working and allowance.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing to teens has never been so pervasive, says Peter
Zollo, president of TRU and author of ``Wise Up to Teens: Insights
into Marketing and Advertising to Teenagers,'' a book on the
subject. ``It blows me away and I have been at this for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Teenagers ``have more power to set trends than they did
before,'' says Whiton S. Paine, a developmental psychologist and
president of the Pennsylvania-based market research firm KidToKid.
``Their ability to set trends and pass information on is
exaggerated because of the Internet. Now, kids get on the Internet
and start telling everyone (even companies) what is hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old style was that trends started on the West Coast or the
inner city and then traveled. Now, they can start anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Teens are the ones who decided that jeans are out _ and thus
sent Levi Strauss's operations into a slump _ and who put Delia's
on the map almost overnight, rocketing the girls' clothing catalog
from $5 million in sales in 1995 to $170 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Teenagers' spending is spread across every industry, specialists
say. Parents and grandparents turn to teenagers for advice on
computer, audio, and even automobile purchases. And no teens have
more responsibility than those who are latch-key children.
</P>
<P>
   While both parents work, or a single parent does, many more
teens are doing shopping that once was the domain of the parent.
Grocery shopping, for example, is normal for most teens. TRU says
half of all male teens do some grocery shopping for the family on a
weekly basis and 60 percent of the girls do.
</P>
<P>
   TRU has for 17 years produced biannual reports, based on a poll
of 2,000 select teenagers, on what the 12 to 19 crowd is doing and
thinking. The list of companies who heed TRU's research reads like
the Fortune 500: Coke, Pepsi, Nike, Reebok, Calvin Klein, Levi's,
the Gap, Procter &AMP; Gamble, Disney, 20th Century Fox, Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We measure everything from what they are buying, what are
their favorite commercials, the coolest brands, to what they like
to do with their families,'' says R. Michael Wood, TRU's director
of research.
</P>
<P>
   Because they are a growing _ and free-spending _ demographic,
determining what it is that teens like and want is becoming a big
business in itself, albeit a tricky one.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, Triple Dot Communications, and its affiliate,
Y-Access, maintains a database of more than 1,000 teenagers, and
positions itself as a communications and marketing agency attuned
to the 12 to 24 market.
</P>
<P>
   Triple Dot's Tru Pettigrew, 30, spends about half his time
talking with teenagers in Boston and around the country, finding
out what they like. It is all part of Triple Dot's effort to help
clients reach that lucrative market.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Pettigrew was in New York talking to teens. On
Thursday, he approached a group in a South Boston playground,
quickly grabbed the basketball they were playing with, and deftly
insinuated himself into the game and the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going on a date this weekend and you got to keep me hip
and cool. What should I wear?'' Pettigrew asks. The answer: FUBU,
said one teenager. Some others shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   But over the next hour, he harvests a wealth of information
about what Sean Flaherty, 16, Rose Broderick, 15, Jean Valentin,
14, and several other teenagers think about everything from
clothes, to music, to commercials to magazines, moving seamlessly
from music to sports to the source of the group's money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of Abercrombie,'' says Sean, complaining that all
the brand's clothes are the same. Jean says black will be the hot
color this summer, and that he reads the magazine Slam.
</P>
<P>
   The questions are not for any particular client. Instead,
Pettigrew will write a report about the afternoon that will be
circulated in-house. When the session is over, Pettigrew reaches
into a duffle bag and pulls out CDs and Converse apparel for the
teenagers. They accept the gifts.
</P>
<P>
   But teenagers _ who have been the targets of marketers since
they were in diapers _ are savvy, discerning customers. They are
more street-smart than their predecessors, and don't always accept
whatever comes their way. If they don't like a product, they find a
way to say so.
</P>
<P>
   Many use e-mail to tell off companies, or use a company's 800
number, says Marta Loeb, president of Y-Access. ``In all my years
of market research, I have never seen a group so expressive and
comfortable with having that voice.'' For example, Delia's gets
some 6,000 e-mails a day from teens commenting about its products
or making suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every industry is targeting teenagers and children,
says James McNeal, a professor of marketing at Texas A&AMP;M University
who has studied marketing to children for the last 36 years. And
when one company in an industry does, the competition quickly
follows.
</P>
<P>
   Zollo says the barrage of marketing has made teens tougher to
reach. ``They have developed firewalls. . . . It can be tough to
get through to them in a relevant way.''
</P>
<P>
   Quieter marketing, such as sponsoring music acts, or a
skiboarding contest, or getting influential teenagers to wear your
product, stands a good chance, he says. ``You have to be pervasive
in their lives and get under the radar screen.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether under the radar screen or in your face, marketing to
teenagers is expected to increase because of the group's size and
spending power. So parents, next time you ground your teenager,
think again. You might be responsible for bringing the nation's
longest peacetime economic expansion to a grinding halt.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Matthew Brelis is the Globe's Focus writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
