<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4841 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALKANS-DURATION-BOS &LR;      04-12 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALKANS-DURATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PAST AND FUTURE, NO SHORTAGE OF SURPRISES FOR SCHOLARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN YEMMA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ It was only last month, but it feels like a
lifetime since Morton Abramowitz was working behind the scenes at
the Kosovo peace talks, a diplomat trying intently to head off war.
</P>
<P>
   Every day since, he says, has been a surprise _ the ``rude and
insulting'' Serb reaction to the Kosovo autonomy plan, the
breakdown of diplomacy, NATO's military inability to bring Slobodan
Milosevic to his knees.
</P>
<P>
   Looking weary and a little worried last week, Abramowitz, a
former US assistant secretary of state who advised the Kosovo
Albanian delegation in the peace talks, sat in a classroom
describing a series of unanticipated events and unforeseen
reactions, and an unpredictable future for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   On Milosevic's hard line: ``I was immensely surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   On ``ethnic cleansing'' in Kosovo: ``I certainly never expected
a systematic expulsion of the people of Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   On bombing: ``The view that Milosevic might change his mind
after he had a whiff of gunpowder was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   It was just one diplomat's view, delivered at a seminar at
Harvard's Kennedy School of Government. Abramowitz, now with the
Carnegie Endowment for International Peace in Washington, was not
the architect of US policy toward Kosovo. But his recounting of the
slide toward war since late March made clear that the big surprise
of the conflict has been the sheer number of surprises.
</P>
<P>
   US and European diplomats did not know how events would unfold.
Nor could they now say with confidence how the crisis would end _
whether Milosevic could forced to capitulate, pull his forces out
of Kosovo, welcome back the refugees, and allow an international
force to police the province.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the big questions being asked in foreign ministries
and at think tanks on both sides of the Atlantic deal with
far-reaching security concerns as the conflict rolls toward Week
Four: Can NATO hold together? Will Russia remain on the sidelines?
Will public opinion remain supportive? How will the conflict end?
</P>
<P>
   Following is the consensus view of a group of analysts:
</P>
<P>
   --NATO: So far, the alliance is holding, but if the air war
drags on, or ground troops are introduced, there could be problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a problem _ not yet,'' said Robert E. Hunter, US
ambassador to NATO from 1993 to '98 and now an analyst at the Rand
Corp. think tank in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tactic that Milosevic is pursuing is precisely to split
the allies, which is what the call for an Easter cease-fire was all
about. . . . That's not been a problem up to now. But what about .
. . four weeks from now?''
</P>
<P>
   If NATO takes significant casualties or introduces ground
forces, Hunter says, unity could crack. But Hunter sees no
alternative to keeping pressure on Milosevic and turning down
partial peace proposals.
</P>
<P>
   --Russia: Again, this is not a problem yet. Although anti-NATO
rhetoric is becoming strident in Russia, specialists say it is
unlikely that Moscow will make a bold move to aid the Serbs or
challenge NATO. On Tuesday, Secretary of State Madeleine K.
Albright will meet with the Russian foreign minister, Igor Ivanov,
to try to keep US-Russian relations from deteriorating further.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Russia, there is almost universal condemnation of the
NATO action, said Michael McFaul, a senior associate and Russia
specialist at the Carnegie Endowment. As a result, no one Russian
faction can gain advantage by playing on the anger.
</P>
<P>
   What that implies, however, is that no viable pro-Western,
prodemocracy politicians are left in Russia, he added. ``Democrats
are going to lose no matter what. The Kosovo issue makes no
difference there.''
</P>
<P>
   --Opinion: Polls indicate that in both the United States and
Europe, support for the air war runs high, and that there is
increasing approval for a possible ground mission. Richard Sobel, a
political scientist at Harvard's Kennedy School, conducted a study
of American attitudes on foreign intervention, which was published
last month. He concluded that the public will back intervention if
it involves a multinational operation and is in a part of the world
that touches the nation's ``vital interest.'' The NATO operation he
says, fits those criteria.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and European leaders do not have to worry
about opinion going soft in the next few weeks, Sobel said, unless
casualties are high. Even then, public support would not disappear
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   --Military options: For now, Clinton and other leaders have
weathered criticism for ruling out use of ground troops. But to win
the war, many military analysts say, NATO troops will have to go
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it is possible to put off the day of
reckoning,'' said Michael O'Hanlon, a military and security
specialist at the Brookings Institution in Washington. ``Every day
counts. We should be sending a vanguard force to Italy right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Although NATO has increased the number of soldiers going into
Albania and has announced that Apache attack helicopters would be
on the way by next week, force levels are still nothing like what
would would be needed in an invasion. US and European officials
continue to say NATO forces will not enter Kosovo except in a
``permissive'' environment _ that is, only with the cooperation of
Yugoslav leaders after they have acquiesced to NATO demands.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing campaign, then, is almost certain to remain NATO's
main strategy to bring Milosevic around. So far, Operation Allied
Force is costing $20 million to $40 million a day, according to an
independent estimate by the Center for Strategic and Budgetary
Assessment. At that rate, NATO has spent around $500 million to
date. There's no sign that the costs so far are straining the NATO
budget, but if the war were to drag on, its expense could become an
issue.
</P>
<P>
   --End game: This baffles most analysts. Clinton and NATO leaders
are adamant that they will not let Milosevic win a halt to the
bombing by offering half-measures. They want full compliance with
the conditions they laid down in the Rambouillet accords that
Milosevic scorned. To settle for less would be a defeat for NATO.
But for Milosevic to agree to those conditions _ especially the
international force in Kosovo _ would be surrender in the eyes of
most Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, administration voices made the stakes higher by
beginning to say that Milosevic must be removed from office.
Abramowitz, for instance, said that negotiating with Milosevic now
is out of the question: ``We must insist on his departure.'' That
will mean a hard fight, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more the US has badgered and pressured, the more Milosevic
has dug his heels in,'' said Minton Goldman, an East European
specialist at Northeastern University. ``It's a matter of face.
When it comes to nationalism, people do go crazy. We'll have to see
it through to the end, but we'll find many Serbs tired of
fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   With Milosevic's very survival at stake, however, the biggest
surprise of all at this point would be a speedy end to the crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
