<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4842 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-ASTHMA-TREAT-2TAK     04-12 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ASTHMA-TREAT-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COPING WITH ASHTMA'S RELENTLESS ATTACKS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (Includes steroids sidebar)  
 (Eds.: IgE is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than 5 million children in the United States have asthma,
and despite the intensifying efforts of schools, public health
officials, physicians and community groups, too many are falling
through the cracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see a lot of patients who are undertreated,'' said Pamela
Fallon, a nurse practitioner at Boston Medical Center's adult
pulmonary clinic. ``They've never gotten on top of their asthma''
with aggressive treatment that could keep them relatively free of
symptoms and acute flareups, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Asthma can't be cured. But with today's best treatments, most
patients can avoid disruption of their lives. Unfortunately,
treatment often involves taking a number of drugs and working
diligently to avoid environmental substances that trigger symptoms.
Surveys show that many people don't maintain the necessary routines
in the long term.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the problem is that life is complicated,'' said Dr.
Christopher Fanta, clinical director of pulmonary and critical care
medicine at Brigham and Women's Hospital and director of the
Partners Asthma Center.
</P>
<P>
   Nine year-old Levell Gillard, a pupil at Mattahunt Elementary
School in Boston, had been suffering from asthma symptoms for many
months. But his family and living situation were in flux and his
symptoms of wheezing and shortness of breath took a back seat.
</P>
<P>
   Levell's asthma was waking him at night, bothering him at
school, on the playground, and _ worst of all _ when he rehearsed
with his ``positive rap'' musical group.
</P>
<P>
   When he tried to sing, he wheezed, coughed and sniffled.
``That's when the bell went off'' that he might need treatment,
said his aunt, Angela Gethers, despite the fact that his primary
care doctor never seemed to take much notice of his asthma.
</P>
<P>
   Even patients in regular care may not be receiving what's now
considered optimal therapy.
</P>
<P>
   When Gethers _ with whom he now lives _ brought Levell to the
asthma clinic at Boston Medical Center this past winter, lung
function tests revealed that his airways were inflamed and severely
blocked: even after he inhaled a drug to open the airways, they
remained constricted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get this under control,'' said Dr. Suzanne
Steinbach, director of the pediatric allergy-respiratory division
at BMC, who eventually sent Levell and his aunt home with a long
list of drugs and inhaler equipment he would need, including
cortisone drugs to begin attacking his runaway asthma immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbach gets many young patients like this who need more
aggressive treatment, often referred by a school nurse or a primary
care doctor. Many parents don't take action when they notice that
their child wheezes or can't participate in activities ``because
they think that's the way asthma is,'' says Steinbach. ``Our job is
to tell them, no, it could be better-controlled''
</P>
<P>
   After a few months of taking the drugs as Steinbach prescribed,
and using a ``peak flow meter'' to monitor his lung function,
Levell said recently he was doing much better _ and his singing was
benefiting as well.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, most patients could do well if they were treated
according to national guidelines issued two years ago, and aimed at
meeting goals set by the National Heart, Lung and Blood Institute,
say asthma specialists. The goals are ambitious but, in theory,
achievable in all but the most severe and intractable cases. The
goals include keeping asthma from disrupting sleep, eliminating the
need to miss school or work, reducing emergency medical visits and
hospitalizations, making it possible for people to exercise, and
maintaining normal, or nearly normal, lung function.
</P>
<P>
   To reach these goals, the NHLBI set out several recommendations
on how to treat patients with varying degrees of asthma.
</P>
<P>
   People who have mild episodes of chest tightness, wheezing and
shortness of breath should take short-acting inhaled drugs called
beta-2 agonists, like albuterol.
</P>
<P>
   If they have symptoms like this more than twice a week, the
guidelines say, asthmatics should be on long-term ``controller''
medications that dampen the inflammation in the lungs. This
guideline probably applies to about half the nation's estimated
17.3 million asthmatics.
</P>
<P>
   There are several types of controller drugs, but inhaled
steroids ``are the most effective long-term control medication for
asthma,'' say the guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Today's drug regimens, which are demanding and have
uncomfortable side effects, may give way to new ones as scientists
find ways to target specific links in the inflammation process.
Most current drugs have a broad, non-specific effect.
</P>
<P>
   In just the last couple of years, drugs called leukotriene
inhibitors are making it possible for some patients to control
their symptoms long-term with pills instead of _ or in addition to
_ inhaled compounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the first designer therapy,'' said Dr. Jeffrey
Drazen, chief of the pulmonary division at Brigham and Women's
Hospital. What he means is that the leukotriene inhibitors home in
on specific molecules in the inflammation process, and are
virtually free of side effects. However, they don't work for all
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Other drugs under development are aimed at antibodies called
IgE, which are spewed into the bloodstream in many asthmatics.
Specific white blood cells called eosinophils are still another
target for new drugs.
</P>
<P>
   All asthmatics should routinely use peak flow meters to
anticipate when an episode of obstructed breathing may be coming
on. These meters are simple devices that the patient blows into,
moving a marker along a measured distance that indicates how
rapidly he or she can blow air out. Some of the meters can now
transmit their readings directly to doctors' offices.
</P>
<P>
   This more aggressive stance on monitoring and treatment reflects
that ``the focus in asthma now has changed to altering the course
of the disease'' not just relieving symptoms, said Dr. Stanley J.
Szefler, an asthma specialist at National Jewish Medical and
Research Center in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   However, there are few if any signs yet that these guidelines
and goals are turning the tide in the asthma epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
