NYT-04-12-99 1354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990412.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4844 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-ASTHMA-TREAT-2ND &LR;      04-12 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ASTHMA-TREAT-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... asthma epidemic.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last year there was a sobering reminder of this from a large
survey, called Asthma in America, sponsored by Glaxo Wellcome Inc.,
the pharmaceutical company, and administered to 2,509 adults who
had asthma or were parents of children with asthma. More than 700
health care providers were also surveyed.
</P>
<P>
   The survey revealed that nearly a third of asthma patients were
awakened at night by their symptoms. Nearly half of children with
asthma missed school because of the disease in the past year, and
25 percent of adults missed some work.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly one-third of children with asthma made emergency room
visits in the previous year, and 41 percent of all people with
asthma sought urgent medical care. One-fourth to one-half of the
asthmatics said they were limited in their social, physical or
sports activities.
</P>
<P>
   The backbone of asthma treatment, specialists say, is an
individual plan worked out between the doctor and patient in the
context of an ongoing relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Besides drugs, the plan usually requires the patient to figure
out what's triggering symptoms, and then to get rid of or avoid
those allergens and irritants.
</P>
<P>
   This means, in the case of people allergic to dust mites and
animals (very common triggers), stripping the sleeping area of
fabrics and objects that harbor dust mites -- microscopic bugs that
live in dust. Pillows and mattresses must be covered with special
materials, and bedding washed in hot water once a week.
</P>
<P>
   Pets are a major problem: in most cases, physicians say they
should be gotten rid of, but children often refuse. At a minimum,
they should be kept out of the sleeping area. Patients are advised
to vacuum frequently using special bags for their machines; to wear
a mask while cleaning, and, in some cases, to get an air-filtering
machine.
</P>
<P>
   Even well-meaning patients get fed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all-consuming,'' said Margaret MacNally, a Westport woman
who has stripped her bedroom and other living areas of books,
plants upholstered furniture and curtains and put special covers on
mattresses and pillows to reduce her exposure to dust mites and
other irritants.
</P>
<P>
   And patients often fail to follow their medication routines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to understand,'' said Dr. George O'Connor, director
of the adult asthma program at BMC. ``It's hard to stay faithful to
taking regular or twice-daily medications,'' he added. ``And once
they're feeling well, they tend to put their inhalers aside and the
benefits wear off and their asthma gets bad again.''
</P>
<P>
   Patients find it hard to really grasp the need for both
long-term and short-term medication, say O'Connor and others. The
long-term anti-inflammatory drugs _ the inhaled steroids,
nedocromil, theophylline and others _ bring no immediate relief. So
patients may gradually stop taking them, and instead overuse the
short-acting beta-2-agonists that open their airways but don't
fight the chronic inflammation.
</P>
<P>
   And in the inner city, the obstacles may loom even larger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people don't have any access to health care except
neighborhood clinics or the emergency room, and they won't get
continuity of care,'' said Ellie Thornton, head of a community
outreach asthma program at Howard University School of Medicine in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   For those without health insurance, preventive care is an
unaffordable luxury. ``You only go to the physician when there's a
problem. The doctor writes a prescription for a $40 drug and a $55
inhaler, and what do you do? You get a quick fix until you can't
breathe again, and then you go back to the doctor,'' Thornton said.
</P>
<P>
   For these reasons, making a dent in the asthma problem calls for
stronger patient-doctor relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a chronic disease like asthma, there has to be a very
rich exchange between physician and patient, so the physician
understands enough about the asthma episodes'' to make the right
diagnosis and treatment plan, said Noreen M. Clark, dean of the
School of Public Health at the University of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   The newly begun Inner City Asthma Study in Boston and other
cities is testing, among other things, a close monitoring of
patients and their families by doctors and nurses, said O'Connor at
BMC. He and Steinbach are co-principal investigators of the study.
</P>
<P>
   Health professionals are calling the families every two months
and asking about their symptoms, their medication and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Another part of the study sends health workers to the homes of
patients, providing expertise and equipment for reducing patients'
exposure to dust mites, cockroach debris, molds, and other
triggers.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kevin Weiss, an asthma specialist at Rush Presbyterian
Medical Center in Chicago, says efforts like these are necessary,
but change isn't easy to effect. ``It's not access to knowledge
that makes a difference,'' said Weiss. ``It's trying to motivate
change at a very local level _ right down in the (medical)
practice.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
USING STEROIDS (sidebar) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many people are confused about treating asthma with steroids _
is it safe? Will it slow my child's growth?
</P>
<P>
   Concern heightened last year after the Food and Drug
Administration directed a labeling change on inhaled steroid drugs
_ commonly used to control inflammation in asthma patients _
because of some evidence that it might slow growth in children or
increase the risk of cataracts.
</P>
<P>
   The answers to these concerns aren't entirely in, and last year
the FDA ruled that the drugs had to be labeled with a warning about
possible effects on growth. The inhaled steroids are drugs like
Pulmacort, Flovent, Azmacort, Aerobid, Vanceril and Beclovent,
which are delivered only to the lungs and aren't absorbed by the
rest of the body.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FDA saw some subtle signs'' of slowed growth in research
studies, ``not major effects,'' said Dr. Stanley Szefler at the
National Jewish Hospital. He said that only children with the most
severe asthma cases need to receive high doses of the inhaled
steroids that could conceivably affect growth. ``Treatment should
be based on controlling symptoms, and using the lowest effective
dose that controls symptoms,'' said Szefler.
</P>
<P>
   And to parents worried about using the steroids, he points out
that severe, untreated asthma itself can interfere with growth.
</P>
<P>
   While further studies may resolve the question more precisely,
Szefler and most other specialists say parents shouldn't avoid
giving their children inhaled steroids, as long as the physician
monitors the child's growth rate twice or more each year.
</P>
</TEXT>
