<SLUG> BC-SCI-SKATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMANS FUELING SKATE'S DECLINE BIOLOGISTS WARN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Homely and obscure, barndoor skates never attracted much
attention as they cruised the ocean floor off the New England
coast. When these sting ray-like creatures turned up in fishing
nets, most fishermen just chucked their carcasses overboard because
almost no one eats them.
</P>
<P>
   But now the barndoor skate could earn the dubious distinction of
becoming the first saltwater fish that humans have driven to
extinction in modern times, an international group of biologists
warn. The same fishing crisis that decimated the cod on Georges
Bank, they say, has almost wiped out the humble skate as well.
</P>
<P>
   Because so many fishermen unintentionally kill barndoor skates,
the biologists estimated that their numbers have fallen by more
than 90 percent since the 1950s, leaving Georges Bank as one of the
barndoor skate's last known strongholds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody was trying to eliminate barndoor skates. We're losing
them because nobody watched for impacts of what we're doing,'' said
Elliott Norse, president of the Marine Conservation Biology
Institute in Redmond, Wash., who organized a meeting of biologists
in Boston last month that resulted in this week's warning about
barndoor skates, one of several skate species.
</P>
<P>
   If the barndoor skate does survive, its days of obscurity may
soon be over. Two environmental groups have petitioned the National
Marine Fisheries Service to list the fish as an endangered species,
which likely would lead to new limits on fishing on Georges Bank,
where thousands of square miles are already closed to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're throwing everything at us now,'' complained Malvin
Kvilhaug, owner of three Fairhaven-based scallop boats. He
suggested that environmentalists are using the skates' plight to
block fishermen from harvesting scallops on Georges Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the National Marine Fisheries Service (NMFS),
mindful of the potential harm to the region's fishing industry, say
they need more information to develop a plan to help the skates,
and they have appealed for a calm, unemotional debate.
</P>
<P>
   But some environmentalists say the agency can't be trusted to
protect the skates, and are already threatening to seek a court
order forcing the agency to do more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We maintain that NMFS has adopted a pro-extinction policy for
marine wildlife, and is literally the fox guarding the chicken
coup,'' said Max Strahan of Boston-based Green World, known for his
provocative tactics and rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the barndoor skate, a relative of the shark, is an
innocent bystander in the fishing crisis. Fast swimmers that grow
up to five feet long, skates live near the ocean bottom in many of
the same areas as cod, scallops and other commercially valuable
seafoods, where they can be swept into fishermen's nets and scallop
dragging gear as they pass.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other types of skate that are increasingly popular at
upscale restaurants, people historically have not eaten barndoor
skates. As a result, biologists in the US and Canada paid limited
attention to their population decline, often not even keeping track
of how many are caught.
</P>
<P>
   But, last year, a pair of researchers at Dalhousie University in
Nova Scotia found that the barndoor skate population had declined
by up to 25 percent a year from the 1950s until recently in the
waters from Newfoundland to southern New England. Barndoor skates
have not been seen in 20 years in some places, while numbers had
been reduced by 99 percent in others.
</P>
<P>
   ``The species almost went extinct without anyone noticing it,''
said Ransom Myers, co-author of the skate paper, published last
year in Science, and a signer of the biologists' statement on the
skates' decline.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Serchuk, a biologist at the National Marine Fisheries
Service in Woods Hole, also signed the warning, but he said that
recent federal surveys offer ``a glimmer of hope,'' an increase in
skates on Georges Bank since the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   However, the skate rebound on Georges Bank may actually bolster
efforts to protect the skates. The increase roughly coincides with
the collapse of codfishing on the bank, and a steep drop in
fishing. As a result, some researchers and activists suggest it
shows the payback from limiting fishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's required now is a very careful and very deliberate
evaluation of the data that we have on the barndoor skate,'' said
Serchuk. His agency will have a year to determine whether the skate
is endangered, and, meanwhile, NMFS will continue research into the
fish's problems.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the agency's decision, the skate debate reflects
the increasingly complex issues descending on fishermen as
fisheries biologists take a broader view of life under the sea.
After years of focusing on commercial fisheries, biologists are
increasingly turning to other creatures from sponges to right
whales that may be harmed by fishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly we're not keeping our finger on the sea's pulse,''
said Norse. ``The drastic decline of the barndoor skate says we
need refuges in the sea where wildlife can live, grow and reproduce
. . . without being killed off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
