<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY DO MOSQUITO BITES SWELL AND ITCH? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. When a mosquito bites you, why does it leave a bump, and why
does it bleed sometimes?
</P>
<P>
   A.B., J.S., D.S., Mattapan, Mass.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Putting it as politely as possible, it's because they spit
into your skin while they're looking for the best place to suck
your blood.
</P>
<P>
   Mosquito saliva is a fascinatingly complex mix of chemicals.
When the insect lands, after finding you by the scent of carbon
dioxide from your breath, lactic acid on your skin, and even by
your infrared heat signature, it pokes its probe into your skin
several times while looking for an arteriole or venule (mini-artery
or vein) from which to draw its moist meal. As it does, the bug
injects saliva, which contains an anesthetic so you don't feel
yourself being poked and slap the little bugger.
</P>
<P>
   The saliva also contains an anti-coagulant to stop the blood
from clotting while the mosquito samples a taste from each spot.
When it finds the right one, it bores in again and this time a
vasodilator in the saliva widens the passageway, increasing the
blood flow.
</P>
<P>
   All those foreign chemicals in the saliva triggers our immune
system. When we're young, we respond with a part of the immune
system that releases histamines, which makes the cells in the
lining of our blood vessels spread apart, letting fluid out into
the skin where it can attack the foreign chemicals. That fluid
causes swelling and itching. After we've been bitten enough and
after our immune systems have matured, a different kind of antibody
carries the saliva off to macrophages, which are like microscopic
garbage disposers in our blood stream that destroy invading
substances. That's why children get bigger bumps from mosquitoes
than adults do.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why do tulips peter out after one spring but daffodils
multiply and rebloom?
</P>
<P>
   DM, Northampton, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Blame it on their bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   Professor of Horticulture August DeHertogh of North Carolina
State University, one of the leading experts in the world on bulbs,
says tulips and daffodils are both true bulbs, but their growth and
development cycles are different as night and day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tulip reproduces by annual bulb replacement,'' he says.
``Each spring, as the tulip bulb is sending up its flower and
foliage above, it's starting next year's bulb, a daughter down
below. By the end of the season, the mother bulb is used up, and
the daughter has grown and stored enough food to start next year's
tulip.''
</P>
<P>
   But lots of things can keep the daughter bulb from getting big
enough to get the flower going again the following year:
</P>
<P>
   If the daughter doesn't get big enough to be next year's Mom,
the tulip behaves more like an annual than a perennial and dies
off.
</P>
<P>
   Compare that to the robust regenerative strategy of the
daffodil. Their bulbs last for three to four years. They're not all
used up in one growing season. A daffodil can survive one or two
bad growing seasons. They're more tolerant of a wider range of
growing conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Daffodils have poisons in their foliage. Animals don't eat them,
so they can manufacture and store energy longer.
</P>
<P>
   And their bulbs have three or more ``cloves,'' each of which
will send up a shoot, compared with the all-or-nothing one-piece
tulip bulb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some cultivated varieties of tulips have a greater genetic
ability to produce large daughters and they'll come back better,''
DeHertogh says. ``But in general, tulips just are not as naturally
perennialized as daffodils.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write
to How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
