<HEADER>
A4849 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-ASTHMA-CAUSE-BOS &LR;      04-12 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ASTHMA-CAUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCH PROBES VARIED FACTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After the fall of the Berlin Wall a decade ago, researchers
compared asthma rates in East Germany, where outdated factories
belched pollution into the skies, with the rates in more affluent,
less polluted West Germany. Surely, they thought, the East would
have far more asthmatics.
</P>
<P>
   But they were wrong. East Germans had less asthma _ although
they had more bronchitis _ while in West Germany, there were more
sufferers of asthma and allergies.
</P>
<P>
   This is just one of many intriguing _ and sometimes perplexing _
studies that leave asthma specialists debating the reasons for the
worldwide asthma epidemic. Many factors appear to contribute, but
there's not enough evidence to link any one of them conclusively to
the disease.
</P>
<P>
   It's been especially difficult to single out potential causes
that have changed over the past 20 or 25 years, when asthma rates
began to take off. Since the increase has been sharpest among
inner-city residents, and children in particular, many studies have
focused on them.
</P>
<P>
   What is known today is that asthma is fundamentally an
inflammatory disease, and emotional factors, such as stress, are no
longer considered important causes, but they can certainly worsen
existing asthma.
</P>
<P>
   Air pollution in general is ``absolutely not'' the answer, said
Dr. Scott Weiss, director of respiratory and environmental
epidemiology at the Channing Laboratory at Brigham and Women's
Hospital in Boston. He points out that U.S. pollution rates have
fallen while asthma rates have climbed, and areas of China with
heavily polluted skies have relatively low asthma rates.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said, there's plenty of evidence that particulate
air pollution, diesel fumes, and other pollutants worsen the
symptoms of people with asthma.
</P>
<P>
   One intriguing theory about the rise of asthma in developed
countries is that infants and toddlers are exposed to fewer and
fewer infections that challenge their immune systems. As a result,
the immune responses of children today may develop along a
different path; thus they are more likely to respond in an allergic
way to substances, like pollen and dust mites, that aren't really
dangerous. But the reaction itself becomes harmful if it leads to
asthma symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like you have this cannon and nowhere to shoot
it,'' Weiss said. ``We've eliminated all these infections (in
childhood) and your immune system is out there looking for things
to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Could indoor pollutants in the increasing number of
tightly-sealed buildings be to blame? Perhaps, but some researchers
point out that people in the inner city probably don't live in the
kind of modern, well-sealed structures that are implicated in
``sick-building'' syndromes. Children would presumably be less
vulnerable to sick building complaints than adults, who are more
likely to work in modern office buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Thomas Platts-Mills, head of asthma and allergic diseases at
the University of Virginia School of Medicine, has been searching
for lifestyle culprits that have changed over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to suburban children, he said, those in the inner city
are more likely to play indoors and to become obese. ``I think
what's happened is you have a population that is getting more
exposure (to dust mites and cockroach droppings), but also has
given up outdoor exercise, and that combination is disastrous.''
</P>
<P>
   There is some evidence linking obesity to asthma susceptibility,
though the exact mechanism isn't yet known.
</P>
<P>
   It is known that some people are genetically more susceptible to
asthma than others. But now researchers in Boston and New York are
wondering if the amount of allergens a child is exposed to _ not
only in infancy but even in the womb _ could be the decisive factor
in whether the individual later develops asthma.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Gold, a researcher at the Channing Laboratory at Brigham
and Women's Hospital, is studying children in 499 families that are
afflicted with asthma in various areas of Boston. She and her
colleagues are measuring the levels of dust mites, cockroach
debris, cat dander, fungi, and other allergens in the homes. The
infants will be monitored for several years to see whether those
exposed to higher levels of allergens develop asthma at a greater
rate than those who had lower amounts in their environment.
</P>
<P>
   By studying these very early risk factors, said Gold, it may be
possible to show that cleaning up the home environment can actually
prevent even those children with a genetic predisposition from
developing asthma.
</P>
<P>
   In Weiss' view, evidence is converging that asthma is similar to
other chronic, multifactorial diseases of Western culture like
diabetes, coronary heart disease, and high blood pressure: all of
them have a genetic component that's triggered by various factors
like diet, stress, obesity, lack of physical activity, and so
forth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to crack this in the next five years,''
predicted Weiss. With scientists' rapidly improving ability to find
genes and proteins that influence health and disease, he said, ``we
may really get a handle on what's happening here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
