<HEADER>
A4851 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-ASTHMA-2TAKES-ART     04-12 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ASTHMA-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEARNING TO BREATHE FREE: THE ASTHMA EPIDEMIC 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo and two graphics are being sent to NYTNS
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (A special report)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At age 13, Steven D'Agostino is shackled to a tedious regimen of
daily drugs and inhalers, limits on his activities, and a bedroom
so stripped down and stark his family calls it ``The Cell.''
</P>
<P>
   But even these strict measures can't always prevent the dreaded
onset of an acute asthma attack, when his chest tightens and he
struggles to breathe. Steven's worst episode, in 1996, put him in
Children's Hospital in Boston for over a week, with a breathing
tube down his throat and a ventilator supplying air as massive
doses of drugs were pumped into his veins.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't talk about it much, but recently, the eighth-grader
recently let the nightmarish memories take shape in a poem. ``In
the dark of the night/another ambulance arrives/Taken from one
hospital to another/losing the fight for air,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Once at Children's, he continues, there was ``The sound of tears
drowned out by the machines of life'' in the intensive care unit.
His mother, Donna, remembers anxious hours when Steven was so
exhausted by his struggle for air that ``he didn't even have the
strength to cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Acute, life-threatening crises like these are the most visible
and dramatic features of asthma, the chronic, inflammatory lung
disease that's rising at epidemic rates in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Since the early 1980s, the incidence of asthma _ which had
previously been dropping _ has soared. The sharpest rise has been
among children, who make up about one-third of asthma patients.
</P>
<P>
   Only in the past few years has the urgency and seriousness of
the asthma problem begun to attract wide attention and new efforts
to attack it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really one of the most important and alarming problems
in child health,'' said Dr. Irwin Redlener, president of the
nonprofit Children's Health Fund in New York City. ``It has snuck
up on us and the reasons aren't entirely understood,'' added
Redlener, who also heads community pediatrics at Montefiore Medical
Center.
</P>
<P>
   The incidence of asthma has risen more than 75 percent in the
United States since 1980, and a startling 160 percent in children
under four. An estimated 17.3 million Americans now have asthma,
and deaths, while fortunately not common, have also increased to
over 5,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the sickness and many of the deaths from asthma are
considered preventable. Yet, despite improved diagnosis and
treatment, the asthma problem overall seems only to be worsening.
</P>
<P>
   Even when attacks are not severe or life-threatening, symptoms
like tiredness and shortness of breath and wheezing can eat away at
quality of life, productivity, and health care dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Asthma is the single biggest cause of missed school days (about
10 million a year), causes half a million hospitalizations, and
costs the economy an estimated $6 billion annually.
</P>
<P>
   This troubling picture is something of a paradox. After all, the
air is cleaner than it was 30 years ago; researchers have gained a
deeper understanding of the asthma process, if not its root cause;
more and better drugs exist to quell symptoms and keep the disease
under control. Yet the epidemic continues.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons not entirely clear, the asthma burden is falling
heaviest on minorities, especially those living in urban poverty.
Blacks and Hispanics have a higher rate of asthma and also get
sicker. Minorities have a threefold greater rate of
hospitalizations, double the rate of emergency room visits, and
``more wheezing days and episodes requiring a parent to miss
work,'' says Dr. Peyton Eggleston, a longtime asthma researcher at
Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore, quoting findings from a
federally funded study.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, research on the causes of asthma and factors that
worsen it has been stepped up, and new drugs are being designed to
augment or replace today's medications, which are inconvenient and
have some adverse side effects. The federal government has issued
guidelines on treating asthma aimed at putting the latest research
findings into practice.
</P>
<P>
   And recently, medical and social campaigns aimed at reducing the
toll of the disease have been launched.
</P>
<P>
   In some medical centers, physicians, nurse practitioners, health
educators and mental health workers are all involved in providing
care.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because it's so common, asthma isn't always taken
seriously. And asthmatics, unlike people with many chronic
diseases, don't stand out. ``People don't really understand that
the kids can look so normal and be so sick when they're acutely
ill,'' said Dr. Robert Liscio, a Hollis, N.H., radiologist whose
son Christopher had severe asthma as a youngster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something people can see and hear and touch,'' said
Representative Patrick Kennedy, Democrat of Rhode Island, ``and
there's enormous pressure (on people who have it) to minimize it.''
Kennedy, son of Senator Edward Kennedy, has had severe asthma all
his life. ``This disease is a real terror, because there is so much
psychological impact on kids who grow up with it,'' added Kennedy,
who said it eroded his self-image in a family where playing
competitive sports was a badge of honor.
</P>
<P>
   Asthma is the most common chronic disease of children, and can
be present almost from birth. The term refers to a group of
symptoms involving the respiratory system: wheezing, shortness of
breath, coughing, and tightness of the chest muscles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
