<SLUG> BC-TEACHERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME LEFT BETTER JOBS, ANSWERED INNER CALL TO TEACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN IWASAKI  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Above the blackboard in Penny Pagels' classroom at
Ballard High School is a cutout picture of a brain and an
admonition. ``This is your brain,'' the sign says. ``Use it to your
advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Pagels, a science teacher who formerly did cellular research for
a biotechnology firm, spurs student thinking with a rat-a-tat
speaking style that mixes quips and facts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, hands are flying in the air,'' she says after asking how
seeds are dispersed during a biology class discussion on plant
reproduction. When a student delivers the correct answer, she
blurts, ``Thank you, Doctor!''
</P>
<P>
   She's in her element.
</P>
<P>
   As teachers in Washington campaign for higher wages, Pagels
represents the educator who has spurned better pay in private
industry to come to the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Applicants to the University of Washington's masters-in-teaching
program ``could be nurses, lawyers, engineers,'' said Allen Glenn,
dean of the College of Education. ``We've had Nordstrom shoe
salespeople.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their background, they seek more significance in life,
not more bucks in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   About half the UW's teaching applicants are making a career
shift, a percentage that generally has remained steady for five
years, said Nathalie Gehrke, director of teacher education.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always stunned to see an applicant with a Ph.d,'' Gehrke
said. ``(Applicants in general) talk about a mission, a legacy,
doing something for other people. They use a language that's much
more spiritual.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Vaughan, associate dean of Washington State University's
College of Education, said the university had 125 applications last
fall for its masters-in-teaching program in Vancouver, Wa., the
highest ever. About three-quarters of those applicants were
changing careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm struck by how many people are saying things like, `I need
to feed my soul,' and I wonder if they know what they're getting
into,'' Vaughan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not idealistic or starry-eyed. They're coming from
jobs where the emphasis is on input and output. It doesn't really
support their need to make a difference with human beings over
time.''
</P>
<P>
   As many as 90 percent of students in Seattle University's
masters-in-teaching program are also shifting careers, said Margit
McGuire, director of teacher education.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are coming from the social service areas,''
McGuire said. ``Maybe they worked in the juvenile delinquency area,
social work, tutoring, some kind of service job. They thought they
could have a greater impact if they could be teachers of these
people'' instead of having them as clients.
</P>
<P>
   Pagels' path to the classroom was through the laboratory, not
social work. After earning a bachelor's degree in marine biology
and zoology from Humboldt State University in Arcata, Calif., in
1986, her peripatetic career included jobs with the National Marine
Fisheries Service, a Japanese fishing company, the Peace Corps, a
marine laboratory in Ireland and Greenpeace in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   After two years at ZymoGenetics, a Seattle biotech firm, she
answered an inner call to the classroom and entered the Seattle
University teaching program. She is in her second year at Ballard
High.
</P>
<P>
   It was during Pagels' Greenpeace stint, when she often spoke at
schools, that she first seriously considered teaching, she said.
Instead of banging heads with a ``not-so-friendly audience'' of
legislators, she thought she could make a difference by winning
over a younger generation.
</P>
<P>
   Her Greenpeace job paid $33,000 a year, about $6,000 more than
she currently earns, even though she now has a master's degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do it (teaching) for money,'' she said. ``It's so
important to me. I wanted to give something back to society instead
of complaining how society is deteriorating.''
</P>
<P>
   Teaching was ``definitely the right choice,'' said Pagels, 34,
who started a new class in genetics at Ballard High and also
teaches biology and biotechnology. ``Every day is different. I get
to have a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   So do her students, thanks to plenty of hands-on, inquiry-based
projects. In a recent biology assignment, students were asked to
develop a fertilizer product, including compiling a list of organic
or inorganic elements, making a ``recipe'' and creating a sales
pitch, all on a mock $10,000 budget.
</P>
<P>
   During their presentations, teams of students hawked their
products, with some saying their specialized mixtures ``turn the
competition green with envy.''
</P>
<P>
   Pagels, who regularly addresses her students with a booming
``Ladies and Gentlemen!'', has ``got fun ways of doing stuff,''
said freshman Aaron Bond. He calls biology one of his two favorite
classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``She knows what she's talking about from experience,'' agreed
sophomore Lily Hereford.
</P>
<P>
   For teacher Scott McMahon at Bellevue's Sammamish High School,
history did nothing for him as a teenager.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not just because of the way it was taught; it was
because I was 17 years old,'' said McMahon, 38. ``I did not have
the life experience to relate to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he does. McMahon came to teaching from Microsoft, where he
was a technical writer for five years. Before that, he was a
sportswriter, copy editor and page designer for newspapers in
Washington and New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft is a fascinating place to work, but you can go
literally weeks at a time without (extensive) people contact,''
McMahon said. ``Since the projects are so long, I just needed
something where I could see the results on a day-by-day basis and
work with real people.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he teaches about 140 students per day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having kids of my own probably gave me a focus for doing
something for the next generation,'' said McMahon, whose children
are 7 and 4.
</P>
<P>
   As for compensation, ``there's no question I made more money at
Microsoft,'' he said, though he doesn't say how much. ``I wouldn't
overplay it. ... If I was living month-to-month, I probably would
not have gone this route.''
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Pittenger, who graduated with McMahon last year in the
UW's masters-in-teaching program, earlier worked as a dietician and
in food service administration for Boeing and for Riverside
Hospital in California.
</P>
<P>
   During the years she took time off from her career to raise two
daughters, now 19 and 13, Pittenger pondered a return to the work
force.
</P>
<P>
   At cocktail parties, ``you were measured by what your job was,''
she said. ``If I said I stayed home with children, people literally
stepped away from me, like I had no value.''
</P>
<P>
   Pittenger, who teaches social studies and language arts at
Kentlake High School in Kent, said teaching appeals to her because
``you really are making a difference,'' she said. ``You don't get
that in a lot of other jobs. ... I like the kind of rewards you get
in education. It's not putting a Band-Aid on the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Monetary rewards are another matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hope you're compensated enough so you're not eligible for
food stamps,'' said Pittenger, who is in her 40s and whose husband
is a manager and engineer at Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be difficult to be a teacher if my husband didn't
have a good job. We all knew up front the reward was not going to
be financial. We're not blind about that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
