<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4854 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANDS-TRIBUTE-SPI &LR;      04-12 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANDS-TRIBUTE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANDS FIND NICHE MIMICKING REAL ACTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TERESA TALERICO  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ If imitation is the sincerest form of flattery, Tyler
Lindsley and his band pay a whopping compliment to The Cars.
</P>
<P>
   They pay tribute, really, by donning skinny ties and
checkerboard sneakers, dubbing themselves the Used Cars and
recreating every last chord of ``Just What I Needed,'' ``My Best
Friend's Girl,'' ``Shake It Up'' and other hits by the 1980s new
wave band.
</P>
<P>
   A Seattle quintet, Used Cars is among hundreds of tribute bands
that have found a niche mastering _ or at least mimicking _ another
group's act.
</P>
<P>
   Call them cheesy. Call them copycats. But fans can't get enough
of these bands, which imitate everyone from Aerosmith to ZZ Top and
have cornered a market thought to be pioneered by the first Elvis
Presley impersonators.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike cover bands, which play music from a variety of
performers, tribute bands devote themselves to a specific artist or
group.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, a city better known for alternative rockers
struggling to perform original music, several tribute bands have
managed to thrive. They include Randy Hansen (Jimi Hendrix),
Whiskey Creek (Lynyrd Skynyrd), Machine Head (Deep Purple), The
Nowhere Men (The Beatles), In Color (Cheap Trick), Bon Scott's Army
(AC/DC), Ham Valen (Van Halen) and The Honky Tonk Revue (Hank
Williams Sr.).
</P>
<P>
   Most, with the exception of internationally famous Hansen,
remain local bar bands. Few can afford to quit their day jobs.
Still, they keep dance floors crowded and live out a fantasy most
music fans only dream about while playing air guitar along with
their stereos.
</P>
<P>
   The Used Cars include a waiter, delivery truck driver and
Lindsley, a self-employed landscape/maintenance worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a big moneymaking venture for us,'' said the
31-year-old drummer/founder. ``We all have regular jobs. This is
kind of more for fun.'' Lindsley was 13 when he discovered The
Cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the first couple of records came out, I was really into
them,'' he said. ``I thought it would be a great idea to put on a
show and play the music I loved so much as a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Clubgoers, in turn, seem to enjoy the tribute bands, essentially
the next best thing to the real McCoy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like seeing a national act,'' says Mark Durbin, a Seattle
promoter who works with tribute bands. ``People like to see that
kind of music. It reminds them of the old school days.''
</P>
<P>
   Some are remarkably good, mastering everything from songs to
style to stage presence. Others make you yearn to hear the real
artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as tribute bands go,'' said Steve Dougan of Machine
Head, ``there are a lot of wannabes, but not that many who have put
it together well.''
</P>
<P>
   At a recent concert at the Tractor Tavern in Seattle's Ballard
neighborhood, the Honky Tonk Revue delivered enough twang and yodel
to make Hank Williams proud.
</P>
<P>
   The nine-piece band, which includes an upright bass, pedal steel
guitar and fiddle, performed ``Your Cheatin' Heart,'' ``Honky
Tonkin'' and other hits by the warbly-throated country legend who
died too young (at 29).
</P>
<P>
   The dance floor never emptied. Guys in jeans and women in cowboy
boots and swirly skirts twirled, two-stepped and did the Western
swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a campy version of the Hank stuff,'' said guitarist
Ron W. Bailey, 51. ``We try to keep it really rooted in the
authentic thing they had going.''
</P>
<P>
   The revue started five years ago, born of musicians that loved
Hank Williams enough to give up their Wednesday nights every winter
to play at the Tractor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just put on one of his records, and after not listening to
him for a long time, I realized how good it was,'' said Bailey, a
video producer by day. ``We said, `Anybody wanna do a tribute to
Hank?' and suddenly we had everyone who could do a Wednesday night,
which is usually an off-night.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Zasky, managing editor for the recently closed Musician
magazine, said he has seen tribute bands make their mark on the
music scene.
</P>
<P>
   Bjorn Again, an ABBA tribute, performs at festivals and venues
bigger than any ABBA ever played. It was a Kiss tribute band that
inspired the original rockers to put their makeup back on.
</P>
<P>
   And the ultimate Cinderella story: The vocalist for the tribute
band British Steel actually went on to replace Judas Priest's lead
singer, Rob Halford, said Zasky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people have managed to make it into a really big thing
and make it a worldwide success,'' he said. ``But most of them
don't really get very far.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Hansen has. The 44-year-old Seattle native started his
Jimi Hendrix act in the 1970s as part of a Las Vegas lounge act
called Kid Chrysler and The Cruisers. Today, he tours the world.
His music was featured in the movie ``Apocalypse Now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started doing this, the only tribute acts out there
were the Elvis tributes,'' he said. ``If there had never been that
first Elvis impersonator, I could never see this stuff happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Hansen says it's not just about pretending to be someone else.
It's about tipping your hat (or in his case, Stratocaster) to
someone you admire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never approached it from the standpoint of, `Oh I'm going to
be Jimi Hendrix out there,''' he said. ``That would be like a
trained monkey. I've approached it from, `God, I love this
music.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
