<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-WINNER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S THE HOTTEST GAME IN TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STRAFFORD, N.H. _ When a handsome new log-cabin home recently
sprouted on a pine-studded hill overlooking Bow Lake, many
townspeople here thought they had finally solved a tantalizing
riddle: Who collected a massive jackpot in January and managed to
keep it secret?
</P>
<P>
   But neighborhood detectives quickly ruled the home on the hill a
false alarm.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when local builder David Whitcher's springtime crews began
work on four breathtaking waterfront houses, eyebrows arched and
tongues wagged again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems every time I turn around, somebody's asking me if
these people are the ones who won the lottery,'' said Whitcher,
president of one of this small town's largest private employers.
``I just tell them, `Nope. These homes have been planned for quite
a while.' We still don't know who won that jackpot.''
</P>
<P>
   As Massachusetts continues to wonder about the identity of last
week's $197 million Big Game lottery winner, there is another
phantom winner here somewhere, tightly shrouded in legal secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   Three months ago, someone walked into a local general store and
walked out with a winning Powerball ticket valued at $67.1 million.
For days, as the pot sat unclaimed, the mystery surrounding the new
millionaire's identity heightened. And then, 13 days after the
drawing, the money was claimed _ not by the winner, but by a lawyer
saying that his clients, ``longtime New Hampshire residents,''
wished to remain anonymous because they ``highly value the
friendly, informal atmosphere in which they live.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, there's been a hot new game in this small (Pop.
3,000) town: Guess Who's the Millionaire? It's part mystery money
story, part parlor game. And across cups of coffee, outside the
local post office, and at the Isinglass Country Store &AMP; Deli, many
are playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we see who's driving the Bentley, that's when we'll
know,'' said Laura Thorne, a Montana native who came here in the
1940s to teach school and never left. ``Everybody's inquisitive
about it. We'll say who we hope got it. We'll say who we hope
didn't get it. We'll watch to see who's buying property.''
</P>
<P>
   When Steve Wright _ jokingly he insists _ told people that his
fishing buddy hit the jackpot, his friend was swiftly deluged with
200 telephone calls from reporters, friends, acquaintances, and
long-lost relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first rumor was that it was a teacher at the school. That
went around all over the place,'' said Wright, who owns Thorne's
Market in the center of town. ``Then I said it was my buddy. I'll
never do that again. Some people are still convinced he's the
winner _ and he isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like our version of `Waking Ned Devine,' '' said
Bill Cranley, a local homeowner, referring to a recent film
centered on lottery-ticket intrigue in Ireland. ``Nobody knows who
it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the locals have few clues about who won the mid-January
Powerball jackpot. But they're laying odds that one of their
year-round neighbors, or possibly a summertime resident here, has
become suddenly _ and quietly _ rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's coming forward. There's not even a leak,'' said Bill
Ward, who with his wife, Cathy, operates the country store that
sold the winning ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Ward said he doesn't know who the winner is. ``If I sell a
ticket, I sell a ticket. I don't ask to see a birth certificate,''
Ward said. And he said he wouldn't say even if he knew. ``But nine
chances out of 10, it's somebody local'' Ward said.
</P>
<P>
   The winning ticket was purchased on Friday, Jan. 15, a wintry
day when local residents figure only those who live or own property
nearby would be in this off-the-beaten-path town.
</P>
<P>
   The combination was among $29 worth of Powerball numbers sold
that day by Ward, who received a cool $30,000 for selling New
Hampshire's fourth and largest Powerball jackpot, available to
bettors in 20 states and the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth Newcomb, the lawyer who represents the trust that
preserves the veil of anonymity, would say only that the winners
(he refers to them in the plural form) will continue to live much
as they had before their bonanza and that they wish to avoid the
damaging consequences that sometimes accompany unexpected fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have chosen to remain anonymous and are confident that
all residents of New Hampshire who cherish their own privacy and
lifestyles will understand and respect this wish to remain out of
the public eye,'' the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   As lottery fever has swept the country, there have been reports
of broken friendships, suicides, and squandered riches as greed and
poor planning have tarnished that winning feeling of knowing that
your ship has come in.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Buddy Post, a former Pittsburgh carnival worker,
hit the Pennsylvania lottery for $16.2 million in 1988. Within
eight years, he had been convicted of assault, his sixth wife left
him, his brother was convicted of trying to kill him, and his
landlady sued him and won one-third of the jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   Like most residents here, New Hampshire lottery officials say
they have no desire to intrude on the winner's privacy. But they
said the situation does present a bit of a public relations
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number-one thing we strive for daily in New Hampshire is
to keep 100 percent integrity,'' said Maura McCann, a spokeswoman
for the state's lottery. ``And sometimes when winners claim it in
the form of a trust, that may lead to some skepticism with the
lottery. It's more difficult to say that ABC Trust has won $67
million versus John Smith winning $67 million.'
</P>
<P>
   John Smith, or whatever his or her name is, ultimately chose to
receive the winnings in a lump sum of $38,049,787.33 _ an amount
that was reduced by 28 percent, or $10,653,940, for federal income
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Even Judith Bates, co-owner of See-It Surveillance Co., which
sells sleuthing equipment, said she has no idea who the winner is.
But that doesn't stop her from guessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are people in town who do know who it is,''
Bates said. ``We sort of think it's somebody who owns a camp up
here and was here that day to check on it. We do feel that things
will be showing up in town _ a new car, improvements to their home
or camp. I just hope it's somebody who can use it.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is no consensus about the winners' identity, their
decision to shield themselves from the public is widely understood
and respected in this town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's a dream everyone has _ to hit the big one,''
said resident Dave Hewitt. ``It's probably a smart idea to stay
anonymous. People would probably hound the heck out of them. This
is a town that likes to live and let live. People are friendly, but
we don't need to get into your business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
