<SLUG> BC-MISSING-TOURISTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY OF YOSEMITE VICTIMS TRIES TO PRESERVE NORMAL LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUREKA, Calif. _ Inside their modest, pale-green California
bungalow, the routines of family life for Jens Sund and his three
children go on much as they always have.
</P>
<P>
   The family's two dogs, Reggie, a bichon, and Gigi, a poodle,
clamor for attention. Dirty laundry is piled up at the washing
machine. And 10-year-old Jimmy does tricks with a yo-yo in the
kitchen and begs his dad to let him go to a friend's house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not tonight,'' said Jens Sund, warming his hands with a cup of
tea. ``You had a friend over for the last 24 hours. Me and you are
going to hang out one-on-one. We're going to go out and buy you
some shin guards and black soccer socks.''
</P>
<P>
   Buying gear for Jimmy's upcoming indoor soccer season is part of
Jens Sund's effort to preserve some sense of normalcy for his
family, despite the mid- February slayings of his wife, Carole,
15-year-old daughter Juli, and family friend Silvina Pelosso, 16,
after their visit to Yosemite.
</P>
<P>
   Walking past a hallway lined with framed family photos assembled
by his wife, Jens Sund opened the door to Juli's room, which has
been left mostly untouched since her death. On her bed were two
Eureka High School yearbooks and a recent issue of Cheerleader
magazine. Posters of her favorite recent movies, ``A Bug's Life''
and ``Titanic,'' hung on the walls next to photos she has taken at
her grandparents' ranch. A snowboard she'd barely touched leaned
against the dresser.
</P>
<P>
   Sund said he is trying to use the room to keep it from becoming
a shrine. He and other family members often take naps on her bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not nearly as morbid or weird as you think,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, the family gathers to pay respects to Carole and
Juli Sund. On Saturday afternoon, under a steady rain, the family
held a private memorial service at St. Bernard's Catholic cemetery.
Of the three bodies, only Juli's remains have been released by the
FBI, so the family has put off a formal burial until a later date.
</P>
<P>
   At least 1,000 people, including Sen. Dianne Feinstein, are
expected at a public memorial service Sunday at 2 p.m. at Sacred
Heart Church in Eureka.
</P>
<P>
   The return to day-to-day life has been a struggle, friends said.
Those close to the family describe Carole Sund as a kind of
Supermom who held the family together with her nonstop energy.
</P>
<P>
   Jens Sund has tried to fill the void for his three remaining
children while he copes with the gruesome nature of Carole and
Juli's deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Jens Sund allowed The Examiner into his home last week as he and
his family prepared for the weekend services. Sund hopes media
attention about the case will help the FBI and other law
enforcement officials find the killer or killers.
</P>
<P>
   As the investigation inches forward, Sund is trying to move
beyond details of the crime to focus on his children, Jonah, 14,
Gina, 13, and Jimmy. All three were adopted by the Sunds as babies.
</P>
<P>
   Each morning, he fixes his youngest son a breakfast of bacon and
eggs, while scanning the morning headlines for news in the case. He
has taken time off work as a vice president at his in-laws' real
estate firm to pick the kids up from school, attend their
basketball games and take them shopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids need me,'' said Sund, standing in the dining room
before a table covered with pictures of Carole and the children,
which will be used for the Sunday service. ``And I think if I can
help the kids, they can help me.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of the children is working with a counselor. Jens Sund also
wants his kids to keep focused on their regular activities.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, he let his two older children go on an American
history trip last week with their seventh- and eighth-grade
classmates to Washington, D.C., that got them back late Friday,
just before the memorial service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carole had planned the trip and paid for it,'' said Carole
Carrington, Carole Sund's mother. ``It was a hard decision. When
something like this happens, it can frighten you and you don't want
your kids to go away across the country. He decided they should go
away on the trip and have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The weeks of stress have taken a toll on Jens Sund. He sleeps
just a few hours a night, which is visible in the dark crescents
under his eyes. He rarely sleeps past 4 a.m. and tries to make the
best of it by going jogging at sunrise on the beach with his dogs.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has given up the few drinks he used to have weekly.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he says he has become obsessed with his workout
machine, the Health Rider. He has lost 13 pounds since his wife and
daughter disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   He said he and his family have gotten a boost from the cards,
poems and teddy bears sent by people from around the country, and
from the kind words of strangers who recognize him from TV. He said
he will continue to do some interviews, including an appearance on
Oprah Winfrey's show to discuss child abuse, but does not want to
become a spokesman for a cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to do this for the rest of my life,'' he said.
``I'm going back to my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends are amazed that Sund has stayed so focused and steady
throughout the ordeal and through countless interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``It blows my mind,'' said David Oehler, a family friend. ``I
can't imagine I'd be handling this anywhere near as well as he has.
He's so methodical. He just takes on one thing right after another.
He's been like that throughout.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been three weeks since the family heard that the red 1999
Pontiac Grand Prix Carole Sund had rented for the trip to Yosemite
had been found charred in remote woods off Highway 108 near Long
Barn, Tuolumne County. DNA tests revealed that the two bodies in
the trunk were Carole Sund and Silvina Pelosso, an exchange student
living with the family.
</P>
<P>
   Juli Sund's body was found the following week 30 miles away near
Moccasin, Tuolumne County.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI believes the trio was either kidnapped or carjacked in
the El Portal area on the night of Feb. 15 or the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   No arrests have been made, but FBI agents and Tuolumne County
sheriff's deputies have been scouring the area, focusing on
residents with criminal records.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 1404EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990412.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4863 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-ASTHMA-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     04-12 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ASTHMA-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 (A special report)  
 UNDATED: ... chest muscles.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some people are only occasionally and mildly affected, while
many others, with moderate to severe asthma, are prone to having
acute attacks when a particularly bad allergy season or a simple
cold causes an exacerbation. Acute attacks can last hours, days or
even weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In people with asthma, the linings of the many-branched air
passageways are supersensitive to irritation: doctors call them
``twitchy.'' Genetic factors no doubt have a lot to do with
asthmatics' over-reactive airway linings, but environmental factors
are also extremely important.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, irritants like smoke and chemicals can send the
airways into spasms, narrowing down or blocking them. Some patients
liken it to trying to breathe through a straw. The person coughs,
wheezes and gasps for air, and often has a tight feeling in the
chest.
</P>
<P>
   Having trouble breathing is terrifying. ``It's like when you
were a kid and somebody pushed you underwater and you get
panicky,'' said Yvonne Joyner, a longtime asthma sufferer in
Dorchester.
</P>
<P>
   Allergies to pollens and other substances are a very common
trigger for asthma attacks. Not all people with asthma are
allergic, but most are, and a child who shows evidence of atopy _
meaning predisposed to react to many allergens _ is more likely to
develop asthma than others.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the muscle spasms, inflammation of the airways
causes the tubes to become swollen and plugged with mucus
secretions.
</P>
<P>
   It's now known that this inflammation is chronic: even when
someone isn't having an attack, cells from the body's immune system
are mistakenly swarming to the airways and causing potentially
permanent damage.
</P>
<P>
   Emotional stress can worsen asthma, but isn't the cause of it.
For most people, allergies are at the root of the airway's
overreactions. Common allergic triggers are tree or grass pollen,
animal dander, dust mites, cockroach droppings, and molds.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to allergens, asthma is often triggered by irritants
that include smoke, scents, cold dry air and colds or other
respiratory infections. As the asthma problem widens, there's a
greater recognition of how many people are bothered by things in
the environment that have no effect on most people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have patients who can't even walk down the soap aisle at
the supermarket'' without a bad reaction, said Kathleen Heitmiller,
a nurse practitioner at the Partners Asthma Center at Brigham and
Women's Hospital in Boston, who spends a lot of time helping
patients figure out what things set off their asthma and how to
avoid them.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic upsurge in asthma has occurred mainly in
industrialized countries, casting suspicion on one or more features
of Westernized lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been speculation about poor air quality and the
environment, but nothing has been convincingly put forward that
explains this large an increase,'' said Redlener of Montefiore
Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Suspects under investigation include specific forms of air
pollution, foul air inside ``sick buildings,'' diet, lack of
exercise, and obesity. One intriguing theory is that children have
less exposure to the infectious diseases of years past, so that the
body's immune system is more prone to overreacting when it
encounters essentially harmless substances like pollen or animal
dander.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best places to see the impact of the asthma is in a
school. School nurses now often say that dispensing asthma
medications is the biggest part of their job.
</P>
<P>
   At the Mattahunt Elementary School in Boston's Mattapan section,
dozens of kids line up before lunch every day outside the office of
nurse Marty Murphy. She lets them in five at a time to use inhalers
or nebulizer machines (``nebs,'' as the kids refer to them) that
administer the drugs via a face mask.
</P>
<P>
   Nurse Murphy opens the doors to a cupboard that's filled with
children's prescribed asthma medications and inhalers: many more
inhalers and nebulizer masks have overflowed into a set of
cardboard boxes on counters and tables.
</P>
<P>
   ``My God,'' said Murphy of the increase since she came to the
school in 1990. ``I used to give three or four treatments a day _
now it's more like 60 or 70.'' She said that all the teachers have
had to become familiar with asthma symptoms because so many kids
have the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The drugs and inhalers aren't simple to use, and if the children
don't follow directions precisely, they won't get enough medicine
into their lungs. The nurses have to show them over and over again.
Kids also have to learn to use ``peak flow meters'' _ handheld
devices calibrated to the patient's lung capacity. If used every
day, the meter can detect early signs of constricted breathing, so
that a change in medicine dosing can avert an attack.
</P>
<P>
   At the Tobin School in Boston's Roxbury section, nurse Sally
Logan said a survey showed that about 20 percent of students there
have the disease. A decade ago, it was only 11 percent, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Health workers worry that the schools themselves are
contributing to the problem. ``A lot of schools haven't gotten rid
of things like furred animals, chalk that makes dust, and scented
markers,'' said Heitmiller, the nurse practitioner at the Partners
Asthma Center at Brigham and Women's. Buildings in disrepair don't
help: at Mattahunt School, a teacher pointed to drooping, soggy
ceiling tile where water has leaked in over many years, potentially
nurturing mold that often triggers asthma symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Such concerns prompted a survey of school conditions by the
Massachusetts Department of Public Health last year, said Suzanne
Condon, head of environmental health assessment for the state.
Seventy percent of schools surveyed reported indoor air quality
problems. The sources of trouble, Condon said, ranged from blocked
ventilating ducts to mold to exhaust fumes from cars outside. Now
the state and the schools are working together to remedy these
potential asthma-provoking conditions, Condon said.
</P>
<P>
   The schools represent a microcosm of the asthma problem: their
efforts to improve the environment for the benefit of asthmatics
are based on anecdotes and educated guesses as much as they are on
solid evidence about what's at the root of the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   Likely, it will turn out that asthma has many interacting
causes. And this confronts medicine ``with a very interesting
challenge _ we know we have a big medical problem and we have to
handle it while researchers are looking for the cause,'' said
Redlener.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
