<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-CHOICES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MENTORS WE TRUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As book and record stores keep morphing from small independents
to Tower Records to Amazon.com, one would think that our range of
interests would grow exponentially. Yet it seems that the opposite
happens _ as choice grows, we tend to retreat into what we know
already. Mass marketing means narrowing of interests _ just look at
the radio dial to see how even one idiom, rock music, has become so
boringly segmented.
</P>
<P>
   How do you break out of the rut and expand your consciousness of
the contemporary arts scene? One way is to find a guru _ literally,
a guide _ who can make sense of all the choices out there by either
putting things in perspective or who, simply by force of
personality, can lead readers or listeners somewhere they might not
otherwise go. Oprah's Book Club serves that function for her
viewers; here are some others.
</P>
<P>
   --Christopher Lydon and ``The Connection'' _ Whether the subject
is Walt Whitman or Norman Mailer, Frank Sinatra or Gustav Mahler,
by the time Lydon and his guests are done dissecting, you want to
read all their books, hear all their music, or see all their
movies. The quality and quantity of the research is phenomenal, but
it's Lydon's curiosity and intelligence that keep ``The
Connection'' fully engaged and engaging. Although I haven't been a
fan of syndicating the show, it has done a laudable job of
promoting local people and stories as national topics. And let's
not forget that the best electronic site for sorting out what's
happening in Yugoslavia has been ``The Connection.''
</P>
<P>
   --Charlie Rose _ Rose isn't nearly as interesting an
interviewer, but as Lydon himself has proved, the art of the TV
interview is different from that of radio. At any rate, the guest
list is usually A-list and if Rose has a tendency to fawn, at least
the likes of Tom Stoppard and Bruce Springsteen are worth it. He's
particularly good at letting writers talk about writing.
</P>
<P>
   --David Byrne _ Can someone be too eclectic? Byrne sometimes
makes you wonder, but whether compiling world music collections for
Luaka Bop, hosting ``Sessions at West 54th'' on public television,
putting together movie soundtracks, appearing on the ``Red, Hot''
CDs or _ best of all _ making records himself, Byrne will introduce
you to everyone from Lyle Lovett to Lucinda Williams, Chocolate
Genius to P J Harvey, the Balanescu Quartet to Cole Porter, Los
Amigos Invisibles to Bloque. His interviews on ``Sessions'' show
that the old dorky persona wasn't an act after all, but so what.
His guests are great and they obviously enjoy speaking with him.
Witness Randy Newman's ``Hey, you've become a talking head.
</P>
<P>
   --Wynton Marsalis's Jazz at Lincoln Center and Herbie Hancock _
If you're looking for a primer on the great jazz musicians of the
century, from Louis Armstrong to Miles Davis, start with Marsalis's
three fine CDs with the Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra on Columbia
(skip ``Blood on the Fields,'' despite the Pulitzer). It's a
limited view of jazz, to be sure, so turn to Herbie Hancock's more
adventurous CDs, which pick up where Marsalis's repertory leaves
off.
</P>
<P>
   --Gidon Kremer _ Pierre Boulez's Deutsche Grammophon CDs make
the best case for the spiky modernists, and David Zinman's Argo and
Sony recordings, particularly those with Yo-Yo Ma, will introduce
you to many of this country's fine contemporary composers, but no
one cuts so convincingly through today's classical scene as Kremer.
(The violinist's recordings of the traditional repertory with
Leonard Bernstein, Nikolaus Harnoncourt, and Martha Argerich aren't
chopped liver, either.) Kremer has drifted from one label to
another but his most CDs are on Teldec, where he has just recorded
one of his finest CDs, ``Le Cinema,'' which includes music from
Charlie Chaplin, Nino Rota, Darius Milhaud, Toru Takemitsu, and
Astor Piazzola. (His three recordings of Piazzola compositions are
also worth checking out.) To unite these sensibilities is as
refreshing an accomplishment as classical music could wish for.
</P>
<P>
   --Stanley Kubrick _ The late filmmaker was one of the greatest
in the history of the medium, primarily for his abilities behind
the camera. Underlining the visual imagery, though, was an
exquisite taste in classical music. Kubrick introduced a whole
generation to the glories of the Strauss boys and Gyorgy Ligeti in
``2001: A Space Odyssey,'' while taking a different slant on Ludwig
Van (via Wendy Carlos) in ``A Clockwork Orange,'' combining
traditional Irish music with Baroque and classical music in ``Barry
Lyndon,'' and awakening the horror in the music of Bela Bartok,
Krzystof Penderecki, and Carlos in ``The Shining.'' The rock score
in ``Full Metal Jacket'' survives less well on its own; let's hope
``Eyes Wide Shut'' is both an earful and eyeful. You could also do
worse than reading Kubrick's literary compadres, particularly
Vladimir Nabokov, Jim Thompson, and Diane Johnson, who wrote the
screenplay of ``The Shining.''
</P>
<P>
   --Salman Rushdie _ Born in India and bred, partly, in England,
Rushdie combines the best of the European tradition and an
outsider's sensibility, not only as a writer but as a critic.
Rushdie's writing, particularly ``Imaginary Homelands,'' is an
eloquent exploration of the (mostly) contemporary literary scene,
one that makes you yearn for the time to read all the writers
represented. His latest book, ``Mirrorwork,'' is a more narrow
compilation of Indian writers.
</P>
<P>
   --Howard Zinn _ Gurus are, of course, teachers and my former BU
teacher still cuts through the media's conventional wisdom with
laserlike sharpness. If I no longer agree with him about everything
_ like the necessity for bombing Iraq _ his abiding humanism and
intelligence can turn around my sometimes all-too-conventional
wisdom _ like the necessity for bombing Yugoslavia. When he turns
his mind to it, he's also a keen critic, as shown in his demolition
of ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   --George Mansour, the Kendall Cinema _ How often have you walked
into this movie house and said to yourself, ``I want to see
everything that's playing here.'' Most of the reason is Mansour's
fine taste in movies, but Landmark has also done a terrific job in
making the place as comfortable as it is. The Kendall, though, has
become a victim of its success. Saturday nights can be a nightmare,
mostly because of the adjoining, independent garage, where you
might have to wait 15 minutes in the cold in order to get out of
the place.
</P>
<P>
   -- Robert Hurwitz, Nonesuch Records _ It's rare these days for
any but independent labels to have as strong a sensibility as
Nonesuch's. As head of the company, Hurwitz has cornered the market
on minimalist composers (Philip Glass, Steve Reich, John Adams),
but there's a wealth of material elsewhere, including Kremer's
Piazzola CDs, Audra McDonald's debut recording of up-and-coming
musical composers, the Kronos Quartet's 10-CD compilation, ``25
Years,'' and the upcoming Caetono Veloso release.
</P>
<P>
   --``Trainspotting'' _ The two CDs from the movie are an exciting
introduction to some of the best alternative groups like Pulp,
Blur, and the more techno Underworld, along with alternative
godfathers Lou Reed, Iggy Pop, and David Bowie. They restore a
faith in the future of rock that stations like WFNX and WBCN seem
to be doing their damnedest to shatter. (Rent the movie while
you're at it.)
</P>
<P>
   --PBS documentaries _ As Joel Cohen's letter to the editor last
week said, public television seems to be doing its best to kill off
the performing arts in favor of ``Cats'' and ``The Courage to Be
Rich.'' The one exception, aside from ``Sessions,'' is the area of
documentaries, as witnessed by those on Leonard Bernstein and Paul
Robeson on ``American Masters''; the Frank Lloyd Wright portrait by
Ken Burns; and the series on African-American artists by Blackside
productions, the last series under the late Henry Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   --The WHRB Orgies _ You couldn't ask for more of an immersion
than WHRB-FM's (95.3) forays into the life of an artist through the
best available (and sometimes unavailable) recordings. The next
orgy period is in May and includes four days of Charles Mingus
along with a somewhat lesser amount of Mahler, Muddy Waters, and
Mark E. Smith and the Fall.
</P>
<P>
   There are any number of other gurus out there. Ella Fitzgerald
and Frank Sinatra are the ways into the great American songbook,
Volume 1. Will Audra McDonald and Cassandra Wilson be Volume Two?
If you're more intrigued by smooth R&AMP;B/jazz than I am, look no
further than Quincy Jones's recently released ``From Q, With
Love.'' The fun, though, is in finding a guru of one's own. Happy
hunting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 1406EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
