<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4866 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      04-12 1462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING A GAIN ON THE SALE OF A HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My mother is 58 years old and is about to realize a $100,000
gain on the sale of her home. She is employed as a waitress, and
her income matches her monthly expenses. She has never invested
before and has no retirement accounts or pension benefits to look
forward to, except Social Security. What do you recommend as an
investment strategy to possibly generate $1,000 a month for her at
age 68?
</P>
<P>
   A.S., Framingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I'll suggest three strategies, ranging from a very
conservative approach to a middle course, and finally to one which
is riskier, but which is far from gambling and which also offers
the possibility of greater rewards. If your mother were simply to
put $100,000 in a solid mutual fund invested in
government-guaranteed mortgages and then reinvest all distributions
for ten years, she could reasonably expect that she would realize
an average 6.5 percent yield over the course of that decade, which
would take her account to $187,713 after 10 years. If she then
simply took the yield in cash, it would provide her with $1,016 a
month, with no invasion of the principal.
</P>
<P>
   What I have in mind here is a mutual fund invested in Ginnie Mae
securities, which are pools of bonds put together by a
quasi-governmental agency called GNMA and then sold to the public
as securities, carrying a government guarantee of both principal
and interest repayments. Despite these guarantees, these funds are
sensitive to interest rate fluctuations and can rise or fall
sharply when rates change. If you look back over a couple of
decades, the track record seems to be that these funds suffer one
or two bad years a decade, but also that they tend to make up the
lost ground fairly quickly. They make good long-term holdings for
retirees, but terrible holdings for people who might have to (or
might want to) cash out at short notice. Good examples here are the
Fidelity or Vanguard GNMA funds, although many other fund families
offer solid funds in this category. One attraction of such a
portfolio is that your mother would not have to change her
portfolio after she retires, but simply to begin drawing down the
yield.
</P>
<P>
   A slightly riskier approach would be to divide the money into
three segments, with half of it in a GNMA fund and 25 percent each
in a short-term corporate bond fund and in a high-yield (or junk)
bond fund. From such a portfolio, she might expect a yield of about
7 percent, but she should also expect a choppier ride in terms of
market value. Again, such funds can be found in most major mutual
fund families.
</P>
<P>
   Finally _ and this is about as far out on the risk spectrum as
she ought to be willing to go _ would be to mix a 50 percent
position in a GNMA fund with an identical holding in a balanced
fund. Balanced funds divide their holdings between stock and bond
portfolios, and although the potential for gains is considerably
greater because of the stock market exposure, the potential for
losses is also greater. She might hope that such a portfolio might
take her nest egg to $206,103 after a decade, representing average
7.5 percent returns. She could then divert all but about $20,000 of
her portfolio to the GNMA fund, where it would give her the same
income stream as I cited above, and she would have the extra
$20,000 in the balanced fund to give her some prospect of portfolio
growth to help her cope with the effects of inflation in the later
years of her retirement. An excellent fund in the balanced category
is Fidelity Puritan.
</P>
<P>
   Which of these three approaches she might take should rely in
good part on her appetite for risk; if she's the kind of person who
would panic or lose sleep if her savings lost a significant amount
of their value, she should certainly steer clear of the third
option. And remember, the first and most cautious approach would
fulfill the need you stated, so maybe she would feel most
comfortable with that limited risk.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, if she is not already contributing to an IRA, she
should begin with the first $2,000 of this money going into an IRA
account, which could be invested in the same manner as the rest of
the portfolio. Each year following, she could move another $2,000
from the taxable account to an IRA. This would reduce her current
tax liabilities, and would be unlikely to cause her very
considerable tax impact in retirement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a 73-year-old retiree who will be receiving $47,000 cash
proceeds from a buyout of a company in which I have held stock.
These shares have been generating a quarterly dividend of $525.60,
and I would like to replace this income or perhaps exceed it if
possible, but at my age I need safety of principal and an income
stream I can rely on. I have had bad experiences with several bond
mutual funds in the past, so I don't want much to do with them
again. CDs and Treasury securities, though safe, obviously don't
pay much any more, so I have thought of dividing the money among
purchases of several investment grade bonds or perhaps preferred
shares of solid larger-cap companies which have a long-term history
of paying a good dividend and perhaps even providing some growth to
keep up with inflation. What do you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   C.S., Hampton, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, the dividends you had been getting represented a yield
of only 4.47 percent, so you certainly can replace the income
stream with a good degree of safety. Even a money market mutual
fund would do the job, with the current rates for the better funds
in the range of 4.5 percent to 4.9 percent. Or you could look to a
five-year CD: Entering this week, the nation's average rate for CDs
under $100,000 was 4.61 percent, and the best rate offered
nationally was 5.90 percent. This would bump your quarterly income
stream from that $525.60 to a little more than $693, which is a
tidy advance. I won't bother to give you the institution with the
highest rate, because it will be out of date by the time you read
this, but check the Data Bank page in the Sunday editions of The
New York Times business section and it will provide the figures and
identify the institutions with the best rates.
</P>
<P>
   As for individual corporate bonds, you would certainly get
better rates, but you would also assume both credit risk and
interest-rate risk _ the risks, respectively, that the company
would default on the bonds, and that interest rates would rise,
rendering the current value of your holdings lower. With
preferreds, you would get a considerably higher yield while facing
the same kind of risks as with bonds, plus a little extra since
bonds take preference to preferreds if the company gets in serious
trouble. And you would have no serious potential for increase in
your principal unless you went with a convertible preferred issue
with terms, which are likely to make its conversion attractive in a
relatively short period of time. But in that instance, the issue is
likely to trade in a pattern that more closely relates to the stock
market than the bond market, so the risk becomes greater still.
</P>
<P>
   It seems to me that if increasing your income stream from what
you got with your old stock, plus safety, are your primary goals,
you can achieve both by shopping very carefully for a CD.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 77 years old and invest primarily for income. Recently I
put some money in Vanguard Intermediate-Term Corporate Bond fund.
Since then, the shares have constantly decreased in value. What
should I do? The distributions are being reinvested.
</P>
<P>
   B.R., Beaumont, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A. Patience is a virtue. This fund lost 0.7 percent in the first
quarter, more or less in line with the 0.6 percent loss for the
median intermediate-term corporate bond fund. Over a year, the fund
showed a 5.5 percent total return, precisely matching the median
results for the category. Over five years, its 7.7 percent average
annual total return compares favorably to the 7.0 percent median
results. Put simply, you shouldn't worry if the results for a bond
fund are poor for such a brief period, particularly when they are
pretty much in step with those of its peer funds. So I suggest you
hang in there, expecting that the worm will turn. Moreover, the
results for the fund have improved markedly since you wrote, and at
least the fund is within a whisker of a break-even for the year _
off by three basis points as this is written. Morningstar rates the
fund average, and year-to-date its performance is a bit better than
the average for its peers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 1407EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
