r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRISTA-McAULIFFE-HNS     04-12 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTA-McAULIFFE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER OF CHALLENGER VICTIM REMAINS SUPPORTER OF SPACE PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM O'BRIEN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, N.Y. _ Despite the death of her daughter Christa McAuliffe
in the 1986 Challenger explosion, Grace Corrigan remains a
supporter of space exploration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is necessary to do all the exploring they can do,''
Corrigan said during a speech Friday at Rensselaer Polytechnic
Institute, which is celebrating Space Week. ``I think it is
important for the International Space Station to go on. Space is
our future and your future.''
</P>
<P>
   Christa McAuliffe was chosen from 11,500 applicants to be the
first civilian passenger in space. President Ronald Reagan had
wanted a teacher to be the first citizen to ride aboard the Space
Shuttle, saying teachers could best communicate the wonders of
space in ordinary language.
</P>
<P>
   Corrigan discussed the impact her daughter's life has had on
others. She told the audience she hoped they would find ``Christa
was a worthy forerunner of yours, with something to teach, the most
important lesson: How to live well.''
</P>
<P>
   She said her daughter's decision to become a teacher was
unintentional, though Corrigan herself was a teacher. At a time
when women's career options seemed limited, McAuliffe thought
teaching her best choice.
</P>
<P>
   After initially struggling, Corrigan said, her daughter
discovered joy in teaching history. She started a course at Concord
High School in New Hampshire on American Women, hoping to give her
female students role models by using diaries of ordinary women.
</P>
<P>
   ``She emphasized the struggle on the homefront as well as the
battlefield were part of history,'' Corrigan said.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe's own brush with history began on Feb. 1, 1985 _ the
last day applications could be mailed to the Teacher in Space
program.
</P>
<P>
   In answering a question on why she wanted to fly into space,
McAuliffe wrote: ``I remember the excitement in my house when the
first satellites were launched. My parents were amazed, and I was
caught up in that wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   She recalled driving on a dark, rainy night and hearing men had
landed on the moon, and she remembered wondering why only men were
there. When Sally Ride began to train as an astronaut, she wrote,
she could see the horizons expand for her female students. Little
did she know she was to be chosen as a similar role model.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here she was a history teacher, and she was going to make
history,'' Corrigan said. ``Because Christa was not an astronaut _
she was somebody's teacher, somebody's neighbor, somebody's friend
_ then we could go there too.''
</P>
<P>
   While some skeptics in the media assumed McAuliffe was looking
to capitalize on her space journey to change careers, Corrigan said
her daughter always planned to return to Concord High.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe also had an independent streak, rejecting NASA's
insistence that the 20-minute lessons she was to give each day be
carefully scripted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christa wanted to do it her way,'' Corrigan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This dream did not die 73 seconds after liftoff,'' she said.
``She has given credibility to the idea that teachers are people
who make things happen. She gave her fellow professionals new
dignity and new honor.'' Today, there are 34 schools in the United
States named after her daughter _ and others in places like Peru
and Mexico. Scholarships are given out in her name to encourage
young people to become teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did Christa touch the heart of the nation? I hope so. And did
she inspire others? I hope so too,'' Corrigan said. ``I hope
Christa's spirit will inspire you in some small way too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
