<SLUG> BC-TRADES-ACCOUNTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCOUNTING HORRORS AWAIT SOME INVESTORS AT TAX DEADLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like a lot of people these days, William Brennan dived head
first into the stock market. The Harvard MBA student now has a
broker at Goldman Sachs, a family member who trades on his behalf,
and an on-line account, which he uses to buy and sell shares over
the Internet. In his quest for gold in the bull market, he's
conducted at least one transaction a day for the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   The payoff has been good, he says. His sizable portfolio has
become even more sizable in recent months, increasing nearly 40
percent since August. But he also got something a little less
desired: A record-keeping nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never ends,'' he says. ``It seems like every time I get
everything sorted out and ready that I've got to turn around and do
it all over again. It's very burdensome, all the paperwork.''
</P>
<P>
   With tax day looming, more and more do-it-yourself investors _
including legions of new on-line investors known as ``hyperactive
traders'' because they buy and sell so frequently _ are confronting
an accounting horror.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't even realize they have to keep track of
every single transaction,'' says Lewis Weinstein, founder and
president of TaxLogic, an on-line accounting service in Needham,
Mass. that has attracted Internet traders. ``If you didn't keep
track of everything you bought and sold, there could be a
significant difference in your tax liability.''
</P>
<P>
   Trouble arises for frequent investors because gains on stocks
held 12 months or less are taxed at the same rate as ordinary
income, which ranges from 15 percent to 39.6 percent. That's
typically a bigger tax hit than the maximum long-term capital-gains
rate of just 20 percent, says Shamus McBride, an accountant at
Arthur Andersen's private client services group in Boston. That
means some trades may be taxed at different rates than others.
</P>
<P>
   Making matters even more difficult, the 1099 forms brokerage
firms send investors and the Internal Revenue Service to report
interest, dividends, and trading revenue generally contain only
data on the sale of a stock, not the specific stock purchase prices
needed to figure the gain or loss on each trade, McBride says.
</P>
<P>
   Without records of each stock purchase and the corresponding
sales, investors could be taxed only on the gains made through
sales while not having the benefit of deducting the costs of buying
the stock in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose you buy 50 shares of stock in the morning at $100
apiece. Later, when the stock has gone up to $120, you buy 50 more
shares. Then you sell 75 of the shares when the stock has is going
for $200. What's your taxable gain?
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to match those lots all together,'' McBride says.
``Your tax bill can change a great deal depending on how you do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the larger on-line brokerages, such as E(asterisk)Trade
Group and Charles Schwab Corp., can automatically feed investors'
trading records into their home computers with personal accounting
software like Intuit's Quicken and Microsoft Corp.'s Money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for that, I'd be lost,'' says Brennan, the MBA
student, who said he downloads his Charles Schwab records with
Quicken. ``I don't have to enter any of the data. At the end of the
month, it's a dream. If I had to do it the traditional way, it
would be a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Brennan says he still has to devote at least half an
hour each day to bookkeeping in order to keep pace with investments
made through his Goldman Sachs broker and the family member who
invests on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm out of town for a few days, I fall way behind,'' he
says. ``I know that if I don't keep up, I'm going to pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Quicken added the stock data function about a year ago,
sales of the popular personal finance program have soared, said
Kevin Reeth, a product manager at Intuit, the Mountain View,
Calif., company that makes Quicken.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's now one of the most popular features,'' he says. ``It
goes right to the heart of why people are buying this program. For
most people, there's too much to keep track of by hand. With the
program, everything you need, including commissions, is taken into
account, and you just print it out on a capital gains report.''
</P>
<P>
   This year _ as the volume of stock trades ballooned to record
levels, especially among investors buying and selling at home with
personal computers _ investors have flocked to accountants seeking
help.
</P>
<P>
   At Weinstein's TaxLogic, business has more than doubled to more
than 1,000 clients nationwide, in some measure because on-line
investors spotted his Web site on the Internet, Weinstein said. His
customers submit their financial data to TaxLogic accountants via
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   While some have come to him well prepared, many haven't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get people who've been trading all year long without keeping
good records,'' he says. ``They'll tell me they have it all in a
statement, and I say, `Are you sure?' Often, they only have a
record of the sales.''
</P>
<P>
   In the cases where clients have detailed records _ either those
they've kept themselves or a statement that records all a
customer's transactions _ ``it makes my life and theirs very much
easier,'' he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
