<HEADER>
A4876 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-KELLEY-BOS &LR;      04-12 1408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-KELLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVID KELLEY: HIS PEN IS MIGHTIER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ In the past decade, no one has left a more
indelible signature on prime time than David E. Kelley, a onetime
Boston attorney turned prodigiously prolific writer-producer.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does Kelley show any signs of reducing a workload that still
makes jaws drop in the TV industry.
</P>
<P>
   With Kelley-created dramas already airing on three networks _
ABC's Emmy-winning ``The Practice,'' Fox's ``Ally McBeal,'' and
CBS's ``Chicago Hope'' _ he is now at work on yet another show,
``Snoops,'' a drama about high-tech detectives that is slated for
ABC this fall. Two weeks ago, ``Ally McBeal'' and ``The Practice''
earned 1998 Peabody Awards for broadcast and cable excellence.
</P>
<P>
   At age 42, Kelley deadpans that he is ``older than most of the
network presidents now.'' Indeed, while he looks more like a
self-effacing English teacher than a TV heavyweight who's married
to actress Michelle Pfeiffer, there's no mistaking Kelley's
gray-eminence standing. Even this season's hottest new
writer-producer, Aaron Sorkin of ``Sports Night,'' says he comes up
short when measured against Kelley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond being one of the best writers in the country, David
Kelley clearly takes some kind of vitamin in the morning that
allows him to do four times as much work as I do,'' sighed Sorkin
during an interview on the set of his show.
</P>
<P>
   ``My show is a half-hour, but he writes two one-hour shows a
week, these two great shows,'' Sorkin added. ``Honestly, how does
he do it?''
</P>
<P>
   Don't ask Camryn Manheim. Even though the actress won an Emmy
last year for speaking his words every week on ``The Practice,''
she has not come close to figuring out Kelley.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, he's like an idiot savant,'' mused Manheim. ``I
don't know if he could do anything else. It's like, can you
understand how someone can drop a box of toothpicks and count how
many there are? You can't. You'll never understand that. Well,
that's like David Kelley.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a bunch of words all over the floor, and before you
know it, there's just a script. He's just phenomenal that way. I
can't figure it out. It hurts my brain when I try and figure out
how he does what he does. I have read a lot of movies-of-the-week,
for possible hiatus work, and a lot of them were legal dramas. But
it's ridiculous to even consider doing another legal drama when you
have David Kelley writing for you every week.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Remaining an enigma &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The man on the receiving end of these accolades is a courteous
but enigmatic figure who clearly does not want his life to be an
open book. Despite his marriage to a famous movie star, Kelley has
tried to draw a curtain of privacy around their lives together, and
his friends do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he learned the virtues of reticence here in New England.
Born in Maine, Kelley attended the Belmont Hill School in Belmont,
then went on to Princeton University, where he was captain of the
hockey team (he still finds time to play hockey once a week).
</P>
<P>
   Upon graduation in 1979, he came back to Boston and earned a law
degree from Boston University Law School in 1983. Kelley began
practicing law in Boston _ an experience that would later find its
way into ``The Practice'' _ but found civil litigation
unsatisfying. More satisfying by far was writing a movie script
about an unconventional young attorney during his spare time.
</P>
<P>
   The script, which eventually became the movie ``From the Hip''
with Judd Nelson, brought Kelley to the attention of Steven Bochco,
executive producer of ``L.A. Law.'' Bochco was looking for lawyers
to bring some real-life legal experience to the show. Kelley
quickly became the show's head writer, and his knack for witty
dialogue and over-the-top storylines (remember Rosalind Shays
stepping into the empty elevator shaft?) spread his renown in
Hollywood. Before long, he got the itch to create his own show, so
he left ``L.A. Law'' to make ``Picket Fences.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry Hamlin, a star of ``L.A. Law'' who left the show in 1991,
says the show wasn't the same without Kelley. ``I left `L.A. Law'
for one reason, and that was because David Kelley was leaving,''
Hamlin said during an interview at a party held by the WB network.
``I said `If you find someone as good as David Kelley, I'll stay.'
They couldn't, because there isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is equally high on Kelley, however. Some critics
have lambasted the perpetually unglued lead character on ``Ally
McBeal'' as an antifeminist throwback, while others have questioned
Kelley's practice of having characters from ``Ally'' show up on
``The Practice'' and vice versa. During the February sweeps, two
dubious plot twists raised eyebrows and hackles: the rekindling of
the played-out Ally-Billy relationship on ``Ally McBeal,'' and the
physical brawl between Lindsey and Elinor on ``The Practice.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A prolific pen &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the overall quality of Kelley's scripts is remarkable,
especially when one considers the quantity. From his prolific pen
(literally; Kelley writes in longhand) have flowed hundreds of
scripts since he left the practice of law behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Picket Fences,'' which Kelley created in 1992 and for which he
wrote most of the scripts, won two Emmys for outstanding drama. In
1994, with ``Picket Fences'' still running, he created and wrote
the medical drama ``Chicago Hope.'' That meant Kelley was writing a
full season's worth of episodes for two shows simultaneously.
``That was a struggle, doing those two at the same time,'' said
Kelley. ``That was pretty grueling.''
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't stop him from placing himself in the same
situation two years ago, when he created two shows set in Boston,
``Ally McBeal'' and ``The Practice.'' Even though he was also
writing scripts for movies like ``To Gillian on Her 37th
Birthday,'' he promptly set about writing virtually every one of
the scripts for both of his new shows. In a business where writing
half a dozen scripts a year is considered prolific, Kelley was
writing 22 episodes per show per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really hasn't been too difficult,'' insisted Kelley. ``For
whatever reason, writing these two shows works for me. I think it's
because the worlds are so different. If I'm away for two or three
days to write one of them, by the time I come back to the other, it
feels like I've been away longer than I really have.''
</P>
<P>
   His insouciance notwithstanding, Kelley's output leaves other
writers shaking their heads, even Kelley's mentor, Bochco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am in awe of David Kelley, simply in awe of David Kelley,''
Bochco said in an interview here. ``He is an amazing guy. He's
unusually gifted, he has an extraordinary capacity to work, and an
amazing imagination. There will come a time, inevitably, when he
won't want to work the way he is working now. But all of us are
fortunate that there was a time in his life when he is willing and
able to work at this level.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Breech, co-executive producer of ``The Practice,''
describes Kelley's writing style as ``Mozartean,'' saying that the
first drafts of Kelley's scripts are often nearly flawless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always feel like Salieri, in the movie, going through a lot
of sheet music, with absolutely no interlude,'' said Breech. ``He's
just a marvel of talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Notoriously reluctant to surrender control of script-writing, a
tendency that reportedly frustrated staff writers on ``Picket
Fences'' and ``Chicago Hope,'' Kelley says he has started to
delegate more this season. But he still writes a lot of the
``Ally'' and ``Practice'' scripts, taking four or five days to
finish each script. And he admits that he can't refrain from
rewriting even those scripts he assigns, with plot outlines, to
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, I enjoy it,'' he said. ``A lot of writers say `I'm
going to features because I can take my time and not have to answer
to deadlines,' but I prefer the pace of television.''
</P>
<P>
   And television likes Kelley right back. The industry bible, TV
Guide, recently anointed Kelley _ after barely 15 years in the
business _ as one of the 45 figures in television history who
``made a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was very flattering, but you take it with a grain of
salt,'' said Kelley. ``When you have several shows on the air, that
counts for something; you stay in the mind-set. That same poll in
15 years might not include me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
