<HEADER>
A4879 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-COUNTRY-BOS &LR;      04-12 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-COUNTRY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARNING THE LAND OF THE `OLD OLD' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CLEA SIMON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
ANOTHER COUNTRY 
The Emotional Terrain of Our Elders 
By Mary Pipher 
Riverhead Books, 328 pp, $24.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mary Pipher could be a translator. The Nebraska-based
psychologist and author ventures into communities and then returns
to explain their truths and ways of being to the rest of us in
clear, clean English. Best known for her exploration of adolescence
in ``Reviving Ophelia,'' Pipher now takes on the world of the aging
in ``Another Country.''
</P>
<P>
   In what is basically a solid primer on generational relations,
Pipher explains that the very old are not like the rest of us.
Distinguishing the ``old old'' (primarily those over 80 and the
infirm) from the ``young old'' (active, healthy people who just
happen to be past retirement age), she tackles the world of these
``old old'' as she would a foreign culture, eager to decipher it
for the rest of us back in her homeland of vibrant, independent
adulthood. Even her approach is anthropological, a methodical
working out of the ways, means, and motives of these people at the
end of life, people who inhabit what is for many of us an exotic
world.
</P>
<P>
   In a readable fashion, she charts the differences categorically.
The language of the old, she says, is different from ours, and
their priorities have been abandoned, if not forgotten, by
mainstream society. For the generation now in its 80s, she says,
``depression'' will always be economic, whereas for her and her
readers it is emotional. Feelings, she claims, are best shown by
the old in actions, in gifts of food or labor, while younger people
want to talk about their inner workings and may interpret as
neglect actions that are accompanied by silence. In between her
analyses of these differences, Pipher provides illustrations:
recounting tale after tale in which an old person's values of
stoicism and perserverance are misinterpreted by a younger person
as denial and a younger person's expressivity is seen as rudeness
or weakness.
</P>
<P>
   Other passages lay out the author's process, venture into the
world of disability and lost loves, and finally make suggestions
for younger people looking to ease relations with the ``old old,''
offering a road map through what is clearly treacherous territory.
Through anecdotes and stories from her therapy practice as well as
plain advice, Pipher shows how miscommunications can be avoided and
needs translated. ``Flexibility works best,'' she advises, adding
that ``a well-timed chocolate cake or pot of chicken soup can
soothe many an aching heart. They could in 1904, and they can
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicken soup cannot solve all difficulties, of course, and
Pipher acknowledges the shifting terrain of aging and also the
necessary fluidity of parent-child (or grandparent-grandchild)
roles. She discusses how difficult it can be for aging parents and
adult children to accept these changes _ for a grown daughter, for
example, to tell her incontinent father, ``You've changed a lot of
my diapers. Now it's my turn.'' And in between some truly
heart-rending stories, she outlines ways for such painful
conversations to begin with dignity and love.
</P>
<P>
   This is worthy work and undoubtedly needed. However, in her
plainspoken way, Pipher treads fearfully close to condescension.
Saying ``generally, the old like physical and verbal affection'' is
akin to saying ``generally, living creatures like to eat when they
are hungry.'' Even more troubling are two underlying assumptions
that flavor the book. The first is that its readers (whom she
presumes will be younger people) will have to do all the
translating. This may often be true, but assuming that the very old
are incapable of learning new ways of communicating plays into one
trap about which she repeatedly warns her readers. She is treating
the elderly like children and cutting them off from paths of
learning and intellectual growth.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, ``Another Country'' is saturated with a kind of
nostalgia that is odd for a psychologist, a somewhat rose-colored
vision of an era she calls ``pre-psychology.'' Pipher seems to be
aware of this bias and repeatedly states her opposition to it. ``I
don't want to eulogize or romanticize the past,'' she writes.
``Real abuse _ sexual, physical, and psychological _ occurred then
as it does now. Denial can keep serious problems from being
solved.'' However, for each bald assertion, she piles on several
heart-tugging stories that seem to show the older generation's way
as better.
</P>
<P>
   Pipher's work is well documented, and her advice seems sound.
And she is probably right when she points out that we have become
more isolated than previous generations have been from our elders.
But in subtle ways, she is undercutting the progress she herself
has been able to profit by. After all, we are able to acknowledge
such problems because of the ways in which our culture has changed.
``Another Country'' reads as if its author was ashamed of change,
not seeking to heal its abrasions. And readers, if not the author,
should be reminded that these new ways of communicating, including
the breakdown of traditional taboos, are what make possible a book
that might help bridge what has been an inevitable gap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
