<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4884 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TIPS-BOS &LR;      04-12 0241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TIPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A Prayer for the Dying'' by Stewart O'Nan (Holt, $22).
Highbrow terror: a spare, ominous fictional portrait of a small
Wisconsin town struck by diphtheria in the years after the Civil
War. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Morgan: American Financier'' by Jean Strouse (Random House,
$34.95). A thoroughly documented, consciously nonpartisan biography
of that colossus of capitalism J. P. Morgan. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Woman: An Intimate Geography'' by Natalie Angier (Peter
Davison/Houghton Mifflin, $25). Learned and witty, exhilarating and
subversive, this ``working map'' dismantles our received wisdom
about how the female body works and what it means. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Little Green Men'' by Christopher Buckley (Random House,
$24.95). A zany sendup of the national fascination with UFOs, this
novel also satirizes the mix of paranoia and influence-peddling
that makes the nation's capital go. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Martin Luther: The Christian Between God and Faith'' by
Richard Marius (Belknap/Harvard, $35). The tormented and tumultuous
life of the great reformer. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Single &AMP; Single'' by John le Carre (Scribner, $26). Drugs,
family, and business collide in the latest by the British dean of
foreign intrigue. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Dreamland'' by Kevin Baker (HarperCollins, $26). A fictional
wild ride through the New York of the turn of the century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 1415EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
