<DOCNO> NYT19990412.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4892 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEACE-STUDIES-HNS &LR;      04-12 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEACE-STUDIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITIES GIVE PEACE STUDIES A CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN WECHSLER  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLONIE, N.Y. _ It's not necessary to get arrested while
studying peace. But it helps.
</P>
<P>
   Peace studies, at least on the college level, is not just
talking about the lack of war. It involves challenges like dealing
with the poor or the homeless, or taking a stand for something you
believe in, baring your soul in front of class. Or getting arrested
during a protest.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes students just find out something about themselves they
never knew.
</P>
<P>
   Today, peace studies programs flourish on 250 campuses
nationwide, including Notre Dame, Syracuse and Colgate. There are
another 250 programs worldwide. And as conflicts like Kosovo
continue to rage, there is never a lack of issues to talk about.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the second day of a peace conference at Siena College
in Loudonville, N.Y., topics ranged from managing emotion to
avoiding racial conflict, to using tourism and the Internet to make
peace. More than 200 students and professors came from around the
country to take part in the conference, put on simultaneously by
both the Peace Studies Association and the Consortium on Peace
Research.
</P>
<P>
   Studying peace is by no means a new idea. As an academic
subject, its roots go back to the post-World War II era. But its
modern practitioners earned their olive branches protesting the war
in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Is it a legitimate course of study? Not everyone agrees.
Jonathan Melle, a 23-year-old graduate student who took peace
studies while attending Siena a few years ago, says he's heard all
sorts of disparaging remarks from professors at the University of
Massachusetts, where he's working for a graduate degree in public
administration.
</P>
<P>
   You can't teach peace, a professor told him. ``Some people laugh
at it,'' he said. ``I've taken courses where people call this
basically silly.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who teach peace, there is no line between the
classroom and the real world. For instance, Tony Bing, founder of
the Peace Studies Association, traveled to Iraq in 1990 in an
effort to convince the government to cease the aggression that was
leading it toward the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   While there, Bing, a Quaker who teaches at Earlham College in
Indiana, says he offered himself as a hostage in exchange for other
hostages being held there.
</P>
<P>
   Ned McGlynn, a Siena professor who heads the peace studies
program there, said he'll back up his beliefs with his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're faced with the problem, `Kill or be killed,'
frankly, I'd rather be dead,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Students of peace do not need to make such fatalistic
commitments, although one professor said he encouraged his students
to use civil disobedience as a form of protest.Others are
encouraged just to open their minds and face their fears. Student
seminar participants have been to Northern Ireland, the Balkans and
refugee camps in Africa to study or volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   Melle, the graduate student, once did a project on homelessness.
He spent the afternoon at a soup kitchen, but never was able to get
the nerve up to actually talk to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why can't I talk to a homeless person?'' he asked. ``That's a
question I still ask myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 1422EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
