u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      04-12 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, April 13:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 3 pages of stories, photos and graphics
on the continuing crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ Developments on Kosovo: NATO foreign
ministers meet on Kosovo. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.N. (United Nations) _ Secretary-General Kofi Annan
offers to meet with Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav president, if
that will help. By Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TRAIN (Grdelica, Yugoslavia) _ NATO hits a Yugoslav
passenger train. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Dateline to kum, Macedonia) _ Five more
busloads of refugees arrive from Kosovo; what they have to say. By
David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Barksdale, La.) _ President Clinton is visiting
military base in Louisiana and then returns to Washington to meet
with congressional leaders over Kosovo at 5 p.m. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GERMANY (Berlin) _ German Chancellor Schroeder wins broad
support from his party for his stand on bombing Yugoslavia after he
rejects calls by left-wingers for a stop to NATO's air assault. By
Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BIN-LADEN (Washington) _ In their self-declared war with Osama
bin Laden, the man charged with blowing up two U.S. embassies in
Africa eight months ago, American officials portray him as the
world's most dangerous terrorist. But The New York Times, working
in cooperation with the PBS program Frontline, has found him to be
less a commander of terrorists than an inspiration for them.
Enemies and supporters alike say he may not be as globally powerful
as some American officials have publicly asserted. But his message
and aims have more resonance among Muslims around the world than
has been understood. By Tim Weiner. (2150 words)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S. (Chicago) _ Chinese officials are confident that
their tour of the U.S. with Zhu Rongji, the prime minister, is
going well; but underlying that is a sense of frustration that
relations could be better. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Top Energy Department intelligence
officials star in open hearings this afternoon on allegations of
Chinese espionage before Senate Armed Services Committee. By James
Risen.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NUKELAB (Los Alamos, N.M.) _ The Senate Intelligence
Committee will hold a news conference at 4 p.m. EDT, following a
tour of the laboratory. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ Russian lawmakers postpone their
debate on impeaching President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MCDOUGAL-TRIAL (Little Rock, Ark.) _ A jury has found Susan
McDougal innocent of obstruction of justice and the U.S. district
court judge declared a mistrial on two contempt counts. She was
accused of obstructing the Whitewater investigation of Kenneth
Starr, the independent counsel. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   PULITIZER-PRIZES (New York) _ The 1999 Pulitizer Prizes are to
be announced in mid-afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   With grpahic.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA-POLLEN (Atlanta) _ The pollen count, ususally hitting a
high of 150, has reached 6000 here and all of Atlanta is sneezing.
By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   VA-POLITICS (Washington) _ A former governor of Virginia, George
Allen, is expected to announce that he will challenge Charles Robb
for his Senate seat, giving Robb his first viable challenger in
years. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   NM-TORTURE (Albuquerque, N.M.) _ An update on Elephant Butte sex
torture case: There has an arrest in the case of a missing woman
which the FBI says is connected to charges of kidnapping and sexual
abuse lodged earlier against a man and a woman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TAXES (Washington) _ President and Mrs. Clinton are to
release their tax return. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Compaq's earnings warning on Friday,
released after the close, drags down computer shares but the market
comes back from its lowest levels of the morning. At midday, the
industrial average was slightly up, while the Nasdaq index was down
19 points, or 0.7 percent. Compaq fell as much as 22 percent.
Elsewhere, prices declined 2.1 percent in Tokyo and 1.4 percent in
Hong Kong. They rose 0.7 percent in Frankfurt but fell half a
percent in London. Shares were off 2.4 percent in Brazil and 0.4
percent in Mexico. On the American debt market, the long bond was
up 10/32 point. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   NEWPORT-NEWS (Undated) _ Folo reports that the Pentagon,
concerned about the continuing consolidation of the defense
industry, is expected to block General Dynamics' $1.4 billion bid
for Newport News Shipbuilding. The latter's stock is down 10
percent. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN-IPO (New York) _ Two developments: Goldman raises the
price of its planned stock offering to between $45 and $55 a share
from between $40 and $50 a share, and it names two outside
directors: Sir John Browne, chief executive of BP Amoco, and James
Johnson, chairman of Fannie Mae. And, as expected, it will invest
$500 million in South Korea's Kookmin Bank. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ECON (Shanghai) _ China reports that its exports fell 7.9
percent in the first quarter. By Seth Faison.
