<P>
   THE CONFLICT IN KOSOVO
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-AID _ WASHINGTON _ With several thousand Kosovar
Albanians homeless and still in the Serbian province of Kosovo, the
United States and NATO allies are struggling with how to get aid to
them. (Montgomery, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES _ BLACE, Macedonia _ A week ago it was a
torrent, now the flow of refugees from Kosovo is a trickle.
Hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanians still in Kosovo have fled
on foot into the rugged mountains to evade Serbian shock troops and
make their way across the border to safety. NATO, which is
considering food-aid drops over
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo, says 400,000 or more displaced residents of Kosovo could
be hiding in remote villages or living rough in the wilderness. A
group of 300 refugees who made their way across the Blace border
crossing Monday recounted alarming experiences of surviving Serb
sieges, only to cope with shortages of food and freezing rain in
the woods. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton meets with
congressional leaders as Congress decides what to do about the U.S.
role in the Kosovo fighting. Some members are pressing for ground
troops, while others want to pull out. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MONITORS _ SKOPJE, Macedonia _ Among the suffering of
Kosovo's ethnic Albanians, the swiftest and most brutal punch by
Serb forces may have been delivered to some of the 1,400 local
employees who had been hired by the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe to monitor compliance with the peace accord
there. Of them, only one has been confirmed dead at the hands of
the Serbs, and some have been identified among the refugees that
streamed out of Kosovo to safety. But many more are presumed to
have been tortured or killed or both, said OSCE officials. (Holmes,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BLACKCOLLEGE-REUNION _ Did the Daytona experience provide any
lessons for Atlanta police, government officals, merchants and
residents. (Suggs, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   BURT'S-RANCH _ JUPITER, Fla. _ There's a buyer for actor Burt
Reynolds' ranch near Jupiter, a lawyer for the creditors in his
bankruptcy said Monday. (Kleinberg, Palm Beach Post). WITH MAP.
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-CLINTON _ BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Hillary Clinton visits Boca
Tuesday to raise money for U.S. Rep. Bob Wexler, perhaps the most
outspoken supporter of the president during his impeachment and
trial. She's stopping at the Jewish Community Center before a
$1,000 a plate dinner at the Boca Raton Hotel &AMP; Club. (Crowley,
Palm Beach Post). 10-12.
</P>
<P>
   INDIANS-CASINOS _ TALLAHASSEE _ Florida Attorney General Bob
Butterworth is expected to file a lawsuit in response to new rules
by the U.S. Interior Department that would allow Seminole and
Miccosukee Indian tribes to open casinos in Florida. (Date, Palm
Beach Post).
</P>
