<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MEANING IN KOSOVO OF `PERSIST AND PREVAIL'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The front-page headline of Friday's newspaper said: ``Belgrade
declares war over.''
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade is the capital of Yugoslavia, of course, which makes it
a headline synonym for Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. This
particular headline referred to an official statement issued by
Milosevic's Serbian government _ a statement claiming that peace
had broken out between the Serbs and ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Since the warring parties were now ready to live in ``harmony
and cooperation,'' the statement suggested, the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization had no further pretext for attempting to bomb
Yugoslavia back to the Stone Age.
</P>
<P>
   Or words to that effect.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately _ or unfortunately, depending on your point of view
_ the war between Yugoslavia and NATO is not Milosevic's to end. He
certainly has it in his power to declare victory in his campaign of
ethnic cleansing, and if he wants to, he can stop torching villages
in Kosovo. But the only way he can stop the air assault against his
country is to accept NATO's terms; he has demonstrated no
inclination to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's declaration of peace was obviously a propaganda
gambit designed to foster the illusion that he's a reasonable guy
who hasn't done a darn thing to deserve the destruction that NATO
is inflicting. Anyone who takes his declaration seriously is hereby
invited to buy some of those bridges that NATO has been blowing up
in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton was having none of it, dismissing Milosevic's
announcement of a unilateral cease-fire as ``not even partial
compliance, but the illusion of partial compliance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO is determined to persist and prevail,'' Clinton vowed.
</P>
<P>
   He keeps saying that. But before the American people can decide
how far they are willing to follow Clinton into the potential
quagmire of Yugoslavia, they need the answer to a crucial question:
What is the president's definition of ``persist and prevail''?
</P>
<P>
   We are talking about a commander in chief, don't forget, who is
capable of disputing what the meaning of ``is'' is. We're talking
about a man who sees a significant distinction between
``misleading'' and ``lying.''
</P>
<P>
   So when he says that the United States and its NATO allies will
``persist and prevail,'' does he mean that the bombing will
continue until all of Yugoslavia is a pile of rubble and Milosevic
is dead or under arrest as a war criminal?
</P>
<P>
   Or does Clinton's definition of ``persist and prevail'' run more
in the direction of achieving some compromise agreement under which
NATO agrees to stop the bombing and Milosevic promises to stop
eradicating Albanians?
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton is leaning toward the latter, his persistence is
somewhat academic, seeing as how Milosevic responded to the bombing
by killing or displacing most of the folks the bombing was supposed
to protect.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about your Pyrrhic victory.
</P>
<P>
   When the airstrikes began last month, the stated objectives were
to stop ethnic cleansing of ethnic Albanians and to force Milosevic
to allow deployment of 28,000 NATO peacekeepers in Kosovo. Lately,
though, Clinton has been saying that NATO's primary objective is to
make sure that exiled residents can return to the ethnically
cleansed region and resume their lives without further threat of
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the objective can be achieved only by the indefinite
occupation of Yugoslavia by foreign soldiers, including Americans.
The plan currently on the table calls for 4,000 U.S. troops to
participate in a post-bombing peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   This military undertaking may be the perfect example of a
lose-lose situation. If Clinton fails to meet his objectives, the
world's lone remaining superpower will have suffered a horrendous
loss of credibility. If he succeeds, the United States will have
won the privilege of establishing a military presence of indefinite
duration in a part of the world where peace has been the exception
and war has been the rule for hundreds of years.
</P>
<P>
   The whole deal is just a terrible idea.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
