<HEADER>
A4948 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALDERSCULPTURE-TEX     04-12 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALDERSCULPTURE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORT WORTH LANDMARK TAKES FLIGHT: CALDER'S `EAGLE' SOLD, CARTED
OFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LAURA VOZZELLA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ ``The Eagle'' has flown the coop.
</P>
<P>
   A 40-foot-tall orange steel sculpture by Alexander Calder that
loomed outside a downtown Fort Worth bank tower for a
quarter-century abruptly took flight on Sunday for parts unknown.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas company that bought the sculpture along with the Bank
One tower last fall said it sold the abstract artwork to finance
building improvements _ including the installation of fire
sprinklers, which the 36-story building lacks.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Cherry, president of Dalcan Investments, declined to
disclose the buyer or the purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   ``Transferring the value of that sculpture to the building will
benefit the tenants and ultimately the downtown area,'' Cherry
said.
</P>
<P>
   Horsefeathers, cried a ruffled arts community, which had
persuaded a previous owner to call off a contemplated sale of ``The
Eagle'' in early 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a desecration of the physical environment of Fort
Worth,'' said Ted Pillsbury, former director of the Kimbell Art
Museum, who lives in a downtown loft near the sculpture's former
roost. ``I think this is a terrible blow to all of us who are
committed to the revival of downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   The orange giant had straddled the northwest corner of Fifth and
Throckmorton streets since 1974, when Fort Worth National Bank
opened the building. It was valued at the time at $144,000.
</P>
<P>
   Installed two years before Calder died, the piece is one of his
last important works. Also known for witty mobiles, Calder
reportedly considered ``The Eagle'' to be one of his major
``stabiles,'' a term the Philadelphia native coined for his
nonmoving sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years after its installation, the sculpture was valued at
$1 million to $2 million. Bank One, which owned the tower and the
artwork at the time, considered selling the sculpture, but backed
down after local art lovers cried foul.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, there was no notice of the sale. Building
tenants had been polled about the potential removal, but they were
not notified that it would take place, said Bill Lawrence, a public
relations specialist hired by Dalcan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of floored,'' said Ronald Watson, chairman of the art
department at Texas Christian University, who has been involved in
the field of public art.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence said there was no intention to keep the removal a
secret. It took place on a Sunday, he said, because street and
sidewalk traffic would be at a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's broad daylight,'' Lawrence said. ``It's not like we came
in at midnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Cherry said that Dalcan is sensitive to the city's artistic
interests and that it may install another sculpture on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not our intention to leave that corner vacant,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As curious passers-by looked on, the artwork came down in about
nine hours Sunday. Workers unbolted the 16-ton sculpture to divide
it into six huge parts, the last of which had to be jackhammered
out of the sidewalk. Two cranes hoisted the parts onto a couple of
flatbed trucks, which took the sculpture to an undisclosed location
for restoration, Lawrence said.
</P>
<P>
   Calder was the first 20th-century American sculptor to win
international acclaim. His brightly painted sculptures grace public
plazas in major cities throughout the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Yet plunking one of his orange abstractions in downtown Fort
Worth was considered a bold stroke in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every 100 years or so a bank should do something a little
flamboyant,'' the Fort Worth National Bank chairman, Lewis H. Bond,
said at the dedication.
</P>
<P>
   Flamboyant or not, the sculpture became a landmark in a city
where cowboys and culture rub elbows.
</P>
<P>
   ``For any of those who walk by the John Portman (designed)
building in July, when there's nothing but glare and heat off of
this black building, at least they had the pleasant relief of this
organic shape,'' Pillsbury said. ``It animated an otherwise rather
desolate public space, playing off the minimal design of the
building.''
</P>
<P>
   Karla Sanchez Zapeda, a graduate art history student at TCU who
recently researched Calder, said she has spent hours admiring the
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the sun, it looked really great there and it made a great
contrast with the surface of the building,'' she said. ``Steel vs.
glass.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is sorry to see it go, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought it was terrible, myself,'' said Gavin
Garrett, 80, a rancher raised in Fort Worth. He watched the removal
from across the street with his wife, Bonilee, who considers
herself a bit of a Calder fan and was disappointed to see it
removed.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they liked the sculpture or not, downtown office workers
got a jolt when they took in the landscape on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Sculptures that are part of the public landscape, that people
can walk up to and under, come to be seen as ``more or less in the
public domain,'' said Mark Thistlethwaite, a TCU art history
professor who teaches a seminar on public sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   Often, of course, they are private property.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get reminded of it,'' he said, ``when something like this
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
