<HEADER>
A4983 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDRA-MCDONALD-IN-HAV     04-12 1488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDRA-MCDONALD-IN-HAVING-OUR-SAY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 AUDRA McDONALD IS HAVING HER SAY  
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Audra McDonald with Lisa Arrindell
Anderson in a scene from ``Having Our Say.'' 
 By MICHAEL J. BANDLER  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Call Audra McDonald the entertainment industry's stealth weapon.
 &HT;    The most celebrated musical-theater actress of her generation _
at 28, she already has three Tony Awards _ she's also won a growing
number of fans as a recording artist. But despite the hurrahs of
those who saw her on Broadway last year in ``Ragtime,'' she's still
an unfamiliar name to audiences outside New York.
 &HT;    For now, anyway. Her breakthrough just might be the television
movie ``Having Our Say,'' which will air April 18 on CBS. Adapted
from Emily Mann's acclaimed stage play _ based on the 1993
bestseller of the same name _ ``Having Our Say'' is the true story
of more than 100 years of African-American history as seen through
the eyes of two sisters, Sarah ``Sadie'' and A. Elizabeth
``Bessie'' Delany.
 &HT;    They saw black America from the Jim Crow era through the 1990s,
and from Raleigh, N.C. _ where the sisters were born as the
children of an Episcopal bishop _ to 1910s New York, where they
attended Columbia University and went on to careers of their own,
Sadie as a schoolteacher and Bessie as a dentist. Bessie Delany
died in 1995 at 104, her sister in 1999 at 109.
 &HT;    McDonald plays the feisty Bessie during her prime, with Lisa
Arrindell Anderson playing Sadie. Ruby Dee and Diahann Carroll play
the sisters as old women.
 &HT;    The first time she read the Delanys' memoir, the actress says,
her first reaction was, ``I have nothing to complain about _
absolutely nothing! And shame on me if I do. Because I have 95
billion percent more chance of getting anywhere I want to be than
these women did and, in my opinion, they far surpassed anything
I've already done _ especially considering the odds they had to
work against.''
 &HT;    The sisters have something important to say to black Americans,
she adds.
 &HT;    ``There's a lot of bitterness and anger within certain aspects
of the black community today that's residual from years past,'' she
says. ``The Delany sisters talk a lot about how you can't hold
bitterness in your heart _ it will ruin your life.''
 &HT;    McDonald grew up in a family not unlike the Delanys, with roots
in rural Virginia and a bedrock commitment to education as the road
to success.
 &HT;    ``Some of the things their father was telling them I have heard
firsthand from my parents, obviously parroting things they heard
from their parents,'' she says. ``They talked about the importance
of a college education, because no matter what happens in your
life, no one can ever take that away from you. You've got that
paper.
 &HT;    ``When I graduated from Juilliard and came home to Fresno,'' she
recalls, ``the first thing my dad said when I got off the plane
was, `Where's the diploma?' That was most important _ a real tool,
a weapon, to use in society for fighting racism.''
 &HT;    The actress comes from a musical family in which, as she puts
it, ``everybody's made some sort of noise with some sort of
instrument or with their throat.'' Her father was a college music
major, her mother was a piano teacher with a master's degree in
music and her aunts and mother even formed a gospel group, the
McDonald Sisters, some years back.
 &HT;    Young Audra, who had been performing in community theater since
she was 9, burst onto the Broadway scene in 1994, fresh out of
Manhattan's Juilliard School. As Carrie Pipperidge in the Lincoln
Center revival of ``Carousel,'' she won her first Tony Award. The
next year she won another for her bristling performance in ``The
Master Class,'' as a budding opera singer being coached by Zoe
Caldwell's Maria Callas. She won her third in 1998 for her
performance as the tragic Sarah in ``Ragtime.''
 &HT;    Her characters are typically passionate women who teeter on the
edge between achievement and disaster. It's an edge which McDonald
knows well since her Juilliard days.
 &HT;    At the prestigious performing-arts school, the singing program
traditionally inclines toward opera. Though blessed with an
awesomely rich operatic voice, McDonald was already enthralled by
the Broadway stage. She spent her first few months at Juilliard
fighting what she calls ``the operatic thing.'' That struggle,
combined with a couple of personal relationships that ``spiraled
downward,'' resulted in a brief breakdown, what she calls a
``mental vacation.''
 &HT;    Fellow students, her parents and therapy helped McDonald through
her crisis, reinforcing her faith in her own sense of her destiny.
Once secure in that, McDonald says, she decided that Juilliard
``should become my friend.''
 &HT;    The rest, as they say, is history.
 &HT;    That experience helped her re-enact a crucial juncture in Bessie
Delany's life. In 1913, en route to a teaching position in Georgia,
she and two other black teachers from New York were sitting in the
``colored'' waiting room of a train station in Waycross, Ga., when
a drunken white man approached and began harassing them.
 &HT;    As he screamed invectives, Bessie's colleagues fled, and a crowd
began to form on the platform. But she continued to sit on the
bench, combing her hair until the train finally came to whisk her
away.
 &HT;    ``I think that's when she realizes how special she is,'' the
actress says, ``that she can take care of herself and is worthy of
that which she seeks and that which she stands for. That's when she
finally cuts her teeth as Bessie.
 &HT;    ``Till her dying day, she was still riled up about that,''
McDonald adds. ``She'd say, `You know, I don't take tea for fever,'
which I take to mean, `Nothing's going to calm me down. If I'm this
angry about something, nothing will be a salve for me. Once I'm
angry, I'm gone!'''
 &HT;    ``Having Our Say'' was McDonald's first experience acting for a
camera instead of an audience, and she admits that she found it
awkward at first.
 &HT;    ``I would much rather get up in front of 100,000 people I don't
know and sing and dance,'' she says. ``For a while, I was very
afraid of the camera. I was like, `Get that thing away from me! Why
is it looking at me?'
 &HT;    ``But then Lynne Littman, the director, told me, `It's like a
member of the audience, and you can't hide from it.' Once she made
that correlation I started to calm down, and it made all the
difference in the world.''
 &HT;    Don't look for McDonald to go Hollywood, though. This summer
she'll be back on the concert stage, appearing at the Tanglewood
Music Festival and elsewhere on tour. She'll also be singing on
film, appearing briefly in Tim Robbins' 1930s political drama,
``Cradle Will Rock,'' as a composer's muse. And toward the end of
the year she'll be starring in Michael John LaChiusa's new musical,
``Marie Christine,'' to be staged at Lincoln Center.
 &HT;    It's no accident that McDonald's next Broadway musical, like her
last, is an original work. She's a great supporter of the new
generation of musical-theater creators, excited by her conviction
that ``dramatic intent is now driving the compositional piece _
lines are being erased, borders are being erased.''
 &HT;    She admits that her advocacy is at root ``a selfish thing. I
want new and exciting projects out there for me, as well as for
everyone else. So it's an investment in my future as well as
theirs, as well as in the future of musical theater.''
 &HT;    Still, she says, she welcomes film and television opportunities
such as ``Having Our Say,'' chances to expose herself to new ideas
and new audiences.
 &HT;    ``It's good to challenge yourself,'' she says. ``As Bessie and
Sadie certainly would say, `Don't be afraid of anything new!'''
 c.1999 Michael J. Bandler  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Michael J. Bandler is a Silver Spring, Md.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
