<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4985 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JENNIFER-JASON-LEIGH-     04-12 1482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JENNIFER-JASON-LEIGH-IN-EXISTENZ-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXISTENZIALIST: JENNIFER JASON LEIGH TAKES ANOTHER WALK ON THE WILD
SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Jennifer Jason Leigh with Jude Law in a
scene from ``Existenz.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Jennifer Jason Leigh has spent the last decade or two playing
square pegs in round holes.
 &HT;    Her latest film, ``Existenz,'' casts her as another misfit, a
superstar virtual-reality-game designer on the lam after an
assassination attempt. It's not hard to see in the awkward,
antisocial Allegra Geller something of Leigh herself, a private and
enigmatic actress who has been called a reluctant star.
 &HT;    The comparisons are not lost on Leigh.
 &HT;    ``I liked seeing a bit of myself in Allegra,'' she says. ``I
liked the idea of playing someone who's very shy and uncomfortable
with people _ I certainly understood that.
 &HT;    ``Allegra is really, really uncomfortable with people,'' Leigh
adds. ```The hell with people' is her motto. It's something I've
sort of said for years, too, but Allegra practically wears it.
 &HT;    ``It's almost pathological how shy she is,'' she says, ``which
is partly because of the work she does. She doesn't have to deal
with people. It's only in the game-testing phase that she has to
face the press, and it's very painful for her.
 &HT;    ``And you know what? It is for me, too. I'm not comfortable. I
love to work, but I don't like to talk about my work or myself that
much, and it doesn't come easy to me.''
 &HT;    Leigh, the 37-year-old daughter of writer/producer Barbara
Turner and the late actor Vic Morrow, laughs.
 &HT;    ``I'm not quite as shy as Allegra,'' she says, ``but I'm
close.''
 &HT;    Written and directed by David Cronenberg, ``Existenz'' _ or, as
the promotions would have it, ``eXistenZ'' _ opens on April 23.
It's a futuristic drama that finds Geller in hiding, accompanied
only by unarmed security guard Ted Pikul (Jude Law), as she tries
to sort out the complications of her new game, eXistenZ, which
thrusts them _ and moviegoers _ into a bizarre universe that blurs
the lines between fantasy and reality.
 &HT;    ``For me, the film is about the desire to escape,'' Leigh says
by telephone from her home in Los Angeles. ``It's very funny and
it's also an existential film, in that you create your reality
moment by moment.
 &HT;    ``I love that the film works on so many levels,'' she says.
``Even playing the scenes, from take to take, there were different
choices to make all the time.
 &HT;    ``It was challenging and exciting to keep track of the levels,
but I wouldn't say it was hard,'' she concludes. ``Jude and I would
just look at each other and say, `Let's do it this way or that
way.'''
 &HT;    Working with Cronenberg was a unique experience, the actress
says.
 &HT;    ``We weren't allowed to change the dialogue, but we could
interpret it any old way,'' she says. ``He enjoys that. David is
lovely to work with, incredibly intelligent, very easygoing and
funny.''
 &HT;    Actors who work with Cronenberg tend to come away saying that
it's hard to believe that so normal a guy could have directed such
out-there brainbenders as ``Scanners'' (1981), ``Videodrome''
(1982), ``Dead Ringers'' (1988) and ``Crash'' (1997).
 &HT;    ``That's true, but it's often the case,'' Leigh says, laughing.
``A lot of directors you meet, who are the healthiest people, make
the strangest films.
 &HT;    ``The reverse is probably true, too,'' she adds, ``but I haven't
worked with a lot of those directors in my career!''
 &HT;    Which isn't hard to believe. Leigh is the actor equivalent of
Cronenberg, a veteran who does her own thing, generally outside the
mainstream. Her credits include ``Fast Times at Ridgemont High''
(1982), ``Last Exit to Brooklyn'' (1989), ``Backdraft'' (1991),
``Single White Female'' (1992), ``Short Cuts'' (1993), ``Dolores
Claiborne'' (1995), ``Georgia'' (1995) and ``Washington Square''
(1997).
 &HT;    There are few box-office smashes and barely a normal character
in the bunch, and Leigh wouldn't have it any other way.
 &HT;    ``If I can keep working without doing too much in the mainstream
that would be great,'' Leigh says. ``Luckily, I've been able to
earn my living doing the films I like, and I haven't had to do
mainstream films too often.
 &HT;    ``You really don't pick what's going to be commercial and what's
not,'' she adds. ``Nobody ever knows that. Honestly, I don't think
you can know that.
 &HT;    ``A lot of films people think will be hugely commercial bomb,''
Leigh says, ``and sometimes a movie that wasn't intended to be a
huge commercial thing hits for some reason. If people had a formula
that really worked, they'd use it more often.''
 &HT;    As for her own movies, she denies any interest in the commercial
end of her work.
 &HT;    ``A lot of the big commercial hits I don't like,'' she says. ``I
liked `Single White Female,' but didn't go into it thinking or
knowing it would be a commercial success.''
 &HT;    Fair enough, but Leigh had to know that its chances for a
lucrative box-office run far exceeded those of, say, ``Georgia,''
which she co-produced.
 &HT;    ``Maybe I did, but that's not why I choose my roles,'' she says.
```Single White Female' did have a better chance _ but, again, that
didn't mean it would be successful.
 &HT;    ``From my point of view, just because they put millions and
millions of dollars into advertising doesn't mean the movies will
make a lot of money,'' Leigh says. ``I'd rather do the films I
like.''
 &HT;    Which means joining forces with directors as willing to take
risks as she. Leigh has worked with most of today's most critically
acclaimed mavericks, including Cronenberg, Robert Altman, the Coen
brothers and Stanley Kubrick.
 &HT;    ``They're all hugely talented and they make their own movies,''
Leigh says. ``They don't make movies by committee. That's what
they've got in common.
 &HT;    ``Their movies set them apart,'' she says. ``Their visions,
ideas and stories set them apart. They're very different
filmmakers, but they're all really fantastic.''
 &HT;    If a Kubrick film featuring Leigh doesn't spring instantly to
mind, there's a reason. Leigh's scenes in Kubrick's swan song,
``Eyes Wide Shut,'' were cut after the actress couldn't return to
the set in London for additional filming.
 &HT;    ``He was brilliant, a total mensch,'' she says. ``I don't know
if he was as obsessive as everybody says he was. I didn't find him
obsessive in a horrible way _ I just found him to be incredibly
detailed and lovely.''
 &HT;    Never one to duck a challenge, Leigh recently took to the stage
in the Broadway revival of the musical ``Cabaret.'' She spent
several months starring as Sally Bowles in the production, to
reviews that generally praised her acting and panned her singing.
 &HT;    ``It was so much fun to do,'' she says. ``The cast was amazing,
and it was an incredible show to go into. Everybody was very
welcoming to me.
 &HT;    ``How fun it was to sing and dance on Broadway. It was insane.''
 &HT;    Speaking of insane, Leigh's next project, ``Beautiful View,''
casts her as a chambermaid obsessed with a guest at the hotel where
she's employed. The film will be directed by her mother, who penned
the script for Leigh.
 &HT;    As the interview comes to an end, Leigh contemplates what she
knows now about her craft that she didn't nearly 20 years ago, when
she made her acting debut in the television movie, ``The Best
Little Girl in the World'' (1981).
 &HT;    ``I think you learn from everyone you meet and everything you
do,'' she says. ``You learn something from every life experience.
Hopefully, you just get deeper and better.
 &HT;    ``I guess I just know more now,'' she says. ``I'm older. I've
lived more. I don't know that I've changed my approach, though, or
that I ever will.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
