<HEADER>
A5006 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AGING-BOOMERS-HNS &LR;      04-12 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGING-BOOMERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABY BOOMERS: WITHER OR NOT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH SHERMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I just received another offer for a newsletter
on aging. It promises that if (and only if) I subscribe, I will
look better, feel better, enjoy life more and generally be the
terrific person they think I should be.
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with who I am now? Apparently, everything.
</P>
<P>
   Today, if you're not worried about being thin, keeping in shape,
removing wrinkles and eating phytofoods, you're obviously not a
human living on this planet.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the Y2K problem _ we're talking real life here. As a
member of the Baby Boomer generation, I am well aware that it is
easier to find products and businesses devoted to de-aging than it
is to locate a reliable neighborhood shoe repair shop. Or
drugstore. Or bookstore. Or bakery.
</P>
<P>
   Every time some local mom and pop store has the rent raised and
is pushed out of business, you can be sure what will come in will
be some ``shoppe'' devoted to herbals, nail care, beauty products,
exercise equipment or tummy tucks.
</P>
<P>
   Every clothing catalog features wildly make-upped, pre-pubescent
female persons frolicking around in what are purported to be
``women's'' sizes.
</P>
<P>
   Every product (whether cosmetics or bathroom detergents) is
promoted showing young, long-haired women in short skirts lazily
smiling as they ardently fondle a bottle or canister, exuding a
message directly for you: ``You would be young, you would be
beautiful, you would be sexy if only you'd use Blabbo Toiletbowl
Cleaner like I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Look around and see how many spokespeople on TV have a few gray
hairs or a few extra pounds. On the surface, it seems like we're
becoming a nation of perpetual children.
</P>
<P>
   At playground soccer games, take a look at the moms and dads.
</P>
<P>
   They're wearing the same clothes as their kids, jumping up and
down like maniacs, just like their kids, trying to live the same
life as their kids.
</P>
<P>
   Their days are crammed full of a wide assortment of activities
and playdates. At night they must be out at the latest movie or
antioxidant lecture to make sure they're up on what's really going
on.
</P>
<P>
   Admitting to being tired is never permitted. It's synonymous
with being over the hill. Plastic surgery has never been more
popular. At parties people make parlor games out of guessing who
had what done.
</P>
<P>
   Surgeons now ``sign'' their work with a characteristic upturned
nose or jowl (``Why, I see you have the Greenberg Jaw. How
delightful!'')
</P>
<P>
   Taking a quick look around in a crowd, you would swear there was
no one over 30 still in existence. A woman I know, with a daughter
in her early 20s, delights in people telling her how much she and
her girl look like sisters.
</P>
<P>
   If someone says she looks like her daughter's mother, she makes
a rude remark or tries to smack them in the face. So what ever
happened to sweetly smiling gray-haired ladies, like those in other
cultures, who are beloved and deeply revered for their years of
experience and wisdom?
</P>
<P>
   Do they still exist? Or do we have to rent films from the '30s
and '40s, featuring frankly ``old'' female stars like Jane Darwell,
Margaret Rutherford or Beulah Bondi to understand what it was like
to enjoy living in your own (untucked) skin? I realize that I'm
beginning to sound like a curmudgeon here.
</P>
<P>
   But, I consider it practice for how I'll be, I hope, in about 30
years. Meanwhile, I have seven vitamins I have to take before my
power walk. Or maybe I'll just take a nap.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Examiner contributor Ruth Sherman is a San Francisco writer and
filmmaker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
