<HEADER>
A5016 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-SABBATHDAY2-BOS &LR;      04-12 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SABBATHDAY2-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STUDY IN SCARLET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE SABBATHDAY RIVER 
By Jean Hanff Korelitz 
Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. 499 pp. $25. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most conventions of popular fiction play to our fantasies while
sheltering our unconscious assumptions: The courtroom thriller uses
a mahogany-trimmed sanctuary in which to unearth its ghastly
crimes; the contemporary romance novel, nodding to the realities of
broken families and transient love, nonetheless promises an inner
life, or at least a willing heart. The domestic drama, steeped as
it is in the comforts and confines of home, particularly relies
upon this covenant of wishful desire and grimmer truth _ insisting
that the hearth be warm and made of brick, even if it's being
smashed to smithereens.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Hanff Korelitz's yeasty drama has elements of each of these
genres, and it follows a recent spate of similar novels, among them
Jacquelyn Mitchard's ``The Deep End of the Ocean,'' Jane Hamilton's
``The Home at the End of the World,'' and Sue Miller's ``While I
Was Gone.'' What these works share is not just dark trouble wrapped
within the cloak of friends and family, but the narrative
perspective of an introspective female character. This viewpoint
bestows the story with a close-focus intimacy that can be both
revealing and claustrophobic. If we've witnessed by the end of the
novel the unraveling of a web of secrets, we also know how
everybody takes his or her coffee and, heaven help us, why.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, ``The Sabbathday River'' has received advance
notice as a ``feminine thriller,'' which is a terrible thing to
call a book, but will no doubt become the shorthand term to promote
it. The novel is actually a morality tale set in the twilight
ambience of small-town New Hampshire, with an adulterous young
woman named Heather Pratt at its center. Much like Hawthorne's
sacrificial Hester Prynne, Korelitz's character becomes a scapegoat
for the rages and fears of a tight-lipped (and tightly wrapped)
community. Most of the thematic parallels to ``The Scarlet Letter''
end there, though Heather's libidinous downfall is at the hands of
a sleazeball with a ponytail named Ashley Deacon. Not even Arthur
Dimmesdale, he.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sabbathday River'' opens in 1985 with the horrid discovery
of a dead infant outside Goddard, N.H., near the jogging path where
Naomi Roth runs. A 35-year-old transplanted New Yorker who has made
a grudging peace with Goddard in her nine years there, Naomi is the
alienated conscience of the novel _ the Jewish outsider whose
hilltop point of view delivers the intersecting stories of the
entire town. Having come to Goddard as a VISTA volunteer with her
piously radical husband, Naomi is now recently divorced and trying
to make her life work. She runs a local crafts cooperative,
Flourish, formed when she convinced the women of Goddard to market
their wares. In the year since her husband, Daniel, high-tailed it
to a commune in Woodstock, she has sheetrocked their A-frame and
made it a home instead of a political statement. And on that sunny
September morning that will change her life, she has found a baby,
lying like a broken doll in the Sabbathday River.
</P>
<P>
   When Naomi panics and takes the child's body to the sheriff's
office, she's initially treated with suspicion for having removed
the corpse from a crime scene. But within hours, the investigation
_ targeted to include any woman in Goddard considered deviant _
ends at the house of Heather Pratt, a sweet, insecure 20-year-old
who lives with her 14-month-old daughter, Polly. Heather has turned
out to be the embarrassment of the town: Dropping out of Dartmouth
after only a few weeks, she returned to Goddard a couple of years
ago and took up publicly with Ashley Deacon, a married handyman who
lists his virility as one of his many skills. Undaunted by the fact
of his pregnant wife, Heather spent several blissful months
steaming up the rear windows of Ashley's car; her own pregnancy,
with Polly, was blindly joyful, and she couldn't understand, or
didn't care, why the townfolk treated her with such disdain. That
scorn was minor compared with Ashley's inevitable rejection, after
which she retreated to her life with Polly and the samplers she
embroiders for Naomi's craft business.
</P>
<P>
   Or did, until this day of the Sabbathday River discovery, when
Heather is ripped away from her daughter and subjected to a
grueling, probably illegal interrogation. Sick with worry and
fatigue, she confesses _ or admits, at least, that she had a
stillborn baby a few days ago, which in her distress and confusion
she left in a pond at the bottom of her property. So we now have
one alleged murderess and possibly two dead infants, as well as a
zealous prosecutor, a bevy of competing medical experts, and an
entire town on the warpath. Not to mention the potential for
several subplots: Caring for Polly while Heather is in jail, Naomi
has to wrestle with her misplaced maternal longings. Judith
Friedman, another displaced New Yorker whom Naomi has just
befriended, is the new public defender in charge of Heather's case
_ when she's not disappearing into mysterious troubles out of town.
And several locals, from the sanctimonious to the scurrilous, have
their own inscrutable agendas; by the end of the trial, which is
woven through the last half of the novel, all of them will have had
their day in court.
</P>
<P>
   Haunting in its painful rendition of the worst kind of death,
purplish in its swollen recitation of Heather's unbridled
sexuality, ``The Sabbathday River'' continually lurches between
melodrama and the tragedy at its center. It has the riveting
components of a good courtroom drama, enhanced by some finely
etched characters (with his nonchalant narcissism, Ashley is
splendidly awful). But some of the moral points of the novel _ that
sensuality is condemned, even criminalized, for instance _ are
driven home with the delicacy of a nail gun. We are afforded very
few gray areas: Most of the residents of Goddard are conservative,
hypocritical, and Christian; their challengers are Jewish, liberal,
and fast-talking urban. Naomi's briefly reappearing ex-husband,
whose name-dropping leftism does, granted, beg caricature, is
nonetheless no greater than the sum of his own cliches. These
stereotypes obscure their characters rather than illuminating them,
and thereby diminish the complexity of sorrow at the novel's core.
</P>
<P>
   Which is, from beginning to end, the retelling of a very old
story: one about the love between parent and child, the sacrifices
made either against or in the name of God, the quest for faith in
an uncertain world. If these themes are articulated unevenly in
``The Sabbathday River,'' Korelitz has managed to make their final
resolution commendably shadowy. There are no victors at the end of
Heather Pratt's trial by fire, unless wisdom itself gets to take a
bow. There is instead the infinite memory of that bright September
day, when ``all the worst things,'' as Naomi remembers, lie
revealed in morning sun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
