<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHATEVER HAPPENED TO SUMMER VACATION? 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ This really isn't the time to be thinking about
August. Spring break was just a few weeks ago, and most school kids
haven't even taken this year's TAAS tests yet.
</P>
<P>
   But next year's school calendar for the Austin Independent
School District is already out, and there it is, as big as life and
very aggravating, an Aug. 11 start date for the ``fall'' semester.
</P>
<P>
   AISD isn't alone. Most districts across the state apparently now
start classes in mid- or early August _ at the hottest time of the
year in Texas and during weeks that many Texas families once
considered prime vacation time.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there ought to be a law against the continued erosion of
summer, but there won't be. Not during this legislative session,
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   For the second session in a row, Sen. Eddie Lucio Jr.,
D-Brownsville, has been thwarted in his efforts to require school
districts to return to what used to be considered tradition and
wait until Sept. 1 or later to start school.
</P>
<P>
   Lucio, however, is optimistic that this year he can at least
force an objective, in-depth look at the issue. His amended bill,
to require a study by the state education commissioner, has won
easy Senate approval, and Lucio predicted it will be endorsed by
the House as well.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, Senate Bill 40, would require the commissioner to
study the effects of a post-Sept. 1 start date on ``students,
parents, school personnel, school districts, local economies and
the state economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner would have to report his findings to the
Legislature early in the 2001 session.
</P>
<P>
   School districts started moving up their start dates several
years ago, partly because of additional teaching days ordered by
the Legislature to help strengthen the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   AISD spokesman Andy Welch said another reason is to complete the
first semester before the Christmas holidays. Scheduling, he said,
also is complicated by the need to set aside days for teacher
preparation and development and bad-weather contingencies.
</P>
<P>
   AISD provides 175 teaching days a year, five fewer than the 180
required by the state. The district obtained a waiver to allow it
to provide more days for staff development and parent-teacher
conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Classes will end this spring on May 25.
</P>
<P>
   Welch said the Austin district hasn't been bombarded with
complaints from parents. He believes most families are adjusting to
school in August.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas State Teachers Association officially backs Lucio's
efforts, but spokeswoman Annette Cootes said individual teachers
have different opinions about when the school year should start.
</P>
<P>
   The tourism division of the Texas Department of Economic
Development already has conducted a study of the early school start
and, not surprisingly, has concluded that it has hurt the Texas
tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
   Lucio's South Texas district, which includes the South Padre
Island playground, is heavily dependent on tourism. And the senator
acknowledged that tourism was one reason he wanted to keep schools
closed until after Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where the whole issue started last session. It was
considered a greedy bill,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, tourism businesspeople aren't the only ones
losing money when school bells start ringing in August. So are
thousands of Texas schoolchildren _ many from low-income families _
who have summer jobs at tourist facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Lucio said he also was concerned about the effects of the early
class start on the children of migrant workers. He said about
200,000 of those children, many of them in his district, attend
public schools in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   They have a high dropout rate, partly because many aren't able
to start school until late September, after they finish helping
their parents in the fields, and quickly fall behind their
classmates.
</P>
<P>
   Their plight is only worsened when classes start in August.
</P>
<P>
   These are among the concerns that the state education
commissioner should address if Lucio's bill passes. Other issues
include the extra cost to taxpayers of cooling school buildings at
the hottest time of the year, the effect on students of riding on
unairconditioned school buses in August and the effects of the
summer ``dog days'' on a child's ability to learn.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner also could take a look at the length of
schools' Christmas holidays and spring breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Many school board members and school superintendents may argue
that any attempt by the state to change their scheduling would
violate ``local control'' over the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   But local control may be a false issue here. If the state can
tell school districts how many days they must teach, which it
already does, it also can tell districts when to start teaching.
</P>
<P>
   Clay Robison is chief of the Houston Chronicle's Austin Bureau. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
