<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, April 13:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EVERGLADES (Undated) _ The Everglades are in serious
decline. Slow-flowing fresh water in some places amounts to half
what it was a century ago. Populations of wading birds are down
some 90 percent. The cause: people have siphoned off too much of
the natural flow of water that once stretched in a continuous sheet
from Lake Okeechobee to Florida Bay. Now, in the nation's most
ambitious attempt at ecological restoration, the Federal and state
governments are about to try to put things right. The idea is to
spend some $8 billion over the next 20 years to re-plumb the
Everglades' water system so that natural conditions can be
re-established or at least mimicked. By William K. Stevens. (3100
words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PHANTOM-SMELL (Undated) _ Phantom senses _ as in feeling
pain in a limb that is not there or a taste that deviates vastly
from the norm _ have traditionally been regarded as annoying side
effects of injuries or dismissed as neurotic symptoms. In recent
years, however, a surge of scientific interest in the mechanisms of
human taste and olfaction has focused new attention on the ways in
which these senses can become disordered, and phantom sensations
are receiving greater scrutiny. A study of 100 cases of taste
phantoms will be presented soon at a meeting of chemoreception
sciences. By Erica Goode. (1700 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STAR-TAIL Astronomers at the University of California at
Berkeley said they were completely surprised when they detected the
spiral pattern of the dust streaming 18 billion miles out from the
star Wolf-Rayet 104. The star is one of a class of extremely hot,
massive stars many times larger than the Sun. The astronomers
hypothesize that the tail was produced by two stars, which are
engaged in a courtly dance around each other. These orbital motions
make the stars behave like a lawn sprinkler. By John Noble Wilford.
(675 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MOLECULES-CANCER (Undated) _ The sophisticated techniques of
a burgeoning field called molecular pathology are suggesting that
cancer comes in countless variations, each with a genetically
determined molecular fingerprint that indicates how deadly or
indolent it is likely to be and how aggressively it should be
treated. Dr. Carlos Cordon-Cardo, director of the division of
molecular pathology at Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in
New York, is a leader among researchers hoping to use molecular
pathology to transform the treatment of many cancers, increasing
patients' chances of cure in some cases and avoiding unnecessary
treatment in others. By Jane E. Brody. (2000 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LAUNDRY-ENZYME (Undated) _ Laboratory scientists are
tackling the rigors of the domestic battlefield knows as the
washing machine. The goal is to eliminate a common laundry-day
disaster, when a washerful of white clothes is forever tinted by
one colored item that, like a rogue agent, has infiltrated the
load. By Henry Fountain. (740 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Short items on science: using DNA to
conduct electricity, sponge breeding and the way changes in water
temperature may affect sea stars and the local ecology where they
are found. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SERVIING-SIZE (Undated) _ Graphic and photos explaining
serving sizes. By Jane. E. Brody.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ More and more businesses and
organizations are recognizing the value of portable defibrillators,
which weigh about four to seven pounds and are computerized to be
easy enough for a child to learn to operate. By Jane E. Brody.
(1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EPISODIC-HYPERTENSION (Undated) _ A doctor in New York has
found an apparent cause and treatment for episodic hypertension,
irregularly occurring bouts of dangerously high blood pressure
leaving people dizzy and dangerously ill. He has linked the
condition to previously suppressed childhood traumas and is
prescribing antidepressants. By Holcomb B. Noble. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FITNESS-FLOW (Undated) _ What athletes call the zone,
psychologists know by the less flashy name ``flow.'' Either way,
this intensely pleasurable, almost mystical, experience may be the
key to helping those who loathe physical activity learn to enjoy
it, believe a group of researchers in North America and Australia.
(700 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ Shorts on health and fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ Health clubs are installing consoles onto step machines and
stationary bikes to allow users to surf the Internet, watch their
own cable televisions, listen to CD's and call up past workout
records. (390 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   _ Working wives over 45 who have pensions are more likely to be
separated from their husbands than married women of the same age
who are employed but do not have pensions, according to a
University of Michigan report. (320 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science questions answered: Why bird
droppings are white. (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   Photos, where indicated, are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphics, to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (212) 556-4204.
