</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Electrifying DNA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DNA is a building block of life, but it might also some day be a
building block of minuscule electronic devices. That is the
tantalizing possibility raised by new research that shows that DNA
conducts electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Previous experiments to determine conductivity have involved
doping the DNA with electron donor and acceptor molecules, and have
been inconclusive. The new work, reported in the journal Nature by
physicists at the University of Basel in Switzerland, is in some
ways simpler. It tests DNA as any substance would be tested for
conductivity, by applying an electrical potential across it and
seeing how much current flows.
</P>
<P>
   With a few strands of DNA, a tiny fraction of an inch long,
however, applying a voltage is not a simple task. The physicists
used a special device known as a low-energy electron point source
microscope that creates a spherical wave of electrons. The
microscope is outfitted with a tiny tungsten tip that is used to
contact the DNA ``wires'' at specific points and apply the
potential to them.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that while DNA will never be a substitute for
copper wire, it does conduct electricity about as efficiently as a
good semiconductor. This property, combined with the fact that it
is now routinely possible to make DNA chains of specific lengths,
makes DNA potentially suitable for constructing submicroscopic, or
``mesoscopic,'' devices.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sponges On the Move &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Sponges do not get around much. Once they form an attachment _
to a stone, shell or other object on the sea floor _ they are stuck
for life. So how do they colonize new areas? Two researchers in
Spain, writing in the journal Nature, have suggested one mechanism.
Like Patsy Cline, brooding sponges may sometimes fall to pieces.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists studied a sponge, Scopalina lophyropoda, that is
found in the western Mediterranean. It reproduces by incubating
embryos that become larvae, which disperse only over short
distances. The researchers found that embryos thrived even after
the sponge was shredded into bits as small as one-twentieth of an
inch across.
</P>
<P>
   Depending upon how far along the reproductive cycle the
shredding occurred, several things happened. In some cases, larvae
were released directly from the loose bits. In others, the pieces
reorganized as sponges, creating an atrium-like chamber where the
embryos continued to incubate.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers suggest that shredding by wave action during a
sponge's reproductive cycle helps its offspring reach new areas.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sluggish Sea Stars &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Sea stars are more mobile than sponges, though even with five or
more legs they will never win a footrace. And a slight decrease in
water temperature, a researcher has found, can turn a slow-moving
sea star into a total slug. This in turn may have profound effects
on the local ecology.
</P>
<P>
   The researcher, from Oregon State University, studied Pisaster
ochraceus, a sea star found on the Oregon coast. Pisaster is what
is known as a keystone predator, an enforcer of affirmative action
in a tidal pool. It feeds on several varieties of mussels, keeping
their populations down and allowing a diverse collection of
organisms to thrive. If Pisaster stops feeding, disaster strikes:
the mussels take over completely.
</P>
<P>
   Pisaster feeding drops drastically, the researcher found, when
water temperatures decrease by 5 to 9 degrees Fahrenheit and many
of the sea stars become inactive. Such drops in water temperature
often occur temporarily along the Oregon coast as ocean currents
cause deep, cold water to well up to the surface during spring and
summer.
</P>
<P>
   The researcher, writing in a recent issue of the journal
Science, noted that during El Nino years, the upwelling water is
warmer. That, plus more systematic changes in water temperature,
could alter the delicate ecological balance between the sea star
and the mussel in a tidal pool.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
