<HEADER>
A5038 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RPT-KLEINBERG-COLUMN1     04-12 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RPT-KLEINBERG-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    REPEATING TO CORRECT NAME OF BOOK IN LAST GRAF
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Needed: One more volume from an aging Marine
 &HT;    For release Wednesday, April 14, 1999.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When last we left Winston Churchill, in the late spring and
early summer of 1940, he had just assumed the role of Prime
Minister of Great Britain, the Germans were racing through Holland
and Belgium, France was being humiliated in the field and Adolf
Hitler's bombers were lambasting England.
</P>
<P>
   So, what happened after that?
</P>
<P>
   It has been 11 years since Volume 2 of William Manchester's
exceptional biography of the British wartime leader was published
and those of us anxious to read the continuation are parched.
</P>
<P>
   This is particularly noteworthy now as some end-of-the-century
retrospectives refer to Churchill as the greatest person of these
past 100 years. Add to that the release this month of a book of
letters Churchill wrote to his wife, ``Winston and Clementine: The
Personal Letters of the Churchills'', and Churchill aficionados are
stirred, now more anxious for Volume 3.
</P>
<P>
   For the longest time, I have been trying to find out where
Manchester is in Volume 3 but neither his publisher, Little, Brown
&AMP; Company, nor Manchester himself is responsive to my queries,
other than to say he's working on the book.
</P>
<P>
   Manchester's first of ``The Last Lion'' series, based on
Churchill's early years (1874-1932) was published in 1984. Five
years later, the second installment was released, bringing
Churchill up to the late spring of 1940.
</P>
<P>
   It was at the conclusion of that volume that Churchill's
predilection to greatness began to emerge. Several days after he
replaced Neville Chamberlain as prime minister, Churchill addressed
the British public via radio. It was during that June 19, 1940
broadcast that Churchill spoke some of the stirring words for which
he is so fondly remembered:
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us therefore brace ourselves to our duties, and so bear
ourselves that if the British Empire and its Commonwealth last for
a thousand years, Men will still say: 'This was their finest hour.'
``
</P>
<P>
   It may have been Manchester's finest hour as well. The writing
(and research) of his first two volumes were outstanding. His
perspective was exceptional, such as this sentence just after the
French sued for peace with the Nazis while the British dug in their
claws.
</P>
<P>
   ``The British were prepared to sacrifice London house by house,
to be destroyed rather than be dishonored. The French loved honor,
but loved Paris more, as they would demonstrate before summer
arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   A newspaper writer joined a group of Manchester's former World
War II Marine Corps buddies at the author's Connecticut home last
October. They reminisced about their days fighting the Japanese on
Guadalcanal and Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manchester is down,'' Paul Reid of the Palm Beach Post
observed of the 77-year-old author. ``He's thin as a nail and just
as tough, but still a little bent at the waist and low in the
shoulder, as if one blow too many fell his way.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, he's aging _ as do us all, but we all didn't go
through the South Pacific with a rifle and bayonet; guys who did
can age quicker.
</P>
<P>
   Letters to Manchester about where he is on Volume 3 go
unanswered, someone at Little, Brown responds to my queries with
the stock answer that Manchester is working on the book and to stay
tuned to future announcements. But none have come since I began
inquiring about the status of Volume 3 last August.
</P>
<P>
   After his October session with Manchester, reporter Reid
commented that Manchester has ``a couple of hundred pages done and
a mountain of notes to collate.''
</P>
<P>
   There are some of us who wonder if Volume 3 of ``The Last Lion''
ever will be completed by Manchester, and it will be a pity if it
isn't. No one can match the perception and ability of Manchester's
writings. We found that out similarly when successors tried to
complete Ernest Hemingway manuscripts. They just weren't Hemingway.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Manchester doesn't feel he owes the world anything; but,
we do _ at least one more volume about that man Churchill.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
