<DOCNO> NYT19990412.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5039 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-STAR-TAIL-NYT &LR;      04-12 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-STAR-TAIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG HIDDEN, STELLAR PINWHEEL EMERGES FROM THE DUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the spiral shapes in nature, like water going down the
bathtub drain, shells like the nautilus or galaxies like the Milky
Way, the long, curving dust tail of two stars was a new sight to
test the explanatory powers of astronomers.
</P>
<P>
   It looked as if a cosmic skywriter had left a fat, upside-down
comma hanging out there in the direction of the constellation
Sagittarius.
</P>
<P>
   In observations by the Keck telescope in Hawaii, astronomers at
the University of California at Berkeley said they were completely
surprised when they detected the spiral pattern of the dust
streaming 18 billion miles out from the star Wolf-Rayet 104.
</P>
<P>
   The star is one of a class of extremely hot, massive stars many
times larger than the Sun. They have a reputation of living fast
and dying young, and this one is probably nearing its explosive
end.
</P>
<P>
   The astronomers had never before been able to focus so finely on
such a distant but dust-obscured star. The spiral tail appeared in
observations of infrared wavelengths that penetrate the dust. The
astronomers compared the achievement to seeing details on the head
of a pin at a distance of two miles.
</P>
<P>
   In a report in the journal Nature last week, the astronomers
showed a picture and gave a likely explanation of the stellar
spiral. They hypothesized that the tail was produced by two stars,
WR 104 and a companion, which are engaged in a courtly dance around
one another.
</P>
<P>
   These orbital motions make the stars behave like a lawn
sprinkler. The stiff winds of gases blowing radially outward from
the stars cool to dust, and rotational motions spin the dust out in
spiral arcs.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter G. Tuthill, a member of the observing team, said that
a sequence of pictures taken over the course of several months last
year revealed motions in the dust plume. ``We saw that the spiral
had moved, had turned on its head,'' he said, ``but it was real.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William C. Danchi, leader of the team, said, ``This is the
first time anyone has gotten any detail of a dusty Wolf-Rayet
star.'' The other team member was John D. Monnier.
</P>
<P>
   Such hot stars, the astronomers explained, are typically three
times the size and 25 times as massive as the Sun. They are
bursting with energy, expelling a high-velocity wind of stellar
gas. In fact, the star has blown off so much of its outer
atmosphere that not much more than its core is left.
</P>
<P>
   But the astronomers realized that the stellar wind, though it
had the necessary chemical ingredients, was so intense that it
should incinerate any dust as soon as it was produced. They
concluded that WR 104 must have another star, almost as massive,
lurking in its vicinity and with a powerful stellar wind of its
own. Both stars are hidden by surrounding dust.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the stellar wind from the companion meets the wind from
the Wolf-Rayet star, a shock front forms, which compresses and
cools the material from the stellar winds,'' Tuthill said. ``It is
in this `cocoon,' shielded from the direct glare of the stars, that
dust formation must flourish.''
</P>
<P>
   From the observations, the extent of the dust tail appears to
correspond to 200 times the distance of Earth from the Sun, or 18
billion miles. Without applying an advanced focusing technique in
infrared at the Keck Observatory, on Mauna Kea, the astronomers
would have seen only a stretched-out blurry patch of light.
</P>
<P>
   The time-lapse pictures showed how the spiral shape seemed to be
the consequence of the dust's being swept radially outward by the
wind from this rotating dust-formation zone. This is the classic
lawn sprinkler spiral, the scientists said, where water is always
flowing straight away from the center, but as the spigot rotates,
the water looks as if it is flowing in a spiral when seen from
above.
</P>
<P>
   As the scientists noted, the pictures are the first to show the
latest addition to the album of celestial phenomena: the spiral
pinwheel star.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 1553EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
