<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEET POTATOES TAKE LOTS OF ROOM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) Q. Will you please tell me how to plant sweet
potatoes? Do you plant the potato or the vines? When? _ P.S.,
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   A: Sweet potatoes are not difficult to grow and are high in
nutrients, but you do need space. Or try a compact variety such as
``Porto Rico'' or ``Vardaman'' in a huge container such as a
whiskey barrel.
</P>
<P>
   To have sweet potatoes for Thanksgiving, plant during the second
half of April or in May, when the soil temperature is about 80
degrees. Sweet potatoes need a long, warm growing season to be
harvested in fall.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the morning glory family, sweet potatoes are high in
vitamins, complex carbohydrates and fiber. Like the baked Irish
potato, a sweet potato can be a meal in itself. Lightly fried sweet
potatoes are delicious. And every family has a favorite casserole.
</P>
<P>
   With the proper start, sweet potatoes are a productive crop. One
gardener reported a yield of 300 pounds from a 5- by 40-foot raised
bed.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet potatoes are grown from slips, the shoots that emerge from
the tuber that are grown into plants. They can be ordered from
Gurney's Seed, 110 Capital St., Yankton, S.D. 57079.
</P>
<P>
   You also can grow your own slips:
</P>
<P>
   Plant the tubers on their sides in a flat filled with damp sand.
Cover the roots with 2 inches of sand. As the slips emerge, add
sand. Then gently pull when the shoots are 6 to 8 inches long.
Store at 80 degrees on top of the refrigerator until they are up,
then move to light.
</P>
<P>
   You can insert toothpicks into the tuber and suspend it
partially submerged in a glass of water in a bright spot. When
sprouts begin to grow from the top of the tuber, gently pull them
off and place them in a jar of water until they root.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet potatoes require a deep, sandy soil for best production.
Heavy soils can result in misshapen roots. Poor drainage makes the
plants vulnerable to insects and diseases. Use compost to enrich
the bed and improve drainage. Work in cottonseed meal, or composted
manure for nutrients.
</P>
<P>
   It's best to work the rows into ridges several inches high. Rows
should be about 3 feet apart. Plant the slips 12 to 18 inches apart
in the rows, and 2 to 3 inches deep.
</P>
<P>
   Once the slips are in the ground, water well until they're
established and the vines are starting to crawl. When growth is
good, skip the extra water and don't fertilize. The enriched soil
should supply needed nutrients. Too much water can cause the tubers
to become long and thin.
</P>
<P>
   The vines are so prolific they often shade the soil and prevent
weeds. If you have a good start and everything's going strong after
June, just wait until November, then harvest.
</P>
<P>
   Mulching a sweet potato bed will help prevent the vigorous vines
from rooting, which will create several small potatoes rather than
a few large ones.
</P>
<P>
   Gently dig out the sweet potatoes when morning temperatures drop
below 50 in the fall. Usually this occurs near Thanksgiving or at
least by early December. Sweet potatoes don't like the cold.
</P>
<P>
   The vegetables need to be cured once they're harvested. Remove
the vines, wash the tubers and let them dry in the sun. You can
place the sweet potatoes on newspaper in shaded boxes in a place
where temperatures are between 70 and 80 degrees. The top of the
refrigerator or a spot by the hot water heater should be fine. Do
not refrigerate the sweet potatoes or they'll rot. Store in this
warm spot until the potatoes harden, usually in just a few weeks,
then store them in a cooler spot where temperatures are 50 to 60
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beauregard,'' which has deep orange flesh,
light-purple/rose-colored skin and is wilt- and nematode-resistant,
has proved productive in southeast Texas. It eats up a lot of
space. This variety needs 90 to 100 days until harvest. Other sweet
potatoes to try in this area are ``Georgia Jet,'' a
deep-orange-fleshed sweet that produces in 90 days; ``Centennial,''
a deep orange; ``Jewell,'' a fine-textured orange that's resistant
to wilt and root-knot nematodes; ``Porto Rico,'' a deep orange
bush/vine; and ``Vardaman,'' a deep red-orange bush sweet potato
that requires a longer growing season.
</P>
<P>
   Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, garden editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents individual replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
