<HEADER>
A5048 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIGS-MEDITERRANEAN-LA     04-12 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIGS-MEDITERRANEAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON-AREA CHEF WRITES `FIGS TABLE' FOR HOME KITCHEN
</HEADLINE>
 (Runs with recipes slugged FIGS-RECIPES, FIGS-CHEF ) 
( For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Rustic, bold, inspired Mediterranean cuisine and
layered flavors soar from Todd English's kitchens and stoves,
whether at his Olives restaurants in Las Vegas or Charlestown,
Mass., or at his four Figs restaurants in the greater Boston area.
</P>
<P>
   ``The essence of Figs and Olives are the same,'' says English,
``but Figs is funkier, everyday food. It's simpler, more casual,
and more affordable than Olives.''
</P>
<P>
   If you've never had an opportunity to sample English's wonderful
cuisine, now you can whip up some of the dishes served in his Figs'
restaurants (along with some of the stuff he does at home) in your
own kitchen. There are more than 100 creations for pizzas,
risottos, pastas, salads and desserts to give you a sense of his
style in his latest and second cookbook, ``The Figs Table,'' (Simon
&AMP; Schuster; $25), co-authored with Sally Sampson. Unlike recipes in
some chefs' cookbooks, English's have been tested and adapted to
home kitchens by Sampson, several friends and a variety of cooks.
</P>
<P>
   Most recipes appear to be user-friendly, simple to prepare and
do-able for home cooks. For the most part, ingredient lists are
manageable, and preparation steps have been streamlined. Many of
the dishes sound so tempting they make you want to scurry into the
kitchen and get cooking as you're reading them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This volume is geared to 30-minute recipes or under, except
for the pizza, which takes longer,'' noted English, adding that
more people are now cooking pizza at home and want to do something
different.
</P>
<P>
   English makes interesting and innovative free-form thin-crusted
pizzas (so thin they are almost brittle) like you've probably never
tasted _ with toppings like littleneck clams; figs and prosciutto
(his Figs signature dish); fresh asparagus and mushroom puree;
kielbasa, sauerkraut, potatoes and Dijon mustard aioli; white bean
hummus and asiago cheese; and spicy shrimp, caramelized leeks and
tomato sauce. The only equipment needed, said English, is a strong
mind, a strong will, an unglazed stone and a wooden peel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The history of what I am about and what I've done can be found
in my first cookbook, `The Olives Table,' which came out a little
more than two years ago. There's a correlation between the two, but
`The Figs Table' is a simpler, easier, everyday, more homey
cookbook,'' noted English.
</P>
<P>
   He'll have succeeded in making this a working cookbook, he said
with a laugh, if cooks' copies have dog-eared and food-stained
pages.
</P>
<P>
   Passionate about his cooking, English boils his philosophy down
to taking common ingredients and doing unusual things with them. He
aims to give diners a choice of culinary fireworks on their plates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe cooking is about using all five of your senses _
sight (visual side), smell (best memory), feel in mouth (textural
difference), how it sounds (sizzle in pan) and, ultimately, taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taste is the most important to me. I never forget that food is
supposed to taste good. I think some of the ugliest food tastes the
best _ like braised greens cooked to death with ham hocks. Eaten
with bread with Parmesan cheese, you're, like, in heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   For his inspirations, English pulls from traditions, the
classics and his travels. ``I don't believe cuisines are 100
percent transferable _ basically meaning that you can bring the
influence but you can't bring the feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're eating spaghetti with clams on the Italian Riviera,
there's a certain air, scent, type of water and such that makes the
dish and meal. Eating the dish in Boston or Los Angeles isn't the
same. However, it's possible to do a dish similar in style and
serve it here, noted English.
</P>
<P>
   Presentation is also important, but English believes it should
not be too fussy and not overplayed. ``It should be very natural,
not contrived.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes ``The Figs Table'' sparkle and come alive are the
accompanying recipe notes, which give a range of preparation and
serving tips along with info about the origin of a recipe _ or
recipe expectations regarding flavor or color. They give you a
glimpse of the chef's personality and cooking style. For instance,
the Basil Aioli recipe notes, ``Don't be surprised when you end up
with yellow aioli; this will not be green.'' Accompanying the Figs
Pizza Dough recipe is this bit of information: ``Our dough is far
wetter than you'd ever believe; it makes a light, crisp crust.''
</P>
<P>
   English has his finger in many other pots besides his
restaurants these days. He's marketing a line of frozen pastas,
salad dressings, beers and mustards, which are currently sold in
Boston supermarkets. Plans are to roll them out nationally within
the next couple of years along with a line of frozen-food entrees.
As the host of a public television cooking show, ``Cooking In With
Todd English,'' he'll be filming the second series of 13 shows next
month. A dessert cookbook is also in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Now savor and share English's robust food with a sampling of
recipes from his cookbooks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
