<SLUG> BC-FIGS-ENGLISH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFILE OF TODD ENGLISH, AUTHOR OF `THE FIGS TABLE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TODD ENGLISH
</P>
<P>
   AGE: 38.
</P>
<P>
   PROFESSION: Chef/restaurateur.
</P>
<P>
   HOMETOWN: Amarillo, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD BACKGROUND: English grew up watching his mom, of Italian
descent and a great cook, and his grandmother prepare lots of
Italian dishes, including ravioli. When he was 9 years old, he
asked for a hand-crank ice cream machine _ and started making ice
cream for the family. He also grilled a lot and did other cooking
to help out in the absence of his father.
</P>
<P>
   During high school, he worked at both Mexican and French
restaurants in Branford, Conn. Then he spent a year working as a
line cook at a hotel in Atlanta and one summer worked at a seafood
restaurant on Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   He debated about going to the ``school of hard knocks'' or
getting formal culinary training. The Culinary Institute of America
in Hyde Park, N.Y., won out, and he graduated in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   After several years' experience out of school, he had his fill
of doing the ``Frenchy thing'' and wanted to get back to the
Italian-style cooking of his roots. He landed a job as the
executive chef at a new restaurant, Michela's, in Cambridge, Mass.
Before he took over, he traveled to Northern Italy and worked in
six different restaurants in six months. His wife, Olivia, who he
met at CIA (she was also a student there) handled the front of the
house at Michela's.
</P>
<P>
   The couple stayed there three years and then left to open their
own 45-seat restaurant _ Olives in Charlestown, Mass. _ in April
1989 _ serving English's interpretive Mediterranean cuisine. The
restaurant has since moved to a larger space and has consistently
been named Boston's favorite restaurant by the Zagat survey.
</P>
<P>
   Today English has eight restaurants, including two that recently
opened in Las Vegas _ Olives in the Bellagio hotel and Onda in the
Mirage _ and one in Westport, Conn., Miramar in the Inn at National
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   COOKING STYLE: Mediterranean-inspired cuisine with a strong
influence from ethnic or everyday food that is rooted in the
traditional cooking of the people.
</P>
<P>
   KITCHEN SECRET: He believes in chemistry on the plate _ and it
is best when it is layered and becomes a melange of flavors that
explodes in your mouth.
</P>
<P>
   MOST POPULAR DISH HE MAKES: Herb and butter-basted spit-roasted
chicken.
</P>
<P>
   THREE FAVORITE FOODS: Spaghetti with butter and Parmesan cheese;
a big, thick grilled sirloin steak; chocolate chip cookies.
</P>
<P>
   FAVORITE JUNK FOOD: Fritos.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD HE HATES: Dill.
</P>
<P>
   SECRET FOOD PASSION: Sushi.
</P>
<P>
   FAVORITE KITCHEN GADGET: Offset spatula (a narrow one).
</P>
<P>
   PET PEEVE: He can't stand dirty spoons on the line (used to
sauce and plate food) and dirty spoon water in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   FAVORITE COOKBOOK: ``Culture and Cuisine, A Journey Through the
History of Food'' by John Francoise Revel (a French book translated
into English; published by Doubleday in 1982).
</P>
<P>
   IDEAL VACATION: A place with a beach, plenty of golf, tennis and
activities _ and of course great food and wine at dinner.
</P>
<P>
   FAVORITE RESTAURANT: Marc Veyrat in Annecy, France.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT DOES HE DO WHEN NOT COOKING?: Plays a lot of sports.
</P>
<P>
   IF HE COULDN'T BE A CHEF, WHAT WOULD HE BE?: A baseball player,
or work in the creative end of advertising.
</P>
<P>
   DREAM JOB: ``I've got it.''
</P>
<P>
   WORST KITCHEN DISASTER: While preparing a special private dinner
for foreign dignitaries at a townhouse in Boston several years ago,
the fire-extinguishing system went off, and all the finished sauces
and food got dusted with white powder. Everything had to be thrown
out, and English had to run out and get other ingredients and food.
It took him about an hour to recover and remake the dinner.
</P>
<P>
   IF HE COULD DINE WITH ANYONE (CURRENT OR IN HISTORY), WHO WOULD
IT BE?: Thomas Jefferson, Auguste Escoffier and Courteney Cox.
</P>
<P>
   MOST MEMORABLE MEAL: Poulet bresse with 40 cloves of garlic at
Tante Paulette, a small restaurant in Lyon, France.
</P>
<P>
   THE WORST PART OF BEING A CHEF: He doesn't have much time to see
his three children, ages 9, 6 and 3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 1606EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990412.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5075 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIGS-RECIPES-2TAKES-L     04-12 1964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIGS-RECIPES-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECIPES FROM `FIGS' AND `OLIVES' 
</HEADLINE>
 (Runs with story slugged Figs-Mediterranean)  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROASTED CARROT AND FETA SALAD WITH ZA'ATAR &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; I first tried this style of salad on mezza tables in Israel and
now I can't get enough. You can also substitute almost any root
vegetable alone or in combination, including potatoes, parsnips,
sweet potatoes or beets.
</P>
<P>
   You can make this without the za'atar, but if you try it, you'll
be glad you did. Although za'atar means ``thyme'' in Arabic, when
used as a seasoning it usually refers to a mixture of sumac, dried
thyme, marjoram, salt and varying amounts of sesame seeds: The end
result is a bit sour and tangy. Brad Stevens, Figs executive chef,
prefers Jordanian za'atar for its lavish use of sesame seeds, but I
prefer Lebanese. Za'atar can be found in Middle Eastern and
specialty food stores.
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 pounds carrots, peeled, if desired, quartered lengthwise
and cut into angled 1-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup crumbled Bulgarian, French OR Greek feta cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon za'atar OR more to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped fresh parsley OR cilantro
</P>
<P>
   Place carrots, olive oil, salt and pepper on a baking sheet;
toss well. Roast in preheated 425-degree oven, shaking
occasionally, about 30 minutes, until just beginning to brown.
Carrots should be firm and not mushy. Transfer to a medium serving
bowl. Add remaining ingredients and toss well.
</P>
<P>
   Serve immediately or cover and refrigerate up to 4 hours. Makes
4 to 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   _ From ``The Figs Table'' by Todd English and Sally Sampson,
Simon &AMP; Schuster.
</P>
<P>
   QUICK WHITE BEAN HUMMUS
</P>
<P>
   I've replaced the traditional chickpeas with white beans to
create a lighter taste and texture. Use this as a dip for crudites
or crispy crackers or as a sandwich spread with smoked ham and
tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cooked white cannellini beans, rinsed and drained
</P>
<P>
   3 garlic cloves, crushed OR finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4 to 1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cumin OR more to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon Hungarian paprika
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   Place beans and garlic in a food processor fitted with a steel
blade and process until smooth. While machine is running, gradually
add remaining ingredients and process until smooth. Serve
immediately or cover and refrigerate up to 3 days. Makes about 1
1/4 cups.
</P>
<P>
   _ From ``The Figs Table'' by Todd English and Sally Sampson,
Simon &AMP; Schuster. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
FIGS PIZZA DOUGH &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; With a little bit of time and effort, Figs pizza dough can
easily be mastered. However, if you don't have the time or are
intimidated by working with yeast, call a local pizza place and see
if they'll sell you some of their dough. Also, some Italian delis
sell the dough. If you use a heavy, bready, prebaked, vacuum-packed
pizza crust, it just won't be the same.
</P>
<P>
   This dough is far wetter than you'd ever believe; it makes a
light crisp crust. It may take you a few tries before you get it
right. Be patient and err on the side of underworking the dough; if
you overwork it, the crust will be tough and dry.
</P>
<P>
   This recipe makes four rounds of pizza, though the topping
recipes make two pizzas. We figure that this way you only have to
make the dough every other time. Simply wrap the remaining two
balls of dough in plastic wrap and freeze, up to two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup whole-wheat flour
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 cups all-purpose flour, plus additional for rolling
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons (1/4 ounce) fresh yeast
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 2/3 cups lukewarm water &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Place whole-wheat flour, all-purpose flour, yeast, salt and
sugar in a mixer fitted with a dough hook. While mixer is running,
gradually add oil and water. Knead on low speed, about 10 minutes,
until dough is firm and smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Divide dough into 4 balls, about 7 1/2 ounces each. Line 2
baking sheets with parchment paper. Place 2 balls on a sheet and
cover with a damp towel. Let rise in a warm spot until doubled in
bulk, about 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   To roll out dough, dab your fingers in flour and then place 1
ball on a generously floured work surface and press down in center
with tips of your fingers, spreading dough with your hand. When
dough has doubled in width, use a floured rolling pin and roll out
until very thin, like flatbread. The outer border should be a
little thicker than inner circle. Pick dough up with a spatula or
back of a knife, allowing it to fold up almost like an umbrella and
transfer to a paddle. Do not worry that pizza is not round; you are
looking for an 8- to 10-inch shape, a cross between an oval and a
rectangle. If you get a hole, simply pinch edges back together.
Repeat with remaining balls and proceed with the following recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 (8- to 10-inch) pizza dough rounds. Each pizza will
serve 1 to 2 people. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; From ``The Figs Table'' by Todd English and Sally Sampson,
Simon &AMP; Schuster. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; FIG AND PROSCIUTTO PIZZA
</P>
<P>
   One of my favorites, this pizza is lush and intense, with the
sweetness of the Fig Jam contrasting with the salt of the
prosciutto and the tang of the Gorgonzola.
</P>
<P>
   You need to take a little extra care when assembling this pizza.
The Gorgonzola must go on in droplets rather than in big clumps and
the prosciutto must be paper thin so that it literally melts onto
the warm pizza.
</P>
<P>
   2 Figs Pizza Dough rounds (recipe above)
</P>
<P>
   Cornmeal for sprinkling
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 pinches kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   2 pinches black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped fresh rosemary
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Fig Jam (recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces Gorgonzola cheese, crumbled into pea-sized pieces
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces thinly sliced prosciutto
</P>
<P>
   1 green onion, thinly sliced lengthwise, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   One hour prior to cooking, place a baking stone in oven and
preheat to 500 degrees F.
</P>
<P>
   Roll out 1 pizza dough round as thinly as possible. Place on a
pizza peel sprinkled with cornmeal. Cover surface with 1 teaspoon
oil, 1/4 teaspoon minced garlic, 1 pinch EACH salt and pepper and
1/2 teaspoon chopped rosemary. Be sure to leave an outer lip of
1-inch all the way around.
</P>
<P>
   Evenly dot 1/4 cup Fig Jam and 2 ounces Gorgonzola cheese on
pizza. Top with 1/2 of prosciutto.
</P>
<P>
   Shake paddle lightly and slide pizza onto baking stone. Bake
about 6 to 7 minutes or until browned. Transfer to a firm surface
and cut into slices.
</P>
<P>
   Serve immediately, garnished with 1/2 of sliced green onion.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat with remaining dough and ingredients. Makes 2 pizzas. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; From ``The Figs Table'' by Todd English and Sally Sampson,
Simon &AMP; Schuster. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; FIG JAM
</P>
<P>
   Fig jam is more like a dried fruit preserve than a true jam. We
use it primarily on our Fig and Prosciutto Pizza, but after you've
tried it, I'm sure you'll come up with your own uses.
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon canola OR vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   3 shallots, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup red wine
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup canned low-sodium chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup veal OR beef broth
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped fresh rosemary
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 rounded cup dried mission figs, quartered
</P>
<P>
   Place a medium skillet over medium heat and, when hot, add oil.
Add shallots and cook until softened, about 3 minutes. Deglaze with
red wine and reduce by 1/2. Add broths and vinegar and reduce by
1/2. Add rosemary and sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Reduce heat to low and cook until sugar has melted, about 3 to 5
minutes. Add figs and cook, stirring occasionally, until
rehydrated, about 10 to 12 minutes. Cook until mixture has
consistency of a liquidy jam, about 10 to 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Use immediately or cover and refrigerate up to 5 days. Makes
about 1 cup.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Figs Table'' by Todd English and Sally Sampson, Simon
&AMP; Schuster. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CLAM PIZZA
</P>
<P>
   Pepe's clam pizza is legendary. It was made famous by Pepe's in
New Haven, Conn., a world-famous pizzeria whose owner claims to
have invented American Pizza. When I was in high school, we used to
hang out at Pepe's, but now that I live in Boston, I always stop
off on my way to and from New York City, which is less often than I
would like.
</P>
<P>
   When you put the clams on the pizza, be sure to include the
liquor, which contributes enormous flavor. And don't be tempted to
increase the Parmesan cheese; if you do, you'll overwhelm the
clams. Keep the clams refrigerated until ready to use and shuck
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   18 to 24 littleneck clams, well washed, shucked and very roughly
chopped, including clam liquor
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons fresh oregano leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 Figs Pizza Dough rounds (recipe above)
</P>
<P>
   Cornmeal for sprinkling
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 pinches kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   2 pinches black pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons freshly grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh parsley for garnish
</P>
<P>
   One hour prior to cooking, place a baking stone in oven and
preheat to 500 degrees F.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, place clams and their liquor, oil and 1
teaspoon oregano in a bowl; toss to combine and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Roll out 1 pizza dough round as thinly as possible. Place on a
pizza peel sprinkled with cornmeal. Cover surface with 1/4 teaspoon
minced garlic and 1 pinch EACH salt and pepper. Be sure to leave an
outer lip of 1-inch all the way around.
</P>
<P>
   Evenly distribute 1/2 of clam mixture, including liquor, over
pizza. Top with 1 teaspoon oregano and sprinkle with 1 tablespoon
grated Parmesan cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Shake paddle lightly and slide pizza onto baking stone. Bake
until browned, about 6 to 7 minutes or until browned. Transfer to a
firm surface and cut into slices.
</P>
<P>
   Serve immediately, garnished with 1/2 teaspoon oregano, 1 1/2
teaspoons Parmesan cheese and 1 tablespoon parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat with remaining dough nd ingredients. Makes 2 pizzas.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Figs Table'' by Todd English and Sally Sampson, Simon
&AMP; Schuster. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHITE-CHOCOLATE CHALLAH PUDDING
</P>
<P>
   This is one of our four most popular desserts. It's luscious and
smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you don't like white chocolate, you'll love this. It has
the appearance of being light, but in fact it is one of the richest
desserts we make. Serve it with a raspberry sauce to cut the
richness or caramel sauce or chocolate sauce to enhance it.
</P>
<P>
   7 large egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   2 whole eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   3 cups whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   10 ounces white chocolate, about 2 cups chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 cups challah cubes, about 1 loaf, crusts removed, if desired
</P>
<P>
   Place egg yolks, eggs and vanilla in a small bowl and mix to
combine. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Place whipping cream, milk and sugar in a 2-quart saucpan over
medium-high heat and cook until scalded or when bubbles begin to
form around edges and it has not quite come to a boil, about 7
minutes. Add white chocolate and mix until fully melted. Gradually
add egg mixture in a slow steady stream, whisking constantly.
</P>
<P>
   Place bread cubes in an 8x8-inch pan and cover with egg-cream
mixture. Press cubes down and let stand, 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cover with foil and place in a larger pan filled halfway with
very hot water. Transfer to preheated 350-degree oven and bake
about 1 hour and 15 minutes until firm and, when touched in middle,
custard does not show up on your finger. Check to see if water
needs to be replenished after 30 minutes. If so, add enough to keep
water level at halfway point. Serve warm with fresh berries,
raspberry sauce or caramel sauce. Makes 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Figs Table'' by Todd English and Sally Sampson, Simon
&AMP; Schuster. &QL; 
(SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
