<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Surfing the Internet Via the Step Machine &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It is no secret that Americans have short attention spans when
it comes to exercise. Go to any gym, and people will be reading
magazines and listening to music to keep themselves entertained on
cardio machines.
</P>
<P>
   To encourage their disenchanted members, health clubs are
installing consoles onto step machines and stationary bikes to
allow users to surf the Internet, watch their own cable
televisions, listen to CD's and call up past workout records each
time they log on to a machine.
</P>
<P>
   Netpulse Communications of San Francisco, started manufacturing
the consoles in 1995, and they are available at about 300 fitness
centers nationwide. The Can Do Club, which opens this week in
Wayne, N.J., is offering Netpulse on all of its compatible exercise
equipment. ``Working out is drudgery for a lot of people,'' said
Steve Polevoy, chairman and chief executive of Can Do. ``We want
the exercise experience to be as pleasant as possible for our
members.''
</P>
<P>
   Pleasant, sure, but are distractions the best way to stay
motivated? Users seem to think so. ``I cycle watching CNN and
CNBC,'' said Hunter Martin, a retired lawyer and member of the
Houstonian Spa in Houston. ``When my workout's almost finished, I
often add another 30 minutes so I can keep watching the market
reports.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Davis, a personal trainer at the San Francisco Bay Club,
met with a client recently who despised exercise, but spent three
hours a day surfing the Internet. Now a Netpulse convert, the
client does his daily surfing at the gym instead of at his desk.
</P>
<P>
   Though the machines motivate, they may not always provide the
best workout, some experts and users say. Sherri Balsam, a
21-year-old student who works out at Crunch Fitness in Manhattan,
said that flipping channels on Netpulse's personal televisions made
time go by quickly at the gym, but added that she found that trying
to type while cycling slowed her down.
</P>
<P>
   ``With less focus on what you're doing, the intensity of your
workouts can suffer,'' said Richard Cotton, chief exercise
physiologist for the American Council on Exercise. ``But let's face
it, staring at a wall while you're working out in a gym is boring.
If this will keep people exercising, why not?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; How Pensions Play in Divorce Court &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The expression ``take the money and run'' may resonate well
among working wives who have pensions and are over the age of 45.
These women are more likely to be separated from their husbands
than married women in the same age range who are employed but do
not have pensions, according to a report released by the University
of Michigan Institute for Social Research.
</P>
<P>
   In the first study of the relationship between pension wealth
and marital dissolution, the researchers examined the marital,
pension and employment status of women in 4,219 couples and placed
working wives into three age categories: under 35, 35 to 44, and 45
and over.
</P>
<P>
   They found that 12 percent of pensioned women who were over 45
were separated from their husbands, while only 2 percent of women
that age who were without pensions had experienced marital
dissolution. The differences were less significant for women in the
two other age groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a huge gap between those who do and don't have
pensions in the oldest group,'' said Dr. Hiromi Ono, a sociologist
at the University of Michigan Institute of Social Research and lead
author of the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a very popular idea that when women get their own
resources it leads them to experience marital dissolution. But it's
not that simple a story.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ono said women who had jobs with pensions were likely to be
committed to their careers, and that deep commitments could
sometimes cause unresolvable issues in marriages no matter the age
of the couple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are not leaving their husbands because they got the
money,'' Dr. Ono said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, women weren't playing a major role as
breadwinners and it made sense for wives to drop out of the labor
market,'' she said. ``Today it's much less clear and there can be
conflicts because of it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
