<HEADER>
A5094 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-EVERGLADES-ART-3T     04-12 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-EVERGLADES-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING THINGS RIGHT IN THE EVERGLADES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By WILLIAM K. STEVENS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ From a helicopter scudding over South Florida, a ribbon
of green farms stretches off to the East. There the avocados and
mangoes are in bloom, tomatoes are green on the vine and field
workers are picking beans. Just beyond are acres and acres of
suburban Miami's characteristic orange-pink roofs.
</P>
<P>
   But directly below, wild nature still holds sway. Or tries to.
</P>
<P>
   What looks like a tawny Western grassland studded by green tree
islands stretches off to the North, West and South. It is the dry
season, and only isolated little pools of water mark the course of
Shark River Slough, a broad but shallow sluice that for 5,000 years
has been the main fresh-water channel through what is now
Everglades National Park.
</P>
<P>
   This winter-and-spring ``dry-down,'' as it is called, is normal.
One of its effects is to concentrate the fish that proliferate
during the summer wet season, and on which the Everglades' famous
wading birds subsist.
</P>
<P>
   The dense concentrations are what fuel the birds' nesting
activities and feed their hatchlings; and as the helicopter
clatters overhead, groups of ibises, wood storks, egrets, anhingas,
herons and a multitude of other species are flocking to the pools.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is pristine Everglades,'' said Mike Slayton, the deputy
director of the South Florida Water Management District. It is also
an Everglades in serious decline.
</P>
<P>
   Slow-flowing fresh water is the ecosystem's lifeblood, but less
than half as much of it flows through Shark River Slough today, on
average, as did a century ago. On the whole, water is insufficient
in the Everglades at large, and it often flows to a given place at
the wrong time or in the wrong amount.
</P>
<P>
   So the huge marsh produces far less life than it used to.
Despite the occasional groups of wading birds, the populations that
once were the hallmark of the Everglades have diminished by more
than 90 percent. Ecologists consider this the best single indicator
of the ecosystem's ill health.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason for the decline is that in a successful effort
to supply fresh water to the cities and farms and to protect them
from flooding, people have siphoned off too much of the natural
flow of water that once stretched in a continuous sheet from Lake
Okeechobee in the north to Florida Bay in the south.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of billions of gallons a year are now routinely shunted
out to sea. Levees divide what remains of the sheet flow into a
series of disconnected pools. The result of all this manipulation
is an ecosystem out of kilter.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the nation's most ambitious attempt at ecological
restoration, the federal and state governments are about to try to
put things right. The idea is to spend $8 billion over 20 years to
re-plumb the Everglades' so that natural conditions can be
re-established or at least mimicked.
</P>
<P>
   The latest version of a complex plan to do this, almost six
years in the making, was made public last week and after further
revision is to be delivered to Congress for its consideration on
July 1.
</P>
<P>
   The project, almost six years in the planning, has provoked both
high hopes and high anxiety, and it raises a number of fundamental
questions: Can the unique, world-class natural area really be
restored, given what has been done to it? If so, to what extent?
And will the proposed project do enough?
</P>
<P>
   THE PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Redirecting Water, Finding Hope
</P>
<P>
   No one believes that South Florida can be put back the way it
was before people started altering it about a century ago. For one
thing, about half the area of the original ecosystem has been
converted to urban areas and farms.
</P>
<P>
   Some environmentalists argue that much of the farmland should be
bought out and re-converted to natural areas. But that idea appears
dead politically, and even if it were successfully revived, the
natural system still would not recover its original size.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, South Florida's population of six million is expected
to double over the next half century, and some experts fear that
pressure to develop some of what is left of the Everglades _ and to
appropriate the water _ will only increase.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this cloud on the horizon, the replumbing plan assumes
that the system will remain essentially its present size for the
next 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Based on that assumption, it aims to recapture most of the
billions of gallons of water that now flow to the Atlantic and Gulf
of Mexico each year. This water will be stored in a variety of
reservoirs, including limestone quarries and underground aquifers,
to be redistributed as needed to the Everglades, the farms and the
cities.
</P>
<P>
   The project is intended to deliver the right amount of clean
water to the Everglades at the right place at the right time, in as
natural a manner as possible. The hope is to recreate conditions in
which the Everglades can revive and recover much of their essential
character _ even though in a different and truncated form compared
with the original.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the plan gets us very close'' to that goal, said
Michael L. Davis, an ecologist and deputy assistant secretary of
the Army. He oversees the Army Corps of Engineers, which devised
the plan in cooperation with many federal, state and local agencies
under the over-all aegis of the Interior Department, and he has
been deeply involved in the plan's preparation.
</P>
<P>
   No one claims that the plan is perfect, or ever will be. After
the initial version was made public last October, some scientists
and environmentalists criticized it on grounds that it did not go
far enough in removing the welter of artificial plumbing in which
the system is trussed up, and that it would take too long to gain
results.
</P>
<P>
   It has since been revised after negotiations among the Army
Corps and other groups, notably the National Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan in its present form, Davis said, 80 percent of
the water that now goes out to sea would be redirected into the
Everglades. This, he said, would give the Everglades half the total
expanded water supply; now, the farms and cities get 70 percent of
a smaller supply.
</P>
<P>
   In the southern part of Shark River Slough, in the heart of the
national park, the flow would be 90 percent of what computer models
suggest was its historic volume. That should be enough to insure
recovery, said Richard G. Ring, the park superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   In the plan as originally proposed last fall, the restored flow
would have been about 70 percent of the historical volume. Ring and
his staff protested, and after intense talks, the target was
changed.
</P>
<P>
   The additional water will come mostly from treated urban runoff,
and it remains to be seen how successfully that water can be
purified. The planners envision a series of filtering marshes to
remove agricultural runoff and other pollutants from reclaimed
water before it flows into the natural system.
</P>
<P>
   The project also is intended to break down the
compartmentalization of the Everglades somewhat by removing some
levees and canals. The first phase of de-compartmentalization has
been speeded up as a result of the recent talks, and is to be
completed by 2010. In all, roughly two-thirds of the project is to
be finished by then.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics are reserving judgment pending more detailed study.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty encouraged'' by the recent improvements, said
Ring, whose staff scientists have been among the most vocal
critics. ``There is nothing in the plan that's a showstopper'' in
achieving ecological recovery, he said.
</P>
<P>
   THE HISTORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A `Perfect' System Is Segmented
</P>
<P>
   In the depths of the last ice age some 18,000 years ago, what is
now the Everglades was an open grassland punctuated by oak and
pine. As the climate warmed and South Florida became semi-tropical,
conditions jelled for the formation of a freshwater marsh within a
shallow limestone saucer bounded by low ridges on Florida's east
and west.
</P>
<P>
   The saucer was tilted slightly from north to south, so that the
water in the marsh ran ever so slowly into Florida Bay. Rising seas
helped retard runoff and hold the water in place, and the
Everglades were in place by about the time the Sumerian
civilization rose in Mesopotamia 5,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   One key to the Everglades' ecological character was that the
slow movement of water enabled the system to store enormous amounts
of rainfall from one season to the next. Another key was the
system's huge size and variety of habitats. As water levels rose
and fell between wet and dry seasons, for instance, wading birds
could always move about and find both nesting habitat and food.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last century, the region was gradually covered by a
latticework of levees (one, stretching all the way from Lake
Okeechobee nearly to Florida Bay, protects Florida's east coast
from floods), canals, sluice gates and pumping stations. The far
northern part of the system, where neat green rows of sugar cane
and emerald fields of sod for suburban lawns stretch across the
landscape, was converted to agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   South of this Everglades Agricultural Area, the central part of
the marsh was compartmentalized into five big pools called water
conservation areas. Still farther south is Everglades National Park
itself, the most nearly pristine part of the ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
   But the park is at the mercy of water flow from the north. Not
only have the wetlands to the north been diminished, but in some
places, outcroppings of development create backwaters that further
prevent water from flowing south. Since the Everglades north of the
park have been diminished in size much more than the park,
re-establishing the sheet flow into the park would result in a far
narrower flow than was the case historically.
</P>
<P>
   While there is some sheet flow within the divided compartments,
the chopping-up of the system has greatly degraded its ecological
character. For instance, water in some parts of the national park
is too deep for ecological health, while other parts are too dry.
Because of this, for example, the endangered Cape Sable seaside
sparrow has trouble finding suitable habitats.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, levees on the southern edges of compartments cause
``ponding'' as southward-flowing water piles up, while other areas
have become too shallow, and even permanently dry. The marsh soil
in these areas has disintegrated and subsided.
</P>
<P>
   Though the marsh is still extensive, its patchwork pattern
greatly reduces its value to creatures like wading birds, who
become confused about where they can feed and nest, says John C.
Ogden, a Water Management District ecologist. Three or four decades
ago, the Everglades were home to huge ``super colonies'' of nesting
wading birds; today these colonies have disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   THE FLOW
</P>
<P>
   Reconnection And Priorities
</P>
<P>
   Since levees, pumps and canals altered the system, they are also
seen by many experts as essential in fixing it. ``This system will
never be a natural system,'' said Dr. Mark Kraus of the National
Audubon Society, which has long been deeply involved in the
restoration. ``You have to keep people dry and put water back into
the system. Water delivery has to be by pumps and canals.''
</P>
<P>
   The general aim, nevertheless, is to keep elaborate engineering
projects on the periphery of the remaining natural area, rather
than inside it. For instance, say advocates of the plan, it will be
necessary to install new pumps, canals and water storage areas just
outside the Everglades, so that water now flowing to the oceans can
be recaptured and pumped, sometimes around obstacles, where it is
needed.
</P>
<P>
   But within the natural area, the goal is to remove as many
artificial structures as possible. More than 240 miles of levees
and canals are to be so eliminated. An important move of this kind
involves the major thoroughfare called Tamiami Trail, which runs
westward out of Miami and divides the national park from the rest
of the natural system to the north.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The highway will be raised and a series of causeways or bridges
will be built, under which water will flow essentially unimpeded
between two of the Everglades' biggest compartments for the first
time in decades. This part of the project is to be completed by
2010.
</P>
<P>
   But experts are divided over the extent to which the historic
sheet flow can and should be re-established. Some believe that the
top priority should be re-establishing the natural depths and
timing of water flows, while others believe that sheet flow itself
should be the top priority.
</P>
<P>
   These goals are not always compatible. For example, if sheet
flow were fully restored, subsidence of the land in some places
would make the water too deep to support much Everglades life.
</P>
<P>
   Also, ponding caused partly by subsidence just northeast of
Tamiami Trail discourages the desire to improve sheet flow by
removing a miles-long major levee to the west. In a recent
compromise, it was decided that a series of notches, or weirs, are
to be cut into the levee through which some water can spill in the
wet season.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, if the subsidence problem can be fixed by filling or
is resolved naturally, the levee can then be removed. (Originally,
the Army Corps proposed to put in more elaborate gates instead of
weirs. Park scientists and others argued successfully that weirs
could be more easily and less expensively removed later, and were a
good interim step.)
</P>
<P>
   Another obstacle is posed by a pocket of homes just east of the
national park that impedes the water flow into Taylor Slough, a
channel on the east side of the park that is the main conduit of
fresh water to Florida Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the bay, some scientists say, has become too salty as a
result of diminished flow from Taylor Slough and is in ecological
decline as a result. A buyout of the homes has been proposed.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Everglades' water flow were perfectly
re-established, that would not complete the work of restoration.
There are the problems of soil loss and subsidence to contend with.
And much of the Everglades has been taken over by exotic plants
from abroad, which are crowding out native species. Some strides
have been made in eliminating one of the most aggressive, the
melaleuca tree.
</P>
<P>
   In a pine-forest island in the Everglades, park scientists have,
after a long period of trial and error simply begun scraping the
land down to bedrock to eliminate another interloper, Brazilian
pepper. Natural vegetation is springing up again, but there is a
long way to go in cleansing the ecosystem of vegetative pollution. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Based on what is known of the Everglades' past and on computer
modeling studies, the scores of specialists most deeply involved in
the restoration project typically express high hopes for the
future, tempered by realities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will never recover the original Everglades,'' Ogden says,
but ``we can make it much healthier than the current system,''
</P>
<P>
   The Future
</P>
<P>
   Optimism And Nervousness
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the experts' optimism is that unlike the
situation in many degraded ecosystems, most of the ecological
pieces of the Everglades are still live there, albeit in reduced
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   In the version of the re-plumbing plan made public last week,
the Army Corps and the Water Management District predict that once
the plan is executed, the abundance of creatures at all levels of
the food web, from minnows and frogs to herons, ibis, otter and
alligators, will increase and return to more natural distribution
patterns.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the effects, the plan predicts, will be seen as early
as a decade from now. About two-thirds of the plan's components
should be in place by then, but other important ones will not be
until about 2020, and some later. Moreover, there is likely to be a
lag between the establishment of a new pattern of flow and the
ecological response.
</P>
<P>
   A big uncertainty in all this is the possible impact of rising
seas. If a warming climate causes the global sea level to rise over
the next few decades as mainstream scientists predict, large areas
of the southern Everglades could be inundated or converted to a
saltwater marsh.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from that, no one knows exactly how the system will
respond to the replumbing; since there is no detailed record of how
the original system functioned, predictions and targets are based
on the computer models. The plan, therefore, is a ``a broad
blueprint and a starting point,'' said Dr. Mark Schaefer, a
biologist who is a deputy assistant secretary of the Interior.
</P>
<P>
   The key to success, he and many others believe, is to remain
flexible so that mid-course corrections can be made. In that sense,
the re-plumbing plan _ and the project itself _ is a perpetual work
in progress.
</P>
<P>
   This has made some environmentalists nervous. They fear that
unless as many details as possible are nailed down now, political
sentiment could change in the future, and urban and agricultural
interests could press for greater advantage at the expense of the
natural system.
</P>
<P>
   Projections call for the population of South Florida to grow
from 6 million to 12 million or more in 50 years, the target period
for the restoration project. All of those people are going to need
housing, and housing will need water that might otherwise go to the
natural system.
</P>
<P>
   ``My greatest fear,'' Mike Slayton, the Water Management
District official, said as the helicopter flew over the sugar cane
fields just north of the Everglades, ``is that the Everglades
Agricultural Area will turn into a bedroom community in 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Ring, the park superintendent, puts it this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless we figure out a way that changes how we grow and build,
the built system is going to continue to move into the natural
system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
