<HEADER>
A5121 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MONITORS-0413-     04-12 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MONITORS-0413-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHAT HAPPENED THE THE WEST'S WORKERS IN KOSOVO?
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0413; KOSOVO-AID-0413.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ Among the suffering of Kosovo's ethnic
Albanians, the swiftest and most brutal punch by Serb forces may
have been delivered to some of the 1,400 local employees of the
group allowed to monitor the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Of them, only one has been confirmed dead at the hands of the
Serbs, and some have been identified among the refugees that
streamed out of Kosovo to safety.
</P>
<P>
   But many more are presumed to have been tortured or killed or
both, said officials of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE).
</P>
<P>
   The security detail of the team leader, American diplomat
William Walker, and the mission as a whole, had been infiltrated by
at least one Serb operative, said Lt. Col. Michael Philips,
military assistant to Walker. One man employed by the OSCE as a
security agent has since been identified as a subordinate of
Yugoslav warlord Zeljko Razhatovic, the feared paramilitary leader
known as ``Arkan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly fearful that some of the OSCE employees were
identified,'' Philips said. Two of Walker's personal bodyguards
were reported killed by the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   At least one former ethnic Albanian employee who escaped to
Macedonia was severely beaten, had his fingers broken and was
forced to swallow his laminated OSCE identification card, officials
said. The man, Ali Ahmeti, was evacuated with his family to Germany
last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The OSCE's Kosovo Verification Mission was created last fall to
monitor a negotiated truce between Serb forces and the Kosovo
Liberation Army (KLA). The unarmed monitors fled Kosovo in just
before NATO's air campaign against the Serbs began in late March.
</P>
<P>
   Some monitors, against OSCE orders, brought their local
translators and drivers with them when they drove out of Kosovo in
a convoy to Macedonia. But the bulk of the local staff remained
behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of guilt about the way it was handled,'' said an
OSCE field worker who worries about the fate of his landlord after
he heard that the house he rented in the village of Dakovica had
been targeted by Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   Philips said local employees were told to ``stay low and stay
indoors,'' but many may have been easily identified as friends of
the OSCE, vilified by the Serbs as a tool of NATO and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, who toured refugee camps in Macedonia on Sunday to the
warm cheers and hugs from refugees, said an armed international
force must enter Kosovo, whether invited or not, to enable the
refugees to return home safely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going back,'' he said at the Stanovac refugee camp near
here. ``Ask any of the refugees (in Skopje) and they'll tell you
we're going back.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
