<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5122 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0413-     04-12 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0413-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS REFUGEE FLOW SLOWS, WHERE ARE THE REST?
 &HT;    700&AMP;add
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-AID-0413; KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0413.
 &HT;    EDs: For the purposes of a locator map Blace is the main border
crossing north of the Macedonian capital, Skopje.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACE, Macedonia _ A week ago it was a torrent, now the flow of
refugees from Kosovo is a trickle.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials and humanitarian relief agencies believe large
numbers of ethnic Albanians still in Kosovo have fled on foot into
the snow-capped mountains along the borders with Albania and
Macedonia to evade Serbian shock troops and find a route to safety.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated and fearful of the consequences of coming out of
hiding, they are struggling against food shortages and frigid
spring rains.
</P>
<P>
   NATO, which is considering food-aid drops over Kosovo to feed
the displaced, says 400,000 or more ethnic Albanians could be
secluded in remote villages or living primitively in the wilderness
along border areas that may have been mined by Serb troops.
</P>
<P>
   Those assessments were backed by evidence Monday when a small
group of Kosovar refugees emerged from hiding and crossed the
border into Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole village was living in the mountains,'' said Kefsere
Nebiu, 32, a mother of four who were among the 360 refugees who
crossed the Blace checkpoint to safety in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees, many from the Kosovo town of Urosevac, about 25
miles south of the provincial capital of Pristina, recounted
similar experiences. Two weeks ago, Serbian army, police and
paramilitary forces entered the town and began a systematic forced
evacuation similar to those reported across Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told us, 'As soon as you leave, we will burn down your
house,''' said Nurije Hysenajzi, 21.
</P>
<P>
   Many families fled into the mountains to the small village of
Sejevo about one mile away. There, they took shelter with friends
and family until last week when Serb forces entered with three
tanks and proceeded to empty the village.
</P>
<P>
   Nebiu said her husband's elderly and frail parents were shot to
death by Serb troops in their home after being ordered to leave.
The couple were unable to move without assistance. Nebiu believes
Serb troops may have thought the couple was disobeying the command
to evacuate the house.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 people in all fled to the woods, mothers
wrapping their babies in woolen sweaters and children carrying as
much of the families belongings as they could.
</P>
<P>
   For several days, the older men remained at the edge of the
forest, waiting to see if they could return to the village. Most
nights, Serb forces apparently fearful of NATO air attacks, would
themselves go into hiding, allowing the villagers to return to find
shelter.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the day we would hide in the mountains, and then we
would come back to the houses at night,'' said Gezim Osmani, 16.
</P>
<P>
   Believing there was safety in numbers, 50 to 60 people would
sleep in a single house. But occasionally hearing gunfire, they
would again flee into the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was cold and raining. There was nothing to eat. We would
share small pieces of bread,'' said Hisnije Mani, 38, who fled with
her husband Rahman, a laborer, three of their children and Rahman's
80-year-old partially paralyzed mother.
</P>
<P>
   After several days, the Serb troops flushed out those hiding in
the village. People still in the woods decided to take their
chances and make their way back to the larger town of Urosevac,
parts of which had been burned and leveled. There, Serb officials
allowed them to board a train for the Macedonian border; but they
had to buy their own tickets -- about $7 per person.
</P>
<P>
   The accounts cannot be independently verified, as Kosovo is
closed to most international journalists and aid workers.
</P>
<P>
   But the stories appear to confirm the fears of NATO and U.N.
High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) relief officials who believe
the refugees remaining in Kosovo face more desperate and dangerous
conditions than those who fled in the mass exoduses? during the
first two weeks of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hear there are a lot of people in the woods, but so far we
haven't seen many of them come out,'' said Francis Teoh(CQ), a
UNHCR field worker on the northern Macedonian border with
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Villagers in the Macedonian hills above the Blace border
crossing said some 2,000 Kosovo refugees were living in the woods
along the border about 10 days ago. They were fed and given
blankets by the residents of the village of Gorno-Blace. But after
two days, they were turned back into Kosovo by Macedonian police
who insisted they had to cross at the official border checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were scared, like they were already dead,'' said Minir
Bardhi, 23. ``They said, 'Better to kill us here (Gorno-Blace) than
to send us back to Kosovo.'''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In a separate incident, Macedonian state television reported
over the weekend that police had discovered the bodies of a young
mother and her baby who had apparently died of hypothermia while
crossing the border over a remote mountain pass.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has considered dropping food, medicines and other supplies
from the air in the hopes of reaching displaced people still in
Kosovo. But NATO planes would have to fly at high altitude to avoid
Serb anti-aircraft fire from the ground, increasing the chances
that the food and supplies could fall into the hands of Serbian
forces instead of the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Relief officials also suspect that the refugees are on the move
to avoid being tracked down by Serb forces, making it difficult to
target air drops of food and aid.
</P>
<P>
   The UNHCR estimates that as many as 1 million people, the vast
majority of them ethnic Albanians, are unaccounted for in Kosovo
since Serb forces stepped up their siege and NATO began its air
assault on Yugoslavia on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo province is home to some 1.8 million ethnic
Albanians. Most refugees have fled to neighboring Albania, which
has accepted some 310,000. About 118,000 have fled to Macedonia and
63,000 to the Yugoslav republic of Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
