   STEALTH-TECHNOLOGY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Just after the downing of an F-117 stealth fighter
over Yugoslavia on March 27, Pentagon officials played down
suggestions that Russia might now be able to catch up on stealth
technology. Now, more than two weeks after the plane went down, the
verdict is mixed. Some leading aerospace experts say the wreckage
of the radar-evading fighter could help Russian scientists learn
how the F-117 Nighthawk is produced and how radar systems can track
it. Others say the technology is too dated to do the Russians much
good. By MICHAEL D. TOWLE. Story will move in ``w'' Washington
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
