</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Nevada Barr came to literary prominence late
enough in life to laugh at herself. After a checkered early career
as an actress and national park ranger, she finally had books
published in her late 30s. ``The secret of my success? Sheer dumb
luck,'' says Barr, 47, who stopped at the Star-Telegram during a
national tour promoting ``Liberty Falling,'' her latest bestselling
mystery novel. ``But I'm enjoying it. As they say, I've been poor
and unknown and now I'm sort of rich and famous. I like rich and
famous better.'' But the poor and unknown years gave Barr the
imaginary basis of her eventual success as an author. Anna Pigeon,
the protagonist in Barr's whodunits, is a park ranger. By JEFF
GUINN. Story will move in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
