<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MIDWAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TBS OFFERS TELLING LOOK AT GREAT NAVAL BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the sea battle lost, what's left of the United States'
naval forces retreat east, unable to defend much of the Pacific
Ocean. Concentrating on its own West Coast border, American
resources otherwise available for the war in Europe are held back.
</P>
<P>
   The Normandy invasion is forestalled by years, if it happens at
all.
</P>
<P>
   It could have happened if events went another way one day in
1942, a day that set the course for the rest of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Conjecture? Not too much. Exaggeration? No. You can't
overestimate the impact of Midway.
</P>
<P>
   The Battle for Midway, on June 4, 1942, pitted American against
Japanese naval forces that clashed in the sea and air over a spit
of coral and sand 1,000 miles from nowhere. Despite facing a more
experienced Japanese fleet _ the same ships that attacked Pearl
Harbor six months before _ the American seamen and aviators won the
day in the most pivotal battle of the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   ``We helped to avenge Pearl Harbor,'' said Pete Montalvo, 74, of
Saratoga Springs, N.Y., who was a seaman second class on the USS
Yorktown, an ill-fated carrier. ``We got back at them.''
</P>
<P>
   Four Japanese carriers were lost as was the Yorktown. It was
arguably the greatest naval battle of all time, one that cost
thousands of lives, decimated the Japanese fleet and paved the way
for the Allies' push in the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Battle for Midway,'' a National Geographic special airing
Wednesday at 8:05 (Eastern) on TBS, is two stories separated by 56
years but linked by that one day. The tales are told in alternating
fashion, yesterday and today and back, the recollections of old men
who were kids forced to mature beyond their years.
</P>
<P>
   Narrated by Peter Coyote, both are stirring tales. One is of the
fight for the fate of the free world. The other is of the search,
for the benefit of history and the men who survived the battle.
</P>
<P>
   The first is the story of the battle, captured in stirring color
at the time by no less than legendary director John Ford (``The
Grapes of Wrath,'' ``The Quiet Man,'' ``The Man Who Shot Liberty
Valance,'' among more than 100 others). Ford, who was making
propaganda films for the military, took mind-boggling risks to
chronicle the battle.
</P>
<P>
   The other tale is the 1998 search for the Yorktown and Japanese
carrier Kaga, an expedition underwritten and filmed by the National
Geographic Society and led by Dr. Robert D. Ballard, the deep sea
explorer who discovered the Titanic and the sunken German ship
Bismarck.
</P>
<P>
   Ballard's expedition included four survivors of the battle, two
Japanese and two Americans. In the end the Yorktown would be found,
more than 16,000 feet down. The Kaga would not. As Ballard notes
about searching for sunken ships, sometimes Neptune lets you in,
sometimes he doesn't. When you add the emotional component of going
with survivors on such an expedition, a new dynamic enters an
exercise of science tinged with tradition and a trace of
superstition.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you do these things and you are going to a place where
people died, and then when you bring survivors ... it is always a
conflicting feeling,'' Ballard said. ``You are trying to find these
ships. There is a part of you that is very happy. That is in direct
conflict with their feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Bill Surgi, one of the two American veterans to make the
trek, the tears shed were also of pride, respect and duty, in
addition to sadness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a nostalgia-plus trip for me,'' Surgi, now retired in
Rockville, Md., said in an interview. ``I was the only one selected
from the Yorktown to go. That made me feel I was representing the
crew.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yorktown fought as well as it could. Damaged in May in the
Battle of the Coral Sea that saved Australia, the ship went in for
three months of repairs. Needed at Midway, the carrier was instead
patched up in three days and sent back into battle.
</P>
<P>
   At Midway, she was hit by one wave of Japanese bombers, but
stayed afloat. A second attack left her listing; the order was
given to abandon ship. Still, the Yorktown struggled to stay up. It
was being towed when a Japanese sub finished her off.
</P>
<P>
   ``She died hard,'' Surgi said. ``She didn't want to give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did the men on board and neither did Ballard.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
