<HEADER>
A5136 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-ICEMAN-SPI &LR;      04-12 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-ICEMAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROADWAY'S `ICEMAN' MOMENTARY UNCLOGS AMERICA'S PIPE DREAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEFFREY ERIC JENKINS  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Before a word is spoken, before an actor is seen,
there is the soft tinkling of a player piano. The music, by the
prolific theater composer Paddy Cunneen, seems both vaguely
familiar and somehow distant.
</P>
<P>
   It is an opening appropriate to Howard Davies' revival of ``The
Iceman Cometh'' by Eugene O'Neill, which opened Thursday night on
Broadway. It will be at the Brooks Atkinson Theatre through June
26. (Tickets: $50-$100, 800-755-4000.)
</P>
<P>
   Each generation seeks its defining moments on the stage. In
1956, actor Jason Robards and director Jose Quintero resurrected
the reputation of O'Neill with their productions of ``The Iceman
Cometh'' and ``Long Day's Journey into Night.'' Their success
forced a posthumous rethinking of the only American playwright to
win the Nobel Prize for Literature. O'Neill was honored in 1936,
three years before he wrote his masterworks.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Kevin Spacey, Tony and Academy Award winner,
strides confidently into the dingy, besotted world of Harry Hope's
Saloon playing the central role of Hickey.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill's work is familiar turf for the tightly wound,
charismatic Spacey, who played the dissolute Jamie in a 1986
Broadway production of ``Long Day's Journey.''
</P>
<P>
   Filled with well-crafted performances by its star-studded
ensemble _ Tony Danza, Robert Sean Leonard and rising film actor
Paul Giamatti among them _ Davies' ``Iceman'' never manages the
tragic heft of Broadway's current ``Death of a Salesman'' by Arthur
Miller. While the two plays may appear to focus on different
themes, each is still concerned with what Tennessee Williams called
``illusion that has the appearance of truth.''
</P>
<P>
   The denizens of this ``Bottom of the Sea Rathskellar'' gradually
rouse themselves from various forms of stupor to anticipate
Hickey's arrival. Scattered about on designer Bob Crowley's
handsomely evocative brick rotunda and antique bar set, these
losers spin ``pipe dreams'' of what tomorrow will bring _
employment, marriage, respectability.
</P>
<P>
   But for today, all that's important is Hickey's arrival _ with
his pockets filled with cash _ to celebrate proprietor Harry Hope's
(James Hazeldine) birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Although set in the 1912 of his youth, O'Neill wrote the play in
1939 as European war grew along with his own despair over what the
world faced. Still escaping from the Great Depression that year,
President Roosevelt declared the United States neutral in the face
of overseas conflict (proving that you needn't be a tart or a drunk
to indulge in pipe dreams).
</P>
<P>
   In ``Iceman,'' hardware salesman Hickey lands on Harry's
clientele like an evangelist on speed. With this visit to his
bibulous buddies, he's selling something and he's determined that
everyone buy. Peddling hardware to a bunch of drunks? No way.
Hickey's seen the light, he's been released from his own pipe
dreams, and he wants to release the others.
</P>
<P>
   With an edgy glint in his eye, Spacey's Hickey unnerves his old
pals. Something's different about him. But, hey, maybe it's just
another one of his gags; like the one about his wife fooling around
with the iceman. As the 4{-hour drama unwinds, though, we realize
that what Hickey has planned is no joke.
</P>
<P>
   One by one he convinces the others to cut through their
illusions and face reality in ways that are often painful and
occasionally humorous to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Pigott-Smith gives a taut performance as the jaded former
anarchist Larry, who resists Hickey's manic charms almost to the
end. Michael Emerson is superb as Willie Oban, an Ivy League
failure who is eclipsed by his father's shadow.
</P>
<P>
   Danza gratifies as the bartender who's convinced he's not a pimp
because he slaps his girls instead of beating them. Leonard is
suitable as the young man who betrays a political movement and,
consequently, his mother. But when the young man seeks answers from
Larry, he finds Hickey fervently selling``truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Betrayal is on the periphery and at the core of ``Iceman.''
There is even a party scene, complete with a Judas, that echoes the
Last Supper. Political, matriarchal and spousal betrayals are what
drive both Hickey and the boy to destruction. The boy is convinced
to cast away his illusions and embrace his own death.
</P>
<P>
   But Hickey? When faced with his own ultimate choice of truth or
illusion, he shifts gears and drops his crusade. In doing so, he
releases himself and us from the true image in the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Then it's ``bottoms up'' and ``wait 'til tomorrow'' as we sink
back into our boozy haze.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
