<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Writers, friends pay tribute to Eudora Welty at 90
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eudora Welty is 90 today, and among the many publications
lighting candles on her cake is The Georgia Review ($7), which
offers brief accolades from such literary lions as Reynolds Price
and Alice Munro, as well as one of the earliest of the Mississippi
writer's stories. Welty's ``The Doll'' is reprinted for the first
time since it appeared in June 1936, in the Tanager, a literary
bimonthly from Grinnell College in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   HAPPY BIRTHDAY TO EU: Another very personal tribute to Welty
comes from Southern writer Willie Morris, who was born in a house
in the Belhaven section of Jackson, Miss., two blocks from Welty's
home. The two have been friends since Morris was in grammar school,
so we're not surprised that he gets what others don't: an
interview. Writing in Vanity Fair ($3.95), Morris shares a glass of
Maker's Mark with the Divine Miss W., and traces his long
acquaintance with a woman he says ``many consider America's
greatest living writer.''
</P>
<P>
   GRATITUDE? Three Atlanta jewelers helped lead police to burglars
who stole $12 million in gems from the home of Palm Beach heiress
Kathleen Ford. The trio expected to cash in on the $1 million
reward, but it is still waiting. People ($2.99) recounts how Randy
Jones, Jeff Meyer and Shawn Slep fingered the culprits after
recognizing the stones on an Internet site, and tells of the
lawsuit they've filed against the widow of Henry Ford II to claim
their payoff.
</P>
<P>
   35 MILLION VIEWERS CAN'T BE WRONG: The glaring phiz of former
Atlanta Falcons nose tackle Bill Goldberg graces the Entertainment
Weekly ($2.99) cover story on the rise of professional wrestling. A
bonus sidebar deconstructs the two leagues: the superannuated World
Championship Wrestling and the glamor-boy goofy World Wrestling
Federation.
</P>
<P>
   BETTER BRAINS THROUGH HARMONY: Physicist Gordon Shaw is credited
with discovering the ``Mozart effect'' _ the power of classical
music to stimulate mathematical ability in students _ which
prompted former Gov. Zell Miller to decree that every Georgia
newborn receive a classical recording. But other scientists have
been slow to confirm Shaw's findings. Forbes ($4.95) tells of a
University of California/Irvine professor's spirited defense of his
claims, and his request that music education, lacking in most
public schools, be reinvigorated.
</P>
<P>
   TWO WORDS: PLASTIC MAN: Pulitzer Prize-winning cartoonist Art
Spiegelman, who has annoyed and delighted New Yorker ($3) readers
with his in-your-face cover illustrations (he once decorated an
Easter issue with a bunny on a cross), shows his reporting and
writing ability with a sharp tribute to cartoonist Jack Cole,
creator of the exuberantly stretchy superhero Plastic Man.
Spiegelman's piece is also a paean to the golden age of comics, and
a lament for the current state of this ailing American art: ``The
industry has never been as close to death as now.''
</P>
<P>
   SEEING THE LIGHT: How do NATO fighter jets bring about pinpoint
destruction in Kosovo? The Smithsonian publication Air &AMP; Space
($3.95) gives a Popular Mechanics-style gearhead backgrounder on
the development of the laser-guided bomb, from its Vietnam
beginnings to its current deployment in Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   LEE'S RETREAT: In April 1865, the retreating Army of Northern
Virginia was making its way through Farmville, pursued by Union
forces under Ulysses S. Grant, when former Virginia Gov. Henry Wise
said to its commander, Robert E. Lee, ``Nothing remains but to put
your poor men on their poor mules and send them home. This army is
hopelessly whipped.'' Lee disagreed, and continued flying to the
west, toward his fate at Appomattox. Forbes American Heritage
($4.95) traces Lee's retreat with a visit to the historic landmarks
along this Virginia trail.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
