<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No `Muskrat Love,' but `Victoria' has Alabama accent
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who turned on a radio or a TV set in the '70s couldn't
miss Toni Tennille, the perky blond half of the decade's hot pop
duo, the Captain &AMP; Tennille. The married couple came out of nowhere
in 1975 to score the top-selling song of the year, ``Love Will Keep
Us Together,'' which copped them a weekly TV variety series and pop
stardom.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Captain (a.k.a. Daryl Dragon) and Tennille went on to
sell 23 million records with vintage, shag-hair hits such as ``Do
That to Me One More Time,'' ``Muskrat Love'' and ``The Way I Want
to Touch You,'' their time on the charts ended just as the decade
did.
</P>
<P>
   Tennille, however, hasn't faded into pop-star obscurity.
Tonight, she arrives in Atlanta for a six-day run in the national
touring production of ``Victor/Victoria,'' the musical that starred
Julie Andrews on Broadway and in which Tennille has been starring
since September 1998. We caught up with her in Cincinnati and
chatted, while the Captain tinkered with his new computer in the
background.
</P>
<P>
   People are inevitably going to compare your performance to Julie
Andrews'. What's the difference?
</P>
<P>
   A:Julie is an English soprano, and that's the way the
</P>
<P>
   show was written. I'm playing Victoria as an Alabama contralto,
because that's what I am. So references that are normally to places
in England now refer to places in Alabama and the South. The accent
I use suggests a Southern thing, but it's not as thick as the one I
grew up with. If I used that, they wouldn't understand me in
Northern cities. Victor obviously can't be Southern, so I have a
continental accent for him.
</P>
<P>
   How hard is it for you to play a male for half the night?
</P>
<P>
   A:My physicality is quite different from Julie's. I'm very tall,
5-feet-11, and pretty small-busted. Julie was generously endowed.
She had to wear a compressor, but I don't have to. I tried it on
once in New York, and said, ``I can't sing in this!'' It's this
flesh-colored, really tight spandex bandage thing. You can't
breathe.
</P>
<P>
   What do you think of when you think about Atlanta?
</P>
<P>
   A:I remember climbing Stone Mountain when I was in my teens. I
sang with the symphony about 14 years ago at Chastain (Park
amphitheater). I remember it's impossible to find your way around.
Everything is named Peachtree, and the streets are not on a grid. I
usually get a rental car, but we're going to keep a limo on call
there because I don't want to drive. What I'm really looking
forward to this time is a busload of gals from Montgomery(,
Alabama) I haven't seen since junior high school are coming to the
show Thursday night. It's going to be a hoot to see these women.
One gal I actually went to kindergarten with at Miss Margaret
Booth's School for Girls.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
