<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOR NATO, ANOTHER HUMANITARIAN CRISIS: HOW TO AID STARVING
ETHNIC ALBANIANS STUCK IN KOSOVO
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-CONGRESS-O413; KOSOVO-MONITORS-0413.
 &HT;    By SCOTT MONTGOMERY 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hundreds of thousands of Kosovar Albanians who
escaped the brutal sweeps of Serb military forces by fleeing to the
cold mountains and forests of Kosovo have now been in hiding for
more than two weeks, and allied officials said Monday that they
fear an even larger humanitarian disaster is brewing beyond their
reach.
</P>
<P>
   The crush of Kosovars overwhelming the borders of the
neighboring countries of Albania, Macedonia -- as well as the
Yugoslav state of Montenegro -- has all but stopped in recent days,
with the U.N. High Commission on Refugees (UNHCR) reporting only
about 4,000 crossed into Albania over the weekend. And Pentagon
officials said Monday adequate food and shelter has been provided
for ``most of the refugees around the periphery'' of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as we deal with one humanitarian challenge, we also are
aware that there is another dramatic one, the one inside Kosovo
itself,'' NATO Secretary General Javier Solana told reporters in
Brussels. ``We are deeply concerned with the fate of all the
displaced peoples there in Kosovo who, as you know, are facing
hunger and exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is another major humanitarian crisis in the making, and
we are urgently considering whether there are ways in which we
might be able to help.''
</P>
<P>
   But this new refugee problem seems more vexing than the last.
</P>
<P>
   Serb military forces and paramilitary gangs control the ground
in Kosovo, Serbia's southern province, making it difficult even to
estimate the size of the refugee crisis. Most journalists and
relief workers were expelled in the early days of the NATO
campaign, so information has primarily been anecdotal, provided
sporadically by those few who are left.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, following a NATO meeting on Monday, Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright blamed the Yugoslav government headed by
President Slobodan Milosevic for generating yet another crisis for
humanity. But she was forced to rely on guesswork in talking about
its scope.
</P>
<P>
   ``True to form, Belgrade is taking every opportunity to make a
bad situation worse,'' Albright said from NATO headquarters.
``We're deeply concerned that as many as 700,000 people are at risk
within Kosovo. It appears that Belgrade is deliberately depriving
them of food and shelter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these people are allowed to die, we will hold the Serb
authorities accountable,'' she warned.
</P>
<P>
   But the more pointed problem NATO faces in dealing with the
possibility of mass starvation is that Serb military units are
still too dangerous to get close to. Throughout the campaign, now
going into its 21st day, NATO air strikes have sought to isolate
Serb ground forces in Kosovo province by targeting supply lines.
</P>
<P>
   And while Pentagon officials say satellite photographs suggest
the strategy is working because Serb units have become less mobile,
they remain well-equipped.
</P>
<P>
   Army Lt. Col. Bill Darley at the Pentagon said arranging an
airlift to drop food already has been discussed and scratched.
Unlike high-altitude bombers or ultra-fast F-16 fighter jets, cargo
planes carrying food would provide easy targets by flying low and
slow.
</P>
<P>
   ``To do that we have to have air dominance,'' Darley said.
``First of all you worry about getting it to the people you intend
it for. And, of course, you want your airframe to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Darley called food drops an ``inexact science,'' and said NATO
wants to avoid fortifying Serb troops. But he also stressed that
since the humanitarian issue was the driving force behind NATO's
military action a high priority has been placed on assessing the
situation within Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be that we have massive starvation in Kosovo,'' he
said. ``We don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
