<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAX TALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This is the week Americans love to hate _ our
income tax returns are due. Inevitable but ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, the annual deadline April 15 has provided
politicians with a golden opportunity to demonstrate easy empathy
with constituents by demanding tax cuts in one form or another. The
Republicans in particular have made this issue a priority ever
since it swept Ronald Reagan into the White House nearly two
decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative GOP members of Congress even tried last year to
wipe out the tax code altogether as a means of forcing Congress to
replace it with an unspecified alternative. Although fortunately
this reckless scheme went nowhere, it dramatically illustrated the
intensity of antitax feeling in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this spring the unusual is happening. Voters don't seem to
care much about getting a fat new tax cut, according to the polls
and political analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally none of us would turn down a tax reduction. We're not
stupid.
</P>
<P>
   But there are other things that seem more important these days
on the public agenda, from spending the projected federal surplus
to protect Social Security and Medicare to using it for
improvements in education.
</P>
<P>
   All the potential 2000 Republican presidential candidates are
promising tax cuts anyway, some of them stressing an
across-the-board slash of 10 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic heir-apparent, Vice President Al Gore, supports
narrowly aimed tax cuts along lines already backed by President
Clinton, such as eliminating the marriage penalty. That particular
inequity as well as some others have been targeted by Republicans
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Publishing heir Malcolm S. ``Steve'' Forbes made his mark in his
first presidential campaign in 1996 largely by crusading for a 17
percent flat tax.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is still around and Forbes still talks about it in his
current presidential campaign. But he has expanded his political
repertory to include other issues that have more resonance. The
flat tax had the appeal of simplicity, but it was also
conspicuously unfair, giving rich folks like Forbes an enormous tax
break and draining the federal treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the GOP presidential frontrunner, is
thus far as ambiguous on the subject of across-the-board tax cuts
as he is on just about everything else. Perhaps he remembers his
father's mistake in proclaiming: ``Read my lips; no new taxes'' _ a
rash commitment for which the elder Bush paid a heavy political
penalty when he later was forced to ignore it.
</P>
<P>
   But there may be a clue to the younger Bush's thinking in the
fact that his chief economic policy adviser, Lawrence Lindsey,
recently championed a 10 percent across-the-board income tax cut as
an essential economic stimulus.
</P>
<P>
   Whether a massive, untargeted tax cut is indeed necessary or
might in fact be harmful in today's flush economy is a subject of
much dispute among experts. Ordinary taxpayers can pick and choose
among the arguments. Statistics can be manipulated to suit
ideologies. Who knows which of competing economic assumptions are
accurate?
</P>
<P>
   But what really matters politically is whether voters feel
excessively and unfairly pinched by the tax system.
</P>
<P>
   And apparently _ for the moment at least _ they do not.
</P>
<P>
   It has helped that not long ago Congress held hearings into
Internal Revenue Service abuses and subsequently instituted
bipartisan reforms. Some civility has been imposed on the process.
Some professional concern for taxpayers' rights has been
acknowledged. And some simplicity in the forms may be on the way.
</P>
<P>
   It's still a painful thing to pay taxes, but we know we can't
legally avoid it.
</P>
<P>
   Taxes have already been reduced in recent years by presidential
and congressional initiatives focusing on ordinary folks. In 1997,
a new child tax credit was passed. Estate taxes have been reduced,
and breaks for education are in the works.
</P>
<P>
   The prosperous economy has also lifted most boats, and the boat
owners are not inclined to rock them. When Reagan popularized tax
cuts in 1980, inflation was in the double digits, unemployment was
high and the economy was in bad shape. That is not true now. It is
difficult to make a case that something as drastic as a major tax
cut that would primarily help the rich is required to keep
middle-class boats afloat.
</P>
<P>
   With his unerring instinct for pandering to the rich, House
Majority Leader Richard Armey, R-Texas, has produced a Web site
espousing the flat 17 percent income tax. He says Americans will be
better off ``if the (federal budget) surpluses were returned to
them rather than squandered by the federal government.'' Armey's
problem is that most Americans don't think spending for Social
Security, Medicare and essential public services is squandering.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the income tax will never be a dead issue. It is
only sleeping for the time being.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
