<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO-FRILLS CARDIAC LIFESAVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JANE E. BRODY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Tighe made history in November. While on an American
Airlines flight from Boston to Los Angeles with his wife, he
suffered a cardiac arrest. A previously healthy 62-year-old jogger
and public health officer in Boston, Tighe stopped breathing and
had no pulse or blood pressure. His heart was beating chaotically,
unable to send blood to his brain or other vital organs.
</P>
<P>
   But before his brain could die, a flight attendant, Kevin Dunn,
quickly started CPR (cardiopulmonary resuscitation) while another
attendant got the flight's first-aid kit. In it was a portable
defibrillator, a device placed on board just three days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn used the book-size automated external defibrillator, or
AED, to administer four electric shocks through palm-size paddles
to Tighe's heart to get its rhythm back on track.
</P>
<P>
   Then the plane made an emergency landing and Tighe, the first
person to have been saved by a defibrillator on a domestic airline,
was taken to a hospital for further treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Tighe is living proof of the value of this $3,000 device. His
rescue supports his own previous efforts to get portable
defibrillators in Boston's fire trucks, high-rises and shopping
malls, which resulted in an 8 percent increase in the city's
cardiac survival rate.
</P>
<P>
   As he told People magazine earlier this year, ``Defibrillators
should be as common as fire extinguishers.''
</P>
<P>
   His view is shared by a fast-growing number of health and safety
personnel around the country.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few months, for example, the five front-line patrol
cars in Denville, N.J., were equipped with AED's through donations
from the local American Legion post. Although they have not yet
saved any lives, Lieut. Rick McConnell, the patrol division
commander, said his officers were ``really gung-ho'' about their
new role as trained and equipped first-responders in a medical
emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Had such a device been readily available when the Cincinnati
Reds played their first home game of the 1996 season, John
McSherry, an umpire who suffered a fatal heart attack during the
game, might be alive today.
</P>
<P>
   So might two basketball stars who died of cardiac arrest: Hank
Gathers of Loyola Marymount University, who died during a game in
1990, and Reggie Lewis of the Boston Celtics, who died in 1993
while shooting baskets in a gym.
</P>
<P>
   Most people are at least aware of the value of CPR and millions
of people have been trained to use it when someone collapses with
no pulse or respiration.
</P>
<P>
   But few people, including those trained in CPR, realize that
this first-aid technique of manually pushing oxygenated blood
through the body buys only a few minutes when a person's heart is
beating erratically.
</P>
<P>
   For every minute that elapses after normal blood flow ceases,
the person's chances of survival diminish by 7 percent to 10
percent. After 10 minutes, there is little hope of survival,
especially of survival with an intact brain.
</P>
<P>
   For some 250,000 people a year in this country, death is the
outcome of a cardiac arrest, according to the American Heart
Association. Survival rates for people who suffer a cardiac arrest
outside of a hospital are now as low as 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Cantwell, a cardiologist in Atlanta and one of the team
doctors for the Atlanta Braves, said that many cardiac arrests
occurred in people with hearts too good to die.
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden, perhaps precipitated by intense emotional or
physical stress or, in the case of some athletes, by a sharp blow
to the chest or a hidden heart muscle disorder, the heart will
lapse into an erratic and useless rhythm called ventricular
fibrillation in the heart's main pumping chamber.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, underlying coronary artery disease is the cause,
Cantwell said. Or a heart may suddenly start beating much too fast,
a condition called ventricular tachycardia, and then lapse into
ventricular fibrillation. In other cases, a heart attack that is
caused by a complete blockage of a coronary artery will touch off
ventricular fibrillation.
</P>
<P>
   A heart in fibrillation will not revert to a normal rhythm on
its own, and the faster it can be shocked back into beating
normally, the better. Until about a decade ago, only hospitals and
highly sophisticated rescue vehicles had defibrillators, and in the
past they were not portable and only doctors were allowed to use
them.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the AED, weighing about four to seven pounds and
computerized to be idiot-proof. Anyone, even a child, can quickly
learn to operate one, since the device takes a reading of the
patient's cardiac status, tells the operator what to do each step
of the way (press a button or not) and is designed not to
administer a shock if one is not warranted; for example, if the
heart is not beating erratically.
</P>
<P>
   The goal now is to get defibrillators and people trained to use
them where they are most likely to be effective, especially in the
public places where people are at increased risk of cardiac arrest
or are distant from rapid emergency medical care.
</P>
<P>
   Cantwell would like to see the devices in health clubs and
fitness centers, high-rise residences, retirement communities,
centers for the elderly, large office buildings, airports and
airlines, cruise ships, golf courses, sports arenas and
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that by adding just a few pennies to the cost of a
ticket at an athletic event, every tier of a stadium could be
equipped with a defibrillator.
</P>
<P>
   In Rochester, Minn., after all the squad cars were given the
devices, survival after cardiac arrest jumped to 50 percent from 20
percent, according to a study by Dr. Roger White of the Mayo
Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Rodman Starke, executive vice president for science and
medicine at the heart association, said that in big cities like New
York or in tall buildings, it took too long to get emergency
personnel to the scene of a cardiac arrest. In many situations, the
defibrillators have to be on the premises to be truly useful.
</P>
<P>
   The heart association is hoping to begin an $18 million
federally financed study to determine the survival value of having
the device and people trained to use them in various locations. In
casinos in Las Vegan, Nev., where several cardiac arrests occur
nearly every day, survival rates sharply improved after the casinos
were equipped with portable defibrillators and the security guards
were trained to use them.
</P>
<P>
   There the response time is often less than a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Leonard A. Cobb, cardiologist at Harborview Medical Center
in Seattle, a leader in cardiac resuscitation, noted that since
``nearly three-quarters of cardiac arrests occur at home, it would
make sense to have a defibrillator in the home of someone with
known heart disease,'' like those who have had heart attacks,
angina attacks or coronary bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost of a portable defibrillator has dropped from $6,000
to $3,000, and I think it will drop further, which would make it
affordable for more people,'' Cobb said.
</P>
<P>
   Cobb published a report in The Journal of the American Medical
Association last week demonstrating a survival benefit when CPR was
administered for just 90 seconds before the defibrillator was
activated, especially if it took four or more minutes to get the
AED to the patient.
</P>
<P>
   But even in a city like Seattle, which has long been a leader in
emergency cardiac care, it often takes eight minutes for rescuers
with a defibrillator to reach a victim of cardiac arrest. Thus, the
best the study could demonstrate was a survival rate of 30 percent
when CPR preceded defibrillation.
</P>
<P>
   One obstacle to the installation of defibrillators for use by
nonmedical personnel has been the fear of liability if the device
is believed to have been misused.
</P>
<P>
   The heart association has been fighting for legislation that
would absolve ``good samaritans'' from such liability. So far, 31
states have granted limited immunity for lay responders, and
legislation to provide immunity nationwide will be introduced in
Congress soon.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the heart association, through its Heartsaver AED
program, is offering a new lifesaving course that includes
defibrillation training at community training centers through the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The four-hour course is available to emergency and rescue
personnel, security guards, airline personnel, family members of
heart patients and other lay rescuers. To locate one, contact the
American Heart Association at (800) AHA-USA1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 1751EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
