<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T PLAY WITH MY FOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Just years ago, I was a champion at the San
Francisco national sport of dining out. The goal is to find a great
restaurant before it's reviewed and the food ghouls arrive, all
ordering exactly the same things mentioned in the review.
</P>
<P>
   You have only two or three weeks to beat the critic to a
restaurant, but afterwards you can say you went there before it was
discovered, and quote culinary authority Yogi Berra.
</P>
<P>
   Now I've moved on to a higher level of foodiedom. I subscribe to
Saveur magazine (for the articles, not just the pictures) and cook
at home. One thing you can say for home: It isn't suddenly overrun
with strangers taking every table, making you eat at either 5:30
p.m or 10 p.m. in about three months.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to call a snotty ``reservationist'' either. We at
least got a snotty maitre d' in days gone by.
</P>
<P>
   I kicked the restaurant addiction when food writers began using
the word ``architectural,'' waiters began talking about serving
meat and fish on ``beds'' of whatever, and ``fusion'' became a
cuisine instead of a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   I don't want to put anything architectural in my mouth, nor live
in an edible building. The only food I like served on beds is
breakfast. With a few notable exceptions, fusion is a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   For twenty years, California chefs have been so creative and
innovative _ the big words _ that they've created innovative new
culinary cliches.
</P>
<P>
   The not-so-specials of every day include miso-glazed Chilean sea
bass and seared ahi with ginger-mango aioli and Thai salsa on beds
of fennel or lentils. The eyes miso-glaze over.
</P>
<P>
   The word ``ahi'' means ``required on any expensive menu,'' just
as ``salmon en croute'' did 25 years ago. The difference is that
the ahi is undercooked and the salmon was overcooked.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter of a century ago Calvin Trillin described the American
palace of high dining as ``La Maison de la Casa House, Continental
Cuisine,'' serving the cliches of those days he called
``Stuff-Stuff with Heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to meat or fish stuffed with other stuff, then
buried in a heavy sauce to ensure indisguishability of ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Now we dine at ``Le Bistro Asia d'Italia, Contemporary Fusion
Cuisine,'' and it specializes in ``With-With on a Bed of.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The following are a few dishes created by Bay Area chefs, as
described in menus and food pages: ``Pacific Rim jumbo prawn
resting on a strip of nori seaweed atop a tower of sushi rice with
black bean wasabi sauce.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind how the prawn rests. Where on the Pacific Rim was it
caught and how long ago?
</P>
<P>
   ``Napoleon of filet mignon layered with grilled red onions, a
portobello mushroom and baby carrots atop potatoes Anna with a
Cabernet demiglace.''
</P>
<P>
   Beef Wellington, defeated by beef Napoleon. But who's Anna?
``Garlic prawn and crispy tofu on a nest of carrots with basil-
chili glaze.''
</P>
<P>
   A nest? Is that a bed for those who eat like birds? ``Day-boat
scallops on a bed of sweet-corn flan.''
</P>
<P>
   What are these day-boat scallops on menus everywhere? Where I
come from, all scallop boats came back daily.
</P>
<P>
   &QC;  &QC;  How did we manage to live back in our iceberg salad days? We
actually ate mashed potatoes without roasted garlic in them, and
the potatoes were served next to the meat, not under it.
</P>
<P>
   We survived because kids will eat anything, just as our parents
would eat any Stuff-Stuff with Heavy. Cooking skipped a generation
in America, but some of us were lucky enough to have our
grandmothers in the house.
</P>
<P>
   My grandmothers were from Maine and I inherited a couple of
great ways to make beans (with onion or without) and the only way
to make lobster (steamed with drawn butter, and pay no attention to
French chefs).
</P>
<P>
   You can't live on beans and lobster alone, so my wife and I have
taken to pillaging other cultures' cooking. From one of our friends
we've picked up a family recipe for making greens with turnip,
onion and a bit of honey, and made it about 20 times this winter
just for the pot likker.
</P>
<P>
   We've struggled with the specific gravity of matzoh balls.
</P>
<P>
   We've experimented with every olive oil between extra-virgin,
cold-pressed picholine to 10W40. We even made Iowa food.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Saveur comes in. This is no cutesy Gourmet
magazine. Saveur is about real food from real places like Albia,
Iowa, Breaux Bridge, La., and North Beach, San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   If you missed having a cuisine as a kid, you can find all you
want in Saveur, with non-precious photographs. Photographers and
cooks are listed in the credits, and no ``food stylists.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the homemade egg noodles cooked in real beef broth and
served on mashed potatoes looked good. They were from a recipe by
an Iowa grandmother, so the potatoes weren't mashed with roasted
garlic.
</P>
<P>
   The noodles weren't served on a bed, but a La-Z-Boy of potatoes.
You wouldn't use the word ``architectural.'' You'd use the words
``splooshy'' and ``carby.''
</P>
<P>
   Like lobster, baked beans, greens or matzoh ball soup, it tasted
a lot better than it looked. That's the way food should be.
</P>
<P>
   When I'm cooking, that's the way you'll get it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
