<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5208 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-EPISODIC-HYPERTEN     04-12 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-EPISODIC-HYPERTENSION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN HIDDEN TRAUMA GROWS SERIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Conn., N.J.)  (The Science Times) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By HOLCOMB B. NOBLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Annette Bauman of Great Neck, N.Y., turned 50 and seemed in
perfect health _ no known ailments, no known emotional problems _
when she awoke in the night feeling extremely dizzy and deathly
ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's happening,'' she told her husband. Then,
within two hours, the sensation passed and she was fine. For a
while.
</P>
<P>
   In the next weeks, the illness struck again three times. Her
blood pressure soared during the attacks, her doctors said, though
they could not determine why. This episode of elevated blood
pressure put her in grave danger of suffering a heart attack or
stroke. But each episode passed, and her blood pressure and health
appeared to return to normal.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks, however, persisted. By 1993, seven years later, she
had seen a virtual army of doctors. Some suspected immediately that
she had a tumor called a pheochromacytoma, which develops in the
adrenal glands and also causes sudden, severe but short-term
hypertension and other similar symptoms. But she did not. She was
treated with a variety of standard hypertension medications but
nothing worked. Eventually the persistent, unpredictable attacks
forced her to give up her job as a piano teacher.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time as Mrs. Bauman's attacks were occurring, Dr.
Samuel Mann, an associate professor of clinical medicine at the
Hypertension Center of New York Hospital-Cornell Medical Center,
was seeing a string of similar cases: strange episodes of
unexplained and severe hypertension occurring sporadically during
periods of what appeared to be perfectly normal health.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Mann said, the cases were baffling, apparently
undiagnosable and untreatable. But then he began to see a pattern
emerge. He describes the finding, along with his view of its
significance, in the current issue of Archives of Internal
Medicine, in which he tells of 21 cases he has treated over the
last seven years.
</P>
<P>
   The arresting moment in his analysis of these episodes came for
him, he said, when two patients in a row arrived at his office with
almost identical medical histories. One he described as a
33-year-old man who had been hospitalized many times with
intermittent and inexplicable attacks similar to Mrs. Bauman's. As
with many others in the article, the man would also be hit with
pounding headaches, severe chest pains, neck pain, nausea and other
signs of serious illness.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Mann, the patient reported being in perfect
health between the attacks and insisted that he had had no
particular emotional stress in his life. But Mann said he
questioned further and the patient began to reveal that his father
had beaten him badly as a child. However, the patient had driven
the trauma out of his consciousness, and expressed a feeling of
strong love for his father, and no anger. The patient was referred
to a psychiatric counselor who diagnosed an anxiety disorder. He
was treated with an antidepressant, and the episodes ceased.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bauman finally crossed Mann's path when she was referred to
New York Hospital's Hypertension Center. After taking her medical
history, he suggested that she consider a psychological evaluation,
and she reacted angrily. ``I thought he was nuts!'' Mrs. Bauman
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Bauman eventually listened to Mann because nothing else
had worked. She saw a therapist, who she said helped her uncover a
troubling but suppressed side of her childhood. Mrs. Bauman said
she had received almost no emotional support from her parents and
had been allowed no emotional closeness. Concluding that this had
caused her deep if hidden stress, the therapist put her on an
anti-anxiety drug while continuing the hypertension medication.
Within months she was free of the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The conclusion Mann draws in the medical journal is that a link
exists between patients with episodic hypertension, also called
paroxysmal hypertension, and powerful emotions or traumatic
experiences that they are either unaware they had or that they have
driven out of their awareness. The signs of this condition, he
said, are the sudden episodes of severe blood-pressure elevation,
often accompanied by physical symptoms like dizziness, headaches,
chest pain and weakness, and finally the return of what appears to
be normal health. The common underlying element, he said, is a
hidden emotional problem and a denial of its existence.
</P>
<P>
   In 13 of the cases reported, the attacks ceased with a treatment
based on the finding that these hidden emotions were factors in the
disorder. In seven of the 13, the treatment combined traditional
hypertension therapy, like the use of alpha or beta blockers, with
an antidepressant. In three, the disorder was cured with talk
therapy alone, without antidepressants or anti-anxiety drugs.
</P>
<P>
   In two patients, treatment failed. For one of the remaining six,
attacks ceased before treatment was begun; another was intolerant
of medication; two died of unrelated causes before treatment could
be assessed and two refused treatment. Dr. William White, chief of
the section of hypertension and clinical pharmacology and a
professor of medicine at the University of Connecticut Medical
School at Farmington, who did earlier studies of hypertension, said
Mann's work was an important advance.
</P>
<P>
   White found correlations between open and obvious panic attacks
and episodic hypertension: In patients afflicted with panic attacks
or acute anxiety, he found episodes of severe blood-pressure
elevation, and, conversely, in studying episodic hypertension, he
found an increased incidence of panic attacks.
</P>
<P>
   White said the finding that hidden anxiety or depression could
be related to these episodes would be of great value to patients
whose doctors were unable to explain the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics on the number and nature of episodic hypertension
cases are not compiled, Mann said, and many doctors regard the
condition as rare. But Dr. Lawrence Krakoff, a professor of
medicine at Mount Sinai School of Medicine in New York, said that,
because it is so often unrecognized, it must be much more common
than thought. Krakoff says he sees three or four cases a year at
Englewood Hospital in New Jersey, where he is chief of medicine. He
estimates that 1 percent or 2 percent of the nation's 40 million
hypertensive patients, or 600,000, suffer episodes from hidden
emotional causes.
</P>
<P>
   Mann, author of ``Healing Hypertension: Uncovering the Secret
Power of Your Hidden Emotions'' (John Wiley &AMP; Sons), said
researchers tried for more than 40 years to prove a link between
ordinary, long-term hypertension and the distressful emotions that
patients were consciously aware of. But the evidence of such a
connection, he said, has been weak.
</P>
<P>
   He said that hidden emotions had a different effect, and that
they might play a role in as many as a quarter of patients with
ordinary hypertension, and those with the episodic form. Consider
the case of a 49-year-old woman whose uncontrollable hypertension
ceased overnight after she revealed that she had been raped at the
age of 14. This, she said, she had never told anyone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
