<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5210 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-FITNESS-FLOW-ART-     04-12 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FITNESS-FLOW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A `FLOW' TO FUEL THE RELUCTANT ATHLETE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., Ohio, N.Y., Ind.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By NANCY STEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For 28 years Bill Gaston, 41, has been running, and for 28 years
he has veered in and out of the ``zone,'' a state of heightened
attention in which exercise seems effortless and time passes
easily. During one recent 3,000-meter race, the long and lean
magazine editor re-entered that familiar territory: ``I grew
strong. I got a beautiful feeling of being in gear. I was
concentrating so much I felt like I was floating.'' Sighing, he
added, ``You live for these kinds of experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   What athletes call the zone, psychologists know as the less
flashy ``flow.'' Either way, this intensely pleasurable, almost
mystical, experience may be the key to helping those who loathe
physical activity learn to enjoy it, according to a group of
researchers in North America and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The experience of flow was first identified in the early 1970s
by Mihaly Csikszentmihalyi (pronounced chik-SENT-me-hi), a
psychologist at the University of Chicago. People can get absorbed
playing games, socializing at parties and working at creative jobs,
but they are especially prone to flow during physical activity,
according to Csikszentmihalyi's research.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get hooked on the sensation,'' said Dr. Jay C. Kimiecik,
an exercise psychology researcher at Miami University in Ohio.
Kimiecik contends that the possibility of flow helps motivate the
15 percent of Americans who exercise regularly to continue their
regimens. ``If more people could develop these positive feelings,
more people would work out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Flow is commonly reported by professional and Olympic-calibre
athletes, but information on ordinary workouts in gyms is scarce.
Dr. Bob Grove of the University of Western Australia, one of the
few researchers to study gym members, learned that some conditions
favor the experience. ``We found that more experienced circuit
trainers (with more than six months' involvement) reported more
flowlike experiences than less-experienced circuit trainers,'' said
Grove, of the department of human movement and exercise science.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that exercisers prone to flow were also
highly susceptible to being hypnotized. Overlapping features of the
flow and hypnotic states ``include dissociation/detachment from
one's surroundings, absorption, feelings of control, and perceptual
distortions such as altered perceptions of time,'' Grove said.
</P>
<P>
   For any exerciser, the stage for flow is set when the skill
level of the exerciser matches the challenge of the activity,
according to research by Dr. Sue A. Jackson, a sport psychology
lecturer at Queensland University of Technology in Australia and
co-author, with Csikszentmihalyi, of the book ``The Sports High''
(Human Kinetics).
</P>
<P>
   ``If a situation is too challenging, you become anxious,''
Kimiecik said. The tennis match against a much-better opponent, the
step routines that cannot be mastered, the too-long run _ all
create distress. Such uneasiness interferes with an exerciser's
ability to attain flow by breaking his or her concentration,
according to a recent study of adult competitive exercisers in the
Journal of Sport and Exercise Psychology.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, too little challenge creates boredom. And
even those who start out engaged may end up understimulated.
``People get better as they exercise, and then they lose the
feeling of challenge,'' Kimiecik said.
</P>
<P>
   For some people, entering competitions supplies the needed zest.
So can working out with a group, as Gaston does as president of the
Van Cortlandt Track Club in the Bronx. ``You can latch on to
someone and a certain group glide happens.''
</P>
<P>
   While not questioning the existence of flow, some sport
psychologists believe that pursuing the mental state is
unnecessary. They doubt that experiencing it motivates people to
exercise more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am completely unconvinced that attaining flow or some other
euphoric state during exercise will systematically enhance exercise
adherence or reduce the risk of drop-out,'' said Dr. Jack Raglin, a
sport psychologist at Indiana University. People quit because of a
change in schedule, time constraints, a nagging injury, the lack of
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Flow researchers would respond that people who enjoyed exercise
would surmount the barriers. They argue that it is more important
to focus on the process rather than the results of working out.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are told to exercise because they'll lose weight, lower
their risk of disease, and live longer,'' said Kimiecik. ``But
people aren't motivated by distant outcomes. More important is what
they're feeling at the moment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
