<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5212 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-SERVING-SIZE-ART-     04-12 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SERVING-SIZE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVOIDING CONFUSION ON SERVING SIZE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JANE E. BRODY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many Americans, upon seeing the number of servings of foods that
the Food Guide Pyramid suggests should be consumed each day, say,
``Impossible!'' Among typical responses to these recommendations
from the U.S. Departments of Agriculture and Health and Human
Services: ``If I ate that much, I'd turn into a blimp'' and ``I
can't possibly fit in all those grains and vegetables in the course
of a normal day.''
</P>
<P>
   But these and other objections mainly arise from a
misunderstanding of just how much _ or, rather, how little _ makes
up one serving of different foods and how easy it is to consume
half or more of the day's recommended allowances in just one meal.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are accustomed to big portions _ two to three times
the portion sizes eaten by the typical French citizen.
</P>
<P>
   The standardized serving sizes on packaged-food labels are not
necessarily the same as those in the food pyramid. For dry foods,
the serving sizes on the labels are determined by a certain number
of grams of the food. For liquid foods, the labels' serving sizes
are based on cups.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, two ounces of uncooked pasta (about 56 grams) is a serving
that when cooked is about one cup of spaghetti but up to two cups
of a large shaped pasta like rigatoni. Yet, according to the food
pyramid, a half-cup of cooked pasta is one serving and one cup
would be two servings of a grain-based food. Furthermore, a more
typical serving of pasta would be two cups, amounting to four
servings on the pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   For ready-to-eat cereals, serving sizes on labels are also based
on grams and range from a half-cup for granolas to two cups for
puffed cereals. But the pyramid considers one cup of a ready-to-eat
cereal a serving, which would match the serving size of a cereal
like Wheaties or Cheerios. For breads, a serving is about one
ounce, or one slice of standard packaged loaf. But a New York bagel
typically weighs about four ounces, or four servings of a grain
food. And a two-ounce hamburger bun is two servings. So it is all
too easy to consume six to 11 servings a day from the grain group.
</P>
<P>
   Nor should it be difficult to get in two to four servings of
fruit and three to five of vegetables, since a serving is only six
ounces of fruit or vegetable juice, one medium apple, a half-cup of
a cooked vegetable or one cup of a raw leafy vegetable.
</P>
<P>
   Note too that in the meat group, portion sizes of meat, poultry
and fish refer to cooked food. Since these foods lose moisture and
fat when cooked, they lose weight. A quarter-pound burger may be
only three ounces cooked, or one serving of meat. And a half pound
of fish may be only six ounces cooked, or two meat servings.
</P>
<P>
   Since the pyramid suggests a range of servings for each food
group, the number of servings you eat each day should be determined
by your ideal weight and activity level. The food pyramid is a
guide for an average-size moderately active adult, with the lower
number of servings in each group considered the minimum intake for
good health. While someone who is 5 feet tall and sedentary may be
able to consume only the minimum to maintain a normal body weight,
a marathoner 6 feet tall who runs 35 miles a week may need far more
than the maximum number of suggested servings.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the number of servings consumed, it is important
to eat foods from each group each day and to choose a variety of
foods from within each group to assure a reasonable balance of
essential nutrients.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 1758EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
