<SLUG> BC-SCI-LAUNDRY-ENZYME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ENZYME TO CHALLENGE ROGUE COLORS IN THE WASHER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (af)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joel Cherry is a scientist, but he is a bit of a drill sergeant
as well. In the boot camp that is his laboratory, he has been
whipping an enzyme into shape, preparing it for the rigors of that
domestic battlefield known as the washing machine.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to eliminate a common laundry-day disaster, when a
washerful of white clothes is forever tinted by one colored item
that, like a rogue agent, has infiltrated the load.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a scourge to all humanity,'' said Cherry, a researcher
for the Danish drug and enzyme producer Novo Nordisk. ``Everybody's
done it at least once.''
</P>
<P>
   The enzyme, an iron-containing peroxidase found in an ink cap
mushroom, Coprinus cinereus, appears to be a handy solution for
neutralizing such mistakes. It catalyzes a peroxide reaction that
removes the color from dyes. But it only works on dyes that have
leached into the wash water; fabrics themselves are left alone. So
the color from an errant sock, say, would not harm the rest of the
load.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the enzyme in its natural state is hardly
tough enough for the job.
</P>
<P>
   It is content to help the mushroom decompose a stump or log in
the relatively benign environment of a forest. A washing machine,
with its hot soapy water, presents far harsher conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Working at a Novo lab in Davis, Calif., Cherry and his
colleagues used a technique known as directed evolution to modify
the enzyme so that it could tolerate higher temperatures and the
alkaline and oxidative conditions created by detergents. He and the
others described their work in the current issue of the journal
Nature Biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   With the technique, mutations are created in the gene that is
responsible for the production of the enzyme. Mutations that alter
the enzyme's amino acid chain and result in improved performance
are saved; those that are harmful are discarded. The good mutations
are then ``shuffled'' _ recombined genetically, in this case in
yeast cells _ to find combinations that perform even better.
</P>
<P>
   The technique, Cherry said, ``allows you to separate the good
from the bad in a very empirical way; by taking a whole pool of
good mutants, you can enrich for the good mutations.''
</P>
<P>
   Without directed evolution, he said, a basic principle of
genetics, known as Muller's ratchet, takes over.
</P>
<P>
   It holds that in nature, mutations go from bad to worse: harmful
ones are accumulated at a greater rate than beneficial ones.
</P>
<P>
   Cherry and his colleagues created the mutations both randomly
and in a more rational way, by examining the structure of the
enzyme for vulnerable areas. In particular, they looked at the heme
group, which contains the iron atom that is essential for the
decolorizing reaction.
</P>
<P>
   They designed three mutations to remove oxidizable residues
around the group, improving the enzyme's ability to stand up to the
peroxides in the wash water. A fourth mutation was designed to help
the enzyme tolerate higher temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   When this mutated gene is shuffled with the beneficial mutations
produced randomly, the result is an enzyme that can withstand water
temperatures over 120 degrees Fahrenheit, as well as high pH and
peroxide levels. It is ready for the washing machine.
</P>
<P>
   Novo hopes to see it in detergents soon. In the meantime,
though, the directed evolution technique holds promise for custom
tailoring other enzymes, said Willem Dr. P.C. Stemmer, co-author of
an analysis of the Novo work in the same issue of Nature
Biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   Directed evolution, Stemmer said, ``is a way to improve very
complex systems without knowing much detail.'' And the improvements
that are possible could result in the greater use of tailored
enzymes, rather than chemicals, as catalysts in industry. Such
chemistry would be ``greener,'' producing fewer waste products.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways it might also be simpler. Rather than a series of
reactions occurring in steps, an industrial process could more
resemble what goes on in a living cell, where many reactions
proceed at the same time, without the formation of unwanted waste,
because there are so many enzymes with quite specific functions.
</P>
<P>
   Stemmer foresees a day when the full set of reactions in an
industrial process could take place in one vessel. A more elaborate
version, perhaps, of a washing machine with Cherry's enzyme
swirling around inside.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
