<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO TEST SCORES ARE UP, BUT WHY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIAN GUTHRIE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco public schools have astounded
educators nationwide by posting six years of consecutive test score
gains.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers from here to New York have gushed over the urban
district's rare winning streak. Schools chief Bill Rojas, credited
for the gains, was named by colleagues administrator of the year.
</P>
<P>
   But an Examiner analysis of tests shows that behind the vaunted
success is an eye-opening district practice: While student
enrollment remains flat, test results from fewer students are being
reported each year, raising questions about whether the gains are
real or manipulated.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in the past decade, the number of student math scores
reported declined by 12 percent, and the number of reading scores
reported plunged 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``In San Francisco, I don't know if big increases in test scores
are from class size reduction or certain pupils being removed from
the testing base,'' said Stanford education Professor Michael
Kirst, who is conducting a statewide study on the impact of class
size cuts.
</P>
<P>
   When Rojas was hired as superintendent in 1992, test scores were
low and languishing.
</P>
<P>
   By 1993, however, scores began a turnaround, and have since
surpassed the national averages in reading and math. The district,
the fifth largest in California, is the only major urban school
system in America to post such steady improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Rojas, who exudes a mix of compassion and egoism, credits the
gains to reforms made between 1993 and 1998, including smaller
classes, better teacher training and increased instructional time
in middle school.
</P>
<P>
   But as scores were rising, two less-publicized changes were
happening in the district.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in 1994, more than 5,000 kids who speak little if any
English _ and typically underperform their English-fluent peers _
were excluded by Rojas from testing. At the same time, Chinese
American students, who typically do well on exams, became the
dominant ethnic group in the district.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you take away a group of kids who are limited in their
ability to speak English, do you have any doubt what the effect
will be on mean scores?'' asked University of California at
Berkeley education professor and statistician Paul Holland. ``In
San Francisco, where kids are being removed from the testing base,
you don't know whether gains are from ethnic changes, a forceful
superintendent or school reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Holland, who worked at the private Princeton, N.J.-based testing
company, Educational Testing Service, for 18 years, said, ``When
you include and exclude students, data are unreliable.''
</P>
<P>
   Until 1994, San Francisco public schools tested children who
spoke limited English after they had been in school for one year.
</P>
<P>
   Rojas changed the policy to test those kids _ who make up 30
percent of the student population here _ after at least three years
of instruction.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is nothing illegal or unethical about excusing
children who lack English skills from taking English-only exams, it
puts San Francisco at odds with other school districts nationwide
that are increasingly testing more rather than fewer students.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Smith, U.S. deputy secretary for Education, said his
agency urges schools to include as many children as possible in the
National Assessment for Educational Progress exam, given every few
years to a sampling of students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Districts should be trying to test and report scores for all
but the most severely disabled kids,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What is questionable, educators and statisticians say, is for
San Francisco to claim consecutive achievement gains without
acknowledging the gains began when a large segment of the
lowest-performing kids were taken out.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco is cooking the scores by excluding all the hard
cases,'' said former San Francisco schools chief Ramon Cortines,
Rojas' predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   UC-Berkeley education Professor Bruce Fuller, co-director of
Policy Analysis for California Education, said there is another
ambiguity in determining whether San Francisco's gains are from
school reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sample of kids in San Francisco is getting increasingly
Asian American and less African American, which means the
concentration of high performers is going up,'' Fuller said.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1987 and 1998, Chinese American enrollment increased by
nearly 5 percent, while black enrollment declined by nearly 4
percent. Fifty percent of all students in the district are now
Asian American; 28 percent of the district is Chinese American.
</P>
<P>
   On the district exam, the Comprehensive Test of Basic Skills,
Asian Americans score significantly higher than students of other
ethnic and racial groups. African Americans score the lowest.
</P>
<P>
   The district defends its practices.
</P>
<P>
   Rojas insists it is a waste of student time and taxpayer money
to test students in a language they don't understand, justifying
his 1994 policy that has now excluded some 6,000 kids from taking
the district exam.
</P>
<P>
   However, he does acknowledge that ``exempting limited-English
proficient students from taking the CTBS test in all likelihood
means that our test score growth is higher than if (such) students
had been included in testing.''
</P>
<P>
   But he says real gains in student achievement are evident in a
variety of other measurements besides test scores.
</P>
<P>
   Since Rojas' arrival in the district, the percentage of San
Francisco students who complete high school has risen 2.3
percentage points to 89.4 percent, well above the state's rate of
83.1 percent. The number of San Francisco students taking exams to
enter college-prep Advanced Placement classes has nearly doubled
since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   While those measures indicate that more city students are
preparing for college, another key indicator of skills is less
promising.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco students' scores on the SAT, the college entrance
exam, lag far behind the state and national average. In 1998, the
San Francisco average for math and verbal scores combined was 968,
compared with 1013 statewide and 1017 nationally. Moreover, the
average math score on the SAT for San Francisco students fell 5
points last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
