<HEADER>
A5229 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PONSOT-POETRY-ART-2TA     04-12 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PONSOT-POETRY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECOGNITION AT LAST FOR POET OF ELEGANT COMPLEXITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ She is 77. She has raised seven children, mostly on
her own. She has published only four books of poetry in a lifetime.
But last month Marie Ponsot won one of the United States' most
prestigious literary prizes, the National Book Critics Circle
Award, for her latest collection, ``The Bird Catcher.''
</P>
<P>
   A Marie Ponsot poem is a little like a jeweled bracelet,
carefully carved, with small, firm stones embedded in it. Her
subjects are domestic life, friendship, marriage and sometimes
swimming.
</P>
<P>
   She was described in The San Francisco Chronicle as ``one of the
most elegant, intelligent poets around.'' A writer for The New
Yorker said: ``The poems reveal the moral drama enacted just
beneath the surfaces of the natural world. Ponsot attends to
elegant forms without losing sight of what they are there to
express.'' Still, Ms. Ponsot's work is little known outside the
world of poetry.
</P>
<P>
   Her poems ``are meant to be beautiful,'' Ms. Ponsot said last
week in her small apartment in Manhattan. ``That's a very
unfashionable thing to say. So unfashionable. Transgressive.''
</P>
<P>
   She is a small, tough, soft-voiced woman who swims in her
building's pool every day. Her apartment is a little dusty and
filled with piles of books, plants, photographs of her children, 14
grandchildren and step-grandchildren. ``I don't have a strong
nesting instinct,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ponsot's poems can be lyrical, as in ``The Story After the
Story,'' from ``The Bird Catcher'' (Alfred A. Knopf), about putting
her seven children to sleep at night:
</P>
<P>
   ``... bed-ready boys. I crib them, warm in their
</P>
<P>
   soft shirts, &AMP; sit to eat a bruised sweet apple
</P>
<P>
   as I nurse Chris and float on mild air ...''
</P>
<P>
   But they can also be tough, as in ``I've Been Around: It Gets Me
Nowhere'':
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the woman always too young to be
</P>
<P>
   holding the diamond the baby exulting.
</P>
<P>
   I am the worker afraid of the rules &AMP; the boss; my
</P>
<P>
   salary heats the house where I feed many children.''
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes they are very harsh. For example, in ``One Is
One'':
</P>
<P>
   ``Heart, you bully, you punk, I'm wrecked, I'm shocked
</P>
<P>
   stiff. You? you still try to rule the world _ though
</P>
<P>
   I've got you: identified, starving, locked
</P>
<P>
   in a cage you will not leave alive ...''
</P>
<P>
   What the poems have in common is verbal precision and
syntactical complexity. They are full of carefully thought-out
rhetorical strategies. She sometimes uses an ampersand to link
words, for instance, instead of ``and,'' creating a short beat
rather than a full beat between words. Ms. Ponsot is fond of
villanelles, sestinas and even tritinas. But more about that later.
</P>
<P>
   Recognition has taken so long to come, a reporter notes, that
the question is unavoidable: If Ms. Ponsot wanted to be a poet, why
did she have seven children? ``Because I loved it,'' she said
firmly, about having her children. No anger here, no sense of time
lost or wasted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had a strong desire to publish a book,'' she said. ``I
had a strong desire to write poems.'' She added: ``I see now that
was queer. I didn't realize that is a big part of what a poet has
to do. I was too busy to sit around and think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ponsot was born in Queens, to a family that relished
language. Her father was a partner in a company that imported wines
for a select list of wealthy New York families. ``He was a servant
of the rich,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother was a schoolteacher. Her grandmother kept scrapbooks
filled with poems she liked. She had a poem for everything, Ms.
Ponsot said. When sunset came, her grandmother would recite
Tennyson's ``Crossing the Bar.'' Ms. Ponsot still knows it by
heart:
</P>
<P>
   ``Sunset and evening star,
</P>
<P>
   And one clear call for me!
</P>
<P>
   And may there be no moaning of the bar
</P>
<P>
   When I put out to sea.''
</P>
<P>
   While she was still a child Ms. Ponsot began having poems
published in The Brooklyn Eagle.
</P>
<P>
   The family was Catholic, and Ms. Ponsot still considers herself
a Catholic. ``I still announce myself because I want to be in
people's face about it,'' she said. ``It's sort of like a club you
can't resign from, but anyone can get in.''
</P>
<P>
   She graduated from St. Joseph's College for Women in Brooklyn
and received a master's degree in 17th-century literature from
Columbia University. Soon after World War II she went to Paris.
</P>
<P>
   One of her fellow passengers on the boat was the poet and
publisher Lawrence Ferlinghetti, who became a friend. When he
started City Lights Books in San Francisco, he published Ms.
Ponsot's first collection, ``True Minds,'' in 1957. But the book
was overshadowed by Allen Ginsberg's ``Howl,'' which Ferlinghetti
had published just before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mine disappeared without a trace,'' Ms. Ponsot said. ``Anybody
who bought `Howl' would not be interested in what I was writing.''
</P>
<P>
   In Paris she met Claude Ponsot, a French painter. ``We picked
each other up in a bar,'' she said. They married and lived in Paris
for three years. Ms. Ponsot said she had not intended to get
pregnant, but after her oldest child, Monique, was born in 1951,
she knew she loved having babies. Monique was followed by six
brothers.
</P>
<P>
   While rearing her children, she translated some 37 books from
French to English, including the ``Fables and Tales of La
Fontaine.'' She also wrote radio and television scripts, though she
didn't own a television set. ``I worked late at night when the
children had gone to bed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband were divorced in 1970, she said, after which
she continued to write while raising her children.
</P>
<P>
   ``People would say, `Poor thing.' I would say, `Yesss!''' she
said, making two fists with her hands. ``The kindest thing he ever
did was to leave,'' she said of her husband.
</P>
<P>
   It took 24 years for her to publish her second poetry
collection. She was an English professor at Queens College by now,
and a friend, the poet Marilyn Hacker, had heard that Knopf was
publishing a new poetry series. Knopf accepted her poems and
published ``Admit Impediment'' in 1981. Her third collection, ``The
Green Dark,'' was published by Knopf in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991 Ms. Ponsot retired from the college and turned full time
to writing. A poet, she said, should write with ``the press of the
whole language coming to bear to say something you didn't know.''
Still, she rewrites her poems ``hundreds of times.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For her, difficult forms like the villanelle, the sestina and
the tritina, enable the poet to achieve more than if he or she were
just free-associating.
</P>
<P>
   Her poem ``Roundstone Cove'' is a tritina, a poem consisting of
three stanzas, each with three lines. Each line ends in one of a
set of three words, but in each stanza the end words are in a
different order. There is an additional line at the conclusion of
the poem that contains all the end words. In ``Roundstone Cove,''
the three end words are ``fog,'' ``-hood'' and ``sun'':
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind rises. The sea snarls in the fog
</P>
<P>
   far from the attentive beaches of childhood _
</P>
<P>
   no picnic, no striped chairs, no sand, no sun.
</P>
<P>
   Here even by day cliffs obstruct the sun;
</P>
<P>
   moonlight miles out mocks this abyss of fog.
</P>
<P>
   I walk big-bellied, lost in motherhood,
</P>
<P>
   hunched in a shell of coat, a blindered hood.
</P>
<P>
   Alone a long time, I remember sun _
</P>
<P>
   poor magic effort to undo the fog.
</P>
<P>
   Fog hoods me. But the hood of fog is sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Difficult, but it's worth it, said Ms. Ponsot, because ``in the
process of turning your brain around, you find something you didn't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Poetic forms like the tritina are ``instruments of discovery,''
she said. ``The forms create an almost bodily pleasure in the poet.
What you're doing is trying to discover. They are not restrictive.
They pull things out of you. They help you remember.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
