<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, April 13, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Brisk winds from the north will transport chilly, moist air from
the Canadian Maritimes into central and northern New England.
Cloudy skies along with a few flurries are expected in the higher
terrain of Maine. On the coast, sunshine will dominate.
</P>
<P>
   A ridge of high pressure stretching from the Great Lakes to the
eastern Gulf Coast will promote dry and seasonable conditions
across the nation east of the Mississippi River. Ample sunshine
will boost temperatures from very cool readings Monday morning in
the Southeast. Florida will stay sunny with an active breeze.
</P>
<P>
   The storm that brought record rainfall to southern California
last weekend will move through New Mexico Tuesday. Heavy snow is
likely in the Sangre De Cristo mountains and along the Front Range.
Snow showers will linger over the higher terrain near the Four
Corners. Gusty showers and scattered thunderstorms will progress
eastward across the valleys of southern Arizona and New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   A chill rain will soak sections of eastern Colorado, Kansas and
Oklahoma. Showers will develop in Texas and western Louisiana and
Arkansas. A few strong thunderstorms may rumble into west Texas.
Cooler air will follow a front in the Dakotas, but only some clouds
will attend the front.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure building near Vancouver, British Columbia, will
sponsor much more pleasant conditions with abundant sunshine in the
West. Offshore winds will direct dry air to the Pacific coast.
Readings will rise well above seasonal levels from the southern
Cascades to the Central Valley. The Southwest will see fewer clouds
as mild air returns.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Fire Danger
</P>
<P>
   The risk of wildfires has returned to Florida. Last June, the
Florida landscape, which had been waterlogged by recurrent rains
during the winter of 1997-98, withered under relentless spring sun,
setting the stage for wildfires. This spring, little rain has
fallen across the peninsula and sunshine has been plentiful as a
warm ridge of high pressure has held steady several thousand feet
above the ground. As a result, the landscape is tinder dry. On
Monday, in the wake of a cool front, dry breezes spread across the
state, accelerating evaporation rates and heightening the risk of
fires.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
