<HEADER>
A5237 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACKCOLLEGE-REUNION-     04-12 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKCOLLEGE-REUNION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Black College Reunion ends amid violence
 &HT;    By Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ If Daytona Beach can serve as any kind of
guide, Atlanta can look forward to a quieter Freaknik this year _
at least until the final hours.
</P>
<P>
   After coasting through a weekend of relative calm, with few
arrests and the occasional gridlock, Black College Reunion exploded
here early Sunday morning with two shootings _ one of them fatal _
and at least two stabbings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last night is always the worst,'' said Bobby Geter, on his
way back to Ohio. ``When you have all that alcohol mixed with women
not wearing much clothes, you get a volatile mix.''
</P>
<P>
   Vada York, a graduate student at the University of South
Carolina, said the problems she saw late at the BCR here were no
different than what she has seen by attending the last two
Freakniks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens is that people come to these things expecting
something to happen,'' said York, a native of Sumter, S.C. ``When
nothing happens, they get anxious and try to force the issue. That
is when you get fights, women getting attacked, people getting
shot. It's crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Monica White, a sociologist at Bethune-Cookman College who
specializes in group dynamics, said a number of contributing
factors can lead to sudden violence, including drugs and alcohol,
hot weather, sexual innuendo and machismo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer the weekend goes, the more people come and those
are more people doing nothing. That whole climate leads to people
doing things they don't normally do,'' said White. ``I would also
venture to say that most of these people are not college
students.''
</P>
<P>
   Police said an argument over a spilled drink led to the shooting
death of 28-year-old Craig Grover, of Jacksonville, who, along with
Ansie Pierre, 24, were shot at around 4 a.m. Sunday morning. The
two did not know each other and were not college students.
</P>
<P>
   But while trying not to downplay the weekend's shootings and
stabbings, local officials contend this year's event went
relatively smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a really good crowd,'' said Sherri Davis of the Daytona
Police Department. ``When you have as many people as we had trying
to get into such a small space, two shootings and a stabbing aren't
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Halifax Medical Center spokesperson Kate Holcomb said Pierre
remained in serious condition in the hospital's injury intensive
care unit.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Sunday morning shooting, BCR had been rather calm as
a heavy police presence minimized traffic gridlock and the area's
wide open spaces gave everyone room to cruise either on the beach
or Atlantic Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of BCR's more vocal opponents admitted that this
year's event had a gentler tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt the behavior was better this time,'' said Frank
Heckman, president of the Beachside Neighborhood Watch, an
association of more than 1,200 residents. ``The shootings and
stabbings were domestic violence. People fighting over boyfriends.
This will happen anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said while more than 100,000 people showed up for BCR this
year, there were only about 330 arrests, including 19 arrests for
carrying guns and only 44 arrests involving college students. About
1,100 traffic tickets were given out.
</P>
<P>
   ``These types of events give college students a bad rap,'' said
Clarence Childs, vice president of Bethune-Cookman College, where
BCR was born 15 years ago. ``I think the college students feel they
have much more at stake. They have futures and they don't want to
jeopardize it by doing something stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   That has also been one of the lingering concerns about Freaknik
in Atlanta. Although it is designed for college students, Freaknik
_ officially known as Black College Spring Break _ attracts mostly
locals and people who aren't in college.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the weekend, Daytona Beach Mayor Bud Asher and City
Manager Carey Smith walked the streets talking and getting their
pictures taken with students, at times even helping to direct
traffic. At about 2:30 a.m. Sunday, right after a rap concert had
been shut down because of on-stage obscenities, nudity and
lewdness, Asher was cautiously optimistic about the weekend's final
hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it stays like this, we will be happy campers, because we
haven't had any major public safety fiascoes,'' Asher said at the
time. ``But we still have a few hours left.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Asher was speaking from experience. At the 1998 BCR
here, police shot and killed a man who had opened fire on them on
the final day of the event.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's Freaknik, which by the final Sunday had spilled onto
Auburn Avenue for the Sweet Auburn Festival, saw increased
incidents of violence toward women, who were chased by young men,
stripped of their clothes and fondled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at Freaknik last year and the longer it went, the worse
it got,'' said Joyce Early, who was sunbathing with York Monday
afternoon. ``I remember I had on a pair of sweats and these guys
tried to rush me. We were (at Woodruff Park) in bright daylight.
They won't see me this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Suggs writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
