<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5238 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-PARTIES-0413-c     04-12 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PARTIES-0413-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WAR DOESN'T STOP POLITICAL FUND-RAISING
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington category and (p) national political
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation is at war in the Balkans, but that has
not diverted top politicians from returning to business-as-usual,
including the ever intensifying hunt for cash.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton goes back on the fund-raising trail Friday,
passing the hat for Democrats in Detroit and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was an initial feeling that it was not
appropriate in the very beginning,'' presidential political adviser
Ann Lewis said Monday. ``But once it's clear that we are in this,
and -- as the president has said -- we're going to continue this,
then we go back to his regular schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of his regular schedule, as a leader of his party, is to
help party committees raise funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's Detroit and Boston appearances this week are joint
Senate-House campaign committee fund-raisers. They will follow a
trip to San Francisco, where Clinton is to address a convention of
the American Society of Newspaper Editors on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The trip is part of the effort by the White House to provide an
appearance of normalcy in which the president is deliberately
indicating he is not consumed by the Kosovo crisis. On Saturday,
Clinton talked about welfare reform in his regular radio address.
He also has an economic address planned for Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   However the fund-raising travel drew criticism Monday from
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think Bill Clinton would be spending his time figuring
out what he wants to do in Kosovo, how it is he wants to to do it
and why and when, instead of having his hand out to fat cat
contributors,'' said Mike Collins, spokesman for the Republican
National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Republican National Chairman Jim Nicholson criticized
Clinton for planning a three-state fund-raising trip that was to
have begun March 25, the day after the bombing campaign started in
the Balkans. The White House canceled that trip.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton won't be alone in looking for cash this week. With
Congress returning from a two-week break, members will resume their
efforts to fill campaign chests. Among them, more than a dozen
House Republicans will host receptions, breakfasts and other
events.
</P>
<P>
   Collins defended lawmakers for their fund-raising-as-usual.
``Congressional Republicans are not the commander-in-chief of the
armed forces of a country at war,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether it was appropriate for lawmakers to have recessed
just as the conflict began, Collins said Congress had a
``previously scheduled work period'' and that the president could
have asked them to return to work.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Collins said, ``It's important that the Congress get
the views of the American people'' on the war over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
