<DOCNO> NYT19990412.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5239 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     04-12 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV14-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE THE WORK OUT OF PICKING A JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Wednesday, April 14)  
(mk 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes, usually after forgetting to take her medication, a
teacher will invite me to school to give career advice to her
journalism students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be a plumber,'' is what I always tell them.
</P>
<P>
   But now, after reading the ``Jobs Rated Almanac,'' it turns out
that I've been giving these impressionable young people bad advice.
</P>
<P>
   I should have been telling them to be an undertaker, a janitor,
a piano tuner or, if they really want to shoot high, a foot doctor.
</P>
<P>
   According to the almanac, which rated the 250 best and worst
jobs in the country, plumbers actually have lousier jobs (210th on
the list) than newspaper reporters (176th).
</P>
<P>
   Using statistics from the U.S. Department of Labor, the census,
professional organizations and telephone surveys, author Les Krantz
ranked the jobs according to these variables: income, stress,
physical demands, potential growth, job security, work environment
and number of frisky interns cavorting about the office.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I'm making that last part up, which could explain why
the job of president of the United States was ranked 229th on the
list. (The reasons the author gives for the low ranking include no
room for job growth, lots of stress and a stagnant salary. No
mention of angry first ladies hurling ashtrays at your head, but
presumably that is a drawback, too.)
</P>
<P>
   The best job in the United States, according to the almanac, is
Web site manager, possibly for the reason that few people have the
slightest idea what a Web site manager is or does. (How much
management does a Web site need anyway? Are some quiet and
industrious while others spend all day talking about baseball and
making personal phone calls? Would you be able to distinguish one
from the other?) With nothing to do and no one confident enough to
tell him or her to do it, Web site managers have lots of free time
to nap and play computer solitaire, interrupted only by loud thumps
announcing the arrival of the next fat paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   The next best job you can have is that of actuary. This is
someone who is paid upwards of $100,000 a year for sitting in a
posh office dreaming up new ways to cancel my car and homeowner's
insurance. (A couple of years ago someone rear-ended my wife's car
while she was stopped at a red light. A few months later, someone
broke into her car and stole her radio. A few months after that she
showed the incredibly bad judgment of allowing someone to plow into
her parked car while she was inside our house eating breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   (I've been told that an actuary actually pulled a hamstring in
his mad rush to cancel my wife's car insurance. The insurance
industry is even more competitive these days, of course, to the
point that irresponsible breakfast-eaters like my wife would not
only have their insurance canceled but would also be arrested,
fined and beaten with rubber truncheons.)
</P>
<P>
   The worst job you can have, even worse than a newspaper reporter
or plumber or sewage plant operator (163rd on the list; one better
than the job of teacher), is that of an oil field roustabout. This
is bad news for parents like me who try to scare their kids into
getting better grades by telling them they're headed for a career
as a french fry cook at McDonald's. According to the almanac, cooks
rank No. 172, four places better than a newspaper reporter and 78
places better than an oilfield roustabout, which is a cool-sounding
job but is probably dirty and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   (``Get those grades up, young man, or you're going to be writing
newspaper columns in the middle of the stinking desert with oil
shooting up your nose! And no interns, either!'')
</P>
<P>
   Other jobs you want to deter your kid from going after include
major league baseball player (No. 202), NBA basketball player (No.
205) and NFL football player (No. 211). These low rankings come
despite the fact that the average salary of a professional baseball
or basketball player is over $1.4 million. Perhaps the stress and
physical demands of carrying around that much money make these jobs
undesirable, I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton will want to get into a better line of work
when he leaves office so he might consider becoming a parole
officer (No. 12) or a dental hygienist (No. 22).
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, he could be a Web site manager who cleans teeth in
his spare time and on weekends dreams up new ways to cancel my
wife's car insurance.
</P>
<P>
   That would be sweet.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 1818EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
