<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5244 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBBINS-ARCHIVES-ART-     04-12 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBBINS-ARCHIVES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVING THE HUMAN DETAILS OF JEROME ROBBINS' ART 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The studio where Jerome Robbins danced out his ideas before
rehearsals was filled with packing boxes. Posters, photographs and
costume and set sketches were propped up against the pristine white
walls and wall-length mirror in this top-floor room of Robbins'
handsome, austere Upper East Side town house.
</P>
<P>
   The air resonated with murmurs of ``Oh, look at this!'' one
recent afternoon as artifacts of Robbins' work and life were
examined and tagged for delivery to a new destination.
</P>
<P>
   The choreographer, who died last year, bequeathed his personal
archives to the New York Public Library for the Performing Arts and
its dance collection, one of the world's major research collections
on dance. The announcement of the gift was made Monday by the
library's president, Dr. Paul LeClerc, at ``Broadway Celebrates
Jerome Robbins,'' a tribute at the Majestic Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins, whom LeClerc described as ``one of the best friends''
of the library, helped the dance collection establish its huge film
and video archive in 1964 with an endowment supported by a
percentage of his royalties from the Broadway musical ``Fiddler on
the Roof.''
</P>
<P>
   With this new Jerome Robbins Collection, the library has
acquired more than 100 boxes of materials and more than 30 file
drawers filled with business papers pertaining to his shows and
ballets, all neatly labeled with titles as dry as ``shows'' and
``contracts'' and as tantalizingly mysterious as ``Exception and
the Rule'' and ``The Misha Project.'' ``Fiddler'' alone has 54
folders. An additional gift of related materials has been made by
Dr. Daniel Stern, a friend of Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   ``This collection will be a reminder of the broad scope of
Robbins' remarkable abilities,'' said Madeleine Nichols, curator of
the dance collection. ``We forget that. Any collection does that.
But Robbins was one of the major creators of our century.''
</P>
<P>
   She estimates that it will take at least two years to catalog
the material, although researchers will be able to use materials as
they become available. Part of the collection, 24 volumes of
journals with entries from 1971 to 1982, will not be available to
the public for 13 to 15 years, as stipulated in Robbins' will.
</P>
<P>
   Such personal collections provide what LeClerc calls ``the most
direct, reliable and precise kinds of insight into the individual
artist's creative process.'' Even a cursory look during the packing
yielded immediate insights into the character, life and thought of
that famously private man.
</P>
<P>
   Jostling for space with framed costume sketches from ``West Side
Story'' and a photograph of Robbins as a slightly wary-looking
toddler on a tricycle, blown up as an undated birthday tribute
signed by theater and society friends, was a sketchbook whose odd
drawings yielded a gold mine of poignantly suggestive information.
</P>
<P>
   Notes in pencil and ink, written in a meticulous, cramped hand,
lined the back of two sketch pages dated October 1969 and labeled
``Goldberg Variations _ Aria.'' ``The Goldberg Variations'' was
created for the New York City Ballet, where Robbins was for many
years a resident choreographer, and was first performed in 1971.
``These drawings were done while leg was in cast with ruptured
Achilles tendon _ couldn't dance or search or demonstrate,''
Robbins wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The next paragraph is addressed to Bob, presumably the City
Ballet musical director, Robert Irving: ``These aren't choreography
_ or floor patterns _ just doodles to help me feel out or parse out
my own impulses to the music because I can't get up and do them
myself. The final dance will contain some of the essences of what
they mean to me _ but I doubt if they'd make any sense to anyone
else. Also _ the dance will (italics)never(end italics) have the
harshness of these line drawings.''
</P>
<P>
   There are amusing notes from two of Robbins' musical-theater
colleagues. After a trip to England in 1967 to fine-tune a London
production of ``Fiddler,'' the composer Jerry Bock reassures
Robbins that ``the show, over all, is in damn good shape ... and
they all seem happy to have some American Jews kvetching.''
</P>
<P>
   An inexpert oil portrait of Robbins by Irving Berlin in 1982 is
explained by the letter accompanying it. ``I started painting but
quickly discovered that as a painter I was still a pretty good
songwriter,'' Berlin writes. ``Occasionally, I wind up with a face
that resembles one of my friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins seems to have started saving everything for posterity
early in his career. One letter reveals an unexpected degree of
hero worship. ``This is a big fan letter and it is really just part
of a continuity of enormous admiration I've had for you and your
work spanning the years from `Flying Down to Rio' to today,''
Robbins wrote to Fred Astaire on June 20, 1974, in a letter
distilled from four carefully edited drafts, all filed with the
finished product and with Astaire's polite, considerably shorter
response.
</P>
<P>
   Writing just after he had seen ``Follow the Fleet'' and
``Carefree,'' Robbins continues: ``I haven't had such a fine time
at the movies in ages. The pure artistry, the sense of delight and
exhilaration, plus the true thrilling quality of your work has
lifted me up on a beautiful high for days. But even more was the
confirmation of something I've always felt, and that is how
(italics)deeply(end italics) influential and inspiring to my own
career and work you have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins ends by thanking Astaire, somewhat shyly, on behalf of
himself and ``the millions of us all over the world'' for ``the
beautiful gift of joy, the belief that living is lovely and that
man is good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 1820EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
