<DOCNO> NYT19990412.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5251 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-WOHLERS-CO     04-12 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-WOHLERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wohlers ready to move on
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The decision was not made lightly. Mark Wohlers is
leaving the only baseball organization he has ever known.
</P>
<P>
   He has no idea where his life is leading. The lone certainty
comes at 2 p.m. Friday, when the Atlanta Braves' rights to the
29-year-old relief pitcher expire.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Wohlers told the Braves that he would not accept an
assignment to Atlanta's Triple-A minor-league team in Richmond. The
Braves, who will release Wohlers if they are unable make a trade,
still will owe him $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the ultimate decision was (that) I think I've tapped
as many resources as I can in this organization,'' Wohlers said
from his Alpharetta home on Monday. ``I just think, for personal
and professional reasons, that this is best for me to get a new
start. I tried the Richmond thing, and it didn't work out. Several
people very close to me _ the therapist I've been working with _
have said that just going back there just kind of repeats history.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the biggest thing,'' Wohlers said. ``I felt like I
had a great spring. If not a great spring, considering where I was
coming from, I would classify (it) as being close to great. Then 10
days ago, I threw the hell out of the ball in the exhibition game,
and I just think I'm too close.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers hasn't been a Brave for half his life. It's actually
been only 40 percent of his life, since the club plucked him as a
bony 18-year-old kid out of Holyoke (Mass.) High School. It would
take him six years before he stuck in Atlanta for good and still
another season before the team gave him the closer's job.
</P>
<P>
   He, Tom Glavine, John Smoltz and Otis Nixon, who returned this
year after five seasons away, are the only Braves remaining from
the 1991 worst-to-first run. No player in any league in recent
history had his problems so publicly scrutinized. If some in the
Braves clubhouse were shocked when the team designated him Friday
for another minor-league assignment, Wohlers say he was not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know something obviously needed to be done,'' he said. ``You
know, I don't blame them for having to make this decision. It's
unfortunate that it's ended this way. It's been a heck of a run for
me, back since 1991. There's nothing more I could have hoped for
than to be able to contribute to this organization's winning
another championship. But it's just not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   During spring training, Wohlers seemed to have reclaimed his
form. Two days before the season began, he retired Cleveland's
Richie Sexson, David Justice and Alex Ramirez in order with the
same dominance he owned in his best seasons. Barely 48 hours later,
he walked four of the first seven Philadelphia Phillies he faced in
the opener.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night was worse: two walks and an error in three
batters. If anything, his first-week collapse was more horrific
than his slow, steady decline of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what happened was that when the bell rang, I didn't
allow myself to make mistakes,'' Wohlers said. ``I wanted to be
perfect. That's part of this. You walk in after going through what
I went through, the ovations and support that I got, you don't want
to let people down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I put too much pressure on myself to meet other
people's expectations, instead of just realizing what my own
expectations should be. If I walk a guy or two, it's no big deal. I
should still be able to get out of it, instead of saying out on the
mound, 'Oh-oh.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what had happened, too, is, there was a pattern being
set. When I had my first BP session in spring training, it was
shaky, and then things got better after that BP. When I had my
first exhibition outing in spring training, it was shaky, and then
things got better. And I was anticipating the same thing happening
here. A lot of people were. A lot of people I spoke to in the
organization and outside the organization said there was a pattern
being set, so be prepared. I have no doubts. Ten days ago when we
played Cleveland, I'm throwing the ball 97, 98 (mph) and hitting
the strike zone with an 88-, 89-mph split.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers and Seth Levinson, his New York-based agent, have
reviewed different scenarios for how this week might work out but
neither knows for sure. While he exercised the ultimate control by
refusing the Braves assignment, Wohlers has no control over what
happens in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   That uncertainty was weighed against what happens with his next
team. He is in the final, $5.2 million year of his contract, and an
option buyout can be worth $800,000 in 2000. But his decision to
leave the Braves has has much to do with his past here as with his
future elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what was going to happen next year,'' Wohlers
said. ``With my contract being up, was I going to have to start
with a new organization next year? I felt, if that was going to
happen and I was going to go to Richmond now, then maybe there's an
opportunity where I can pitch in the minor leagues for someone
else. Maybe I'd have an opportunity to come back and pitch in the
big leagues this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knew the writing was on the wall, that my chances
for coming back next year were slim. Not by my choice, but by the
way things were working out.''
</P>
<P>
   He leaves with another extended round of thanks for the Braves
organization, from owner Ted Turner to manager Bobby Cox, for the
club's support throughout his struggle. But that allegiance leaves
the Braves holding that $6 million bill for what Wohlers is still
owed, an awkward final chapter of what has become an awkward tale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thought a great deal about that,'' he said. ``I've asked
several people, because there's a guilt factor. Somebody told me,
``If you had a kid who was in the same situation, what advice would
you give him?'' Part of signing a long-term deal is the risk.''
</P>
<P>
   And if Mark Wohlers is leading the majors in anything, it must
be risk.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
