<HEADER>
A5254 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      04-12 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Tuesday, April 12. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. The final FRONTPAGE will move
later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ NATO's foreign ministers pledged today
to keep up the air attacks against Yugoslavia but at the same time
searched for the shape of a political settlement in Kosovo and
urged Russia to be part of it. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TRAIN (Grdelica, Yugoslavia) _ In its expanding air war,
NATO warplanes bombed two bridges this morning over the Juzna
Morava River, one highway, one railway, a narrow structure of steel
girders painted a dull gray. The train, five cars pulled by a
bright red, white and blue engine, was on the bridge, and the
missile cut it in half. At least nine people were killed, said
police at the scene, and at least 16 others, badly wounded, were
brought to a hospital in nearby Leskovac. NATO hits a Yugoslav
passenger train. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   BIN-LADEN (Washington) _ In their self-declared war with Osama
bin Laden, the man charged with blowing up two U.S. embassies in
Africa eight months ago, American officials portray him as the
world's most dangerous terrorist. But The New York Times, working
in cooperation with the PBS program Frontline, has found him to be
less a commander of terrorists than an inspiration for them.
Enemies and supporters alike say he may not be as globally powerful
as some American officials have publicly asserted. But his message
and aims have more resonance among Muslims around the world than
has been understood. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   MCDOUGAL-TRIAL (Little Rock, Ark.) _ A federal jury today
acquitted Susan H. McDougal of obstructing justice for her refusal
to testify before a grand jury about the Arkansas financial
dealings of President Clinton and his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton.
But the jury, in its third day of deliberations, deadlocked on two
other counts of criminal contempt and the judge, George Howard Jr.,
declared a mistrial. Although the jury's action was a mixed result,
it amounted to a setback for Kenneth W. Starr, the independent
counsel for Whitewater matters who Ms. McDougal claimed was out to
get Clinton. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-AUCTIONS (Undated) _ While retailers continue to spend
furiously to draw more customers on line, the Internet is suddenly
teeming with buyers and sellers making their own markets. Items
range from a 50-gallon fish tank to painted plaster Hula girls.
Economists say the blossoming of on-line bidding is no surprise.
Auctions are theoretically the most efficient form of commerce, the
perfect nexus of the supply and demand curves. But they have
traditionally been expensive to hold and limited in reach. The
Internet solves both of those problems. By Amy Harmon and Leslie
Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-RETURNS (Washington) _ As Congress returned to
Washington on Monday, House Democrats prepared to mount a quick
challenge this week to the House Republican leadership in an effort
to force campaign finance legislation to a vote. At the same time,
Republicans were quietly considering whether to drop their
traditional opposition to another Democratic issues _ a minimim
wage increase. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONTEMPT (Washington) _ Judge Webber Wright finds
President Clinton in civil contempt for his lies in the Paula Jones
civil deposition. She wrote: ``It is difficult to construe the
president's sworn statements ... as anything other than a willful
refusal to obey this court's discovery orders.'' The judge said,
``The record demonstrates by clear and convincing evidence that the
president responded to plaintiffs' questions by giving false,
misleading and evasive answers that were designed to obstruct the
judicial process.'' By John M. Broder.
</P>
</TEXT>
