<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKATE-SPEAK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINGO OF FINGERBOARDERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PHIL DAVIS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
LOS ANGELES _ Fingerboarders use the skateboard vernacular. Here is
some common skatespeak terminology:
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Deck &LR; : The board in skateboard. It's curved at both ends. The
deck is usually adorned on the bottom with a design or cartoon that
reflects the attitude and style of the skater. Skaters are mostly
teen boys, so the designs are usually sinister or gross. For
example: a homicidal skunk wielding a bloody skull-knife.
</P>
<P>
   T &UR; rucks &LR; : The metal things that attach the wheels to the deck.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nose &LR; : The front curve of the deck.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tail &LR; : The deck's back curve.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ollie &LR; : The most basic skate trick _ basically popping the
board up with the back foot _ or finger _ and then shifting forward
to front for a flat landing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ollie flip &LR; : An Ollie, but the board flips end over end before
the skater lands on it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kick flip &LR; : A good one for fingerboards. Like the name says,
the skater kicks the board into an end-over-end flip _ 180 or 360
degrees _ so it lands back on its wheels.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 50/50 grind &LR; : Using the Ollie to pop up and skid along a curb
or, for the tiny fingerboard, something smaller, like a geography
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pop  &LR; s &UR; hove-it &LR; : Flipping the board 180 degrees to bring the
back to the front, or vice versa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 1834EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
