<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5258 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-TRICKLE-NY     04-12 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-TRICKLE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DICK TRICKLE HAS WON FANS, BUT NOT RACES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CHRIS WINSTON   
 Spartanburg, S.C., Herald-Journal   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRISTOL, Tenn. _ Dick Trickle has won more than 1,200 races over
a 40-year driving career, but is known as one of racing's biggest
losers.
</P>
<P>
   He makes commercials that joke about his zero career Winston Cup
victories and show him getting hit in the head with a Frisbee.
</P>
<P>
   He demonstrates his sense of humor by sneaking up on other
drivers and grabbing them around the neck and by inviting himself
over to eat lunch in their trailers when he gets hungry.
</P>
<P>
   After four tough hours of racing Sunday at Bristol Motor
Speedway, he forced his crew members to break into smiles with a
deadly serious comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I don't know where they got the water in this bottle
in the car,'' Trickle called over the radio after 490 laps. ``But
it's awful.''
</P>
<P>
   Team owner Joe Falk squelched his laughter long enough to reply,
``It must be tap.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is life working with one of NASCAR's biggest supporters,
critics, draws and clowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a lot of fans out there, and we have a lot of fans
because we work with him,'' Falk said. Some of those fans
approached Trickle before Sunday's race. And although time was
short before driver introductions, he gladly stopped to autograph
shirts and papers and have his picture taken.
</P>
<P>
   Trickle does not acknowledge himself as a symbol for the sport,
and even refuses to allow himself to be known as a racing icon.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's an icon?'' asked Trickle, 57, with a smile and a quick
Wisconsin accent.
</P>
<P>
   Things haven't been going well on the track for Trickle recently
and Sunday's Food City 500 was no exception.
</P>
<P>
   A flat tire, being flagged for speeding down pit road, being
caught out of line trying to get to the pits, and pulling into the
wrong pit stall on the final caution were all taken in stride by
Trickle, who finished 31st, some seven laps off the pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Jeff Gordon had a flat, they would have thrown a caution on
the next lap,'' said Trickle, who is usually smoking a cigarette
when he's outside a race car and sometimes in one. ``But at least
that was the only bad thing to happen to us today.''
</P>
<P>
   Falk, trying to be conservative, estimates the team could have
grabbed a top-20 finish as Trickle had moved from 29th up to 25th
in the race's first 10 laps.
</P>
<P>
   It's been 10 years since Trickle, at 48, won the Rookie of the
Year campaign while subbing for the injured Mike Alexander for the
Stavola Brothers. But his NASCAR career goes back another two
decades when Trickle started the 1970 Daytona 500 in his own car
but was unable to finish.
</P>
<P>
   His driving career goes back to Midwestern short tracks, where
he won nine ARTGO championships, more races than he can count _ at
least 1,200 _ and became known as stock car racing's winningest
driver.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's race was his 286th Winston Cup race. Six months ago,
however, Trickle wondered whether he would be driving for anyone
this season. After piloting Junie Donlavey's No. 90 car for 2 1/2
half seasons, Trickle had to leave when the team lost its
sponsorship and a lot of the crew.
</P>
<P>
   Trickle has raced for 21 different Winston Cup owners over his
career.
</P>
<P>
   He climbed into Bill Elliott's second car to try to qualify for
February's Daytona 500, but a 27th-place finish in the 125-mile
qualifier was not enough. He didn't attempt to qualify for the next
three races, but joined up with Falk's team at Darlington, S.C.,
where he qualified 31st for the TranSouth 400. He finished 26th but
then failed to qualify two weeks ago in the Primestar 500 at Texas
Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making the show is an achievement at this stage,'' Trickle
said. ``And finishing a race is an achievement. And we did both
this weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear how much longer Trickle will be with the Falk
team. After next weekend's Goody's Body Pain 500 at Martinsville,
Va., Falk has no sponsorship lined up.
</P>
<P>
   Trickle hasn't finished in the top-20 in points since 1992, even
though he made 32 of 33 races last season and posted a top-10
finish in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   While his professional career has sent him from team to team, he
has been married to his wife, Darlene, for 30 years. The couple
have three children.
</P>
<P>
   Trickle said he wants to race until he finally wins a Winston
Cup race. His string of 286 races without a victory is the
second-longest active streak behind Michael Waltrip's 369 races.
Trickle, however, has finished third in Winston races five times,
most recently in August 1997. And more than 100 races on NASCAR's
Busch Series have netted him two victories, both in the past two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really need to win a Winston Cup race to cap my career off.
I really do. But we've got to get competitive first, and then it
will happen,'' Trickle said. ``It's going to happen when you least
likely expect it. I know that.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Spartanburg, S.C., Herald-Journal is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
