<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEVADABARR-MYSTERIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OLDER, WISER NEVADA BARR WATCHES HER `ANNA PIGEON' MYSTERIES
TAKE WING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Nevada Barr came to literary prominence late
enough in life to laugh at herself. After a checkered early career
as an actress and national park ranger, she finally had books
published in her late 30s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secret of my success? Sheer dumb luck,'' says Barr, 47,
who stopped at the Fort Worth Star-Telegram during a national tour
promoting ``Liberty Falling,'' her latest bestselling mystery
novel. ``But I'm enjoying it. As they say, I've been poor and
unknown and now I'm sort of rich and famous. I like rich and famous
better.''
</P>
<P>
   But the poor and unknown years gave Barr the imaginary basis of
her eventual success as an author. Anna Pigeon, the protagonist in
Barr's whodunits, is a park ranger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making (Anna) a ranger means I can expose her and my readers
to adventures in the most incredible sites,'' Barr says. ``It
means, when I'm thinking up my plots, that I can start by deciding
which park somebody's body will be found in. I can take everything
else in the story from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Readers are attracted by middle-aged Anna's personal growth.
Barr says that mimics her own life, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as I'd hate to think I wasn't learning new things,
embracing new ideas, well, I'd have no interest in writing about a
character who had to be the exact same person over and over again
in every book,'' Barr says. ``In `Liberty Falling,' for instance,
Anna is placed in the middle of New York City. It's different for
her; she has to learn to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Readers always seem happy to deal with Anna. Barr is on a
one-a-year Anna Pigeon book schedule. Her publisher, Putnam, backs
each with a substantial marketing budget. That means Barr spends a
month or so each year on the road, promoting books. It isn't always
fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like a vacation when you get to go sight-seeing,''
she explains. ``You have interviews, book signings, and then it's
get on the plane to fly to the next place and do it all over again.
But that's the hard part. I still enjoy meeting my readers. They
seem able to differentiate between fiction and real life. They know
Anna is based on me, but that she's not me.''
</P>
<P>
   While Barr tours to promote ``Liberty Falling,'' she has already
finished Anna Pigeon's next adventure and is trying to plot
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm supposed to have a new book out every spring, so I have to
stay focused. I give myself three months off between finishing the
last one and starting the next one.''
</P>
<P>
   When Barr begins a new book, she doesn't overprepare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know most mystery writers sit down and write complex plot
outlines, but I just like to start writing and see what happens,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   After Barr finishes her book tour this week, she'll take some
time for fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a new granddaughter to go look at,'' she says,
beaming. ``And after that, I'm excited about getting back to
Mississippi and staying home for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   But not for too long. After completing another Anna Pigeon
novel, Barr says, she's off on a grand adventure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to go to Nepal,'' she says. ``I wonder if there are
any national parks there for Anna to solve a murder at?''
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7720, or e-mail:
jguinn(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
