<HEADER>
A5272 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUCTION-COX     04-12 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUCTION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Real estate gems going once, going twice...on auction block
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ During the 1990s, as affluence has swept the country,
the number of ``trophy houses'' changing hands has soared, and the
auction gala _ a black-tie affair that auctioneers liken to an
elaborate wedding reception _ has become a more commonplace method
to sell them.
</P>
<P>
   Although a multi-million-dollar house is a challenge to build,
it can be even more of a challenge to sell. While the original
owner may regard all those gold bathroom fixtures and Italianate
marble fountains as the height of good taste, subsequent buyers may
recoil from them. In other instances, the upkeep on a stately
mansion can strike people as too troublesome. Sometimes, insolvent
owners send the houses into foreclosure.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the motivation, more and more owners have been calling
auction companies, prompting industrywide sales to reach $40
billion last year, according to 84-year-old J. P. King Auction Co.
of Gadsden, Ala., one of the leading American real estate auction
houses.
</P>
<P>
   This evening, three Atlanta residences _ including a showy
palace known as Lionheart _ will go on the block by National
Auction Group, also of Gadsden. All are foreclosures by Bankers
Trust of California being sold at absolute auction.
</P>
<P>
   They could bring millions, or they could bring next to nothing.
It depends on whether the auction is ``reserve,'' in which case the
owner can refuse to accept a high bid, or ``absolute,'' in which
case the owner is obligated to sell to the high bidder.
</P>
<P>
   The sometimes unique nature of these houses means there are no
standard measures of value such as comparables. Their owners range
from people like cosmetics queen Mary Kay Ash and former Treasury
Secretary Lloyd Bentsen to those with murky sources of income.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, Lionheart and a property on Wildercliff Drive were
formerly owned by a Pakistani father and son, Mohammad Sharif and
Mohammad Javaid. In 1995, the pair came under legal scrutiny for
allegedly buying houses, selling them to themselves at much higher
prices and using the higher valuations to raise cash. Lionheart,
for instance, was bought by a Sharif company four years ago for
$5.5 million and sold the same day to Sharif for $12 million. He
took out a $5 million mortgage and a $2 million line of credit
using the house as collateral.
</P>
<P>
   None of the people associated with the transactions could be
reached for comment Monday. The third foreclosure is a big house on
Spalding Drive. It was formerly owned by a man who built swimming
pools.
</P>
<P>
   Whether banks have foreclosed on the houses that go to auction,
or whether they go to market for another reason, ``there is usually
no emotional attachment,'' said William Bone, president of National
Auction Group. ``These people (owners) . . . are risk-takers who
want to move the place, and move it fast.''
</P>
<P>
   He expects his company will sell 60 properties, or $7.2 billion
worth of residential real estate, this year. At an average 6
percent commission, he could see millions in profits.
</P>
<P>
   It has also meant increased competition. As the auction has
become a preferred selling tool _ and an excuse for a fancy party _
even some Atlanta-based MBAs have sought to taste the hors
d'oeuvres. Tom Hunter and John Johnson of Interstate Auction Co.
have joined with Jeb Howell III of Auction Management Corp. to form
Interstate Auction Management.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the property is a funeral home or former Atlanta Braves
outfielder Mike Devereaux's 3 1/2 story house at the Golf Club of
Georgia, it can often find a buyer at auction.
</P>
<P>
   Here is how Craig King, second-generation president of J.P. King
Auction, described the process.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of a $5 million house decides to move on. He is not
looking for the record price in the neighborhood _ just, King said,
``a fair price.'' A foreclosing lender, on the other hand, wants
its money back.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the houses are sold furnished.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want it to be in a good area, well cared for, and not
overly improved ,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   When an auction deal is signed, the seller pays the auction
house expenses, including marketing. The sales commission is an
additional 5 to 7 percent. On top of that, the buyer has to pay a 6
percent premium, above the bid amount, to cover closing costs and
other fees.
</P>
<P>
   The terms are strictly cash or short-term financing. It costs
$50 to get in to tonight's absolute auction. Potential bidders will
bring at least $100,000, cash or check, to participate. Should the
winning bid be accepted, the high bidder has until noon Wednesday
to pay the rest of the money. He or she never has longer than 30
days.
</P>
<P>
   Devereaux's house, incidentally, did not sell at its reserve
auction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was obviously disappointed,'' Devereaux said. ``Despite
heavy promotion, we did not attract bidders willing to pay what I
thought the house was worth.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he added, he hopes one of the 50 people who walked
through his house will come back with an offer.
</P>
<P>
   Often, said Craig King, they do.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Harte writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
