<HEADER>
A5277 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATURE-INDOORS-TEX     04-12 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATURE-INDOORS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER FORECAST CALLS FOR ENJOYING NATURE INDOORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GAILE ROBINSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The warning signs are here _ a short, almost nonexistent winter,
an early, warm spring, less rainfall than normal _ all indicators
pointing to a meltdown summer.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are all these new books: ``The Garden Room:
Bringing Nature Indoors'' by Timothy Mawson (Clarkson Potter, $24),
``Garden Style'' (Better Homes and Garden Books, $34.95) and
``Gardenhouse: Bringing the Outdoors In'' by Bonnie Trust Dahan
(Chronicle Books, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   They too must be a sign that this summer will be a time of
legend, a season to hide from the heat, to retreat from the sun.
</P>
<P>
   To enjoy nature, we must move it in from the outside.
</P>
<P>
   We must consider the ``indoor world as an extension of the
natural world, not cut off from the realms of soil, sun and growing
plants,'' writes Mawson. He enthuses about rooms created ``with the
glow of the garden about them'' for entertaining, dining, relaxing.
</P>
<P>
   This is the emphasis of interiorscaping _ imbuing the formality
of public rooms with the sensual earthiness of the garden.
</P>
<P>
   In her book, Dahan includes photos of settings with similar
sympathies. A porch swing hangs inside a small house in lieu of a
sofa. Behind it, an outdoor awning covers a window like a curtain.
It's ``a private spot for bridging the sometimes conflicting
intentions of resting inside and getting out to the garden.''
</P>
<P>
   Dahan has found extreme cases of dragging the great outdoors
inside. She shows a kitchen that is home to a potting bench, now
used as a potholder, and a refrigerator that is sheathed in old
fence wood. On the freezer door is a small flower box that holds
drying hydrangeas. Branches of fresh lemons are entwined through
the chandelier. A rust-flecked outdoor chair wedged between the
fridge and the potting bench provides a space for company and
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing to tear down the privacy fence and use the wood
to face the refrigerator. The editors of ``Garden Style'' show
rooms that seem overloaded with posies, yet most of them are of the
printed sort. A floral rug and floral-print throw pillows go a long
way to enliven a room.
</P>
<P>
   In another instance, floral-print curtains with a gingham check
border are held aloft by multiple twigs bound together to form a
curtain rod. In the same room, a lampshade is covered with green
silk leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, just the organic shape of a tree branch or a few
fallen rose petals is enough to soften a formal interior.
</P>
<P>
   The easiest way to bring a little nature into the nest is with
plants. In the years since macrame plant hangers were popular,
house plants have taken on a new identity.
</P>
<P>
   The practice of interiorscaping involves hauling soil and plants
inside. Becky Blackmon, interiorscape supervisor for Fort Worth's
Worthington hotel, is an expert at this, recently bagging her
second ``Best Project Award'' from Interiorscape magazine. The
lovely jungles of plants she creates in the hotel's lobby were her
entry. Considering the low-light ambience, it's a wonder she gets
anything to live. (She admits that many of the plants have to be
replaced.) The dark, severely air-conditioned lobby, which is so
soothing to newly arrived travelers, is not the best atmosphere for
plants.
</P>
<P>
   Blackmon, a Master Certified Nursery Professional, says that
most garden centers have people with similar qualifications who can
assess your houseplant needs. To be a successful houseplant person,
you need to critically assess the room, the availability of light,
and the amount of time you are willing to spend fussing over your
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Most people ``underestimate how much light plants need,'' says
Blackmon. Moving a plant just 3 feet can diminish available light
by 20 percent to 50 percent; a distance of 6 feet can reduce it up
to 90 percent. ``Light, temperature and humidity will play the
largest role in overall success of maintaining healthy plants,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   The best combinations for indoor-outdoor design combine such
varied elements as tropical plants, topiaries, flowering plants,
eclectic furniture, architectural elements and garden ornaments. A
final chapter in ``Garden Style'' includes the most helpful of all
information _ the stores that provide the key elements for
interiorscapes.
</P>
<P>
   Salvage One Architectural Artifacts in Chicago looks like a
great source for giant, statement-making, wrought-iron fencing and
finials. Kay O'Toole's place in Houston, Antiques and
Eccentricities, is mentioned, as is Ryan Gainey's place in Atlanta,
Ryan Gainey &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   The editors must have overlooked local shops Into the Garden in
University Village and House to Garden on Vickery. Both are
excellent sources for interiorscape materials such as plants,
garden ornaments and furniture.
</P>
<P>
   With all these references, lists, sources and advice, summer, it
seems, can be an enjoyable season _ spent indoors surrounded by the
garden.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   How to buy houseplants
</P>
<P>
   Advice from Becky Blackmon, interiorscape supervisor for The
Worthington hotel in Fort Worth:
</P>
<P>
   _Avoid plants with brown or yellow spots or with thin,leggy
shoots.
</P>
<P>
   _Blooming plants should be just at the cracked color stage (not
fully open).
</P>
<P>
   _Inspect for insects: undersides of leaves, ends of shoots.
</P>
<P>
   _Look for name and care tags.
</P>
<P>
   _Shop where there are certified nursery professionals so you can
get reliable answers to your questions.
</P>
<P>
   _Flowering plants generally need high light, whereas
large-leafed ones can tolerate lower light levels. Thick leaves
generally require less frequent waterings, whereas soft, fleshy
plants usually need more frequent watering.
</P>
<P>
   IMPORTANT: No matter what the water frequency demands, always
supply enough water to saturate the root ball.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Best-bet houseplants
</P>
<P>
   Becky Blackmon, interiorscape supervisor for The Worthington
hotel, lists these choice indoor plants:
</P>
<P>
   Kentia palms: large, and pricey, but worth it if you have the
room.
</P>
<P>
   Sansevieria: Very easy and reliable.
</P>
<P>
   Pothos ivy: old standby, and easy to grow from cuttings.
</P>
<P>
   Aglaonemas: Very pretty and easy if you don't overwater.
</P>
<P>
   Spathiphyllums: Large assortment of varieties, from table size
to floor size.
</P>
<P>
   Nephthytis, White Butterfly: Great for table centerpieces.
</P>
<P>
   Balfour aralia: Elegant floor plant, deep green.
</P>
<P>
   Aspidistra: Very low-light tolerant, large, deep green leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Dracaenas, Janet Craig, Massangeana, Warneckei: Low light, easy.
</P>
<P>
   African violets: Don't let them scare you; they really are easy.
Self-watering containers take the guesswork out of watering and
fertilizing.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
