<HEADER>
A5288 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-ATLFIRE-COX     04-12 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ATLFIRE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Courage in Cabbagetown
 &HT;    By Jay Bookman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It must be solitary work _ sitting in a crane all day
hundreds of feet above a construction site, your only contact with
your fellow man coming from disembodied voices carried into your
cab by radio. But that day-to-day routine could not have prepared
Ivers Simms for what happened to him Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Because for many long minutes yesterday, Simms looked more alone
than any man alive.
</P>
<P>
   A massive fire had broken out at one of the buildings in the
19th-century Fulton Bag and Cotton Mill, where Simms was running a
construction crane. The other workers had fled, but Simms could not
escape his 250-foot tower. Below him, a blood-red inferno belched
black, poisonous smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to escape the heat and the smoke, Simms scrambled as far
from the fire as possible, until he ran out of crane and could go
no farther. Hundreds of people watched helplessly from the ground
below; many thousands more watched in horror on television. The
flames would die down briefly, then erupt skyward as if trying to
snatch Simms from his lonely perch.
</P>
<P>
   And below, the fire was blackening the white steel crane.
</P>
<P>
   Already, however, hundreds of people were scrambling to help. A
small police helicopter flew close enough to offer him the only aid
it could give at the moment, which was reassurance that he had not
been abandoned. A larger helicopter from the state Department of
Natural Resources arrived at the scene prepared for a rescue
attempt. Its pilot, a DNR veteran, was Boyd Clines, and he was
assisted by Larry Rogers. Matt Mosely, a firefighter from the city
of Atlanta, volunteered to dangle from the chopper in a rope
harness, land on the crane and then strap in the beleaguered Simms
for rescue.
</P>
<P>
   The heat and smoke were not the only dangers. A fire that hot
creates its own wind _ strong updrafts that can easily slap a
helicopter around. The DNR crew had prepared for work in forest
fires and for extracting hikers injured in narrow mountain gorges,
but this would be something new.
</P>
<P>
   And they pulled it off perfectly. What had seemed to be a
heart-rending tragedy in the making, with a human life almost
literally hanging in the balance, was transformed by the courage of
well-trained men and women willing to risk their lives for others.
</P>
<P>
   The fire will be a terrible setback for Cabbagetown, a
long-neglected part of Atlanta that had only recently begun a
revival. The cotton mill was on the National Register of Historic
Places, and the nine-building complex was in the midst of a
renovation into more than 500,000 square feet of loft apartments,
offices and other space.
</P>
<P>
   However, more than half of the renovation project has been
completed and is already occupied, and those buildings survived the
fire unscathed. The neighborhood itself _ a mix of urban pioneers
and hardy longtime residents _ is too tough to accept this setback.
For inspiration in their rebuilding, they need only look back at
Monday's events.
</P>
<P>
   Because as lonely as he looked out there on that crane, Ivers
Simms wasn't alone at all.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Bookman is an editorial writer for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
