<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5290 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-12 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TIME TO MAKE THE COMMITMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBNAY, N.Y. _ The fragility of the NATO coalition grows, it
seems, almost by the day as airplanes from the alliance bomb ever
more targets in Yugoslavia with perhaps marginal effect to bring
Slobodan Milosevic to heel.
</P>
<P>
   Second-guessing is rampant, especially in Washington, as early
hopes for a quick resolution disappeared and the Serbs proceeded to
implement their war aims despite escalating air attacks. The Serb
and Yugoslav forces apparently have registered great success in
decimating the Kosovo Liberation Army and in depopulating the
province of its ethnic Albanians, who comprised 90 percent of the
population of 1.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   There is a naive, not to say child-like, quality to the falling
out among the generals and the diplomats, each accusing the other
of having forced this war. It comes only days after a retreat from
the war's inception, in backroom strategy sessions, even as a
confident posture was maintained in public.
</P>
<P>
   The collateral of military action, the inevitable civilian
casualties, are sharpening the critical arguments, leading to
mindless restrictions on what targets may be legitimately bombed.
Some oppose the destruction of bridges across the Danube, because
that affects not only the military infracstructure but also the
lives of ordinary people. Other critics are against bombing
television facilities, even though they play the essential role in
the Milosevic regime's control of the information Serbs are
permitted to obtain.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the horrors that attend this war, the stark truth is
that it is either going to be lost by NATO, which is to say by the
United States, or it is going to be won through staying the course.
What is required is ratcheting up the deployment of state of the
art weaponry that only a while ago was deemed gratuitous overkill.
Even the possible use of ground forces, once considered by the
allies the Rubicon that under no circumstances could be crossed, is
gaining credence.
</P>
<P>
   The justification for this intervention is not to elevate one
side or the other in the long-lived ethnic, religious and
nationalistic conflicts that have characterized this troubled land.
NATO has no special competence to untangle the rights and wrongs of
the various claims and counterclaims of victimhood.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one legitimate reason for unleashing the might of
the 19 nations of the NATO alliance against the rump of what once
was Yugoslavia: To halt the inhumane persecutions, killings and
expulsions which the Serbs are using to settle up with the ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   That drastic action was employed by Milosevic first to gain
power among the Serbs and then to maintain it. In the process, he
moved from stirring rhetoric to bloody action, shocking much of the
world. It is likely that what he has unleashed meets the definition
of genocide as spelled out in international law.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly his actions trigger remembrances of the slaughter of
millions in the Holocaust in the Second World War. While Serb
actions have not gone to the lengths of rounding up an entire
religious group for extermination in death camps, mass killings of
Muslims by Serbs have been documented in Kosovo, as they were
earlier in Bosnia (where NATO was reluctant to intervene until
after thousands had perished).
</P>
<P>
   The pictures of Kosovars, many women and children and old
people, being herded onto trains to be transported into exile
brought to mind how Germans shipped Jews to the death camps. The
world should not have stood idly by, giving the Serbs time and
space to impose new and perhaps more drastic persecutions.
</P>
<P>
   It is an historic irony that during the Second War, the Serbs
were fierce enemies of the Germans. Many of their foes today were
in the Nazi camp then. But that does not give them leave to deal
with their problems of national integrity, however gravely they
regard them, by these intolerable means.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best that can be said about this horror is that in
the end, the world, or much of it, did not forget, did not
rationalize doing nothing, but took up arms on behalf of a
humanitarian cause.
</P>
<P>
   Many critics of NATO point to all the places where similar
atrocities were committed but no action was taken.
</P>
<P>
   Philosophers and ethicist rightly view the world through the
moral logic enunciated by the metaphysician Immanuel Kant: ``Act as
if the maxim from which you act were to become through your will a
universal law.' Would that were possible in all worldy affairs
(indeed, in all personal ones). It is plain to see that it is not.
There are more times when, for a host of rationalizations, we do
not resort to action, such as the genocide in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   Remorse over that failure likely helped to energize the Kosovo
response. In the end, failing the test of Kant's categorical
imperative should not immobilize us from acting when we can sort
out our politics, consider the implications and the costs, and make
the commitment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large at the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
