<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORES-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILENT KILLER TARGETS POOR WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VERONICA FLORES  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Estelle Lawton, a public health nurse supervisor,
is no longer surprised to hear 50-year-old women tell her they've
never done a breast self-examination.
</P>
<P>
   The stresses faced by the population Lawton serves help to
explain the trend:
</P>
<P>
   _ Women often are working, but in low-wage jobs that have
insufficient health-insurance coverage. They don't do self-exams
and may avoid screening for fear they'll find a costly health
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think if they don't know, they don't have a problem,''
Lawton says.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cultural taboos inhibit them from getting to know, much less
touch, their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy is that these obstacles prevent many poor women from
seeking medical help before it's too late. Disparate survival rates
among women who've been diagnosed with breast cancer demonstrate
their folly.
</P>
<P>
   While white women have an 84 percent survival rate after their
diagnosis, Hispanic and African-American women, who make up a
disproportionate share of the nation's poor, respectively have
rates of 70 percent and 69 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Lawton, who works with Adult Health Services of the San Antonio
Metropolitan Health District, says studies show Hispanic and
African-American women tend to be diagnosed after the cancer has
reached an advanced stage. Limited resources to offer preventive,
low-cost screening exacerbate the problem.
</P>
<P>
   That's where groups like the Susan G. Komen Breast Cancer
Foundation come in. Events such as the ``Race for the Cure'' raise
money to fund research, prevention and treatment of breast cancer.
The Dallas-based organization then is able to fill in the
health-care gaps as it has in San Antonio by helping the
Metropolitan Health District expand the scope of its low-cost
breast-cancer screenings.
</P>
<P>
   Federal funding for the screenings performed under Adult Health
Services programs is limited to women 50 and older, the group most
at risk of developing breast cancer. Women over 65 are covered by
Medicare. Left out are women who are 40 to 50.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Herbert Brown, director of the district's Women's Health
Services, says grants from the Komen Foundation have helped fill
the gap.
</P>
<P>
   But key to preventing needless deaths to the silent killer
remains in education and prevention, a hurdle that Lawton believes
the medical community finally, if incrementally, is beginning to
overcome, even in the hard-to-reach low-income community.
</P>
<P>
   Media campaigns that target the group are making inroads, as are
federal programs such as ``Comadres,'' an initiative aimed at
educating women over 65 who are on Medicare about the availability
of low-cost mammograms.
</P>
<P>
   Lawton points out, too, that breast cancer diagnosis no longer
means certain disfigurement by mastectomy, a prospect that long has
scared many women away from screenings.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, Lawton says the single most motivating factor
that prompts women to perform self-examinations is that knowing
someone who's had breast cancer or who has found a lump in her
breast.
</P>
<P>
   There are greater motivators. The American Cancer Society
reports that 175,000 women will be diagnosed with breast cancer
this year; more than 43,000 will die. The Komen Foundation points
to research showing that the mortality rate could decrease by 30
percent if all women age 50 and older in need of a mammogram had
one.
</P>
<P>
   What more motivation do women need?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Veronica Flores is a columnist for the San Antonio
Express-News, P.O. Box 2171, San Antonio, TX 78297.)
</P>
</TEXT>
