<HEADER>
A5298 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STEALTH-TECHNOLOGY-TE     04-12 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEALTH-TECHNOLOGY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS DISAGREE ON VALUE OF F-117 WRECKAGE IN COPYING STEALTH
TECHNOLOGY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL D. TOWLE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Just after the downing of an F-117 stealth fighter
over Yugoslavia on March 27, Pentagon officials played down
suggestions that Russia might be able to catch up on stealth
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Now, more than two weeks after the plane went down, the verdict
is mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Some leading aerospace experts say the wreckage of the
radar-evading fighter could help Russian scientists learn how the
F-117 Nighthawk is produced and how radar systems can track it.
Others say the technology is too dated to do the Russians much
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they gain from this is an actual example of the materials
that go into the airplane, its wings and its components,'' said Tim
Lomparis, a weapons technology expert at St. Louis University in
St. Louis. ``There is a big advantage to being able to look and see
what the plane is made of and not just having to speculate about
what it is believed to be made of.''
</P>
<P>
   Lomparis said that Russian scientists _ who are expected to gain
access to the wreckage _ will probably try to recreate the material
that makes up the plane's skin. Once a closely guarded military
secret, this composite, nonmetallic substance makes the aircraft
almost invisible to radar.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can bounce radar blips off it to see exactly how stealth
materials actually diffuse and scatter radar beams,'' Lomparis
said. ``They would still have to develop radar technology to be
able to overcome the problem, but they could see exactly what the
problem is. That plane's wreckage could help them a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force has declined to make any detailed comment on the
downing of the F-117, whose pilot bailed out and was rescued. The
service has yet to say officially whether the plane was shot down.
Pentagon officials say that the matter is under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the mishap, Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon said:
``To the extent that other countries have not been able to
duplicate our ability in stealth, there obviously is some risk.''
But he added that the Lockheed Martin plane, developed in the late
1970s in a top-secret project, is too old to provide meaningful
information on current stealth technology.
</P>
<P>
   Many at the Pentagon say privately that they hope Bacon is
right. The United States has invested billions developing stealth
aircraft, including the F-117, the B-2 bomber and the F-22
air-superiority fighter. If the Russians were to develop a radar
system that could track stealth aircraft, they could dramatically
improve their air defenses and earn billions in the international
arms market.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Interfax news agency has reported that the Yugoslav
government already has turned over some of the wreckage to the
Russians. The Yugoslavs reportedly want to exchange the rest of the
wreckage for Russian-made surface-to-air missiles. Aerospace Daily,
an industry trade journal, said one engine of the F-117 is believed
to have survived the crash with little damage.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Brown, a retired Lockheed executive and former program
manager and chief engineer for the F-117A, said the ``basic
principles of stealth'' are well known in the aviation community.
But he acknowledged that Russian scientists might learn additional
details from the downed plane's wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may know in general how the materials are done, but they
may see something they did not know,'' Brown said. ``Designers do
that all the time. You may see something on another plane that you
believe may be incorporated into what you are doing. I doubt it
would be a breakthrough for them. It would probably be a secondary
design idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the key to a stealth plane's design is enclosing the
parts most visible to radar within the radar-evading material.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can calculate what kind of a signature you will get from
the basic plane,'' Brown said, ``and then the rest of the game is
making sure all the details are inside the tent _ things like
controls, exhaust nozzles and inlets.''
</P>
<P>
   Some aerospace experts said they believe that the Russians will
be wasting their time if they ``reverse engineer'' the downed
F-117.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Sweetman, author of ``Stealth Bomber,'' a 1989 book on the
B-2 and other stealth programs, said the wreckage would reveal
little that is not already known.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the materials, technology and design for the B-2
and F-22 are significantly different from that of the F-117 and
that the Russians could learn nothing from the Nighthawk to help
counter the two later aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the bits and pieces that went into the F-117 were
particularly exotic,'' Sweetman said. ``The goal was to get a
stealth aircraft into service very quickly. A lot of the materials
used were derived from commercial products on the open market.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Aboulafia, a defense and aerospace expert with the Teal
Group in Fairfax, Va., said the Russians have little interest in
developing a stealth aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the Russians taking the opportunity to poke Uncle
Sam in the eye,'' Aboulafia said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
