<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USUAL OPTIMISM RULES AT FENWAY OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Citizens of Red Sox Nation are a resilient lot.
Rightfully cynical in August and September, they are wild optimists
in April. In this spirit, the Red Sox will return to an
enthusiastic, overflow crowd at Olde Fenway for the 99th home
opener of Boston's American League franchise.
</P>
<P>
   In the Hardball Hub of the Universe, Opening Day beats First
Night every year. Kind professors cancel class, cool parents write
excuse notes, and shopkeepers lock their stores and hang ``gone
fishin' '' signs on the door. This is the day when high-roller,
front-running ``fans'' (like those Catholics who attend Mass only
on Christmas and Easter) get cold and leave early, and blow-dried
news anchors refer to manager Jimy Williams as ``coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Happily (some would say surprisingly), there is hope for the
local nine. A week of good games (five wins and one loss) against
the much-buffeted Kansas City Royals and Tampa Bay Devil Rays has
erased some of the doubt and anger of the Red Sox' horrid
offseason.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that the schedule-maker was a friend to the Red
Sox. Had the team opened at home, free agent acquisition Jose
Offerman would have gotten the Antoine Walker treatment, general
manager Dan Duquette would have needed a Groucho mask (to go with
those natty white sneakers), and fans might have boycotted
concession items in a show of solidarity for the working-class
heroes in the pushcarts around Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   But all of that negativity was erased by a 5-1 start that
featured the pitching, speed, and defense the Sox promised, and a
heroic introduction for the much-maligned Mr. Offerman (six
multihit games and a .483 average).
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox were the last major league team to taste defeat in
1999 and are off to their best start since the 1946 World Series
edition. When Bret Saberhagen toes the rubber just after 1 Tuesday,
Boston will be in a first-place tie with the vaunted and hated
world champion New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see the electricity,'' malaprop manager Williams said
when he arrived at Fenway Monday morning. Three hours before his
one-year contract extension was announced, Williams greeted veteran
groundskeeper Joe Mooney and accepted kind questions from the
``surprised'' Boston media.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we played well in the first week,'' said Williams.
``The kids were focused when they went about their work in the
spring and I think it carried over into the season. We've gotten
good pitching and we've caught the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox have not played at Fenway since Oct. 3, when their
92-win season fizzled in a playoff loss to the Cleveland Indians. A
cruel winter followed, lowlighted by the defection of Mo Vaughn to
the Anaheim Angels and Duquette's difficulty at getting a big-name
free agent slugger to come to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the hideous offseason, this first week of the
season couldn't have worked out better for Duquette: The Sox are on
fire and Mo is on crutches. Meanwhile, Offerman has been the second
coming of Willie Wilson and Boston's pitching simply smothered the
woeful Royals and Rays.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Rice will throw out a first ball and Fenway fans should be
prepared for new signage in and around the old yard. Like
everything else (except the Masters), baseball is on the way to
becoming Winston Cup racing; we are only a few years away from John
Valentin wearing a Valvoline patch on his sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 home opener set the tone for Boston's wild card season.
The Sox trailed, 7-2, in the ninth inning, but rallied for seven
runs without making an out against the beleaguered Seattle bullpen.
Vaughn's walkoff homer launched a successful season and the Sox see
no reason why they can't do it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think our fans are looking forward to opening up and
watching these kids play,'' said Williams. ``I'm looking forward to
it. It's Boston and it's Opening Day.''
</P>
<P>
   A raft of brittle pitchers, a dearth of power, and the mighty
wallets of the Yankees may yet dissolve some of this early-season
exuberance, but not today. Your mailman and your butcher are
talking baseball again.
</P>
<P>
   It's Opening Day and the Red Sox are in first place.
</P>
<P>
   This could be the year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
