<SLUG> BC-SKA-ACCUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COACH DENIES CHARGE LEVELED BY FORMER PUPIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Richard Callaghan, one of the world's most distinguished figure
skating coaches, has strongly denied charges that he engaged in
sexual misconduct with a former pupil who later became his coaching
assistant.
</P>
<P>
   In a story in Sunday's New York Times, Craig Maurizi said that
Callaghan, who directed Tara Lipinski to an Olympic gold medal and
Todd Eldredge to a world title at the Detroit Skating Club, had
initiated a sexual elationship with him when Maurizi was 15.
Maurizi, now a 36-year-old husband and father, said the
relationship continued sporadically until two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Times also reported that two other male skaters said
Callaghan had made sexual overtures to them and that a former
coaching colleague said three male skaters told her that Callaghan
had made sexual advances to them or others. Callaghan said the
reports were untrue.
</P>
<P>
   The 53-year-old Callaghan, who is married with a grown daughter,
did not return a phone call Monday but ``fervently denied''
Maurizi's charges through his lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Callaghan and his family are shocked and deeply dismayed
that Mr. Maurizi has made these unsubstantiated allegations,''
Michigan attorney Dean Groulx said in a statement. ``They have
always viewed Mr. Maurizi as an invaluable member of their extended
family and hope he will be able to resolve his emotional
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Maurizi, who was traveling Monday and did not return a phone
call, has said he will file a formal grievance against Callaghan
with the US Figure Skating Association. The USFSA's top officials
were also traveling Monday and unavailable for comment. But a
spokesman said the association, which was aware of Maurizi's
allegations before the Times story, would wait until receiving the
grievance before proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Maurizi, who trained with and coached alongside Callaghan for
more than two decades and asked him to be best man at his wedding,
has been seeing a therapist to deal with what he later concluded
was an exploitative relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, I thought the sex was consensual,'' Maurizi told
the Times. ``Now, when I look back, I don't think it was
consensual. I don't care how old a student is, whether it's a boy
or a girl, a coach should never have sex with a student.''
</P>
<P>
   Callaghan, who announced last month that he would leave the
Detroit Skating Club at the end of the spring and retire from
active coaching after 27 years, has the most accomplished record of
any American coach in the last quarter-century.
</P>
<P>
   Besides coaching Lipinski to her Olympic victory at Nagano last
year, Callaghan has directed Eldredge to five world medals and five
US titles and was Nicole Bobek's coach when she won the 1995 US
crown and world bronze medal.
</P>
<P>
   Eldredge said Monday he was ``shocked'' by Maurizi's charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never experienced anything like that with Richard, so I
don't know what he's talking about,'' said the 27-year-old
Eldredge, who grew up in Chatham, Mass. and has been coached by
Callaghan since he was 10. ``Richard has been like a father to me,
especially with me living away from home for so long. I've been
pretty much a part of the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Maurizi, who is leaving the Detroit club to become skating
director at the New England Sports Center in Marlborough, Mass. in
June, began training with Callaghan in Buffalo when he was 13 and
followed him to Philadelphia and Colorado Springs.
</P>
<P>
   He said Callaghan began a sexual relationship with him two years
later and that they had hundreds of intimate encounters in hotels,
in rink offices, and at Callaghan's house. Maurizi said he ``never
had the guts'' to break with his mentor until recently.
</P>
<P>
   Maurizi told the Detroit Free Press that he met with Callaghan
for five hours in February before he decided to speak publicly.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I confronted him, I asked him point-blank why he did to
me what he did . . . and he said, `To tell you the truth, I felt
that it was something that you wanted to do. That's why I did it,'
'' Maurizi said. Callaghan has denied discussing the issue with
him.
</P>
<P>
   After Maurizi retired from competitive skating in 1987, he was
Callaghan's assistant for several years in San Diego and joined him
again four years ago in Detroit. The two parted ways last year
after Lipinski switched from Callaghan to Maurizi. Callaghan has
said professional rivalry is the motive behind Maurizi's charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
