<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBANIA-VOLUNTEERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLUNTEERS TRAIN, MOVE OUT IN SUPPORT OF KLA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOLSCH, Albania _ Gunfire crackled in the hills of this village
Monday, as dozens of volunteers to the Kosovo Liberation Army
arrived for a brief training session before venturing north to the
border, where fighting intensified with Serb troops.
</P>
<P>
   The new soldiers, dressed in the red-speckled camouflage uniform
of the KLA, ran from field to field clutching Kalashnikov rifles
against their chests. In formation, they dropped to the ground,
aiming their weapons into the valley below.
</P>
<P>
   And although their open-air exercises appeared rudimentary _
with soldiers running back and forth across a two-lane highway,
twirling their rifes in the air _ several recent arrivals said they
are just days away from joining a convoy mission into southern
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Such missions appear to have increased in recent days, provoking
a sustained firefight at the Kosovo-Albanian border, which Albanian
officials fear may spill farther south to the country.
</P>
<P>
   Serb shelling has already begun to penetrate deep into the
region. Civilians in the northern town of Tropolje were killed on
Sunday. Two hundred rounds of mortar fire reportedly fell on Sunday
in the town of Padesh as well. And Monday, an outside monitor said
he witnessed a burning house in the town of Kamenica, just south of
the Kosovo border.
</P>
<P>
   ``The firefight is continuing and it is escalating,'' said Leo
Dobbs, a field monitor for the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe, from a station in Bayram Curri. ``The Serbs
are firing mortar and more artillery into Albania. ... It is
getting worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Albanian officials responded by asking NATO for ground support,
saying the integrity of its borders is being violated by Serb
troops. NATO and US officials have repeatedly said they have no
intention of sending in ground forces. Although 6,000 NATO soldiers
will help with the humanitarian effort here and some 2,000 US
troops are expected to arrive in Albania in the coming days to
accompany 24 Apache helicopters, there was no indication of new
troop dispatches.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of the KLA repeated their pleas for outside help
and arms to supply the guerrilla force, whose aim is to create an
indepedent Kosovo outside of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview early Monday, three soldiers, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said they had arrived at the training camp
here less than two weeks and had been fitted with KLA uniforms and
rifles.
</P>
<P>
   They said their KLA counterparts in two strongholds within
Kosovo were running desperately low on supplies and had no more
than a few days of artillery left.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the men said they had fled Kosovo within the last year,
one to Germany, the other to Switzerland. The third said he was not
from Kosovo, but was instead a former member of the Albanian
military who had joined the KLA to provide training support.
</P>
<P>
   The third man said numberous other Albanians had joined the
force, in official and unofficial capacities, accompanying the
estimated 1,200 members of the Kosovo diaspora who are returning to
fight the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the new members have traveled from abroad to help defend
family members who are trapped inside Kosovo, according to the KLA
members interviewed and Dobbs, the Western monitor, who said he
spoken to KLA members who had come from as far as New York City.
</P>
<P>
   A KLA recruit from Germany said he still had two children and a
wife inside Malashava, although he had no way of knowing whether
they had fled or were even alive.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the Kosovars interviewed said they were planning to
cross the border as soon as possible. ``I'm going in three days,''
the soldier from Switzerland said. ``Our families in there, so we
are going to protect them.''
</P>
<P>
   Four KLA members have been killed and two injured in the border
skirmishes in the last two days, Dobbs said. Several Albanian
border police have been injured, as Serb troops have begun aiming
shells and sniper fire at the local military posts.
</P>
<P>
   The shelling at Kamenica grew so severe Monday that border
police were spending ``most of their time hiding in the bunkers,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The violence reignited last week, presumably as a result of KLA
forays into Kosovo, where they have secured two towns, Koshare and
Batusha, Dobbs said. Since then, however, Serb troops have becom
increasingly aggressive across the border, ``quite possibly to
escalate the conflict and provoke Albania,'' Dobbs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was the original aim of the KLA to cause a
clash,'' he said. ``It seems they wanted to do reconnaissance and
to defend the refugees inside Kosovo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 1917EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990412.0322 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5313 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-AUCTIONS-ART-2     04-12 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-AUCTIONS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: are proliferating. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Ebay's diverse population is any indication, the new sites
may well find customers. A considerable part of the online auction
crowd is made up of longtime collectors who buy and sell off line
as well. But the Web seems to be igniting the collecting impulse
among those who might otherwise have been content to buy retail or
not at all.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Cannode, 23, a nurse in Kenton, Ohio, for instance,
recently began collecting My Little Ponies, which she remembers
fondly from her not-so-distant youth. After showing off her online
finds, Ms. Cannode must now contend for computer time with her
father, who scours the auction boards for Zippo lighters; her
mother, whose passion is Beanie Babies. and her brother, who
recently went to a Nascar race with tickets he bought on Ebay.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most seductive aspect of the auction is the scent of
a good bargain. Frequent bidders tend to develop elaborate
strategies to outwit the competition, from listing a top bid at the
outset and letting the computer take care of the rest, to swooping
in during the final minutes after competing bidders have shown
their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Darren Jer of Manhattan, who bought a digital camera
at a Cyberian Outpost auction last week for $620 plus $6 shipping,
come away crowing. ``When it comes to buying consumer electronics
equipment on the Web, I'm pretty assiduous about finding the best
price,'' said Jer, 25, who said he had never tried an auction
before. ``And I got this for $100 below market value. I'm a happy
customer.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are more familiar with the notorious ``winner's curse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got to have something, that will definitely push you
over the edge,'' said Tony Porzio, 38, of Albuquerque, N.M., who
concedes he may have overpaid just a tad for a 1964 World's Fair
subway map. ``But if you've got to have something, you'll pay what
you have to pay. That's really the beauty of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The other half of the equation is a country full of
entrepreneurs tickled to make a buck as they clean out their
basements. Mark Siegel, a computer programmer in Miami, has taken
to ransacking his closets for items to offer on Ebay. No wonder. So
far he has sold a Tori Amos CD, the import version of ``Upside
Down,'' for $142, and a copy of the first American issue of Maxim,
a men's magazine, that he describes as ``basically worthless'' for
$71. ``I personally get a thrill out of selling junk that I would
have probably thrown out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Lavallie, 28, of the Bronx started out as a buyer but
quickly became a seller after hearing a friend's sheepish account
of having paid $325 for some ``Planet of the Apes'' action figures
that he could have bought at a toy store for $75.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a seller I just saw that people were insane enough to pay
ridiculous prices for some items,'' Lavallie said. ``It's not like
you actually have your cash in your hand, so you don't realize what
you're doing. You lose track of logic and reason.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact the barriers to selling on the Web through auction are
so minimal that a small but significant group of people have quit
their jobs to become full-time merchants. A much larger number sell
as a hobby or to make petty cash.
</P>
<P>
   Take Danny Friedman, a 12-year-old Manhattanite, who has
discovered that he can make up to $125 a month buying Beanie Babies
cheaply in New York City and reselling them to collectors in rural
areas. Just recently, he bought Spooky the ghost for $5 and
auctioned it off for $38.
</P>
<P>
   While hobbyists rushed in, more established retailers (even pure
Internet merchants) resisted the auction format, worried that a bad
customer experience could damage their name brand credibility. But
that's changing. Deva Hazarika, founder of MOAI, a firm that
designs auction software, has seen a surge of interest from
professionals looking for tools to differentiate their sites from
the crowd. ``Companies selling directly to consumer see it as a way
to create excitement,'' he said. It will not be long, he predicts,
before retailers routinely offer online auctions as an alternative
format for holding sales.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Van Kleeck, spokesman for the National Retail Federation,
also sees a future where traditional retailers use net auctions as
a possible way to dump excess inventory. ``Why not have a factory
outlet on line where people bid for goods?'' he asks. ``Ultimately,
it makes logical sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, sellers of fixed-price goods face pitfalls in
entering the auction venue. They must avoid, for example, the
potentially ire-inspiring situation where consumers end up bidding
more for merchandise than they would have paid in the store. The
Web site for Lands' End has been experimenting with reverse
auctions for almost two years. On Saturday it puts a limited
quantity of some clothing item, like a denim dress, on sale for 25
percent off, but alerts customers that as the week progresses it
will continue to mark down the goods. Customers then have to weigh
the extent of the discount against the likelihood of the item
selling out when deciding whether to bid, but they never risk being
burned by paying more than an item's original listed worth.
</P>
<P>
   But for some the spread of such clever efficiency could defeat
the whole purpose. ``It's spread the knowledge of what the market
price is to every tiny little town in the world,'' said William
Gibson, the science fiction author who coined the term
``cyberspace,'' and who wrote about his Ebay addiction in a recent
issue of Wired magazine. ``Sometimes I worry there will be such a
severe rationalization of the market that the fun will go out of
the hunt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
