<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5317 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      04-12 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS COULD BE LOOKING FOR OFFENSIVE LINEMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The Patriots didn't get much of a bang for the $37
million investment they made in veteran linemen Bruce Armstrong,
Todd Rucci, and Max Lane a year ago, and youngsters Ed Ellis, Damon
Denson, and Jason Andersen didn't grasp the opportunities dangled
in front of them.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, only Heath Irwin among the younger linemen will enter
the '99 season with a chance to be a starter _ at center, after
Dave Wohlabaugh left for Cleveland as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   All of which indicates that the Patriots could be big players in
the offensive line market in Saturday's draft. Some think the
Patriots will take as many as three linemen with their first five
picks, and many draft experts predict that they'll wind up with
Boston College center Damien Woody.
</P>
<P>
   Woody is projected as a first-rounder, which is not all that
common for centers. At 6 feet 3 inches, 328 pounds, he also could
play guard or even tackle in the NFL. Woody is very quick for a big
guy, running a 5.13 40-yard dash, and could definitely be an
effective run-blocker. Scouts say that the junior has not peaked
and that if he takes his talents even more seriously than he has,
he could be a dominating player in the league.
</P>
<P>
   The BC offensive linemen are considered to be well-coached and
strong on technique, which is why Doug Brzezinski is rated the top
guard in the nation by some scouts. At 6-4, 307, he's not as quick
as Woody, running a 5.4 40, but he has tremendous technique and
could be a second-rounder.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus top pick among offensive linemen is Brigham
Young's John Tait, who should be gone by the time the Patriots
pick. At 6-6, 310, Tait has great strength, quickness, and
toughness, and he does more than pass-block, which is usually the
strength of a BYU lineman.
</P>
<P>
   Right behind him is Wisconsin's Aaron Gibson, the most massive
tackle in the draft. Gibson is just under 6-7 and 390 pounds. He
can be a devastating run blocker, which is precisely what the
Patriots need, but he might give up something on the pass blocking
end, as his size makes him vulnerable to the outside rush.
</P>
<P>
   Eastern Michigan's L.J. Shelton, son of former Seattle Sonic
Lonnie Shelton, seems to be rising. At 6-5 1/2, 338, Shelton had a
big Senior Bowl and has tested well in front of scouts. He may be a
project, not someone to step in and play right away.
</P>
<P>
   Other possible first-rounders include Georgia's Matt Stinchcomb,
a talented tackle who may be the smartest of the available linemen;
Penn State's Floyd Wedderburn (6-5, 333), a converted defensive
tackle still trying to remove the stigma of a major knee injury in
1995; West Virginia's Solomon Page, who some believe should stay in
school another year; Michigan's Jon Jansen; and Baylor's Derrick
Fletcher (6-7, 374), who is pretty quick (5.25) for his size.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's Kris Farris, a 6-8, 315-pound tackle, gets a lot of
attention as the Outland Trophy winner and could go in the second
round. But scouts don't consider him as good as Tait, Shelton,
Gibson, or Woody.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's Zach Pillar, who broke combine records for bench
presses (225 pounds 40 times), could be an attractive guard to be
taken somewhere in the third round.
</P>
<P>
   If the Patriots don't take Woody, they could wait around for
other highly rated centers such as Arizona State's Grey Ruegamer or
Colorado State's Mike Newell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
