<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5318 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-HUNGARY-BOS &LR;      04-12 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-HUNGARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVOY SQUABBLE WITH RUSSIANS POINTS UP HUNGARY'S DILEMMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDAPEST _ It wasn't a scene Hungarians expected to see again,
so soon after joining as powerful a military force as NATO: five
Russian armored vehicles on Hungary's eastern border with Ukraine
demanding to get in Monday along with 68 trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Decades ago, it was Russian tanks that rolled into Hungary,
putting down a 1956 revolution attempt and cementing Russia's
then-Communist control over the Central European nation.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, Hungary held the military cards, and refused
entry to the truck convoy, which the Russians insisted held
humanitarian aid headed for Yugoslavia, a longtime ally of
Russia's.
</P>
<P>
   Russia warned that the episode could have ``grave
consequences,'' and deemed the detention of the trucks an
``unfriendly act.'' The dispute was resolved Monday afternoon, as
Hungary agreed to accept most of the trucks, turning back the
armor-plated vehicles and some trucks containing diesel fuel _ a
substance controlled by UN sanctions against Yugoslavia because it
could be used for the Yugoslav war effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We solved the question on a ministerial level in short
order,'' Interior Minister Sandor Pinter told reporters Monday.
``This humanitarian assistance will pass through Hungary.''
</P>
<P>
   The quibble with Russia defused, Hungary is still finding itself
in the middle _ caught between its new relationships with its
neighbors, and its even-newer commitment to NATO, which Hungary
lobbied so strongly to join.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is pretty much the first case where Hungary was needed to
act in accord with international sanctions and stand up against the
Russians,'' Hungary's one-time mortal enemy, said political analyst
Attila Ledenyi. ``Of course, it would have been nice if we could
have celebrated the first month of NATO membership,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Hungary was officially admitted into NATO last month, and the
NATO assault on Yugoslavia, which lies right under Hungary's
southern border, began less than two weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have our honeymoon,'' said Laszlo Poti, an analyst
with the Institute for Strategic and Defense Studies in Budapest.
``It is a paradox that we joined the `old' NATO, and instead found
ourselves in a `new' NATO, one with a ``much more activist role,''
Poti said.
</P>
<P>
   Geographically, Hungary is in a vulnerable position.
Land-locked, Hungary shares seven, porous international borders _
five of them with countries that until recently used to be part of
other countries. Hungary, a nation of just 10 million people, is
completely surrounded by non-NATO members.
</P>
<P>
   Hungary also has had to forge new relationships with nations
with whom it has had an uneasy past. Ukraine, on its eastern
border, used to be part of the hated Soviet Union; Hungary has had
squabbles with both Slovakia and Romania about the rights of ethnic
Hungarians living there.
</P>
<P>
   Hungary has been run over numerous times over the centuries, by
the Turks, the Mongols, the Germans, the Russians, the Austrians
and now, some nostalgic types here grumble _ by the American
capitalists. Hungary was on the losing side of both World Wars.
</P>
<P>
   The nation has had a reasonably friendly relationship with
Yugoslavia, where there is a substantial ethnic Hungarian
population in the northern Serbian province of Vojvodina.
</P>
<P>
   But the fight between NATO and Yugoslavia has forced Hungary to
the Western side, against some of its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Hungary will not send ground troops, should the war escalate to
that level. But Hungary has been a good metaphorical soldier for
NATO, allowing use of its air space and saying it is open to the
sending of Hungarian engineers and medical personnel as part of a
post-war peace-keeping mission.
</P>
<P>
   Gabor Horvath, spokesman for the Foreign Ministry, insists that
Hungary is not more vulnerable now that it has abandoned its Warsaw
Pact membership for NATO. Nor do the Hungarian people regret
joining the military alliance, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the Russian convoy, he said, ``First, the situation
could have happened as early as October,'' before Hungary was in
NATO. ``It is better to be in NATO when this is happening,'' so the
entire military alliance would protect Hungary if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   To the minority of NATO detractors, the Yugoslav war and the
Russian dispute are just two examples of why Hungary should have
stayed out of the military alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians are supposed to look ahead. But they didn't. They
looked West, where the money comes from,'' said Toma Sik of Alba
Kor, or Circle of Dawn, an anti-NATO group. ``We must replace a
Warsaw Pact with a capitalist NATO? What's the point?'' Sik said.
``A small country should be neutral.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
