<SLUG> BC-NATO-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO WILL `STAY THE COURSE,' CLINTON SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BARKSDALE AIR FORCE BASE, La. _ With several B-52s arrayed on a
runway behind him, President Clinton vowed Monday to continue the
air war against Serbian forces until Slobodan Milosevic ends his
campaign of ``racial atrocities'' in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton condemned Milosevic for persecuting ethnic Albanians
``to erase the presence of these people in their own land
forever,'' and declared, ``We must not let that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the United States and its NATO allies remained
united and intended to keep pressure on Milosevic until he
withdraws his troops from Kosovo, permits the refugees to return
home, and allows an international peacekeeping force in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Declaring that NATO has ``the patience to deal with all the
questions and stay the course,'' Clinton said, ``There are a lot of
people who didn't think this alliance of 19 countries could do what
we have done and could stay together as we have stayed together.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hammered Milosevic for creating a situation in Kosovo
with ``thousands of innocent people uprooted, many of them killed,
some of them dying from disease in refugee camps, some families
divided forever, not because of anything they did, but because they
happen to be Albanian instead of Serbian, Muslim instead of
Orthodox Christian.''
</P>
<P>
   Under clear early-morning skies, Clinton flew to this base of
the Air Force's Second Bomb Wing to deliver thanks to personnel who
have been carrying out raids over the past three weeks and to
pledge his undiminished commitment to complete the mission.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting privately with crew members, Clinton made a public
address before several thousand Air Force personnel and hundreds of
civilian visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Though the president, who avoided the draft during the Vietnam
War, experienced unease when dealing with the armed forces early in
his administration, the reception here was warm. The crowd
punctuated Clinton's remarks with applause and cheers.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of demonstrators protesting the bombing campaign was
kept outside the base's gate.
</P>
<P>
   A poll conducted before his arrival by The Times, a newspaper
covering this region, found that 59 percent of respondents in the
area supported the NATO action. It also found that 45 percent
approved of Clinton's job performance compared to 38 percent who
disapproved.
</P>
<P>
   To underscore national solidarity, Clinton was accompanied by
members of his national security team, including the chairman of
the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Gen. Henry H. Shelton, and Defense
Secretary William S. Cohen, who hailed Clinton for placing ``our
nation on the right side of history'' in the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana's Democratic senators, John Breaux and Mary Landrieu,
were also on hand to praise the president. Breaux said Clinton
would be remembered for his ``leadership and understanding of the
history of the Balkans.'' Landrieu, a member of the Senate Armed
Services Committee, said: ``Mr. President, we're in it. Let's win
it!''
</P>
<P>
   After the program, several members of crews taking part in the
European operations were made available to reporters with the
understanding that they would not be identified.
</P>
<P>
   A major said he was satisfied Clinton was ``100 percent behind
us.'' Asked if servicemen were troubled by Clinton's lack of a
military background, the officer said, ``I don't think so. We've
seen Iraq and now we're seeing Kosovo. He's behind us, the
country's behind us, and that's a good feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Barksdale Air Force base was chosen as the site for the
commander in chief to voice his support for the American role in
the NATO operation because the B-52 base has a history of allied
engagements dating from the time French fighter pilots trained here
during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   During his private meeting with Air Force personnel, Clinton
asked about the longevity of the B-52s and was assured that the
fleet would be good for another 40 years, according to a briefing
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that it had become ``much harder to get and keep
good people'' in the military, Clinton told the crowd he had
``listened carefully'' to the expressions of concern by crew
members during his personal talks, and he promised to take steps to
ensure better pay and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   As one measure, the president announced an executive order which
would extend tax deadlines and offer some income tax exemptions for
military personnel serving in the combat zone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
