<HEADER>
A5321 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDSON-PULITZER-COX     04-12 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDSON-PULITZER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta teacher wins drama award
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Margaret Edson, an Atlanta kindergarten teacher who
wrote ``Wit,'' the off-Broadway drama about a woman with cancer,
won the 1999 Pulitzer Prize for drama Monday and said pizza was
next on her plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consolation prize, if I hadn't won it, was also a pizza,
though perhaps with not quite as much garlic on it,'' quipped the
playwright, sounding pleased but perfectly collected, her usual
witty self.
</P>
<P>
   The 37-year-old Edson, who was unknown before ``Wit,'' her first
play, opened six months ago to rave reviews off-Broadway, received
the news from the play's New York press agent by phone at
Centennial Place School, where she was just finishing her teaching
day. She was to be joined at the late dinner by partner Linda
Merrill, a curator at the High Museum of Art. When asked to explain
the subdued celebration, Edson said with joking primness, ``It is a
school night, after all.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill, who offered to pick up the pizza tab, said, ``I'm
thrilled but not terribly surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wit'' was indeed a favorite for the Pulitzer Prize in drama,
but only after a long saga of proving itself against many doubters.
The starkly unsentimental but deeply moving portrait of an ovarian
cancer patient, based on Edson's experience as a volunteer social
worker and hospital clerk in her native Washington, was written in
1991. Only one theater (in Southern California) was willing to
produce it before 1997. Then a Connecticut theater mounted it, then
an off-off-Broadway company, which in January moved it into the
off-Broadway Union Square Theatre, where it's still selling out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that (the prize) affirms all of the people who took a
chance on the play,'' Edson said Monday. ``I've made many friends
among the many wonderful artists who've brought it to life.''
</P>
<P>
   The cast and crew reportedly plan to gather on the Union Square
stage to offer a champagne toast to Edson before tonight's
performance.
</P>
<P>
   The playwright, meanwhile, plans to be in her downtown classroom
bright and early today, as usual, and won't visit New York until
mid-May, when she's due to take part in an after-performance
symposium.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably Edson will also be on hand when the Alliance Theatre
mounts the play in its 1999-2000 season. By coincidence, the
Alliance is currently presenting the 1998 Pulitzer winner, Paula
Vogel's ``How I Learned to Drive''; Edson's Pulitzer marks the
first time that two women have won the prize in consecutive years.
Only 10 women have won or shared the Pulitzer for drama since it
was established in 1917.
</P>
<P>
   While many well-known playwrights won Pulitzers early in their
careers, at a younger age than Edson, no one in memory emerged so
suddenly from a nonwriting career. In fact, Edson is dedicated to
teaching as a lifelong calling and has written only one other play,
unproduced, which she describes as ``hokey'' celebration of country
gospel music. She will write another play ``if and when a
compelling idea strikes me.'' Even lucrative screenwriting offers
(a film version of ``Wit'' is being discussed) will not budge her
from the classroom, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Edson moved to Atlanta last summer when her partner, Merrill,
got her High Museum job. Edson soon signed on at Centennial Place,
where she quickly became known as an inventive teacher, setting
lessons to the tunes of Cole Porter and George Gershwin. Even while
being interviewed about the Pulitzer, she kept turning the subject
back to her teaching. She excitedly described her newest project,
``Six Legs Over Georgia,'' a lesson about insects set to the tune
of Buddy Holly' ``Peggy Sue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wit'' has generated some controversy with its unsparing view
of a medical establishment that's more interested in the heroine _
Vivian Bearing, a professor of 17th-century poetry _ as a test
specimen than a human being. Nor is the Bearing presented a noble
martyr, but rather as a haughty, aloof intellectual who earned her
own isolation. Though Bearing's sharp wit in the face of medical
indignities and certain death keeps audiences laughing even to the
point of tears, ``Wit'' is among the least commercial, least
``audience-friendly'' plays ever to win the Pulitzer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a play about kindness, the human touch,'' Edson said in
January, ``and one way to show that is through its opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   Edson was asked how she felt joining a pantheon of Pulitzer
winners that includes Vogel, Eugene O'Neill and Tennessee Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terrific,'' said the teacher , ``I'm only sorry that
Sophocles couldn't be with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert is the theater critic for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
