</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-BUS-ART-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST BUS RIDERS, CAUGHT UP IN SHUTTLE DIPLOMACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Repeating to add photos to art advisory)  
(ART ADV: Two photos and a locator map is being sent to NYT graphic
photo and graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ON THE GRAND TRUNK ROAD, India _ The buses, like this shiny
white one, run back and forth between New Delhi, India, and Lahore,
Pakistan, four days a week now, each a fragile thread suturing the
wound inflicted 51 years ago when these two nations were hacked
from Britain's Indian empire at independence.
</P>
<P>
   Emblazoned with the logo of Pakistan's Tourism Development
Corp., and loaded with ordinary Indians and Pakistanis, the bus
jounced through the potentially hostile territory of India, past
fields of cut hay and the humming factories of the Punjab. Indian
police vehicles escorted it for the eight-hour drive to the
Pakistani border.
</P>
<P>
   The bus carried Amna Khartoum, a toothless 65-year-old woman
from Bombay, to what will probably be a last reunion with her
youngest brother, who lives in Pakistan. A troupe of Pakistani
musicians fresh from a tour of India, an Indian scholar on his way
to do research in Islamabad, and bearded Muslim holy men going to a
wedding in Rawalpindi were also aboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only time will tell whether this bus will bring people
together, but it is a good thing that it has started,'' said Rafiq
Sutarrya, an Indian plywood salesman whose sentiments echoed those
of his fellow travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two months ago, the prime minister of India, Atal
Behari Vajpayee, made the inaugural ride on this new bus service.
It links two countries that have fought three wars since 1947 and
whose people have been largely cut off from each other for the
decades since, with only trickles allowed to travel into each
other's territory.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee emerged from the bus at the border and embraced his
Pakistani counterpart, Nawaz Sharif. Since then, the buses that
followed have become icons of the hope for peace and friendship
between two countries born in a paroxysm of religious hatred in
which an estimated million Muslims, Hindus and Sikhs perished.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif, leader of the Muslim nation of Pakistan, and Vajpayee,
head of predominantly Hindu India, promised in February that they
would seek to build closer ties and to overcome their bitter
history.
</P>
<P>
   Whether their bus diplomacy leads to something bigger or turns
into just another symbol of disappointment is now more uncertain
than ever. A nuclear competition between the two countries
continues. And the coalition government Vajpayee heads may lose its
majority in Parliament, possibly within the next week, and Sharif
could find himself without his dance partner.
</P>
<P>
   But high-level politics seemed to be the last thing on the minds
of passengers, who had each paid $38 for a round-trip ticket. The
Indians and Pakistanis on this Pakistani bus _ India has buses
making the trip too _ spent a couple of hours mesmerized by a
megahit Hindi movie from India _ a sugary romantic musical called
``Kuch Kuch Hota Hai'' (``Something Is Happening''), which played
on a screen suspended at the front of the bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Pakistan and India, the music is the same, the languages
are similar,'' said Fakhar Zaman, who plays the harmonium in a
well-known Qawwal, or traditional Sufi, musical group from Pakistan
that had just finished performing to packed houses in India.
``There are no barriers.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When the movie ended, the passengers dozed or sat staring
wordlessly out the windows. Most were either going to or coming
from family visits.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Khartoum, her stooped shoulders wrapped in a shawl of black
lace, was lost in thoughts of a past she had been unable to share
with the much younger brother she was on her way to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my mother was dying,'' she said, recalling a day when she
was a young woman and her brother but a boy, ``she put him on my
lap and said: `Look after him. He's yours.'''
</P>
<P>
   But that was 45 years ago. After her mother died, her father
moved with his young son to Pakistan to live with family there.
Mrs. Khartoum, who had just married, remained in India. On opposite
sides of the border, Mrs. Khartoum and her brother, a ship worker,
have seen each other only a few times in the intervening decades.
</P>
<P>
   On two earlier trips to Pakistan, she had taken an Indian train
to the border. There it had taken a grueling 12 hours to get
through customs. Once on the other side of the border, she had
boarded a Pakistani train.
</P>
<P>
   Her grown sons agreed to let their spindly, ailing mother go
this time, accompanied by her daughter and grandchildren, only
because she could take a comfortable, air-conditioned bus straight
through from New Delhi to Lahore, with a stop of only an hour or
two to clear customs at the border.
</P>
<P>
   Still haunted by the promise she made to her mother, Mrs.
Khartoum said she felt she had to see her brother one last time.
``I'm like his mother,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The bus has also opened a new route for cultural exchanges
between the countries. The Qawwali group, led by Badar Ali Khan,
has made two tours of India since Vajpayee's bus trip to Pakistan.
Their manager was able to get them visas in a day, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The young men, dressed in flowing white shalwar kameez, the
traditional dress of Pakistani men, said they wished the border
between Pakistan and India was as easy to cross as that between the
United States and Canada, where they have performed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we drove by car to Canada, the Americans just had to show
their drivers' licenses,'' said Fez Fareed Khan, who plays the
harmonium. ``If you could do that between India and Pakistan, life
would be easier for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Zaman, the group's pessimist, said, ``It can't happen here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Inshallah,'' replied the fatalistic chorus singer, Munawar
Hussein. ``God willing, it shall be done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
