<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kind words about Wohlers fill Braves clubhouse
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ If there were hard feelings that Mark Wohlers
refused his minor league assignment and thereby effectively ended
his Braves career, they were hard to find around the Braves
clubhouse on Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he feels he needs a different change of scenery,'' Ryan
Klesko said. ``We're going to definitely miss him. We're all
pulling for him, especially with the way he threw in the spring. I
figured he'd go down (to the minor leagues) and get right again.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Cox called Wohlers in Atlanta on Monday afternoon
to wish him well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's smart on his part,'' Cox said. ``There will be 29
clubs clamoring to get him. I think a fresh start will be good for
him. I'm pulling for him. I hope he goes to the American League and
shoots lights out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have until 2 p.m. Friday to trade or release Wohlers.
If they release him, they owe him his $5.2 million salary, plus the
$800,000 buyout for his option year. If they trade him, they will
likely only get compensated for a small fraction of Wohlers'
salary. Either way, the business relationship is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess he's my ex-teammate now, but he's still my friend,''
Greg Maddux said. ``Obviously he feels going to a different
organization is in his own best interest and I support him 100
percent. I totally understand. Am I surprised? Yeah, but I think
you're always surprised the first time something like this
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Chipper Jones: ``I would have liked to see him work his
problems out in Atlanta. But a guy's got to do what a guy's got to
do. Maybe a change of scenery will help him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullpen health update
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Mike Remlinger has played catch each of the last two
days and has his eye on returning to action when he's eligible to
come off the disabled list on Sunday when the Braves are in Denver.
Remlinger has been on the DL since April 3 with a pulled lat muscle
in his back. He's been treating it with heat and taking
anti-inflammatory medicine. He plans to test it by throwing a
little harder on Wednesday....
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Kevin McGlinchy had to leave Monday's game after taking
a hard hit ball in the right hand off the bat Mike Lieberthal in
the eighth inning. McGlinchy's hand was bruised around the base of
his right thumb. He'll re-evaluate it on Thursday after taking
today off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sore,'' McGlinchy said. ``But no bone, just flesh. I'll
see (Thursday) if the grip bothers me.''...
</P>
<P>
   John Rocker had back spasms on Monday and was unavailable to
pitch, Cox said. So Rudy Seanez pitched the final two outs of the
eighth and the entire ninth and picked up his first save of the
season along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Boyz II Men, the singing group from Philadelphia, was scheduled
to perform the national anthem before Monday's game but cancelled
when only two of the four singers were late. Group spokesman
Quadree El-Amin sent along their apologies, saying they got stuck
in traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
