<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990412.0334 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5329 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-12 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: RUSSIAN ROULETTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talk about strange bedfellows ...
</P>
<P>
   The game of footsie that Israel's prime minister, Benjamin
Netanyahu, and his foreign minister, Ariel Sharon, have been
playing lately with Yevgeny Primakov, Russia's prime minister,
surely takes the cake.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing wrong with Israel's trying to foster better
ties with Moscow in hopes of eliciting Russian cooperation in the
Middle East. In fact, if done in a sophisticated, strategic
fashion, it could really make sense. But to launch such an
initiative, primarily in order to gain Russian votes in Israel's
upcoming election _ after years of hammering on the White House,
Congress and U.S. Jewish groups to impose sanctions on Russia _ and
then to do it without any prior coordination with Israel's closest
ally, America, is reckless.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's recent visit to Moscow _ and Sharon's decision to
tone down any criticism of the Serbs and to be restrained in his
support for NATO's operation in Kosovo _ appear driven by poll
numbers: Russian Jews now make up 15 percent of the Israeli
electorate. Netanyahu understands from his polling that he is in
trouble with his traditional supporters among both Sephardic Jews
and nationalist settlers. The Sharon-Netanyahu strategy is to
compensate for that weakness by winning over the vast majority of
Israel's new Russian immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   But these are not your grandmother's Russian Jews _ those who
left Russia as ``refuseniks'' in the 1970s, with bitter memories of
Cossacks and commissars. This recent huge influx of Russian Jews to
Israel left the former Soviet Union freely, after the collapse of
Communism, and they still have some warm feelings about Mother
Russia, and many business dealings. So the Netanyahu-Sharon
strategy has been to cultivate the Russian vote by cultivating the
Russian government. During Netanyahu's recent trip to Moscow, word
was ``leaked'' to Israeli reporters that Primakov said that if he
were an Israeli he would vote for Bibi.
</P>
<P>
   Says the Haaretz diplomatic writer David Makovsky: ``When you
think of everything that Primakov represents for Israelis _ we're
talking about a guy who boasts that he has good chemistry with
Saddam Hussein _ it boggles the mind that someone would want his
endorsement.''
</P>
<P>
   Primakov leaked his endorsement of Netanyahu the same day he
departed for Washington to win U.S. backing for a new IMF loan.
Shortly after, Netanyahu personally asked the IMF to give the
Russians the $4.8 billion loan they were seeking. This after months
of Israel asking the United States to suspend emergency aid to
Moscow until Russia stopped selling nuclear materials to Iran.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't get much more cynical than this _ just
coincidentally a month before Israeli elections, Bibi suddenly
starts chasing after the Russians,'' says one senior U.S. official.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish lobbying organizations on Capitol Hill refuse to comment
on Israel's Russia adventures. But at a time when these lobbyists
have been trying to persuade Congress to squeeze Moscow to curtail
Russian business deals with Israel's enemies, the Jewish lobbying
groups are clearly upset and feeling that Israel's out-of-the-blue
overture to Moscow is compromising their effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``A high proportion of Israel's international strength derives
from its close relationship with Washington,'' said Itamar
Rabinovich, the former Israeli Ambassador to the U.S. and the
author of a smart new book on Israeli-Arab relations called
``Waging Peace.'' ``But if that Israeli influence in Washington is
abused, and relations are undermined, Israel will find itself with
empty pockets in dealing with other parts of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder that Israel's top military analyst, Ze'ev Schiff,
wrote that ``Sharon's Russia strategy, in which the U.S. decidedly
plays second fiddle, infuriates [Defense Minister Moshe) Arens. ...
The initiative, maintains Arens, hobbles Israel's struggle against
the immediate Iranian threat to our survival, a threat that Russia
is promoting. Principally, however, argues Arens, the issue could
undermine Israeli-American relations.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the same old story with Bibi. His defense minister
is pulling one way, his foreign minister another, and he shuttles
between the two depending on which position will advance his
political interests today. The only strategy is political and the
only sacred principles are what will get him re-elected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 1930EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990412.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5330 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEX-FEMALELIBIDO-TEX     04-12 1379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEX-FEMALELIBIDO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT JUST IN YOUR BEDROOM: WOMEN IN 20S AND 30S TURNING AWAY
FROM SEX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It used to be that she never stopped thinking about it,
anticipating yet another romantic encounter with her husband. She
bought sexy lingerie, painted her toenails and shaved her legs.
</P>
<P>
   And then the children came. First a son and then another one 18
months ago. As responsibilities soared at her home, at her private
law practice, in the community, her libido sagged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now when I crawl into bed at night, all I want is to read a
little bit,'' the 40-year-old attorney says. ``The last thing on my
mind is sex, and unfortunately that's night after night after
night.''
</P>
<P>
   If this seems like a singular existence or one limited to the
baby-boomer crowd, that is hardly the case. Contrary to popular
belief, everyone is not having more and better sex than you.
</P>
<P>
   In fact there is so little going on _ for lack of female libido
_ in the nation's bedrooms, it has inspired a book by former model
and television talk-show host Cristina Ferrare.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled to be in bookstores nationwide next month, ``Okay So I
Don't Have a Headache: What I Learned (And What All Women Need to
Know) About Hormones, PMS, Stress, Diet, Menopause _ And Sex'' is
the 49-year-old Ferrare's first-person account of her sleeping
libido and what she did to restore the passion in her marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrare says she had been struggling with limited libido for
three years, when she suddenly blurted out on national television
that she had lost interest in sex and feared for her marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Then ``The Oprah Winfrey Show'' and ``Dateline'' called to
interview her about her public revelation. After those shows, she
heard from thousands of other women suffering from the same
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judging from the responses I received, women who want it are
in the minority,'' says Ferrare, who is scheduled to appear on
``Oprah'' again in May. ``Most of the women I talk to are having a
real problem.''
</P>
<P>
   But what surprised her most, Ferrare says, is that the majority
of women who wrote to her are ages 24 to 38.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I was ready to help my fellow baby boomers get through
this transition,'' she writes in ``Okay,'' ``when I realized that
this was a larger, more serious problem than I thought, involving
women of all ages.''
</P>
<P>
   According to research published this year in the Journal of the
American Medical Association, more than 40 percent of American
women ages 18 to 59 report some sort of sexual dysfunction, such as
lacking interest in or enjoyment of sex, performance anxiety, or
inability to achieve or hold off orgasm. In addition, it said that
women ages 18 to 39 were slightly more likely than older women to
report a lack of interest in sex or performance anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much more common than reaches the ear of physicians
because problems with sexuality are among the most difficult to
discuss,'' says Dr. Marianne Legato, founder-director of the
Partnership for Women's Health at Columbia University. ``I think
it's time we pulled up the shade and let some light in on what is
obviously a very difficult subject to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ferrare went to her doctor, she found that a lack of
testosterone in her body was key to her loss of sexual interest.
The doctor prescribed a testosterone cream, she says, that put her
back in the mood and thrilled her husband.
</P>
<P>
   But because she was facing menopause, Ferrare says she wanted to
find out more about how hormone levels affect the body and how
``everything we do and eat affects our hormone levels.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Okay, So I Don't Have a Headache,'' which includes excerpts
from some of the letters she received and 50 pages of recipes that
helped to improve her diet and overall well-being, is a candid and
often witty account of what she went through and what she learned
along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times when I was writing the book, my husband asked,
`Do you have to leave that in?''' she recalls, laughing. ``But he's
really proud of what I've done, because if this can help one
husband understand what a woman goes through, I've done a great
service.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   TWO WOMEN'S STORIES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Annette is a 38-year-old Fort Worth librarian and mother of four
children. Her sex life with her husband of five years comes down to
this: once or twice a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be every day,'' she says. ``Now I don't even think
about it. I don't want to touch. I don't want to kiss.''
</P>
<P>
   But not unlike the 40-year-old attorney, who asked not to be
identified, she only makes love with her husband when she starts to
feel guilty.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney says: ``He wants to know what's wrong with me. I
tell him I'm still attracted to him. I don't fully understand it
myself so it's hard to explain to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Both women say they have sought help from their physicians, and
both doctors attributed the problem to stress.
</P>
<P>
   But other experts say that, in all likelihood, it is probably
more than that.
</P>
<P>
   Legato and Dr. Joseph McWherter, a Fort Worth obstetrician and
gynecologist who specializes in hormone replacement, say that a
loss of libido may signal any range of physical impairments,
including hormonal imbalance, poor nutrition, depression and
fatigue from chronic sleep deprivation. It can also be caused by
negative emotions like anger or anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many times women will come to me and say, `My sex life with my
husband is nonexistent,'' says Legato. ``And I say, `What about on
vacation?' and they say, `It's fine.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen many women responsible for small children abandon
all need for a personal life because the needs of the children are
so compelling. Somebody once said, for example, that it's hard to
play an active game of tennis and feel depressed at the same
moment. I think that when we are in situations of intense demand,
luxury functions like introspection, meditation, and libido are
suspended.''
</P>
<P>
   McWherter says that 40 percent to 50 percent of women he sees
each week are complaining of some problem with libido, often
related to job stress and marriage difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this, McWherter recently decided to add a question
about libido on his patient questionnaire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them are not going to talk about it unless it's
asked,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of suffering in silence, doctors say women should be
proactive when it comes to their sexual health.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every woman who feels her sexual desire has changed
should have a complete physical exam to make sure there is no
condition that would make it difficult for her,'' says Legato.
``That's easier than going on and not having any possibility of
knowing what is wrong. I have never met a patient who didn't feel
better after at least inquiring about it.''
</P>
<P>
   McWherter says that in his practice, low testosterone levels in
women have been a common problem.
</P>
<P>
   The male hormone does three basic things, he says. ``It gives a
woman a sense of well-being, provides an energy boost and is linked
with improved libido and also is responsible for the sensitivity of
the clitoris, so it enhances orgasm.''
</P>
<P>
   Estrogen also plays an important role in libido, McWherter says,
because in many cases it relieves such symptoms as depression,
anxiety, fatigue and insomnia, all things that suppress the sex
drive.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrare admits she was skeptical when her doctor prescribed the
testosterone cream for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I walked out of the office, I said to myself `This cannot
be this easy,''' she recalls. ``But it worked. I'm not back to
where I was when I was 19 or 20, but at least when my husband
reaches for me, I respond.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   FYI: For more information about women's health during menopause,
contact Vitality For Life at (202) 263-0125 or its Web site,
www.menopausehealth.com.
</P>
<P>
   Also on April 30, the Office of Research on Women's Health of
the National Institutes of Health will co-sponsor a symposium,
``Gender and Human Sexuality,'' at the National Press Club in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Okay, So I Don't Have a Headache,'' St. Martin's Press,
Tentative price $19.95
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
