<HEADER>
A5332 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PULITZER-WINNERS-BOS &LR;      04-12 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PULITZER-WINNERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PULITZERS AWARDED FOR 83RD TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hartford Courant took top honors for its coverage of a
deadly shooting spree at lottery headquarters, and The New York
Times' Maureen Dowd won for her sharp-elbowed commentary on
``Monica-gate'' when the 83d annual Pulitzer Prizes were announced
at Columbia University in New York Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Three news organizations each captured two of the 14 Pulitzers
awarded in the journalism categories. Also at the Times, the news
staff, with Jeff Gerth singled out, won in national reporting for
articles on the sale of American techonology to China, pushing its
total number of Pulitzers to 79. (The Boston Globe is owned by The
New York Times Co.)
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal garnered the international reporting
prize for its coverage of the Russian financial crisis, and the
Journal's Angelo B. Henderson took the feature writing Pulitzer for
his portrait of a man driven to violence after being a crime victim
himself. The Associated Press captured Pulitzers in the spot news
and feature photography categories for its photographs of the
embassy bombings in Kenya and Tanzania and for a collection of
pictures capturing the yearlong White House impeachment scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Pulitzer winners in the letters and drama categories included
Michael Cunningham's ``The Hours'' in the fiction category;
Margaret Edson's play ``Wit'' _ performed last summer at the
Shakespeare and Company in Lenox _ in the drama category; and A.
Scott Berg's ``Lindbergh'' in the biography category. A special
citation was awarded to the late jazz great Edward Kennedy ``Duke''
Ellington, commemorating the centennial year of his birth.
</P>
<P>
   The Courant's breaking news stories on the Connecticut Lottery
massacre in March 1998 in which a gunman killed four coworkers and
then himself, earned the paper its second ever Pulitzer. The story
broke only a month after new editor Brian Toolan took over the
reigns in the newsroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good on behalf of the pros who made it happen,'' said
a celebratory Toolan Monday. ``We at least attempted to to put
answers'' to the lottery tragedy. ``Our narrative approach on how
it happened was exceptional.''
</P>
<P>
   A victorious Dowd _ who helped transform Beltway and New York
Times journalism with her character-based dissections of the
nation's leading politicians _ told the Associated Press Monday,
``My reaction is I'm just so grateful to President Clinton that he
never spoke the words, `Young lady, pull down that jacket and get
back to the typing pool.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Several other leading newspapers also took home Pulitzers
Monday. The Washington Post won in the public service category
(which earns the winner a gold medal instead of the usual $5,000
prize) for a series that examined careless gunplay by municipal
police officers. Chuck Philips and Michael A. Hiltzik of the Los
Angeles Times took beat reporting honors for stories on corruption
in the entertainment industry. And Blair Kamin of the Chicago
Tribune won for criticism for his coverage of Chicago's
architecture, with particular emphasis on the city's famous
lakefront.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Herald earned the Pulitzer in investigative reporting
for unearthing the pervasive voter fraud in a city mayoral election
that was eventually overturned. The (Portland) Oregonian's Richard
Read won a Pulitzer in explanatory reporting for his profile of a
local french fry exporter that illustrated the domestic impact of
the Asian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The editorial board of the (N.Y.) Daily News won in the
editorial writing category for its campaign to rescue the
threatened Apollo Theatre landmark. And the editorial cartooning
winner was David Horsey of the Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   Although The Hartford Courant was the only New England winner,
four Boston entries also made it to the finals of the journalistic
Pulitzer competition. The Boston Globe earned three finalist spots.
Delores Kong's and Robert Whitaker's work disclosing how
psychiatric researchers callously performed drug experiments on
mentally ill patients was a finalist in public service. Globe book
critic Gail Caldwell was a finalist in criticism. And Globe
photographer Bill Greene's images reflecting the work of Donald
Anderson, who helps the residents of poor Southern communities
improve their lives, earned him a finalist designation in feature
photography. Clay Bennett, of The Christian Science Monitor, was a
finalist in editorial cartooning.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the letters and drama competition, Edwin G. Burrows
and Mike Wallace won the history award for ``Gotham: A History of
New York City to 1898'' while the general nonfiction prize was
given to John McPhee for his book ``Annals of the Former World.''
Mark Strand's ``Blizzard of One'' took top honors in the poetry
competition, and the Pulitzer for music was awarded to Melinda
Wagner for ``Concerto for Flute, Strings and Percussion'' which was
premiered last May by the Westchester Philharmonic in Purchase,
N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
