<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEES FACE HARDSHIPS IN MACEDONIAN CAMPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-U.N., KOSOVO-TRAIN, KOSOVO-REFUGEES,
KOSOVO-GERMANY, KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-RUGOVA,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA) 
(lb) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RADUSA, Macedonia _ After fleeing Kosovo with hundreds of
thousands of other ethnic Albanians, Florije Havolli watched in
horror last week as an abscess on her 18-month-old daughter's
throat steadily grew larger. Three separate times, she asked the
Macedonian police ringing the refugee camp here to allow her
daughter, Arietta, to go to a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was having problems breathing,'' Ms. Havolli said. ``She
couldn't drink. She couldn't get milk out of the bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   But Macedonian officials, who run this squalid tent city of
3,000 on a barren hillside in northeastern Macedonia, refused to
allow her to leave or let international aid groups enter. After a
meeting between the Macedonian government and relief agencies on
Saturday, aid agencies were finally allowed to enter the camp.
</P>
<P>
   Relief workers rushed Ms. Havolli's daughter to an Israeli army
field hospital. Dr. Jacob Adler, the pediatrician who treated
Arietta, said she could have died if the abscess had become
infected. ``We escaped from there to save our lives,'' Ms. Havolli
said bitterly. ``Now these people here almost killed my daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Conditions in the camp, international aid workers said, are far
below those of the half-dozen camps erected by NATO soldiers and
run by international aid organizations. The Radusa camp is the
latest example, they said, of the Macedonian government's callous
treatment of 130,000 ethnic Albanian refugees who have poured over
the border from Kosovo in the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Aid workers accuse the government of mistreating refugees as
part of an effort to get them to resettle in camps in neighboring
Albania. Ethnic Macedonians, who make up a majority of the
population here, fear that they could be reduced to a minority in
their own country if ethnic Albanians from Kosovo resettle here.
Before the crisis began, 22 percent of Macedonia's 2 million people
were ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   During the first week refugees poured in from Kosovo, heavily
armed Macedonian policemen corralled a seething mass of 40,000
Albanians in a makeshift refugee camp in the border town of Blace.
</P>
<P>
   With no warning, the Macedonian police then bused and flew the
refugees en masse on Wednesday night to Greece, Turkey, Albania and
a half-dozen smaller camps around the country, including Radusa.
Refugees were beaten by the police and families were separated
during the frenzied process.
</P>
<P>
   Emilija Geleva, an adviser to the Macedonian prime minister,
Ljubco Georgievski, said Macedonia had done its best with limited
resources to care for the refugees. She said aid agencies were
allowed access to the Radusa camp if they were properly registered
with the government.
</P>
<P>
   But aid groups say that they were blocked from entering the camp
and that facilities there must improve. ``Some of the conditions
are unacceptable,'' said Paula Ghedini, a spokeswoman for the U.N.
high commissioner for refugees. ``We are currently negotiating with
the government of Macedonia to take it over.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Radusa, families live in burlap tents on a rock-strewn
hillside with swirling winds that create bitterly cold nights,
refugees said. With no drainage system, a rainstorm on Friday night
sent water coursing down the hillside, flooding tents laid out on
bare ground.
</P>
<P>
   Six latrines serve 3,000 people, a single trash container
overflows with putrid refuse, and there is no running water.
Cardboard boxes lined with plastic bags function as makeshift sinks
where women wash clothes. Dr. Ferko Ory, who is working in the camp
for the group Doctors Without Borders, said he feared the spread of
disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``The water and sanitary facilities are absolutely
unacceptable,'' he said. ``Thirty babies I treated yesterday had
diarrhea.''
</P>
<P>
   In many of the NATO-built camps, by comparison, the health-care
situation has stabilized, septic systems and showers are being
installed, and communal sinks provide running water. Foreign aid
agencies provide services ranging from toys for children to
satellite phones with which refugees tell anxious relatives they
have survived.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees shipped here by the Macedonian police were stunned
to hear of the better conditions in other camps. ``We didn't know
anything _ they just brought us here,'' said Idriz Rexhepi, a
52-year-old farmer living in a tent with his wife. ``I haven't
taken a shower in three weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the alienation, aid workers said, is tight security.
Policemen armed with Kalashnikov assault rifles patrol the camp's
perimeter. Refugees, even if they have money of their own, are not
allowed to venture down the hill into the town to buy food.
Visitors to the camp are not allowed inside, and reunions occur
only through a 6-foot-tall wire mesh fence as a policeman looks on.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Geleva, the Macedonian government official, said the police
were present to halt smuggling. But Astrit Bajrinovci, a
32-year-old refugee whose family lives beside an overflowing trash
container in the camp, said he felt like a prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a concentration camp,'' he said. ``We want to call
our families and tell them we are alive, but we can't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
