<SLUG> BC-HORSEY-PULITZER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARST EDITORIAL CARTOONIST WINS PULITZER PRIZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK, N.Y. _ David Horsey, Seattle Post-Intelligencer
editorial cartoonist, has won the 1999 Pulitzer Prize in Journalism
for editorial cartooning.
</P>
<P>
   The prize, one of the most prestigious awards in American
journalism, is administered by the Columbia University School of
Journalism. The winners were announced Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Pulitzer editorial cartooning honor recognizes ``a
distinguished cartoon or portfolio of cartoons ... characterized by
originality, editorial effectiveness, quality of drawing and
pictorial effect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very exciting day for Hearst Newspapers,'' said
George B. Irish, president of Hearst Newspapers and vice president
of The Hearst Corporation. ``This preeminent honor calls attention
to Hearst Newspapers' long-standing commitment to producing
journalism of distinction. We heartily congratulate David for his
achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   On learning of the Post-Intelligencer's first Pulitzer Prize,
publisher and editor J.D. Alexander said, ``This is great news. We
are enormously proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Horsey, 47, has been on the Post-Intelligencer staff since 1979.
His cartoons are syndicated in more than 450 newspapers and
magazines. Earlier this year, Horsey was named Berryman Cartoonist
of the Year by the National Press Foundation. The Society of
Professional Journalists (SPJ) awarded Horsey first place for
editorial cartooning in the Pacific Northwest in 1996 and 1997,
adding to his 10 first place SPJ regional awards for cartooning,
governmental reporting and spot news reporting.
</P>
<P>
   The Post-Intelligencer is one of 12 daily newspapers published
by The Hearst Corporation. Others include the Houston Chronicle,
San Francisco Examiner, San Antonio Express-News and Albany Times
Union.
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst Corporation is one of the nation's largest
diversified communications companies, with interests in magazine,
newspaper, book and business publishing; television and radio
stations; newspaper comics and features syndication; cable
television networks; television production and syndication, and new
media activities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 1941EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990412.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5341 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-TORNADO-CLEANUP-     04-12 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-TORNADO-CLEANUP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Financial burden the latest storm to hit weary Ohioans
 &HT;    (EDS: Box at end of story with help numbers.)
 &HT;    By Tim Tresslar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARREN COUNTY, Ohio _ After the roar of Friday morning's tornado
faded into the distance, Bill and Joy Pace looked out the window
into the predawn darkness, hoping to see what had just happened.
</P>
<P>
   Darkness prevented the Warren County couple from seeing the
carnage that surrounded their 1834 farmhouse. But the Hamilton Twp.
couple saw something missing _ the trees.
</P>
<P>
   When dawn finally broke, they got a clearer picture: the tornado
had uprooted or snapped 29 beech, white pine and ash trees from
decades-old moorings, tossing them around the couple's property
like toothpicks.
</P>
<P>
   While their insurance will cover structural damage, such as lost
shingles, to their home and barn, they question how they can afford
to remove the downed trees from their property.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how we can do it on our budget,'' Joy Pace said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The couple hopes someone will take the trees for firewood or
lumber.
</P>
<P>
   Residents and officials continued Monday to grapple with the
post-tornado cleanup of Warren, Hamilton and Clinton counties. In
Deerfield Twp. south of Lebanon, for example, state road crews
moved and mulched trees while technicians from Time Warner Cable
and Cinergy worked on downed lines.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents like Patricia Maynes, whose Deerfield Twp. home
was damaged when a tree hit her roof, postponed full-scale cleanup
until her insurance adjustor could assess the damage later this
week. The Paces also awaited a meeting with their insurance agent
before they begin cleaning up the damage.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Young, director of emergency services for Warren County
Emergency Management, said that Federal Emergency Management Agency
officials will visit Warren County today as part of a larger
inspection of southwestern Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Gov. Bob Taft's said Lt. Gov. Maureen O'Conner
will accompany FEMA officials today as they survey the devastation.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Small Business Administration estimates the tornado
damaged 630 homes throughout southwestern Ohio, leaving 130
uninhabitable. SBA officials tallied the damage at $5.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Warren County officials estimate the county sustained about $2.2
million damage.
</P>
<P>
   The SBA hasn't finished assessing the damage to businesses and
the agency postponed a decision on whether to provide disaster
loans until the White House determines whether the region qualifies
for FEMA grants.
</P>
<P>
   In Warren County, Young said state, county and township crews
continue to pick up downed trees in Hamilton and Deerfield
townships, a process he expects to last through the end of the
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seem to be making pretty good progress,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   In Sycamore Twp., workers from the Ohio Department of
Transportation as well as Columbia and Delhi townships used
front-loaders, wood chippers and trucks to remove debris. Countless
volunteers handed out food, carried debris and helped bury pets.
</P>
<P>
   Against a backdrop of piled bricks, scattered clothes and
abandoned children's toys, Sycamore Twp. Administrator Lori
Thompson said township officials look for cleanup to take another
six weeks. On Monday, sheriff's deputies continued to block
affected neighborhoods and township officials limited the number of
volunteers so heavy equipment could remove debris.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson didn't rule out asking the Ohio National Guard for help
in clearing the neighborhood, but said the township first must max
out state transportation crews before seeking help from the guard,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Other northern Cincinnati suburbs affected by the storm also
were continuing cleanup efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect by the end of this coming week, the reconstruction
will be ready to start,'' said Marvin Thompson, city manager of
Blue Ash.
</P>
<P>
   Demolition began over the weekend in Blue Ash. Montgomery
residents have been asked to clear their belongings from severely
damaged homes so demolition can begin Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sycamore Twp. is making contractors register with the township
to cut down on con-men who might prey upon distraught residents
needing home repairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern, obviously, is fraud,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Classes were canceled today in the Sycamore school district,
which encompasses the area. Sycamore High School suffered $1
million in damage and many streets remained closed or clogged with
repair trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot keep kids out of harm's way with so many
construction vehicles on the roads,'' Superintendent Bruce
Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   Red Cross counselors were available to talk to residents
traumatized by the tornado, which touched down during the predawn
hours. Two motorists and a couple swept from their home were
killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like a war. It'll change you,'' said Dr. Edward
Otten, who was at the tornado scene with Hamilton County's Urban
Search and Rescue Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   Lee and Jacque Cook died when the tornado hit their home. Daryl
Coffey of Kings Mills found Cook's gasoline credit card over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm seven or eight miles away from their house,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Lasiewski found a magazine belonging to Cook on top of his
roof in Maineville, in Warren County about five miles away from the
couple's home.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio National Guard will provide relief this week for weary
police departments watching over the ravaged neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the 324th Military Police Co. from Middletown will
help provide security, control traffic and offer other assistance
in Blue Ash and Montgomery beginning today.
</P>
<P>
   The suburbs asked Taft's office for National Guard help on
Sunday, spokesman Scott Milburn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it looks like they're going to basically (help) the
local police, who are obviously in need of some relief. They've
been going strong for the past few days,'' Milburn said.
</P>
<P>
   The unit from Middletown will staff eight one-person posts 24
hours a day in Blue Ash and a couple of two-person posts during
daylight hours.
</P>
<P>
   Staff Sgt. Jim Desrosiers said his troops were guarding damaged
businesses in an industrial park hit hard by the tornado.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the buildings are falling down so we're keeping people
away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Tresslar writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Staff Writer Scott Montgomery of the Washington Bureau and The
Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   How you can help
</P>
<P>
   Area Kroger stores are accepting donations of non-perishable
foods, such as canned and boxed foods and cleaning supplies, such
as bleach and mops.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart stores accepting cleaning supplies and money, which
they will forward to the Salvation Army. Tax break for victims
</P>
<P>
   Families affected by the tornado will get a reprieve from filing
state taxes, with the deadline pushed back from Thursday to Aug.
16, Gov. Bob Taft announced.
</P>
<P>
   Affected families should call (800) 282-4310 to become eligible
for an extension.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
