<HEADLINE>
BOSTON TO HOST OLYMPIC CONGRESS IN 2002 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston has been awarded the rights to host the United States
Olympic Congress in 2002, the Massachusetts Sports Partnership and
the Greater Boston Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 of the most powerful sports leaders in the
country are scheduled to attend the meeting, including heads of the
national governing bodies of individual Olympic sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fairly small event in terms of the revenue the event
itself will produce, locally,'' said Lou Kovacs, the marketing
coordinator of the sports partnership. ``But, with all of the
various officials of all of the individual sports coming in, it is
going to be a real chance to show off Boston as a potential venue
for their championships and other events in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the first time the US Olympic Congress will meet in New
England, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The annual meeting consists of workshops and educational
sessions designed to encourage participation in the Olympics and to
instruct those representing the individual sports about how to
foster sponsorship and licensing relationships, officials said. It
includes an extensive exhibition in which companies display the
goods and services they offer to the Olympics and the sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably going to generate about $1.8 million locally,
considering we need space in three hotels and the fact that the
different groups and organizations will be in town for four or five
days,'' said Patrick B. Moscaritolo, president of the Boston
Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau. ``But, if in the process of showing a
lot of these people our town and the services we can offer for the
various events within their sports it leads to other events, it
could yield tens of millions of dollars, eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic Congress includes a youth program called Champions
In Life in which dozens of Olympians from New England will visit
local middle and high schools to promote sports, education and
Olympic ideals.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting will be among a series of Olympic-related events in
Boston over the next several years, said Soosie L. Lazenby,
president of the sports partnership, a private, nonprofit
corporation established in 1993 to further the development and
growth of sports in the area. Those events include the meeting of
the board of directors of the US Olympic Committee in 2000, the
2000 US Olympic Gymnastics Trials and the 2001 US Figure Skating
Championships.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
