<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5355 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-YUGO-BOS &LR;      04-12 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-YUGO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAVS SEEK `UNION OF SLAVS,' INCLUDING RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Bombing Yugoslavia is one thing. But would NATO dare
take on an alliance armed to the teeth with nuclear weapons and the
latest in anti-aircraft missiles? Say, for example, one that
included Russia?
</P>
<P>
   That is the question Yugoslav lawmakers hoped to raise Monday as
they overwhelmingly voted to include their land in a loose ``Union
of Slavs'' with the former Soviet republics of Belarus and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians in Belarus, a mainly Slavic nation of 10 million
people with strongly anti-Western leaders, applauded the idea. The
same for Russia, a mainly Slavic nation with 6,600 nuclear warheads
and state-of-the-art S-300 anti-aircraft missiles. Neither nation,
however, has formally voted for union.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav supporters of the Slav alliance, proposed by President
Slobodan Milosevic last week, made no secret of the idea that
joining Russia and Belarus' loose confederation had one goal: to
stop the NATO airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our future is in the east, in the embrace of Mother Russia. We
are making this decision under the burden of bombs which has only
speeded it up,'' said Deputy Prime Minister Vojislav Seselj.
Seslelj has been stumping to ally Orthodox Christian Slavs for
years, an idea that used to mark him as a radical nationalist.
</P>
<P>
   In wartime, the idea appeals to other Serbs as well. Outside
parliament in Belgrade, a crowd of about 2,000 greeted Monday's
vote with cries of ``Serbia!'' ``Russia!'' ``Belarus!'' as the
country's leaders cheered what they sought to portray as the end of
Yugoslavia's isolation.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO, the United States and their satellites thought that
Yugoslavia would surrender and remain alone,'' Yugoslav Prime
Minister Momir Bulatovic told parliament after the vote. ``It
neither surrendered nor remained alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Dragan Tomic, the speaker of the parliament of Serbia:
``Yugoslavia has done its part of the job. Russia and Belarus are
now expected to do the same. We hope that will happen soon.''
</P>
<P>
   How soon a Slav union will happen depends partly on Russian
President Boris N. Yeltsin. The volatile Russian leader has given
contradictory signals, but Monday, Yeltsin's foreign minister, Igor
Ivanov, said Moscow ``looked favorably'' on the idea of a Slav
alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin and his government have strongly condemned NATO's
bombardment but have tried to avoid a total break with the West _
such as violating international sanctions against arms shipments to
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the domestic pressure on Yeltsin to take a tough stand
on Yugoslavia may have eased Monday, when the State Duma, the lower
house of parliament, postponed planned impeachment hearings that
had been due to start Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Duma speaker Gennady Seleznyov said last week that a Slav union
would serve as a deterrent against NATO attacks because the US-led
alliance ``would never bomb our allies.''
</P>
<P>
   But for a threat to work, the other side has to perceive it that
way. NATO foreign ministers attending a meeting in Brussels Monday
barely flinched at the Slav union proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Air strikes will be pursued until President Milosevic accedes
to the demands of the international community,'' NATO responded in
a statement. Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright will likely
deliver that message Tuesday to Ivanov in Norway in the first
face-to-face US-Russian talks on Yugoslavia since Moscow suspended
ties with NATO to protest the airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice if the US believed in the westward expansion
of Moscow and Minsk,'' state Russian TV commented, almost
wistfully. ``That would end the war quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   But a Slav union is a tough sell to the outside world. Calls for
Slavic unity ignore NATO's support by Slav nations such as Poland,
Slovakia and the Czech Republic. Cries of Orthodox Christian
solidarity fail to account for Greece, an Orthodox Christian member
of NATO. Appeals to aid the ``brotherly Serbs'' forget that from
1948, when Yugoslav leader Jozip Broz Tito broke ties with Soviet
dictator Josef Stalin, until the mid-1980s, the Kremlin regarded
socialist Yugoslavia with the same suspicion as the democracies of
Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the idea of a union with Yugoslavia has many proponents
here in Russia, already disillusioned by the failure of market
reforms. NATO bombing has sparked anti-Western protests nationwide
here.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian parliament is dominated by people who view
Milosevic's iron rule and anti-Western defiance with nostalgia for
the days when the Soviet Union was like that. Both houses of the
Russian parliament have voted to ask the Kremlin to send arms to
Yugoslavia; both support a Slav union.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to help our Slavic brothers not only in word, but if
necessary with military equipment,'' said Communist Duma member
Sergei Reshulsky, a supporter of union with Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Critics wonder how even a loose confederation with Yugoslavia,
which has no common border with either Russia or Belarus and was
never part of the Soviet Union, would work. Thus far the
Russian-Belarus union has brought few tangible fruits, other than
giving Belarus' authoritarian president, Alexander Lukashenko, a
broad forum in Russia for his calls for the restoration of the
Soviet Union. Lukashenko Monday accepted Milosevic's invitation to
visit Belgrade soon.
</P>
<P>
   Some Russian commentators asked if it made sense to go along
with a deal that seems to force Russia closer to open confrontation
with the West at a time when Moscow is asking for the International
Monetary Fund to help restructure billions in foreign debts. ``If
we form a Union, that means that tomorrow we will have to wage war
against the US and the West, and that would be something Russia can
ill afford to do,'' said Vladimir Lysenko, a centrist Duma
lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   One recent survey of Russians said that although most Russians
condemn NATO attacks against Yugoslavia, only 24 percent want to
send Belgrade military aid. Nor was everyone in Yugoslavia happy
with the idea of a union with Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Predrag Popovic, deputy speaker of legislator in the Yugoslav
republic of Montenegro, described the proposed union as Milosevic's
``last and desperate effort to save his power and the ideology of
which he is a slave.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
