<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5356 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPAQ-HNS &LR;      04-12 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPAQ WILL FACE SALES QUESTIONS AT TRADE SHOW 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Compaq Computer Corp.'s Innovate trade show, which
starts Tuesday, was supposed to be a celebration of its new status
as fully grown computer company.
</P>
<P>
   But instead, its executives will face questions about depressed
sales and profits that sent Compaq's share price crashing Monday,
pulling other personal-computing stocks down with it.
</P>
<P>
   A warning issued Friday that its first-quarter profits would be
half what analysts were expecting is going to be an issue at the
biennial show expected to draw 4,500 high-level customers and 250
journalists to the George R. Brown Convention Center in downtown
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq's announcement was blamed for the Dow Jones Industrial
Average index plunging more than 77 points when the market opened
Monday, though it rebounded aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq's stock on Monday closed down 6 ~ _ or more than 22
percent _ to 24 1/16. The Dow rebounded, however, closing at at
10,330.51, up 165.67.
</P>
<P>
   During a pair of conference calls with analysts on Monday,
Compaq chief executive Eckhard Pfeiffer reiterated the reasons why
his company expects a less-than-stellar performance when final
earnings numbers are released on April 21.
</P>
<P>
   He said a combination of decreased demand for business PCs,
falling prices and customers opting for less-profitable products
will result in profits of about 15 cents a share on sales of $9.4
billion. Analysts had been expecting 32 cents a share on sales of
$9.7 billion to $9.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our preliminary results clearly did not meet our
expectations,'' Pfeiffer said.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer said during the call that Compaq is not the only
PC-maker being buffeted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been significant changes in the technology
marketplace, and all major PC suppliers have experienced them,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts disagreed, saying the issues appear to be confined
to Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone else is having a bad quarter,'' said
Michael Kwatinetz, an analyst with Credit Suisse First Boston in
New York. ``I follow Dell, Gateway, Apple, Hewlett-Packard and
Micron Electronics. All five are having decent quarters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a little surprised (at Pfeiffer's assertions) because
we are not seeing broad signs of a slowdown,'' said Andrew Neff, an
analyst with Bear, Stearns in New York.
</P>
<P>
   A large part of Compaq's problem is that the business PC market
is beginning to resemble the consumer arena. Businesses are
beginning to snap up lower-priced PCs that can easily handle the
same tasks as more expensive, state-of-the-art systems.
</P>
<P>
   But these lower-priced systems carry smaller profits. Even if
Compaq sells more of the cheaper products, it is not enough to make
up the difference in profits.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer said sales ``across the commercial sector'' have been
soft in North America; Europe has been slightly stronger. In
addition, intense competition has forced Compaq to keep prices low.
</P>
<P>
   Add to this the fact that first-quarter business PC sales are
traditionally slow.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer also sought to kill speculation that recent moves by
Compaq to sell more computers directly to the public have hurt the
company's relationship with resellers, the middlemen who
traditionally have peddled Compaq's PCs to businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our relationship with the channel is excellent, let me say
that very loud and clear,'' Pfeiffer said.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq created an entire line of PCs just to be sold via the Web
and over the phone. The company sought to assuage resellers by
offering a bounty for each customer they sold.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Compaq expanded its direct-sales Prosignia line,
allowing customers to buy the machines in retail stores as well.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Hill with First Call, which monitors analyst ratings on
companies, said nine of 27 analysts contacted had cut their ratings
and earnings expectations on Compaq the year as well as the
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are viewing this as a more-than-one-quarter problem,''
Hill said.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
