u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-KOSOVO-BOS &LR;      04-12 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-KOSOVO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO NOT HIGH ON CONGRESS' AGENDA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nearly three weeks after NATO bombing of Yugoslavia
began, Congress is returnsing to work this week with no clear
agenda on how to deal with the conflict. Proposed resolutions are
being circulated that variously call for sending in ground troops
or withdrawing all funding for the operation, but no consensus has
emerged.
</P>
<P>
   And no votes are likely this week, both leaders of the House and
Senate signaled Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not expect to have any votes regarding Kosovo this
week,'' House Speaker Dennis Hastert said in a statement Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott told GOP officials he did not
plan to open a floor debate on Kosovo this week.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, Hastert and two other congressional leaders from each
party met Monday night with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Before the meeting, a number of Democrats and Republicans urged
Clinton not to rule out the use of ground troops in Kosovo, which
some believe will be necessary to expel Serbian forces. Some
senators, including Democrats Edward M. Kennedy and John F. Kerry
of Massachusetts, said Monday that the option of ground troops
should be kept open in order to keep pressure on Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exit strategy is victory, which to me means the capacity
to have an autonomous and safe Kosovo,'' Kerry said. ``I am very
clear that it should never have been taken off the table as an
option. Hopefully it is something you should never have to use.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has said from the start of the Kosovo conflict that it
would not be necessary to send ground troops to the region. Monday,
Defense Secretary William S. Cohen reiterated that position, saying
there was ``no need'' for ground troops, and that ``we would not
even consider it'' unless conditions change.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's actions in Kosovo may be increasing support in
Congress for ground troops. Senator Christopher Dodd, the
Connecticut Democrat, who just returned from a visit to refugee
camps over the border from Kosovo in Macedonia, said any doubts
about the operation were erased by his trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the message that we send in the next 48, 72 hours out
of this Congress on this issue, I think, could have a huge effect
on the outcome of this conflict,'' Dodd said. If Congress sends a
divided message, ``I think you extend this conflict a lot longer
than necessarily need be the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodd and others who support the possibility of ground troops
said they are concerned that ruling out such an option would tell
Milosevic he can remain in Kosovo as long as he is willing to
sustain the air attacks.
</P>
<P>
   But Senator Byron Dorgan, Democrat of North Dakota, said the
introduction of ground troops ``could be a very, very significant
mistake.'' He said, ``NATO allies have a special responsibility
especially in their neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo conflict has put many members of Congress in unusual
positions. For example, Kennedy and Kerry, who both initially
opposed the Persian Gulf War, are among a majority of senators who
last month backed airstrikes in Kosovo and now are urging that the
option of ground troops be kept open.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, many Republicans who normally would be
considered hawks, including Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
voted last month to oppose airstrikes. Lott has since stayed mostly
quiet on the matter, not wanting to speak against the Kosovo action
while US troops are engaged in a battle overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate this week could begin debates over Kosovo, but the
format has not been set. The Senate, for example, could do
everything from voting on a ``sense of the Senate'' resolution to
approving a declaration of war, which hasn't been done since World
II.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is an appetite and desire to have some kind of
discussion about this,'' said Lott's spokesman, John Czwartacki.
``The question is what the vehicle is for that discussion to take
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, in his statement, said congressional committees will
hold hearings on Kosovo in the coming days. Furthermore, he said,
``at the end of this week, a senior delegation from the House will
fly to the region and further investigate the situation in Kosovo.
I have instructed this delegation to make report about the latest
situation in the Balkans upon their return.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
