<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5366 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANCOCK-PUBLIC-BOS &LR;      04-12 0431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANCOCK-PUBLIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANCOCK MAY MOVE UP DEMUTUALIZATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Encouraged by strong 1998 earnings and a stock market
that regularly hits record highs, John Hancock Mutual Life
Insurance Co. said Monday it would seek to speed up plans to
convert to a publicly traded company and sell shares to investors
in the first quarter of 2000, three months earlier than originally
targeted.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock, like other mutual insurers, is owned by its
policyholders, not stockholders. A host of other mutual insurers,
including giants Prudential Insurance Co. of America and
Metropolitan Life Insurance Co., are seeking to convert to publicly
traded companies _ a process known as demutualization _ to gain
access to capital and expand their business.
</P>
<P>
   Providing 1998 figures Monday at its annual shareholders meeting
in Boston, Hancock reported a 19.2 percent rise in net gain from
operations last year, to $627 million. Net gain from operations is
the statutory measure of operating profit for a mutual life
insurance company, and excludes realized capital gains and losses.
</P>
<P>
   Management surplus, or capital, rose 8.2 percent to a healthy
$4.7 billion, reflecting the firm's increasingly conservative
approach to its core insurance business. Capital is the amount of
extra funds available after all obligations to policyholders,
employees, and creditors have been met, and is a measure of a
firm's financial strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Hancock continues to experience excellent growth and
profitability,'' chief executive Stephen L. Brown said in a
statement. ``We had superior financial results, solid growth in
assets, and our ratings of financial quality continue to be among
the highest in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown told shareholders that the company tentatively planned to
go public in the first three months of next year, Hancock spokesman
Brian Carmichael said. The state Division of Insurance, which
regulates mutual insurance companies, must approve the company's
demutualization plan.
</P>
<P>
   An insurance industry analyst who requested anonymity speculated
that Hancock might be speeding up its plans as a result of the
strong stock market and a favorable environment for initial public
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock, the state's largest insurer, saw assets under
management rise 10.2 percent last year to $124.4 billion. Retail
sales of life and long-term insurance, mutual funds, and annuities
_ accounting for over half of Hancock's business _ rose 9 percent
to $680 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
