<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5367 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-ART-65     04-12 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-ART-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MILITARY PRESENCE IN ALBANIA ALREADY SIZABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ As the debate about committing ground troops
to Yugoslavia continues, the American military already has a
sizable presence here, backed by a fleet of Sea Dragon helicopters
and tons of equipment with more on the way.
</P>
<P>
   The nearly 500 American military personnel here are, for the
time being, dedicated primarily to delivering aid to refugees.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday morning, American soldiers manned the gates to Rinas
Airport, Albania's most important airfield. U.S. Air Force
personnel have also taken almost complete charge of the airport's
air-traffic control tower following last week's vote by the
Albanian Parliament to effectively surrender control of Albanian
airspace and military bases to the allied forces.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, Belgium, NATO officials said there was no intention
of introducing ground troops into Yugoslavia, but they warned
Yugoslavia against attempting to widen the conflict by provoking
other countries.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Albania's president, Rexhep Meidani, accused the
Yugoslavs of trying to widen the scope of the fighting by attacking
a northern Albanian village over the weekend. Two Albanian
civilians were killed and eight others wounded; a man identified as
a French reporter was also wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Meidani vowed to ``resist all types of provocation'' and to
continue supporting the NATO allies in every way possible.
</P>
<P>
   That includes allowing the U.S. Air Force to install
sophisticated navigational and guidance systems and to station
troops at the Rinas Airport, which handles both commercial and
military operations.
</P>
<P>
   The equipment allowed the airstrip to be used in the dark for
the first time overnight Sunday. Big C-17s and other cargo planes
are landing on average every hour throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   American military officials say their primary mission is to
provide relief supplies to the hundreds of thousands of Kosovo
refugees in remote camps in Albania. But advance teams from the
U.S. Army were beginning to work on preparations to receive 24
Apache helicopters. They are expected to fly missions against
Yugoslav forces, either from a portion of the airport, or from a
nearby location, officers said.
</P>
<P>
   Deployment of the Apaches has been delayed by the primitive
conditions of the Albanian airstrips. Establishing fueling,
maintenance and security services for the Apaches and their support
crews are the Army advance team's immediate focus, said Air Force
Maj. Thomas Dolney, a military spokesman at Rinas Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The airport, on the outskirts of Tirana, is so badly rundown and
ill equipped that when the first relief supplies and military
equipment arrived here more than two weeks ago, there was not one
working forklift available to help unload the aircraft that brought
them. The airstrip was built between the First and Second World
Wars, and was extended by Italian occupation forces.
</P>
<P>
   During the long period of Albania's isolation after World War
II, when most Albanians were not allowed to leave the country and
few outsiders were permitted to enter, the airport was used
primarily by the longtime dictator, Enver Hoxha, to greet communist
dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the American troops, 150 French military personnel,
and troops from Greece, Turkey and Italy, appear to be working
together at Rinas Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot more multinational cooperation than I've seen on
other missions,'' said Chief Warrant Officer Steven Weagle, a
25-year veteran now with the Sea Dragon team from the minesweeper
USS Inchon, anchored in the Adriatic Sea. ``Everybody's fired up
about being involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gregory Geisen of the Navy's 6th Fleet headquarters said the
addition Monday of 10 heavy-duty MH-53E Sea Dragon helicopters had
significantly increased the ability to lift food, blankets and
other relief supplies to hard-pressed refugee camps like those at
Kukes, in northern Albania.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The helicopters can carry up to 16 tons of equipment and can
make several trips daily.
</P>
<P>
   That will relieve some of the pressure on the French forces,
which have been providing the bulk of the transportation of relief
supplies until now. In all, the relief supplies are being
transported by 11 different organizations, including the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   While American troops tried to erect their tents near muddy
fields Monday, the dusty Rinas airstrip was covered with pallets of
blankets, high nutrition drinks and sacks of wheat. The deliveries
are being coordinated by the U.N. high commissioner for refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian Parliament voted last week to offer the NATO allies
control of the airspace over the nation to coordinate relief and
military efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the widest possible expression of support,'' said
Mentor Nazarko, an assistant to Meidani.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian troops remain at Rinas Airport, but mostly are involved
in controlling traffic at the entrance gate and assisting in
handling security.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working in cooperation with the Albanians,'' said
Dolney, of the Air Force, ``but the U.S. controls the airspace.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, a French commando team on a rescue mission landed
two Puma helicopters in a remote area of northern Albania where
members of the Kosovo Liberation Army are believed to have set up
camp. The commandos were responding to the reports about the French
reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Guillaume de Saint-Bon said the helicopters, carrying
three doctors and 10 commandos, landed near a soccer stadium in
Bajram Curri, the provincial capital of the Tropoja region in
northern Albania, near the border with Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian officials said that Yugoslav forces fired mortar rounds
and used automatic weapons against a group of border policemen and
Albanian civilians at a remote border crossing, the latest in a
series of such incidents.
</P>
<P>
   Two Albanians died when their car was hit with a mortar shell,
an Albanian official said. Eight others were wounded.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian government said it had evacuated civilians from the
area where the skirmish took place. Albania will respond to further
aggression by the Yugoslavs, said Nazarko, of the Albanian
president's office, but will not cross the border into Yugoslav
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. de Saint-Bon did not know the identity of the man who was
said to be a French reporter, but said the man's thigh bone had
been shattered by a bullet. The man was flown back to Rinas Airport
Monday morning, where he was transferred to an ambulance and taken
to a local hospital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
