<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBINSON-HUMPHREY-HDEPOT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home Depot builds e-commerce presence
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Home Depot is nearly ready to test two new business
ventures, including a long-anticipated shot at electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based retailer is revamping its Web site to handle
online sales as early as this summer, said Marshall Day, senior
vice president of finance and accounting. A new version of Home
Depot's Web page, which will feature more interactive elements,
will launch next month, Day said Monday at Robinson-Humphrey Co.'s
28th Institutional Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The conference, which continues today and half-day Wednesday,
features executives of more than 170 companies who discuss the
challenges and strategies of their businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot won't say what products it will sell online.
Maintenance Warehouse, the company's mail-order subsidiary that
sells plumbing, lighting and hardware to owners of office buildings
and apartments, will process orders. Day indicated that the company
is still working out pricing issues.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Villager's Hardware, the company's smaller
convenience concept, will open its first store in June in East
Brunswick, N.J. Aiming at the small-project customer who wants to
avoid the sprawling warehouse stores, the new format is less than
half the size of a Home Depot. Two more stores will open in the
next 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Villager's Hardware will overlap less with Home Depot than
originally planned, Day said. For example, the stores will carry
small appliances, as well as more cleaning and storage products
than Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   New stores are driving most of Home Depot's sales and earning
growth. Home Depot expects to continue to increase its store count
by at least 21 percent annually. By the end of 2002, the company
will have 1,600 stores, more than double its current size.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot's recent expansion of proprietary brands is helping
to drive sales at existing stores. The Ridgid tool brand, launched
last year, has been a success, Day said, and six new products will
hit stores later this year. A new line of General Electric water
heaters is also being rolled out. The company is betting on
continued growth by courting the contractor market.
</P>
<P>
   Patti Bond writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
