<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5379 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-2TAKES-NY     04-12 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT NATO MEETING, FOREIGN MINISTERS VOW TO KEEP THE PRESSURE UP
</HEADLINE>
   (ac) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ NATO's foreign ministers pledged Monday to
keep up the air attacks against Yugoslavia but at the same time
searched for the shape of a political settlement in Kosovo and
urged Russia to be part of it.
</P>
<P>
   At the first gathering of the 19 ministers since the bombing
began, the allies joined in reaffirming their basic demands of
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, stating that he must
withdraw his forces from Kosovo, allow Albanian refugees back and
permit the stationing of an international military presence.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the show of solidarity, there did not appear to be
any concrete plan or method to achieve those ends, save an effort
to bring Moscow in to serve as a bridge between the alliance and
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who
is attending the gathering, said that there was no agreement among
the allies on the form Kosovo would take but that ``some kind of an
international protective status'' was the most common thread in all
of the ideas.
</P>
<P>
   On the fighting front, as NATO maintained the military pressure
against Yugoslavia, Serbian authorities said that a NATO missile
hit a passenger train on Monday in southeastern Serbia, killing at
least nine people and badly injuring 16 others. At NATO
headquarters, a spokesman said ``we cannot dismiss the reports of
casualties,'' but that they could not be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   As for the refugees, a NATO spokesman said allied military
planners have been asked to come up with ways of air-dropping
supplies to an estimated 260,000 ethnic Albanians believed to be
stranded in Kosovo after being evicted from their homes by Serb
forces. So far, air drops have been ruled out because of the danger
of Serb ground fire aimed at pilots flying at low altitudes, and
the chance of supplies falling into Serb hands.
</P>
<P>
   Washington officials said last week that a total of up to
700,000 Albanians were believed to be displaced inside Kosovo and
that their lack of food was of growing concern.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these people, still at great risk from Serbian forces,
were believed to have found temporary accommodation with relatives.
But even for those with some shelter, food shortages were alarming,
the administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In northern Albania and in Macedonia, officials said that the
dismal physical conditions for the estimated 500,000 Albanians
expelled from Kosovo were beginning to improve as more tents, food
and other supplies were flown in from Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the effort to draw the Russians into the NATO
diplomatic effort, Albright is scheduled to meet with Russian
Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov in Oslo on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   French President Jacques Chirac spoke by telephone on Monday to
the Russian president, Boris Yeltsin, and said afterwards he was
encouraged by the Yeltsin's ``positive'' attitude.
</P>
<P>
   In another diplomatic effort, the U.N. secretary-general, Kofi
Annan, who backed NATO's demands against Milosevic last week, was
expected to join European Union leaders on Wednesday for a meeting
about Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Annan said in New York on Monday that he was prepared to meet
with Milosevic if it would help resolve the conflict. At a press
conference at U.N. headquarters, Annan said he had written to the
Yugoslav leader on Saturday to underscore the five-point appeal he
issued the day earlier, which, among other things, calls on
Yugoslavia to stop at once its ``campaign of intimidation and
expulsion of the civilian population'' from Kosovo and to permit
``refugees to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My good offices are available in any situation,'' Annan said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said they welcomed the entrance
of Annan onto the Kosovo stage. A third party in addition to the
United States and NATO would almost certainly be needed when the
time came to deal with Milosevic, they said.
</P>
<P>
   In talks with Albright on Monday, the Greek foreign minister,
George Papandreou, offered to try and arrange with the Belgrade
authorities for food to be shipped across the borders of Macedonia,
Albania and Montenegro into Kosovo, a Greek government official
said. A non-governmental Greek agency was still operating inside
Kosovo and could be a conduit for the supplies, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   In discussing some kind of ``international protective'' status
for Kosovo, the foreign ministers had clearly moved beyond that
peace proposal fashioned in Rambouillet. It called for an
autonomous Kosovo within Serbia, a NATO-led force of 28,000
soldiers and the disarming of the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overtaken by events,'' was how Albright referred to elements
of the agreement that she spent days crafting in the French town of
Rambouillet.
</P>
<P>
   That accord, signed by the ethnic Albanians but not the Serbs,
called for about 5000 Serb police and Yugoslav soldiers to be
stationed in and around Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, Albright said that for the 500,000 ethnic
Albanian refugees to return to Kosovo as the allies demanded, all
Serb and Yugoslav forces would have to leave.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees would not return to Kosovo if they were vulnerable
to being ``terrorized'' by the very forces that had expelled them,
she said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   France and Germany stressed on Monday that they wanted U.N.
involvement, or at least endorsement, of any plan for post-conflict
Kosovo. On this point, the French foreign minister, Hubert Vedrine,
was unambiguous.
</P>
<P>
   For a political settlement in Kosovo to be acceptable, the U.N.
Security Council would have to be involved, Vedrine said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because this is a matter of the principles that govern
international relations, the whole of the international community
should be involved and first of all the United Nations Security
Council,'' he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The German foreign minister, Joschka Fischer, was less adamant
about the Security Council's involvement but said that a mandate
from the United Nations for any security force that entered Kosovo
was ``desirable.''
</P>
<P>
   One question that remained unresolved centered around under what
conditions would prevail in Kosovo for the international security
force to enter the province.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has talked of a ``permissive environment'' for the
security force, which NATO officials repeated on Monday would be
NATO-led.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials have said that the security
force, which would be responsible for ensuring the return of the
refugees, would not fight its way in against Serb troops. These
officials have also said that ``permissive'' meant the consent of
the government in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   When asked at a news conference what ``permissive'' meant, the
secretary-general of NATO, Javier Solana, said, ``Why don't you
help me a little and not ask me to define the word permissive.''
</P>
<P>
   While the foreign ministers appeared impressed with themselves
for the unity they had maintained behind the bombing campaign, they
did not rule out more unpleasant surprises from Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   In the communique issued after their meeting, the 19 ministers
warned that they were concerned that Milosevic may try to unseat
the government of Montenegro, which after Serbia is the smaller of
the two republics in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The president of Montenegro, Milo Djukanovic, an opponent of
Milosevic, is supported by the West although NATO has bombed
targets in Montenegro in its efforts to break up the Yugoslav Army.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Milosevic sacked high ranking generals in
Montenegro and replaced them with his loyalists, a prelude to a
possible coup d'etat attempt against Djukanovic. Monday's
communique said that Milosevic ``should be in no doubt that any
move against President Djukanovic and his government will have
grave consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   A leader of the Kosovo Liberation Army, Jakup Krasniqi, who was
a member of the ethnic Albanian delegation at the peace talks at
Rambouillet, was present at NATO headquarters Monday and met with
foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
   He had a private meeting with Albright where he thanked the
secretary for the NATO campaign, a State Department official said.
He also asked that the ethnic Albanian refugees now in Albania,
Macedonia and Montenegro be kept as close as possible to Kosovo
rather than being flown to Europe or the United States, as
originally proposed.
</P>
<P>
   A Clinton administration official said that Washington still
stood behind the proposal in the Rambouillet accord that the Kosovo
Liberation Army had to be disarmed once an international security
force established itself in Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 2010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
