<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PHILS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves ruin Phillies home opener, win 8-6
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Ah, Opening Day in Philly.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies home opener at Veterans Stadium came complete with
the ``Rocket Man'' shooting around the outfield with a jet pack on
his back before the game, a hang-glider sweeping down to home
plate, and a fourth inning slug fest in the center field stands.
</P>
<P>
   It caught on.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the Braves 8-6 win, it was a slug fest on the
field too.
</P>
<P>
   After the Braves and Phillies exchanged three-run innings, they
brought out the big sticks. Bret Boone went first with a two-run
home run in the seventh, his first as an Atlanta Brave to put the
Braves up 6-4. Then came Alex Arias and Scott Rolen for the
Phillies who each belted solo home runs to left field off Mike
Cather to tie it 6-6 in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Javy Lopez was the last man deep, driving a line drive home run
to center field for his first home run of the season, a two-run
job, for an 8-6 lead in the eighth inning and the eventual winning
runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the right time for me to do something,'' said Lopez,
who drove a 2-1 fastball to center for his first hit of the day.
``We're tied in the eighth inning. I was 0 for 3. I found the pitch
I was looking for and I didn't waste it.''
</P>
<P>
   Buried under the pile of runs were starters John Smoltz and
Carlton Loewer, the same two guys who five days ago dueled to a 4-0
Braves win. Smoltz didn't feel that far off but made a couple bad
pitches in the second inning. That was enough to leave him holding
four earned runs, the most he's allowed since last August 21
against San Diego, eight regular season starts ago.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Smoltz was extremely nasty. He struck out eight,
matching his total from his first start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   After coasting through the first inning, Smoltz loaded up the
bases without recording an out to start the second. A strikeout of
Mike Lieberthal and a 2-2 count on Desi Relaford made it look like
Smoltz was on his way out of the woods. Right about that time
Relaford connected for a triple to the right field corner, scoring
all three base runners to give the Phillies a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a pretty good lesson today about pitch selection
with the bases loaded and the pitcher on deck,'' said Smoltz, who
hung a changeup to Relaford. ``You don't want to get beat with your
fourth pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz started a three-run rally of his own with his first hit
of the year on a line drive to right field. He was followed by
back-to-back run scoring doubles to the gap in left center by Otis
Nixon and Boone. Brian Jordan completed the rally with an RBI
single past second baseman Marlon Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones had another frustrating outing on Monday. He went
0 for 5, lowering his season average to .206. But he had a good
time watching the multiple fights that broke out in the center
field seats during the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will say this,'' Jones declared. ``They made more contact
than I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
