<P>
   The New York Times plans 3 pages of stories, photos and graphics
on the continuing crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels, Belgium) _ NATO's foreign ministers
pledged today to keep up the air attacks against Yugoslavia but at
the same time searched for the shape of a political settlement in
Kosovo and urged Russia to be part of it. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   (Moved)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TRAIN (Grdelica, Yugoslavia) _ In its expanding air war,
NATO warplanes bombed two bridges this morning over the Juzna
Morava River, one highway, one railway, a narrow structure of steel
girders painted a dull gray. The train, five cars pulled by a
bright red, white and blue engine, was on the bridge, and the
missile cut it in half. At least nine people were killed, said
police at the scene, and at least 16 others, badly wounded, were
brought to a hospital in nearby Leskovac. NATO hits a Yugoslav
passenger train. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   (Moved)
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ Gen. Clark, NATO's top commander,
is asking for added equipment for the air campaign in Yugoslavia.
By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Radusa, Macedonia) _ Conditions in the refugee
camp here, international aid workers said, are far below those of
the half-dozen camps erected by NATO soldiers and run by
international aid organizations. The Radusa camp is the latest
example, they said, of the Macedonian government's callous
treatment of 130,000 ethnic Albanian refugees who have poured over
the border from Kosovo in the last two weeks. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   (Moved)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Dateline to kum, Macedonia) _ Five more
busloads of refugees arrive from Kosovo; what they have to say. By
David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Tirana, Albania) _ As the debate about
committing ground troops to Yugoslavia continues, the American
military already has a sizeable presence here, backed by
helicopters and tons of equipment with more on the way. By Anthony
DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   (Moved)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUGOVA (Brussels, Belgium) _ What happened to Ibrahim
Rugova, the leading ethnic Albanian advocate of nonviolence in
Kosovo, during the Serbian offensive against ethnic Albanian
civilians there has preoccupied NATO since the allied bombing
campaign against the Serbs began on March 24. This week's issue of
the German newsmagazine Der Spiegel, published Monday, included a
diary by Renate Flottau, its correspondent in the Balkans. She
stayed with him until last Monday, according to her diary, which
reports that, far from being a willing collaborator of Milosevic's
repression, Rugova was forced by the police to do their bidding. By
Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Barksdale, La.) _ President Clinton is visiting
military base in Louisiana and then returns to Washington to meet
with congressional leaders over Kosovo. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GERMANY (Berlin) _ German Chancellor Schroeder wins broad
support from his party for his stand on bombing Yugoslavia after he
rejects calls by left-wingers for a stop to NATO's air assault. By
Roger Cohen.
</P>
