<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5398 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PULITZER-HORSEY-SPI &LR;      04-12 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PULITZER-HORSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE POST-INTELLIGENCER'S DAVID HORSEY WINS CARTOONING
PULITZER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELLIS E. CONKLIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer's David Horsey won the 1999
Pulitzer Prize for Distinguished Editorial Cartoons Monday in the
nation's most prestigious journalism contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I had a very strong year _ thanks largely to Bill
Clinton and Monica Lewinsky,'' the 47-year-old Horsey said with a
smile. ``There have been a group of very talented cartoonists who
have been doing this for years. Others were extremely deserving,
but I'm glad it's me.''
</P>
<P>
   The P-I newsroom erupted into cheers and applause as a beaming
Horsey came in to share the celebration with his colleagues. There
were handshakes and hugs all around. Bottles of California
champagne were uncorked in preparation for the congratulatory
toasts. Some of the bubbly found its way onto Horsey's mane of red
hair.
</P>
<P>
   The award marked the P-I's first Pulitzer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is tremendous news for David and the
Post-Intelligencer,'' said P-I Publisher and Editor J.D. Alexander.
``He deserves it. In a year when it was a great time to draw, he
knocked out everyone in the country. David had a hell of a year.
</P>
<P>
   Said P-I Managing Editor Ken Bunting: ``I am enormously proud
for the Post-Intelligencer, and extremely proud and happy for
David, who is a tremendous talent and deserving of this
recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   Editorial page editor Joann Byrd joked that Horsey, after
winning the Pulitzer, came to her to demand a raise and asked that
his cartoons from now on always run full page in size.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I didn't mind a bit,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Horsey left his vacationing family in Barra de Navidad, a small
Mexican city south of Puerta Vallarta, to fly back to Seattle on
Sunday to await word from the Pulitzer committee. The weeklong
getaway had been planned months ago, long before Horsey became
aware that he was one of three finalists for the prize.
</P>
<P>
   Since there was no phone at the home he was renting, Horsey made
sure to carry a cell phone so he could share the news with his wife
of 22 years, Nole Ann.
</P>
<P>
   Horsey plans to return to Mexico today to complete his vacation
with his wife and two children, Darielle and Daniel.
</P>
<P>
   A nationally syndicated editorial cartoonist and columnist,
Horsey's work appears in more than 450 newspapers. Earlier this
year, the National Press Foundation named Horsey Cartoonist of the
Year for 1998, honoring him with the prestigious Berryman Award for
Editorial Cartooning.
</P>
<P>
   The regional Society of Professional Journalists recently picked
Horsey to receive the 1999 Susan Hutchison Bosch Award for
outstanding achievement in journalism.
</P>
<P>
   George B. Irish, president of Hearst Newspapers and vice
president of The Hearst Corp., which owns the P-I, said the honor
``calls attention to Hearst Newspapers' long-standing commitment to
producing `journalism of distinction.'''
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, Seattle Mayor Paul Schell said he was thrilled
to hear the news. ``Not only is Horsey a great cartoonist, he's an
excellent writer as well in his occasional published pieces,''
Schell said. ``I've been a big fan of his for years. He's
terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   Horsey, the only full-time editorial cartoonist working for a
Seattle daily newspaper, is well regarded for his quick wit,
effervescent personality and his penchant for skewering the
powerful.
</P>
<P>
   As P-I reporter Scott Sunde put it, ``David goes after more
sacred cows than a love-sick bull.''
</P>
<P>
   A Pulitzer finalist in the the late 1980s, Horsey submitted 20
of his editorial cartoons for this year's judging. Many of them
lampooned the Clinton sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Horsey's favorite, and the one he believes might have drawn the
most critical acclaim from the judges, was titled ``Beltway
Apocalypse.'' The full-page cartoon that Horsey inked in the style
of a Renaissance painting ran on the cover of the Feb. 22, 1998,
Sunday P-I Focus section and portrayed the full montage of
characters involved in the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Horsey said it's difficult to describe how he goes about
crafting a stand out editorial cartoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It starts with what's in the news,'' he said. ``And I do a lot
of reading so I can respond to some event with some intelligence.
But how it all comes together, I can't really explain it. I just
hope it keeps happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Horsey said his passion for drawing began as a child. But it was
at the University of Washington, where he earned his bachelor's
degree in communications in 1976, that he realized he might have
some real talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a weight training class and I drew this rude
caricature of the instructor,'' Horsey recalled. ``He didn't get
mad like I expected him too. Instead, he said that I ought to work
for the UW Daily.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Evansville, Ind., Horsey has lived in Seattle since
1954. He was an honor student at Ingraham High School. Before
joining the P-I in 1979, he worked briefly at the weekly Sammamish
Valley News before joining the Journal American in Bellevue, where
he covered the state legislature as a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Horsey's work for the P-I has taken him to national political
party conventions, on the campaign trail during presidential
primaries, the Olympics, Japan and Europe. In 1993, Horsey was one
of only 25 Americans chosen to take part in the European Community
Visitorship Program in Brussels. More recently, he completed a year
at Hearst Newspapers' Washington Bureau where he took a closer look
at Congress and the White House.
</P>
<P>
   He has published four collections of his cartoons, the most
recent titled ``The Fall of Man'' in 1994. Horsey is now putting
the finishing touches on his first novel, ``Beyond the Border,'' a
story set in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   About a half-hour before the Pulitzer announcements were made,
Horsey remained at his desk in the third-floor graphics department
in the P-I building. He admitted he was nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to keep him loose,'' said Horsey's colleague
Duane Hoffmann.
</P>
<P>
   Just after noon, Horsey and a swarm of P-I editors gathered
around Alexander's desk waiting for The Associated Press to file
the story. The atmosphere was quiet and tense. Then the phone rang.
It was for Horsey. The caller was Laura Parker, a former P-I
reporter, now at USA Today in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congratulations,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you mean?'' Horsey replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won. You know that,'' Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   A minute later, the report came over the wire. Everyone cheered.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters and editors in the newsroom, Horsey said:
``I'm a nice guy, but I'm no more talented than anyone of you. It
takes all of us to put out a good newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Said P-I senior correspondent Andrew Schneider, a two-time
Pulitzer Prize winner: ``David graciously acknowledged the truth _
that Pultizer's are not won by a single person, but from a team
effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander echoed that sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This award for David's work gives further recognition to the
Post-Intelligencer's enormously creative staff,'' he said. ``His
colleagues and I are proud of David's Pulitzer Prize, and I am very
proud of all of them as well for the splendid journalism they
provide each day to our readers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
