   BIN-LADEN (Washington) _ In their self-declared war with Osama
bin Laden, the man charged with blowing up two U.S. embassies in
Africa eight months ago, American officials portray him as the
world's most dangerous terrorist. But The New York Times, working
in cooperation with the PBS program Frontline, has found him to be
less a commander of terrorists than an inspiration for them.
Enemies and supporters alike say he may not be as globally powerful
as some American officials have publicly asserted. But his message
and aims have more resonance among Muslims around the world than
has been understood. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   2-column hed.
