<P>
   SCI-EVERGLADES (Undated) _ The Everglades are in serious
decline. Slow-flowing fresh water in some places amounts to half
what it was a century ago. Populations of wading birds are down
some 90 percent. The cause: people have siphoned off too much of
the natural flow of water that once stretched in a continuous sheet
from Lake Okeechobee to Florida Bay. Now, in the nation's most
ambitious attempt at ecological restoration, the Federal and state
governments are about to try to put things right. The idea is to
spend some $8 billion over the next 20 years to re-plumb the
Everglades' water system so that natural conditions can be
re-established or at least mimicked. By William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `a' category.)
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA-POLLEN (Atlanta) _ The pollen count, usually hitting a
high of 150, has reached 6000 here and all of Atlanta is sneezing.
By David Firestone.
</P>
