<HEADER>
A5400 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      04-12 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON VISITS AIR CREWS INVOLVED IN KOSOVO CAMPAIGN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHREVEPORT, La. _ President Clinton on Monday praised the work
of air crews and support personnel involved in the NATO air
campaign against Yugoslavia as he stressed the alliance's
determination to end the violence in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are determined to continue the mission and we will prevail
because of you and people like you,'' Clinton told crews of B-52
bombers and A-10 attack planes as he visited Barksdale Air Force
Base. They have flown missions over Bosnia and will be headed back
to the Balkans in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
   He said NATO ``would like to nip this conflict in the bud before
it destabilizes Europe'' and he warned Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic that he ``should be under no illusions that we will end
it from weariness.''
</P>
<P>
   Relating what he called the ``horrifying'' stories of atrocities
committed by Serb forces in Kosovo, Clinton said American and
allied personnel involved in the air campaign are ``trying to get
people to live in human terms so that people will not be called
upon to fight a wider war caused by someone else's madness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The stories we're hearing now are truly horrifying,'' Clinton
said of Milosevic's effort to rid Kosovo of its predominantly
ethnic Albanian population.
</P>
<P>
   Reciting accounts of mass killings, villages burned and looted,
Clinton accused the Yugoslav dictator of ``seeking literally to
erase the presence of these people in their own land.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We must not let that happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the 20th day of the bombing, Clinton flew to the home base of
some of the B-52s and A-10s involved in the allied operation to
show his support for the crews and families attached to the 8th Air
Force's 2nd Bomb Wing and 917th Air Reserve Wing, both of which
have deployed planes and personnel in Europe to participate in
Operation Allied Force.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton was meeting privately with some crews just
returned from flying missions over Yugoslavia, Defense Secretary
William Cohen was playing down the possibility of deploying ground
troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no consensus for ground troops in the NATO alliance.
There's no consensus for it in Congress or in the country at this
point. And there's no need for it,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen also said that NATO airstrikes against Yugoslav military
targets ``will accelerate'' in the coming days. ``We are now
determined to grind his military forces down.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen added that there will be no negotiations with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Citing intelligence sources, Cohen pointed to growing evidence
that Milosevic's forces are beginning to fall apart under the
steady and intense bombing campaign waged by the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   He said many of the Yugoslav military and police units operating
in Kosovo have been cut off from their command structures. He cited
instances of declining morale among Yugoslav troops and some
desertions, although he offered no details.
</P>
<P>
   Upon his return to Washington on Monday, Clinton met with
congressional leaders to make his case for continuing the air
campaign and once again to stress that he does not believe ground
troops will be necessary to help drive Milosevic's forces from
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has committed about 500 planes to the NATO
operation as part of an allied force of about 700 planes. The
undertaking is a costly one, and Clinton also planned to ask the
lawmakers in his meeting Monday and in another scheduled for today
for at least $2.5 billion to help pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was accompanied by a number of lawmakers, including
Reps. Max Sandlin, D-Texas, and Mac Thornberry, R-Texas. Thornberry
said Congress, which reconvenes Tuesday following a two-week Easter
recess, would undertake ``serious discussions'' over whether to
vote on an authorizing resolution for ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   Thornberry had been opposed to the NATO intervention in Kosovo.
But he said with the air campaign well under way, ``We are where we
are.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the use of ground forces should be part of the
overall NATO planning for resolving the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned that we have no good options to ground forces
now. But I think we have to be careful. I think it will take
something other than air power. I'm not saying it's ground troops,
but it's going to take something else to ... end it.``
</P>
<P>
   The comments reflected a growing mood in Congress for ending the
fight with Milosevic as soon as possible, even it takes committing
U.S. soldiers to battle.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to delivering remarks to 2,000 base personnel,
Clinton also met privately with the families of seven people who
died in the tornadoes that struck nearby Bossier Parish last week.
The president used the meeting to announce the availability of
federal aid programs to help uninsured people who were displaced by
the tornadoes repair or rebuild their homes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
