<HEADER>
A5409 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUGOVA-NYT &LR;      04-12 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUGOVA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOURNALIST GIVES ACCOUNT OF TIME WITH KOSOVAR ALBANIAN LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ What happened to Ibrahim Rugova, the leading
ethnic Albanian advocate of nonviolence in Kosovo, during the
Yugoslav offensive against ethnic Albanian civilians there has
preoccupied NATO since the allied bombing campaign against the
Yugoslavs began on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia announced a
unilateral cease-fire last week and said Rugova was negotiating a
peace settlement with him that would allow refugees to return.
Earlier, Yugoslav state-run television showed the Kosovar Albanian
leader smiling and chatting easily with Milosevic, and NATO said
the images were a montage aimed at creating a false propaganda
image of Rugova as a collaborator.
</P>
<P>
   This week's issue of the German newsmagazine Der Spiegel,
published Monday, included a diary by Renate Flottau, its
correspondent in the Balkans. The German reporter wrote that she
was in Rugova's house in Pristina, the provincial capital of
Kosovo, when Yugoslav forces put him under house arrest on March
31.
</P>
<P>
   She stayed with him until last Monday, according to her diary,
which reports that, far from being a willing collaborator of
Milosevic's repression, Rugova was forced by police to do their
bidding.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, March 31, as armed Yugoslav thugs and uniformed
police were systematically driving Albanians from their homes, she
wrote that she arrived at Rugova's house shortly before 11 a.m. and
found him alive and defiant.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I was about to leave,'' she wrote, ``Rugova's
brother-in-law burst into the room with a warning finger on his
lips. We crept carefully down the stairs from the second floor and
saw police cars and armored vehicles approaching the house and then
stopping in front of it. Two dozen men from the Yugoslav special
police jumped out.''
</P>
<P>
   Police broke down the doors and pushed the 17 adults and
children in the house into a single room on the second floor of the
three-story building. Rugova and the reporter agreed that it would
be too dangerous for her to declare that she was a journalist, so
she pretended to be a family friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside, we can hear the shattering of windows, the smashing
of doors,'' she wrote. ``The police are apparently occupying all
the surrounding houses.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Radovan Urosevic, from the Serbian Media Center, a
propaganda center in Pristina, arrived. ``Rugova is told he has to
go on camera and say he is in good health and a free man,'' her
account continues. ``Anything other than that will not be broadcast
over state television and radio. And it will also be dangerous for
all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, April 1, Rugova was driven to Belgrade, the
Yugoslav capital, for a meeting with Milosevic. ``When Rugova comes
back at 6:30 p.m., he is visibly upset,'' Mrs. Flottau writes.
``The puzzled world public is shown pictures of a relaxed, smiling
Rugova talking with Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Rugova told her, the meeting was tense and President
Milosevic was furious. ```Not a hair on your head will be harmed,
our people are making sure of that,''' Milosevic told Rugova, who
signed a communique prepared for him.
</P>
<P>
   ```It was just `a sentence,' he explains later over a glass of
whisky,'' she writes. ``Besides, he says he is convinced that
western leaders will read no significance into his signature.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, April 2, still a prisoner in his own home, Rugova had
an assistant call the U.S. ambassador, Christopher Hill, in Skopje,
the capital of Macedonia, and later Milosevic's office in Belgrade.
Rugova asked for safe passage to Skopje. But he was refused.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, April 3, Yugoslavia's deputy prime minister, Nikola
Sainovic, arrived at the house at 9 p.m. ``Rugova, he says in a
mocking tone, is a free man. He can go to Macedonia if he wants.
But he should be aware that on the way, angry Serbs could `stage'
all manner of incidents. An unmistakable warning.''
</P>
<P>
   On Easter Sunday, April 4, ``Rugova waits for a reassuring call
from Belgrade. It comes around noon, but with the news that he is
to receive the Russian ambassador in the evening together with
Sainovic.''
</P>
<P>
   For security reasons, Ambassador Yuri Kotov postponed the visit
until Monday, April 5. After a night of NATO bombing that shook the
house to its foundation, he arrived in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rugova sees an opportunity for me to get away,'' Mrs. Flottau
concluded, and she melted into the crowd of Yugoslav and other
journalists the police allowed into the house to cover the meeting.
She returned to her hotel on April 6, Mrs. Flottau wrote, but after
being interrogated and searched by Yugoslav police, she was warned
by friends on the hotel staff to flee, and she arrived by bus in
Belgrade last Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials consider her account vindication of their concern
for Rugova's safety and well-being. The magazine has been sharply
critical of the allied bombing campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
