<HEADER>
A5412 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-SCHOLARSHIPS-COX     04-12 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-SCHOLARSHIPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio seniors win scholarships for proficiency
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ More than 40,000 Ohio high school seniors earned
$500 scholarships by acing all five sections of the 12th-grade
proficiency test they took in February.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, 41 percent of the 99,515 Ohio seniors who took the
tests in writing, reading, mathematics, citizenship and science
passed all five sections and earned the scholarships, which can be
used to meet any educational expense in any public or private
college in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The scholarships, offered for the first time for the class of
1999, are designed to provide an incentive for students to excel on
a test that is not a requirement for graduation, as is the Ohio
Ninth Grade Proficiency Test.
</P>
<P>
   All 12th-grade students who have passed the ninth-grade exam _
and who are not excused from having to take the test because of
disabilities _ are required to take the 12th-grade proficiency
tests. Students must take both the ninth- and 12th-grade tests, but
they are not required to pass the 12th-grade test.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio Department of Education released results of the
12th-grade test on its web site (http://www.ode.ohio.gov) Monday,
though its district-by-district results do not include figures on
the number of students in each district who took and passed all
five sections of the test. A department spokeswoman said the scores
of a small number of makeup tests have not been tabulated and
included in the school district statistics, so state officials
decided not to release incomplete data.
</P>
<P>
   This year's senior class improved math, science and writing
scores compared to last year's class, education department
officials said. Citizenship scores fell slightly, while reading
scores remained about the same as last year.
</P>
<P>
   Students also can earn honors-level scores on the 12th-grade
exams. Those who achieved an honors score in at least one test area
and those who meet proficient-level standards in all five test
areas will be awarded a Certificate of Recognition by the state
board of education. About 51 percent of seniors tested this year
were recognized for their performance, compared to 46 percent of
last year's seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Herbert Franklin, superintendent of the Jefferson Twp. school
district, where 36 of 37 seniors passed the writing portion of the
proficiency exam, said it appeared extra efforts in writing
appeared to be paying off. The 97-percent passage rate for the
writing section placed Jefferson Twp. among the region's
highest-scoring districts in that section. But on the citizenship
and math portions of the test, only about one-third of seniors met
the state standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to give up. We're going to keep trying and
keep looking for answers and keep trying new things,'' Franklin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton school administrators were not available for comment
Monday, but a testing official said the district's overall passage
rate on the 12th-grade test rose from 18 percent in 1998 to 24
percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   The 12th-grade scores are among the criteria the state uses to
assess the performance of school districts in the state ``report
cards.'' The trial run for the cards was released last week.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Tave Zelman, Ohio's superintendent of public instruction,
said of the test results: ``More and more, our students are meeting
the challenges put forth by higher education and the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fisher writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
