</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-POLLEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATLANTA FINDS ITSELF GASPING FOR AIR UNDER BLANKET OF POLLEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Okla., Texas) (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In an awesome burst of friskiness, the trees of
northern Georgia have coated Atlanta with a thick yellow veil of
fertility, and the city is beginning to wheeze under the weight.
</P>
<P>
   Pollen, the male reproductive agent of plants, is everywhere. In
the mornings it is heaped in sticky mounds and swirls on the
sidewalks, the windshields, the patio furniture, the dogs. Sweep it
up _ wearing, of course, one of the white surgical masks on half
the faces of the city _ and it is back again, drifting through the
window screens and electrifying once-proper dark shoes.
</P>
<P>
   No one is paying attention to the Dow anymore; instead, the city
has awakened for the last week to watch the pollen count reach
ever-more-absurd heights. One radio station had a pollen-count
guessing game on Friday, and no one even came close. On Monday
morning the count for the Atlanta area reached an all-time high of
6,013 grains per cubic meter, which is virtually unimaginable
considering that the national scale says a count of 120 is
considered ``very high.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's count is 33 percent higher than in any previously
recorded spring in Atlanta, and far higher than any other city in
the country, except for Tulsa, Okla., which reported a count of
6,299 over the weekend. Michael Muilenberg, a Harvard University
public health instructor who keeps the records for the National
Pollen Bureau, said the highest count ever recorded was about
14,000 two years ago in Tulsa, which has a high concentration of
extremely prolific mountain cedars. But he said the Atlanta count
was quite impressive.
</P>
<P>
   The sneeze count, naturally, is also off the charts. Margaret
Higgins, a nurse at the Atlanta Allergy and Asthma Clinic, which
has kept the city's pollen counts for the last decade, estimated
that she sneezed 30 times in five minutes at one point during the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the mistake of eating outside on the patio,'' Ms.
Higgins said. ``An allergy sufferer cannot do that. I usually wear
a mask and goggles when I go out, but it was so nice that I
couldn't resist. Now I'm paying for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of patients at her clinic and others scattered around
the area are also experiencing one of the worst weeks of their
respiratory lives.
</P>
<P>
   Allergy clinics are booked up three weeks in advance. Some
pharmacies have experienced shortages of Claritin, Allegra or
Benadryl, and regular users have been known to panic and plead with
their druggists for refills.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists say it may be another product of the recent global
weather phenomenon known as La Nina: a warm, dry winter, followed
by an early spring and an unusual confluence of the germination
cycles of several species of trees. The lack of rain recently and a
wind strong enough to whip up a spectacular fire just outside
downtown on Sunday have also been blamed, but for most residents
there are no satisfactory explanations. There is only the
chartreuse torrent of spring, and it is in every lung in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Though the most visible pollen _ the fertility agent of pine
trees _ is said to be relatively harmless to breathers, it has its
own form of pathology. Last week, a combination of pollen and a
light coating of drizzle was blamed for slickening the pavement of
Interstate 285, causing a chain-reaction pileup that damaged or
destroyed 18 vehicles in DeKalb County, northeast of town.
</P>
<P>
   Many people will not even venture into their back yards.
Electrostatic air filters have become popular, and the television
meteorologists are advising everyone to take frequent showers, wash
their hands constantly, stay away from pets and avoid drying
clothes outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate it, but there's nothing else to do,'' said Lee R.
Woodall, a designer with Kitchens of Atlanta whose eyes water and
chest contracts the moment she walks outside. ``When they go to the
bio-hazard suits, we could wear those. I look good in silver.''
</P>
<P>
   A good rain would rinse the air, but there has not been a good
rain in a few weeks. Many sufferers say they are ready to seed the
clouds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just one good, solid rain _ that's all we need,'' said Marc S.
Komisarow, a financial planner whose wife spent the weekend in bed
inhaling steroids and ingesting Zertac, an anti-allergen. ``And
also, if people would just stop planting trees in their yards.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even for Atlanta, one of the most heavily forested cities in the
country with an abundance of southern pine and oak trees, the
numbers seemed a bit impossible. Several national experts said the
count seemed unlikely, and questioned whether the Atlanta counting
machine might be a little too close to a libidinous conifer.
</P>
<P>
   But at the Atlanta Allergy and Asthma Clinic, Dr. Kathleen
Sheerin said there was little doubt that the numbers were correct.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in Dallas over the weekend, and they were all excited
because they had a count of 1,000,'' Dr. Sheerin said. ``To me, it
was like a breath of clean, crisp air.''
</P>
</TEXT>
