<HEADER>
A5414 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-CLEVELAND-ROYALS-     04-12 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CLEVELAND-ROYALS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tribe win on Fryman's extra-inning homer
 &HT;    By Sean McClelland
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The more Dave Burba thought about it, his
late-inning vantage point couldn't have been better.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the competitor in him would have preferred to have the
ball in his hands a little longer Monday, but what difference did
it make in the end? The Cleveland Indians, for whom he had gotten
the first 19 outs of a new Jacobs Field season, beat the Kansas
City Royals, 5-2, on Travis Fryman's three-run homer in the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Said Burba, a Dayton native who grew up in Springfield, ``It was
just a lot of fun to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Burba was in the clubhouse with ice on his right arm in the
eighth inning. He was watching on television when center fielder
Kenny Lofton threw out Joe Randa at home plate to complete a double
play, and in the home half, when Enrique Wilson, filling in at
shortstop for the injured Omar Vizquel, drove a game-tying, two-run
homer to right field off Scott Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just sat in here and screamed myself hoarse,'' said Burba,
who was able to leave 15 tickets for family members after obtaining
six from backup catcher Einar Diaz. ``I knew somewhere down the
line someone would get the big hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Fryman's first home run of the season came off Jose Santiago
after Jim Thome had walked and Wil Cordero had singled.
</P>
<P>
   It sent a crowd of 42,798 into hysterics and made the afternoon
worthwhile for Burba, who never before as a major leaguer had
started any kind of opener. This made up for last season, he
figured, when the Cincinnati Reds pulled the Opening Day assignment
out from under him, dealing him to Cleveland at the last minute for
first baseman Sean Casey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a special day, a real thrill for me,'' Burba said. ``I
tried not to think about it, because the more you think about it,
the more pressure you put on yourself. I was a little nervous, but
I got through it. You can't let outside influences determine how
you pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   The Royals took a 1-0 lead in the third on Johnny Damon's RBI
single, then made it 2-0 in the fourth when Jermaine Dye sliced an
opposite-field homer to right that barely found its way into the
seats.
</P>
<P>
   When Burba faltered in the seventh, allowing a double to Chad
Krueter and a one-out single to Carlos Febles, manager Mike
Hargrove summoned lefty Mark Langston, who got Carlos Beltran to
ground into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland (6-1) has won six in a row, and this was just another
example of how things have been breaking right for the team.
Langston joined the Indians on Monday, replacing Ricky Rincon, who
was placed on the 15-day disabled list with soreness and swelling
in his elbow.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, Randa's leadoff triple against Langston seemed to
spell trouble, especially when Damon, the next batter, drove one to
left-center. But Lofton, who caught the ball running toward left
field, unleashed a perfect throw and Sandy Alomar withstood the
collision. It would be Kansas City's final threat as Paul Shuey
then retired the next seven batters, striking out four.
</P>
<P>
   Lofton also made an amazing over-the-head catch to rob Mike
Sweeney leading off the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do you start?'' Burba wondered. ``There were too many
turning points, too many heroes. It just goes to show you how much
talent we have here.
</P>
<P>
   Sean McClelland writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
