<HEADER>
A5417 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-REDS-CUBS-COX     04-12 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-CUBS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reds use four home runs to ruin Cubs opener 7-2
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The men of muscle always are affixed with a
frightening nickname _ Murderer's Row, The Pittsburgh Lumber
Company, The Big Blue Brew Crew, The Bronx Bombers, The Bash
Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   So, is it too early to find something powerful and catchy to
supply headline writers for the 1999 Cincinnati Reds?
</P>
<P>
   Probably, it is. Even utility infielder Mark Lewis made the
point Monday afternoon in the postgame Wrigley Field clubhouse
after the Reds pounded four home runs to spoil the home opener for
the Chicago Cubs, 7-2.
</P>
<P>
   With the four home runs, the Reds have 16 in seven games _ the
first Cincinnati team since 1986 to hit homers in its first seven
games. The 1986 Reds homered in its first 12 games, but only hit 17
in that 12-game span.
</P>
<P>
   In the joyous clubhouse, the players hooted and hollered when
ESPN flashed a graphic about Monday's explosion _ two homers by
Mike Cameron, one by Barry Larkin, one by Eddie Taubensee.
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, in down-in-the-gutter terms, Lewis advised his
teammates not to submerge themselves in self-congratulatory
postures so early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   But, indeed it is fun right now for a team that appeared to have
little power coming out of spring training, except for maybe Greg
Vaughn, who has only two of those 16 homers.
</P>
<P>
   Well, today, April 13, 1999, the Cincinnati Reds lead the
baseball world in home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe pitching coach Don Gullett was being prophetic before the
game when he bounced a new baseball off the carpeted clubhouse
floor and when it ricocheted to his chin he said, ``Tell me the
baseballs aren't hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Cameron was the day's happiest man, returning to Chicago for the
first time after the team on the other side of town, the White Sox,
traded him in the off-season. His two home runs not only stabbed
the Cubs, they tore the guts out of the Bleacher Bums, who cascaded
insults onto the Reds' center fielder.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were on me all day, telling me how bad I am,'' Cameron
said. ``I just laughed inside and said nothing because we have two
more games here.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, though, put it best for Cameron. As Cameron walked into
the post-game clubhouse, Vaughn welcomed him with, ``Welcome back
to Chi-town.''
</P>
<P>
   Cameron broke open a close game with a home run in the eighth
against Matt Karchner that made it 4-1 and a two-run blast over the
bleachers and onto Waveland Avenue in the ninth off Rod Beck that
made it 7-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some fun today, doing it in Chicago, and it was some of
the best fun I've had since I started playing baseball,'' Cameron
said. ``Today was a great showing of me. . .doing the type of
things I can do. I had a tough time in Chicago last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jack McKeon says a swirl of talent is bubbling just
beneath the surface of the 26-year-old leadoff hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential is there,'' McKeon said. ``He hit 14 home runs
two years ago for the White Sox and he has five-tool talent. The
question is when all that talent comes through. This has to lift
his confidence up. We think he has a chance to be a hell of a
ballplayer who can hit. . .and hit with power.''
</P>
<P>
   Larkin started the barrage with a two-run blast off starter
Kevin Tapani in the third, then Tapani departed with a stiff back.
Taubensee led the seventh with a homer, then Cameron's double
explosion finished it off.
</P>
<P>
   The beneficiary was pitcher Steve Avery, who breezed through
seven innings and held the Cubs to one run and three hits. . .and
it could have been no runs and two hits if Cameron hadn't lost
Mickey Morandini's fly ball in the sun in the third. It fell for a
double and Morandini scored on Lance Johnson's single.
</P>
<P>
   Avery was the fifth straight Reds starter to pitch into at least
the seventh inning and a Cincinnati staff hasn't done that six
straight times since June 25-July 1, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Although he walked five, Avery spread them out and kept the Cubs
lunging by throwing 40 changeups among his 108 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitching the way I did last year, without a fastball, paid off
today,'' Avery said. ``My changeup was working and I threw some
good fastballs on certain counts. When I get my fastball working,
I'll be more effective. I needed 108 pitches for seven innings.
When I cut down the walks, I'll be able to go nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I stayed with the changeup . . . they weren't looking good
on changeups, so I stayed with it,'' Avery added.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
