<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO FOREIGN MINISTERS SHOW RESOLVE AGAINST MILOSEVIC 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO foreign ministers expressed strong resolve
Monday to force Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to give up
his campaign against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo and allow an
international force to police a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance's air campaign ``will continue until our terms are
met,'' Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said after her first
meeting with NATO colleagues since the airstrikes began three weeks
ago today.
</P>
<P>
   Despite scattered cloudiness over the Balkans, NATO struck
throughout the day, including what appeared to be a missile attack
on a bridge in southern Serbia just as a passenger train bound for
Greece, was crossing. Serb officials said nine people were killed.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the four-hour foreign ministers' meeting, Albright
praised ``a really very strong and remarkable unity among 19
members of this alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly Milosevic is trying to divide NATO,'' Albright said.
``But we will not be divided.''
</P>
<P>
   The foreign ministers issued a communique restating the aims of
getting Serb forces out of Kosovo and sending in an international
force that would give confidence to the hundreds of thousands of
ethnic Kosovars Albanians who have fled that they can return home.
</P>
<P>
   Signaling the costs that lie ahead after the fighting is over,
NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana said alliance countries and
other developed nations would need to help rebuild war-ravaged
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike earlier alliance statements, the communique did not
emphasize the central role NATO would play in a cease-fire force,
perhaps with a thought to making participation more palatable to
Russia, which has strongly condemned the airstrikes on a fellow
Slav nation.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said, however, that ``it would be a mistake for people
to think that there's any attempt not to make it quite clear that
NATO is the core aspect of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright flew from alliance headquarters in Brussels to a
meeting Tuesday in Oslo, Norway, with Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, the Yugoslav parliament took the symbolic step of
voting to join an alliance with Russia and Belarus, apparently
looking to get Moscow's military involved against NATO _ a step
that Ivanov, in the Russian capital, said is not in the offing.
</P>
<P>
   In the day's military action, the train was struck while
crossing a bridge near Grdelicka, 180 miles south of Belgrade. NATO
described the bridge as ``an important resupply route'' for
Yugoslav forces in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   NATO also struck for the second time one of Yugoslavia's oil
refineries in the industrial town of Pancevo across the Danube
River from Belgrade and a Yugo car factory in a complex at
Kragujevac southwest of Belgrade that also makes military vehicles
and weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Away from the NATO foreign ministers' meeting, German Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder rejected calls by left-wing members of his Social
Democratic Party to end the alliance's air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``An end to airstrikes would not bring us one millimeter
closer'' to peace in Yugoslavia, Schroeder said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a responsibility toward our allies in NATO,''
Schroeder said. ``We also have a responsibility toward the people
of Kosovo, who have become victims of the most gruesome human
rights violations.''
</P>
<P>
   In London, Defense Minister George Robertson said that ``if
President Milosevic assumed that NATO would drop a few bombs and
just leave, he has now been proved conclusively wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The outcome of this campaign is not in doubt, it is only a
question of how long it takes NATO to reverse Milosevic's ethnic
cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Albright said that under any settlement, ``the people
of Kosovo must be given the democratic self-government which they
have too long been denied,'' she denied that partition of the
province was not the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no discussion of that, or that is not an option that
is being considered, certainly not an option that I favor,''
Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   Solana said that NATO's ``operations are taking a heavy toll of
President Milosevic's army and security forces. We are tightening
the screw on those forces in Kosovo, which are responsible for
repressing civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the political and the resources to maintain our
military pressure until Milosevic backs down.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen, in Louisiana with President
Clinton to visit B-52 pilots, renewed the administration opposition
to using ground troops in Kosovo before a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there is no need, according to our commanding officers,''
Cohen said. ``So until such time as that changes ... we would not
even consider it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said NATO's airstrikes ``are systematically choking off
the Yugoslav army and security forces in Kosovo by cutting their
supply lines. As we isolate and weaken the Serb forces in Kosovo,
we are launching aggressive attacks against troops on the ground by
hitting staging areas, headquarters and forces in the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Detailing the damage, Maj. Gen. Charles Wald, vice director of
strategic planning for the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said the Yugoslav
coordinated air defense system ``has been impacted, I would say in
a big way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of their TV reception from a military standpoint, from
their command and control standpoint, has been degraded,'' Wald
said. ``The sustainability for petroleum oil and lubricants and
ammo has been reduced significantly. The military production has
been moderately damaged in the industry and infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Wald said that although all of Milosevic's ability to produce
petroleum oil and lubricants has been destroyed, ``he still has
quite a bit of reserve.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
