<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-OFFERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Schott entertains offers for Reds
 &HT;    By Marc Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Between rushing from and to their luxury
automobiles, members of the Cincinnati Reds ownership group spent a
long time in the Queen City Club Monday afternoon discussing Marge
Schott's sale of her majority interest in the team.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it was not something any of the group would
discuss as they left.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Lindner, a local business icon, was the last to arrive for
the meeting, called for 2 p.m. (he pulled his Rolls Royce into the
lot at 2:15) and the first to leave at 4:50.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had any comment, Lindner _ shy with the media _
said, ``No, not one thing.''
</P>
<P>
   About five minutes later, Schott had her Buick Riviera driven by
a valet close to a back door and did not acknowledge the presence
of a half dozen reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was held because Schott, who owns 6 1/2 of the Reds
15 shares _ or 42 percent _ was recently offered $65 million for 5
1/2 of those shares by Cleveland attorney Larry Dolan.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds limited partners _ including Lindner, George Strike,
Bill Reik and Louise Nippert _ have the option of matching that
offer, and speculation was they did Monday.
</P>
<P>
   However, apparently no action was taken as the sides dickered
through their lawyers over what constituted a legitimate purchase
offer. Schott wants more for her shares, and a printed report
Monday suggested she had an even higher offer from Steve Schott,
former director of business operations for the Reds and the cousin
of Schott's late husband.
</P>
<P>
   By 6 p.m., Strike, Reik, Nippert and several lawyers were still
inside the building arguing (according to a witness) merits of the
sale. They would not comment on what they decided or whether they
decided anything.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Katz writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
