   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; PAGE ONE &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; GAS _ &LR;  Furious about gasoline prices that are highest in the
nation, California motorists are lining up behind a grassroots
boycott of filling stations set for Friday, April 30.
</P>
<P>
   The symbollic protest, being promoted over the internet,
appeared to pick up speed this week following the release of a
national survey showing that San Franciscans are paying an average
of $1.71 a gallon for regular unleaded gasoline, more than
residents of any other city. Overall, California prices were
highest of any state. By Rebecca Smith
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; OTHER BUSINESS &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; FRAUD  &LR; _ Claiming it is the latest victim of ``cybersmear,''
Liviakis Financial Communications is filing late today a defamation
suit in Marin superior court to curb what it calls maliciously
false statements on the Internet. The suit, which seeks $20 million
in damages, accuses four online defendants of defamation and unfair
business practices. Industry observers said the episode underscores
how the Internet has shifted from a hotbed of unfounded gossip and
innuendo to become a place for individuals to inflict financial
harm on companies. By Jon Swartz
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMPAQ  &LR; _ The wheels appear to be coming off of Compaq
Computer. The world's largest seller of PCs saw its stock plummet
as much as 25 percent as investors reacted to news that
first-quarter earnings would be half of expectations. By David
Einstein
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STREET &LR;  _ Mark Veverka's financial column.
