<HEADER>
A5428 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETFILES-NETFILES_SFC     04-12 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETFILES-NET </SLUG>
 FILES _ SF CHRON  
 Jon Swartz/The Net Files  
 Netcasters Who Run With the Bulls 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
``Digital extremist'' Chris Courtney briefly debated whether he
should mount a tiny camera on the horns of a raging bull for his
online company's latest excellent adventure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought about it, but decided that the bulls are sacred and
we didn't want to piss anyone off,'' said Courtney, 30, founder of
1stbyte.com ( &LR; www.1stbyte.com &LR; ), a San Francisco company that &UR;  &LR; is
earning a reputation for Webcasting off-the-wall events.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he and his GenX online cohorts will be wearing cameras
on their heads and other body parts when they participate in the
running of the bulls in Pamplona, Spain, in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other camera person is a paramedic, so if either of us is
gored we'll be OK,'' he said. ``It should make for a pretty
interesting cybercast.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, 1stbyte's roving digital cameras have gone to the Webby
Awards in San Francisco last month and on some wild club dates at
SoMa nightspots. The gigs are paid for by event organizers who want
their shows broadcast on the Internet. Three to 12 people work on
each broadcast. &UR;  &LR; Courtney said his crew takes about six weeks to
prepare for a show.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, covering an event can be painful. During a
mountain-climbing competition in February, one of the company's
daredevil crew members sprained an ankle after falling off a cliff.
</P>
<P>
   On tap: coverage of the X Games in San Francisco this summer
(``We're going skydiving with the athletes if they let us,''
Courtney said) and a series of Hawaiian surfing contests in the
fall. 1stbyte.com is also considering an offer from a professional
wrestling organization in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to broadcast static sports; we want to show
extreme events,'' Courtney said. ``My dream is to Netcast sumo
wrestling in Japan or a foreign war with a handheld camera.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ONE LAST BARK &QL; 
To the end, former Netscape Communications CEO Jim Barksdale was
the quintessential Southern gentleman.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a brutal online turf war with Microsoft and stinging
criticism from the press over Netscape's strategy, Barksdale
maintained a cool demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   But mention that America Online's $10 billion acquisition of
Netscape effectively marks the end of Netscape, and his drawl turns
to a growl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not the dearly departed,'' he said last week. ``Most
people in business would like to be in the position (Netscape) is
in. Look, the company (has) one of the most well-known brands in
the world. It was and will continue to be a trendsetter.''
</P>
<P>
   It is clear that Netscape's hyperkinetic history took its toll
on Barksdale, who is bowing out as CEO at the relatively young age
of 56.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going into active management ever again,'' vowed
Barksdale. Instead, he will spend his time pushing for better
education and housing in his home state of Mississippi, lobbying on
behalf of AOL and raising campaign funds for presidential hopeful
George W. Bush. Barksdale is a member of AOL's board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Barksdale and wife Sally are moving from Palo Alto to Colorado
this summer, and will also build a part-time residence in
Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MORE THAN ZERO &QL; 
NetZero, based in the Los Angeles County hamlet of Westlake Village
(until now, best known as the headquarters for Jafra Cosmetics),
overnight has bolted into the Top 10 Internet service providers in
the country, with 740,000 customers. It ranks far behind America
Online, with 16 million members, but ahead of Prodigy, which has
638,000.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, NetZero had 500,000 users.
</P>
<P>
   If it continues growing at the same pace, CEO Ronald Burr
predicts that by next spring it will hit 6 million subscribers and
turn a profit. NetZero is planning an initial public offering by
year-end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Word-of-mouth reaction has been phenomenal,'' said Janet Daly,
NetZero's vice president of marketing. ``Where we are today has far
exceeded all of our internal forecasts.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, it's hard not to grow rapidly when you're giving
away your service for free. Most ISPs charge users about $20 a
month. NetZero relies solely on ad revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The only ``price'' users have to pay is to endure a barrage of
one-by-three-inch  &LR; 1-by-3-inch banner ads, which NetZero displays
on computer screens whenever its users are online. If you close an
ad, the service shuts down. NetZero's advertisers include eBay,
Macy's and Disney.
</P>
<P>
   Subscribers are stampeding the 2-year-old company's site
( &LR; www.netzero.com &LR; ) to download software for free Net access. They
get also get free e-mail and a choice of browsers _ Netscape
Communicator or Microsoft Internet Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   NetZero is not the first to offer free Net access. Atbigger.net
of San Jose promised customers free Net access for life, before it
folded last year.
</P>
<P>
   NetZero says it can avoid a similar fate because it has deeper
pockets. It is backed by Pasadena's Idealab, the same venture
capital firm that financed Free-PC.com, a Pasadena company that
gives away personal computers to people who agree to watch ads on
them.
</P>
<P>
   But some industry observers question whether NetZero can
maintain its lightning-fast growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not entirely convinced the free movement isn't a passing
gimmick,'' said Greg Tally, associate editor at BoardWatch magazine
in Golden, Colo. ``Banner ads aren't as effective as advertisers
hoped. The click-through rates are dropping; the novelty of this
new form has worn off.'' Plus, NetZero will probably face the same
problems that other ISPs encountered as their subscriber base
swelled: bottlenecks, long waits for technical support and a higher
churn rate as customers get frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   Cautions aside, most Internet sages are high on NetZero. In
fact, they're convinced the company won't get a chance to go public
because a larger ISP (read America Online) will swoop in and
acquire NetZero with its bulging customer list.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; SITES OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who says money doesn't grow on trees? For proof, peruse
 &LR; www.treeloot.com &LR; . If you think that's out on a limb, then
consider  &LR; www.butterisbest.com &LR; , described by its creators as ``the
ultimate Web site for butter lovers everywhere.'' Talk about
spreading it on ...
</P>
<P>
   Finally, get the picture of some startling digital images at
 &LR; www.photoloft.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
