<HEADER>
A5429 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RESCUE-COX     04-12 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESCUE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dramatic rescue unfolds as firefighters battle blaze
 &HT;    By Sandra Eckstein
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The first call came in at 2:35 p.m. Monday, a fire at
the Old Cotton Mill. But arriving firefighters quickly realized
this was not a routine fire. Huge orange balls billowed from
windows, and thick black smoke, stoked by strong winds, quickly
filled the afternoon air.
</P>
<P>
   At 3:10 p.m. Ivers Sims was discovered clinging to the top of a
massive crane next to the burning building, and a clock begins
running as rescuers scrambled to beat the heat and fire that
threaten Sims life. Here's how the rescue unfolded:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  3:14 p.m. Sims climbs from the gondola that housed the
controls for the crane and moves to the far end of the crane to
escape the heat and smoke.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  3:15 p.m. The roof of the burning build collapses, causing
nearby buildings to catch fire as the flames, now fanned by a 30
mph wind, begin to spread.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  3:16 p.m. Sims reaches the far end of the crane. He hugs a
rail and looks downward at the flames licking the base of his
crane.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  3:20 p.m. Connie Smith, a spokeswoman for the Atlanta Fire
Department, puts out a call for help. Smith says the department
needs a chopper ``that can withstand this intense heat.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  3:25 p.m. The Department of Natural Resources and the Georgia
Department of Transportation call and offer helicopters for the
rescue.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  3:33 p.m. Sims, perched 220 feet in the air, carefully climbs
onto the counterweights to escape the heat and smoke.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  3:34 p.m. Pilot Boyd Clines of the DNR takes off from Charlie
Brown Airport in a Bell Long Ranger L-4 helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  3:37 p.m. Sims lays down on the weights in the strong winds,
stretching out on his stomach.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  3:42 p.m. A local news traffic helicopter lands in a nearby
field and firefighters rush to outfit it for the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  3:49 p.m. The DNR helicopter arrives, and the decision is made
that it is better suited for the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  3:51 p.m. The gondola of the crane bursts into flames from the
intense heat below.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  3:55 p.m. A Life Flight helicopter goes by, checking the heat
in the area.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  3:56 p.m. The DNR helicopter lifts off, with firefighter Matt
Moseley dangling below from a 50-foot line. &QR;  4:01 p.m. Moseley
touches down on the crane as Sims sits up on top of the
counterweights. Moseley secures a harness to Sims.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  4:03 p.m. Moseley gives the sign and Clines lifts off with
both men dangling from the line below.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  4:04 p.m. The two men are flown in a circular fashion to avoid
sudden winds, taking them over the railroad and MARTA tracks,
buildings, billboards and Oakland Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  4:05 p.m. Clines gently lowers the men down on a grassy area
between two roads. The men's feet touch the ground, and they drop
to their knees and begin unfastening the harnesses. Seven firemen
run to assist them. Two men bring in a gurney. Sims stands, then is
helped onto the gurney.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  4:07 p.m. Sims is loaded into the ambulance and raced to
Atlanta Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Eckstein writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
