<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER DELAY IN RUSSIAN COMPONENT OF SPACE STATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The crucial, Russian-fabricated third component of the
U.S.-led international space station faces another two-month delay,
a NASA spokesman said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The 43-foot-long service module, which will serve as the living
quarters for the first crews of astronauts and cosmonauts, has been
re-scheduled for a late November launching by the United States,
following a week of meetings in Moscow between top managers for the
project from the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   The new U.S. assessment is at odds with the more optimistic
Russian view. In statements to the ITAR-Tass news agency late last
week, Russian space agency chief Yuri Koptev predicted a September
liftoff for the module.
</P>
<P>
   The service module, for which NASA has no replacement, has been
chronically tardy because of financial difficulties in Russia
dating back to the 1993 U.S. invitation to the former Cold War
rival to join Europe, Japan and Canada in the massive undertaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask the Russians, `Can you meet a September launch
date? They would say, `Yes, with the proper funding,' '' said Kyle
Herring, a NASA spokesman for the station program. ``But the
reality is they have not been getting the proper funding.''
</P>
<P>
   Following Russia's addition to the station project, the
launching of the service module was targeted for April 1998. In
January, even with $60 million in payments for the United States
last fall, the Russians acknowledged a third slip in fabrication
and testing of the service module, placing the launch on Sept. 20,
1999.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the service module now appears by U.S. estimates to be
19 months late, a setback that has caused station costs to rise.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the disparity in launch date estimates, the Americans
and Russians have agreed to host a ``roll out'' ceremony for the
service module on April 26 as it leaves its testing laboratory at
the RSC-Energia plant in Moscow. The large module will then be
shipped by rail to the Baikonur Cosmodrome in Kazakhstan, the
launch complex used by the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Following its arrival, a final round of components will be
installed, and the service module will undergo a last round of
pre-launch tests. It is the length of this phase of preparation
that NASA and the Russians are in disagreement over, Herring said.
</P>
<P>
   The first major components of the new station were launched late
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The series of meetings in Moscow has not changed previously
scheduled plans to launch the first crew to the outpost in late
January of next year. The team, led by American Bill Shepherd and
including cosmonauts Yuri Gidzenko and Sergei Krikalev, plans to
remain aboard for about six months.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
