<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5432 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-RETURNS-NYT &LR;      04-12 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-RETURNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS RETURNS, LOOKING TO DEFINE 2000 CAMPAIGN WITH 1999
LEGISLATION
</HEADLINE>
   (ac) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Congress returned Monday, House Democrats
prepared an offensive against the House Republican leadership
intended to force a vote to overhaul campaign finance laws. At the
same time, House Republicans contemplated embracing an issue
traditionally championed by Democrats _ an increase in the minimum
wage.
</P>
<P>
   The jostling for position indicated that after the impeachment
trial of President Clinton, followed by weeks of relative silence
in Congress, the battle is about to intensify over which party
controls the political agenda, particularly in the narrowly divided
House. And as they struggle over a wide range of domestic concerns
from health-care policy, to tax cuts, to spending, to the shape of
the Social Security system, both parties face calculations about
which issues they want to promote, which they want to neutralize
and which they want to campaign on in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans are trying to keep attention on four primary
themes this spring: Social Security, tax cuts, education and
national defense. Monday they reconciled minor differences in House
and Senate budget blueprints, and they planned to push through both
houses this week a budget that they say will wall off Social
Security payroll tax receipts so that they could not be diverted to
other uses. The budget plan for the 2000 fiscal year would also
make room for at least $15 billion in tax cuts next year, growing
to as much as $800 billion in tax cuts across the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   The budget is a policy blueprint that sets the guidelines for an
array of spending bills and tax-cutting legislation and a
monthslong struggle is expected with Clinton over the size of tax
cuts and the shape of domestic spending programs. Anticipating that
battle, congressional Republican leaders on Monday sought to rally
the public behind tax cuts at a town hall meeting in
Fredericksburg, Va., alongside Gov. James Gilmore, a Republican who
won election in 1997 by pledging to eliminate the state's unpopular
personal property tax on cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often in government there's competing philosophies,'' said
Rep. Thomas Davis, R-Va., who heads the House Republicans'
re-election effort. In a swipe at the Democrats, Davis said,
``There's one group in government that seems to believe that if it
moves tax it, if it keeps moving regulate it and if it stops moving
subsidize it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Republican plan to cut taxes, though walling off Social
Security money, would require stiff spending cuts that many of the
Republicans charged with writing the spending bills have complained
would prove too difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are pushing their own agenda including an increase in
the minimum wage, an array of education programs and an overhaul of
the campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
   They also want to pass a measure that would put stricter
controls on health maintenance organizations and they are hoping to
be able to draw moderate Republicans to their side on some of these
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we're going to spend a lot of time getting a budget
done,'' said Rep. Martin Meehan, D-Mass. ``But we've had nothing on
health care, nothing on HMO reform. Really if the speaker wanted to
send a message he was going to work in a bipartisan way, the first
bill he would have considered is campaign finance reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year a coalition of House Republicans and Democrats managed
to overcome an array of obstacles put before them by the Republican
leadership and pass by a 252-179 vote a bipartisan campaign finance
bill sponsored by Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., and Meehan. The
measure, which died in the Senate, would ban the unregulated and
unlimited donations to political parties that were at the heart of
the campaign finance abuses in the 1996 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The new speaker, J. Dennis Hastert has indicated that while he
will allow a campaign finance debate this Congress, he does not
plan to take up the measure until all of the year's spending bills
are passed. But proponents of the Shays-Meehan bill want it passed
quickly so that there will be pressure on the Senate to act.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to force the issue to the House floor, Rep. Jim
Turner, D-Texas, said that a group of Democrats on Wednesday will
begin to collect signatures on a petition demanding a vote. It
takes the signatures of 218 House members to succeed. A key
question will be how many Republicans join the Democrats. ``I don't
know that I anticipate Republican members joining us immediately,''
said Turner. ``But I think the pressure will increase as the days
pass.''
</P>
<P>
   The House Republican leadership is showing more flexibility on
another measure usually associated with Democrats _ an increase in
the minimum wage. The Republicans' traditional allies in business
oppose the bill. But it is popular with the public and a number of
Republican moderates such as Rep. Jack Quinn, from upstate New
York, favor the measure, which means that it is likely to have the
votes to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Republican strategists say they are now considering
moving a minimum wage hike bill to the floor in the summer to
deprive Democrats of the potent issue. ``You get it on the floor
and get it off the floor as quickly possible,'' said a Republican
House strategist. ``Why drag it out and let them make a huge issue
out of it given the vote margin we have?''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats want to raise the minimum wage _ which is now
$5.15 an hour _ to $6.15 across two years. Quinn would raise it to
$6.15 over three years and index it for inflation in future years.
It was not clear what kind of increase the Republican leadership
would allow to the floor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
