<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5437 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENEZUELA-MILITARY-70     04-12 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-MILITARY-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW ROLE, VENEZUELA ARMY RUNS CLINICS AND SHOPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ After decades in the background, the
Venezuelan military has begun playing a more active and prominent
role under a new president who is himself a former army colonel and
paratrooper. But it nevertheless came as a shock to Judith Gonzalez
to find soldiers selling meat and cheese out of the back of a truck
at a weekend market in her working-class neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles away, a team of military doctors was running a
medical clinic, delivering pediatric, gynecological and dental care
to residents of a slum neighborhood too poor to afford medical
care. Out in the countryside, meanwhile, other units of Venezuela's
120,000-strong military were building or repairing roads, sewers,
schools and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I would ever see the army doing this, but it
is welcome,'' Mrs. Gonzalez, a schoolteacher, said as she stood in
line at the market on a recent Saturday morning. ``Just the
presence of the military here inspires order and discipline, and
that is exactly what this country needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Venezuelans, however, view the military's newly enhanced
mission with alarm. President Hugo Chavez, who took office on Feb.
2 after winning 57 percent of the popular vote, led a failed coup
attempt in 1992, and his critics fear that he is now trying to
achieve by stealth what he could not accomplish by force of arms:
the militarization of a government that for more than 40 years has
been under civilian control.
</P>
<P>
   The news magazine Primicia, for instance, recently warned of a
surge of what it called ``military nationalism'' in a cover article
that also compared Chavez to the late Panamanian strongman Omar
Torrijos Herrera and Gen. Gamal Abdel Nasser of Egypt. Chavez, the
magazine wrote, ``is a proponent of linking the armed forces to
social tasks for the purpose of advancing `a revolution,''' that,
the magazine cautioned, comes ``with its ration of authoritarianism
included.''
</P>
<P>
   Since assuming office, Chavez has indeed appointed several
officers who joined him in the coup attempt to important government
posts. Colleagues from the military now serve as the minister of
transportation, governor of the Federal District, chief of the
federal Bureau of Taxation and director of the secret police.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, two other former coup plotters were elected
president of the Senate and governor of the important oil-producing
state of Zulia. Chavez has also appointed a pair of colonels still
on active duty to the board of directors of Petroleos de Venezuela,
the powerful government-owned oil company that the president has
criticized as ``a state within the state.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in his office at the same presidential palace
that he and fellow rebels tried to storm, Chavez, 44, played down
his reliance on his former colleagues, saying, ``The military
presence is minimal, not even reaching 1 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Technical capacity and leadership skills are what
have oriented the placement of some military officers in important
posts, so as to lead and to struggle against corruption and
incompetence.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez acknowledged that one purpose of the social works
program, called the Plan Bolivar 2000, is to improve the armed
forces' standing in the eyes of the people. The image of the
military was damaged a decade ago when, as he put it, ``a genocidal
government used the army against the people, to massacre the
people'' in quelling a popular uprising.
</P>
<P>
   But the main objective of the military's expanded role, Chavez
said, ``is to attend to the country's most urgent needs, the
necessities of housing, work, food, health, education and combating
corruption, since poverty is so exaggeratedly high.'' The army has
the manpower, equipment and other resources required for such an
effort, he said, and it would be wasteful not to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, the strategy seems to be popular. In neighborhoods
where troops are now deployed and working with assistants hired
from the local civilian population, residents refer to them
affectionately as ``soldaditos,'' or ``little soldiers,'' and do
not hesitate to seek their advice when problems, ranging from
bureaucracy to crime, arise in their communities.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Eloy Vivas, for example, was looking forward to having the
military rebuild and recondition the school of which he is
principal. But, he said, he received a written directive from the
Ministry of Education ordering him ``not to allow any expansion or
improvements'' of his school, which has 650 pupils.
</P>
<P>
   So, Vivas said, he took the document to the chief of the army
battalion that is stationed in his slum neighborhood, Tacagua.
After conferring, they decided to ignore the Ministry's order and
plunge ahead with the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a miracle for us that they are even here,'' Vivas said
of the soldiers. ``We were without water here for three years, our
pleas completely ignored, so for somebody to tell me to turn help
away is completely absurd, ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Government officials have said that they plan to spend $12
million in public money on the social works program, which they
hope will be supplemented by donations from private enterprise. In
addition, members of civic groups and, to the suspicion of those
wary of the president's intentions, leaders of Chavez's Fifth
Republic Movement are working as volunteers on the more than 400
projects that are under way across this country of 23 million.
</P>
<P>
   The health and construction programs have been almost
universally welcomed, especially by the poor who are their main
beneficiary and the backbone of the president's support. But the
military-run ``people's markets'' have been more controversial,
despite the bargains they offer consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're damaging our livelihood and hurting our image,'' said
a butcher in the working-class neighborhood La Vega, where the army
has set up a weekend market that sells chicken, vegetables, cheese
and pasta at rock-bottom prices. ``We're not speculators, we're
just trying to make a living, and of course the army, with all its
resources, can sell products at prices cheaper than ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez said he was aware of the concerns stirred by the
military's more active role, and has taken steps to calm fears that
he plans to rule as a military strongman. Since being criticized
for wearing combat fatigues to one event, he has worn civilian
clothes, usually a business suit, at all his public appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, military jargon and habits continue to permeate
his daily routine. In speeches designed to rally the people to his
side, he often refers to ``battlefronts'' and ``taking to the
trenches'' to achieve his goals, which he and his supporters
maintain are being blocked by a corrupt Congress and a judiciary
beholden to traditional political parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the only resource that he can depend on,'' said a
general who works closely with the president. ``Some of us went to
the academy with him, others were his students, and still others
were his commanders or his subalterns. But we know him, and he
knows us, and that counts for a lot right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
