<SLUG> BC-CASPIAN-OIL-ART-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIPELINE WILL REDUCE NEW NATIONS' RELIANCE ON RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAKU, Azerbaijan _ The new nations of the Caucasus and Central
Asia will take a giant step away from their former masters in
Moscow this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Several presidents and a host of other political and business
leaders are expected to gather on Saturday at the Georgian port of
Supsa for a ceremony opening a 515-mile pipeline that will carry
oil from the Caspian Sea. By opening the pipeline, they will
symbolically cut an old umbilical cord that has bound this region
to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in the region believe that oil is the key to their
prosperity, but until now all pipeline routes have led through
Russia. That has given Russia the power to control and even choke
the region's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   The new pipeline breaks this monopoly. It gives a profoundly
important new option to countries that are beginning to exploit the
vast oil reserves under and around the Caspian.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means the world to us,'' said Vafa Guluzade, chief
foreign-policy adviser to President Heydar Aliyev of Azerbaijan,
the center of the Caspian oil boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``This pipeline gives Caspian countries a reliable way to export
our oil without going through Russia. It is hugely important in an
economic sense, but it is even more important politically. Now, for
the first time, we have direct access to the West. We are freeing
ourselves from Russia after 200 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The new pipeline begins at Baku, the capital of Azerbaijan, and
will carry 115,000 barrels of crude oil each day. After the oil
reaches Supsa, it will be loaded onto tankers that will carry it
across the Black Sea to the Mediterranean and to Western markets.
</P>
<P>
   Oil for the pipeline is being produced by a consortium of 11
companies from eight nations, including the United States. With the
addition of new pumping stations, and lubricants to make it flow
faster, the capacity of the line can be more than doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, oil from the consortium's undersea field has been
shipped out by rail and through an unreliable pipeline that snakes
north from Baku through the turbulent Russian republics of Chechnya
and Dagestan to Russia's Black Sea port of Novorossisk.
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline is intermittently closed by the separatist regime
in Chechnya, and shivering Russians who live along the way often
drill holes in it to divert oil for their needs.
</P>
<P>
   The new line has taken the consortium more than two years to
build and cost about $1.5 billion. At the peak of activity, more
than 3,000 people worked on it.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the oil companies, the most immediate beneficiaries of
the project will be Azerbaijan and Georgia, the two countries
through which it runs. Leaders of both countries complain that
Russia is trying to destabilize their fragile governments, and they
are eager to find new friends in the West.
</P>
<P>
   The Baku-Supsa pipeline will not be able to carry the large
amounts of oil that are expected to be produced by Caspian nations
in the coming years, though. Production is expected to exceed 1
million barrels a day by the end of the next decade. The United
States wants that oil to be exported through a pipeline that would
run from Azerbaijan across Georgia and Turkey to the Mediterranean,
but no contract has been signed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although most of the new Baku-Supsa pipeline runs underground,
there are security concerns. It runs near areas of Georgia where
separatists could pose a threat. Nonetheless, Georgian leaders are
as enthusiastic about it as their Azerbaijani counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a vitally important project for the entire region,
defining the region in the broadest sense as stretching from
Ukraine all the way to Uzbekistan and Kazakhstan,'' said Zurab
Zhvania, speaker of the Georgian Parliament. ``It gives us a chance
to connect ourselves to each other and to the world in a way that
keeps us free from political pressure or influence or manipulation
of any kind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a great deal to us,'' he continued, ``which is why
not everyone around us likes the idea. I'm talking about Russia,
but also about Iran. They are not happy, and I can understand why.
Actually, I think our enemies understand the importance of this
project better than our friends.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
