<HEADLINE>
REFUGEES REPORT ON YUGOSLAV TROOP MOVEMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANKOVIC, Macedonia _ Two hundred more Albanian refugees from
Kosovo crossed into Macedonia Monday, bringing with them fresh
accounts of an apparent Yugoslav effort to force Albanians out of
an area near Kosovo's border with Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav military forces have also been seen recently taking
defensive positions in the area, a Western diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   Such attacks and troop movements could be occurring throughout
Kosovo, the diplomat said, but the border area has major military
significance both for NATO and for the Kosovo Liberation Army, the
ethnic-Albanian separatist rebels.
</P>
<P>
   If NATO were to decide to use ground forces, an invasion of
Kosovo might include a thrust from Macedonia, across the border to
the southeast. And this border area is one possible route for the
rebels to smuggle weapons into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last week, Yugoslav forces have been expelling Kosovar
Albanians and taking up defensive positions on a far larger scale
along the border with Albania, to the southwest. The rebels have in
the past smuggled many of their supplies over the Albanian border.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees arriving Monday reported seeing Yugoslav army
convoys moving inside Kosovo. The convoys of tanks, jeeps and
trucks appeared to be rotating their positions to avoid NATO air
attacks, they said. Yugoslav soldiers are also sleeping in
residential areas, parking their vehicles there to avoid
bombardment, they said.
</P>
<P>
   All of the newly arrived refugees came here from the town of
Urosevac in southeastern Kosovo, about 30 miles from the border,
and they described a Yugoslav campaign to sweep Albanians out of
villages in the area over the last ten days. Their stories
dovetailed with accounts from the several hundred refugees who have
arrived here in sporadic groups since the Yugoslav forces
effectively sealed Kosovo's borders last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bislim Bebihu, a 32-year-old former traffic policeman, said
soldiers burned his village, Sojeve, which is near Urosevac, on
April 6 and killed his mother and father. He said he and his wife
and their son and three daughters fled to his aunt's house in the
town. Hiding indoors for the next ten days, he watched houses
burned and looted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a really dangerous situation,'' he said. ``They are
shooting and harassing people, entering houses and taking whatever
they like.''
</P>
<P>
   Idriz Pergadini, a 47-year-old farmer who said his village,
Mirashe, was shelled a week ago, believed that only two villages
around Urosevac had not been burned by Yugoslav forces. Residents
of those gutted villages are hiding in the woods or in the town
itself, he said, and both groups are desperately short of food.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have anything to buy,'' he said. ``There was no
food, nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Pergadini and the other refugees who recently arrived said they
were not forced to leave the town. They said fear that they would
be killed and a lack of food drove them to take a 7:30 a.m. train
from Urosevac to the Macedonian border.
</P>
<P>
   There, instead of being robbed, threatened or turned back at the
border crossing as other refugees were last week, they were allowed
by Yugoslav border guards to walk into Macedonia, they said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bebihu estimated that 300 ethnic Albanians remain trapped in
the town of Urosevac.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
