<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rescue effort critical for pilot, navigator
 &HT;    By Stacy Shelton and Milo Ippolito
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Boyd Clines steadied his helicopter less than 100
feet above a burning crane Monday to pull a stranded construction
worker to safety, it wasn't his first daring rescue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I joined the Army at 18 and I've been flying ever since,''
Clines, 52, of Douglasville, Ga., said.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Clines used the same techniques to pluck a
rafter stranded on an island in Sweetwater Creek floodwaters. But
probably the most harrowing flights the Arkansas native has made
were decades ago as a combat assault pilot in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of my rescues have been up in mountains or in jungles,
swamps and rivers,'' Clines said. ``In the army, I did a lot of
rescues of Special Forces teams in Laos and Cambodia.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cabbagetown fire was his ``first urban rescue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Downtown buildings are sort of like mountains. When the wind
comes through, it causes turbulence,'' Clines said.
</P>
<P>
   State officials gave equal credit to Clines' navigator on the
mission, Larry Rogers. It was Rogers who leaned out of the
helicopter, looking down to judge distances and guide Clines.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I did was look straight ahead,'' Clines said.
</P>
<P>
   Clines joined the Georgia Department of Natural Resources in
1979. He now regularly fights forest fires, and performs search and
rescue missions.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Clines had to do a particularly tricky piece of
flying. The winds were strong, and flames and smoke billowed up
from the five-story cotton mill. He had to fly within about 100
feet of the burning crane and keep the craft steady as a
firefighter was lowered by cable to the trapped worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we actually got (the firefighter) on the crane, I
thought, 'Well, this is going to work,' '' Clines said.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said he was not worried during the mission.
</P>
<P>
   Watching from another helicopter nearby, DNR Chief Pilot Michael
Thompson said it was ``good, good, good flying. . . I've been
flying 30 years and I was impressed. It was some piece of flying,
it really was.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those congratulating Clines Monday were Gov. Roy Barnes
and Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell. Both called to congratulate him.
</P>
<P>
   DNR Chief Pilot Michael Thompson,. who watched from another
helicopter, said it was ``good, good, good flying. I've been flying
30 years and I was impressed. It was some piece of flying, it
really was.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County Deputy Police Chief Steve Hogan, a friend of
Clines' watched the rescue on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I recognized his touch,'' Hogan said. ``I could tell
by watching that wasn't a rookie up there. Boyd and whoever that
fireman was hanging on that rope, yeah buddy, they earned their
money today.''
</P>
<P>
   Stacy Shelton and Milo Ippolito write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga. Sandra Eckstein contributed to
this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
