<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-COLBASE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE WCC STARS CATCH THE EYE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pepperdine sophomore Dane Sardinha is one of the nation's top
catchers, but he might not be the best catcher in his own
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Loyola Marymount's Scott Walter, also a sophomore, was the West
Coast Conference's Player of the Year in 1998. Walter sets the
standard, Pepperdine coach Frank Sanchez said, because he has
already proved himself as an elite college player.
</P>
<P>
   They will be on the same field this weekend, when third-ranked
Pepperdine plays at LMU in an important three-game series. The
Waves (31-4) are 11-3 and in first place in the Coast Division. The
Lions (20-16) are 9-5 and leading the West Division, one game ahead
of St. Mary's.
</P>
<P>
   Sardinha, one of the most sought-after prospects in the nation
as a senior in high school, made two unexpected decisions before he
even played a game at Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   First, he surprisingly chose the Waves over perennial powerhouse
Miami. He said he made his decision based on ``location and
coaching.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I also like being with the underdog team,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sardinha, who went to high school in Hawaii, also spurned the
Kansas City Royals after they made him a second-round pick in the
'97 amateur draft. He wanted a signing bonus of more than $1
million, but the Royals wouldn't go over $750,000 and the
negotiations broke down.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals, like every team, loved Sardinha's defense. He has a
strong arm _ he once picked off a runner from his knees _ and
Pepperdine pitcher Brad Tucker admires the way Sardinha ``frames''
pitches to get a strike call on a pitch that is out of the strike
zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``(He) is just a natural, gifted catcher,'' Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, Sardinha has improved from last year, when he hit
13 home runs but only batted .263. He's batting .382 with seven
homers and his total of 36 RBI is just two behind all of last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was widely publicized that he potentially was one of the
elite catchers in the country as a high school guy,'' Sanchez said.
``We typically try to stay away from guys that are going to turn
pro. With Dane, we knew it was a gamble. We came out smelling like
a rose.''
</P>
<P>
   LMU head coach Frank Cruz, Sanchez's former staff-mate at USC,
had a similar situation with Walter. The Dodgers drafted Walter in
the 16th round out of Loyola High and then offered him $375,000 to
sign. Walter held firm to his commitment to Cruz and the Lions, who
hadn't finished above .500 since 1991 and were coming off a 21-39
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been a dream of mine to play college baseball,''
Walter said. ``I thought that it would be a worthwhile experience.
I wouldn't have made a different decision, looking back on it. Not
at all. I'm having a great time.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's having his second straight outstanding season. He leads
the Lions with a .383 average and has seven homers and 33 RBI. Last
year, he batted .383 with eight homers and 67 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Staying the course: Cal State Northridge freshman shortstop
J.T. Stotts was given the option to redshirt the season a month ago
when his broken left foot was in a cast.
</P>
<P>
   Stotts and his parents decided against it.
</P>
<P>
   That judgment proved to be wise. Stotts, who batted .395 in 13
games with the Matadors before the injury, returned to action
Sunday at UCLA and singled in his first at-bat before the game was
rained out.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he expects to be rusty when CSUN plays a three-game
series at Washington this weekend, being hurt wasn't a total loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've learned a lot just by watching,'' he said. ``I've
also been in the weight room, getting stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Stotts was turning into one of the Matadors' best players before
he got hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Stotts' injury) was a real big thing that hurt us,'' senior
right-hander Jim DeBiase said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Another loss: When USC All-American catcher Eric Munson
went down with a broken hand on March 27, freshman Beau Craig
returned to the position where he was an all-state player in high
school.
</P>
<P>
   Craig, one of the nation's top recruits and an outstanding
defensive catcher, was more than a capable replacement; he was in
the lineup every game as the starting third baseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good one,'' USC coach Mike Gillespie said of Craig.
``He's a very good throwing catcher. I don't think he's overmatched
or overwhelmed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Craig is also hurt. He strained a muscle on his right side
lifting weights. Gillespie calls it a ``very unusual injury.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
