<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO EXPAND NATO ATTACKS, U.S. TO SEND 300 MORE WARPLANES TO
YUGOSLAVIA
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: 2nd take will move within 30 minutes.)  
(ac) 
 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO's senior commander, Gen. Wesley K. Clark,
Monday asked the Pentagon to contribute about 300 more warplanes to
the fight against Yugoslavia, in what would make possible a rapid
and strident expansion of NATO's attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The request, which officials said would be approved, will
increase the number of American and NATO aircraft committed to the
campaign to nearly 1,000, more than double the number _ 430 _ the
alliance had on hand when it began the the first strikes on March
24.
</P>
<P>
   For the United States, the latest increase _ a 60 percent jump
in warplanes _ significantly deepens the nation's involvement in
the war. The addition almost certainly means that the Air Force
will have to call up a number of reservists to provide crews for
all the aircraft, particularly the aerial refuelers, a senior
defense official said.
</P>
<P>
   While Pentagon and NATO officials have portrayed the raids on
Yugoslavia as successful, despite foul weather, the rapid buildup
underscores the limits of their impact on Yugoslavia's forces. With
the Clinton administration and NATO still adamantly ruling out the
use of ground forces, Clark's only option is an intensification of
air power.
</P>
<P>
   And as the air campaign moves into its third week, NATO
commanders have expressed their frustration at the Serbian military
force's entrenched, elusive positions. In recent days, NATO and
Pentagon officials have tried to prepare the public for several
weeks more of air strikes, a campaign that military officials
insist can cripple Serbian's military over a sustained period of
time.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels Monday, at the first gathering of NATO foreign
ministers since the bombing began, they pledged to keep up the air
attacks but at the same time searched for the shape of a political
settlement in Kosovo and urged Russia to be part of it.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's request came only two days after the Pentagon announced
that it had approved an earlier request for 82 more planes,
including F-16's designed to destroyed air-defenses and refuelers.
The officials declined to specify the exact number and type of
aircraft in his latest request but said they included both combat
and support planes, including F-15's and A-10's designed to go
after targets on the ground and still more refuelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to focus more heavily on the Yugoslav Army and
special police forces on a 24-hour basis,'' the senior defense
official said, speaking on  &UR; the  &LR; condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
