<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY SHARES ASIDE, STOCKS RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks rebounded from a decline in big technology
shares early Monday and ended the session soaring to new records,
as investors began to shift their attention to market sectors that
have underperformed.
</P>
<P>
   The sharp rise in prices came as a surprise to many analysts and
traders. Most market professionals had expected a rocky session
following Compaq Computer Corp.'s announcement after the market
closed on Friday that its first-quarter profits would be less than
half of what analysts had expected.
</P>
<P>
   Market averages did drop sharply at the opening, and computer
and other big technology companies remained under pressure
throughout the day. But buyers outside the technology sector soon
asserted themselves, setting the stage for what became a broad
rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today surprised everybody,'' said Richard Bernstein, chief
quantitative strategist at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. ``Anyone who says
they expected this to happen is a fibber.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up a robust 165.67 points,
or 1.63 percent, to 10,339.51, its first close above 10,300.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index gained 10.29 points, or
nearly 0.8 percent, to 1,358.64, a new closing high. The Nasdaq
composite index, which contains many technology issues, even
managed to eke out a gain, rising 5.76 points, to a closing high of
2,598.81.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Russell 2000 index of smaller-company stocks, which has
trailed other market indicators for nearly a year, rose 6.46
points, or 1.6 percent, to 412.32.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that money can come out of what has been the
strongest group and have it flow into other areas shows that the
game is still intact,'' said Michael Clark, head of U.S. stock
trading at Credit Suisse First Boston. ``And the market's improved
breadth is a healthy sign.''
</P>
<P>
   For a day at least, investors who have ridden technology stocks
to their current lofty heights seemed to conclude that the Compaq
announcement cast a cloud over first-quarter results for other
companies that make either personal computers or their components.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq was severely punished. The stock fell 6 7/8 a share, or
more than 22 percent, to 24 1/16. It was by far the most heavily
traded issue on the New York Stock Exchange on Monday, with more
than 111.3 million shares changing hands.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq's announcement was not seen as good news for other big
technology companies, either. IBM fell 2 7/8 a share, to 183 7/16,
and Hewlett Packard lost 1\, to 68 3/8.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, which is expected to report its first-quarter results
after the market closes Tuesday, fell 4 1/8 a share, to 61\. Lucent
Technologies dropped 4 3/16, to 59 7/16. Microsoft was down 1\, to
93. EMC lost 4 5/16, to 130 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology is going to have problems, but I am not sure those
problems will last long,'' said John Manley, equity strategist at
Salomon Smith Barney. ``I think we are late in the game for
technology, but it is such a high-quality group that the risk of
writing its epitaph prematurely exists.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as worries about earnings were pushing investors out of big
technology stocks, they were snapping up shares of Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought a key indicator of what would happen in the wake of
the Compaq announcement would be the behavior of Internet stocks,''
said William Meehan, chief market analyst at Cantor Fitzgerald.
``That is a group where you don't have to worry about earnings
announcements.''
</P>
<P>
   After slumping at the opening, Internet stocks surged. By the
close Thestreet.com's Internet index had gained 58.44 points, or 8
percent, to a new record of 790.37.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, optimism about first-quarter earnings helped to
increase prices of shares in finance, drug and heavy-equipment
companies.
</P>
<P>
   American Express led the Dow index higher, rising 7, to 135 3/8.
General Electric gained 4 5/16, to 116{, a new 52-week high.
Caterpillar gained 2 5/8, to 51 3/8, after an analyst at Merrill
Lynch raised his long-term rating on the company.
</P>
<P>
   Among drug stocks, Merck gained 1} a share, to 85, and Pfizer
rose 4 1/8, to 150 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   Among financial-service companies, Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette
jumped 8 a share, to 94. Merrill Lynch gained 1 13/16, to 99 15/16.
And Charles Schwab rose 9, to 135; since the start of the year, the
stock has gained more than 140 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with recent Mondays, the trading activity on Monday was
quite brisk. Volume on the Big Board was 810.8 million shares. On
the Nasdaq, 1.1 billion shares changed hands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
