<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEIGHBORHOOD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Neighbors hope for 'speedy' recovery in Cabbagetown
 &HT;    By S.A. Reid and Kim Byrd
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cabbagetown was a melting pot of emotions Monday as
residents watched the spectacular fire gut the historic Fulton Bag
and Cotton Mill lofts , the biggest symbol of their Southeast
Atlanta neighborhood's quiet rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   The smoke and fire fanned feelings ranging from disbelief that
such an important project would suffer a setback of this magnitude,
to anger by some who say the blaze was a tragedy waiting to happen.
</P>
<P>
   A common thread, however, is concern about the fire's cause,
whether it could have been prevented or has any possible connection
to long-smoldering complaints about the project by community and
mill residents.
</P>
<P>
   These hot button issues most likely will dominate today's
Cabbagetown Neighborhood Improvement Association meeting scheduled
for 7 p.m. at the Salvation Army's Boy's and Girl's Club, where the
fire forced the evacuation of 20 children Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, no one would have wished this to happen. We hope
recovery will be speedy and damage minimal,'' said Gerry Weber,
CNIA president. ``What we expect is that there will be a thorough
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   One community concern is the perception of some that mill and
its residents have been slow to integrate into the neighborhood.
Mills residents themselves have their own set of complaints about
shoddy construction and missing amenities that prompted them to
petition for a management change.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the complaints, city officials, neighborhood leaders and
residents credit the mill as a positive addition but say the
marquee project isn't the only thing Cabbagetown has going for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been real neat to watch it (the mill) being built,'' said
Lisa Shinault who rushed from her job at downtown's Apparel Mart to
rescue her cat ``chickey.'' A lot of neat people have moved into
the neighborhood. There are a lot of cool things that are suppose
to happen, and I think they will still happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But Peggy Williams, director of the Cabbagetown Revitalization
and Future Trust, sees the picture as a little less rosy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're real fortunate we didn't lose any more houses,'' said
Williams whose community land trust organization has renovated 50
homes during the past decade on Carroll and Savannah streets.
</P>
<P>
   `` What can you say. It's devastating. I just feel for the
people I saw walking up and seeing their houses burn.''
</P>
<P>
   S.A. Reid and Kim Byrd write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
