<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5449 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      04-12 1373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO HITS REFINERY, CAR FACTORY, AIRPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES AND LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite bad weather, NATO unleashed a flurry of
attacks Monday on Yugoslavia, targeting its biggest oil refinery,
the factory that makes Yugo cars, and Pristina's Slatina airport.
An allied missile intended for a railroad bridge in southeast
Serbia hit a passenger train, killing at least 10 people and
injuring 16.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, fighting on the Kosovo-Albania border between Serb
forces and Kosovo Liberation Army guerrillas entered its fourth
day. Albania said it would accept the deployment of extra NATO
troops to augment the 8,000 soldiers due to arrive soon to help
provide aid for refugees fleeing Kosovo and to secure Albanian's
borders.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, NATO foreign ministers, meeting for the first time
since the nearly three-week-old air campaign began, presented a
united front against Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, saying
the airstrikes had taken a toll on the Serb army and security
forces and vowing to press ahead until he accepts the alliance's
terms for ending the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav officials reported scores of casualties and injuries
from the 20th day of NATO attacks, including the train deaths and
three others who died in an attack on a car near the Kosovo capital
of Pristina. And as darkness fell Monday, air raid sirens went off
in Belgrade, Nis, Kragujevac and Podgorica, heralding another night
of air strikes. A few hours later, Yugoslav anti-aircraft defense
systems fired at NATO planes flying over Belgrade, state news
reported.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments Monday:
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX) The Yugoslav parliament voted to join an alliance with
Russia and Belarus _ a move apparently designed to try to get a
reluctant Russia to stop the NATO airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX) Pentagon officials said the first of 24 Apache
helicopters could arrive in Albania later this week to join the
NATO strike force, increasing substantially the alliance's ability
to destroy Serb tanks and troops.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX) Defense Secretary William S. Cohen said there was no
consensus in the United States or in NATO for the introduction of
ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force Major General Charles Wald said cloudy and rainy skies
once again compromised NATO strikes over the weekend, a situation
likely to remain for several days. But, he added, bombs rained down
on at least two dozen targets anyway, as the allies pulled out
their all-weather weaponry and hit sites across Kosovo and Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, allied warplanes struck Yugoslavia's biggest oil
refineries, the airport in Pristina, and again hit the Yugo car
factory, which is housed in a complex that also makes weapons.
Serbia's second-largest city, Novi Sad, where two major bridges
were damaged early in the air campaign, also was hit again.
</P>
<P>
   In the train incident, a missile hit the second coach, and three
other cars caught fire and derailed, according to Yugoslavia's
state-run Tanjug news agency. The report said the train was bound
from Belgrade to Salonika, Greece.
</P>
<P>
   NATO issued a statement saying it had hit a rail bridge that was
an important military supply line and had taken ``extraordinary
measures to avoid collateral casualties'' during the airstrikes.
But ``regrettably, we cannot exclude the possiblity of casualties
in this instance.''
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, Cohen said the United States had learned of Serbs
deserting from combat units in Kosovo and of a growing effort by
young Yugoslavs to evade being called up by the reserves.
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary General Javier Solana said, ``Our operations are
taking a heavy toll of President Milosevic's army and security
forces. We are tightening the screw on those forces in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Along Yugoslavia's border with Albania, fighting between Serb
forces and Kosovo rebels was reportedly intensifying. The Tanjug
news agency claimed at least 150 rebels were killed in a border
clash.
</P>
<P>
   Albania, struggling to cope with an influx of some 300,000
Kosovar Albanian refugees forced to flee their homes by Serb
soldiers and police, asked for NATO assistance to help prevent
further attacks against its territory.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to speed up the humanitarian relief effort, the US
Navy for the first time began using helicopters to deliver food,
water, tents and other supplies from Tirana, the Albanian capital,
to an area near the Kosovo border.
</P>
<P>
   Using the helicopters will allow relief workers to deliver
supplies four times as fast to 260,000 refugees in 11 Albanian
camps.
</P>
<P>
   On another front, Yugoslavia's parliament voted to join an
alliance with Russia and Belarus _ an effort regarded as an attempt
to draw Russia into the military conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Russia favors the idea of incorporating Yugoslavia into its
alliance but said membership wouldn't be granted immediately, and
military aid would not be automatic.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright, who is scheduled to
meet Tuesday with Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov in Oslo,
Norway, said she would seek ``common ground'' on the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Two New England Air National Guard refueling tankers have been
sent to Europe to support NATO forces. The two KC-135 tankers,
three air crews and a small group of maintenance workers from the
101st Refueling Wing left Bangor, Maine, over the weekend to take
part in Operation Allied Force, Col. William I. Smith, the wing
commander, said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   And, after a much-criticized delay, the Pentagon announced
Monday that the first of 24 low-flying, high-performing Apache
helicopters could arrive in Albania this week to enhance NATO's
airpower and ability to strike tank columns and troops loyal to
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have accused the Pentagon of moving too slowly to deploy
the Apaches, considered one of the most lethal aircraft in the
world and one of the most effective at destroying targets such as
the Yugoslavian army units.
</P>
<P>
   However, NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said: ``Let me not give the
impression _ which I think would be erroneous _ that the Apaches
are somehow the 7th Cavalry arriving on the scene.''
</P>
<P>
   The US Army is shifting 2,500 support troops equipped with radar
detectors and missile launchers to protect and cover the Apaches
that will be based in Tirana. Many observers say this move
represents the closest involvement of US ground forces in the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Senators John McCain, a Republican from Arizona who is on the
Armed Services Committee, and Joseph Biden, a Democrat from
Delaware who is on the Foreign Relations Committee, Monday
circulated nearly identical resolutions that would give President
Clinton ``the authority to use all necessary force'' to meet NATO's
goals in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But Cohen sought to quell any clamor in Congress for ground
troops. He said NATO's military brass ``has indicated they do not
believe it is necessary... and have not requested it. And so any
consideration for ground troops is something for the future, and we
do not believe is necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   With an estimated 700,000 refugees inside Kosovo and at risk of
starvation and death, the NATO ministers meeting in Brussels
considered for the first time establishing the province as a
protectorate as a way to shield it from the Yugoslav military.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was discussed during a closed session of the North
Atlantic Council as part of plan to support autonomy for Kosovar
Albanians after the conflict is settled and the refugees returned.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said that although NATO was not considering cutting
Kosovo out of the Yugoslavian federation, the foreign ministers
considered ``some kind of international protective status'' for the
region.
</P>
<P>
   Such a protectorate would allow the 1.8 million Kosovar
Albanians living in the province before the airstrikes to have ``a
high degree of self-government without the threats and terror that
they have been living under,'' Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, however, ruled out arming the rebel Kosovo Liberation
Army. NATO also announced that Milosevic would not be allowed to
maintain any military presence in Kosovo as a condition for peace.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material used to prepare of this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
