<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5453 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLEET-BASEBALL-BOS &LR;      04-12 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEET-BASEBALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEET FIRST BANK TO SPONSOR MAJOR LEAGUE BASEBALL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Fleet Financial Group Monday became a national sponsor
of Major League Baseball, announcing an agreement said to be worth
$4 million to $6 million over three years.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first such national marketing deal between a bank and
any of the four major sports leagues, officials and observers said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike their cousins in the more nationally based financial
services and insurance industries, banks _ traditionally regional
or local entities _ have not pursued national sports sponsorships.
But Fleet's recently announced intention to merge with BankBoston
made sponsoring the Major Leagues more attractive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes even more sense now, having announced our intentions
with BankBoston,'' said Terrence Murray, Fleet's chairman and chief
operating officer. ``We are even more of a national bank with
national customers. Sponsoring Major League Baseball is more
evidence of how willing we are to play at that level.''
</P>
<P>
   But to create exclusivity, Fleet and Major League Baseball had
to squeeze into a niche adjacent to another Boston institution, the
John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co. Hancock is the exclusive
sponsor of Major League Baseball in the financial services
category.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of this deal, Fleet will either be seen as the brave
pioneer among banks in national sports sponsorships, or it will be
seen as having paid too much for a category that is now too
narrow,'' said Lance Helgeson, editor of the IEG Marketing Report,
in Chicago. ``But my sense is that they did well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like Fleet, more and more banks are expanding and that
means their marketing areas are growing, too,'' Helgeson said. ``So
there's a sense out there that other banks may well follow Fleet
into this area.''
</P>
<P>
   The positioning of the banking and financial services categories
in Major League Baseball may be especially crucial for Hancock. Its
president and chief operating officer, David D'Alessandro, has said
that, given his much-publicized displeasure with the International
Olympic Committee, he is reviewing whether to pull the Olympic
sponsorship dollars _ and he may decide to put them on baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Major League Baseball is my ace in the hole,'' D'Alessandro
said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet officials said Hancock's sponsorship was part of the
consideration between the negotiators for the bank and Major League
Baseball. Observers said it likely lowered, at least somewhat, the
value and cost of the Fleet sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Finucane, Fleet's senior vice president and director of
corporate marketing and communications, said the bank will not
adverstise any of its investment services, through the baseball
sponsorship, because that is deemed part of Hancock's category.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did what we could to accommodate Fleet, while not taking
away from Hancock,'' said Derrick Johnson, a spokesman for Major
League Baseball. ``We think there is plenty of room for both the
financial services category and a bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball and bank officials declined to release the terms of the
deal, which were provided by sports industry observers like
Helgeson.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet officials say they will leverage the new sponsorship with
a major marketing campaign, including television, radio, print,
outdoor, in-stadium, and public-transit advertising. The campaign
theme will be: ``Fleet Keeps Baseball Going.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleet last year arranged a $425 million credit deal with Major
League Baseball, among the largest ever in sports-related
financing. It is used by participating teams, in part, to refinance
existing debt. Fleet does banking with 12 of the 30 Major League
franchises, and is a sponsor of both the Boston Red Sox and the New
York Yankees. It also has relationships with sports-related vendors
who manufacture equipment, build stadiums, and provide concessions,
bank officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet used the announcement at Fenway Park Monday to show off
its new advertising sign on the right field wall and to also
announce that it will sponsor the 1999 Major League All-Star Game,
to be played at Fenway in July.
</P>
<P>
   The bank also announced a new endorsement agreement with Red Sox
shortstop Nomar Garciaparra. Garciaparra will work with a variety
of community service groups catering to youth on behalf of the
bank.
</P>
<P>
   When Garciaparra asked Murray to play catch with him, as a way
of welcoming the bank to Major League Baseball, Murray smiled,
blushed, and seemed every bit as happy as any kid given the same
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember being a boy and catching the train from Woonsocket,
R.I., to come up to Fenway with my friends,'' said Murray, who once
played left field for Harvard, as he adjusted his glove. ``So this
is a real treat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 2109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
