<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-PLANE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLOMBIAN REBELS SUSPECTED OF HIJACKING PLANE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN OTIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia _ A passenger plane with 46 people aboard was
hijacked Monday by suspected leftist rebels and forced to land at a
clandestine airstrip in northern Colombia, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The passengers and crew disappeared after armed men herded them
into boats on a nearby river, said air force Gen. Hector Fabio
Velasco. Among the passengers was a Colombian congressman.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were people in civilian clothes and some in uniform
directing the passengers down to the river,'' Velasco said.
</P>
<P>
   The twin-engine Fokker-50 aircraft was operated by Avianca,
Colombia's largest airline. Flight 9463, with 41 passengers and
five crew members aboard, was scheduled to make the short hop from
the northern city of Bucaramanga to the Colombian capital of
Bogota.
</P>
<P>
   The plane took off at 10:32 a.m. and disappeared shortly
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   At first, officials feared an accident. But the aircraft was
spotted about three hours later at an airstrip near the town of
Simiti, 225 miles north of Bogota in Bolivar state. Private pilots
flying over the area reported seeing a large group of people
boarding boats.
</P>
<P>
   Ernesto Huertas, director of Colombia's civil aviation
authority, said police visited the scene and ``found the plane, but
there were no passengers or crew.''
</P>
<P>
   The remote jungle area is infested with leftist rebels as well
as right-wing paramilitary death squads. Army Gen. Rafael Hernandez
Lopez said that police and army troops were combing the region.  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Radionet of Bogota reported that police intelligence agents
believed the crime may have been a joint operation of Colombia's
two main rebel groups _ the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia,
known as the FARC, and the smaller National Liberation Army, or the
ELN.
</P>
<P>
   The FARC and the ELN have funded their 35-year war against the
government, in part, by kidnapping prominent Colombians and
foreigners and by demanding huge ransom payments. They usually
carry out their kidnappings at highway roadblocks.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia has the highest rate of kidnappings in the world. Last
year, the guerrillas were blamed for 1,385 of the 2,216 kidnappings
reported in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The abductions have continued even though the FARC and the
Colombian government opened peace talks in January. Last month,
FARC commandos kidnapped and executed three Americans who were
working with one of Colombia's indigenous groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that the guerrillas reflect'' on their behavior, said
Sabas Pretelt, a member of the National Peace Commission, which is
advising the government on negotiations with the rebels. ``Grabbing
50 or 60 people cannot be pardoned, even by God.''
</P>
<P>
   A new round of peace talks between the FARC and the government
is scheduled to begin next week.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's hijacking was the first of a Colombian commercial
aircraft in 12 years. Many Colombians rely on air travel, even for
short distances, because guerrilla roadblocks are so common.
</P>
<P>
   The passengers on the Avianca flight included Juan Manuel Corzo,
a Conservative Party congressman, as well as the major of the town
of Zulia and the president of a state-run natural gas company.
Several women, children and elderly people were also on board.
</P>
<P>
   Marta Flores, the sister of one passenger, said her brother
suffers from pulmonary problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in very delicate shape,'' Flores said. ``It's impossible
for him to endure something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, a top FARC commander threatened to kidnap Colombian
lawmakers unless they passed a prisoner-exchange law. The FARC is
holding about 300 police and army troops and wants to exchange them
for 450 jailed rebels.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
