<HEADER>
A5462 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIRE-DRAMA-COX     04-12 0334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRE-DRAMA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cotton mill fire: The moment that stopped Atlanta's heart
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As five-story flames roared through a massive piece of
Atlanta history, it was the human drama _ one man risking his life
to save another; a swooping, dangling rescue on the crest of an
inferno _ that enthralled people Monday.
</P>
<P>
   All Atlanta watched in stunned amazement for 90 minutes as
trapped construction worker Ivers Sims, perched on a wind-blown
crane 250 above the ground, waited as the flames grew higher and
higher, closer and closer.
</P>
<P>
   And then in soared firefighter Matt Moseley, clamped
precariously to a 50-foot rope below a helicopter, looking like
some superhero thrust from comic book into real life.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 3 p.m. on a balmy day, people in offices and homes
seemed to stop everything as two men's lives hung in the balance of
a heart-stopping drama. Hung by the thread of narrow cord.
</P>
<P>
   With flames from the Fulton Bag and Cotton Mill licking at their
heels, Moseley landed on the crane's arm and maneuvered to the far
end, where, through the intense heat, he cracked a joke. He told
Sims he had been sent to tell him he could knock off early.
</P>
<P>
   With that, the firefighter strapped the man into a harness and
they held onto each other as the helicopter swept away from the
conflagration, over treetops and cars and people watching amazed
from byways, bridges and buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The Cabbagetown community of southeast Atlanta may have lost a
treasured bit of its past, but the perfectly executed courage of a
firefighter reminded people that some things transcend buildings
and history, that in an age when real-life heros seem as elusive as
smoke, ordinary men can sometimes work magic.
</P>
<P>
   They landed out of harm's way, on the green grass. Sims walked
to a stretcher. People applauded as he was wheeled to an ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
