<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5464 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONTEMPT-2TAK     04-12 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONTEMPT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE HOLDS CLINTON IN CONTEMPT FOR HIS TESTIMONY IN PAULA JONES
CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER and NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge on Monday held President Clinton in
contempt of court for willfully providing false testimony under
oath about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky in the sexual
misconduct lawsuit filed by Paula Jones.
</P>
<P>
   In a scathing 34-page ruling, U.S. District Court Judge Susan
Webber Wright of Little Rock, Ark., said that Clinton had
deliberately refused to obey her orders to provide truthful
testimony during a Jan. 17, 1998, deposition before her and Mrs.
Jones' attorneys. She said the president's actions had subverted
the rule of law and violated Mrs. Jones' right to information
relevant to her case.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's order was the first time a president has been held in
contempt of court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court takes no pleasure whatsoever in holding this
nation's President in contempt of court,'' wrote the judge, a
onetime law student of Clinton's who was appointed to the bench by
President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   However, she said, ``The record demonstrates by clear and
convincing evidence that the President responded to plaintiffs'
questions by giving false, misleading and evasive answers that were
designed to obstruct the judicial process.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Wright cited the president for civil contempt and ordered
him to pay ``any reasonable expenses'' _ including legal fees _
incurred by Mrs. Jones as a result of Clinton's false testimony.
She gave Mrs. Jones' lawyers 20 days to submit an estimate of their
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   She also ordered Clinton to reimburse her court $1,202, the cost
of her travel to Washington in January 1998 to preside over the
deposition in the Jones suit, which was taken in the office of
Clinton's attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   And she referred the matter to the Professional Conduct
Committee of the Arkansas Supreme Court, which has the power to
revoke Clinton's license to practice law or impose other sanctions
on him. The panel hears all types of complaints against lawyers,
but is likely to take a referral from a federal judge particularly
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Wright said she attempted to treat Clinton as he would any
other defendant in a civil proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that regard,'' she wrote, ``there simply is no escaping the
fact that the President deliberately violated this court's
discovery orders and thereby undermined the integrity of the
judicial system. Sanctions must be imposed, not only to redress the
President's misconduct, but to deter others who might themselves
consider emulating the President of the United States by engaging
in misconduct that undermines the integrity of the judicial
system.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House referred all questions about the ruling to
Robert S. Bennett, one of Clinton's private attorneys. Bennett's
office said he would have no comment until he had a chance to
review the judge's order.
</P>
<P>
   But a member of the president's legal team, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said that it may not be in Clinton's legal,
political or financial interest to challenge the contempt citation.
To do so would involve several months of motions and hearings that
would keep the matter alive in the media and cost thousands of
dollars in additional legal fees. However, the president and his
advisers have not yet decided what to do, this lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   John W. Whitehead, one of several lawyers who represented Mrs.
Jones last year, said he could not give an accurate estimate of the
cost of Clinton's false testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to do an accounting,'' he said. ``We have to look at
everything that occurred after Jan. 17 and see if it can be
attributed to the president's answers that day.'' He said the
figure would likely be in the ``tens of thousands of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jones sued Clinton in 1994, alleging that he had made a
crude sexual advance to her in a Little Rock hotel room when he was
governor of Arkansas and she was a low-level state employee.
Clinton denied the allegations and sought to have the case quashed,
but the Supreme Court in 1997 unanimously ruled that the president
was subject to civil litigation even during his tenure in office.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Wright dismissed Mrs. Jones' lawsuit last April, saying
that the president's behavior, while boorish if proven, did not
meet the standard of sexual harassment under federal law. Mrs.
Jones appealed, and last November, Clinton settled her claim with
an out-of-court settlement and a payment of $850,000.
</P>
<P>
   As the Jones case was winding down, the criminal investigation
of the president was moving forward. On Aug. 17, Clinton appeared
by videotape before a federal grand jury and admitted that he had
had a sexual relationship with Ms. Lewinsky over a 21-month period
from late 1995 through early 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``The President directly contradicted his deposition testimony
by acknowledging `inappropriate intimate contact' with Ms. Lewinsky
on numerous occasions,'' Judge Wright said in Monday's order,
referring to his grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The judge said that she first learned that Clinton had given
false testimony in the Jones suit when Clinton went on television
that night to admit to having given ``misleading'' answers to Mrs.
Jones' lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was during the President's televised address that the Court
first learned the President may be in contempt,'' Judge Wright
said.
</P>
<P>
   She revealed that she was considering citing Clinton for
contempt in a footnote to an order last September. She waited until
now to act, she said on Monday, because she did not want to
interfere with the ongoing criminal investigation and the
congressional impeachment inquiry and trial.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Wright ruled on Monday that Clinton testified falsely in
January of last year when he said that he did not recall being
alone with Ms. Lewinsky and denied having had a sexual relationship
with her. The judge said those statements were demonstrably false
and had denied Mrs. Jones the right to information that might have
supported her sexual harassment claim.
</P>
<P>
   The House of Representatives in December impeached Clinton on
two counts, perjury before the federal grand jury in August and
obstruction of justice. Members voted not to cite him for false
statements in the Jones lawsuit, in part because the case had been
dismissed by Judge Wright eight months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate acquitted Clinton on both charges in February.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's ruling, Judge Wright made several references to
other ``contumacious'' conduct by the president, which she said she
chose not to address in the interest of bringing the matter to a
reasonably swift conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   She specifically cited Clinton's violation of her order not to
discuss his deposition testimony with anyone outside his legal
team. She noted that a day after giving testimony, Clinton summoned
his private secretary, Betty Currie, to the White House to review
his testimony with her. Judge Wright noted that others had violated
her confidentiality order as well.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also said that she had not addressed other conduct by
the president because it was under investigation by Kenneth Starr,
the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Wright said she found the president in contempt without
holding extensive hearings because she limited her order to factual
matters that were not in dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``The President has essentially admitted that he intended to
mislead plaintiff in her efforts at gaining information deemed by
this Court to be relevant,'' the judge wrote, ``and hearings would
not assist the Court in addressing the President's misconduct
regarding his failure to obey this Court's discovery orders.''
</P>
</TEXT>
