<HEADER>
A5466 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIREMAIN-COX     04-12 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIREMAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Massive blaze engulfs historic neighborhood; 1 man trapped,
rescued
 &HT;    By Jay Croft, Gita Smith and Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The fire that consumed a Cabbagetown mill and the
resources of the entire Atlanta Fire Department began in a trash
can and was somehow caused by a construction torch, officials said
Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Within moments, it had become Atlanta's biggest blaze in 15
years, leading to the dramatic, televised rescue of a construction
worker as nearby homes and businesses were charred and more were
threatened.
</P>
<P>
   The blaze started about 2:35 p.m. at 170 Boulevard S.E., between
the fourth and fifth floors of the five-story Mill No. 1 at the
Fulton Bag and Cotton Mill, which was being renovated into a $45
million loft apartment complex.
</P>
<P>
   Winds gusted through large open windows, swirling the fire and
heat around the inside of the building, with each floor flaming
down to ignite the one below it.
</P>
<P>
   The fire department devoted virtually all its personnel and
equipment, with 110 firefighters, 35 engines and 10 ladder-trucks.
Atlanta Police and the Fulton County Sheriff's Department sent
dozens of officers, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind just made it horrendous,'' said Terry Wilson of
Forest Park, Ga., who was back visiting his old neighborhood in
southeast Atlanta when the fire started. ``This is sad to see. It's
like `Gone with the Wind.' Here goes Cabbagetown.''
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen houses and three or four apartment buildings were
substantially damaged by windswept flames, and other small fires
started on roofs.
</P>
<P>
   Several fire engines were assigned to look for flying debris on
the streets of Cabbagetown, an old part of town undergoing patch
urban renewal to emerge as something of a Bohemian quarter. Other
old mills have been renovated into businesses and residences; yards
are full of sculptures and tended gardens. The destroyed mill sat
in the center of a wheel, with streets extending like spokes.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors grabbed hoses to put out burning embers and rescue
dogs, since many people were not home during the middle of the
workday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty intense, a lot of people working together,''
said Lorrie Hulston, 31, as she sat against a wire fence. ``We
saved a lot of houses, I think, with garden hoses.''
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters arrived quickly, Hulston said. ``When they (the
homes) started collapsing, they asked us to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Embers burned through the roof and into a back closet of the
home of John Buck, 85. He was painting his home at the time because
he recently put it on the market and now said he has lost
everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen a lot of things in my life, but I never expected
this,'' he said, unsure if he had insurance. ``I was going to sell
my house and move back to Minnesota where I was born. I figured I'd
end up there. Now, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood and much of metro Atlanta were riveted by the
cinematic rescue of construction worker Ivers Sims, who was
stranded on top of a 220-foot crane above the fire for more than an
hour. Firefighter Matt Moseley was lowered from a helicopter rope
and strapped Sims into a harness. Both were then carried to safety
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an intense fire, and we were really just praying for
the guys' safety,'' said Byron Harris, 37, who was working at A &AMP; R
Welding, across from the mill.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be up there and something like that, not knowing what the
outcome's going to be, seeing buildings crumble around you _ you
can't help but be scared. I know I would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something you had to see to know how dramatic it was,
and then to see the rescue.''
</P>
<P>
   Sims, 49, was taken to Atlanta Medical Center, where his first
request was for a Coca-Cola, said the doctor who treated him,
Howard Zaleznak.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing very well, as well as can be expected for someone
who was rescued from 220 feet in the air,'' Zaleznak said. ``Our
concern for him was gas from the fire and the heat, but we've found
no injuries. He's very quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   Sims of Woodland, Ala., a Birmingham suburb, was discharged from
the hospital's emergency room but was expected to spend the night
in visitors' section.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell said he will give a ``hero's
reception'' for Moseley, his squad and the helicopter pilot and his
assistant at noon Wednesday in the City Hall Atrium.
</P>
<P>
   The Campbell administration and fire department have been at
odds for years over issues like pay and staffing.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters union president David Rhodes said firefighters'
efforts were hindered Monday because each of 10 ladder-trucks was a
man short. Rhodes said he will plead with the city's Public Safety
Committee today to support the department.
</P>
<P>
   The department was also hindered by the dryness of the Atlanta
climate lately and powerful winds, Perhaps contributing to
tinderbox conditions, a cold front passed through the area,
dropping the relative humidity even lower, to 29 percent around the
time of the fire, said Jim Blair of the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been dry for almost two weeks,'' Blair said. ``It
doesn't take long for things to dry out in this Georgia sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Croft, Gita Smith and Lyda Longa write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
