<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-DUQUETTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUQUETTE WITH VAUGHN-LESS SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hey, he told you so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our communication with our fans during the offseason was that
we would have pitching depth, good defense, and still an exciting
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Duquette resisted the urge to say, ``Mo Who?'' as he made
that assessment Monday at Fenway Park on the eve of the Red Sox'
home opener. In fact, the general manager waged a heroic campaign
against indulging in any approximation of gloating.
</P>
<P>
   But even his best deadpan could not hide the immense pleasure he
is taking in the fact that his ball club _ the one he decided over
the winter could live without Mo Vaughn or a facsimile of a power
replacement _ is making him look good after months of maligning.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox' 5-1 start was a virtual blueprint of the GM's grand
design. Granted, it was against the Kansas City Royals and Tampa
Bay Devil Rays, the American League's soft underbelly. But it came
on the road, which can be treacherous terrain regardless of the
opponent, and it showcased superb starting pitching, an almost
flawless bullpen, trusty defense, and enough hitting to get by. Oh
yes, and a substantial portion of that hitting was provided by Jose
Offerman, the anti-Mo whom Duquette procured as his major winter
offensive acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   It all added up to five straight wins out of the gate, the first
such achievement by Boston since the 1946 pennant winner. And when
they finally faltered Sunday in Tampa, the Sox gave the Devil Rays
apoplexy by erasing a four-run deficit before falling, 5-4, as they
just missed duplicating the 1918 world champions' 6-0 start. ``So
we're in good company,'' said Duquette.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, on the eve of the home opener, Boston's record was
almost as spotless as Fenway. The nagging question: Like the
ballpark's appearance, is the team's performance an aberration?
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Duquette thinks not. And he offers 12 good
reasons to support his confidence _ starting pitchers Pedro
Martinez, Bret Saberhagen, Tim Wakefield, Mark Portugal, and Pat
Rapp, plus a bullpen anchored by Tom Gordon. Rapp was the only
starter who failed to win, and despite his troubles Sunday, the
game wasn't a lost cause because of the work of retread Rheal
Cormier and newcomers Kip Gross and Mark Guthrie. They kept the
Rays at bay until the Sox drew even, 4-4. And even though Derek
Lowe gave up the decisive homer to Danny Clyburn in the eighth, it
was only the second run surrendered by the bullpen, a large reason
the staff ERA is 1.40.
</P>
<P>
   ``With pitching like that,'' said Duquette, ``we're going to be
in a lot of games. And we're certainly going to be in a lot more
games than we were last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, of course, the Sox made the playoffs, which no one
expected of that crew and fewer do of this one. Still, while the
home team always is embraced by the local populace before its
Fenway debut, there should be a touch of euphoria in Tuesday's
forecast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning always helps,'' said Duquette of the fan perception.
``There's more interest and excitement in the team when you win
ballgames. That's true any time.''
</P>
<P>
   It may prove irrelevant this time, considering that a mere 156
games remain. Duquette is well aware that the season is barely a
heartbeat old, but he's also a student of history, and he knows
that a fast getaway beats the alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1984, Detroit got off to a good start (35-5) and ran away
with it,'' he said. ``In 1995, we had a good start (14-5) and made
the playoffs. In '96, we dug such a hole for ourselves (3-15) that
even though we had the best record in the second half, we came up a
couple of games shy.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 Sox are making Duquette's vision reality. For a week,
anyway. It remains to be seen whether it proves a mirage once the
weather and the competition heat up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
