u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-NUKELAB-ART-NYT     04-12 0380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-NUKELAB-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR DENOUNCES `HEMORRHAGING' OF NUCLEAR-BOMB SECRETS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ALAMOS, N.M. _ Directors of the nation's nuclear bomb
laboratories should put a ``tourniquet'' on visits by foreign
scientists, the leader of a Senate delegation said Monday after two
days of security briefings at the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Denouncing the ``hemorrhaging'' of bomb secrets to foreigners,
Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., stood in front of the 10-foot-high
metal fence at the laboratory's main gate and said, ``I would put a
tourniquet on it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very concerned about the faxes, e-mails, people walking
through,'' said Shelby, chairman of the Select Committee on
Intelligence. ``It is a question of a very few people, who have _
in the past and I am sure will in the future _ tried to damage our
national security.''
</P>
<P>
   In the laboratory, the classified computers remained shut down
for the second week in a row as scientists attended security
seminars and laboratory directors worked on improving systems to
protect the nation's bomb secrets from outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We submitted plans on Friday to Secretary Richardson on what
we would do to improve security, to make it extremely difficult to
transfer information out of classified files,'' Sylvia Brucchi, the
laboratory spokeswoman, said Monday. She was referring to concerns
of Energy Secretary Bill Richardson that file diskettes containing
classified information could be inserted into nonclassified
computers to be sent by e-mail to outside computers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite senators' concerns about foreigners, it was accusations
about spying by an American citizen employed here that caused
concerns about laboratory security to mushroom last month. In early
March, the FBI identified that citizen, Wen Ho Lee, a Taiwan-born
computer scientist, as the prime suspect in the transfer of
advanced nuclear bomb plans to the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   On March 8, Lee was fired from his job at the laboratory for
security violations. But he has not been arrested or charged with
any crime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 2120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990412.0414 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5469 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-CONGRESS-NYT &LR;      04-12 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENERGY OFFICIAL SAYS ADMINISTRATION DISMISSED NUCLEAR SECRETS
THEFT
</HEADLINE>
   (ac) 
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A senior intelligence official at the Energy
Department said Monday that his superiors and other Clinton
administration officials repeatedly downplayed or dismissed
evidence that China had stolen nuclear weapons secrets from a
government weapons laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Notra Trulock, who was in charge of analyzing the
case for the Energy Department, told the Senate Armed Services
Committee that in some cases, senior officials made it clear to him
that information about the suspected espionage would harm the
credibility of the laboratories, hurt their efforts to work with
scientists in China and Russia, or might be used by Congress to
attack President Clinton's China policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must tell you,'' Trulock said in his first public statement
on the case, ``that our warnings were ignored, they were minimized
and occasionally even ridiculed, especially by laboratory
officials.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's session was the first public congressional hearing on
the mounting furor over the administration's handling of evidence
of China's theft of nuclear secrets. Several Democratic senators
objected, arguing that the matter was so sensitive that it should
be dealt with only in classified hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Trulock testified that in 1997, two senior Energy Department
officials tried to prevent him from briefing the new energy
secretary, Frederico Pena, about the investigation into China's
suspected theft of the design of America's most advanced nuclear
warhead, the W-88, from Los Alamos National Laboratory. Trulock
said that Victor Reis, the assistant energy secretary for defense
programs, and Kenneth Baker, the acting director of
non-proliferation at the department, prevented him from briefing
Pena for several months in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I was given on more than one occasion was that this
information could potentially hurt the credibility of the
laboratories,'' Trulock said. He added that Reis told him that the
information might also harm the laboratories' efforts to win
congressional financing for new initiatives for maintaining nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Trulock also said that in July 1998, Elizabeth A. Moler, then
acting energy secretary, blocked him from briefing Rep. Porter
Goss, R-Fla., chairman of the House Select Committee on
Intelligence, who had requested a briefing on the Los Alamos
espionage case. He said that Ms. Moler told him that the Congress
would only use the matter as ammunition with which to attack
Clinton's China policies.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Moler, now a Washington lawyer in private practice,
testified Monday that she could not recall ever being told about
Goss' request for the July 1998 briefing on the espionage case. But
she adamantly denied that she actually told Trulock not to brief
Goss.
</P>
<P>
   She could not explain, however, how a memo from Trulock
concerning the briefing request, which was made public Monday, was
later found in her safe in her office.
</P>
<P>
   The July 21, 1998, memo, from Trulock to Ms. Moler and Ernest
Moniz, the energy undersecretary, states that Trulock had received
a request from the House intelligence committee staff the day
before requesting the briefing for Goss, along with Rep. Norman
Dicks, D-Wash., the ranking minority member, and members of their
staffs.
</P>
<P>
   The memorandum was retrieved from her safe when she left the
department and returned to the Energy Department's intelligence
office without any notations on whether she concurred with his
request to brief the committee or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deal with large volumes of information,'' Ms. Moler said.
``But I don't have any rational explanation for this incident.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Moler stressed, however, that she had taken the issue of
possible Chinese espionage seriously, and that she and Pena worked
hard to improve counter-intelligence and security programs at the
labs.
</P>
<P>
   With lawmakers focusing on the conflicting testimony of Trulock
and Ms. Moler, she attacked Trulock's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have respect for Mr. Trulock as an analyst,'' Ms. Moler
said. ``I don't believe he is always careful with the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Trulock also told the committee that Gary Samore, the National
Security Council's senior director for non-proliferation, told him
in 1997 that the Los Alamos spy case would not interfere with the
Clinton administration's policy of using the laboratories as ``a
tool to further its engagement policy with China.''
</P>
<P>
   Samore's comments came when Trulock was briefing him on the spy
case, in August 1997, at a time when Samore was also helping the
White House prepare for an October 1997 summit with China.
</P>
<P>
   Samore said in an earlier interview that if he did make such a
comment in the midst of a briefing on the spy case, he was joking.
</P>
<P>
   Trulock did add, however, that Samore did ``encourage us to go
forward with our counter-intelligence efforts in order to protect
sensitive information at the laboratories.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
