<HEADLINE>
RAMBIS THRIVES ON COMPETING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Kurt Rambis was wearing those familiar
thick, black-framed specs and had to sit down to catch his breath
after a physically demanding workout. He looked like a guy ready
for the big game.
</P>
<P>
   Ready to PLAY in the big game. He sounded like it too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love playing against (top) competition. I would rather play
82 games against the best teams in the league than have to do
anything else. . . . I like competition, I like good players, I
like great teams. To me, that's what makes basketball fun,'' the
Lakers' coach said Monday, on the eve of his team's first showdown
with the Portland Trail Blazers, owners of the NBA's best record.
</P>
<P>
   In this most unusual of seasons, the schedule has kept apart the
Pacific Division's top two teams until today, game 40 of the
Lakers' 50-game slate. They'll make up for it by playing four times
in the next three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps still pumped from practicing with his players, Rambis
almost had to be reminded he wasn't playing in this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was a player, I'd love to be in this game,'' he said.
``I'm a coach and I'd love to watch a game like this, I'd love to
coach a game like this.''
</P>
<P>
   At 25-14, the Lakers are 4{ games behind the Trail Blazers
(28-8), and there's time to wrest away the division title that L.A.
was favored to win.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say, the Lakers have eagerly anticipated this
meeting, though they will be shorthanded tonight _ Glen Rice is ill
and did not make the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody's a little curious to see what kind of game
it's gonna be,'' Kobe Bryant said. ``We know they're gonna come out
with everything they've got, play with a lot of emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   The sixth seed in the playoffs a year ago, the always-talented
but formerly underachieving Blazers have blossomed into one of the
top teams in the league and hold the No. 1 seeding in the Western
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   It's partially a product of growth, partially an infusion of
talent that has made Portland deep enough to play two unique
starting units. Five players average double figures in scoring, and
seven average at least 8.5 points and 20 minutes per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep team. Deep team,'' Bryant said. ``They can come at you in
waves. It doesn't stop. Nonstop energy.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Hold the Rice: Without Rice (sore throat, fever), the Lakers
aren't sure what lineup they'll throw at Portland.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Ruben Patterson got the start Sunday but played only 11
minutes. Rambis might opt for Rick Fox or Robert Horry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still weighing our options,'' he said. ``We not only
have to worry about starters, we have to worry about (how it
affects) our bench punch as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Travis Knight, on the injured list with Achilles tendinitis,
also caught a fever and sore throat and did not practice Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
