<SLUG> BC-FIREMAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hero firefighter, 30, 'felt completely at home' dangling in air
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Sharon Hembree found at work about the raging
inferno at the Fulton Bag and Cotton Mill lofts Monday afternoon,
she knew her only child , an Atlanta firefighter, was right in the
thick of it. But little did she know then, that her son Matt
Moseley, was the hero who dangled under a helicopter hundreds of
feet in the air to save another man's life.
</P>
<P>
   Hembree found when she walked into the apartment she shares with
her mother Lottie Hembree.
</P>
<P>
   The older woman, frightened but calm, pointed to the TV:
''That's your son up there,' `` Lottie Hembree told her daughter.
``I was overwhelmed. My mom just knew it was him even though she
couldn't see from what they showed on TV. She just had a feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Hembree ran to another room and flipped on the set. She also had
a feeling that the man in the yellow firefighter's suit, sailing
over hundreds of cheering people who lined up along DeKalb Avenue
and other streets, was her 30-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   There was no question among Moseley's workmates from Squad Four
on Ellis Street downtown who would take the ride to save Ivers'
life, said Atlanta Capt. Tom Doyle.
</P>
<P>
   ''We just told Matt you're getting in the harness and you're
going up,'' Doyle said. ``He never questioned me, he was ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Moseley came to Atlanta in 1996 from the Fayette County (Ga.)
Fire Department, where he was firefighter of the year in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Moseley was anxious to get in the air. ''I felt completely at
home when I was in the air, because I knew I was on my way to
saving this man,'' Moseley said. ''I wasn't doing anything on the
ground. I had trained long and hard for this moment. I knew I was
going to get him.''
</P>
<P>
   Moseley's confidence comes from the hours of training he and the
other firefighters in Squad Four on Ellis Street downtown must go
through. The courses, called High Altitude Rope Rescue, are
required of all firefighters who work the Squad Four station
because of the skyscrapers downtown.
</P>
<P>
   When he finally reached Sims as he lay silent and motionless
across the steel crane, Moseley said he carefully swung towards the
man and cracked a joke: ``Your boss told to come up here so you
could knock off work early,'' Moseley said. ``He didn't say a word
to me. I told him not to touch me. I told him I would get him out
of there. I knew I would.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Hembree said Moseley called her as soon as he could,
shortly after taking a call from Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I answered the phone he said, 'Hi mom. What are you
doing? Turn on the TV,'' 'Hembree said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I told him, 'I'm already watching TV. What are you doing.
</P>
<P>
   '' By then, I knew he was all right. We were so proud of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyda Longa writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
