<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRANDED-MAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Construction worker stable in hospital
 &HT;    ATTENTION: Alabama editors.
 &HT;    By David Pendered and Rhonda Cook
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The world was burning beneath Ivers Sims Monday so he
found safety perched precariously 220 feet above the ground.
</P>
<P>
   About an hour later, an angel dressed as a firefighter swooped
down to rescue the 49-year-old Alabama man.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's resting, but he still has a lot of monitors hooked up to
him,'' the Rev. Benford Stellmacher said after praying with Sims in
his hospital room. ``God was with him, and angels of God were with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sims was resting in stable condition after being treated for
smoke inhalation and exposure to heat at Atlanta Medical Center
Monday evening. With him was his wife, Marilyn; his two sons and
daughter; a brother and his sister-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   ```Reverend, the Lord sure was with me,' '' Stellmacher said
Sims told him.
</P>
<P>
   Stellmacher, an associate minister of Antioch East Baptist
Church in Atlanta, said he reminded Sims to ``keep cool and calm
down. You didn't panic and that firefighter risked his life to come
save you.''
</P>
<P>
   Stellmacher, who hadn't met Sims before Monday, said if Sims is
not a Christian, ``he's a believer now.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49-year-old Woodland, Ala., man had been working
construction 20 years when he found himself holding on for dear
life above a Gay Construction Co. worksite Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   He had been working atop the crane _ as he had many times before
_ when a fire started in the 124-year-old mill that was being
converted into loft apartments in an area of east Atlanta known as
Cabbagetown.
</P>
<P>
   Sims crawled to the top of a concrete counterweight at the end
of the crane's horizontal arm, waiting on his stomach about 20 feet
from the black smoke and flames that appeared to climb up the
center of the structure. He seemed calm even as the crane swayed in
wind gusts over 30 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Until firefighter Matt Moseley swooped down from a rope and
quipped that Sims' boss had sent him up to fetch him so he could
knock off work early.
</P>
<P>
   After dangling hundreds of feet above the ground, Sims, a
humble, quiet man, was greeted with applause and cameras when he
was dropped on a grassy spot far from the burning mill.
</P>
<P>
   He was not seen again after he was put into an ambulance and
taken to Atlanta Medical Center (formerly Georgia Baptist
Hospital), where he was reported to be in good shape.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital officials described Sims as being in ``good spirits''
despite his experience and a little reluctant to talk to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Medical Center emergency room physician Dr. Howard
Zaleznak said Sims was ``very quiet'' after his ordeal. ``I can
imagine he's thinking about his experience and how lucky he is.''
</P>
<P>
   While Sims was discharged by doctors from Atlanta Medical
Center, he was expected to stay the night in a guest room there,
hospital officials said. His family was to stay with a relative
living in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   David Pendered and Rhonda Cook writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
