<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5475 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      04-12 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: Internet Companies Perceived as Threats to Old
World  Newspapers 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Mark Veverka &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Is Wall Street's voracious appetite for all things Internet
punishing newspaper stocks, and should dead-tree publishers respond
by spinning off pieces of their Web sites to the public?
</P>
<P>
   Just a couple of questions for newspaper executives to ponder as
the American Society of Newspaper Editors' annual convention gets
under way this week at San Francisco's Fairmont Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   It's with a twist of irony that the Old World newspaper
establishment is holding its yearly confab in a city delirious with
Internet fever. And if the editors take a quick glance at local
real estate classifieds in between noshes of jumbo shrimp, they'll
get a taste of the dramatic impact that dot-com mania is having on
the economies of San Francisco and Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Residential real estate values in the Bay Area have rocketed to
insane levels as digital barons plunk down cash for million-dollar
homes in what is now, arguably, the most expensive place to live in
the country. (Apologies to New Yorkers who beg to differ.)
</P>
<P>
   Flush with pre-offering stock options, warrants and shares, the
media executives of tomorrow find themselves richer on paper than
most of today's top newspaper publishing brass.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they aren't alone. Programmers, designers and other
techies are also grabbing their pieces of the pie. As are the
bankers, analysts and lawyers who encourage Internet companies to
go public _ often before earning their first dime _ and tend to
advise them to merge before holding their first shareholders
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what do frothy share valuations for Internet stocks have to
do with newspaper companies?
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, investors' infatuation with Net stocks is hurting
the share prices of traditional newspaper publishers, such as the
New York Times, the (Chicago) Tribune and Knight Ridder (publisher
of the San Jose Mercury News and the Contra Costa Times), says
financial analyst John Morton of Silver Spring, Md. (Chronicle
Publishing, by the way, is privately held.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite a relatively strong economy and flat newsprint costs,
the average stock price of the top publicly held newspaper
companies slipped 5.4 percent during the first two months of this
year, according to Morton, who tracks 16 companies in that group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wall Street is in the throes of ecstasy with Internet
companies, which are perceived as threats to newspapers,'' says
Morton, who was a journalist before making the transition to
financial analyst.
</P>
<P>
   (First-quarter financial results for newspaper companies have
been mixed. But yesterday, Dow Jones, Gannett and E.W. Scripps
reported robust profits that, on average, jumped 14.6 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   Concerns over whether the U.S economy could continue to hum in
1999 prompted many investors to hold back on buying newspaper
stocks during the first quarter of this year, Morton says.
</P>
<P>
   But the perception that Web-based media could eventually begin
to erode the advertising bases of newspaper publishers has been the
primary anchor weighing down their share prices, he says.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest threats to traditional newspaper revenues is
the meteoric success of Internet companies that compete for
classified advertising business, such as online auctioneer eBay and
job placement concerns, such as TMP Worldwide, owner of Monster.com
_ an Internet job-finding site.
</P>
<P>
   Classified advertising, which is mostly local, accounts for
roughly 50 percent of an average newspapers' revenues, Morton says.
So far, the online auction operations haven't established regional
sites, which would allow people to sell goods to each other in the
same city.
</P>
<P>
   But Internet analysts say that day is not far off. And once
regional sites are launched, newspapers will face serious threats
to their bread-and-butter classified ads.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, many major newspaper companies, such as Tribune and
Gannett, are diversified beyond just newspapers. They also own
broadcasting and other media operations. However, each of the
publishing companies tracked by Morton relies on newspaper proceeds
for the majority of its revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the newspaper companies Morton follows have established
formidable Internet properties built on the credibility and
news-gathering capabilities of their flagship papers.
</P>
<P>
   So, why don't newspaper companies unlock the value of their
Internet properties by spinning off minority stakes of their Web
operations to the public? Why fight the tape?
</P>
<P>
   Major broadcasting, cable and entertainment conglomerates, such
as Time Warner and CBS, are mulling strategies to sell stakes in
their Web sites. (Of course, Time Warner is also a magazine
publisher.) And now, another media giant, Walt Disney is reportedly
considering different strategies that would allow its Internet
investments to fetch sky-high Net valuations.
</P>
<P>
   Disney, whose stock has been lagging during the past 12 months,
controls various Web sites through its many divisions, including
ESPN and ABC. It also has a 43 percent stake in Infoseek, a public
company that operates a search engine.
</P>
<P>
   And according to at least one financial analyst, Laura Martin of
CS First Boston, entertainment giants like Disney have little
choice but to take their Web sites public. Martin says, despite the
legal and brand-control complications of breaking off pieces of
Disney, it is imperative because Disney sorely needs an
Internet-like stock valuation to compete with Web superstars such
as America Online, Yahoo and Amazon.com
</P>
<P>
   In order to attract top talent and remain competitive with new
media upstarts, entertainment conglomerates must pay employees in
stock options of Internet concerns. What's more, the parent
companies need the currency of inflated Internet shares in order to
afford acquisitions, Martin says. ``It's simply too expensive to
buy an Internet company using Disney stock or Time Warner stock,''
Martin says.
</P>
<P>
   The same may hold true for newspaper companies, if they hope to
grow and compete with new media juggernauts during the next
century. Instead of waiting for the Internet to fully develop,
newspaper publishers may need to act now and sell minority stakes
of their online divisions in order to keep up with the new kids on
the information block. ``But there is some danger in that,'' Morton
warns. If newspaper companies try to spin off their Web sites to
fetch higher stock valuations, they will probably hurt the shares
of the parent company, he says.
</P>
<P>
   He contends that newspaper bulls who believe in the future of
dead-tree publishing stocks are banking on the potential profits
generated by their fledgling online operations. If newspaper
stalwarts spin those operations off, Morton feels that shares of
the parent companies would go down because the Internet is
considered a key to their futures.
</P>
<P>
   More important, if and when the Internet bubble bursts, the
newspapers' Internet operations might eventually be valued less
than they are today as part of their larger, old-guard parent,
Morton says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because, who knows how long the (Internet frenzy) will last?''
Morton says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
