<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSIONAL LEADERS MEET WITH CLINTON ON KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Ill., Okla., S.C., Va.)  (lb) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On their first day back after a two-week recess,
congressional leaders told President Clinton on Monday night that
they are prepared to support his actions in Yugoslavia but that he
must make a better case, to them and to the public, particularly if
the United States decides it is necessary to send ground forces to
the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   At their meeting Monday evening at the White House, the
president reviewed the NATO air campaign and discussed an emergency
appropriation to finance the Kosovo mission. Monday night's
hourlong meeting served as a high-level briefing and gave the
president an idea of what to expect on Tuesday morning when he
meets with a bigger group of several dozen lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Several top administration officials have spent the past few
days anticipating growing support for ground troops among some
returning members of Congress, and debates on varying resolutions
regarding Kosovo are to take place in Congress later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional representatives and some senators have been
critical of the administration's lack of a plan for ending the
action in Yugoslavia, and of what they say is its refusal to
seriously evaluate the use of ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   During the congressional recess, a subtle policy shift has
occurred as the air campaign continued with lackluster results, in
part because of bad weather and the refugee crisis. Pentagon
officials have stopped ruling out completely the use of ground
forces, although they insist no plans are currently on the table.
</P>
<P>
   As late as Monday, Defense Secretary William Cohen said there
was no consensus among NATO allies for the use of ground troops. He
acknowledged that military planners had considered the option
months ago, and said plans could be quickly updated should the need
arise.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, Sen. Trent Lott, the Republican leader from
Mississippi, told reporters that he expected the president to have
more specific information Tuesday, such as how much the mission
will cost and how the military commanders are judging the success
rate of the bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Lott also said that after a two-week recess in which he talked
with voters in four states, he believes most Americans still do not
understand the mission against the Yugoslav president, Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would describe it in one word _ quizzical,'' he said of the
general reaction. ``Like, why? And what? They're not certain
exactly what our national security interests are.''
</P>
<P>
   The leaders met the president Monday night after he returned
from a quick day-trip to Louisiana, where he spoke to bomber crews
at Barksdale Air Force Base. He said the allied forces would
continue the air assault on Serbian troops until Milosevic
withdraws from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   He made no new policy, but used the trip as he did a similar
visit to the Norfolk Naval Station 10 days ago to thank the troops
involved in the Balkan conflict and to project an image of an
active commander-in-chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is America at its best,'' he told the troops. ``We seek
no territorial gain; we seek no political advantage. This is
America trying to get the world to live on human terms, so we can
have peace and freedom in Europe and our people will not be called
to fight a wider war for someone else's madness.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's 20-minute address was somber and the tarmac crowd was
subdued. But the president did win an ovation when he announced
that all servicemen and women in the Balkan conflict would be
exempt from income taxes while they are deployed. All will also
receive an automatic extension of the April 15 tax-filing deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The tax break, which is customary for extended service in combat
zones, applies to what the Pentagon calls the Kosovo area of
operations: Yugoslavia, Albania, the Adriatic Sea and the northern
Ionian Sea. The tax break will also apply to personnel serving in
Bosnia-Herzegovina, Macedonia and Croatia under earlier
deployments.
</P>
<P>
   All American members of the military serving in the region also
will receive $150 a month in hazardous-duty pay.
</P>
<P>
   As members of Congress returned from their spring break, it was
clear that Kosovo would quickly rise to the top of their agenda.
Some are urging the use of ground forces, some are urging caution,
and some are reflecting a growing anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message that we send in the next 48, 72 hours out of this
Congress,'' said Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., ``could have a
huge effect on the outcome of this conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   Many members of Congress are questioning how the military effort
should be paid for, others whether it should continue at all,
especially in the absence of a formal declaration of war. Senate
Democrats are promoting a resolution to express Senate support for
the use of ground troops if that becomes necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Dennis Hastert said that Congress intends to spend the
next few days gathering information from the Clinton administration
and the next few weeks holding hearings. He also said a senior
delegation from the House would fly to the Balkans at the end of
this week to investigate.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people have several questions about our efforts
in Kosovo,'' the speaker, R-Ill., said. ``Does continued American
involvement in the region further our national interests? Do we
have a long-term strategy? What are the costs of this action? What
are the costs of inaction? Do we have an exit strategy?''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., the majority whip, criticized the
president for making a ``mess'' of things by using only airstrikes
and ruling out the use of ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, he said, ``probably made a mistake and said, `We're
going to do half a war, we're just going to bomb, we're not going
to do ground troops.' I don't know that you can do it halfway. He's
got us into this mess, and I'm very troubled by it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Floyd Spence, chairman of the House Armed Services
Committee, said he found ``the absence of clearly defined
objectives'' for NATO's war plans ``deeply troubling.''
</P>
<P>
   ```Not losing' does not constitute a viable strategy,'' Spence,
R-S.C., said in a written statement. He said he was worried about
the ``uncertainty over the extent of the U.S. military commitment
in the months and years ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of a congressional delegation, Dodd spent most of the
two-week recess at NATO headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, and in
the Balkans, and visited a refugee camp in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Of Milosevic, Dodd said, ``I think it's extremely important, to
the extent possible, that he understand that there is a common
purpose and common resolve in this country, among Democrats and
Republicans, to prevail in this contest of wills.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other Democrats, Dodd supports using ground troops if the
military leaders deem it necessary. ``Everything should be left on
the table, including the option of using ground forces in Kosovo,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Sen. John Warner, chairman of the Senate Armed
Services Committee, urged a cautious approach. ``I want my
colleagues in the Senate, if they vote, to understand the
ramifications'' of authorizing Clinton to send ground troops to
fight in the Balkans, said Warner, R-Va., in an interview. He said
there was no way to assess the support in the Senate for deploying
soldiers until members grasped those risks and costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress needs, right now, to get a complete understanding of
all the options'' for ground forces, he said, adding that that
``the sizes, composition, risks and likelihood of success'' of some
of those options would be sobering to senators, given ``the
terrain, the weather, the tremendous hostility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
