<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-OPENRECORDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Governmental staff briefings should be public, House says
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ City councils, school boards and other
government bodies would no longer be allowed to conduct secret
staff briefings under a bill the Texas House approved Monday.
</P>
<P>
   House members passed the bill on second reading, and may amend
it when they weigh final passage today.
</P>
<P>
   Bill sponsor Rep. Steven Wolens, D-Dallas, said the Austin
school board's actions during the ongoing controversy over doctored
Texas Assessment of Academic Skills test results fueled his
determination to eliminate the staff briefings loophole. ``There
was some cheating on the TAAS scores, and they went into executive
session to discuss that _ and that kind of got my goat,'' Wolens
said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the state's open meetings law, a government body must
announce its meetings in advance and open them to the public. But
the law doesn't apply to staff briefings, even when a quorum _ the
minimum number of members required to conduct official business _
is present.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, board members gather information, rather than
debate, when government employees brief them on an issue. But
supporters of House Bill 156 say questions posed by board members
and the answers given by staff constitute deliberations that should
be conducted publicly. Opponents say the exemption allows officials
to discuss sensitive issues more candidly.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which still must be approved by the Senate, would
eliminate the exemption for staff briefings where a quorum is
present. It would preserve existing exemptions for discussions
about litigation, personnel matters, real estate and other
sensitive subjects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The information that these elected officials are receiving is
information paid for by the taxpayers,'' said Suzy Woodford of
Common Cause Texas, a government watchdog group. ``We think the
public should be able to get the same information so that the
public will know whether or not the decisions these government
officials are making are being made in the public interest or in a
vested interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar bills have failed in recent sessions, but several groups
and government entities that were against eliminating the exemption
in previous years dropped their opposition this time around.
Woodford said a drumbeat of media criticism may have spurred the
turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   William Cunningham, chancellor of the University of Texas Board
of Regents, said his board simply found that it could live without
the staff briefings exemption.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an easy vehicle for discussing some controversial
issues for the Board of Regents,'' Cunningham said. ``But we have
learned we can have candid discussions in the open and that the
public is well-served by open and frank discussions of
controversial matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott S. Greenberger writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
