<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 How to Keep Track Of Splits
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Arthur M. Louis &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I want to take advantage of the stock-split calendar
provided on the Yahoo Web site. Would you please explain the
footnote indicating ``optional'' next to a company's name? Does
that mean the stock probably will split but not definitely?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  This might be a good time to pay your annual visit to
the optometrist. Take a closer look at the footnote and you will
find that the word is ``optionable.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if you had read it correctly, I can see where you might
be puzzled. ``Optionable'' is Wall Street jargon meaning that it is
possible to buy options on the stock in question. If you are
speculating that a split will cause a sharp increase in the stock
price, Yahoo is hinting that you might want to buy call options,
rather than the stock itself, to get extra leverage.
</P>
<P>
   This new fad of buying stock in companies simply because they
plan to (or might conceivably) split their shares has me perplexed.
The purpose of a split is to keep the share price at a reasonably
low level, so it will be affordable by virtually all investors. It
produces no change whatever in the underlying asset. Earnings
aren't going to rise because a company suddenly has twice as many
shares outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, as advocates of this investment technique
observe, a stock split may signify that a company's management is
rousingly optimistic about future prospects. If management thought
the stock was too high and likely to decline, it wouldn't bother
splitting the stock.
</P>
<P>
   There is logic in that view _ provided the optimism isn't
overdone or faked. And it certainly is true that stocks often make
big, short-term leaps when stock splits are announced, or when the
split takes effect. If you can make money at it, more power to you.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone else interested in taking the plunge, the Yahoo split
calendar can be found on the Internet at  &LR; biz.yahoo.com/c &LR; 
 &LR; /s.html &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   BofA Stock
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the recent merger of Bank of America with NationsBank, I
exchanged my old BofA stock for new BofA stock. As part of the
transaction, I received $35 in cash in lieu of a fractional share.
How do I handle this on my tax return? Is this considered a cash
dividend, or is there a capital gain? If a capital gain, how do I
compute the amount? I had been buying BofA shares from time to time
during the past 20 years, so which share would represent the cost
basis in figuring my gain?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: According to the bank, the Internal Revenue Service said
the transaction must be treated as a capital gain. You received
$35, so part of that is a capital gain, while the rest represents
your purchase price and is not taxable.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how to figure your gain, as explained by a BofA
spokesman:
</P>
<P>
   The value of one share at the time of the merger was calculated
by the company at $56.3625. Divide $35 by $56.3625 and you get
0.62. So your cash payment represented 0.62 share.
</P>
<P>
   Your next step is to determine how much you paid for that 0.62
share. The IRS normally requires you to report share sales on a
first-in, first-out basis. So look up the price you paid for the
first share you bought.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know what that price is. But let's say you paid $3 per
share _ adjusted for subsequent splits. Then your cost basis would
be $3 times 0.62, or $1.86. Subtract that from the $35 you received
for the fractional share and you get $33.14 _ the amount to report
as a capital gain.
</P>
<P>
   Check your purchase price, substitute it in the example above,
and you will have the amount of your actual capital gain, which you
should report on Schedule D of federal Form 1040.
</P>
<P>
   Zero-Coupon Investing
</P>
<P>
   Q: How does one calculate the current yield and the yield to
maturity of a zero-coupon bond? I am considering an investment in
the American Century Target Maturities Trust, Series 2025, which
invests in zero-coupon U.S. Treasury securities maturing in 2025.
The price recently was quoted at $28.53 per $100 face value.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Since your question gives the American Century trust some
free publicity, I asked David Schroeder, the trust manager, to do
the hard work for you.
</P>
<P>
   He points out that there is no such thing as a current yield on
a zero-coupon bond, because you receive no interest payments
between the time you buy it and the time it matures. Your profit
from a zero is the difference between the price you receive when
the bond matures and the amount you paid originally.
</P>
<P>
   You can find yields to maturity of individual zero-coupon bonds
listed in some publications, such as Barron's. Or, in the case of a
trust, you can always call the manager.
</P>
<P>
   But if you are intent on doing it yourself, try this formula,
which you should be able to solve quickly enough with a scientific
calculator:
</P>
<P>
   First, divide the current price of the bond into its value at
maturity. In the example you give, you would divide 100 by 28.53,
which equals 3.505.
</P>
<P>
   Second, determine the number of years to maturity, double that
figure _ to simulate the twice-a-year interest payments you get
with ordinary Treasury bonds _ and divide it into 1. Since there
are 26 years remaining until 2025, the result, in your example,
would be 1/52, or 0.0192.
</P>
<P>
   Take the figure in step one _ 3.505, in your case _ and raise it
to a power of 0.0192, the figure you got in step two. (This is
where the scientific calculator becomes essential.) The answer is
1.0244.
</P>
<P>
   Now, multiply that result by 200 _ don't ask why, just do it _
which in this example gives you 204.88. Then subtract 200 (again,
don't ask), which in your example leaves 4.88. That figure _ 4.88
percent _ is the average annual yield to maturity.
</P>
<P>
   With other maturity dates and other prices, the annual yield may
differ.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to moneybag(at
sign)sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
