<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRAUD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Corporations Fight Internet `Cybersmear'
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Jon Swartz &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Corporations are declaring war in court to clear their names from
``cybersmear'' accusations.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest legal action, Liviakis Financial Communications of
Sacramento late yesterday filed a lawsuit in Marin Superior Court
to curb damaging statements on the Internet about the firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cybersmear'' is a practice in which individuals post malicious
messages about businesses in online forums, to manipulate the stock
or to hurt a company they have a grievance against. The
perpetrators often are disgruntled ex-workers or short sellers
attempting to manipulate stock.
</P>
<P>
   The Liviakis suit accuses 100 unnamed defendants _ who used such
online handles as ``ChiliBob,'' ``Kiddollars,'' ``Mr.Pink'' and
``Harvly'' _ of defamation and unfair business practices. In one
posting, John Liviakis, CEO of the $47 million public-relations
firm, is called a ``pedophile'' and ``swindler.'' In another, the
suit says, Liviakis is accused of ``unlawful short selling of
stock, unethical `dumping' of stock and market manipulation.''
</P>
<P>
   The 16-page complaint seeks unspecified compensatory and
punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   Lizbeth Hasse, a San Francisco attorney representing Liviakis,
said several of the company's clients _ including Data Race, a
communications company in San Antonio, Texas _ also have ``been
hurt by incredibly damaging stuff'' on Yahoo and the Silicon
Investor site in March and April.
</P>
<P>
   The messages erroneously said Data Race executives were selling
off stock in Data Race or had resigned, according to Hasse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know if there's one person behind it or 10,'' said
Hasse, who is preparing to subpoena Yahoo and Silicon Investor, a
financial chat site, for the e-mail addresses of the people who
posted statements on the message boards. ``This is nasty, prurient
material.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Skalla, Data Race chief financial officer, said the company
is ``frustrated and irritated'' by the messages.
</P>
<P>
   The Marin case highlights the awkward position of Yahoo and
other Web sites with bulletin boards. While the boards allow for
anonymous free speech, they can be a source of misleading
information that can affect company stock prices or harm
reputations. It also underscores how the Net has become a powerful
medium for anyone _ sometimes anonymously _ to spread misleading
information and gossip to millions of people.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's suit comes on the heels on the most elaborate cyber
hoax yet. Last week, an unidentified person manipulated the stock
of PairGain Technologies Ltd., a Southern Californian
communications gear maker, by creating a Web site that looked like
a Bloomberg news wire article saying the company was about to be
acquired. (Yesterday, Bloomberg LP, which denied it posted such a
story, filed a lawsuit against the unidentified people who posted
the bogus report.)
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission confirmed last week that
it is investigating the PairGain case.
</P>
<P>
   And, in many cases, companies are suing unnamed individuals to
put a lid on rumors. Lawyers said it is the only way to track down
and stop the e-mail users. In each case, Yahoo Finance _ a popular
chat area where consumers exchange tips and gossip _ was accused of
serving as a breeding ground for malicious rumors and speculation
about companies.
</P>
<P>
   For example:
</P>
<P>
   _On Friday, the Shoney Corp. restaurant chain sued ``John Does
1-3'' over inflammatory messages posted on Yahoo Finance.
Fraudulently signed with the names of Shoney's founder, CEO and
chairman, the messages claimed the Nashville company may file for
bankruptcy and close restaurants, according to the suit. Shoney's
has asked Davidson County Chancery Court in Tennessee to subpoena
Yahoo to turn over the names of the e-mail authors.
</P>
<P>
   _Wade Cook Financial Corp. last month filed a slander suit
against 10 as-yet unidentified users, who in January allegedly
claimed on Yahoo Finance that Wade Cook, who runs the Seattle
investment advice firm, had been arrested for accepting kickbacks
from companies he touted online.
</P>
<P>
   _ITEX, a Portland, Ore., online financial services company, is
suing two former employees for $1.5 million for purportedly
claiming on Yahoo that ITEX is in deep financial trouble and that
its management is ``corrupt.''
</P>
<P>
   ITEX obtained a subpoena forcing Yahoo to track down the
message-board users' e-mail addresses. After Yahoo complied, ITEX
gained a court order to force Internet service providers to divulge
the names of the individuals who posted the messages.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo does not monitor its approximately 1,000 bulletin boards
and chat rooms that post tens of thousands of messages daily and
``doesn't intend to,'' said Mike Riley, senior producer of Yahoo
Finance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're unmoderated public forums,'' Riley said. ``To take an
anonymous post and then trade on it isn't smart. Take these message
boards for what they are _ not a reputable source of information.
You don't know who the other person is or their motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo's only warning to consumers is a disclaimer that says all
of the information on its bulletin boards may not be correct.
Individuals found guilty of spreading false statements face
eviction from Yahoo's service, according to company rules.
</P>
<P>
   The Communications Decency Act protects Yahoo and other Web
sites from being sued for libel for false statements that appear on
their bulletin boards and chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  When such statements affect stock prices, the SEC is
responsible for policing them. But state and federal authorities
have been slow to investigate cybersmear cases, industry observers
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called the SEC earlier this month, and they treated it like
an isolated instance,'' said Hasse, the San Francisco attorney
representing Liviakis. ``I guess PairGain changed that.''
</P>
<P>
   The posting online of a bogus Bloomberg ``article,'' which
claimed PairGain was being acquired by Israeli-owned ECI Telecom
Ltd. for $1.35 billion, sent PairGain stock on a wild ride.
</P>
<P>
   Over just a few hours on Wednesday, its shares soared 32 percent
to $11.13, before slumping to $9.38 after the story was exposed as
a fake.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel violated and terribly irritated,'' said Charles
McBrayer, chief financial officer of PairGain. ``Maybe this has
finally awakened the feds about what goes on in chat rooms and on
the Net.''
</P>
<P>
   However, PairGain doesn't plan to sue the unknown cyber
perpetrators. ``We're plenty pissed off, but it would be difficult
to prove our stock was damaged,'' McBrayer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
