<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Compaq Stock Tumbles on Profit Warning
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By David Einstein &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Houston, you have a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Compaq Computer, the world leader in personal
computers, plummeted more than 20 percent yesterday as investors
reacted to the announcement that first-quarter profits will be half
of analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   No fewer than 10 brokerages downgraded Compaq's stock amid
grumbling that the Houston company had pulled a fast one by waiting
until after the close of trading on Friday to sound its earnings
warning _ even though the quarter ended more than a week earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq fell $6.81 to $24.13 yesterday on volume of nearly 100
million shares, making it the most heavily traded U.S. stock. The
shares have lost more than half of their value since late January,
when they hit a 52-week high of $49.25.
</P>
<P>
   Fearful that Compaq's misfortune could portend a slowdown for
the PC industry, investors also knocked down the stocks of other
top companies. Dell slid $1.74 to $41.81, despite predictions it
will meet quarterly expectations. Hewlett-Packard fell $1.38 to
$68.25, Gateway lost $2.88 to $69.88, and Intel, which makes the
chips for most PCs, fell $4.25 to $61.25.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts insisted that the PC business as a whole is
healthy and that Compaq's problems are mostly its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see a lot of problem with the other companies,'' said
Tim Ghriskey, a senior portfolio manager at Dreyfus.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq on Friday warned that its first-quarter revenues will be
about $9.4 billion _ 6 percent less than the $10 billion Wall
Street had expected. Earnings will be around 15 cents a share,
compared to 31 cents a share expected by Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts yesterday, Compaq chief
executive Eckhard Pfeiffer attributed the company's troubles to
weak demand in the PC industry, competitive pricing and the shift
toward lower-margin products.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq appears to have contributed to its own dilemma by slicing
PC prices in an effort to fend off Dell, HP and other companies
that have been gaining market share. Despite its price cuts, Compaq
has lost business to other companies that offer entry-level PCs for
less than $500.
</P>
<P>
   On other fronts, as well, Compaq has run into difficulty:
</P>
<P>
   _It has yet to reap the benefits of its $8.4 billion takeover of
Digital Equipment _ a deal that Compaq hoped would enable it to
compete head-to-head with IBM for big corporate accounts by
offering extensive service along with computing equipment.
</P>
<P>
   _It seems to have gotten itself into a no-win situation by
trying to emulate the direct-sales approach of Dell while also
continuing to sell through distributors and retailers. The strategy
may have confused customers while irking channel partners who don't
like the idea of working with a PC-maker that's also competing for
their business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compaq's hybrid model of part direct and part indirect is not
working well,'' said analyst Steven Milunovich of Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   _The company has yet to define its Internet strategy. Compaq
owns AltaVista, a major search engine, and recently purchased
Shopping.com, an e-commerce site, for $220 million. But industry
observers are unimpressed with Shopping.com's volatile history and
lack of profits, and so far Compaq has yet to leverage the Internet
components into its overall business strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Kimball Brown of Dataquest figures it could take Compaq
two more quarters to get things straightened out. ``It's really
hard to execute on all these things at once, and their message is
blurred because they're feeling their way,'' he said. ``But I think
this is the low point.''
</P>
<P>
   Compaq's poor quarter seems certain to cast a pall over the
company's annual sales and marketing conference, Innovate Forum
'99, which begins today in Houston. The event was to serve as an
opportunity for Pfeiffer to expound on Compaq's plans for
Web-enabled corporate computing.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he may find himself answering questions about how
earnings could drop 50 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
