u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PULITZER-PRIZES-ART-N     04-12 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PULITZER-PRIZES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHER TURNED PLAYWRIGHT IS AMONG THE WINNERS OF 22 PULITZER
PRIZES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An Atlanta kindergarten teacher, a biographer of
Charles Lindbergh and a writer who spent 20 years researching the
geologic history of North America were awarded Pulitzer Prizes on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher, Margaret Edson, was awarded the prize for drama,
for her intricately layered play, ``Wit,'' which chronicles a
college professor's death from cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The Pulitzer Board gave the award for biography to A. Scott
Berg's ``Lindbergh,'' a book that examined the aviator's complex
life, from his 1927 one-man flight from New York to Paris to his
Nazi sympathies, a transformation one onlooker at the time
described with the phrase ``from Jesus to Judas.''
</P>
<P>
   John McPhee, a staff writer at The New Yorker for 34 years and a
professor at Princeton University, won the general nonfiction award
for ``Annals of the Former World,'' a 696-page examination of the
geologic life of North America.
</P>
<P>
   Two prizes were awarded to The New York Times. Maureen Dowd, an
Op-Ed page columnist, won the award for commentary for a series of
columns on the national impact of President Clinton's affair with
Monica Lewinsky and his pursuit by the independent prosecutor. The
award for national reporting was given to the staff, with a special
mention for Jeff Gerth, for a series of articles that reported that
despite national security risks, two aerospace companies had
improperly shared expertise with China with the approval of the
U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   The prize for editorial writing was awarded to the editorial
board of The New York Daily News, for its campaign to rescue the
Apollo Theater in Harlem from financial mismanagement. It was the
newspaper's third Pulitzer in the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press won the prize in feature photography for
its collection of photographs of the major figures and events
stemming from Clinton's affair with Ms. Lewinsky. And for the first
time, a single news organization won both prizes for photography:
The AP was also awarded the prize for spot news photography for its
portfolio of images following the embassy bombings in Kenya and
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   The prize for investigative reporting went to the staff of The
Miami Herald for revealing pervasive voter fraud in a city mayoral
election. The results of the election were later overturned.
</P>
<P>
   The award for beat reporting was given to Chuck Philips and
Michael Hiltzik of The Los Angeles Times for their stories on
corruption in the entertainment industry, including articles about
a sham sponsored by the National Academy of Recording Arts and
Sciences and the resurgence of payola in the radio industry.
</P>
<P>
   The award for international reporting was given to the staff of
The Wall Street Journal for the newspaper's coverage of the Russian
financial crisis. The Hartford (Conn.) Courant staff was given the
award for breaking news reporting, for its coverage of a shooting
rampage in which a state lottery worker killed four supervisors and
then committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The staff of The Washington Post won the award for public
service, for a series that identified and analyzed patterns of
reckless gunplay by city police officers who were inadequately
trained or supervised.
</P>
<P>
   The prizes are administered by the Columbia University Graduate
School of Journalism.
</P>
<P>
   The Pulitzer administrator, Seymour Topping, said the singling
out of Gerth from among six reporters was rare for a staff award,
which is given to work produced by more than three reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we see an instance where a reporter has done very
outstanding work and carried a great deal of the burden of the
story, we adjust the citation to take note of that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For more than two decades, Gerth has been at the forefront of
the nation's investigative reporting. In 1992, he wrote the
original story on the financial dealings of the president and Mrs.
Clinton in the failed Arkansas real estate venture known as
Whitewater.
</P>
<P>
   The award for feature writing was given to Angelo Henderson of
The Wall Street Journal. Richard Read of The Oregonian in Portland,
Ore., was awarded the prize for explanatory reporting.
</P>
<P>
   In a year that was notable for long novels introduced with great
public-relations fanfare _ like Tom Wolfe's ``Man in Full'' _
Michael Cunningham's book ``The Hours,'' a slim novel that arrived
quietly, won the fiction award for its retelling of Virginia
Woolf's ``Mrs. Dalloway'' from three perspectives.
</P>
<P>
   The prize for history was awarded to ``Gotham: A History of New
York City to 1898'' by Edwin Burrows and Mike Wallace. Mark Strand
won the award for poetry, for his volume titled ``Blizzard of
One.''
</P>
<P>
   And a special posthumous citation was bestowed on Edward Kennedy
Ellington, the jazz legend better known as Duke.
</P>
<P>
   The citation states: ``Bestowed posthumously on Edward Kennedy
(Duke) Ellington, commemorating the centennial year of his birth,
in recognition of his musical genius, which evoked aesthetically
the principles of democracy through the medium of jazz and thus
made an indelible contribution to art and culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Edson, speaking from the office of the assistant principal
at Centennial Place Elementary School in Atlanta, said she was told
of the award as she was cleaning up after a class project about
insects. She said she would tell her kindergarten class about the
prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, as much as they get the idea of the Pulitzers, they
will be very pleased,'' she said, adding that she had no plans to
quit her job as a kindergarten teacher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
