<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5495 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-2NDTA     04-12 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON:   of anonymity. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although clouds have once again hampered strikes, NATO carried
out more air raids Monday night, striking refineries in the city of
Novi Sad in northeast Serbia and at Pancevo, not far from the
capital, Belgrade, according to the Yugolsav news agency. There
were also reports of explosions in Pristina, the provincial capital
of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Although Yugoslavia's air defenses have been mounting an
intensified challenge to aircraft, NATO has not lost a warplane
since an F-117 stealth fighter was shot down more than two weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Secretary of Defense William Cohen said Monday that
NATO aircraft had achieved ``tactical maneuverability'' over
Yugoslavia. ``This allows us to fly where we want and when we want
with acceptable risk,'' Cohen said, speaking at Barksdale Air Force
Base in Louisiana during a visit with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The weakening of Yugoslav air defenses is what has enabled Clark
to envision widening the strikes, the officials said. Clark
signaled his plans last week in an interview at NATO's military
headquarters in Mons, Belgium, saying Yugoslavia remained a potent
enemy with ``many, many targets'' still to be hit.
</P>
<P>
   The increase is clearly intended to have a psychological effect,
as well as a military one, signaling NATO's resolve to inflict
still more damage as efforts to find a diplomatic solution get
underway in Brussels and other capitals.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the warplanes, the United States and other NATO
powers are increasing other forces on the ground around Yugoslavia.
Pentagon officials said Monday that 4,800 Army soldiers are now
expected to accompany the two dozen Apache helicopter gunships
being sent to Albania.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon had initially said the Apaches would be accompanied
by only 2,000 troops. A senior Army official said the growing
number of troops reflected concerns about security in northern
Albania, close to the Yugoslav border, as well as the difficulty of
creating a base for the helicopters in Albania, which is Europe's
least developed country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going into Albania, the middle of nowhere, with no
infrastructure,'' the official said, adding that the exact number
of soldiers headed to Albania was still being worked out.
</P>
<P>
   The rapid growth in the force that will accompany the Apache
helicopters has also contributed to their slow deployment. A week
after NATO approved their use, officials have said it could take a
month before the full force is ready to strike inside Yugoslavia,
though Monday they said at least some helicopters could be ready
within the next seven to 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   Britain is also expected to announce that it plans to send
another 2,000 to 3,000 troops _ along with 20 tanks and 50 armored
personnel carriers _ to the NATO force it leads in Macedonia, a
NATO diplomat said. That force, originally the vanguard of a
planned peacekeeping force in Kosovo, now totals about 12,000
troops. Most of them are involved in providing aid to the thousands
of Albanians driven from their villages in Kosovo by the campaign
of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's armed forces have heavily fortified their positions
throughout Kosovo, according to NATO and Pentagon officials, and
this is complicating efforts to destroy tanks and other armored
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Aerial photographs have confirmed reports from refugees fleeing
Kosovo that Yugoslav forces are laying mines along Kosovo's
borders, digging trenches and building bunkers, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the United States and NATO continue to rule out the use
of ground forces against Yugoslavia, the fortification suggested
that the military and armed police forces in Kosovo have shifted
their tactics from a campaign to drive Kosovo Albanians from their
homes to a consolidation of their gains as NATO has pressed its air
and missile strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen various signs of hunkering down,'' a Defense
official said. ``There's been new mining. There are new bunkers.''
</P>
<P>
   Another American official with access to intelligence reports
said the Yugoslav Army had dug in along both major routes into the
country from Macedonia, apparently in preparation for an invasion
from NATO troops. The entrenchment of forces was reported on the
road from the Macedonian capital, Skopje, into Kosovo and on the
road from Macedonia to Nis, which is in Serbia proper.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav tactics have made it more difficult to strike. ``To
the extent they go underground,'' one official said of the evidence
that new bunkers are being constructed, ``it doesn't make it any
easier.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon also released aerial photographs showing armored
vehicles parked in the middle of two villages, Malisevo and
Volujak, a tactic that the Yugoslav Army appears to have been using
to shield its forces from attacks by NATO forces wary of causing
large numbers of civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
   ``So they are actually parking their vehicles in among the
villages in some places, which is bad because it is hard to find
them and you have to really watch for collateral damage,'' said
Maj. Gen. Charles F. Wald, the deputy director of strategic plans
and policy for the Joint Chiefs of Staff. ``But it's also good
because it means he is hunkered down and not moving around very
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Although NATO jets have begun to strike some ground forces,
including columns of armored vehicles, NATO's strategy is to
whittle away at the Yugoslav supply lines, which are easier to find
and hit, while letting the forces in the field wither. Wald said
Monday that the strikes had destroyed ``100 percent'' of the Serb's
ability to produce petrolium products for the military.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing has also hurt the Yugoslav air defenses, he said,
especially their ability to use and replace their surface-to-air
missiles. He said that despite the poor weather over the Balkans,
allied war planes were flying ``quite a few'' bombing missions and
using all the weapons in their arsenal. He said NATO had struck 24
targets over the previous two days, far less than the number
attacked when the skies over the Balkans were clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``The army and police have been reduced,'' he said. ``Their
coordinated air defense has been impacted, I would say, in a big
way. Some of their TV reception, from a military standpoint, from
their command and control standpoint, has been degraded. The losses
are continuing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
