<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5496 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS14-COX     04-12 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS PUTS OFF DEBATE ON KOSOVO
 &HT;    380&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional leaders, meeting with President
Clinton on Monday after their spring recess, postponed for at least
a week a debate over authorizing ground troops in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Leadership of both parties emerged from the 90-minute White
House session saying they were determined to give President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia no comfort by showing cracks in
support for the U.S. troops and the NATO action on behalf of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., who weeks
ago voted against the bombing campaign, offered hints that he is
far from persuaded on the U.S. role in the conflict. He said he
found the public ``quizzical'' as he traveled during the two-week
recess.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that they're not certain exactly what our national
security interests are,'' Lott said. He said Americans feel
sympathy for the suffering refugees, ``but I think they're still
not certain why we're there.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid calls from some members of both parties to authorize an
immediate insertion of ground troops into the region, Lott said he
expected Congress to take a formal vote before any forces were sent
to fight their way into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think we're at that point yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis J. Hastert, R-Ill., said he too expected to
have a formal debate, including one over whether the administration
was conforming to the War Powers Act _ but not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It think we need to see how this thing progresses,'' the
speaker said. His own party is divided among those who want to give
the president more authority to ``win'' the war, those who want no
expansion beyond the current bombing campaign, and those who want
to halt the fighting altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic leaders, by contrast, stood rock-solid behind the
president's handling of the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to give up,'' said Senate Minority Leader Tom
Daschle of South Dakota. ``We're going to hang in there until this
job is done.''
</P>
<P>
   Without mentioning the potential for ground troops, House
Minority Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri restated the president's
demands that Milosevic clear his troops out of Kosovo and allow the
refugees to return home under the protection of an international
force.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt asserted, ``That's what we want, and we're united in
sticking with that policy until we accomplish it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   For all of the solidarity, however, some of the leaders were
clearly picking their words carefully. House Majority Leader Dick
Armey, R-Texas, repeatedly praised the troops for their ``high
morale'' and for the ``size of their hearts'' in the effort to
assist Kosovo's refugees. He avoided saying anything in support of
the military operation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton continues his consultations with Congress on Tuesday,
when he is scheduled to meet with members of military and foreign
affairs committees.
</P>
<P>
   At Monday's White House session, the leaders were given a
briefing on the air war, but no cost estimate for the operation.
Unofficial estimates go as high as $40 million a day, which would
soon put the total near $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said he expected the administration to seek the funding
soon as part of an emergency supplemental bill that includes aid to
Central American victims of Hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   Less certain is how the Congress and the White House would find
budget savings to offset the added military costs. The choices, all
of them unpopular, include trimming other military spending, making
cuts in other programs, reducing Republican plans for tax cuts, or
slicing off some of the Social Security surplus that all parties
have vowed not to touch.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
