<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5510 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-MARKETPLACE-840&AMP;AD     04-12 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-MARKETPLACE-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: AT GM, SPECULATION ON CHAIRMAN'S SUCCESSOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Harry Pearce, the vice chairman of General Motors
Corp., has largely recovered from leukemia and is again a leading
candidate to succeed John F. Smith Jr., GM's chairman and chief
executive, who turned 61 last Tuesday, auto industry executives
said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith had been delegating considerable responsibility this year
to Pearce, 56, and to Richard Wagoner Jr., 46, who became GM's
president and chief operating officer in October. Wagoner is likely
to play a prominent but slightly more junior role in combination
with Pearce after Smith retires, said industry officials, all of
whom insisted on anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's increasing delegation of responsibility and often
visible weariness have prompted considerable speculation here that
he might retire, possibly within the next year. He has avoided
giving any clear, public indication of whether he would like to
stay until he turns 65. Steven Harris, GM's vice president for
worldwide communications, said Monday that Smith had ``no plans at
this point'' to retire.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing discussions of Smith's eventual successor come as GM
is profiting handsomely from a vigorous economy. But the world's
largest automaker is also losing market share at home, partly
because it failed to foresee the strength of demand for full-sized
pickup trucks and sport utility vehicles. The company's stock has
risen sharply since the end of a crippling, two-month strike last
summer but has generally trailed shares of GM's archrival, Ford
Motor Co.
</P>
<P>
   GM's shares rose $2.50, to $88.125 on Monday as the company
announced that next month it would spin off its 82.3 percent stake
in its auto-parts division, Delphi Automotive Systems Corp. The
United Automobile Workers union has opposed the spinoff but
declined to comment Monday afternoon on GM's action.
</P>
<P>
   J.T. Battenberg III, Delphi's chairman and chief executive, said
that Pearce ``has been an active participant'' in the spinoff.
</P>
<P>
   Pearce, a lawyer who rose through the general counsel's office
at GM, is again playing a central role in setting GM's strategy,
officials said. He is guiding policy on a wide range of issues,
including the spin-off of Delphi, while overseeing subsidiaries
like Hughes Electronics and tackling strategic problems that are
not part of the daily management of the auto business, which
Wagoner handles.
</P>
<P>
   Pearce was diagnosed early last summer with leukemia, but
continued doing considerable work from home so as to remain
involved with the company. He said in a brief telephone
conversation last week that he was feeling fine and on the path to
recovery; he has begun giving interviews again this month as the
company presents him as once more a physically fit executive able
to carry broad responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Steven J. Harris, GM's vice president for worldwide
communications, said Monday that that no decision had been made on
who would become GM's next chairman. He said that Pearce was
working at least four days a week now, characterizing that schedule
as ``full time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is back full time and fully engaged _ as far as what he'll
be doing longer term, that is for the board,'' he said. ``The board
routinely and regularly discusses succession issues, but there's
nothing new to report.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearce was treated at the Mayo Clinic. Dr. Esperanza
Papadopoulos, a bone-marrow specialist at Memorial Sloan-Kettering
Cancer Center in New York, said that many leukemia patients fully
recover from their illnesses these days, particularly those who
receive early treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Papadopoulos said that while she had not treated Pearce, it
was ``certainly possible'' that he was well on the way to a full
recovery, although it might take one to five years to be completely
certain, with the period depending on the type of leukemia and the
treatments used.
</P>
<P>
   After Pearce began bone-marrow treatments for his illness,
Smith's successor had appeared to be Wagoner, who had been GM's
executive vice president for North American automotive operations
before becoming GM's president and chief operating officer last
October. But Pearce is much better known among board members than
Wagoner and a decade older; Wagoner is the youngest member of GM's
board by three years.
</P>
<P>
   Wagoner is also relatively little known to the board. He became
a member last autumn and attended meetings infrequently in previous
years. By contrast, Pearce has been a favorite with many board
members since becoming general counsel in 1987, frequently
attending board meetings thereafter because of the numerous legal
issues the automaker faced, a former GM board member said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry did an outstanding job and he came to the attention of
the board,'' the former board member said. Pearce joined the board
in January 1996, when he became vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The most likely scenario is that Pearce will play the senior
role in some sort of partnership with Wagoner, with Pearce serving
as chairman and possibly as chief executive for a while too,
several auto-industry officials said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The result would be the latest in a series of two-person
leadership teams at big automakers, an approach that Ford and
DaimlerChrysler AG are using now and that GM itself tried from 1992
through 1995, when Smith was GM's chief executive but John Smale, a
powerful outside director, was GM's non-executive chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Bennis, a business professor at the University of
Southern California and the author of a recent book on dual leaders
at large corporations, said that automakers were particularly
suited to such leadership because of their sheer size. GM is the
world's largest company in terms of sales and Ford is the
second-largest.
</P>
<P>
   Always reluctant to be in the spotlight, Smith has cut back his
public appearances even more than usual this year. Wagoner gave
most of the company's semiannual presentation to Wall Street
analysts in January, with Smith making only a few, brief remarks.
Wagoner also gave the keynote speech at the New York International
Auto Show earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Conspicuously absent from auto-industry officials' discussions
of who might succeed Smith is Louis Hughes, GM's executive vice
president for new business strategies. The new title, which does
not include operational responsibilities, was created for Hughes in
October when his previous job, overseeing GM's international
automotive operations, was added to Wagoner's responsibilities.
Hughes was a finalist for the post of chairman of United Airlines
earlier this spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
