<HEADER>
A5511 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLALEGIS-SEX-INSURANC     04-12 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLALEGIS-SEX-INSURANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bills target women's medical rights
 &HT;    By Marcia Gelbart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Four years ago, when she was still in the
Florida House, Mandy Dawson-White helped create a law allowing
women insured by health maintenance organizations to select a
gynecologist as their primary care physician. Now the Fort
Lauderdale Democrat is at it again.
</P>
<P>
   Elected to the Senate in March, Dawson-White is pushing a bill
that would guarantee women direct access to a gynecologist
regardless of whom they choose as a primary doctor.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was one of two bills passed Monday by the Senate
Banking and Insurance Committee that seeks to broaden women's
medical rights.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jim Sebesta, R-St. Petersburg, cited his wife's own
protracted battle with breast cancer in urging the 12-member panel
_ which includes two women _ to support Dawson-White's bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a dickens of a time getting by the gatekeepers,'' he
said about referrals required by primary care physicians before a
woman can see a gynecologist.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Sens. Jim King, R-Jacksonville and Pat Thomas,
D-Tallahassee voted against the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Noting their dissension after the hearing, Dawson-White blamed
their stance on their gender. ``They would probably vote `yes' if
they had boobs and ovaries,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The second bill, sponsored by Sen. Patsy Kurth, D-Palm Bay,
would require health insurers to provide coverage for birth control
pills, which cost $20 to $30 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Both measures drew opposition from insurance companies, who said
the bills would drive up their costs and possibly force small
businesses to drop their health plans.
</P>
<P>
   Sebesta, one of four opponents of Kurth's bill, compared birth
control pills to sunglasses, saying, ``They're a matter of choice;
they're not drugs, they're not medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the vote, Kurth said Sebesta's remark ``showed an
insensitivity to what women go through.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurth said she introduced the bill after learning that 49
percent of insurance companies that pay for prescriptions exclude
oral contraceptives.
</P>
<P>
   Also voting against the bill: Sen. Tom Rossin, D-West Palm
Beach; Sen. Al Gutman, R-Miami; and Sen. Pat Thomas, D-Tallahassee.
Rossin later said he wanted more details about the impact on small
businesses, but would probably support the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The committee approved an amendment to exclude religious health
plan sponsors. The Florida Catholic Conference had said the bill
violates the beliefs of some of its employees.
</P>
<P>
   Both Kurth and Dawson-White anticipate opposition from the
well-heeled insurance industry when their bills reach the Senate
floor for a vote. Associated Industries of Florida, a business
lobbying group, and Blue Cross Blue Shield gave a combined $682,000
in campaign contributions to political candidates and the
Democratic and Republican state parties since January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Gelbart writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
