<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5515 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-CAMBODIA-$ADV1     04-12 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CAMBODIA-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMBODIA, NOW AT PEACE, HOPES FOR TOURISTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 18) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia _ From time to time these days, an
unfamiliar sight appears on the streets of this threadbare,
battle-weary city: a tour bus.
</P>
<P>
   There is really not that much to see here: small temples, small
marketplaces, reminders of the Khmer Rouge ``killing fields'' of
the 1970s. But Cambodia is a country of warmth and rural beauty, a
glimpse back into the Indochina of the past that so attracted
outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   And now, for the first time in nearly 30 years, it is a country
at peace. The Khmer Rouge insurgency is dead, and the last
upheavals of the civil war that followed it seem finally to have
sputtered out.
</P>
<P>
   It is a question now of convincing tourists and tour operators
abroad that Cambodia is no longer a danger spot _ although rural
banditry, urban crime and occasional flare-ups of political
violence will continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that tourism is going to increase,'' said
Jacques Guichandut, managing director of Diethelm Travel in
Cambodia. ``A lot of things have changed since 1997.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that travel to Cambodia through Diethelm had increased
by 48 percent over the past year as the country began to stabilize
after a coup and a violent, disputed election. Though no reliable
figures are available for travel to Siem Reap, the site of the
temples of Angkor, tour groups also began to return to Angkor Wat,
which had for a time been almost deserted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have just come back from promoting Cambodia in Europe,'' he
said. ``Still, we get the same questions: Is Cambodia safe or not?
So definitely, confidence is not back. They definitely ask about
mines. Before, tourists used to ask about the general political
situation. Today, the main concerns are about mines.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, land mines pose little danger to tourists. Though
millions of mines remain scattered through the country, they are in
remote and well-defined areas, unlikely to affect travelers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to worries about safety, tourism to Cambodia is
still hampered by poor infrastructure. Apart from Phnom Penh, the
capital, and Siem Reap, there are no first-class hotels. Roads are
poor, and air connections can be uncertain. Local food is often
excellent, but cleanliness is a concern.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Cambodia offers just one major tourist draw: the
magnificent 12th-century temple of Angkor Wat and the scores of
temple ruins that surround it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to strengthen infrastructure, we must diversify the
market more,'' said Cambodia's tourism minister, Veng Sereyvuth.
``It is not just Angkor Wat which is interesting. We need to
develop things like eco-tourism, the Tonle Sap. I am not saying we
can do it in 24 hours, but these things definitely need to be
upgraded.''
</P>
<P>
   He spoke enthusiastically about developing part of the vast
Tonle Sap lake (the largest freshwater lake in Southeast Asia) as a
wildlife sanctuary, of building a road network to link Cambodia
with its neighbors, Thailand and Vietnam, and even of installing
trolleys to take visitors among the temples at Angkor.
</P>
<P>
   But at the moment, as with so many of its endeavors, Cambodia
seems to be focused on immediate gain rather than long-term
planning. It has permitted a Thai airline, Bangkok Air, to begin
direct flights from Bangkok to Siem Reap that allow tourists to fly
in for a day, see the temples and fly out again. This quick
money-earner for the entrepreneurs who put it in place is leading
growing numbers of visitors to bypass Phnom Penh and the rest of
the country entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in the centuries-old battle between Thailand and
Cambodia for control of Angkor, some Cambodians see the direct
flights as a first step by the Thais to recolonize the temples _ in
this case as part of the package tours of the ``Amazing Thailand''
promotional campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some visitors may even think Angkor Wat is a part of
Thailand,'' said Jean-Pierre Kaspar, general manager of the Hotel
Sofitel Cambodiana in Phnom Penh. ``When they advertise the flights
in Thailand, they don't say much about Cambodia. Knowing how
aggressive the Thai tourism industry is, they may just take over
Angkor Wat.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bangkok Air has its way, one more direct route to Siem Reap
will begin this year, from the island resort of Phuket in southern
Thailand. For the Thais, who have tourists to spare, this will
relieve a problem with overbooking at the popular beach resort. For
the Cambodians, whose tourist industry hovers just above zero,
every dollar will count.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
