<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5517 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2T     04-12 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2TAKES-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH SUMMER, CAMP INCLUDED  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 18) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By EMILY LAURENCE BAKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's sad but true: a lot of teen-agers would rather stay at home
with their friends than go on vacation with their parents _ even if
offered a trip to Europe. Unless you're prepared to leave the kids
at home with grandparents or cousins or send them to summer camp, a
European venture could be marred by gloomy faces and a perpetual
chorus of ``Oh, do we have to go there?'' One solution is to take
the kids to Europe _ and then pack them off on a mini-holiday of
their own. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Britain has a number of vacation packages for children ages 6 to
19. The mix of English and European children who attend British
summer programs could give an American child a window on foreign
cultures. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   British camps are likely to be housed in dormitories of vacant
colleges or school campuses. Activities tend to be outdoors, which
seems a bit odd in a rainy climate. But all programs offer
foul-weather alternatives. Nighttime activities are more likely to
be discos and drama than singing around the campfire. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because the British school term doesn't finish until early July,
most summer programs begin at the end of July and run through the
last week of August. The earlier weeks of the summer will have more
European children, while British children predominate in August.
Programs are structured by the week, but it's possible to stay
longer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is no one organization that regulates all aspects of
children's summer programs. But the Adventure Activities Licensing
Authority is a government body that issues licenses for most
outdoor pursuits, including water sports, climbing, caving, and
trekking.
</P>
<P>
   It monitors only adventure activities, so it's wise to make sure
that a summer program is registered with the British Activity
Holiday Association, which monitors general safety, cleanliness and
staffing of association members. Except for Marlborough College,
all the programs listed below meet the standards of one of these
two groups. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The largest children's adventure vacation company in Britain is
PGL, which runs programs at 23 sites in England, Wales, Scotland
and France. Children are divided into four age groups: 6 to 9, 8 to
13, 12 to 15 and 14 to 19, with about 12 children to a group
leader, although younger groups are smaller. Staff members are
trained by PGL under the guidance of national sports associations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Children can choose from standard multi-activity camps or study
one sport, such as golf, motorized karts or horseback riding. Beam
House, near Bideford on the Devon coast, is popular for water
sports, said Louise Freyer, a PGL spokeswoman. Children who visit
Tregoyd House in Wales can hike in the Black Mountains, while those
who attend Court Farm in Herefordshire can canoe on the River Wye
and sleep in converted brick farm buildings.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Themed weeks are popular, Mrs. Freyer said. On the Indiana Jones
holiday, children unravel clues to solve the pyramid puzzle while
using canoes, rappelling equipment and a zip line, or aerial wire.
Other theme weeks include Robin Hood, Down on the Farm and Action
Man. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The company's Double Decker trip to France for ages 12 to 18
includes three days of canoeing in the Ardeche Gorge followed by
three days of water sports on a Mediterranean beach near
Languedoc. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At Club Correze, a tiny village on the Correze-Dordogne border,
children sleep in sandstone cottages. Activities include pony
trekking, climbing, sailing and windsurfing. In the southern French
Alps, 12- to 18-year-olds (in separate groups) camp in tents at
night and by day pursue vigorous sports, including white-water
rafting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A PGL French-language holiday combines intense French lessons
with sports. Overseas holidays range from $495 to $688 a week,
including overnight bus and ferry transport from London. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Programs run from July 3 to Sept. 4. United Kingdom programs
start at $350 for one week up to $575. At some centers, weekends
are available from $135, three nights from $180 and four nights
from $220. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A more intimate experience can be found at Mill on the Brue, a
family-run activity center in rural Somerset. For 18 years, Tony
and Tricia Rawlingson Plant have sponsored programs to ``develop
the whole person'' through outdoor activities.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the year, the Rawlingson Plants are host to corporate
and independent groups, but in summer their 20 acres of land are
turned over to a maximum of 44 children. Activities include grass
skiing and tobogganing, kayaking, hiking, rafting and video
making. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Children 8 to 14 are divided into groups of 10 to 12 with a
staff member for every five. Each week there is a day trip to a
nearby town such as Bath or Bristol. Older children are taken on an
overnight hiking trip. Children usually stay for a week but can
come for a few days or two weeks. Boys and girls sleep in separate
buildings in rooms with 8 to 10 children.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Bailey, spokeswoman for the camp, said that about 70
percent of the children are British and the remaining 30 percent
Europeans, with a few Americans. Programs run from July 18 through
Sept. 4 and cost $516 a week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Camp Beaumont, a 19-year-old program, is similar to an American
summer camp. There are four camps in England, one of them on the
Isle of Wight, for children 6 to 16. Activities include water
sports, archery, motorized karts and other standard camp fare. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For young children who have never been away from home, Jane
Dumble, a camp spokeswoman, recommends Kingswood, in Staffordshire.
The program features numerous activities and it's possible to go
for three or four days. The London Country College campus in Surrey
features a soccer camp with professional players as visiting
instructors. In Norfolk, at Runton Sands, children attend circus
school in a big top with circus performers as instructors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Camp Beaumont owns a chateau in southern Normandy, where it
operates a program for children 9 to 16. The weekly price is $558,
including bus fare from London. Beaumont also has eight day camps
in the London area. There are separate programs for children 3 to
15, which include crafts, fencing and drama.
</P>
<P>
   The Wimbledon location is popular with Americans, Miss Dumble
said, because of its pickups in Knightsbridge and Kensington _
popular tourist areas. Day programs run from about 8:30 a.m. to
5:30 p.m., including bus travel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Opening dates vary among campuses, but programs run from mid-
July to the end of August. Whitecliff Bay in the Isle of Wight
opens on June 19. Prices start at $478 a week for residential camps
and $253 for day camps. Some centers offer three- or four-day
packages that start at $215 and $285. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Experience UK (XUK) also runs day and half-day camps in north
London for children 3 to 14. Activities include singing, magic
shows, arts and crafts, drama, tennis and swimming. Children are
grouped by age with a staff-to-children ratio of 1 to 5. XUK also
has an overnight camp in a country mansion in Suffolk, about 120
miles northeast of London, for $415 a week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For a slightly more intellectual approach to summer, Marlborough
College Summer School in Wiltshire offers 200 courses for all ages
from July 18 to Aug. 7. Children 10 and over can go on their own
and stay for one to three weeks to study a single activity, like
golf or cooking, or pursue a variety in the general children's
programs. These are divided into five age groups: 3 to 6, 6 to 10,
10 to 12, 13 to 15 and 14 to 17.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many children attend with their parents; families can stay
together or in different dormitories so that they are ``independent
together,'' according to Marek Kwiatkowski, the director. Adults
might take a wine workshop or study history while the little ones
take Meddle With Magic or practice Art for Aliens.
</P>
<P>
   Dormitory accommodation for unaccompanied children is $184 a
week with a $96 weekend charge for those staying two weeks. Course
prices vary but most children's courses are about $135 a week. Two
courses fill the day. Round-trip bus transport is available from
London for $48. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PGL Travel, Alton Court, Penyard Lane, Ross-on-Wye,
Herefordshire HR9 5GL; telephone (44-1989) 764211, fax (44-1989)
766306. Book by early spring.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mill on the Brue, Trendle Farm, Bruton, Somerset BA10 0BA;
(44-1749) 812307, fax (44-1749) 812706. An $80 deposit per child
per week, is payable at time of booking. Programs fill up by June. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Camp Beaumont, Linton House, 164-180 Union Street, London SE1
0LH; (44-171) 922-1234, fax (44-171) 928-7733. Reserve in early
spring, but some places may be available later. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Experience UK, Poolside Manor, Lyndhurst Gardens, Finchley,
London N3 1TD; (44-181) 349-1945, fax (44-181) 349-9057. Discounts
are available if you book before May 31 for two weeks or more.
Programs begin to fill up in March, and most places are usually
booked by the end of May. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marlborough College Summer School, Marlborough, Wiltshire SN8
1PA; (44-1672) 892388 or 892389, fax (44-1672) 892476.
</P>
</TEXT>
