<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5520 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-AIRQUALITY-COX     04-12 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-AIRQUALITY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Voluntary plan to limit air pollution advances
 &HT;    By Osler McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Countering one, two, three punches, the Senate
knocked out efforts Monday to limit a proposal that would allow
industrial air polluters to agree on their own to restrict their
pollution.
</P>
<P>
   After beating back three amendments, the Senate by 21-9 gave
preliminary approval to voluntary air-pollution permit procedures
for plants in operation before the state adopted air-quality
standards in 1971. The so-called grandfathered plants have not been
subject to the Clean Air Act.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush's support for the measure was framed as a
test of his environmental policy by environmental lobbies opposed
to the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of Senate Bill 766, sponsored by state Sen. J.E.
``Buster'' Brown, R-Lake Jackson, contend the legislation allows
some of the state's worst air polluters to decide whether to clean
up their emissions. Opponents say it also continues a fee schedule
that lets the worst polluters pay state fees at the same rate as
lesser-polluting companies.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's bill would allow the plants that were not covered by the
1971 law voluntarily to seek an air-quality permit within two
years. The legislation would allow them to buy emissions-reducing
equipment that meets 10-year-old technology guidelines, instead of
the more recently designed equipment now required.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Royce West, D-Dallas, in one of the three failed
amendments, advocated requiring grandfathered plants that operate
near schools, nursing homes or parks to comply with strict
air-quality standards after two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't want to do it for the entire industry, . . . then
do it for our children,'' West urged.
</P>
<P>
   But senators rejected West's amendment, as well as one by state
Sen. Carlos Truan, D-Corpus Christi, and another by state Sen.
Rodney Ellis, D-Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Truan proposed eliminating a fee cap that allows polluters to be
assessed for no more than 4,000 tons of emissions spewed into the
air. ``This fee arrangement is giving the dirtiest companies in the
state incentive to pollute more,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis' amendment would have forced compliance by plants that did
not seek a permit during the two-year voluntary period. Without a
``hammer'' for Texas' air-quality enforcement, Ellis said, the
state could lose federal highway construction money because of smog
problems in Houston and Dallas-Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to make a bad bill better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown said his bill struck a balance that Ellis' amendment
would upset and Truan's proposal on a new fee structure should be
left to the Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission to
devise. He offered to help West work on separate legislation to
accomplish the fee goals.
</P>
<P>
   Under Brown's bill, plants in operation before 1971 would have
to meet the air-quality standards that were in place 10 years
before they voluntarily apply for a permit. The plants, which would
have until Sept. 1, 2001, to sign up for the voluntary program,
would not be required by legislation to enter the program; however,
Brown said, they could face even stricter regulations if they did
not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a shame that the Senate voted today for a policy
of letting the polluters decide whether or not to comply with our
clean air laws,'' said Peter Altman, Texas director of the
environmental group Sustainable Energy and Economic Development,
``especially at a time when more Texans than ever live in counties
that fail or are about to fail national air quality standards.''
</P>
<P>
   As many as 50 plants have pledged to apply for the permits.
About 1,000 of the state's 2,500 industrial plants are
grandfathered.
</P>
<P>
   Osler McCarthy writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
