<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5521 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-HNS &LR;      04-12 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Masters turns back on Love once more
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to Augusta National, Davis Love III can't get any
love.
</P>
<P>
   He's a Georgia native, loves the golf course, lives a couple
hours away by car and basically is the adopted son of the Masters.
Yet he may never win there.
</P>
<P>
   Love was one hooked tee shot from having a serious chance to win
at Augusta on Sunday. He smashed his drive at the par-5 13th into
the little tributary that trickles into Rae's Creek. There was only
a driplet or two of water in the gully that meanders down the left
side of the 13th, then crosses in front of the green. But it might
as well have been the mighty Mississippi when Love saw his ball
submerged in two inches of water.
</P>
<P>
   He still managed a par at that hole, but with his length, it was
a sure-fire birdie, if not an eagle, if he plays a good shot off
the tee.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the things that happen at Augusta, particularly to
Love. He lost the 1995 tournament to Ben Crenshaw by a stroke. That
was an emotional loss in which Love said that if he couldn't win,
he was glad it was Crenshaw who did.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Jose Maria Olazabal has won another green jacket in a
heartfelt story of returning from painful foot problems. Again,
Love said that if he couldn't win, he's glad it was Olazabal on the
victory platform.
</P>
<P>
   But enough is enough. Love is getting a little tired of being
the nice guy finishing second. It gets no easier with experience.
In fact, it probably is tougher.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't come to the Masters to finish second,'' Love said.
``You don't make as many birdies as I did (18 over four rounds) and
expect to finish second. But it's another step in the right
direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are four or five guys who can say, `I could have won
very easily.' And I'm one of them. It's disappointing. But I'll
build on it.''
</P>
<P>
   There's not that much left to build on for Love, who now has
four consecutive top-10 finishes at Augusta. He was seventh in '96
and '97.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy for Jose Maria to come back from what he came
back from to win the Masters,'' Love said. ``I know he loves this
place. And after the start he had, to go all the way down to
4-under par and come back, I'm very happy for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, anything I would say is sour grapes.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is not Love's style. He'll just keep plugging away like he
has the past few years, rolling up one of the biggest bankrolls in
PGA Tour history. He's currently fifth on the all-time money list.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he ever wins a Masters or not, though, Love is
guaranteed a spot in Augusta lore after what he did Sunday. Making
his 12-yard chip shot from the left side of the 16th green was
probably the single most memorable shot from the '99 Masters. Love
bumped the ball out of medium-length grass onto the green about 15
feet beyond the hole. It came to rest on the incline that separates
the two plateaus of the green.
</P>
<P>
   Then it began it's slow, tantalizing drift back toward the lower
tier. As Greg Norman said: ``I saw that shot on replay and the ball
was moving so slow, you could count the dimples.''
</P>
<P>
   The ball made just enough revolutions to drop into the side door
of the cup for a most improbable birdie.
</P>
<P>
   But, as always with Love, it wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Love will head to Hilton Head, S.C., for the MCI
Classic at the Harbour Town Golf Links. He is returning to the
scene of his last victory, having won last year _ the week after
the Masters. He has 13 wins in the last dozen years and has won at
least once every year since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, he's come up empty, thanks again to the lack
of love from Augusta National.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
