   (NYT9) BOSTON -- April 12, 1999 -- SCI-ASTHMA-BOS, 04-12 -- At
the Mattahunt Elementary School, Klara Perez uses an inhaler to
administer her asthma medication. She is just one of the many
students who line up before lunch every day to use inhalers or
nebulizer machines in the nurse's office. (John Blanding/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) RINAS AIR FIELD, Albania -- April 12, 1999 --
KOSOVO-AIRBASE-2-COX, 04-12 -- Air Force security stands guard
Sunday as troops unload a C-17, one of the scores of transport
planes that have landed here in the last week with food and
supplies for the ethnic Albanian refugees. The effort is part of
the humanitarian mission here called Task Force Shining Hope.
(Marcia Kunstel/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) RINAS AIR FIELD, Albania -- April 12, 1999 --
KOSOVO-AIRBASE-1-COX, 04-12 -- Members of the Air Force First
Combat Communications Squadron from Ramstein, Germany, assemble a
20-foot satellite antenna Sunday that will give the U.S. military
here everything from internet to secure international telephone
connections. The job was made more challenging by ankle-deep mud
left after three days of off-and-on rainstorms. (Marcia Kunstel/Cox
News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- April 12, 1999 -- SCI-DEFIBRILLATORS, 4-12 --
Portable defibrillators - which weigh about four to seven pounds
and are computerized to be easy enough for a child to learn to
operate - are making a major difference in cardiac survival rates.
More and more businesses and organizations are recognizing their
value. (Naum Kazhdan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- April 12, 1999 -- SCI-MOLECULES-CANCER, 4-12
-- Dr. Carlos Cordon-Cardo, director of molecular pathology at
Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in New York. Cordon-Cardo is
a leader among researchers hoping to use molecular pathology to
transform the treatment of many cancers, increasing patients'
chances of cure in some cases and avoiding unnecessary treatment in
others. (Don Hogan Charles/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW HAVEN, Conn. -- April 12, 1999 -- SCI-PHANTOM-SMELL,
4-12 -- Dr. Linda Bartoshuk, a psychologist specializing in taste,
recently set up a video camera in her Yale University laboratory,
where she videotapes tongues in tracking down phantom tastes like
burning mouth syndrome. Dr. Bartoshuk and her colleagues will
present some of their work at the annual meeting of the Association
for Chemoreception Sciences in Sarasota, Fla., this week. (George
Ruhe/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WAYNE, N.J. -- April 12, 1999 -- SCI-VITAL-SIGNS, 4-12 --
Members of the Can Do Health Club in Wayne, aloft in cyberspace.
Health clubs are installing consoles onto step machines and
stationary bikes to allow users to surf the Internet, watch their
own cable televisions, listen to CDs and call up past workout
records. (Dith Pran/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- April 12, 1999 -- SCI-FITNESS-FLOW, 4-12 --
Exercising in a group, like the Van Cortlandt runners in the Bronx,
can create ``flow.'' This intensely pleasurable, almost mystical
experience may be the key to helping those who loathe physical
activity learn to enjoy it, says a group of researchers in North
America and Australia. (Chris Maynard/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- April 12, 1999 -- SCI-EPISODIC-HYPERTENSION,
4-12 -- Dr. Samuel J. Mann of New York Hospital/Cornell Medical
Center has seen a string of patients who have experienced sudden
episodes of severe hypertension. He has linked the condition to
previously suppressed childhood traumas and is prescribing
antidepressants. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
