<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-Astros-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros not starting to worry
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _ In 1986, the Astros began the season 3-3. They
finished with 96 victories, went to the playoffs and came up two
victories shy of a trip to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, they broke out of the gate with a 6-0 start _ and
finished 10 games below .500.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, the Astros opened with victories in five of their first
six games _ and finished 82-80, 12{ games out of first place.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Astros started 3-3 and stayed around .500 the
first three weeks of the season. They occupied sole possession of
first place the final 150 days of the regular season, won a
franchise-record 102 games and earned a second straight National
League Central Division championship.
</P>
<P>
   After starting with a less-than-impressive 3-3 homestand in
1999, the Astros open the road portion of their schedule against
the San Francisco Giants tonight at 3Com Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no sense in pressing or even worrying,'' center
fielder Carl Everett said.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it's not where you stand in April that matters. Check
back Oct. 3.
</P>
<P>
   If the season were based on one week, the Astros, Atlanta Braves
and Texas Rangers, division winners a year ago, wouldn't be among
the eight playoff qualifiers. Struggling, yes. Out of the race,
hardly.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, the Astros could draw few, if any, conclusions
to losing two of three games to Chicago and barely slipping past
projected division doormat Milwaukee with two wins in three games.
</P>
<P>
   Their motto: ``Six of 162.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to win every game. That's the idea,'' first
baseman Jeff Bagwell said. ``You're not going to play well all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell pointed out that the New York Yankees began last season
0-3 and finished with a major-league record 125 victories (playoffs
included) and their 24th World Series championship.
</P>
<P>
   By the time of the Yankees' victory parade down the streets of
Manhattan in late October, few remembered where the Bronx Bombers
stood in the AL East standings on April 4 _ in last place.
</P>
<P>
   The source of the Astros' early-season woes can be attributed to
one eye-catching statistic _ 2.8 runs per game. They are batting
.246. Before they posted season highs of five runs and 13 hits on
Sunday, the average was .213 _ last in the NL.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't hitting. That's not us,'' said Everett, who leads
the team with a .364 average. ``We thrive off hitting. Teams come
in worrying how many hits the Astros are going to get today. We
hadn't done that the first five games.''
</P>
<P>
   The top of the Astros' order is where the hitting sag is most
obvious. Three of the top hitters _ Craig Biggio, Jeff Bagwell and
Ken Caminiti _ are batting a composite .175 (10-for-57) with one
home run and three RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we hit, I'll take it (a 3-3 start),'' Bagwell said.
``I think we hit as bad as we could hit in the first six games.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggio, who started the season 0-for-13 before hitting a home
run Saturday, said it's easy to assume something is wrong when the
bats are slow to heat up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a crazy homestand,'' said Biggio, who has hit .300 or
better in four of the past five seasons. ``It's not that we're flat
going out there. It might appear like we're not focused, but we
are. When you're not swinging the bats well it looks that way.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not unprecedented for the Astros to get off to a slow
start. Since 1980, the Astros have started at .500 or under 13
times. Eight of those teams ended with a winning record.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, the Astros opened 0-6. They rebounded to finish 85-77,
six games out of the lead in third place.
</P>
<P>
   During the club's NL West-winning 1986 season, the Astros were
14-6 after the first month despite two of their best hitters _
Glenn Davis (.227) and Jose Cruz (.121) _ struggling at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   After winning consecutive division titles the past two seasons,
lofty expectations have been placed on the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expectations are high in this clubhouse in the way we feel
about ourselves,'' Biggio said. ``I think they are also high in the
community and around the league. When you win the division the last
two years straight, everybody is shooting for you and everybody
wants to kick your butt. Everybody gets fired up to play us.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the price of winning. And while the wins have been slow in
coming, the Astros aren't ready to concede anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fine,'' closer Billy Wagner said. ``It's not a sprint
but a marathon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
