<HEADER>
A5534 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HYDRON-TAKEOVER-COX     04-12 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HYDRON-TAKEOVER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ousted Hydron CEO wants to give company a face lift
 &HT;    By Marguerite M. Plunkett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Hydron Technologies' board fired Harvey
Tauman. He's looking to return the favor.
</P>
<P>
   Tauman, the founder and former chief executive of the Boca
Raton-based skin care products company, and his wife now control
6.9 percent of Hydron's shares after their latest stock buy _
137,000 shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plan is to change the board,'' Tauman said Monday. ``Our
plan is to take over.''
</P>
<P>
   Countered Thomas Burns, Hydron's vice president of finance:
``Anybody's entitled to buy shares. If he accumulates more than 5
percent, he has a right to attempt to do whatever he wants to.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns deferred further comment to interim President Richard
Banakus, who was not available Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Tauman, known as ``Hydron Harvey'' when he pitched the company's
products on the QVC cable channel, said he and his wife, Jennifer
Canon Tauman, are ``going to make our move as soon as we can.'' But
he declined to provide additional details.
</P>
<P>
   Tauman pointed to Hydron's sagging sales as the reason he should
be returned to the top of the company that ``illegally and
wrongfully terminated'' him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've been watching the financial results, it's been
catastrophic,'' he said. ``It's gone straight down. Sales were half
from the year before.''
</P>
<P>
   Hydron, which employs 12 people, reported $4 million in sales
last year, down 45 percent from $7.3 million in 1997. The company
lost $1.9 million last year, an improvement over the $2.6 million
in red ink in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Hydron blamed the sales decrease on declining sales via QVC.
Tauman, when he was the company's CEO and president, said he once
used the shopping channel to move $2.7 million in Hydron products
in one day, including $1.2 million during one show.
</P>
<P>
   Hydron's board, including Tauman's son, Richard, fired him in
September 1997 after a disagreement over the company's direction.
Harvey Tauman sued the company a month later. Hydron countersued
and accused Tauman of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Tauman has since started a new line of skin care products under
the name Greyson International. As the ``Greyson Guy,'' he pitches
the stuff on QVC's cable rival, the Home Shopping Network.
</P>
<P>
   Tauman challenged the Hydron board Monday: ``Give the
shareholders a chance and don't waste any more company assets. To
fight us would be futile.''
</P>
<P>
   Hydron stock (Nasdaq: HTECC) closed down 19 cents Monday at
$1.06 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Marguerite M. Plunkett writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
