<HEADER>
A5535 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICS-DYNASTIES-AR     04-12 1428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-DYNASTIES-ART-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIPS OFF THE OLD BLOCK, AND STUMP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: R.I., Texas, Tenn., Fla., Ohio, Ind., Colo., Ariz., N.M.,
Mass., N.H., Minn., Kan.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. _ Skimming the headlines last month, more than
a few Rhode Islanders must have felt a tug of confusion. One day,
the big news was that ``Chafee'' would retire from the U.S. Senate.
The very next day, the story was that ``Chafee'' would run for the
seat.
</P>
<P>
   But the seeming contradiction was really the latest example of
the blood relativity of American politics, where yet another family
tree had taken root.
</P>
<P>
   John Chafee, 76, a Republican who had represented Rhode Island
in the Senate for more than two decades, was taking himself out of
the running in 2000, when his term ends. A son, Lincoln Chafee, 46,
the Republican mayor of Warwick, R.I., was putting himself into the
race.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in Warwick last Thursday, the younger Chafee
emphasized his experience leading the state's second-most-populous
city for the last six years, not his pedigree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Warwick is the best-run city in the state, and I'm
prepared to defend that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his surname helped make him an instant front-runner for
the Republican nomination, and it drew attention to the enduring
prominence of political progeny in a country whose next
presidential race could pit Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the son
and namesake of a former president, against Vice President Albert
Gore Jr., the son and namesake of a former U.S. senator.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the concern that Americans often profess when insiders
hold the reins of government, the sons, daughters, brothers,
sisters, nephews and nieces of prominent lawmakers continue to
thrive in politics.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln Chafee, like several other second-generation politicians
interviewed for this article, said it was largely a matter of
exposure and rearing. Relatives of politicians, he said, were
simply more likely than others to enter the political arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's woven into our daily lives,'' he said, then drew an
analogy to the blood ties prominent in another profession. ``We're
always criticized for nepotism in the Fire Department here. But
it's natural. You see your Uncle Don running out to catch the
alarm, and it's contagious.''
</P>
<P>
   The children of politicians enjoy tactical advantages. John
Chafee demonstrated that as he and two aides hustled from his
office in Providence to a news conference in nearby Barrington last
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to the governor,'' the elder Chafee said, reporting
on a telephone conversation he had recently with Gov. Lincoln
Almond, a fellow Republican. ``He was very solicitous about Linc
and will help him. I asked him point blank.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in his office later that day, Chafee said his
contacts could play a large part in helping his son raise the $2.5
million estimated to be necessary for a successful Senate campaign
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it would be people who gave to me,'' Chafee said.
``They probably thought, `Oh, boy, we're spared,' when they read
that I was going to retire. But there's another Chafee running!''
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts and historians said dynasties have waxed and
waned. They said one reason for all the familiar surnames these
days could be the escalating price tag of running, a situation that
favors anyone with ready access to donors.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 elections not only returned George W. Bush to the
governor's office in Texas for a second term, but also installed
his brother, Jeb, in the governor's office in Florida for a first.
</P>
<P>
   In the Midwest, Bob Taft, the son and grandson of U.S. senators
and the great-grandson of a president, was elected governor of
Ohio, while Evan Bayh, the son of a U.S. senator, was elected to
the Indiana Senate seat that his father once held. In Texas, Rep.
Charlie Gonzalez, the son of Henry Gonzalez, succeeded his father.
</P>
<P>
   Voters in Colorado elected Mark Udall to the House; he is the
son of Morris Udall, who represented Arizona in the House for three
decades. Meanwhile, voters in New Mexico elected Mark's cousin Tom
Udall to the House; he is the son of Morris' brother Stewart Udall,
also a former Arizona congressman and Interior secretary in the
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedys, of course, are the best example of dynasty, with
two family members now in Congress, Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.,
and his son, Rep. Patrick Kennedy, D-R.I. And New England may be
the most fertile soil for the tradition.
</P>
<P>
   One of Connecticut's two senators, Christopher Dodd, a Democrat,
is the son of Thomas Dodd, who also represented Connecticut in the
Senate after losing his first bid for that office to Prescott Bush,
grandfather of the governors Bush. One of New Hampshire's two
representatives in the House, John Sununu Jr., a Republican,
inherited the name and interests of his father, a former New
Hampshire governor and presidential chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   But a blood line is no guarantee, and last fall's elections also
provided a compelling example of that. In the Minnesota governor's
race, the Democratic nominee, Hubert Humphrey III, son of a former
U.S. senator and vice president, lost to the ultimate outsider, a
former professional wrestler, Jesse Ventura.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``There's a continuing tension in American politics between
professionals and amateurs,'' noted Darrell West, a political
science professor at Brown University in Providence. ``People who
support term limits believe fervently in the citizen politician,
whereas others value political experience, which plays directly to
dynasties.''
</P>
<P>
   What plays just as directly to dynasties is the limited
attention of voters. It makes winning name recognition a tall
hurdle and favors any candidate with a well-known father or other
relative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half the voters are going to get confused and think it is the
dad running,'' said Christine Matthews, a Republican pollster. ``If
I were to do a poll in September of next year for Linc Chafee,
people would be saying, `Well, I think he's done a good job in the
Senate.'''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a number of pollsters have suggested that some of George
W. Bush's support comes from such confusion. But political progeny
arguably are propelled into office just as strongly by internal
factors.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez of Texas said he wanted to honor his father's career by
perpetuating it and that, unlike many people contemplating a run
for public office, he had not been daunted by the public scrutiny
or demands on his time that such a decision would bring.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've seen someone else handle it up close and personal, so
you know you can survive it,'' he said. ``It's not so foreign to
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln Chafee, one of six children, also grew up amid the
trappings of elective office. Before his father became senator in
1976, he was governor from 1963 to 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Stevens, one of Lincoln Chafee's boyhood friends,
recalled that Gov. Chafee ``would come in after a long day in
Providence, dealing with all these statewide issues, and say, `OK,
you're the governor of Rhode Island, this crisis is happening, what
do you do?'''
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln Chafee was not the most vociferous respondent, not the
one who would have seemed destined, alone among the Chafee
children, to end up in politics. He took a circuitous route,
choosing classics as his major at Brown and then working for the
better part of a decade as a farrier, shoeing race horses.
</P>
<P>
   His first election was to the Warwick City Council in 1986. In
1990, he tried and failed to become mayor, but won four subsequent
elections to two-year terms, even though there are many more
Democrats than Republicans among the city's roughly 85,000
residents.
</P>
<P>
   His father said the family name was indeed an asset, but only if
used the right way. He cited, as an example, the balance struck by
former Sen. Nancy Landon Kassebaum, a Kansas Republican, whose
campaign slogan had been ``a fresh face, a trusted name,'' the
latter phrase referring to her father, Alf Landon, a former
governor of Kansas and presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Chafee pushed the same slogan on Lincoln for one of his first
local races. The senator recalled that when he subsequently showed
his son's campaign literature to some of his colleagues and
friends, ``They said, `Oh, yeah, a trusted name. Lincoln.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 2216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
