<DOCNO> NYT19990412.0450 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5536 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAZARETH-PLAZA-ART-69     04-12 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAZARETH-PLAZA-ART-690(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOD'S HALF-ACRE, BUT WHOSE GOD? A TOWN IS TORN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZARETH, Israel _ In modern history, this sleepy Israeli Arab
town, the traditional childhood home of Jesus, has been a stranger
to the tensions roiling the Mideast. Christian and Muslim Arabs
lived together here in harmony. Together they depended on the
Christian pilgrims who sustained their feeble tourist economy, and
together they took pride in their sweets, exported as delicacies
throughout the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
   Starting on Easter Sunday, however, the sleepy town awakened to
violent conflict. Stones, bricks and firebombs were thrown; the
town _ including the churches _ was effectively shuttered, and the
seemingly sturdy balance between Christians and Muslims was upset.
</P>
<P>
   Against the backdrop of the Christian-Muslim conflict in Kosovo,
it could seem a piddling controversy: a battle over a half-acre of
land, a few injuries and some broken windowpanes. But it threatens
to grow into an international diplomatic incident, pitting the
Muslim world against the Vatican _ with Israel, an interested
party, in the unlikely role of gendarme.
</P>
<P>
   This is the problem: In the heart of this scruffy town, on the
land in question, Mayor Ramez Jerayseh, who is Christian, plans to
build a plaza for the millennium next to the Basilica of the
Annunciation, an elegant modern building atop the ruined walls of a
12th-century Crusader church. It is a major Christian holy site,
the place where tradition says that the angel Gabriel told Mary she
was pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   The town's Muslim leadership, however, has other plans for the
land, which Muslims consider sacrosanct, too. Right next to the
church, they want to erect a twin symbol for their town _ a $20
million megamosque, to be financed by donors in the Persian Gulf
nations. It would be a multispired edifice topped by a soaring
325-foot-tall minaret with a laser crescent at its peak.
</P>
<P>
   Gazing at the site, Ahmed Zoubi, an engineer who helped design
the mosque and who is also a City Council member from the Islamic
Movement, stood between piles of nougat in the Center Sweets Shop
across the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is not to overshadow the church,'' he said calmly.
``We are willing to build a bridge connecting the mosque and the
church. The point is that Nazareth, which may be known to the world
as Christian, is a Muslim-majority city. It has two identities.''
</P>
<P>
   Anan Hayek emerged from a wedding at the church wearing a
pin-striped suit and soft leather loafers. A tourist bus driver who
is Christian, he sees the matter very differently, and in outrage
he shook a bag of the covered almonds that are used to shower the
bride and groom.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the city of Jesus,'' he said. ``They want to connect
our church to a mosque with a bridge! That is unthinkable. What is
happening here now is planting enmity in our hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also bad public relations for the tourism industry here.
It has high hopes for the year 2000, even if its development
projects are a bit behind schedule _ leading some officials to
declare that the year 2000 does not have to start in January for
everybody.
</P>
<P>
   In March 2000, Pope John Paul II is scheduled to visit, a
supremely important event for Nazareth. And Roman Catholic
authorities, who have expressed concern over the issue, are
cautioning the Israelis that a failure to resolve fairly the
delicate matter over the mosque could jeopardize their
participation in the millennial celebration in Israel, said Avi
Blushtein, the director general of the Israeli Ministry of
Religious Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Israelis and the Palestinians are trying to mediate the
conflict, although the Israelis, whose Land Authority owns the
property, are the official government authority here. But the
Israeli intervention is perceived as so manipulative _ the Likud
government is seen as wanting to end the conflict in a way that
will bring it Arab votes _ that it could be the catalyst to reunite
Nazareth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Israeli Arabs should be fighting them, not each other,''
said Mahmoud Nassar, a Muslim who owns the Peace Restaurant
downtown. But then he added, ominously, ``This city will burn if
the big mosque doesn't get built.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The conflict here underscores how varied and finely nuanced are
the internal divisions within Israel. Outsiders find it difficult
to understand the many ways in which Jews here are divided, much
less to fathom sectarian rifts among Israeli Arabs, who account for
one-sixth of the population.
</P>
<P>
   In Nazareth, Muslims outnumber Christians about 42,000 to
18,000, although the Christians _ both Roman Catholics and Greek
Orthodox _ tend to be more affluent and better educated. Through
the Communist Party, which they dominate, Christians have
controlled the town's affairs for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Three months ago, however, the Islamic Movement swept to a
majority in the City Council, even though Jerayseh held onto the
mayoralty. And the issue that carried the Islamic Movement to power
was the disputed half-acre.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen months ago, Jerayseh, with permission from the
government of Israel, had bulldozed the site. He cleared it of an
old school but left a tiny mosque that Muslims believe contains the
tomb of a holy figure from the 12th century.
</P>
<P>
   Outraged, Muslims erected a huge protest tent, a shabby
structure in the shadow of the basilica that Christian tourists
found repellent. Construction on the plaza never began, even as the
Nazareth 2000 project raced against the clock to renovate the city
for the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The Christians and Muslims were in a static tug of war over the
land. The Israeli government left them alone, although in recent
weeks it stepped up its mediation efforts and seemed to back the
construction of the mosque, to the outrage of the Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few months, although there were outbursts of
violence, tension over the land did not permeate the general
population of the city, which is well integrated.
</P>
<P>
   But on Easter Sunday, the town erupted. It is hard to know what
really happened. The Muslims say Christian youths began throwing
rocks at the tiny mosque, chanting that Mohammed would fall just as
Jesus ascended. The Christians say that Islamic activists
surrounded an Easter procession and picked a fight.
</P>
<P>
   There were brawls, a dozen people were injured and a few dozen
cars were smashed as scores of police officers in riot gear
apparently chose not to intervene. In subsequent days, firebombs
were hurled at both Christian and Muslim businesses and homes.
</P>
<P>
   While thousands of Muslims crowded the tiny protest site for
Friday prayers, the church had taken the unusual step of closing
the basilica for two days. Christians shut themselves in their
homes; the mayor, who received death threats, was forced to
disconnect his phone.
</P>
<P>
   The basilica reopened Sunday for Mass, for tourists, and for
several local weddings. Cars outside were festooned with roses,
individual red ones taped to the windows. But the celebrations were
quieter than usual and anxiety-ridden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been locked inside our houses,'' Nadira Hayek said,
holding her little son's hand tightly after a wedding. ``When we go
outside, we've been hassled because we wear crosses around our
neck. Racism is coming to the surface here, and it is very sad.
We're afraid for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Zoubi, the council member, said the fear was unfounded. The
Muslims are willing to delay construction of the mosque until after
the millennium celebration is held, he said. Such is their spirit
of compromise, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact,'' he said, ``we are ready to invite the pope to lay
the cornerstone himself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
