<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5540 &Cx1f; tad-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CBS-BIGENTERTAINMENT-     04-12 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CBS-BIGENTERTAINMENT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big Entertainment, CBS make `robust' promotion deal
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving to (f) Financial and (E) Entertainment categories.)
 &HT;    By Stephen Pounds
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Shares in Big Entertainment more than doubled
Monday to $32.38 after the company announced a deal that gives CBS
35 percent ownership of the Boca Raton firm's Hollywood.com Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   To get its stake, CBS agreed to provide $100 million in
promotion for the Web site during the next seven years. CBS will
tout Hollywood.com on television, radio and syndicated programming.
</P>
<P>
   Big Entertainment will own 65 percent of the Hollywood.com
venture, which has one of the Web's largest collections of
movie-related multimedia offerings, plus movie listings and show
times as well as Hollywood news and celebrity interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Big Entertainment (Nasdaq: BIGE) closed up $16.63 a
share Monday, an increase of 105.56 percent.
</P>
<P>
   All this comes even though Big Entertainment has yet to complete
its $31 million stock deal with Los Angeles-based Times-Mirror Co.
to buy Hollywood Online, Times-Mirror's Hollywood.com subsidiary.
But Big E Chief Executive Officer Mitchell Rubenstein said the
company's major shareholders have pledged to support the deal,
making approval a certainty.
</P>
<P>
   For Big E, which has 97 employees in Boca Raton, the CBS deal
offers more than just promotion. CBS also intends to sell
advertising on Hollywood.com, which would benefit both companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a valuable addition to their ad sales. We give another
thing to sell,'' Rubenstein said. ``This is really robust.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal is structured in much the same way as CBS' agreements
with Sportsline USA, the Fort Lauderdale Web site that develops
sports content, and MarketWatch, a California-based Web site that
offers business and financial news. The two now are public
companies, and CBS' stake in them has grown to more than a
half-billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
   In both instances, CBS took an equity position in exchange for
promotion on its TV shows and radio stations. Then, when the
companies made initial stock offerings, CBS, without investing
cash, became a large shareholder in growing Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   In this instance, Rubenstein would have to spin off
Hollywood.com as a separate public company from its parent, Big E,
which already is a public company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying that that's what is going to happen, but
Sportsline and MarketWatch went public, and their value was created
through their public offerings,'' Rubenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Big E was founded by Rubenstein and his wife, Laurie Silvers,
founders of the Sci-Fi Channel, a cable channel that was sold in
1992 to USA Networks. They took Big E public in 1993, planning to
develop comic book characters that could be adapted to books,
movies and TV. That effort struggled, along with their next
strategy for Big E, to open entertainment-related retail kiosks.
</P>
<P>
   The company has had only two profitable quarters in about five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Big E's fortunes began to change in November, with the launch of
its bige.com Web site to sell entertainment and movie merchandise.
The site found a following, and some deft deals since have lifted
the company's position on the Internet as well as its stock price.
</P>
<P>
   In another deal Monday, CBS said it will get a 50 percent
ownership stake in storeRunner.com, a San Diego-based Web site that
scans Internet locations for good deals for shoppers. CBS will lend
its name to the site.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Pounds writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
