A5543 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-INDIANS-CASINOS-C     04-12 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-INDIANS-CASINOS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush deals out lawsuit to stop Indian casinos
 &HT;    By Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Gov. Jeb Bush took his opposition to
gambling to court Monday, suing the federal government for writing
rules that could allow full-blown casinos on American Indian tribal
land in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Florida have really spoken, repeatedly, at the
ballot box,'' Bush said, referring to three statewide referendums
on casinos that have been rejected in the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Attorney General Bob Butterworth announced a joint
Florida-Alabama federal court lawsuit in response to the
long-expected publication of rules by the Department of Interior
that could let tribes operate slot machines, high-stakes card
tables and craps tables whether a state government approves or not.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, two tribes operate five casinos offering high-stakes
bingo, low-stakes poker and _ in the state's view: illegally _ slot
machines.
</P>
<P>
   The Miccosukee tribe operates a casino in Miami-Dade County.
</P>
<P>
   The Seminole tribe, which runs casinos in Hollywood, Tampa,
Immokalee and Glades County, has been trying for years to expand
its gambling operation, even accusing the state in a lawsuit of not
negotiating in good faith, as is required by a 1988 federal law.
</P>
<P>
   It was the result of that lawsuit _ a 1996 decision by the U.S.
Supreme Court saying tribes couldn't sue states _ that led the
Interior Department to draft a rule to resolve disputes between
states and tribes over gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Florida and other states objected, saying the Interior
Department has an inherent bias on the subject because it
administers tribal land.
</P>
<P>
   Department lawyers noted these objections in the Federal
Register on Monday, but essentially denied a conflict of interest
and said department Secretary Bruce Babbitt would consider
opposition from states when deciding whether and what sort of
gambling to allow.
</P>
<P>
   ``States will be invited to participate in mediation if they
wish,'' said the published explanation of the rules. ``They can
also submit comments on the proposed scope of gaming . . . and on
any other matter pertaining to an Indian tribe's proposed
procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not good enough, said Assistant Attorney General John
Glogau, Florida's lead lawyer on the issue. He said having a
back-door route to casinos usurps the authority of the state and
thwarts the will of the electorate, which in 1994 resoundingly
defeated a proposed constitutional amendment to allow casinos in
Florida. Similar efforts in 1978 and 1986 were defeated as well.
</P>
<P>
   The tribes, however, say the will of Florida voters is
irrelevant. ``Because the federal government is supreme in matters
regarding Indians,'' said Bruce Rogow, a Fort Lauderdale lawyer
representing the Seminole Tribe. ``The Seminoles should be allowed
casino gaming.''
</P>
<P>
   If full-blown casinos do come, they would come only to places
already owned by tribes prior to 1988, Glogau said. Attempts to
establish casinos on land acquired after 1988 would require
permission of the governor _ who Monday repeated his opposition to
gambling and its embedded ``something for nothing attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Glogau said he expects the whole question ultimately to go back
to the U.S. Supreme Court to decide once and for all. In the
meantime, casinos will not start appearing in Florida anytime soon,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Interior Department built in comment and review periods of
several months in its new rule. Glogau said he believes Babbitt
will not move faster than the courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've assured me they're not going to get out in front of us
on that,'' Glogau said.
</P>
<P>
   Shirish Date writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
