<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VA-POLITICS-515&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG NAME FOR SENATE IN VIRGINIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ George Allen, a Republican known for his
congeniality and conservatism when he was governor of Virginia, is
expected to announce on Tuesday that he will run for the Senate
next year, challenging the two-term incumbent Democrat, Charles
Robb.
</P>
<P>
   Highly popular in the state from his years in the Virginia
Legislature, Allen became governor in 1993, winning 58 percent of
the vote. After his single four-year term, which is all Virginia
law allows for governors, he returned to private practice as a
lawyer and began planning for a Senate campaign by raising money
and speaking across the state.
</P>
<P>
   Terri Hauser, a campaign spokeswoman, said she did not want to
pre-empt Allen's announcement plans but added, ``He's been testing
the waters, and they're feeling mighty fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before Allen indicated that he would run for the Senate,
forming an exploratory committee in December, Robb was viewed by
many political analysts as one of the most vulnerable of the 14
Democratic senators seeking re-election next year.
</P>
<P>
   While Republicans were winning control of Congress in 1994,
Virginia voters found Robb's admitted marital infidelities only
slightly less objectionable than the role his opponent, Oliver
North, the former Marine lieutenant colonel, played in the
Iran-contra affair.
</P>
<P>
   But Allen, 47, has no such baggage, and already statewide polls
have shown that he would defeat Robb, 59, by a comfortable margin.
Neither candidate is expected to face a major challenge before the
general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``He enters this race as an incumbent underdog,'' Robert
Holsworth, a professor of political science at Virginia
Commonwealth University, in Richmond, said of Robb. ``I think the
race is likely to be close, but the early polls show Allen beating
him in a head-to-head race.''
</P>
<P>
   As governor, Allen left a firm legacy, reflecting Republican
ideals that are popular among many Republican governors. He pushed
through one of the country's toughest welfare-to-work programs, and
he led an effort to eliminate parole for violent offenders.
</P>
<P>
   He also worked to establish standards of learning in Virginia's
public schools, setting them so high that only 2 percent of the
state schools passed them last year when they were measured for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   Allen would also seem to benefit from a state Republican Party
that is more unified now than it was six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   North won the party nomination after a bruising fight with James
Miller, a former budget director in the Reagan administration. Then
he failed to win the endorsement of the state's most popular
Republican, Sen. John Warner, or his commander in chief, President
Ronald Reagan, a setback that effectively split the party through
the fall campaign season.
</P>
<P>
   With Warner backing Marshall Coleman, a
Republican-turned-independent, Robb won in the general election
with 46 percent of the vote to 43 percent for North and 11 percent
for Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   State Democratic officials say they expect Robb to attack Allen
as a conservative who is out of step with most Virginia voters.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Craig Bieber, chairman of the state Democratic Party, says that
though Allen ``cultivates a moderate facade, he is really as
right-wing as North was.''
</P>
<P>
   Bieber also said Allen could prove vulnerable for taking credit
for state economic expansion that would have occurred anyway and
for policies that have made Virginia a leading importer of
prisoners and garbage from other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Robb will run on the fact he is a moderate voice of
reason in the United States Senate,'' Bieber said. ``It will be up
to us to point out that Allen is as extreme as Ollie North was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
