<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5548 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-COMPOSERS-SFCHRON &LR;      04-12 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-COMPOSERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC AND LIFE IN HARMONY IN PBS' `GREAT COMPOSERS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOSHUA KOSMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Television may not be the ideal vehicle for teaching people
about classical music, but in the right hands it can pack a
tremendous amount of material into a compact stretch of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great Composers,'' a splendid three-week, six-part series
co-produced by BBC and New York's WNET-TV that begins airing
Wednesday, offers thoughtful, fascinating introductions to the
lives and works of six titans of Western music, and does it with
both visual flair and seriousness of purpose. This is an
entertaining, educational feast not to be missed.
</P>
<P>
   This week's two hourlong episodes, on Mozart and Beethoven, are
by far the strongest, but there is plenty to savor in the coming
weeks _ segments on Wagner and Mahler are slated for April 21,
followed on April 28 by Tchaikovsky and Puccini.
</P>
<P>
   The first sign that the series has been done right is the list
of participants, a starry A-list drawn from the worlds of
performance and scholarship. Many of the artists _ including
Michael Tilson Thomas on Beethoven and Mahler, or Sir Colin Davis
on Mozart, or Sir Charles Mackerras on Puccini _ have cogent and
fascinating things to say, and even the less articulate musicians,
such as tenor Jose Cura or pianist Evgeny Kissin, are welcome
additions.
</P>
<P>
   The academic side is equally well represented, with some of the
most eminent and knowledgeable scholars brought in for each
composer. William Meredith, who heads the Beethoven Center at San
Jose State University, is just one among many big guns.
</P>
<P>
   Using a combination of location shots, talking heads and
performance footage, each episode traces the life story of its
subject, interpolated with wonderfully specific explanations of his
importance to music history. The result, at its best, is an
amazingly deft blend of biography and musicology.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt that's what any such project should aspire to, but in
practice the balance is devilishly hard to pull off. Too often, the
life and the music are kept separate, with the former falling prey
to romantic mythologizing and the latter to oversimplification.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great Composers'' doesn't entirely avoid these pitfalls, but
it does keep them at bay with remarkable thoroughness. The Mozart
segment, for instance, takes an unsentimental view of the
composer's popular success and subsequent decline, and relates it
with a few swift strokes to the cultural politics of imperial
Vienna. Salieri's name, thank God, is never mentioned, despite the
presence of ``Amadeus'' playwright Peter Shaffer.
</P>
<P>
   Beethoven and Mahler, too, are treated with the sympathy due
their respective plights, without lapsing into the grandiose hero
worship with which each man tended to view himself. Most enjoyable
is the Puccini segment, for which the producers have rounded up
some of the composer's long-ago neighbors, now garrulous old women
who are only too happy to spill the beans about his marital
peccadilloes.
</P>
<P>
   Even more rewarding, though, is the high level of musical
discussion to be found in most of these segments. Certainly, there
are the usual empty superlatives _ most of them from performers _
about how this one's music is extraordinary and that one's music is
unlike anything ever composed.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also plenty of concrete observations, backed up
with musical examples _ about the effect of Mozart's first
encounter with the music of Bach, or the nature of Beethoven's
early keyboard style, or Puccini's relationship to the Italian
opera tradition from which he grew.
</P>
<P>
   The exception is Tchaikovsky, about whom there is apparently
nothing of substance to be said. The producers deal skillfully with
the historical controversy surrounding his death _ was it cholera
or (as some implausibly claim) suicide? _ but other than that,
there is only vaporous yammering about how his music touches the
heart. Not even his life story is told with anything approaching
coherence.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to whine, as some commentators have already begun to
do, about all that's been left out in these sketches _ about the
rapid forced march through each life or the brevity of the musical
excerpts, not to mention the inevitable fact that six composers
were selected and countless more omitted.
</P>
<P>
   But we're dealing, after all, with one-hour television segments
that attempt to encapsulate some of Western music's most stunning
achievements. What's striking is not how much is left out but how
much the creators have managed to pack in.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
