</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
(HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ON-LINE AUCTIONS TURNING MILLIONS INTO BIDDERS
</P>
<P>
   Millions of people have begun embracing the on-line auction, an
Internet phenomenon that in a matter of months has captivated the
nation's bargain hunters and spawned a market for nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   While retailers spend furiously to draw more customers on line,
the Internet is suddenly teeming with buyers and sellers making
their own markets. Testimonials about bargains abound in the chat
rooms where the auction aficionados gather, and some will admit
that the thrill of the game is worth it even when they lose or
overpay.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN RAISES PRICE OF OFFERING
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, Sachs, Wall Street's last large, privately held
investment bank, said that it would raise the price range of its
highly anticipated initial public offering to $45 to $55 a share,
up from a range of $40 to $50. And that promises to create some fat
wallets on Wall Street. For example, the firm's co-chairman and
chief executive, Henry M. Paulson Jr., who owns the largest
individual stake in Goldman, would see his shares valued at about
$227 million.
</P>
<P>
   TYCO TO ELIMINATE 4,000 AMP JOBS
</P>
<P>
   Tyco International, the top maker of electrical connectors since
its purchase a week ago of AMP, said that it would cut 4,000 AMP
jobs and that it expected profit to rise by 25 percent in five to
six years. The reductions are on top of 4,200 already planned by
AMP.
</P>
<P>
   SAVINGS ASSOCIATIONS' SHARES FALL
</P>
<P>
   Golden State Bancorp shares fell, as did other securities tied
to lawsuits by savings and loan associations against the
government. On Friday, a judge awarded Golden State less than
investors had expected, although he agreed the Government had
broken a promise of special regulatory treatment.
</P>
<P>
   FORD TO BUY CAR-REPAIR CHAIN
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor agreed to buy the European car-repair chain Kwik-Fit
Holdings for $1.63 billion in cash. Analysts said the move would
allow Ford to compete with independent repair shops and to sell
more Ford parts.
</P>
<P>
   IBM AND REAL NETWORKS IN DEAL
</P>
<P>
   IBM said that it had enlisted Real Networks, the online
multimedia company, to help its effort to create a standard for
sending music over the Internet. The cooperation between the
computer industry giant and the Internet start-up is the latest
development in the race to market a consumer-friendly way of
distributing music on line while guarding against piracy. Shares of
Real Networks rose $39.50, to $247.
</P>
<P>
   CHINESE EXPORTS FELL IN QUARTER
</P>
<P>
   China's exports fell 7.9 percent in the first quarter, as sharp
declines in shipments to Europe more than offset increased exports
to the United States. The report was worrisome because economists
fear that China's economy, the largest in Asia after Japan's, may
stumble, as did other Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
   ADELPHIA EXPANDING IN CABLE
</P>
<P>
   Adelphia Communications, moving to become the fourth-largest
cable-television company, agreed to buy Harron Communications'
cable systems for $1.17 billion in cash to expand in New England
and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   PROFITS UP AT NEWSPAPER COMPANIES
</P>
<P>
   Gannett and two other newspaper publishers, Dow Jones and E.W.
Scripps, reaped better-than-expected quarterly profits as
advertising revenue grew and newsprint prices fell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
