<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS RIDE RISING TIDE OF GOOD PITCHING AND DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Not even a flood in his office could dampen Mets
Manager Bobby Valentine's mood Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Not after Bobby Jones hit his first career home run to break a
1-1 tie in the Mets' home opener, all while tossing seven dominant
innings to resemble the Bobby Jones who was named a National League
All-Star two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And certainly not while Robin Ventura did his best Brooks
Robinson imitation at third base while breaking open the game with
a two-run double in a very auspicious Shea Stadium debut, as the
Mets pulled away for an 8-1 victory over the Florida Marlins before
an announced sellout crowd of 52,052.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing, it seems _ not even sewage from a pump failure _ can
sink Valentine's hopes for this season right now. Not as long as
the Mets, who have won four straight games and six of eight to open
the season, keep rolling through the early part of their schedule
the way they did again Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was a very, very good day,'' Valentine said in full
uniform in the Jets' old dressing room a full half-hour after the
game. It wasn't that Valentine did not want to take a shower, it
was that he and his players and coaches could not, because of the
flood waters swirling around part of the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll get all of that cleaned up,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   All last week, while the Mets were on the road, Valentine kept
speaking of how much he looked forward to going home so he could
see his team's revamped clubhouse. Imagine Valentine's surprise
then when he walked into his office late Sunday night and was
greeted by a desk as big as an ocean liner.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the concern that Valentine must have felt
when he raced into the clubhouse to grab a cup of coffee in the
sixth inning Monday only to find his office _ including that same
desk and boxes of his prized collection of World Series programs _
just beginning to submerge into a rising tide of waste water. The
problem, the Mets said, was a pump failure that flooded Valentine's
office, the showers and the coaches' room.
</P>
<P>
   After a weekend in which his team lost its most productive
hitter, Mike Piazza, and one of its most reliable starting
pitchers, Rick Reed, to injuries, Valentine could have been
forgiven if he felt as if he were trapped in some sort of disaster
movie.
</P>
<P>
   But after the Mets had dismantled the low-budget Marlins for the
third time in a week since an embarrassing opening day loss in
Miami, Valentine and his players chose to laugh the whole mess off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like Little League,'' said Bobby Bonilla, who
went 3 for 3 with two runs scored and his first run batted in of
the season after opening the year 1 for 17 on the road. ``You play
the game and shower at home.''
</P>
<P>
   But first, Ventura had to find his way to his new home, near
Bonilla's in Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt real strange,'' said Ventura, who spent his first 10
seasons in the major leagues with the Chicago White Sox before
signing a four-year, $32 million deal in the off season with the
Mets. ``Even when we flew in yesterday, it was just different. Not
knowing how to get here, where to park, where the clubhouse is, my
locker, the field.''
</P>
<P>
   But from the very first pitch Monday, Ventura looked as if he
felt at home. The five-time American League Gold Glove winner
robbed the fleet Luis Castillo of a bunt single up the third-base
line with a magnificent charge, barehand grab and throw in the
first inning. Ventura pulled off almost the same combination on
Castillo _ Valentine said it was harder because Castillo's bunt was
perfect _ in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bunted two times, give me one _ one for him, one for me,''
said Castillo, who seemed in awe. ``He's the best third baseman in
the National League.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, however, Ventura insisted he was not flashy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not flashy,'' Valentine said. ``He's just good. Brooks
Robinson wasn't flashy either.''
</P>
<P>
   To torment the Marlins' second baseman even further, Ventura
reached into the stands to grab a Castillo foul pop in the eighth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura also broke up a double play in the second inning that
resulted in a wild relay to first and the first run of the game.
After the Marlins tied the score, Jones gave himself the lead back
with a solo shot off Livan Hernandez in the bottom of the fifth
that landed just inside the left-field foul pole.
</P>
<P>
   What the Mets really need from Jones is for him to be more
consistent on the mound. ``I've always had my good games and my bad
games,'' Jones said after allowing one run on four hits. Still,
Monday was the 29-year-old right-hander's second strong
seven-inning performance in a row against the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take those two starts any time,'' said Jones, who had
tossed seven shutout innings in a 6-0 victory in Miami five days
before. ``It's as close to as good as I could have done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
