<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-BOSTON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Multitalented family to play visible roles as Boston starts NFL
career
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NFL historians can look long and hard and never find a football
family as unique as the Bostons.
</P>
<P>
   David Boston left Humble for Ohio State, where he became one of
the best receivers in the country. On Saturday, an NFL team will
draft him in the top half of the first round and eventually make
him a multimillionaire.
</P>
<P>
   If Boston has a problem with his agent during contract
negotiations, he can call his mother to complain. Why? Because his
sister, Dallas attorney Alicia Boston, is the agent who is
representing her younger brother.
</P>
<P>
   If Alicia Boston has a problem with her client, she may be the
only agent in the country who can punch him and not get fired.
</P>
<P>
   Even if she gets him one of the best contracts in history, the
Bostons won't be popping a bottle of champagne to celebrate. David
is only 20, which means he's too young to drink and has to get his
mother or father to co-sign his contract to make it legal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carolyn and I advised David to stay in school for his senior
year for two reasons,'' says Byron Boston, the patriarch of the
family. ``We felt he was too young to come out early, and if he
stayed another year, he'd be closer to getting his degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've always told David to follow his heart, and this is
what he wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Byron Boston, a tax consultant, is an NFL line judge who has a
chance to make history in the preseason. Jerry Seeman, the league's
senior director of officiating, is thinking about assigning Boston
to one of his son's preseason games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something we'd ever do in regular season, but we
might in preseason because it's something that's never occurred,''
Seeman says.
</P>
<P>
   Once the league sees which team Boston will play for, they will
give him and his father a chance to make history in preseason.
Before that game, they will be in the national spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't usually put much emphasis on that kind of thing, but
I'd like to have a couple of pictures of it because it would be
unique,'' Byron Boston says.
</P>
<P>
   Byron has played a major role in his son's development into a
high No. 1 draft choice. At Humble High School, Boston was an
outstanding football and basketball player. In football, he was
actually a better defensive back than receiver.
</P>
<P>
   When he made the decision to attend Ohio State, he elected to
give up basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once David made that decision and turned that page of his
career, that's when he really began to develop,'' Byron says.
``He's always had a great work ethic, and we've always thought he
would be successful no matter what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Alicia Boston is an attorney in the Dallas firm of Worsham,
Forsythe and Wooldridge. She doesn't plan to be an agent, but when
her brother told her he'd like to keep it all in the family, she
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My firm's been great about it,'' she says. ``They're excited
about it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to get David the best deal possible. He's a
talented player who's smart and has good character. He deserves to
be paid what he's worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Alicia Boston has been doing her homework. The NFL Players
Association has been providing help and information. She has hired
two experienced agents as consultants, but she is the only one who
will negotiate the contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure David's heard something like, `Your sister's going to
mess up your deal,' but he hasn't told me about it,'' she says.
``He knows I have his best interests at heart. One advantage of
being brother and sister is that I can be brutally honest with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not nervous about it. I'm very excited, actually.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Boston signs his first contract, he plans to start a
corporation. He already knows who will be his CEO _ his mother. If
he decides to pay big bucks for a director of security, he can hire
his older brother, Byron Boston Jr., a policeman in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family means so much to me,'' Boston says. ``I know they'll
always have my best interests at heart. I wouldn't be in this
position without my family. I wanted to keep as much as I could in
the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alicia's a lawyer, and she's smart. I started to seriously
consider her (to negotiate the contract) in the middle of last
season when I began to think about coming out early. That was a
very difficult decision, especially since my parents wanted me to
stay in school, but I'm comfortable with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston was an extraordinary athlete growing up in Humble.
Success came naturally to him at an early age, but his parents
provided him with an outstanding work ethic that helped him star as
a freshman at Ohio State and made him one of the best NFL prospects
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a kid, I was catching passes all the time,'' Boston
says. ``I didn't want to be the quarterback. I just wanted to catch
the ball. I always liked to run deep routes. My dad could throw it
deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad has been a big influence on my life and my football
career. He taught me how to handle different situations, how to
deal with people. I'm very protective of myself, and I don't let
people take advantage of me.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom did everything for me when I was growing up. She cooked
three meals, ironed my clothes. She taught me how to act. She just
made my life a lot easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston has been paying a lot of attention to his father, who
sees NFL players up close and personal every Sunday during the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's talked to me about how fast and physical the NFL is,''
Boston says. ``I don't know where I'll go, but I think I bring
size, speed, strength and determination to the NFL. I have no fear.
A lot of people think I'm cocky, but I think I'm just a tough
competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about the draft, but I'm getting a little
impatient. I'm anxious to find out where I'm going to be playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Boston has more sympathy for officials than most
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, guys don't think about what referees go through, how fast
things happen, and it doesn't matter what sport it is,'' Boston
says. ``Things happen in an instant. Sometimes, they can't see
everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they miss one, it's going to be all over television, but if
they get 5,000 right, no one says anything. There's a lot of
pressure on them. They can't go to Las Vegas, can't be around any
gambling. They have to stay squeaky clean.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless a good team trades up in the first round to get him,
there's a chance David will watch his father reach the Super Bowl
before he does.
</P>
<P>
   A former Southwest Conference official, Byron Boston has been in
the NFL for four years. He already has officiated in conference
championship games the last two years. There's only one more step
to go, and Seeman says Boston is already one of the league's better
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, if I get drafted high, that means I'm probably going to
a team that didn't do too well last season,'' David Boston says.
``That means my dad will probably get to a Super Bowl before I do.
But you know what? I'll be real happy for him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 2233EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
