<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDMAN-IPO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDMAN RAISES PRICE RANGE FOR ITS STOCK OFFERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., taking advantage of financial
markets that have rebounded from last fall's doldrums, said Monday
that it would raise the price range of its highly anticipated
initial public offering by as much as 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And that promises to create some very fat wallets on Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Documents filed Monday with the Securities and Exchange
Commission as part of the revised offering provide a glimpse of the
riches that would be harvested by Goldman's partners if the shares
sold at the high end of the expected range.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's co-chairman and chief executive, Henry M. Paulson
Jr., who owns the largest individual stake in Goldman, would see
his 4.132 million shares valued at about $227 million. Two men
considered to be vying to succeed Paulson one day, the co-chief
operating officers John A. Thain and John L. Thornton, would hold
stakes valued at $171 million and $166 million, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman's directors and executive officers as a group, 13 people
in all, would hold a stake in the firm valued as high as $1.43
billion. Goldman's two largest outside shareholders, Sumitomo Bank
and an educational concern controlled by Hawaii's Bishop Estate
trust, would have stakes worth as much as $1.15 billion and $1.2
billion, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The holdings of Jon Corzine, Goldman's former co-chief executive
who was ousted in a January coup led by Paulson, were not
disclosed, though some analysts said his stake would be roughly
equivalent to that of Paulson. Corzine has said he plans to leave
Goldman after the offering, which is scheduled for May 3.
</P>
<P>
   Other Goldman executives with big holdings include the vice
chairman, Robert J. Hurst, with a $211 million stake, and the chief
financial officer, David A. Viniar, with a $94 million stake. John
L. Weinberg, the former co-chief executive and a current director,
owns shares that would be worth about $24 million.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes have been built up over the years, and the partners
who hold them must hold onto their shares for five years before
selling.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman canceled an initial public offering last September
because of financial volatility at home and abroad that left the
firm with tens of millions of dollars in trading losses.
</P>
<P>
   The offering of a 14.8 percent stake in Wall Street's last
large, privately held investment bank will be priced at between $45
and $55 a share, up from a range of $40 to $50 expected last month.
As detailed in the revised filing, the offering, which would raise
$3.1 billion to $3.8 billion, values all of Goldman at as much as
$25.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Valued at the high end of that trading range, Goldman would rank
as the third-largest investment bank in the country behind Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter, which has a market value of about $63.4
billion, and Merrill Lynch, which is valued at about $36 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that the revised offering price is entirely
reasonable and even expected,'' said John Keefe, president of Keefe
Worldwide, a financial-services consulting firm in New York.
``Market conditions make that almost mechanical.''
</P>
<P>
   The revised offering price was first disclosed in The Wall
Street Journal Monday and coincides with an international sales
push this week by Goldman aimed at wooing investors worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   In a nod to the rich valuations investors are placing on any
stock even remotely connected to the Internet, Goldman _ although
still a neophyte when it comes to cyberspace _ emphasized a nascent
Internet strategy in the offering document. Goldman noted its
investments in electronic commerce concerns and the development of
its online capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The offering also disclosed more about Goldman's finances and
reveals just how dependent the firm is on highly unpredictable _
and often risky _ trading revenue.
</P>
<P>
   For its first quarter, which ended in February, Goldman earned
$1 billion on revenue of $3 billion, compared with $884 million on
revenue of $2.5 billion in the quarter a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Trading remains Goldman's dominant line of business, making up
$1.36 billion of the revenue in the quarter, while investment
banking contributed $902 million. Revenue from asset management was
$736 million in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Within the trading operation, bond trading brought in $876
million in revenue and equity trading brought about $455 million.
Within the investment banking unit, Goldman's vaunted
mergers-and-acquisitions business had revenue of $522 million,
while underwriting had revenue of $380 million.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman earned $1.3 billion on revenue of $8.5 billion for the
fiscal year that ended Nov. 30. Trading losses caused Goldman's
fourth-quarter pretax profit to fall 81 percent, to $107 million,
its worst quarter in four years, down from $567 million in the
quarter a year earlier. Those losses helped undermine Corzine's
standing at the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman also named two new directors to its board, increasing
its size to 13. The new members are Sir John Browne, chief
executive of BP Amoco PLC, and James A. Johnson, chairman of Fannie
Mae, the mortgage-financing giant.
</P>
<P>
   Signaling that the firm has faith that South Korea's economy
will strengthen, Goldman also confirmed Monday that it had agreed
to buy a 17 percent stake in Kookmin Bank, a South Korean consumer
bank once owned by the government, for about $500 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
