<SLUG> BC-CHINA-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA'S EXPORTS FALL 7.9 PERCENT IN QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ China's exports fell 7.9 percent in the first
quarter, the government said Monday in a report that illustrated a
weakness in one of the most important growth engines in the Chinese
economy. Sharp declines in exports to Europe more than offset
increased exports to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Economists are anxiously watching for signs that China's
economy, the largest in Asia behind Japan's, may stumble into the
same downward spiral that has hurt several Asian nations. A fall in
exports, in particular, could increase the pressure on China to
devalue its currency, the yuan, to help make those exports cheaper
and more competitive.
</P>
<P>
   But economists said that even with falling exports, it was
unlikely that China would devalue any time this year. A devaluation
could also force other developing countries to devalue their
currencies.
</P>
<P>
   Economists also point to other signs of economic strength in
China, notably an 11.6 percent increase in first-quarter imports
and an 8.3 percent overall economic growth rate in the
January-March period.
</P>
<P>
   The trade figures were released as business executives in China
expressed disappointment at China's failure to win entry into the
World Trade Organization, the group that makes the rules for global
commerce, during a trip to the United States by Prime Minister Zhu
Rongji. That setback was apparently caused more by politics in
Washington than by serious differences among trade negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu, Beijing's strongest advocate of dismantling China's trade
barriers, may now be vulnerable to critics in Beijing who oppose
making significant concessions that open China's markets to greater
international competition.
</P>
<P>
   But China's politics are so secretive that any diminishing of
Zhu's standing would only become evident slowly. On Monday, China's
media reported positively on the WTO negotiations, stressing
secondary agreements that were made and the commitment by
Washington and Beijing to reach agreement on China's membership in
the trade organization by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   China's fall in exports came principally from weaker demand from
Europe, Chinese officials said, citing a 9.1 percent drop in
exports to Europe in the first two months of the year. In contrast,
China's exports to the United States grew by 8.4 percent in the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``China's exports to the European Union do not look promising in
the first half of this year,'' Sun Zhenyu, deputy foreign trade
minister, said at a weekend seminar on the euro, Europe's single
currency. ``The launch of the euro has created more competition to
Chinese exports.''
</P>
<P>
   Sun said that the euro's decline against the dollar of roughly 9
percent this year depressed demand for Chinese goods in the
European Union. Southern members of the European Union that produce
goods at relatively low costs gained some price advantages over
Chinese goods.
</P>
<P>
   China's exports to neighboring countries in Asia have fallen
sharply over the last year as the Asian economic crisis has
diminished demand in countries like South Korea, Indonesia and
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   The New China News Agency reported that exports to those
countries rose in the first quarter, though the agency gave no
figures.
</P>
<P>
   For all of 1998, exports grew by just 0.5 percent, compared with
20.9 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Positive signs also lurked in the mixed economic data coming out
of China on Monday. The most notable was a 21 percent rise in March
imports, which suggested an increase in domestic demand _ evidence
of economic strength.
</P>
<P>
   Rising imports are also seen as another reason that a
devaluation of the yuan is unlikely for the time being. Those
imports include many materials for assembly into products that are
exported, so a devaluation would make those materials more
expensive for Chinese exporters to buy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
