<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5582 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-U.S.-1STLD-WRIT     04-12 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE OFFICIALS FRUSTRATED BY ADMINISTRATION'S WAVERING ON TRADE
DEAL
</HEADLINE>
  (Subs 10th graf for rewriting; subs to kill 12th graf to delete
redundancies.) 
 (sw) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ When President Clinton visited China last summer, he
and China's top leader, Jiang Zemin, held a press conference
broadcast live around China in which they discussed every sensitive
issue in U.S.-China relations, from Tibet to allegations of illegal
Chinese donations to American political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, some fellow Chinese leaders considered it perhaps
the biggest risk Jiang had taken in the decade since he assumed
Chinas top political titles, an unprecedented concession to demands
for more political openness. The Chinese public had never before
seen live broadcasts of a U.S. president, much less one debating
head-to-head with his media-shy Chinese counterpart. The
risk-taking paid off when Clinton's visit was judged a success by
both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Just 10 months later, Prime Minister Zhu Rongji has complained
at every stop on his six-city tour of the United States that
Clinton ``does not dare'' to take what he considers to be a much
smaller political risk: allowing China to join the World Trade
Organization under terms that even Clinton's own trade negotiators
considered a slam dunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know our American counterparts very well. We have been
negotiating this agreement for 13 years,'' said senior Chinese
official traveling with Zhu who had close involvement in the talks.
``When you are doing these things for so long, you know when you
have a deal. We had a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials accompanying Zhu on his visit pointed to this
asymmetry _ Jiang taking the gamble of his political life, Clinton
overruling his own staff _ as an illustration of what they see as
endless frustration in their dealings with the United States. Yes,
they say, democracies work differently from dictatorships, but that
does not justify what they perceive as Clinton's intolerable
fickleness.
</P>
<P>
   The frustration has built even as officials gush about Zhu's
visit to America. The prime minister has shown that he can stand
face to face with he best American politicians and argue
persuasively for his views, they say. He might even succeeded in
rallying public support for China's entry into the trade
organization, though some Chinese officials have been known to
overestimate the political influence that business leaders have.
</P>
<P>
   That confidence was in evidence on Monday when 1,500
businessmen, including chief executives of Motorola, United
Airlines, Bank One and a dozen other companies based in the
Midwest, gathered at a Chicago banquet for Zhu. With the prime
minister seated at the podium, several chief executives vowed their
support for China's entry as Zhu nodded in appreciation. Commerce
Secretary William Daley, in town for the occasion, also assured Zhu
that China's admission ``is not a question of if, but when.''
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials also reacted favorably to word that some 100
businessmen showed up for a White House briefing on China trade
talks on Monday. Several executives who attended complained that
the Clinton administration misread both public and congressional
sentiment when it scuttled the deal with China, according to
participants.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Galvin, Motorola's chief executive, said that
support for China's entry into the WTO has gelled enough during
Zhu's visit that he wishes the prime minister had visited
Washington at the end of his nine-day stay instead of at the
beginning. ``Then we might have a deal,'' Galvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such optimism, the damage from Clinton's wavering may
run deep. One of Zhu's top aides, likely reflecting the views of
other pro-Western officials in China's political hierarchy, said
Clinton's role in the trade talks was not unlike his decision in
1995 to bow to congressional pressure and allow President Lee
Teng-Hui of Taiwan to visit the United States. Although Lee's visit
to Cornell University, his alma mater, was billed as private,
Beijing, which views Taiwan as a renegade province, saw it as an
attempt to bolster the island's official status.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as now, Congress appeared to make China policy instead of
the White House, said this aide, who declined to be identified
further. Then, as now, Clinton intervened at the last moment and
overturned an approach that had the firm backing of his China
experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton's memory is short,'' this Chinese official said. ``Our
memory is longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that while China's foreign policy puts
relations with the United States at the top of the agenda, the
United States juggles many international priorities. It is no
coincidence, one Chinese official said, that Clinton rejected a
trade deal as the United States led the NATO assault on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration insists that China is a high
priority. But Chinese officials doubt that. The administration, for
example, has so far failed to find a suitable replacement from its
ambassador to China, James Sasser, who has made his intention of
leaving that post known for months.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The war in Yugoslavia is also a direct affront to the two major
pillars of China's foreign policy, peace and noninterference in the
internal affairs of sovereign countries. Where the United States
sees a severe humanitarian crisis, China sees the threat of foreign
intervention in Taiwan and Tibet, its own restive regions.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the biggest worry, at least among Zhu's aides, is
their fear that the Clinton administration did not appreciate the
delicate nature of the process that produced China's revised bid to
join the WTO.
</P>
<P>
   China has sought entry to the trade body for 13 years, but it
has really made only two strong pushes for membership. The first
came in 1994, when the WTO was born of its predecessor, known as
the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. The application then
came amid a rush of economic reforms. Chinese officials made GATT
the symbol of its modernization drive, only to have the United
States block entry.
</P>
<P>
   China's interest in joining the trade body, which requires
demolition of tariffs and trade barriers that shield many
inefficient sectors of its economy from outside competition, faded
in the intervening years. It was fully revived only late last year.
Then, Zhu, newly appointed prime minister, made entry into the
trade organization his personal mission.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese trade officials said that never before had a senior
Chinese leader taken an interest in the details of negotiations the
way Zhu did.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you don't have a senior leader involved in the details,
then the negotiators cannot get instructions,'' said a trade
official. ``Without Zhu, it would never have been smooth.''
</P>
<P>
   Crucially, the push to join the trade body became the symbol of
a new stage in China's reform program. Economic reforms previously
focused on agriculture and manufacturing industries. But the new
drive aimed at opening the country's undeveloped service sector _
telecommunications, banking, consulting, accounting, entertainment
and many other areas _ to both domestic and foreign competition.
</P>
<P>
   With the Asian financial crisis dragging down growth in China
and the country flooded with over-investment in unproductive
industries, the opening of services was seen as one of the few ways
to promote quality economic growth. The trade organization offered
a framework to change myriad internal Chinese rules and regulations
that keep services off limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Service sector reform and the WTO are the same thing for
China,'' said this trade official. ``We won't get one without the
other.''
</P>
<P>
   China could still get both if negotiations pick up where they
left off before Clinton pulled the plug. But the Chinese side,
while publicly indicating continued support for a deal, privately
frets that restoring momentum will be tricky.
</P>
<P>
   There are no more scheduled visits of Chinese or American senior
leaders. The Clinton administration, which the Chinese already view
as weak, may see its remaining clout to push a trade deal through
Congress only diminish as Clinton approaches the end of his term.
And, perhaps most worrying for the Chinese, trade was supposed to
be the unbreakable bond between the two countries that keeps them
talking even when military, diplomatic and human rights concerns
strain ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trade is the one area where our two interests are really in
line,'' the Chinese trade negotiator said. ``So if we don't even
agree on trade, the outlook is not so good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
