<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ABORTION-DOCTOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE DEFEND WORK IN ABORTION-CLINIC DOCTOR'S SLAYING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (af)  
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Responding to questions about why it took almost six
months to find a rifle that may have been used to kill a Buffalo,
N.Y.,-area doctor who performed abortions, law enforcement
officials defended the thoroughness of their investigation on
Monday and said metal detectors had been used soon after the
killing to scan the area around the doctor's home, though with no
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``All agencies are pursuing this case aggressively,'' said Major
Michael McManus, the troop commander of the New York State Police
in western New York and one of the few officials willing to comment
on the inquiry into the death of Dr. Barnett Slepian.
</P>
<P>
   The rifle was found on Thursday buried about a foot below the
surface in piney woods roughly 200 feet behind Slepian's residence,
where he was killed by a sniper on Oct. 23. A short statement by
law enforcement officials said that ``weather and ground
conditions'' in the days after the slaying delayed the kind of
refined search that turned up the rifle.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and neighbors of the family have asked why the rifle was
not found sooner, pointing out that last autumn was fairly warm and
dry and that heavy snowfall did not start until January. Some
independent investigators also wondered why the gun had not been
found sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're looking for a gun, it's one of the easiest things to
use a metal detector to find,'' said Michael G. Cherkasky, a former
prosecutor who is chief operating officer of Kroll Associates, a
private investigative firm.
</P>
<P>
   Replying to such comments, a federal and a state law enforcement
official, both of whom refused to be identified, said Monday that
the grounds behind the doctor's home in Amherst, N.Y., had been
thoroughly searched in the weeks after the slaying. Some of the
searches were conducted by hand, but a metal detector was also
used, they said. One of the officials said using a detector could
be a ``hit or miss'' proposition.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have not said how the rifle was found, nor have they
described it other than to say it resembled the weapon that would
have fired the caliber of bullet that killed Slepian. It has been
taken to Washington for ballistics tests.
</P>
<P>
   The contention that the authorities were diligent was partly
bolstered by the account of two of the Slepian family's neighbors,
Sandy Arno and Mary Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   They recalled that in the days after the slaying, they saw a
line of at least a dozen investigators working shoulder to
shoulder, sometimes on their hands and knees, searching the four
acres of backyards and woods behind the Slepians' house.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Arno and Mrs. Wilson do not recall seeing anyone using a
metal detector. ``It struck me as so amazing that they found
strands of hair but not a rifle because they seemed to be doing
such a thorough job,'' Mrs. Arno said. ``It seemed extremely
well-organized.''
</P>
<P>
   Slepian, the mainstay of Buffalo's only clinic still performing
abortions, was shot to death at 10 p.m. as he stood in his kitchen
talking with his wife and sons. The sniper hid in a stand of trees
about 100 feet behind the house, which is surrounded by a fenced-in
yard that encloses a swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   The rifle found on Thursday, which has not yet been positively
identified as the murder weapon, was unearthed 100 feet deeper in
the woods near one of several paths the Arnos have carved out for
walking dogs and for children to caper. Monday, the water-filled
trench created by the digging was marked by mustard-colored spray.
</P>
<P>
   An expert in metal detectors said they can be unfailingly
accurate if they are properly adjusted to seek a specific metal.
Sean Rabbani, owner of A&AMP;S Co. in Santa Clara, Calif., a large
distributor of the devices, said a detector of conventional quality
could sense metals as deep as a foot and a half below the surface,
and some can detect metal as deep as 20 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The iron or steel in a gun, he said, would require settings for
``lower discrimination'' than the quarters a beachcomber might look
for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they didn't know how to use it,'' Rabbani said. ``If I
was there I would find it in a couple of acres in eight hours.''
</P>
<P>
   The police have not yet named a suspect in the slaying, but they
have issued a warrant for the arrest of James C. Kopp as a material
witness. Kopp, who has made a practice of joining abortion protests
across the country, was seen jogging in the neighborhood in the
days before Slepian was killed.
</P>
<P>
   A federal law enforcement official said Monday that the
authorities did not know where Kopp was, and he indicated that he
did not believe reports that Kopp may have fled to Mexico.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
