u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRONGFUL-BIRTH-SUIT-C     04-12 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRONGFUL-BIRTH-SUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High court considers 'wrongful birth' suit
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Parents should be able to sue their obstetricians for
medical malpractice if doctors fail to properly diagnose birth
defects in a fetus, the Georgia Supreme Court was told Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Without proper genetic testing and counseling, a mother's right
to an abortion is infringed because she was denied the chance to be
fully informed about the health of the fetus, Atlanta lawyer Myles
Eastwood told the court during oral arguments. If obstetricians
fail to provide the standard care, they should be liable in
``wrongful birth'' lawsuits, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The high court considered a medical malpractice lawsuit filed by
Andrew and Jennifer Etkind against their obstetrician, Ramon
Suarez, who practices at Piedmont Hospital. According to the
lawsuit, Suarez did not conduct all the customary prenatal tests on
the Etkinds' fetus, born in September 1995 with Down syndrome,
brain defects and other deformities.
</P>
<P>
   The Etkinds said they would have aborted their fetus had they
known of the birth defects, and the couple wants Suarez to pay for
the extraordinary costs of raising their son. Suarez has strongly
denied allegations that his prenatal care was below standard.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years ago, the seven-member Supreme Court addressed the
wrongful birth issue, but prohibited these kinds of lawsuits,
saying the matter should be left to the Legislature. But five new
justices have since joined the court.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice Robert Benham, who was on the court in 1990 and
said at the time that wrongful birth lawsuits should be allowed,
expressed uneasiness about overturning precedent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Precedent is the court's stock and trade, allowing
predictability and certainty in the law,'' he said. ``Under what
circumstances should the court abandon that?''
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood agreed it would be ``unusual'' for the court to abandon
its precedent, but noted that 28 states now allow wrongful birth
litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta lawyer Judson Graves, who represents Suarez, urged the
court not to overturn its 1990 precedent, and he said that allowing
wrongful birth suits ``denigrates people who are genetically
inferior.''
</P>
<P>
   If the court allows wrongful birth lawsuits, obstetricians will
be more willing to perform amniocentesis on mothers who express
even the slightest concerns about the condition of a fetus, Graves
said, noting this invasive procedure can cause a miscarriage.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Norman Fletcher, who wrote the 1990 decision, said that
genetic testing is becoming so refined that in the ``not too
distant future'' doctors may be able to determine all sorts of
characteristics about the fetus.
</P>
<P>
   He asked where the courts draw the line.
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood replied that obstetricians set their own standards for
genetic counseling and care.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they violate their own standards, they should be held
actionable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The court has until early December before it has to issue a
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rankin writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 2247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990412.0471 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5586 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      04-12 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: FOR CLINTON, A JARRING LEGAL AFTERSHOCK 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CLINTON-CONTEMPT) 
(mk) 
 By JILL ABRAMSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having survived impeachment, President Clinton and his defenders
had hoped that the legal repercussions from the Monica Lewinsky
imbroglio were over. By holding Clinton in contempt on Monday,
Judge Susan Webber Wright dashed those hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Where the president has denounced congressional charges of legal
wrongdoing in the Lewinsky matter as partisan, he will have a more
difficult time dismissing Wright's ruling, which noted, in her
dispassionate and lawyerly 32-page order, that she ``takes no
pleasure whatsoever in holding this nation's president in contempt
of court.''
</P>
<P>
   In a rare show of restraint, White House lawyers and the
president's personal lawyer said they would not comment on the
ruling until they had a chance to read it.
</P>
<P>
   Because the president is the highest law-enforcement official in
the land and the nation's highest court officer, the contempt of
court finding is another embarrassing mark on Clinton's legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Although Wright said she would delay enforcement for 30 days to
give the president and his lawyers a chance to ask for a hearing or
file a notice of appeal, her ruling is more than symbolic. Clinton
has already settled the Paula Jones sexual misconduct lawsuit in
which Wright cited him for contempt, but her ruling could have
important legal and practical effects on him.
</P>
<P>
   One is monetary. Wright ordered the president to pay $1,202 to
cover her expenses for traveling to Washington for the president's
deposition in the Jones case on January 17, 1998. Ms. Jones'
lawyers may also submit their expenses connected to the deposition
for reimbursement because Wright has found that Clinton's false
testimony ``tainted'' the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling could also effect the president's future earnings, if
he ever intends to practice law in Arkansas after he leaves office.
Having found that he gave ``intentionally false'' testimony in the
Jones case and found him in contempt of court, Wright said she
would refer the matter to the Arkansas Supreme Court's Committee on
Professional Conduct. The disciplinary panel could sanction
Clinton, including moving to disbar him. The American Bar
Association's Model Rules of Professional Responsibility make it
clear that giving false testimony is misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   No other president has ever been held in civil contempt, and it
is rare for high government officials to be faced with such
charges. Last February, Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt and
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin were cited for civil contempt by
U.S. District Judge Royce Lamberth in Washington for failure to
comply with the judge's orders in a case involving Indian trusts.
</P>
<P>
   But the charges against these officials involved their
government duties, not the kind of private misconduct for which the
president was cited for giving false testimony in the Jones case.
In other lawsuits, judges have used civil contempt citations, some
with jail terms, to enforce their rulings.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's ruling came on the same day as the verdict in the
criminal contempt trial of Susan MacDougal, a former Arkansas
business partner of the Clintons. She served 18 months in jail for
civil contempt because she would not answer questions from the
office of the independent counsel, Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, in a high-profile family court case, an
investment banker was jailed for three years and cited for civil
contempt for refusing to comply with a judge's order to pay child
support.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Saltzburg, a professor of criminal law and procedure at
George Washington University Law School in Washington, said parties
to lawsuits were seldom held in civil contempt for false testimony.
More commonly, people are fined for violations of court discovery
rules.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Wright formally cited the president for contempt,
Saltzburg said, ``suggests that the violation is probably clearer
and more reprehensible than some.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she wanted to make it clear that the president flouted
the dignity of the court and insulted the court,'' Saltzburg added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 2250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
