<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5588 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-BANKS-530&AMP;ADD-     04-12 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-BANKS-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL'S STEEP RATES SQUEEZE CONSUMERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Eliana Nascimento's trip to the beaches of
Australia was her first vacation abroad. The interest rate her bank
is charging could make it her last.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other Brazilian travelers, Ms. Nascimento, a
25-year-old advertising executive, was shocked upon her return home
in mid-January. The government had just devalued the currency, the
real, so her purchases on credit in Australia almost doubled when
translated into reals.
</P>
<P>
   Her savings exhausted by the trip, she used the overdraft
privilege offered by Banco Bradesco to write a check for the
credit-card bill. That's when she got her second rude shock. The
bank had raised the interest rate on overdrafts, already high at
104 percent a year, to 140 percent, after its borrowing costs got
higher.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few weeks she got her third rude shock. Interest
rates charged to banks have declined to pre-devaluation levels. But
the banks have not passed on the lower borrowing rates to their
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They give no truce to their small clients, like me, who are
struggling right now,'' said Ms. Nascimento, whose office is a
short stroll from Avenida Paulista, a mile-long thoroughfare of
skyscrapers and futuristic billboards that symbolize Brazil's
powerful banks.
</P>
<P>
   Many Brazilians are repeating Ms. Nascimento's complaint. The
banks were quick to raise rates for customers but have been slow to
lower them.
</P>
<P>
   As gloomy prospects for the economy have subsided, the central
bank has responded by cutting its main lending rate to banks twice
in the last two weeks, from 45 percent to 39 percent, the
pre-devaluation rate. Another cut could come as soon as Tuesday or
Wednesday, with analysts expecting the rate to decline to below 35
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Although still high when compared with borrowing costs in many
other countries, this decline in interest rates here has
strengthened investor confidence in the economy and has benefited
financial institutions probably more than any other economic
sector.
</P>
<P>
   Already two of Brazil's biggest banks, Banco Bradesco and Banco
Itau, have successfully tapped borrowing markets abroad through the
sale of dollar-denominated notes, the first such transactions since
the currency was devalued in mid-January.
</P>
<P>
   The improved outlook for the economy as a whole, though, and for
banks in particular, has yet to trickle down from the boardrooms of
Sao Paulo and the bureaucratic corridors of Brasilia to many
hard-pressed people.
</P>
<P>
   Although Brazilians have lived with at least double-digit
interest rates since the beginning of an economic stabilization
program begun by President Fernando Henrique Cardoso in 1994, their
patience is waning.
</P>
<P>
   ``After taking a loan out last year, I told myself, `Never
again,''' said Ana Cecilia Ribas de Aguiar, 40, the owner of a
language school, who paid a monthly interest of 4.75 percent on her
small-business loan _ an annual rate that exceeds 60 percent. ``I
was shown how greedy banks can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ribas de Aguiar reacted by attempting to switch banks, to
see if competition would reduce her costs. But, she said,
``switching banks is like switching husbands; it's such a hassle.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The resentment expressed by Ms. Ribas de Aguiar has been
heightened because banks are one of the main fixtures of
middle-class life here. In this city, Brazil's largest and richest,
a customer's bank is often a signal of social standing.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, exclusive institutions, including foreign banks
such as Citibank and BankBoston, require a high minimum salary from
prospective customers. Other banks with more extensive branch
networks and less flashy exteriors, such as the state-owned Banco
do Brasil, have a more plebeian reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Brazilians also have to spend a large amount of their time each
month at their banks since almost all bills must be paid directly
in branches, because the postal system is not trusted for sending
personal checks. And the millions of Brazilians too poor to open a
bank account have to go to branches to cash their paychecks,
however meager they may be.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Internet is changing things somewhat, through the
introduction of online payment methods, it is still common to see
lines at banks stretch out onto the street with people waiting to
pay their rent or utility bills.
</P>
<P>
   Banks, for their part, respond to customer anger over interest
rates by suggesting that their hands are largely tied. Even if the
cost of borrowing has come down for the banks themselves since the
turmoil following the devaluation, many banks say they must
continue to charge higher rates because the economy has been
weakened and more customers could default.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the rates we charge can be punitive,'' said Antonio
Bornia, the vice chairman of Banco Bradesco, the largest bank in
Brazil that is not government-owned. ``But we're going through a
recession in which employment levels are not favorable and the risk
levels of many potential borrowers remain quite high.''
</P>
<P>
   Another banker, Rogerio Estevao, the director of products at
Unibanco, a large Sao Paulo-based bank, said: ``We have to wait and
see if this current scenario of optimism will continue. I see some
space for small declines in rates but not that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the growing resentment against banks, together with
reports of fattened profits at some institutions so far this year,
has been transformed into an issue by some legislators in Brasilia.
Following the currency devaluation, one legislator, Aloizio
Mercadante of Sao Paulo, contended that several banks used inside
information to profit from the shift in exchange-rate policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're dealing with now is a society with violence and
unemployment on the rise, while the government seems to go out of
its way to help financial institutions,'' Mercadante said in a
telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Mercadante, a member of the left-wing opposition Workers'
Party, and some of his colleagues in the Chamber of Deputies and
the Senate are pressing forward with plans for a congressional
inquiry into his charges, in addition to allegations of an
unethical, and perhaps, illegal, bailout by the central bank of two
small Rio de Janeiro investment banks. The central bank is
conducting its own investigation of the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiries into bank misbehavior are not lost on Ms.
Nascimento, the advertising executive. Now, as she struggles to pay
expenses as basic as her telephone bill, she does not know when she
will get the chance to travel outside Brazil again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I could have planned something modest, like a
weekend in Buenos Aires,'' she said. ``Now, I'm not sure if I'll
take any vacation at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
