<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-JUDGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN JUDGMENT OF A TEACHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (See related CLINTON-CONTEMPT)  
 (af)  
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Judge Susan Webber Wright found Bill Clinton
in contempt of court, she was ruling not just against the president
of the United States but against one of her former teachers.
</P>
<P>
   More than two decades ago, Susan Webber studied navigation law
under Professor Bill Clinton at the University of Arkansas School
of Law, where she was editor of the Arkansas Law Review and
graduated in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's student was also his political adversary: a
conservative Republican, she campaigned on behalf of Rep. John Paul
Hammerschmidt, whom Clinton tried to unseat in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   She was a clerk for Judge J. Smith Henley of the 8th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals, covering much of the Middle West, then
taught law at her alma mater and two other universities before
being named to the federal district court by President George Bush
in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Married to Robert R. Wright III, a prominent legal scholar,
Judge Wright, 50, has won praise in Arkansas legal circles for her
intellectual acumen and sense of fair play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think a judge should be a personality,'' she said in
an interview several years ago. ``My focus is to be fair to all
sides.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Gov. Bill Clinton appointed the judge's husband to be
the special chief justice on the Arkansas Supreme Court to review
the appeal of a conviction of a former state official.
</P>
<P>
   In previous rulings in the sexual-misconduct suit brought by
Paula Jones, Judge Wright has sided with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In a decision overturned by the U.S. Supreme Court, she ruled in
late 1994 that the trial of Ms. Jones' lawsuit should wait until
the president left office.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, she dismissed part of the suit, and on April 1, 1998,
she threw it out altogether. (Ms. Jones and the president later
reached a settlement.)
</P>
<P>
   But Monday, she handed down a decision that, if it caused
discomfort for the president, seemed to sadden the judge, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court takes no pleasure whatsoever in holding this
nation's president in contempt of court,'' she wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 2255EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990412.0474 </DOCNO>
