<HEADER>
A5620 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PULITZER-WINNERS-2TAK     04-12 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PULITZER-WINNERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIST OF PULITZER PRIZE WINNERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (With PULITZER-PRIZES) 
 (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DRAMA
</P>
<P>
   MARGARET EDSON
</P>
<P>
   ``Wit''
</P>
<P>
   It seemed somewhat unlikely dramatic fodder, but by weaving
together the sonnets of John Donne with a literature professor's
battle with ovarian cancer, Ms. Edson wrought a play which, Peter
Marks' wrote in his New York Times review, ``finds poetry in the
reading of a sonogram and science in the deconstruction of a
sonnet.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Edson, 37, is a first-time playwright and full-time
kindergarten teacher in Atlanta. (She was called out of her
classroom to the principal's office when the award was announced.)
She said that the play, which played Off Off Broadway before moving
to an Off Broadway theater, was inspired by her experiences working
in a cancer and AIDS ward in a hospital in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really about the relationship between love and
knowledge,'' she said Monday. ``And in the end, about grace.''
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL NONFICTION
</P>
<P>
   JOHN McPHEE
</P>
<P>
   ``Annals of the Former World''
</P>
<P>
   Starting in 1978, McPhee crisscrossed the United States to
gather information about the country's formation over billions of
years. The book combines his four previously published volumes on
American geology, including ``Assembling California,'' and adds a
fifth section on the American Midwest. It tells not only geological
history but the history of geology and the stories of the
scientists who have worked out the histories of rock and mountain
from the plains of Brooklyn to the San Andreas fault.
</P>
<P>
   POETRY
</P>
<P>
   MARK STRAND
</P>
<P>
   ``Blizzard of One''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Strand, who was born in Canada, is the author of nine books
of poetry. He teaches in the Committee on Social Thought at the
University of Chicago. Strand, 65, has been called a ``Platonic''
poet. His verse is spare, magisterial, his themes universal rather
than particular. Thus, in the poem that provides the title for his
prize-winning collection, a snowflake is not simply itself, but
rather a focal point for Strand's meditation on absence and death:
</P>
<P>
   From the shadow of domes in the city of domes,
</P>
<P>
   A snowflake, a blizzard of one, weightless, entered your room
</P>
<P>
   And made its way to the arm of the chair where you, looking up
</P>
<P>
   From your book, saw it the moment it landed. That's all
</P>
<P>
   There was to it. No more than a solemn waking
</P>
<P>
   To brevity, to the lifting and falling away of attention,
swiftly,
</P>
<P>
   A time between times, a flowerless funeral. No more than that
</P>
<P>
   Except for the feeling that this piece of the storm,
</P>
<P>
   Which turned into nothing before your eyes, would come back,
</P>
<P>
   That someone years hence, sitting as you are now, might say:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time. The air is ready. The sky has an opening.''
</P>
<P>
   BIOGRAPHY
</P>
<P>
   A. SCOTT BERG
</P>
<P>
   ``Lindbergh''
</P>
<P>
   Berg has written three exhaustive biographies. The first two
were of editor Maxwell Perkins and film producer Samuel Goldwyn.
For ``Lindbergh'' (G.P. Putnam's Sons), Berg spent nine years
researching the life of the pioneer aviator whose flight across the
Atlantic in 1927 made him what Berg calls ``the first modern media
superstar.'' Berg, 49, who lives in Los Angeles, found Lindbergh an
immensely complicated figure, cold and distant to his family and
tainted by words of support for Adolf Hitler, but nonetheless a
``solid-gold hero.''
</P>
<P>
   HISTORY
</P>
<P>
   MIKE WALLACE and EDWIN G. BURROWS
</P>
<P>
   ``Gotham: A History of New York to 1898''
</P>
<P>
   For two decades, Wallace and Burrows labored in the shadows with
``Gotham: A History of New York to 1898'' (Oxford University
Press). Their 1,383-page populist tale brings humor and narrative
drive to the story of New York City. Wallace is a history professor
at John Jay College of Criminal Justice; Burrows is history
professor at Brooklyn College.
</P>
<P>
   FICTION
</P>
<P>
   MICHAEL CUNNINGHAM
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hours''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Hours'' (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux), Cunningham conjures
a parallel between Virginia Woolf's ``Mrs. Dalloway'' and his own
novel, moving from a fictionalized portrait of Woolf herself in
London in the 1920s to Los Angeles in 1949 and New York in the
1990s. The theme of ``The Hours,'' a reviewer wrote in The New York
Times Book Review, is ``the haunting of present lives by memories
and books, by distant pasts and missed futures, by novels and poems
to be read and written.''
</P>
<P>
   An excerpt from ``The Hours'':
</P>
<P>
   ``It had seemed like the beginning of happiness, and Clarissa is
still sometimes shocked, more than 30 years later, to realize that
it was happiness. ... There is still that singular perfection, and
it's perfect in part because it seemed, at the time, so clearly to
promise more. Now she knows: That was the moment, right then. There
has been no other.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, who was born in Cincinnati in 1952, graduated from
Stanford University and the University of Iowa. He teaches writing
at Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   MELINDA WAGNER
</P>
<P>
   Concerto for Flute, Strings and Percussion
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wagner, a 42-year-old composer who was born in Philadelphia
and lives in Ridgewood, N.J., is an imaginative musical fantasist
who once described her accessible, inviting music as ``not really
about anything that could happen in the world, but about the
exploration and potential of ideas concerning sound.'' In her
three-movement concerto, considerable expressive variety is
demanded of the solo flute line, which is set against a sparkling,
tactile orchestral texture. The work was given its premiere by Paul
Dunkel, the flutist, with the Westchester Philharmonic on May 31,
1998.
</P>
<P>
   SPECIAL CITATION
</P>
<P>
   DUKE ELLINGTON
</P>
<P>
   On the centennial of his birth, the Pulitzer Prize Board cited
Edward Kennedy (Duke) Ellington for his indelible contribution to
art and culture through the medium of jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Duke Ellington's protean career, lasting over 50 years,
connected jazz's beginnings before the 1920s with its most modern
aspects in the 1970s. From his earliest recordings until his death
in 1974, he strengthened his command of jazz composition and
arrangement. By the 1940s, at the helm of an 18-piece band, he was
one of the most innovative and popular composers in America,
bridging the realms of dance music and sophisticated art song.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in 1943, Ellington composed a string of tone poems,
suites and sacred music, including ``Black, Brown and Beige'' and
``Such Sweet Thunder.'' His final extended pieces were the
liturgical ``Sacred Concerts.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   JOURNALISM:
</P>
<P>
   PUBLIC SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
   In its series ``Deadly Force,'' The Post concluded that District
of Columbia officers shot and killed more people per resident than
any other large city police force.
</P>
<P>
   A Post reporter suspected that the FBI collected but did not
disclose police-shooting data. Through repeated requests under the
Freedom of Information Act, the Post's computer-assisted reporting
team got the data and then analyzed it. Then reporters reviewed
previous homicides, talked to the police and prosecutors and at one
point test-fired police handguns.
</P>
<P>
   The Post concluded that shootings were so numerous because of
poor police training, hair-trigger handguns and questionable
tactics, like shooting at moving cars.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL REPORTING
</P>
<P>
   Staff of The New York Times
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times staff, notably reporter Jeff Gerth, was
honored for a series of stories disclosing the corporate sale of
American technology to China, with the approval of the U.S.
government despite national security risks.
</P>
<P>
   The Times reporters documented how the Democratic Party's newest
financial backers, high-tech entrepreneurs, had lobbied the Clinton
administration to change the rules. The series prompted
investigations and significant changes in policy.
</P>
<P>
   BREAKING NEWS REPORTING
</P>
<P>
   Staff of The Hartford Courant
</P>
<P>
   The Courant was awarded the prize for its ``clear and detailed
coverage'' of a shooting rampage in which a state lottery worker
shot four supervisors before turning the gun on himself.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the shooting, The Courant published some 13
stories accompanied by a map that traced the gunman's violent trek
through the building and a detailed timeline of events.
</P>
<P>
   Coverage also included a profile of the gunman, who had called a
Courant reporter the day before the killings.
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL WRITING
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News' Editorial Board
</P>
<P>
   The Apollo Theater on 125th Street in Harlem may once have been
``where stars are born and legends are made,'' as its motto avers.
But more recently, the historic theater has been in decay, as
editorial writers from The Daily News discovered during a visit in
March 1998, said Michael Goodwin, editor of the editorial page.
</P>
<P>
   The News' editorial board began a campaign to rescue the
theater, which is now owned by the state and run by a foundation. A
series of editorials exposing financial mismanagement at the
foundation prompted the attorney general to file a civil suit to
try to remove the board of directors, and led state officials to
take a more active role in revitalizing the landmark theater.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURE WRITING
</P>
<P>
   ANGELO B. HENDERSON
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
   Henderson, The Journal's deputy bureau chief in Detroit, read an
account of a pharmacist who shot and killed a would-be robber. He
guessed it was a man he had interviewed years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson contacted him, as well as the family of the victim.
``Two lives came to a crossroads that day,'' he said. His story was
honored for illustrating the lasting effects of crime.
</P>
<P>
   Now a senior special writer, Henderson, 36, a native of
Louisville, lives in Detroit, where he is also a deacon of his
Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   BEAT REPORTING
</P>
<P>
   CHUCK PHILIPS and MICHAEL A. HILTZIK
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Times
</P>
<P>
   As business writers for The Los Angeles Times, Philips and
Hiltzik examined corruption in the entertainment industry. They
exposed a charity sham sponsored by the National Academy of
Recording Arts and Sciences, detoxification programs illicitly run
for wealthy celebrities and a resurgence of radio payola.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL REPORTING
</P>
<P>
   Staff of The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
   The Journal staff won for its in-depth, analytical coverage of
the Russian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew T. Higgins, 41, the Moscow bureau chief, and a team of
five reporters explained what propelled Russia's crisis in a series
of front-page articles last year. Higgins has been assigned to the
Moscow bureau since July 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The stories were also written and researched by Bob Davis, 48,
who covers the White House; Steve Liesman, 35, who covers
international oil and gas industries in New York; Elizabeth W.
McKay, 37, a reporter in Moscow; Carla Anne Robbins, 45, who covers
national security issues and diplomacy, and Mark Philip Whitehouse,
32, a reporter in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   EXPLANATORY REPORTING
</P>
<P>
   RICHARD READ
</P>
<P>
   The Oregonian (Portland, Ore.)
</P>
<P>
   Read, 41, who covers international business for The Oregonian,
won for ``The French Fry Connection,'' a series last fall that, by
chronicling the journey of 20 tons of potatoes from Oregon to
Southeast Asia, documented how the Asian financial crisis
threatened the economy of the Pacific Northwest. ``The fate of of
one particular load of french fries,'' Read wrote, ``and the lives
and cultures of those who handled it, illuminates the causes and
effects of Asia's anguish the way no economic treatise ever
could.''
</P>
<P>
   INVESTIGATIVE REPORTING
</P>
<P>
   Staff of The Miami Herald
</P>
<P>
   A team of reporters on the staff of The Herald won for a series
of six articles leading to a reversal of the 1997 election of
Xavier Suarez as mayor, a post he had held from 1985 to 1993. The
reporters uncovered hundreds of fraudulent ballots including ones
from voters outside the city, voters who claimed their signatures
were forged on absentee ballots and voters who were paid $10 each.
As a result, the election was nullified by a judge, and Joe
Carolla, Suarez's opponent, was appointed mayor.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY
</P>
<P>
   MAUREEN DOWD
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Dowd, a columnist for the New York Times Op-Ed page, was
honored for her clever, cutting and irascible columns on the impact
of President Bill Clinton's affair with Monica Lewinsky. When
Kenneth Starr's report came out in September, Ms. Dowd concluded:
``These are not grounds for impeachment. These are grounds for
divorce.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dowd joined The Times as a metropolitan reporter in October
1983. She was appointed a columnist of the Times in January 1995
after serving as correspondent in its Washington bureau from August
1986.
</P>
<P>
   CRITICISM
</P>
<P>
   BLAIR KAMIN
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Tribune
</P>
<P>
   Kamin said memories of body surfing as a boy in New Jersey
inspired his six-part series on developing Chicago's lakefront.
That series helped shape the city's thinking on the future of its
lakefront parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The edge where the land meets the water is a sacred place that
everyone in a democracy deserves access to,'' Kamin said. Calling
himself a practitioner of ``activist criticism,'' Kamin, a graduate
of Amherst College and the Yale Graduate School of Architecture,
has also crusaded to improve public housing. In 1993, he
spearheaded The Tribune's national design contest for public
housing, and in 1995, he wrote a six-part series on how to create
public housing that works.
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL CARTOONING
</P>
<P>
   DAVID HORSEY
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer
</P>
<P>
   David Horsey, 47, won the Post-Intelligencer's first Pulitzer
for cartoons that focused on a tangled sexual abuse case in
Wenatchee, Wash., and the turmoil in Washington.
</P>
