<DOCNO> NYT19990412.0479 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 23:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5652 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     04-12 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 SPORTS COLUMN: NOT A CHANCE OF CONFUSING THESE TEAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The first ball was thrown out by a man who, unlike
last week's returning hero, buried his hatchet years ago. Tom
Seaver captured the poignancy of his Shea Stadium moment when he
turned to Bobby Jones, the Mets' starting pitcher, and said, ``Who
would have thought that two guys from Fresno would have been
standing out on the mound on opening day?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I laughed,'' Jones said dryly, obviously overcome by Seaver's
cosmic disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   From one home opener to another, the Mets' was windblown family
entertainment to the Yankees' quixotic, theatrical drama. In the
Bronx last Friday, George Steinbrenner's team had Yogi Berra to
assume his rightful role as the greatest living Yankee, Joe Torre
to receive prayers and Joe DiMaggio to be mourned. The Mets of Fred
Wilpon and Nelson Doubleday had Seaver to bounce his first pitch to
the injured Mike Piazza, Buddy Harrelson to stop by the press box
and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani to fake being their fan.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees raised another championship flag. The Mets put Rick
Reed, their No. 2 starter, on the disabled list. The Yankees played
under an appropriately somber sky, in a persistent, divine rain. On
an otherwise cheerful afternoon, the Mets were sent fleeing from
their clubhouse by a burst water pipe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they didn't spend too much on the renovation,'' said
Bobby Bonilla, who had three breakout hits in his return to New
York and still had to deal with a postgame stink.
</P>
<P>
   ``They,'' meaning ownership, didn't spend as much as was
sacrificed on the lineup's redecoration. The Mets did beat the
five-and-dime Florida Marlins, but you could argue that the day's
most compelling human interest was the appearance of a Yankee,
Orlando Hernandez. El Duque sat in a box behind home plate, where
he watched Livan _ his half-brother, who preceded him out of Cuba
and into the World Series by a full season _ inspire no notions of
perfection in the four and two-thirds innings it took for him to
help the Mets to a 5-1 lead on the way to an 8-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   This potential tear-jerker of a tale died when Livan was run
from the mound and El Duque quickly departed the park. For the
record, Mets manager Bobby Valentine said he was deeply moved when
his pinch-hitter, the rookie Mike Kinkade, doubled in the eighth
inning for his two first major league runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   By then, everyone was smiling in the Mets' dugout, if not in the
clubhouse, because other than the news of Reed's slight tear to his
calf muscle and a couple of balls that blew over Rickey Henderson's
head, opening day was a showcase for the Mets, those old (Bonilla),
new (Robin Ventura, who had a two-run double and excelled
defensively at third), borrowed (Henderson, who stole his first
Shea base as a Met and even caught a ball in left) and blue
(Valentine, whose office took the brunt of the sixth-inning flood).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all so nice and new and pristine,'' Valentine sighed.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it. The Mets were just not going to open like the
Yankees, and it's doubtful they have the capability to close like
the defending World Series champions, either. On a more optimistic
note, if New York is going to be treated to a competitive baseball
summer, it is far more likely to occur in Queens, where the Mets
could finally make a run at the Braves for their division and
should be no worse off than right in the middle of the wild-card
chase.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza is already on the disabled list for a couple of weeks,
but, no problem, the early competition has been the Marlins and
Montreal Expos, teams whose combined payrolls (roughly $36 million)
are slightly more than half of the Mets' $63.5 million. Then there
is Bonilla, purporting to be the wise old hand who has endured
through the capriciousness of four New York summers, who has
returned to advise those who have not so endured to block out the
noise (though not by literally plugging up their ears).
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're going pretty good, they'll cheer you on,'' Bonilla
said. ``When you're going pretty bad, they'll get all over you. I
understand it. I'm trying to convince the other guys of that.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first tour in town, Bonilla began with a smile that soon
turned sour. He tried to carry a load that he could not. He once
threatened a reporter by telling him, ``I'll show you the Bronx,''
his home borough. The Bronx may have tough neighborhoods, but it
also happens to be where baseball begins with pathos and panache.
Shea is where tender moments are few and they are drowned out by
ascending jets and bursting pipes. At least it's not Fresno.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
