<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5688 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOS-FASHION-ART-NYT &LR;      04-12 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOS-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH OF SEVENTH, OR OFF THE MAP? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Outside the Puck Building in SoHo last week, a couple
of photographers were lolling around when one, an old guy with the
alert expression of a trauma nurse, spied a young woman coming
through the downtown crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly he was alive, crouching low to snap her leather sandals
and then rising to capture the full bohemian length of her: the
long gray dress made of sweatshirt fabric, the old Levi's jacket
with its sleeves hacked off, the blond hair wound around a piece of
wood _ a twig _ with a clump of knotted leather streaming down her
back like a jungle vine.
</P>
<P>
   She looked utterly oblivious of the man. But he was in heaven.
At last! Something novel to photograph.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Puck Building, it was a different story. South of
Seventh, the alternative fashion camp that sprang up last year to
promote budding talent, was showing the fall collections of 30
designers.
</P>
<P>
   That the presentation came six weeks after the major New York
shows ended was only part of the problem. With the exception of
Geoffrey Beene and Joan Vass, Seventh Avenue veterans who had
chosen not to show in February, and Russell Simmons' Phat Farm
label, the names during the three days of shows, which ended
Friday, were scarcely recognizable.
</P>
<P>
   Who were Joseph Israel, Elena Bajo, Eduardo Lucero and Ann
Hitchcock? Who was anybody?
</P>
<P>
   The South of Seventh organizers had obviously gone to a great
deal of trouble to create a hip atmosphere in which to coax
interest, and ultimately sales, out of store buyers and editors.
There was a lounge area with modern sofas, and a couple of bars
selling sandwiches and cappuccino.
</P>
<P>
   But by late Wednesday _ after Israel's ``She Blinded Me With
Science'' collection, with its uninspired nylon cutout skirts, and
Carla Westcott's rhinestone cowboy revue, in which she handed out
sacks of Southern snack food, including Big Mama pickled sausages _
it seemed clear the organizers had overestimated the audience's
good will.
</P>
<P>
   After all, many in this crowd had just come off nearly a month
of European shows. They had seen some wildly inventive clothes from
designers in weird places, showing without sponsorship, and
certainly without cappuccino. And with New York crawling with young
talent, the fashion pros would hardly feel benevolent just because
the designers were earnestly struggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point in the game they have to be extraordinary,''
said Julie Gilhart, the vice president for fashion merchandising at
Barneys New York, as she waited between shows. ``Because, by now,
we've seen everything.''
</P>
<P>
   With a handful of exceptions, the clothes were much less
individual than what was going on in the streets. Outside, the
young women looked serenely unencumbered by fashion. They had on
T-shirts, sexy little trousers, things that looked homemade.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, Fiona Walker showed some delightful hand-knit sweaters,
with loopy fringe, and Margie Tsai casually mixed structured
clothes, like a pony jacket over jersey separates. Yet one couldn't
help feeling that they were designing in a vacuum and that these
clothes had more in common with a design school exercise than with
what flesh-and-blood women were wearing.
</P>
<P>
   Once Gabriella Zanzani's show settled down, there were signs of
strong tailoring _ and good eye for detail _ but her attempts to
manipulate her silhouette by bunching and crimping the fabrics
looked pointless.
</P>
<P>
   Eduardo Lucero is one who obviously does know his customers. His
clothes display a hard, sexy drive, with just a dash of vulgarity,
which has brought him a following in Los Angeles. (Drew Barrymore
wore one of his dresses to the Oscars last month.) Working in a
subdued palette of olive, burgundy, brown and black, Lucero uses
sharp tailoring to convey his modern message. Pantsuits, some in
shimmering pinstripes, snuggle over loose, asymmetrical tops or
shells. Lucero's clothes don't immediately suggest an identifiable
style, leaving his customers room to inject their own.
</P>
<P>
   Elena Bajo opened her show with a couple of nude dancers and a
pair of artists nonchalantly painting their canvases in the
background. Predictably, the naked dancers _ ``nekkid,'' as Big
Mama the sausage queen might say _ produced snickers.
</P>
<P>
   While the artists dabbed away at their paintings (one of them
looked like an abstract shark), models cavorted in Ms. Bajo's airy
knits, which wrapped and draped around the body. And though it was
distracting to look at so many unclothed bodies _ at one point four
men and women, all naked, were doing a kind of maypole dance around
a guy holding a candle _ Ms. Bajo's clothes artfully evoked a
similar freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, after Ms. Bajo's show, one of the young models appeared
in a black halter top with strands of leather across the back and a
cotton wrap skirt. When asked who designed her skirt, the girl
looked bored and replied snippily, ``I made it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ann Hitchcock made her clothes, too, using an old Singer sewing
machine, four ancient dress forms and a razor blade. Ms. Hitchcock,
30 and exuberant, with deep red hair, who describes her life until
recently as that of a quintessential slacker from Austin, Texas,
has almost no design training. Yet her clothes, with free-form
draping, minimal stitching and fraying edges, were the most
imaginative at the shows.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hitchcock readily admits she was influenced by
deconstruction. ``Martin Margiela, Yohji Yamamoto, Ann
Demeulemeester,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hitchcock buys remnants (``I'm a 99-cent-table girl,'' she
said) and drapes and sews them directly on a form, often leaving
the loose threads hanging. As she spoke, a buyer from Patricia
Field, the downtown boutique, approached and said she wanted to
place an order. Ms. Hitchcock's eyes popped open like Texas stars.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it would be a mistake to assume that this young creator sees
herself as anything other than a round peg in a square world. The
next day, while she slashed a piece of cotton jersey and
transformed it in minutes into a T-shirt for a model, Ms. Hitchcock
said she had no desire to ``be the next Calvin Klein.'' When it was
suggested that she might apprentice herself to one of her muses,
she vehemently shook her head.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would inhibit my style,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
