<HEADLINE>
ICE WON'T CHILL RACIAL COMMENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NHL has received well-justified negative publicity on
several occasions the last couple of years for slurs by white
players against the league's few black players.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, San Jose's Bryan Marchment called Vancouver's
Donald Brashear, who is black, ``a big monkey.'' Marchment admitted
making the remark, apologized, said he calls all large opponents
``big monkeys'' regardless of race, and served a one-game
suspension.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of this episode of epic ignorance, there was a
broadcast report last week that the NHL was concerned about another
form of on-ice ethnocentrism: English Canadians making derogatory
remarks to their French-Canadian countrymen.
</P>
<P>
   An NHL spokesman denied that the league was concerned, and based
on a small sampling of French-Canadian Kings, it appears
anti-French comments on the ice are fairly infrequent, though no
more defensible than slurs against any other minority.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have been (slurred this season), I didn't hear it,'' Luc
Robitaille said. ``But I did call a few French guys `frogs.' They
look at me like, `What the hell?' You've got to find the limit of
what you say. There's no place for racial comments. But I'd rather
have a guy yell comments at me than hit me with a stick over the
head.''
</P>
<P>
   Ian Laperriere said, ``Once in awhile, you're going to hear
`frog.' Until I know what it means, I won't get upset. I'm still
trying to figure out what it means. I know it's a green animal, a
reptile. I laugh at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Winger Donald Audette said the number of anti-French comments on
the ice has decreased in recent seasons, perhaps because of greater
overall sensitivity resulting from the presence of a growing number
of blacks and other minorities in the game the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   When he hears a derisive comment, Audette said, ``It comes
through one ear and goes out the other one. They're the ones who
look stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the players downplay the impact the remarks have on them,
the French-English issue has long been a serious one in Canada.
When he played in the NHL from 1966-67 to 1981-82, Kings vice
president Rogie Vachon said comments were fairly frequent.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he dealt with it, Vachon said, ``You'd concentrate on
the game, and besides, I played with a lot of big French-Canadian
players. I just had to tell one of my French-Canadian defensemen
what was said, and they took care of business. . . . There's no
room for that. We're going into the 2000th century. Everybody
should be above that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   __ World Wide Web: Obviously not realizing the comments could
come back to haunt him, Pittsburgh's Jaromir Jagr criticized coach
Kevin Constantine in a recent interview with the Czech newspaper MF
Dnes. Jagr's quotes subsequently popped up, translated into
English, on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the way (Constantine) prepares the team and I'm
not the only one among the players,'' Jagr told the Prague-based
daily. ``His communication with us is just awful. Either he yells
at us or he just hides somewhere. Right now, it's just impossible
to talk to him.''
</P>
<P>
   When a Pittsburgh writer told Jagr he'd seen the quote, the
NHL's leading scorer reacted with surprise and embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   Constantine's reaction?
</P>
<P>
   ``Those (comments) are water under the bridge as far as I'm
concerned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Angry Oilers:The Edmonton Oilers were fuming when Colorado
goalie Patrick Roy twice tried to shoot the puck into an empty net
in the final minute of a recent victory by the Avalanche. What
upset them was that Roy skated far out of his net into the corner
to chase a loose puck with a two-goal lead, all so he could bid for
the first goal of his 14-year career.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wants to be a forward,'' coach Ron Low asked, ``why
shouldn't we be able to hit him?''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant coach Ted Green added, ``He's got an ego bigger than
the Goodyear blimp.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Cutting Edge: Calgary defenseman Steve Smith probably wonders
why he came out of retirement this year.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 35, was injured last week when the skate blade of Toronto
forward Ladislav Kohn sliced open the side of his throat, narrowly
missing his jugular vein. Kohn's skate severed a nerve in Smith's
neck, causing him to lose all feeling on the right side of his
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a plastic surgeon do some microsurgery on the
nerves,'' Smith said calmly. ``The whole side of my head, I can't
feel. They said it would be a year before the feeling would return.
I can't feel my ear. I can't feel anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith wanted to play six nights later but was told he'd risk
permanent loss of feeling if he was re-injured. &QL; 
BLUE LINES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ MR. ZERO: Former King Byron Dafoe last week became the first
Boston Bruins goalie with 10 or more shutouts in a season when he
blanked the Montreal Canadiens. Since the NHL began its era of
expansion in 1967-68, it has been a rare feat:
</P>
<P>
   SHUTOUTS GOALIE TEAM SEASON
</P>
<P>
   15 Tony Esposito Blackhawks 1969-70
</P>
<P>
   13 Dominik Hasek Sabres 1997-98
</P>
<P>
   12 Bernie Parent Flyers 1973-74
</P>
<P>
   12 Bernie Parent Flyers 1974-75
</P>
<P>
   10 Tony Esposito Blackhawks 1973-74
</P>
<P>
   10 Ken Dryden Canadiens 1976-77
</P>
