<SLUG> BC-AURORA-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: AURORA AIMS TO TAKE THE HO-HUM OUT OF ITS BRANDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mo., Ohio)  (lb) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is Aurora the dawn of a new day for some venerable brands?
</P>
<P>
   The brands are the subjects of an ambitious reclamation project
by Aurora Foods Inc. of San Francisco, which was formed to
rejuvenate familiar though fading products that were pantry
mainstays when the big star named Marilyn was Monroe not Manson.
</P>
<P>
   The brands, acquired by Aurora when they were sold off, spun off
or cast off by larger marketers like Procter &AMP; Gamble, Quaker Oats
and Unilever, include Duncan Hines baking mixes, Log Cabin and Mrs.
Butterworth's syrups, Aunt Jemima and Celeste frozen foods, and
frozen-fish products under the Mrs. Paul's and Van de Kamp's names.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy is to stimulate sales by significantly increasing
the duration and budgets of advertising and promotional campaigns,
particularly through such highly visible steps as returning the
brands to television, while expanding product offerings by adding
flavors, varieties and packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are great American icon brands, like old friends,'' said
Tom Hall, chairman and chief executive officer at Ogilvy &AMP; Mather
Chicago, the agency for the Aurora syrups. ``It's amazing how
quickly they can come back to life.''
</P>
<P>
   Aurora's plans are emblematic of marketers' willingness to try
awakening tired old brands, especially in an economic boom, when
consumers will spend freely for products priced higher than store
brands or generics.
</P>
<P>
   Others embarked on similar efforts include Pepsico Inc., for the
Cracker Jack snack brand; Keebler Co., for the Sunshine and Famous
Amos lines of cookies and crackers, and Vlasic Foods International,
for grocery brands like Vlasic pickles and Swanson frozen meals.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the recession of the early 1990s has left shoppers more
skeptical than ever, determined to embrace only the brands they
deem to deliver value. Products they decide are played out or no
longer relevant will be consigned to a Madison Avenue branch of
Valhalla.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Favorite Brands International, which markets
products including marshmallows and caramels once sold under the
Kraft name, is reorganizing under Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brands have life cycles,'' said Hall, whose agency is part of
the Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide unit of WPP Group PLC, ``and there
are brands whose cycles have run out.''
</P>
<P>
   In those cases, he added, a revival ``doesn't work at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Aurora executives believe their brands are ripe for
restoration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an elegantly simple formula,'' said Tony Bevilacqua,
executive vice president for sales and marketing for the VDK Frozen
Foods division of Aurora in St. Louis. ``We revitalize brands by
investing in advertising and improvements, putting products in
front of people that better meet their needs.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the Mrs. Paul's and Van de Kamp's frozen seafood
brands are being broadened with baked and flavored varieties and
are being promoted with TV commercials, print ads and cents-off
coupons. There are also larger portions and larger packages of
products like Mrs. Paul's Select Cuts and Van de Kamp's Tenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to see the brands sparking to what consumers
consider value added,'' said Stacey Goldman, group account director
at Louis London Advertising and Sales Promotion in St. Louis, which
recently added advertising duties to its sales promotion
assignments for Aurora.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did a couple of store stops the other day to see the new
packaging,'' she added, ``and it was nice to see we had been
shopped.''
</P>
<P>
   The division of Aurora overseeing nonfrozen foods is working on
similar projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are products that are still very well known, just not
marketed,'' said Gary Willett, executive vice president at the
Columbus, Ohio, office of Aurora that is responsible for dry
groceries.
</P>
<P>
   ``They became noncore brands for their parents, which started to
pull advertising and stopped product initiatives,'' he added. ``Our
job is to reverse all that.''
</P>
<P>
   So for the syrups there are new flavors and new packages,
including premium-priced glass bottles for Log Cabin, aimed at
adults, and plastic squeeze bottles with drip-proof caps for Mrs.
Butterworth's, aimed at children. And ad budgets that dwindled to
virtually nothing have been increased to $5 million for 1998 and
$10 million for 1999, enabling the brands to come back onto TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tremendous legitimization through prime-time
television,'' Hall of Ogilvy Chicago said. ``It's a potent,
powerful weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   N.W. Ayer &AMP; Partners in New York, part of MacManus Group, is
using that same weapon for Duncan Hines, creating a campaign
carrying the theme ``You're why I bake.''
</P>
<P>
   The ads have shifted from a previous product-driven focus to
``connecting with the emotional feelings of baking for family,
friends and neighbors,'' said Mary Beth Casey, chief executive at
Ayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned from research that we can convince people to bake
more often,'' she added, ``and invite in people who haven't made
baking a part of their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If Aurora sees the opportunity in brands it believes had or
have strong equity that could be parlayed into stronger
presences,'' Ms. Casey said, ``we'd like to participate.''
</P>
<P>
   Aurora executives have a shopping list of ``well-established
brands that could be nurtured a little bit better,'' Willett said,
citing as an example the Cream of Wheat cereal line sold by a unit
of RJR Nabisco Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Next on a very special episode of ``Supermarket Sweep'': nature
vs. nurture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
