<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEE-STADIUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM STEINBRENNER, A TRIPLE PLAY FOR FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After 13 years of agitating about a move to Manhattan
or New Jersey, George Steinbrenner III, the principal owner of the
New York Yankees, has now publicly expressed interest in keeping
the team in the Bronx but has also extended his requests for
government investment in a new stadium to include not only the
state and the city but the federal government as well.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief comment in this week's issue of Crain's New York
Business that was expanded upon Monday by his spokesman,
Steinbrenner suggested that city, state and federal officials
develop a comprehensive plan for revitalizing the area surrounding
Yankee Stadium in the South Bronx, including improvements to
schools and transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who had strongly advocated building a
stadium for the Yankees on the West Side of Manhattan, hailed
Steinbrenner's willingness to remain in the Bronx. ``If the end
result is that the Yankees want to stay in the Bronx, that is the
best possible result for me and for the city and for everyone
else,'' Giuliani said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, who was at Shea Stadium for the New York Mets' home
opener against the Florida Marlins, portrayed Steinbrenner's change
of heart as a renewed interest in a plan by the administration to
build a new stadium and baseball ``village'' in the South Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``The model that we are talking about is a model that we
presented to him,'' said Giuliani, explaining that the city, the
state and the Yankees had contributed equally to the model's costs.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor did not mention the political opposition that had
grown around a West Side stadium from Republicans like Gov. George
Pataki and Democrats like the City Council speaker, Peter Vallone.
</P>
<P>
   Elaborating on Steinbrenner's comments, his spokesman, Howard
Rubenstein, said: ``George Steinbrenner most recently said if the
federal, state and city governments will come to him and the
Yankees with a plan to revitalize that area in the Bronx and not
just a new Yankee Stadium, he would seriously consider it. And when
he talks about revitalization, he is talking about possible retail
outlets, entertainment center, transportation, highway access, a
vast variety of things that will impact favorably on that
borough.''
</P>
<P>
   Such developments would most closely resemble a plan proposed by
the Bronx borough president, Fernando Ferrer, who has long
maintained that the Yankees should remain in their historic home.
But meeting Steinbrenner's current requests would require
substantially more planning, including the involvement of federal
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Some of that planning has already begun. Since the fall,
Steinbrenner has been involved in discussions with Rep. Charles
Rangel, a Harlem Democrat, about the possibility of using federal
empowerment-zone statutes to transform the area around 161st
Street, where the stadium is located.
</P>
<P>
   Rubenstein said Steinbrenner was seeking not just government
money but assurances that the project could be completed. ``It has
to be a plan that demonstrates where the financing would come from
and who would be in charge of doing it,'' Rubenstein said. ``He
wants the government to be very specific on a wide-ranging basis
about the Bronx. He wants to see not only what a plan would be but
how it could and would be executed. He is concerned that if an
election comes and goes, suddenly the plan doesn't materialize.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Monday, Ferrer praised Steinbrenner's remarks.
``I think it's a very positive first step,'' he said. ``We are
getting there. It is an acknowledgment, I think, that there isn't
an economic rationale for being in New Jersey and there isn't any
political support for a West Side stadium. The mayor found that out
very dramatically last year.''
</P>
<P>
   The team's lease at Yankee Stadium, which is owned by the city,
expires in 2002. While Steinbrenner had long kept city and state
officials guessing by threatening to move the team to New Jersey,
that possibility was essentially squelched by a recent business
agreement linking the Yankees to the New Jersey Nets basketball
franchise, which is seeking money from New Jersey to build a new
arena in Newark and would not want the Yankees lobbying for state
money for a new stadium at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said Monday that a stadium project in the Bronx could
end up costing more than a stadium on the West Side. ``It makes the
most sense for the Yankees to stay in the Bronx from an emotional
standpoint, and because that's the house that Ruth built and it has
tremendous history and that alone has tremendous value,'' he said.
``It may end up costing more but it will end up having lots of
benefits.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
