<HEADLINE>
RAINOUT SPURS SOME CHANGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Arizona's Randy Johnson vs. the Dodgers' Kevin Brown
was an intriguing opening-day matchup, but rain KO'd Thursday's
proposed rematch.
</P>
<P>
   However, Dodgers manager Davey Johnson's decision to push back
his starters a day _ thanks to Sunday's rainout against Colorado _
presented a pair of equally interesting matchups.
</P>
<P>
   Chan Ho Park, accused by Arizona players of throwing at Matt
Williams last week, got to pitch against the Diamondbacks on Monday
at Bank One Ballpark. This means Dodgers right-hander Kevin Brown's
next start will come Friday in San Diego, against the team he led
to the World Series six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, Brown didn't seem to care either way. He said he'll
discard the emotion of facing the Padres and returning to the city
in which he helped rejuvenate baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just another game,'' said Brown, who was asked whether
he'll be jeered or cheered in San Diego. ``I have no idea. It can't
affect me one way or the other. I can't worry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Davey Johnson pushed his starters back a day,
right-hander Darren Dreifort will oppose Randy Johnson in
Thursday's series finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally there would be somebody you want to bump, but this
isn't a normal rotation,'' Davey Johnson said . ``I'm going to do
everything I can to keep things in a normal rotation.''
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson did say he would most likely bump pitchers when the
Dodgers are off April 22 and 26.
</P>
<P>
   __ Cadaret free: Time lapsed and no one called the Dodgers for
pitcher Greg Cadaret, meaning the left-hander is a free agent. The
club gave Cadaret his unconditional release Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he will be paid for it. The Dodgers, who designated
Cadaret for assignment last Sunday, signed the veteran to a
guaranteed $375,000 contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called that an early-winter insurance policy to make sure
we had plenty of left-handers for Davey to chose from,'' general
manager Kevin Malone said. ``Who would have thought (Onan) Masaoka
would have earned a spot?''
</P>
<P>
   Cadaret thinks he can pitch in the big leagues so he refused the
Dodgers' minor-league assignment. But Cadaret's agent, Barry
Meister, said there haven't been any takers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really just started reviewing his options,'' Meister said.
``We're just trying to get a sense of who's interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Dodgers unconditionally released minor-league pitcher
Arnold Gooch, who was acquired in the Todd Hundley trade.
</P>
<P>
   __ Mondesi honored: Dodgers right fielder Raul Mondesi was named
the National League Player of the Week for the period April 4-11.
Mondesi hit four homers and drove in 10 runs while batting .381 and
having a .500 on-base percentage. Each of Mondesi's homers either
tied the game or gave the Dodgers the lead.
</P>
<P>
   __ Quick hitters . . . and pitchers: Former Milwaukee Brewer and
Hall of Famer-to-be Robin Yount threw out the first pitch for the
Diamondbacks' home opener, and he threw it right over the backstop
_ albeit on purpose. Nobody came out to catch the ceremonial pitch.
. . . Arizona activated right fielder Tony Womack (broken wrist)
before the game and he made an immediate impact. He robbed Devon
White of a homer in the top of the first inning. . . . In their
second season, the Diamondbacks didn't sell out the opener until
Monday morning. . . . The Dodgers' sported ``Los Angeles'' across
their uniforms for the first time since 1970.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
