<HEADLINE>
A MOUNTAIN OF TROUBLE FOR HILL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Ken Hill is a confused pitcher right now.
</P>
<P>
   Hill had his second consecutive poor start Monday, giving up
five runs and five hits. But most telling was his seven walks in
only four-plus innings.
</P>
<P>
   That the Angels offense came up big in a 13-5 win didn't make
Hill forget that he's got some work to do. He was so confused on
the mound Monday that in the fourth and fifth innings, he tried
going back to his old windup, something he abandoned last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was searching, trying to find something, find some rhythm,''
he said. ``Right now I'm (messed) up in terms of mechanics. I'm
worried about doing this, doing that. Until I get comfortable, I've
got to find a way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had taken an 8-3 lead in the top of the fifth, and in
the bottom of the inning Hill faced Rafael Palmeiro, who walked on
four pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to let him hit the ball,'' Hill said. ``Basically
I was trying to lay it right in there and I couldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   __ A no-show: The visiting clubhouse had a cubicle set up for
center fielder Jim Edmonds. His uniform was there, his shoes, cap
and batting gloves.
</P>
<P>
   Only there was no Jim Edmonds.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he expected Edmonds to show up sometime during the
four-game series against the Rangers to take batting practice and
be ready to join the lineup Wednesday in Oakland when he's eligible
to come off the disabled list. Now, Collins doesn't know what to
think.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's coming,'' Collins said, ``because I haven't
been told. I have no idea (when Edmonds will be activated).''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds is on the DL with a strained groin and a cyst in his
right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   __ Behind the plate: Todd Greene got his first start at catcher
in a major-league game since Aug. 20, 1997. Shoulder problems had
kept him out, but he got a chance to test it early in Monday's
game.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' Tom Goodwin, one of the best basestealers in the
game, led off the first inning with a walk and tried to steal
second. Greene's throw sailed into center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball just slipped,'' Greene said. ``I did that two or
three times in spring training because I was trying to be too quick
and I didn't get a good grip on the ball. I was laughing. Maybe
I'll make one of those blooper videos.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene said he threw the ball despite not having a good grip on
it because he didn't want anyone to think he was afraid to throw it
and test his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Greene caught six innings and was replaced by Charlie O'Brien to
start the seventh. No other Rangers baserunner tried to steal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
