<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5735 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-1STLD     04-12 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON PLANS TO ADD 300 PLANES TO BATTLE YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to refocus on probability of Pentagon
approving more planes, reserves being called up; ADDS details on
deployment of added planes, background throughout; trims material
from bottom; story now in two takes.) 
 (ac) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon plans to approve the deployment of 300
additional warplanes in the fight against Yugoslavia, deepening
American involvement so significantly that President Clinton will
almost certainly have to call up reserves for the first time,
senior officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The added planes, which were requested by NATO's supreme
commander, Gen. Wesley K. Clark, would increase the number of
American and NATO aircraft committed to the campaign to nearly
1,000. That is more than double the number _430 _ that the alliance
had on hand when it began the strikes on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's request would increase the American contribution by 60
percent, from nearly 500 to 800.
</P>
<P>
   With the expansion, the Air Force would need to rely on
reservists to provide crews for the aircraft, particularly the
aerial refuelers, a senior defense official said. Until now, the
only reservists involved in the campaign are those who volunteered.
</P>
<P>
   Although Pentagon and NATO officials have portrayed the raids on
Yugoslavia as successful, despite foul weather, the rapid buildup
underscores the limits of their effects on Yugoslavia's forces.
With the Clinton administration and NATO still adamantly ruling out
the use of ground forces, Clark's sole option is to intensify air
power.
</P>
<P>
   And as the air campaign moves into its third week, NATO
commanders have expressed their frustration at the Serbian military
force's entrenched, elusive positions. In recent days, NATO and
Pentagon officials have tried to prepare the public for several
weeks more of air strikes, a campaign that military officials
insist can cripple the Serb military over a sustained period of
time. In Brussels Monday, at the first gathering of NATO foreign
ministers since the bombing began, they pledged to keep up the air
attacks but at the same time searched for the shape of a political
settlement in Kosovo and urged Russia to be part of it.
</P>
<P>
   Clark made his request two days after the Pentagon announced
that it had approved an earlier request for 82 more planes,
including F-16's, which are designed to destroyed air-defenses, and
refuelers. The officials declined to provide a full breakdown of
the numbers and types of aircraft in his latest request but said
they included both combat and support planes, including F-15's and
A-10's designed to go after targets on the ground and still more
refuelers. The United States had already committed about 10 percent
of its fighter force to the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to focus more heavily on the Yugoslav army and
special police forces on a 24-hour basis,'' the senior defense
official said, speaking on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon needs to work out many details about the added
planes, including where to base them. Bases in Italy, from which
most of the strikes are being carried out, are increasingly
overcrowded. NATO is considering bases in other countries,
including the Czech Republic, France, Germany and Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   The planes requested last week are just starting to be moved
overseas. If approved, the roughly 300 aircraft could be under
Clark's command in a week.
</P>
<P>
   Although clouds have again hampered strikes, NATO carried out
new air raids Monday night, striking refineries in the city of Novi
Sad in northeast Serbia and at Pancevo, not far from the capital,
Belgrade, according to the Yugoslav news agency. There were also
reports of explosions in Pristina, the provincial capital of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As they have in response to recent strikes, Yugoslav air
defenses mounted an intensifying challenge to aircraft, although
NATO has not lost a warplane since an F-117 stealth fighter was
shot down more than two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Defense William Cohen said Monday that NATO
aircraft had achieved ``tactical maneuverability'' over Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This allows us to fly where we want and when we want with
acceptable risk,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   The weakening of Yugoslav air defenses is what has enabled Clark
to envision widening the strikes, the officials said. Clark
signaled his plans last week in an interview at NATO's military
headquarters in Mons, Belgium, saying Yugoslavia remained a potent
enemy with ``many, many targets'' still to be hit.
</P>
<P>
   A third of the additional aircraft are aerial tankers, KC-10's
and KC-135's. During the strikes, the tankers have flown in loops
over the Adriatic Sea, allowing the fighter and attack jets to dart
into Yugoslavia, return to refuel and then return for more strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some recent days of foul weather, the number of combat
missions flown each night _ or what military officials call
``strike packages'' _ has steadily increased over the last week.
There are now as many as nine a night, from an average of four or
five, the senior defense official said.
</P>
<P>
   The increase is clearly intended to have a psychological effect,
as well as a military one, signaling NATO's resolve to inflict
still more damage even as efforts to find a diplomatic solution
begin.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and other NATO powers are increasing other
forces on the ground around Yugoslavia. Pentagon officials said
Monday that 4,800 Army soldiers are now expected to accompany the
two dozen Apache helicopter gunships to Albania.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon had initially said the Apaches would be accompanied
by only 2,000 troops. A senior Army official said the growing
number of troops reflected concerns about security in northern
Albania, which is close to the Yugoslav border, as well as the
difficulty of creating a base for the helicopters in Albania, which
is Europe's least developed country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going into Albania, the middle of nowhere, with no
infrastructure,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The rapid growth in the force that will accompany the Apache
helicopters has also contributed to their slow deployment. A week
after NATO approved their use, officials have said it could take a
month before the full force is ready to strike, though Monday they
said at least some helicopters could be ready within the next seven
to 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   Britain is also expected to announce that it plans to send
another 2,000 to 3,000 troops _ along with 20 tanks and 50 armored
personnel carriers _ to the NATO force it leads in Macedonia, a
NATO diplomat said. That force, originally the vanguard of a
planned peacekeeping force in Kosovo, now totals about 12,000
troops. Most of them are involved in providing aid to the thousands
of Albanians driven from their villages in Kosovo by the campaign
of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's armed forces have heavily fortified their positions
throughout Kosovo, according to NATO and Pentagon officials, and
this is complicating efforts to destroy tanks and other armored
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Aerial photographs have confirmed reports from refugees fleeing
Kosovo that Yugoslav forces are laying mines along Kosovo's
borders, digging trenches and building bunkers, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the United States and NATO continue to rule out the use
of ground forces against Yugoslavia, the fortification suggested
that the military and armed police forces in Kosovo have shifted
their tactics from a campaign to drive Kosovo Albanians from their
homes to a consolidation of their gains as NATO has pressed its air
and missile strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen various signs of hunkering down,'' a Defense
official said. ``There's been new mining. There are new bunkers.''
</P>
<P>
   Another American official with access to intelligence reports
said the Yugoslav Army had dug in along both major routes into the
country from Macedonia, apparently in preparation for an invasion
from NATO troops. The entrenchment of forces was reported on the
road from the Macedonian capital, Skopje, into Kosovo and on the
road from Macedonia to Nis, which is in Serbia proper.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon also released aerial photographs showing armored
vehicles parked in the middle of two villages, Malisevo and
Volujak, a tactic that the Yugoslav Army appears to have been using
to shield its forces from attacks by NATO forces wary of causing
large numbers of civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
   The deputy director of strategic plans and policy for the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, Maj. Gen. Charles F. Wald, said NATO had struck 24
targets over the previous two days, far less than the number
attacked when the skies over the Balkans were clear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
