<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI TAKES ANOTHER STEP TOWARD A RACE FOR THE SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani set up a committee Monday to
finance a possible run for the Senate next year, as aides to
Hillary Rodham Clinton, also a potential candidate for the seat,
announced that she would spend three days traveling New York next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's decision to register a reconfigured Friends of
Giuliani Committee with the Federal Elections Commission, with the
express purpose of raising money for a Senate race, was the latest
indication that the Republican mayor is now close to a decision on
his next political move. He is barred from seeking re-election
after his term expires in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Mrs. Clinton's visit to New York was presented by
her aides as the routine business of a first lady, rather than a
concerted effort to stoke interest in her potential candidacy.
``It's all the kinds of things that she's been doing all along as
first lady,'' said the first lady's press secretary, Marsha Berry.
``She's not a candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mrs. Clinton's trip has all the hallmarks of a New York
campaign swing. Her schedule is packed with appearances before
environmental groups, teachers, Jewish leaders and women, and
includes stops on Long Island and in Niagara Falls, on New York's
western edge. Its scope seems likely to inspire another round of
attention to the first lady's potential ambition to succeed Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, the Democrat who is retiring in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has until now left open the possibility that he might
be interested in being considered for vice president, or in running
for governor. But his filing with the FEC offered the clearest sign
to date of which way he is leaning.
</P>
<P>
   From a technical point of view, said Bruce Teitelbaum, who is
overseeing Giuliani's political efforts, the change allows him to
collect $2,000 per person, rather than $1,000. From a political
point of view, it allowed the mayor to clarify his intentions
further.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a formal statement by the mayor that should he run for
federal office, he has now identified the office he would seek,''
Teitelbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican who has said he may be interested in seeking
the Republican nomination, Rep. Rick Lazio of Long Island, signaled
that he intended to stay in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the third time since December, I spent a week traveling
through upstate New York,'' he said. ``The feedback was
overwhelmingly positive, and leads me to believe that I'm the best
person to serve the state of New York in the U.S. Senate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
