<SLUG> BC-BLASS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLASS AND BEENE: TWAIN THAT DON'T MEET 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bill Blass and Geoffrey Beene are in a league by
themselves, but that doesn't mean they think alike, or even get
along.
</P>
<P>
   The day before his show last Wednesday at Le Cirque 2000, Blass
was in his Seventh Avenue office. He was in a jovial mood and, at
77, he appears to have lost none of his charm. When a reporter
suggested that something looked ``cool,'' he growled: ```Cool' is
out, babe. Didn't you read that in The New Yorker? `Round' is in.''
(Earlier that day, he had told Blaine Trump she ought to get with
it and buy a sweater that showed her navel.)
</P>
<P>
   He said: ``You can write anything you want about the collection,
I don't care. You can be as candid as you want.'' Blass broke into
a grin, which was followed by a huge laugh. ``And if you want to be
candid about Geoffrey Beene, I won't care about that, either.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a reference to an old feud, best left unstoked. Suffice
it to say that Blass was in top form with his fall collection,
which he said was based on ``client clothes.'' That meant drop-dead
simple luxury: a loden suit with a jacket trimmed at one corner in
velvet; a waffle-knit cardigan in creamy cashmere with smoke velvet
trousers; an all-American peacoat, but now in black corduroy and
worn for evening with beaded silk pants, and a perfectly snooty
suit in pale satin embroidered with noisy flowers.
</P>
<P>
   The colors were autumnal, but nothing like an Indiana pumpkin
patch: brown mixed with pale blue, reds with dusky orange. There
was even a mustard-yellow leather coat _ this from a man who hates
yellow so much he has the daffodils at his place in Connecticut
mowed down.
</P>
<P>
   There has been talk of Blass retiring, but that doesn't seem
imminent _ and his clients don't like the prospect. When asked, Nan
Kempner, the Park Avenue hostess and couture stalwart (she was
wearing a tan Saint Laurent suit), uttered a vulgar word that
teen-age girls use with reference to bands they don't like. Mrs.
Kempner shrugged, ``He's going to have to clone himself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been talking about retiring for 20 years,'' Pat Buckley
said, rolling her eyes. ``He never will. Besides, what are we going
to do for frocks?''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Blass treated his ladies to lunch. This week, he
plans to see Nancy Reagan in New York.
</P>
<P>
   People often think of Beene as a cerebral designer, but that
makes him sound dreary, and he isn't that. Before his show at the
Puck Building on Thursday (he liked the idea of showing with the
young South of Seventh designers), Beene said his collection was
about order and protection _ think armor.
</P>
<P>
   And he added that his muses were Joan of Arc and Helen of Troy.
Given that Joan was burned at the stake, Beene was asked to comment
about Helen's fate. He laughed impishly. ``I don't know what
happened once she got off the horse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Beene's show, in fact, was filled with order but also held
surprises. There were simple jersey dresses in black and taupe with
raised seams suggesting armored plates, and some heathery tweeds
with a solid sense of propriety. But there were also curvaceous
black gowns with rhinestone zippers that brought to mind the glam
era of Gianni Versace (funny, that) and a ruby-red gown with a
breastplate of sequins. There was also a sweet bolero that could be
unzipped around the shoulders to make the collar into a saucy
muffler.
</P>
<P>
   Beene, who has the prestige of dressing some of the smartest
women around, ended his show with a nod to his newer compatriots.
He played Petula Clark's ``Downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   Being in SoHo seemed to work for Joan Vass, too. Her collection,
called ``Anything Goes!'' opened with a model sauntering out in
black wool trousers, a sweater with ``carpe diem'' knitted into it,
and a silver-fox stolelike something called a ``fribble'' nestled
around her shoulders. The collection was strong on youthful
shearling and fur coats, and Ms. Vass' wonderful hand-knits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
