<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-JURY-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT REPORT SEEKS TO LIMIT SEQUESTRATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By VIVIAN S. TOY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jurors in trials involving violent crimes, except for
the handful of death penalty cases that arise each year, should no
longer be required to be sequestered during deliberations,
according to a report released Monday by New York state court
officials.
</P>
<P>
   New York is the only state that requires the sequestration of
jurors in trials involving violent crimes. But a study done by the
Office of Court Administration found that a statewide experiment
allowing jurors in nonviolent criminal trials to go home during
deliberations has saved the state $3.5 million in the last four
years and has not caused any increase in allegations of jury
tampering or in mistrials, as some prosecutors and defense lawyers
had feared.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen that separating juries works in the interest of the
public on all levels,'' said Jonathan Lippman, the state's chief
administrative judge. ``We're able to take better care of jurors,
save money and continue the administration of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Lippman said he hoped that legislation enacting the study's
recommendations would be passed by the state Legislature and signed
by Gov. George Pataki this year.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders in both houses of the Legislature said they were
amenable to the idea. State Sen. James Lack, the chairman of the
Senate Judiciary Committee, said that committee would review the
study and act on it quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly have no built-in bias in favor of a court system
that is costly and not necessary for the administration of
justice,'' said Lack, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Helene Weinstein, a Democrat from Brooklyn who is the chairwoman
of the Assembly Judiciary Committee, said she would reserve
judgment until she could study the report, but she said, ``The
Assembly would definitely be open to looking at this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also want to talk to affected parties such as defense
attorneys, district attorneys, judges and court officers before I
really go further,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1995, juries in all criminal trials were required to be
sequestered during deliberations. But Pataki signed a temporary law
that year allowing judges to send juries home except in cases of
violent felonies, like murder, rape and assault. Jurors in those
cases could avoid being sequestered only with the agreement of the
judge and all parties to the case.
</P>
<P>
   The temporary law expires in June, and the report recommends
that it be made permanent and expanded to lift required
sequestration from all criminal trials, except for death penalty
cases.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the law have argued that mandatory sequestration
discouraged people from wanting to be on juries and that juries
often speeded up their deliberations not on the merits of the case
but simply to avoid being held overnight.
</P>
<P>
   The report found that there was only one mistrial out of 935
criminal trials in which juries were not required to be sequestered
in the last two years. In that case, which involved a drug-dealing
charge, the judge declared a mistrial when one of the jurors did
not show up on the second day of deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were concerns that by separating juries you run the risk
of jury tampering, but there virtually were no problems
whatsoever,'' Lippman said. ``So we feel there's no logical reason
or public purpose for continuing to sequester juries.''
</P>
<P>
   Lack said that he had not received any complaints from judges or
lawyers since the temporary law was enacted.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that since 1995, about 15,000 jurors have
avoided overnight sequestration because of the temporary law,
saving the state nearly $3.5 million in security, hotel and meal
costs. The report estimated that it costs the state $2,800 per
night to sequester a jury.
</P>
<P>
   Lippman said that broadening the law to violent crime trials
would affect about 1,000 cases each year and would save the state
an additional $2 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Lefcourt, a Manhattan lawyer who is a former president of
the National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers, said he
agreed with the study's recommendations, noting that the policy has
long been routine in all federal criminal trials. He called
mandatory sequestration ``an antiquated law which is a waste of
costly resources.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good thing not to have jurors locked up if
there's no threat to their ability to be impartial,'' he said.
``There is very little downside to this that anyone has ever
suggested.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Compton, the president of the New York State Supreme
Court Officers Association, which represents 1,400 of the state's
3,700 court officers, said Monday night that his group opposes
lifting mandatory sequestration.
</P>
<P>
   He said any money that the state might save in court officers'
overtime would be offset because judges might be inclined to keep
juries in session beyond normal court hours. ``Court salaries are
probably $3,000 a day,'' he said, ``and when that jury stays out
another five, six, seven days, they're blowing that $3 million they
think they're saving.''
</P>
<P>
   Calls to the governor's press office were not returned Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
