<SLUG> BC-NYC-COL-PRIZE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITOR'S EYE IS ON A PRIZE: THE TRUST OF HIS READERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The only good part of knowing in advance that you
have not won your craft's most prestigious award (take it from an
old hand at this) is that you get to sleep well the night before.
No anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   So Bernard Stein was well rested when he awoke Monday, the day
they handed out the latest batch of Pulitzer Prizes. You can hardly
win a contest you have not entered. Stein figured why even bother
this time, since he had won the prize only a year ago for his
hard-nosed editorials in The Riverdale Press, the weekly community
newspaper in the northwest Bronx that his family has run for nearly
half a century.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he confessed to a vague sense of letdown. Not that there
is really any comparison, but he kind of understood how a Miss
America must feel on the last day of her reign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised I felt that way,'' he acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Oh well. Life goes on, and Stein does have his coveted Pulitzer
safely in hand.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more important, he also has his newspaper (circulation
14,000), with its articles about his neighborhood and its notices
of future local meetings that are not destined to find their way
into larger newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Those items are the very oxygen of a community newspaper, said
Stein, 57, who is the editor and co-publisher, with his brother,
Richard. For him, the message of all publications like his comes
close to a holy invocation: ``to persuade people that their lives
are important.''
</P>
<P>
   He was sitting Monday in a coffee shop near the Bronx County
Courthouse, where a school board corruption case that he had long
been following was about to go to trial. There was time to talk for
a little while about what happens when it is your turn for the
proverbial 15 minutes of fame that is supposedly due all of us.
After all, it isn't every year that a newspaper as small as his
grabs the brass ring.
</P>
<P>
   Does life suddenly change?
</P>
<P>
   No, it would seem. And yes.
</P>
<P>
   The nature of his work is the same, Stein said, and so, sad to
say, is the newspaper's circulation. He doesn't find it any easier
``getting a table in a restaurant other than the one my
sister-in-law's family runs.''
</P>
<P>
   But he quickly learned that winning a big-deal award can mean
that your opinion, on everything from the Bronx to Bosnia, is
sought by people who might never have heard of you before. He even
had the American Journalism Review on the phone asking for his
favorite words. (Try ``nugatory,'' which he missed on his SATs
years ago. It has nothing to do with a box of candy. It means
``trifling'' or ``worthless.'')
</P>
<P>
   What he finds most gratifying about his Pulitzer, Stein said, is
that many Riverdale neighbors and readers feel that it belongs to
them, too, in a way. Sure, critics of his editorials can put him
down with a new flourish: ``And you call yourself a Pulitzer Prize
winner!''
</P>
<P>
   But more typical is a man he bumped into at the doctor's office.
``It's like the home team hit one over the fence,'' the fellow
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The home team.'' That notion is what community newspapering
boils down to, whether in the Bronx or in Podunk.
</P>
<P>
   Far from being ``journalism's minor league,'' Stein said, his
type of paper can give readers a sense of their worth, while the
``big media help to make people feel powerless.''
</P>
<P>
   This last Year of Monica has been far from American journalism's
best, many critics would say. Small newspapers, Stein said, have
found themselves caught up in the breast-beating over the press'
failings. But only up to a point. By definition, what he writes can
affect readers in very real and immediate ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're accurate about something they know about on a
consistent basis, they do come to trust you,'' he said, adding:
``When I use `we' in an editorial, it's not the editorial `we.'
It's we, the residents of our area.''
</P>
<P>
   And then he had to go. There was a court case to cover.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
