<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-WILLIAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL TEAMS MAY BE FLUNKING THEIR OWN TESTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time when all that mattered about Texas running back
Ricky Williams was his performance on the field. Then came the hair
issue. Some teams did not like his braids. Then there was the agent
issue. Some teams thought his manager, the rapper Master P, would
be a hindrance in contract negotiations. Then the weight issue. He
was supposedly 20 pounds too heavy.
</P>
<P>
   The truth? Williams, the Heisman Trophy winner, did not show up
to the Indianapolis scouting combine two months ago with 20
rappers, just several friends and business partners. The person who
will negotiate his contracts is not a rapper but the agent Leland
Hardy, a graduate of the Wharton School of business. The weight?
Not 20 pounds over but 7 or 8.
</P>
<P>
   Williams (5 feet 10 inches, 224 pounds) recently completed a
six-team, six-city tour that lasted three days and, contrary to
speculation, remains a serious possibility for the Cleveland
Browns, who select No. 1 overall in this weekend's National
Football League draft.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is not the only one who has undergone intense scrutiny.
Despite throwing for over 4,000 yards at Kentucky last season, Tim
Couch is facing questions about his arm strength. Akili Smith was
smart enough to step into Oregon's starting lineup last year and
complete 58 percent of his passes, but there are questions about
his smarts because he once scored poorly on the Wunderlich
intelligence test.
</P>
<P>
   What is going on here?
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more teams are paying attention to the things that
count the least, like the combine or workouts or other things,''
said Russell Lande, a former scout for the St. Louis Rams, who
publishes his own draft guide.
</P>
<P>
   It is almost as if the Browns and other teams are beginning to
outthink themselves. That is why the 1999 draft has an uncertain
feeling about it, one similar to that of the 1995 draft, in which
Terrell Davis was selected in the sixth round by Denver and Jamal
Anderson in the seventh by Atlanta. Both players were in the Super
Bowl last season.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland is deciding among Couch, Smith, Williams and even
trading the pick. At this point, the Browns are unsure what to do.
Many teams seem to be undecided, and the possibility of at least
two trades in the first round _ perhaps even within the first five
picks _ remains a strong one.
</P>
<P>
   Browns coach Chris Palmer said the three players are ``neck and
neck coming down the stretch.'' Browns President Carmen Policy said
a decision might not be made until draft day. This is more than
just talk; the Browns can't make up their mind.
</P>
<P>
   This draft is shaping up to be quite different from last
season's, when everyone with a football IQ over 10 knew the
Indianapolis Colts were going to take Peyton Manning with the first
pick and the San Diego Chargers, selecting second, were locked onto
Ryan Leaf. There was no confusion and, for the most part, the draft
fell into place with few surprises.
</P>
<P>
   This year there is plenty of guessing, in part because teams are
paying less attention to on-field performance and more to
postseason workouts. This is bound to lead to players slipping who
should be drafted higher, and the escalation of a player's stock
who should be drafted lower.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is a perfect example of a player who has been through
the analysis wringer. He was hot, then not, and is now hot again.
Still, scouts have tried to find something wrong, picking at him
like leftover turkey. During a workout in California, he was timed
by the Browns as running a 40-yard dash in around 4.5 seconds. This
was viewed by some league scouts as disappointing. Why? Almost
every team knew that what made Williams a great back at Texas was
not blazing speed, but toughness, elusiveness and durability.
</P>
<P>
   One team desperate to draft Williams is New Orleans, owners of
the 12th overall pick. General Manager Bill Kuharich began calling
the top five teams this week about a trade in which the Saints
would offer all seven of their draft picks plus at least two more
from the 2000 draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at the poker table, we have our cards, and so far no
one is at the table with us,'' Kuharich said. ``But that will
change once the draft gets here. We'll have some company.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
