<SLUG> BC-UTEXAS-RUTGERSCOACH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas hires Rutgers assistant
 &HT;    By Randy Riggs
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When he accepted an assistant's job at Rutgers
two years ago, Rob Lanier told himself his next professional move
would be to become a head basketball coach.
</P>
<P>
   He reconsidered, however, when Rick Barnes came calling.
Consequently, the 30-year-old Lanier on Monday became Barnes'
newest assistant at the University of Texas _ primarily because of
Barnes' track record of having his assistants get head coaching
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Lanier replaces Ricky Stokes, who became the fifth Barnes
assistant to land a head coaching job when he left UT for Virginia
Tech last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky's a really good friend of mine,'' Lanier said Monday.
``When I saw the picture of him at the podium at the Virginia Tech
press conference, I thought it would be a great opportunity to work
with Rick Barnes. I'm glad it's all worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Lanier, cousin of former NBA great Bob Lanier, is renowned as a
strong recruiter who helped reverse the fortunes at Rutgers in his
two years at the Big East school. The fact he left during the
current spring signing period and began working for Texas on Monday
did not please Scarlet Knights head coach Kevin Bannon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not great timing. It's a delicate time, actually,''
Bannon told the Newark (N. J.) Star-Ledger. ``But Rob has done a
great job for us. I wish him the best. It's a great opportunity for
him. We'll just have to keep the ship afloat in terms of
recruiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Lanier _ who has extensive recruiting contacts overseas,
especially in Africa _ acknowledged that his departure ``wasn't
very well received in the (Rutgers) basketball office, and I
understand that. There is no right time. But for me, the chance to
come to Texas and work for Rick is the opportunity of my career. It
was a big-picture decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Stokes had the title of associate head coach at UT, but Lanier
will be an assistant, along with current assistant Brian Cousins.
Both will be allowed to recruit off-campus.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes was unavailable for comment on Monday, but in a prepared
statement he called Lanier ``one of the top assistant coaches in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rob is a great recruiter with solid connections all over the
country . . . but he's more than just a great recruiter,'' Barnes
added. ``He is skilled in every area of the coaching profession,
and I know he'll be a fine head coach in the near future.''
</P>
<P>
   Lanier, a native of Buffalo, N.Y., spent five years as an
assistant at his alma mater, St. Bonaventure, before going to
Rutgers. He began his coaching career at Niagara University. He was
married this past summer to Dr. Dayo Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Riggs writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
