<SLUG> BC-NJ-OFFICER-SLAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT GUILTY PLEA IN NEW JERSEY OFFICER'S KILLING
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ A 24-year-old man pleaded not guilty Monday to
the murder of a police officer in Orange, and his lawyer said
afterward that he would soon present evidence that the man was
elsewhere at the time of last Thursday's shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, Terrance Everrett, stood motionless and silent
during his arraignment on murder, robbery and weapons charges. His
lawyer, Raymond Hamlin, entered not guilty pleas to each count, and
Judge Betty J. Lester ordered Everrett held on $1 million bail.
</P>
<P>
   The police say Everrett accosted people on the street at
gunpoint on Thursday evening, minutes before he was stopped by
Officer Joyce Anne Carnegie, 38, whom they say he shot to death.
</P>
<P>
   After a manhunt by scores of officers, Everrett was arrested on
Saturday night at the East Orange home he shares with his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters after Monday's arraignment, Hamlin said he
would show that his client was not at the scene of the shooting,
but he would not say when he would present the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready, willing and able to show that he didn't do the
things he is charged with,'' Hamlin said. ``We understand that
someone else was taken into custody, and the fact that my client
has been arraigned doesn't mean that this might not be resolved
favorably for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer was referring to raids at two Newark apartments on
Sunday night by investigators from Orange and Newark police and the
Essex County Prosecutor's office.
</P>
<P>
   In one raid, James Coker, 29, was arrested and charged with
possession of crack and with trying to swallow the drugs when the
police arrived at his apartment.
</P>
<P>
   A Newark police official said Monday that the raids were part of
the investigation into the shooting of Carnegie. But the official
did not say what led them to Coker, who has not been charged in
connection with Carnegie's death.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Weiss, a spokesman for the prosecutor, would not comment on
the raids or the arrest of Coker, except to say that the
investigation was continuing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-12-99 2357EDT &QL; 
