</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-GAMBLING-BILL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Senate bill to help prosecute 8-liner games passes hurdle
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Senate gave tentative approval Monday to a
bill it said strengthens anti-gambling laws by making it easier to
prosecute operators of eight-liner machines, but critics say the
measure actually expands some forms of gambling and puts corporate
profits above community fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texans shouldn't be fooled into believing this is
anti-gambling legislation,'' said Bob Young, president of the
Amusement and Music Operators of Texas. ``This bill is designed to
grab a few headlines and quietly eliminate the competition for
corporate gaming interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill sponsors bill discounted the criticism and said the bill
ensures that eight-liners won't continue to spread across the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers and Gov. George W. Bush have argued for years
that eight-liners are illegal. They add, however, that the law
needs to be clarified so that prosecutors can effectively go after
people who own and operate the machines.
</P>
<P>
   Eight-liner operators say their machines are legal but admit
that some people are pushing the limits of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Eight-liners often look and operate like slot machines. They
offer eight ways by which players can win. In some parts of the
state, owners and operators have set up ``casinos'' filled with
eight-liner machines.
</P>
<P>
   Current law makes most games of chance _ those that require
little or no skill to win _ illegal. The state lottery, charity
bingo and betting at dog and horse races are exceptions to the law.
</P>
<P>
   Another exception are ``Fuzzy Animal'' games. Those games, like
crane machines that are common in children's arcades, cannot give
prizes worth more than $5 and cannot give any cash prizes. They
often give novelty items and stuffed animals.
</P>
<P>
   Some eight-liner operators use the fuzzy animal exception to
give away gift certificates _ the paper itself not worth more than
$5 _ that can be traded for cash or prizes worth more than $5.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. David Sibley, R-Waco, wants to rid the state of
eight-liners and any other games that look like or operate like
slot machines and gambling devices.
</P>
<P>
   Sibley's Senate Bill 970, expected to go to the House today
would redefine ``Fuzzy Animal'' machines as ``bona fide amusement
devices.'' Skill would have to be the predominant factor to winning
the games, and prizes still could not be worth more than $5. If the
machines gave out certificates or vouchers, they would have to be
redeemed at the same place the game was played and couldn't be
redeemed for prizes worth more than $5 per play.
</P>
<P>
   A person still could play a game several times, collect several
certificates and receive a prize worth more than $5. The average
wholesale price of any prize couldn't be worth more than $10.
</P>
<P>
   Officials for the Veterans of Foreign Wars organizations, which
do charity and community fund-raising, want eight-liners to remain
legal. But they said requiring on-site redemption would severely
limit their charity work.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also allows owners and operators of race tracks, bingo
halls and lottery retailers that also sell liquor for on-site
consumption to offer games that give away certificates redeemable
for lottery tickets, free bingo games and pari-mutual bets. Young
and veterans' groups say that's putting corporations ahead of
nonprofit groups and mom and pop stores that use eight-liners.
</P>
<P>
   Juan B. Elizondo Jr. writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
