u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS-SUNS-COX     04-12 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-SUNS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elie ignites Spurs to easy win over Suns
 &HT;    By Mark Rosner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO, Texas _ Mario Elie does more than talk tough. He
plays that way, too.
</P>
<P>
   Elie, the first-year San Antonio Spur who has sometimes
criticized his teammates' level of intensity, showed them how it's
done in the fourth quarter Monday, when it really counted. After
the Spurs allowed Phoenix to cut a 20-point lead to nine, Elie
scored seven straight points, recharging the Spurs, who pulled away
for a 94-77 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Elie, who did not start the second half, scored seven of his
eight points in the fourth quarter. Early in the period, neither
San Antonio's Avery Johnson nor Phoenix's Jason Kidd could control
a jump ball at midcourt. Elie outwrestled Chris Morris for the
loose ball and completed a three-point play, dribbling quickly to
the basket for a dunk while Morris fouled him. Elie then hit two
jump shots from just inside the three-point line.
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, San Antonio (25-11) split its four-game season
series with Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Duncan led the Spurs with 26 points. Johnson scored 20, and
David Robinson had 13 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix (18-20), trailing by 20 with 2:30 left in the third
quarter, finished the period with a 9-0 run, making the Spurs work
some more for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Robinson scored 25 for the Suns, and Kidd was effective
against the Spurs for the fourth straight game this season
o(accent) 22 points, nine rebounds and nine assists. Kidd arrived
in San Antonio averaging nearly a triple-double in three games
against the Spurs o(accent) 14 points, 13 assists and 9.7 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson scored 15 points in the first half, hitting seven of
eight shots. Left open when the Suns double-teamed Duncan inside,
Johnson hit three perimeter jumpers. He scored three times on
fastbreak layups. On one of them, Johnson froze Rex Chapman with a
hesitation move before blowing by for the easy basket that
completed a 20-3 run for the Spurs in the second quarter. They led
by 19 at the half.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan had a hard-earned 17 points in the half, working through
the double-teams to hit eight of 14 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd had 11 points, eight assists and five rebounds in the half
for Phoenix, the type of production the Spurs expect from him
against them. Phoenix played Monday without two starters, forward
Tom Gugliotta and center Luc Longley, both of whom have
hyperextended knees.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs have to play three games in three days this week. They
are at Dallas tonight and return to the Alamodome to play Minnesota
on Wednesday. San Antonio played three games in three days earlier
this season, sandwiching victories over Denver and Dallas around a
loss to Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Rosner writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
