<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-GURNEY-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GURNEY FOLLOWS FATHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ It was only natural that Alex Gurney would
want to pursue auto racing. After all, his father, Dan Gurney,
spent 15 years racing all over the world. It was also natural that
Alex's parents would want to protect their son from the dangerous
sport and steer him to another career.
</P>
<P>
   But Alex wouldn't have it any other way. He convinced his
parents that his passion was real and now they fully support their
son, who is preparing for the most important journey of his young
life.
</P>
<P>
   Alex embarks on his second year as a professional and first in
the Kool/Toyota Atlantic Championship when the series opens at the
Long Beach Toyota Grand Prix on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Newport Beach native has been a fan at the Long Beach race
for as long as he can remember. But instead of being in the
grandstands, he will be behind the wheel this time, in front of
family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something I've dreamed about,'' said the 24-year-old,
who is a member of Team Kool Green.
</P>
<P>
   What makes it better is that his father, his hero, is behind
him.
</P>
<P>
   Alex wasn't even born when his father retired from professional
racing and formed All American Racers, which designs and
manufactures race cars. Dan became the top road racer in America
and was very popular on the European Circuit from 1955 to 1970. By
the time young Alex saw his father compete, Dan was racing in the
Celebrity-Pro Race in Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dangerous, difficult way of making a living,'' said
Dan, who is the co-grand marshal for the Long Beach Toyota Grand
Prix. ``I felt that I didn't want to encourage him. But by the same
token, we said if sufficient passion is there, if you graduate from
college with a degree and then if the flame is still burning to be
a race-car driver, by then you have to say, `Well, maybe this is
real.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It was. Alex graduated with a business degree from the
University of Colorado and raced go-karts in his spare time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I started winning and started to show that this is really
what I wanted to do, they got a little more open to it,'' Alex
said.
</P>
<P>
   He made his professional debut last year in the Barber Dodge Pro
Series, where he finished 10th. He had 12 starts, four top-10
finishes, and won the pole at Homestead, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Although the cars are similar in form, the Atlantics are a step
up. And so are Alex's goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm shooting for Rookie of the Year,'' he said. ``I obviously
have a lot to learn. I hope to be in the Atlantics next year as
well, but we plan to be competitive at every race. We've done a lot
of testing.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex will be tested against an experienced field of top
returnees: Lee Bentham, who won the championship last year; Andrew
Bordin, who finished second in the series and second at Long Beach;
Buddy Rice, who won the pole here last year, and Anthony Lazzaro.
</P>
<P>
   But Alex won't feel out of place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long Beach is an interesting place for me to start out,'' he
said. ``I've been coming here, basically, since I was born. I've
been up in the stands every year. It will be a pretty special
feeling being out there in a real race car.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
